{'istart': 124, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'We are informed that Imperial Commander Lu Zhi has been struggling with a horde of rebels led by Zhang Jue at Guangzong. Lu Zhi was once my teacher, and I want to go to help him.', 'context': 'After the celebrations in honor of victory were over, Commander Zhou Jing proposed to return to Youzhou. But Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 345, 'talk': 'I am able to surround these rebels here. But the other two brothers, Zhang Bao and Zhang Liang, are strongly entrenched opposite Huangfu Song and Zhu Jun at Yingchuan. I will give you a thousand more troops, and with these you can go to find out what is happening, and we can then settle the moment for concerted attack.', 'context': 'Lu Zhi said to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 257, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'The rebels are camping in the field. We can attack them by fire.', 'context': 'So Liu Bei set off and marched as quickly as possible to Yingchuan. At that time the imperial troops were attacking with success, and the rebels had retired upon Changshe. They had encamped among the thick grass. Seeing this, Huangfu Song said to Zhu Jun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'But your uncle said you were in a fit; are you better?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'I have never suffered from fits or any such illness,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 132, 'talk': "But I have lost my uncle's affection, and he has deceived you.", 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'What manner of man am I?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'In peace you are an able subject; in chaos you are a crafty hero!', 'context': 'Then Xu Shao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'The rebel power is quite broken here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'but they will surely make for Guangzong to join Zhang Jue. You can do nothing better than hasten back.', 'context': ' said the commanders, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 595, 'talk': 'I had surrounded the rebels and was on the point of smashing them, when Zhang Jue employed some of his supernatural powers and prevented my victory. The court sent down Eunuch Zhuo Feng to inquire into my failure, and that official demanded a bribe. I told him how hard pressed we were and asked him where, in the circumstances, I could find a gift for him. He went away in wrath and reported that I was hiding behind my ramparts and would not give battle and that I disheartened my army. So I was superseded by Dong Zhuo, and I have to go to the capital to answer the charge.', 'context': 'Lu Zhi explained, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'The government will take the proper course,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'You must not act hastily!', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 260, 'iend': 288, 'talk': 'Zhang Jue the Lord of Heaven', 'context': "retook the road. Two days later they heard the thunder of battle behind some hills. Hastening to the top, they beheld the government soldiers suffering great loss, and they saw the countryside was full of Yellow Scarves. On the rebels' banners were the words “"},
