{'istart': 39, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'Tomorrow, then, will I prepare counter magic in the shape of the blood of slaughtered swine and goats and dogs. This blood shall be sprinkled upon their hosts from the precipices above by soldiers in ambush. Thus shall we be able to break the power of their shamanic art.', 'context': ' said Zhu Jun. “'},
{'istart': 235, 'iend': 263, 'talk': 'Zhang Bao The Lord of Earth,', 'context': 'Zhang Bao quickly saw his magic had been countered and turned to retire. Then he was attacked on the flanks by Guan Yu and Zhang Fei, and in rear by Liu Bei and Zhu Jun. The rebels were routed. Liu Bei, seeing from afar the banner of “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 322, 'talk': 'Huangfu Song did not forgotten his friends. His first act after he had attained to power was to memorialize the Throne concerning the case of Lu Zhi, who was then restored to his former rank for his meritorious conducts. Cao Cao also received advancement for his services and was preparing to go to Jinan to his new post.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'Seeing that the founder of the Han Dynasty, Liu Bang the Supreme Ancestor, could welcome the submissive and receive the favorable, why reject these?', 'context': 'Said Liu Bei to Zhu Jun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'The conditions are different,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 512, 'talk': 'In those old days disorder was universal and the people had no fixed lord. Wherefore submission was welcomed and support rewarded to encourage people to come over. Now the empire is united, and the Yellow Scarves are the only malcontents. To receive their surrender is not to encourage the good. To allow brigands, when successful, is to give way to every license, and to let them surrender when they fail is to encourage brigandage. Your plan is not a good one.', 'context': ' replied Zhu Jun. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 454, 'talk': "Not to let brigands surrender is well. But the city is surrounded as by an iron barrel. If the rebels' request be refused, they will be desperate and fight to the death, and we can hardly withstood a myriad of such men. Moreover, in the city there are many times that number, all doomed to death. Let us withdraw from one corner and only attack the opposite. They will all assuredly flee and have no desire to fight. We shall take them.", 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'We can capture these,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 395, 'talk': 'The Yellow Scarves rebelled because the eunuchs sold offices and bartered ranks. There was employment only for their friends, punishment only for their enemies. This led to rebellion. Wherefore it would be well to slay the Ten Eunuchs and expose their heads and proclaim what had been done throughout the whole empire. Then reward the worthy. Thereby the land would be wholly tranquil.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'Surely some one who rendered some service against rebels resents being passed over.', 'context': 'However, the eunuchs took counsel together and one said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Magistrate, what was your origin?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'I am descended from Prince Faubus of Zhongshan. Since my first fight with the Yellow Scarves rebels at Zhuo County, I have been in some thirty battles, wherein I gained some trifling merit. My reward was this office.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'You lie about your descent, and your statement of services is false,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Now the court has ordered the reduction of your sort of low class and corrupt officials.', 'context': ' roared the inspector. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'This pompous attitude only means the inspector wants a bribe,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I have never wronged the people to the value of a single coin; then where is a bribe to come from?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'The inspector has compelled the underlings to bear false witness against our magistrate, with the desire to injure the virtuous Liu Bei. We came to beg mercy for him but are not permitted to enter. Moreover, we have been beaten by the doorkeepers.', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Oppressor of the people, robber!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Do you know me?', 'context': ' cried Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'General Zhang Fei had bound somebody to a post and was thrashing him.', 'context': 'They told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'If we do not beat this sort of wretch to death, what may we expect?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Noble Sir, save me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 225, 'talk': 'If I hear that you injure the people, I will assuredly kill you. I now spare your life, and I return to you the seal. We are going.', 'context': "Liu Bei contented himself with hanging the official seal about the inspector's neck, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Sire, how can you be feasting with these when the empire is at the last gasp?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'All is well,', 'context': ' said Liu Tao. “'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Where is anything wrong?', 'context': ' said the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'Robbers swarm on all sides and plunder the cities. And all is the fault of the Ten Eunuchs who sell offices and injure the people, oppress loyal officials and deceive their superiors. All virtuous ones have left the services, and misfortune is before our very eyes.', 'context': 'Said Liu Tao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'If Minister Liu Tao disapproves of us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'we are in danger. We pray that our lives be spared and we may go to our farms. We yield our property to help defray military expenses.', 'context': ' they said, “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 125, 'talk': "You also have servants; why can't you bear with mine?", 'context': 'And they wept bitterly. The Emperor turned angrily to Liu Tao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'My death matters nothing. The pity is that Han Dynasty, after four centuries of reign, is falling fast.', 'context': 'Liu Tao cried aloud, “'},
{'istart': 122, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'Strike not! Wait till I have spoken with His Majesty.', 'context': "The guards hustled him away and were just about to carry out the Emperor's order when a minister stopped them, shouting, “"},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'For what fault is Counselor Liu Tao to be put to death?', 'context': 'It was the Minister of the Interior, Chen Dan. He went in to the Emperor, to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'He has vilified my servants; and has insulted me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 290, 'talk': 'All the empire would eat the flesh of the eunuchs if they could, and yet, Sire, you respect them as if they were your parents. They have no merit, but they are created nobles. Moreover, Feng Xu was in league with the Yellow Scarves. Unless Your Majesty looks to it, the state will crumble!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'There was no proof against Feng Xu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'About the Ten Eunuchs, are there none faithful among them?', 'context': ' replied the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 237, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'If Liu Xian is to succeed, He Jin must be killed to prevent countermoves.', 'context': 'Empress Dong had always tried to persuade her son to name Liu Xian as the Heir Apparent, and in fact the Emperor greatly loved the boy and was disposed to do as his mother desired. When he fell ill, one of the eunuchs, Jian Shuo, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'This must be a trap of Jian Shuo to destroy you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'What do inferiors like you know of the ways of government?', 'context': 'He Jin eyed down and saw General of Military Standards Cao Cao. He Jin was very angry at this speech and cried, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'The Emperor is no more. The eunuchs have decided to keep the death a secret and forge a command to the Imperial Guardian to come into the palace to settle the succession. Meanwhile to prevent trouble they have inscribed the name of Liu Xian on the roll.', 'context': 'And in the midst of the confusion Pan Yin came to say: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'The matter for the moment is to set up the rightful heir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'The other affairs can wait.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Who dares to join me in supporting the rightful heir—Prince Bian Liu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'Give me five thousand veterans, and we will break into the palace, set up the true heir, slay the eunuchs, and sweep clean the government. Then peace will come to the empire.', 'context': 'At once one stood forward saying, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Their gangs have broken; the most opportune moment is now to slay all the eunuchs.', 'context': 'Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Fear not,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'I will protect you.', 'context': ' said Empress He, whose son had just become Emperor, “'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Slay them, root and branch,', 'context': 'fate, and his clan will be punished. But we need not exterminate the whole party nor injure his colleagues.” “'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'or they will ruin you!', 'context': ' cried Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'I have decided;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'say no more.', 'context': ' said He Jin, coldly, “'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'It was I who first brought forward the sister of He Jin. Today her son is on the throne, and all the officials are her friends, and her influence is enormous. What can we do?', 'context': 'Said she, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 256, 'talk': "Your Highness should administer the state from 'behind the veil.' create the late Emperor's son Liu Xian a prince; give your brother, the Imperial Uncle Dong Chong, a high rank, and place him over the army; and use us. That will do it.", 'context': 'Zhang Rang replied, “'},
{'istart': 215, 'iend': 561, 'talk': 'It is not fitting that we two should meddle in state affairs. In the beginning of the Han Dynasty, when Empress Lu laid hands upon the government, all her clans were put to death. We ought to remain content, immured in our palaces, and leave state affairs to the state officials. That would be well for the country, and I trust you will act thus.', 'context': 'When Empress He saw this, she prepared a banquet to which she invited her rival Empress Dong. In the middle of the feast, when all were well warmed with wine, Empress He rose and offered a cup to her guest saying, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 300, 'talk': 'You poisoned Lady Wang out of jealousy. Now, relying upon the fact that your son sits on the throne and that your brother is powerful, you speak these wild words. I will command that your brother be beheaded, and that can be done as easily as I turn my hand.', 'context': 'But Empress Dong only got angry, saying, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'I tried to persuade you with fair words; why get so angry?', 'context': 'Empress He in her turn waxed wroth and said, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'You low born daughter of a butcher, what do you know of offices?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 620, 'talk': 'The two eunuchs, Zhang Rang and Duan Gui, are spreading the report outside that you has caused the death of the late empress and is aiming at the throne. This is an excuse for you to destroy them. Do not spare them this time, or you will pay like Dou Wu and Chen Fan, who in the previous reign missed their chance because the secret had not been kept, and they paid by their own deaths. Now you and your brother have many commanders and officers behind, so that the destruction of the eunuchs can be but an ease. It is a heaven−sent opportunity. Delay no further!', 'context': 'Commander Yuan Shao went one day to see He Jin, saying, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Let me think it over.', 'context': 'But He Jin replied, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 306, 'talk': 'The General is the chief support of the new Emperor, yet he is not gracious and merciful but thinks wholly of slaughter. If he slays the eunuchs without cause, it may bring about revolution.', 'context': 'gifts to the younger brother He Miao. Corrupted by these, he went in to speak with his sister Empress He and said, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 291, 'talk': "Those officials look after palace affairs and are old servants. To kill the old servants just after the death of their master would appear disrespectful to the dynasty's ancestral temple.", 'context': 'Soon after He Jin entered and told her of his design to put the eunuchs to death. She argued with him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'What about it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'She will not consent; what can be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Call up an army and slay them; it is imperative. Never mind her consent.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'That is an excellent plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'The view of a mere book−worm,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 486, 'talk': 'The eunuch evil is of very old standing, but the real cause of the present trouble is in the improper influence allowed them by the emperors and the misplaced favoritism they have enjoyed. But a gaoler would be ample force to employ against this kind of evil, and getting rid of the main culprits is quite enough. Why increase confusion by summoning troops from the regions? Any desire to slay all of them will speedily become known, and the plan will fail.', 'context': 'What Cao Cao said was this: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Then, Cao Cao, you have some scheme of your own to further,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'The one throwing the world into chaos is He Jin!', 'context': 'Cao Cao left the meeting, proclaiming, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'Though a formal summons has come, there are many obscurities in it. It would be well to send up a memorial stating plainly our aims and intentions. Then we can proceed.', 'context': "Dong Zhuo's adviser and son−in−law, Li Ru, said, “"},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'A fierce wild beast; if he comes, his prey will be humans!', 'context': 'He Jin read this memorial and showed it to his partisans. Then said Minister Zheng Tai, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'You are too timorous; you are unequal to great schemes.', 'context': 'He Jin replied, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'Long have I known this man; in appearance innocent, he is a very wolf at heart. Let him in, and calamity enters with him. Stop him, do not let him come, and thus will you avoid chaos.', 'context': 'But Lu Zhi also said, “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'The General, feigning to act under command, has called up armies to the capital to destroy us. We pray you, Your Majesty, pity and save us!', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Go to the General and confess your faults,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'The eunuchs are certainly behind the order and mean your harm.', 'context': 'advised him not to enter, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Our plot is no longer a secret;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'still you may go if you are ready to fight your way in.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Get the eunuchs out first,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Silly children!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'If you will go, then we will come as a guard, just as a precaution.', 'context': 'Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'The orders are to admit the Imperial Guardian and none other.', 'context': 'holding swords, went as escort. When He Jin neared the palace, the eunuchs said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 353, 'talk': 'What crime had Empress Dong committed that she should have been put to death? And when the Mother of the Country was buried, who feigned sickness and did not attend? We raised you and your paltry, huckstering family to all the dignity and wealth you have, and this is your gratitude! You would slay us. You call us sordid and dirty; who is the cleaner?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Thy carriage waits, O General!', 'context': 'So He Jin died. Yuan Shao and Cao Cao waited long. By and by, impatient at the delay, they called through the gate, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'He Jin has contemplated treachery and therefore has been slain. It pardons his adherents.', 'context': 'For reply the head of He Jin was flung over the wall. A decree was proclaimed: “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'The eunuchs have slain the High Minister. Let those who will slay this wicked party come and help me!', 'context': 'Yuan Shao shouted, “'},
{'istart': 226, 'iend': 269, 'talk': 'You rebel, how dare you abduct the Empress?', 'context': 'Lu Zhi, since he had resigned office, was at home, but hearing of the revolution in the Palace he donned his armor, took his spear, and prepared to fight. He saw the eunuch Duan Gui hurrying the Empress along and called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'You also were in the plot to slay your own brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'You shall die with the others.', 'context': ' cried Wu Kuang. “'},
