{'istart': 343, 'iend': 364, 'talk': 'Traitors, stop, stop!', 'context': 'Meanwhile, Zhang Rang and Duan Gui had hustled away the Emperor and the Prince. They burst through the smoke and fire and traveled without stopping till they reached the Beimang Hills. It was then the third watch. They heard a great shouting behind them and saw soldiers in pursuit. Their leader, Min Gong, a commander in Henan, was shouting “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'This is no a place to stay in;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'we must find some way out.', 'context': ' said Prince Xian, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'God is helping us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'To what household do you belong, young gentlemen?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'Where is the Emperor?', 'context': 'It has been said that Min Gong had gone in pursuit of Eunuch Duan Gui. By and by Min Gong overtook Duan Gui and cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'He disappeared. I do not know where he is.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'The state cannot be without its ruler,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'I pray Your Majesty return to the city.', 'context': ' said Min Gong. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Do you have the Emperor?', 'context': 'From under the shade of an embroidered banner rode out a general, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo, Imperial Protector of Xizhou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Have you come to protect the Chariot or to steal it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'I have come to protect,', 'context': ' said Prince Xian. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'If that is so, the Emperor is here; why do you not dismount?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'This man harbors some evil design and should be removed.', 'context': "Imperial Commander Bao Xin spoke of Dong Zhuo's behavior to Yuan Shao, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Nothing can he done till the government is more settled,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Let us talk it over,', 'context': 'Then Bao Xin saw Minister of the Interior Wang Yun and asked what he thought. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'The government is really without a head; there can be no better time than this to carry out your plan. Delay will spoil all. Tomorrow assemble the officials in the Wenming Garden and address them on the subject. Put all opponents to death, and your prestige is settled.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'I have something to say; listen quietly all of you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'No! No! Who are you that you dare utter such bold words? The Emperor is the son of the lawful consort and has done no wrong. Why then should he be deposed? Are you a rebel?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 186, 'iend': 305, 'talk': 'But this is the banquet chamber, and state affairs should be left outside. The matters can be fully discussed tomorrow.', 'context': 'Ding Yuan a particularly dangerous looking henchman of his, who was now handling his halberd threateningly, and whose eyes were blazing with anger. So Li Ru hastily interposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Is what I said just and reasonable?', 'context': 'His fellow guests persuaded Ding Yuan to leave, and after his departure Dong Zhuo said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'You are mistaken, Illustrious Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'That is Lu Bu, the adopted son of Ding Yuan. You must keep out of his way, my lord.', 'context': 'thus, Dong Zhuo noticed a spearman galloping to and fro on a fiery steed and asked Li Ru who that was. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'Unhappy indeed was this state when the eunuchs became so powerful that the people were as if trodden into the mire under their feet. Now you, devoid of the least merit, dare to talk of deposing the rightful emperor and setting up another. This is to desire rebellion and no less.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'This Lu Bu is a marvel,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'If he were only on my side, I would defy the whole world.', 'context': ' said Dong Zhuo. “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'Be content, O my lord! I am a fellow villager of his and know him well, his bravery, his prowess, his cupidity, and his unscrupulousness. With this little, blarneying tongue of mine, I can persuade him to put up his hands and come over to your side.', 'context': 'At this a man advanced saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'What arguments will you use with him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 212, 'talk': "You have a fine horse, Red−Hare, one of the best ever bred; I must have this steed, and gold and pearls to win his heart. Then will I go and persuade him. He will certainly abandon Ding Yuan's service for yours.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'What think you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'One cannot grudge a horse to win an empire,', 'context': ' said Dong Zhuo to his adviser Li Ru. “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Please tell General Lu Bu that a very old friend has come to visit him.', 'context': 'Li Su reached the camp and said to the guard, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Worthy brother, have you been well since we last met?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'How long it is since we last saw each other!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'And where are you now?', 'context': ' replied Lu Bu, bowing in return. “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'What return can I hope to make for such a creature?', 'context': 'Lu Bu was delighted with the horse and said, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'What return can I hope for? I came to you out of a sense of what is right,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'We have seen very little of each other, but I am constantly meeting your honorable father,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'You are drunk,', 'context': ' said Li Su. “'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'My father has been dead for years.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Not so; I spoke of Ding Yuan, the man of the day.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Yes, I am with him but only because I can do no better.', 'context': 'Lu Bu started. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'If I could only find a master to serve!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'The clever bird chooses the branch whereon to perch; the wise servant selects the master to serve. Seize the chance when it comes, for repentance ever comes too late.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Now you are in the government. Who think you is really the bravest of all?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'I despise the whole lot except Dong Zhuo. He is one who respects wisdom and reveres scholarship; he is discriminating in his rewards and punishments. Surely he is destined to be a really great man.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'I wish that I could serve him, but there is no way, I fear.', 'context': 'Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'What is this? What does it mean?', 'context': 'Then Li Su produced his pearls and gold and the jeweled belt and laid them out before his host. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Send away the attendants,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo has long respected your valor and sent these by my hand. Red−Hare was also from him.', 'context': ' requested Li Su. And he went on, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'But, if he loves me like this, what can I do in return?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'If a stupid fellow like me can be a general in the Imperial Tiger Army, it is impossible to say what honors await you.', 'context': 'Li Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I am sorry I can offer him no service worth mentioning.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'If you would do that, there could be no greater service. But such a thing must be done quickly.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'My son, what is afoot?', 'context': 'Seeing who came in, Ding Yuan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'I am a bold hero,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 83, 'talk': "Don't you think I am willing to be a son of yours.", 'context': ' said Lu Bu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Why this change, Lu Bu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'He was an unjust man and I have slain him. Let those who back me stay; the others may depart.', 'context': 'and said, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'Your coming is welcome as the gentle dew to the parched grass,', 'context': 'who led him to Dong Zhuo. Dong Zhuo received him with a warm welcome and had wine set before him. “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'He who is above us being weak and irresolute is unfit for the duties of his high place. Wherefore I, as of old did Yi Yin and Huo Guang, will set aside this Emperor giving him the title of Prince of Hongnong, and I will place on the throne the present Prince of Chenliu. And those who do not support me will suffer death.', 'context': 'Then suddenly the host arose and drew his sword, saying, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'The Emperor was innocent of any fault, and to set him aside in favor of a commoner was rebellion and nothing else.', 'context': 'Fear seized them in its grip and they were silent, all but Yuan Shao who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'The empire is in my hands;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'and when I choose to do this thing, who will dare say nay? Think you my sword lacks an edge?', 'context': ' cried Dong Zhuo, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'If your sword is sharp, mine is never blunt,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'You must not kill rashly while the business hangs in the balance.', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo was on the point of slaying Yuan Shao, but Li Ru checked him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Your nephew behaved improperly, but I pardon him for your sake; what think you of my scheme?', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo said to Imperial Guardian Yuan Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'What you think is right,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'If any one opposes the great scheme, he will be dealt with by military law,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao is fond of scheming, but he fails in decision and so is not to be feared. But it would be well to give him rank and thus win popular favor.', 'context': 'Wu Qiong said, “'},
{'istart': 198, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'The Emperor is a weakling unequal to the burden of ruling this land. Now listen ye to the document I have prepared.', 'context': 'On the first day of the ninth month, the Emperor was invited to proceed to the Hall of Virtue where was a great assembly of officials. There Dong Zhuo, sword in hand, faced the gathering and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'I pray the Prince of Chenliu to accept the throne in conformity with the decrees of Heaven and Earth, the desires of people, and the fulfillment of the hopes of humankind.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'So he shows his resentment by writing poems, eh! A fair excuse to put them all out of the way,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'If it be the wine of longevity, you may share it too,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'You will not drink?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'The cup, or these?', 'context': 'He called the men with daggers and cords and bade the Emperor look at them. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'And who may you be to die for a prince?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Let me say farewell to my mother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is awaiting my report,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Who told you to rebel?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 190, 'iend': 275, 'talk': 'This is my birthday, I pray you come to a little party in my humble cot this evening.', 'context': 'The letter arrived but Wang Yun could see no chance to plot against Dong Zhuo. One day while among the throng in attendance, mostly people of long service, Wang Yun said to his colleagues, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'We certainly will,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'and wish you long life.', 'context': ' they cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Sir, on your birthday too, why do you weep?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'It is not my birthday,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'If all the officers of the government weep till dawn, and from dawn weep till dark, will that slay Dong Zhuo?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Your forbears ate the bounty of the Hans; do you feel no gratitude? You can laugh?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'These later days,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 331, 'talk': 'I have bowed my head to Dong Zhuo with the sole desire of finding a chance to destroy him. Now he begins to trust me and so I can approach him sometimes. You have a sword with seven precious jewels which I would borrow, and I will go into his palace and kill him. I care not if I die for it.', 'context': ' Cao Cao continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'What good fortune for the world that this is so!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Where is the Prime Minister?', 'context': 'The next day Cao Cao, with this short sword girded on, came to the palace of the Prime Minister. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'In the small guest room,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Why so late, Cao Cao?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'My horse is out of condition and slow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Some good horses have come in from the west. You go and pick out a good one as a present for him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'This traitor is doomed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Now is the time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'What are you doing, Cao Cao?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Just as I was coming up, it seemed to me as if that fellow was going to stab you, only a sudden panic seized him and he presented the weapon instead.', 'context': 'Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'I suspected him too,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has no family here in the capital but lodges quite alone and not far away,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'Send for him. If he comes forthwith, the sword was meant as a gift; but if he makes any excuses, he had bad intentions. And you can arrest him.', 'context': ' said Li Ru. “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 320, 'talk': "Cao Cao had not returned to his lodging but rode in hot haste out of the eastern gate. To the gate commander's questions he replied that he was on a special message for the Prime Minister. He went off at full speed.", 'context': 'They sent four prison warders to call Cao Cao. They were absent a long time and then came back, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'His conscience pricked him and so he fled; there is no doubt that he meant assassination,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'And I trusted him so well!', 'context': ' said Li Ru. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'There must be a conspiracy afoot. When we catch him, we shall know all about it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'They say the Prime Minister treated you well; why did you try to harm him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'And where are you going?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Home to my county. Thence I shall issue a summons calling all the bold spirits to come with forces to kill the tyrant. This is my desire.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 256, 'iend': 438, 'talk': 'I am called Chen Gong. My aged mother and family are in the east county of Dongjun. I am deeply affected by your loyalty and uprightness, and I will abandon my office and follow you.', 'context': ' Thereupon the Magistrate himself loosened the bonds of the prisoner, led him to the upper seat, and bowed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 331, 'iend': 464, 'talk': 'There lives my uncle, Lu Boshe, a sworn−brother of my father. Suppose we go and ask news of my family and seek shelter for the night?', 'context': 'Cao Cao was delighted with this turn of affairs. Chen Gong at once collected some money for the expenses of their journey and gave Cao Cao a different dress. Then each took a sword and rode away toward Qiao. Three days later at eventide they reached Chenggao. Cao Cao pointed with his whip to a hamlet deep in the woods and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Excellent!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'I hear the government has sent stringent orders on all sides to arrest you. Your father has gone into hiding to Chenliu. How has this all come about?', 'context': 'Lu Boshe greeted them and said to Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Had it not been for this man here with me, I should have been already hacked to pieces.', 'context': 'Cao Cao told him and said, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'You are the salvation of the Cao family. But be at ease and rest, I will find you a bed in my humble cottage.', 'context': 'Lu Boshe bowed low to Chen Gong, saying, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'There is no good wine in the house. I am going over to the village to get some for you.', 'context': 'Lu Boshe then rose and went into the inner chamber where he stayed a long time. When he came out, he said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'He is not my real uncle; I am beginning to doubt the meaning of his going off. Let us listen.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said to Chen Gong, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Bind before killing, eh?', 'context': 'So they silently stepped out into a straw hut at the back. Presently some one said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'As I thought;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'now unless we strike first, we shall be taken.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'You have made a huge mistake,', 'context': 'After this they searched the house. In the kitchen they found a pig bound ready to kill. “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'and we have slain honest folks.', 'context': ' said Chen Gong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Why are you going, Sirs?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Accused people dare not linger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'But I have bidden them kill a pig! Why do you refuse my poor hospitality? I pray you ride back with me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Who is that coming along?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'You were wrong enough before,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'What now is this?', 'context': ' cried Chen Gong. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'To kill deliberately is very wrong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'I would rather betray the world than let the world betray me!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'I joined him to do righteous things. Now if I killed him, I would only do unrighteousness and the people would condemn me. I rather leave in silence.', 'context': 'At the close of the last chapter, Chen Gong was about to slay Cao Cao. But Chen Gong reflected, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'Chen Gong thinks me brutal because of a couple of egoistic phrases I used, and so he has gone. I ought to push on too and not linger here.', 'context': 'Cao Cao awoke with the day and missed his companion. Thought he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Our possessions are but small,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'and not enough to do anything with. However, there is a graduate here, one Wei Hong, careless of wealth but careful of virtue, whose family is very rich. With his help we might hope for success.', 'context': ' said his father, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 331, 'talk': 'The Hans have lost their lordship, and Dong Zhuo is really a tyrant. He flouts his prince and is cruel to the people, who gnash their teeth with rage. I would restore the Hans, but my means are insufficient. Sir, I appeal to your loyalty and public spirit.', 'context': 'A feast was prepared and Wei Hong was invited. Cao Cao made him a speech: “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'I have long desired this but, so far, have not found a person fit to undertake the task. Since you, Cao Cao, have so noble a desire, I willingly devote all my property to the cause.', 'context': 'Wei Hong replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Good brother, what do you here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'You were kind to me once, and on your recommendation I was made the magistrate of this county. I heard you were passing through and came to salute you. May I pray you, my elder brother, enter into the city and rest your steed?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Who are these two?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'These are Guan Yu and Zhang Fei, my sworn brothers.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Were they fighting with you against the Yellow Scarves rebels?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'All my success was due to their efforts,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'And what offices do they fill?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Guan Yu is a mounted archer; Zhang Fei is a foot archer.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Thus are able humans buried!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'I should like to go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'If you had let me kill him that other time, you would not have this trouble today,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Since things are so, let us pack and go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'We have been moved by a noble sense of right to assemble here. Now must we first choose a chief and bind ourselves to obedience.', 'context': 'Then spoke the Governor of Henei, Wang Kuang, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'For four generations the highest offices of state have been filled by members of the Yuan family, and its clients and supporters are everywhere. As a descendant of ancient ministers of Han, Yuan Shao is a suitable man to be our chief lord.', 'context': 'Then said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'It must be he; there is no other!', 'context': 'Yuan Shao again and again declined this honor. But they all said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'It behooves us all to obey the chief we have this day set up, and support the state. There must be no feeling of rivalry or superiority based upon numbers.', 'context': 'Presently Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'Unworthy as I am, yet as elected chief I must impartially reward merit and punish offenses. Let each see to it that he obeys the national laws and the army precepts. These must not be broken.', 'context': 'Yuan Shao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Only thy commands are to be obeyed!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'My brother, Yuan Shu, is appointed Chief of the Commissariat. He must see to it that the whole camp is well supplied. But the need of the moment is a van leader who shall go to River Si Pass and provoke a battle. The other forces must take up strategic positions in support.', 'context': 'Then Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'You are valiant and fierce, and equal to this service,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'Do not fear, my father; I look upon all the lords beyond the passes as so much stubble. And with the warriors of our fierce army, I will put every one of them to death and hang their heads at the gates of the capital.', 'context': 'Lu Bu stood forth and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'With your aid I can sleep secure,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'An ox−cleaver to kill a chicken! There is no need for the General to go; I will cut off their heads as easily as I would take a thing out of my pocket.', 'context': 'But some one behind Lu Bu broke in upon his speech saying, “'},
{'istart': 441, 'iend': 457, 'talk': 'Flee not, rebel!', 'context': 'Among the feudal lords, Bao Xin, the Lord of Jibei, was jealous lest the chosen Van Leader Sun Jian should win too great honors. Wherefore Bao Xin endeavored to meet the foe first, and so he secretly dispatched his brother, Bao Zhong, with three thousand by a bye road. As soon as this small force reached the Pass, they offered battle. Fast reacting, Hua Xiong at the head of five hundred armored horsemen swept down from the Pass crying, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Helpers of a villain! Be quick to surrender!', 'context': 'Sun Jian advanced to the Pass and hailed the defenders, crying, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 339, 'talk': 'This Sun Jian is a very tiger in the east. Should he take the capital and destroy Dong Zhuo, we should have a tiger in place of a wolf. Do not send him grain. Starve his troops and that will decide the fate of that army.', 'context': 'Sun Jian also sent an urgent message for supplies to the commissary. But a counselor said to the Controller Yuan Shu, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'We will launch tonight a speedy attack against Sun Jian in front and rear so that we can capture him.', 'context': 'Li Ru made a plot with Hua Xiong, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 130, 'talk': "My lord's purple turban is a mark that the rebels will too easily recognize. Give it to me and I will wear it.", 'context': 'Then spoke Zu Mao, “'},
{'istart': 214, 'iend': 467, 'talk': 'The brother of General Bao Xin, disobeying the rules we made for our guidance, rashly went to attack the enemy; he was slain and with him many of our soldiers. Now Sun Jian has been defeated. Thus our fighting spirit has suffered and what is to be done?', 'context': 'When news of the disaster reached Yuan Shao, he was greatly chagrined and called all the lords to a council. They assembled and Gongsun Zan was the last to arrive. When all were seated in the tent Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Who are those men behind you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'This is Liu Bei, Magistrate of Pingyuan and a brother of mine who shared my humble cottage when we were students.', 'context': 'Gongsun Zan told Liu Bei to come forward, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'It must be the Liu Bei who broke up the Yellow Scarves rebellion,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'It is he,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Since he is of the Han line, he should be seated,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'This consideration is not for your fame and office; I respect you as a scion of the imperial family.', 'context': 'Said Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Who dares go out to give battle?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I will go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'What a pity my two able generals, Yan Liang and Wen Chou, are not here! Then should we have some one who would not fear this Hua Xiong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 122, 'talk': "I will go, take Hua Xiong's head, and lay it before you here.", 'context': 'He had not finished when from the lower end a voice tolled, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Who is he?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'And what is he?', 'context': 'Gongsun Zan told them it was Guan Yu, brother of Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'He is in the train of Liu Bei as a mounted archer.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What! An insult to us all!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Have we no leader? How dare an archer speak thus before us? Let us beat him forth!', 'context': ' roared Yuan Shu from his place. “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'Peace, O Yuan Shu! Since this man speaks great words, he is certainly valiant. Let him try. If he fails, then we may reproach him.', 'context': 'But Cao Cao intervened. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Hua Xiong will laugh at us if we send a mere archer to fight him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'This man looks no common person. And how can the enemy know he is but a bowman?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'If I fail, then can you take my head,', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Pour it out,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'I shall return in a little space.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'We high officials are too meek and yielding. Here is the petty follower of a small magistrate daring to flaunt his prowess before us! Expel him from the tent, I say.', 'context': 'Again arose the angry voice of Yuan Shu, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Shall we consider the station of him who has done a great service?', 'context': 'But again Cao Cao interposed, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'If you hold a mere magistrate in such honor, then I simply withdraw,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Is a word enough to defeat a grand enterprise?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 457, 'talk': 'We have lost our best leader, and the rebel power has thereby become very great. Yuan Shao is at the head of this confederacy, and his uncle, Yuan Wei, is holder of the office of Imperial Guardianship. If those in the capital combine with those in the country, we may suffer. Therefore we must remove them. So I request you, Sir Prime Minister, to place yourself at the head of your army and break this confederation.', 'context': 'Li Ru summed up the situation, saying, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 125, 'talk': "The occupation of the Pass would cut our armies in two; therefore, must we oppose Dong Zhuo's army on the way.", 'context': 'Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Who dares go out to fight him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'No one can stand against the prowess of Lu Bu. Let us call up all the lords and evolve some good plan. If only Lu Bu were taken, Dong Zhuo could easily be killed.', 'context': 'The fighting then ceased, and after their return to camp another council met. Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Stay, O twice bastard!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I, Zhang Fei of Yan, await you.', 'context': ' roared he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Certainly there is Dong Zhuo,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 656, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo and I had no personal quarrel. Yet now I have thrown myself into the battle regardless of consequences, exposed my person to the risk of wounds and fought bloody battles to their bitter end. And why? That I might be the means of ridding my country of a rebel and—for the private advantage of your family. Yet you, heeding the slanderous tongue of certain counselor, formerly withheld the supplies absolutely necessary to me, and so I suffered defeat. How can you explain, General?', 'context': 'Thereupon Sun Jian with two trusty generals, Cheng Pu and Huang Gai, went over to the camp of Yuan Shu. Tracing figures on the ground with his staff, Sun Jian said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Some officer has come riding down from the Pass to see you, General; he is in the camp.', 'context': 'Then suddenly they told Sun Jian, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Wherefore come you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'You are the one person for whom my master has respect and admiration, and he sends me to arrange a matrimonial alliance between the two families. He wishes that his daughter may become the wife of your son.', 'context': 'Li Jue replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 401, 'talk': 'What! Dong Zhuo, that rebel and renegade, that subverter of the throne! I wish I could destroy his nine generations as a thank−offering to the empire! Think you I would be willing to have an alliance with such a family? I will not slay you as I ought, but go, and go quickly! Yield the Pass and I may spare your lives. If you delay, I will grind your bones to powder and make mincemeat of your flesh.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 536, 'talk': 'If you think out this couplet, it applies to the present juncture. Half the first line refers to the founder of the dynasty, Liu Bang the Supreme Ancestor, who became ruler in the western city of Changan, which was the capital during twelve reigns. The other half corresponds to Liu Xiu the Latter Han Founder who ruled from Luoyang, the eastern capital during twelve latter reigns. The revolution of the heavens brings us back to this starting moment. Thus if you remove to Changan, there will be no need for anxiety.', 'context': 'Li Ru continued, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Had you not spoken thus, I should not have understood!', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo was exceedingly pleased and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Do you oppose the state plans?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 350, 'talk': 'The East of the Pass is full of sedition, and all the empire is in rebellion. The city of Changan is protected by the Yaohan Mountains and the Hangu Pass. Moreover, it is near Longyou, whence can be easily brought timber, stone, brick, and building materials. In a month or so palaces can be erected. So an end to your wild words!', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'How can I stop to consider a few common people when my scheme affects the empire?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'We venture to try to dissuade you from moving the capital to Changan.', 'context': 'Said Zhou Bi, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'They used to say you two were supporters of Yuan Shao; now he has already turned traitor and you are of the same party.', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo replied, “'},
{'istart': 198, 'iend': 374, 'talk': 'We are short of money and food, and the rich people of Luoyang could be easily plundered. This is a good occasion to link them to the rebels and to confiscate their properties.', 'context': 'And without more ado he bade his guards take both outside the city and put them to death. The command to remove to the new capital immediately was issued. Speaking to Dong Zhuo, Li Ru pointed out, “'},
{'istart': 543, 'iend': 563, 'talk': 'Traitors and Rebels,', 'context': ' Dong Zhuo sent five thousand troops out to plunder and slay. They captured many thousand wealthy householders and, having stuck flags on their heads saying they were “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo has gone west; we ought to follow and attack his rear without loss of time; why do you remain inactive?', 'context': 'Cao Cao went to see Yuan Shao and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'All our colleagues are worn out, and there is nothing to be gained by attack,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 275, 'talk': 'This moment was most propitious in the utter confusion that reigned, palaces burned, the Emperor abducted, the whole world upset, and no one knowing whither to turn. The villain will soon be ended, and a single blow could exterminate Dong Zhuo. Why not pursue?', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Those unworthy ones cannot discuss worthy thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'As there is some danger of pursuit, it would be well to order the Governor of this place to lay an ambush outside the city. He is to let the pursuers pass and be ready to cut off their retreat, when our army beats them off. That will teach any others not to follow.', 'context': 'Li Ru said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Rebels, abductors, drovers of the people, where are you going?', 'context': 'Cao Cao rode forward, crying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Treacherous simpleton, what mad words are these?', 'context': 'Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'I am doomed, Good Brother; go and save yourself!', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'My lord, mount my horse quickly; I will go afoot,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 133, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'If those wretches come up, what then?', 'context': ' said Cao Hong. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'The world can do without Cao Hong, but not without you, my lord!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'If I live, I shall owe you my life,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'This is my fate;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'I am really doomed.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 328, 'iend': 345, 'talk': 'Hurt not my lord!', 'context': 'Cao Cao all wet pushed on. Dawn was near. They went on another ten miles and then sat down to rest under a precipice. Suddenly loud shouting was heard and a party of horse appeared. It was Governor Xu Rong who had forded the river higher up. Just at this moment Xiahou Dun and Xiahou Yuan, with several dozens men, came along. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': "The Emperor's star is dulled,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'No wonder a rebellious minister disturbs the state, the people sit in dust and ashes, and the capital is a waste.', 'context': ' said Sun Jian with a sigh. “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'There is a beam of colored light rising from a well.', 'context': 'Then a soldier pointing to the south said, “'},
{'istart': 587, 'iend': 670, 'talk': 'I have received the command from Heaven: may my time be always long and prosperous.', 'context': 'Sun Jian bade his people light torches and descend into the well. Soon they brought up the corpse of a woman, not in the least decayed although it had been there many days. She was dressed in palace clothing and from her neck hung an embroidered bag. Opening this a red box was found, with a golden lock, and when the box was opened, they saw a jade seal, square in shape, an inch each way. On it were delicately engraved five dragons intertwined. One corner had been broken off and repaired with gold. There were eight characters in the seal style of engraving which interpreted read, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 419, 'talk': "I heard this treasured seal had been lost during the trouble in the Palace when the Ten Regular Attendants hurried off the Emperor. It was missed on His Majesty's return. Now my lord has it and certainly will come to the imperial dignity. But you must not remain here in the north. Quickly go home—Changsha, south of the Great River ((Yangtze River))—where you can lay plans for the accomplishment of the great design.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Your words exactly accord with my thoughts,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Tomorrow I will make an excuse that I am unwell and get away.', 'context': ' said Sun Jian. “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'I am rather unwell and wish to return to Changsha.', 'context': 'Next morning Sun Jian came to take leave, saying , “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Whence these words?', 'context': 'This was a shock to Sun Jian, and he paled but said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'How could the seal get into my hands?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Where is the article out of the well?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I have it not; why harass me thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Quickly produce it, or it will be the worst for you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'After an oath like this we think he cannot have it.', 'context': 'The lords all said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'When you pulled that thing out of the well, was this man there?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You touch that soldier and it is an insult to me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 870, 'talk': "My object was for the public good, and all you gentlemen nobly supported me. My plan was to get Yuan Shao with his Henei troops to approach Mengching; and my force at Qiao to keep Chenggao; while the others of you to hold Suanzao, to close the passes of Huanyuan and Daigu, and to take possession of the granaries, to control the points of vantage, and thus to secure the Capital District. I planned for Yuan Shu with his Nanyang army to occupy the counties of Danshi and Xilin and go into Wu Pass to help the three supports. All were to fortify their positions and not fight. Advantage lay in an uncertain military force showing the empire's possibilities of dealing with the rebellion. Victory would have been ours at once. But then came delays and doubts and inaction, and the confidence of the people was lost, and I am ashamed.", 'context': 'During the feast Cao Cao said sadly, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'This Yuan Shao is an incapable, and things will turns chaotic. We would better go too.', 'context': 'Then Gongsun Zan said to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Why are you thus barring the road with armed troops?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': "Why do you, a servant of Han, secrete the Emperor's special seal? Leave it with me at once and you go free,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 179, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'Why did you, on the faith of a letter from Yuan Shao, try to coerce the chief of a neighboring region?', 'context': 'However, there arose the sound of gongs and drums on the hills behind, and there was Liu Biao in person with a large army. Sun Jian rode straight up to him and bowing low spoke, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'You have concealed the state jewel, and I want you to restore it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'If I have this thing, may I die a violent death!', 'context': " was Liu Biao's reply. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'If you want me to believe you, let me search your baggage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'What force have you that you dare come to flout me thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 227, 'iend': 355, 'talk': 'You are really the strongest power here about; why then depend upon another for food? Jizhou is rich and wide; why not seize it?', 'context': "Yuan Shao was in Henei. Being short of supplies, he sent to borrow from the Imperial Protector of Jizhou, Han Fu, whence he obtained the wherewithal to support his army. Then one of Yuan Shao's advisers, Peng Ji, said to him, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'I have no good plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 466, 'talk': 'Governor Gongsun Zan of Beiping is commanding a huge and strong army. If he came to attack us, we could not stand against him, especially if he had the help of Liu Bei and his brothers. At present, Yuan Shao is bolder than most, and he has many able and famous leaders under him. You cannot do better than ask him to assist in administering this region. Yuan Shao will certainly treat you with generosity, and you need have no fear from Gongsun Zan.', 'context': 'Xun Chang said, “'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 344, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao is a needy man with a hungry army and as dependent on us for existence as an infant in arms on its mother. Stop the flow of milk and the infant dies. Why should you hand the region over to him? It is nothing less than letting a tiger into the sheepfold.', 'context': 'But the commander of the palace, Geng Wu, remonstrated with his master, saying, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'I am one of the clients of the Yuan family, and I know the abilities of Yuan Shao, which is far better than mine. Why are you all so jealous? The ancients counseled yielding to the sage.', 'context': 'Han Fu replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Jizhou is lost!', 'context': 'Geng Wu sighed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'I want to see your elder brother himself. He and I have things to discuss,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'We are guards of Prime Minister Dong Zhuo,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 268, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'Renegade, how dared you mislead me?', 'context': 'Gongsun Zan brought up all his force to the attack. Learning the movement, Yuan Shao sent out his army, and they met at River Pan. They halted on opposite sides of the river, over which was a bridge. Gongsun Zan took his station on the bridge and cried to his enemy, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'Han Fu yielded place to me because he was unequal to the rule. What concern is it of yours?', 'context': 'Yuan Shao rode to the other end of the bridge and, pointing at Gongsun Zan, replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'Formerly you were regarded as loyal and public spirited, and we chose you chief of the confederacy. Now your deeds prove you cruel and base and wolf−hearted in behavior. How can you look the world in the face?', 'context': 'Gongsun Zan replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Who will capture him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 557, 'iend': 586, 'talk': 'Down! Dismount and surrender.', 'context': "where the two engaged. Ten bouts showed Gongsun Zan the terrible power of Wen Chou, and so he drew off. The enemy came on. Gongsun Zan took refuge within his formation, but Wen Chou cut his way in and rode this way and that, slaying right and left. The four best of Gongsun Zan's generals offered joint battle, but one fell under the first stroke of the doughty warrior, and the other three fled. Wen Chou followed clearing through to the rear of the army. Gongsun Zan made for the mountains. Wen Chou forced his horse to its utmost pace, crying hoarsely, “"},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 357, 'talk': 'My name is Zhao Yun from Changshan. I first served Yuan Shao; but when I saw that he was disloyal to his prince and careless of the welfare of the people, I left him and I was on my way to offer service to you. This meeting in this place is most unexpected.', 'context': 'Gongsun Zan hurried down the hill and asked the young fellow who he was. He bowed low and replied, “'},
{'istart': 378, 'iend': 396, 'talk': 'Commanding General', 'context': "In this fight Gongsun Zan employed his new adherent Zhao Yun for the first time and, as Gongsun Zan did not feel assured of Zhao Yun's good faith, put him in command of a company at the rear. The Van Leader was Yan Guang, and Gongsun Zan himself commanded the center. He took his place on horseback on the bridge beside an enormous red standard on which was displayed the word “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 7, 'talk': 'Ha ha!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Gongsun Zan is an incapable.', 'context': ' Yuan Shao laughed. “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Sir, take refuge in this empty building here.', 'context': 'Tian Feng then said to his master, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'If you had not come to our help, we should have been in very bad case.', 'context': 'After the usual greetings Gongsun Zan said, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'The two active leaders of today are Yuan Shao and Gongsun Zan, who are at grips at River Pan. Pretend you have an imperial command to make peace between them, and both will support you out of gratitude for your intervention.', 'context': 'His adviser, Li Ru, went to see his master and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Good!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I used to think Gongsun Zan a true hero, but 1 see now that he is no different from Yuan Shao. They are both alike.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun said with a sob, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'But you are now in his service; we shall surely meet again,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I cannot bear Liu Biao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'He certainly did bar my way home, and I may wait many years for my revenge if I let slip this chance.', 'context': ' said Sun Jian as he finished reading this letter. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You may not trust Yuan Shu; he is very deceitful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'I want revenge on my own part; what care I for his help?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 307, 'talk': 'Put General Huang Zu at the head of the Jiangxia army to make the first attack and you, Sir, support him with the forces from Xiangyang. Let Sun Jian come riding the rivers and straddling the lakes; what strength will he have left after arriving here?', 'context': 'Kuai Liang told him to be free from anxiety, and said, “'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 452, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo is the real ruler of the state, for the Emperor is a weakling. The whole country is in rebellion, every one is scrambling for territory. Our area is comparatively peaceful, and it is wrong to begin a war merely for the sake of a little resentment. I pray you, Brother, think before you start.', 'context': "As Sun Jian was leaving on this expedition, his brother Sun Jing with all his six sons stood in front of Sun Jian's steed and dissuaded him, saying, “"},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Brother, say no more. I desire to make my strength felt throughout the empire, and shall I not avenge my injuries?', 'context': 'Sun Jian replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Then father, if you must go, let me accompany you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'You swarm of rebels from Changsha! Why do you invade the land of a scion of the ruling house?', 'context': 'Flourishing his whip, Huang Zu abused his enemy, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Sun Jian was too strong for my army.', 'context': 'Huang Zu led his defeated troops back and told Liu Biao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'A stupid move,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'He is brother−in−law to Liu Biao; who will capture him?', 'context': 'up his battle line. Sun Jian led the invaders, now flushed with success. When Cai Mao approached, Sun Jian looked at him and said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Cai Mao ought to be put to death by military law. This defeat was due to his obstinacy.', 'context': 'Kuai Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Very inauspicious!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'We ought to go back.', 'context': ' said Han Dang. “'},
{'istart': 231, 'iend': 285, 'talk': 'There was a group of horsemen going out from the city.', 'context': 'Lu Gong having received these directions, prepared his force to carry them out. As soon as day began to close in, he went quietly out at the east gate. Sun Jian was in his tent when he heard shouting and a soldier came to report: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': "How can I return home leaving my father's corpse with them?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 136, 'talk': "We have Huang Zu as our prisoner. Let one enter the city and discuss peace, giving up our prisoner for our lord's body.", 'context': 'Huang Gai said, “'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'I am an old friend of Liu Biao. I volunteer to take the mission.', 'context': 'He had barely finished speaking when an officer in the army, Huan Jie, offered himself as messenger, saying, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 258, 'talk': "The body is already laid in a coffin and ready to be delivered as soon as Huang Zu returned. Let us both cease fighting and never again invade each other's territories.", 'context': 'Sun Ce agreed. So Huan Jie went and peace was discussed. Liu Biao told Huan Jie, saying, “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'No, no! Let me speak and I will see to it that not a single enemy can survive. I pray you first put this person to death and then to employ my means.', 'context': 'Huan Jie thanked him and took his leave. But as Huan Jie went down the steps, Kuai Liang suddenly broke in, saying, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'Sun Jian is now gone and his sons are but youths. Seize this moment of weakness to break into Changsha, and it is yours in one beat of the drum. If you return the corpse and make peace, you give them time to grow powerful, and evil will ensue to Jingzhou.', 'context': 'This is what Kuai Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'How can I leave Huang Zu in their hands?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Why not sacrifice this blundering warrior for a region?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'But he is my dear friend and to abandon him is wrong.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'An evil that pressed hard upon my heart has been removed!', 'context': 'Meanwhile, Dong Zhuo at Capital Changan, when he heard of the death of the turbulent Sun Jian, said, “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Imperial Rector,', 'context': 'From this time forward his arrogance and domineering spirit waxed worse and worse. He styled himself “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'He was always so. Take Minister Zhang Wen outside.', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo smiled and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Do not fear,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 250, 'talk': 'Minister Zhang Wen was in league with Yuan Shu to assassinate me. A letter he wrote fell by mistake into the hands of my son so I have had him put to death. You gentlemen, who have no reason, need have no fear.', 'context': ' said Dong Zhuo smiling. “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'What mischief are you up to there, you naughty girl?', 'context': 'After listening for some time, Wang Yun suddenly called out, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Would thy unworthy handmaid dare to do anything wrong?', 'context': 'The maiden dropped on her knees in terror, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Then what are you sighing about out here in the darkness?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'May thy handmaid speak from the bottom of her heart?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Tell me the whole truth; do not conceal anything.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Who would think that the fate of Han lay on your palm? Come with me!', 'context': 'A sudden idea came to Wang Yun, and he stuck the ground with his staff. And he said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'You can sympathize with the people of Han,', 'context': 'Said Wang Yun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'My lord, as thy handmaid said just now, use her in any way; thy handmaid will never shrink,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 826, 'talk': "The people are on the brink of destruction, the prince and his officers are in jeopardy, and you, you are the only savior. That wretch Dong Zhuo wants to depose the Emperor and not a person among us can find means to stop him. Now he has a son, a bold warrior it is true, but both father and son have a weakness for beauty, and I am going to use what I may call the 'chaining' plan. I shall first propose you in marriage to Lu Bu and then, after you are betrothed, I shall present you to Dong Zhuo, and you will take every opportunity to force them asunder and turn sway their countenances from each other, cause the son to kill his adopted father and so put an end to the great evil. Thus you may restore the altars of the land that it may live again. All this lies within your power; will you do it?", 'context': 'Wang Yun knelt, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Thy handmaid has promised not to recoil from death itself. You may use my poor self in any way, and I must do my best.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'But if this gets abroad then we are all lost!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Fear not;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'if thy handmaid does not show gratitude, may she perish beneath a myriad swords!', 'context': ' said she, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Thank you, thank you!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'I am but a simple officer in the palace of a minister; you are an exalted officer of state; why am I treated thus?', 'context': 'Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Let the child come in!', 'context': 'guest was very mellow, Wang Yun suddenly said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'My little child begs you, General, to take a cup or two. We all depend upon you, all our house.', 'context': 'Wang Yun feigning intoxication said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'I should like to present her to you as a handmaid; would you accept?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'If that is so, you may rely upon my abject gratitude,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'We will choose a propitious day ere long and send her to the palace.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'I would ask you to remain the night, but the Prime Minister might suspect something.', 'context': 'However the time came for the guest to leave, and Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'I wish that you would deign to come to dine at my lowly cottage; could your noble thought bend that way?', 'context': 'Some few days later when Wang Yun was at court and Lu Bu was absent, Wang Yun bowed low before Dong Zhuo and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Should you invite me, I would certainly hasten,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 153, 'talk': "The great Prime Minister's abundant virtue is as the high mountains; neither the ancient sages—Yi Yin and Duke Zhou—could attain thereto.", 'context': 'Said Wang Yun, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 475, 'talk': "From my youth up I have understood something of astrology and have been studying the aspect of the heavens. I read that the days of Han are numbered, and that the great Prime Minister's merits command the regard of all the world, as when King Shun succeeded King Yao, and King Yu continued the work of King Shun, all by the strength of their own merits, conforming to the mind of Heaven and the desire of people.", 'context': 'Here the host raised a goblet and drank to his guest, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'How dare I expect this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'From the days of old, those who walk in the way have replaced those who deviate therefrom; those who lack virtue have fallen before those who possess it. Can one escape fate?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'If indeed the decree of Heaven devolves on me; you shall be held the first in merit!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Excellent!', 'context': 'there happens to be in the house a little maid that might please you.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'Who is she?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'A singing girl; her name is Diao Chan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Then can she sing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Thy unworthy handmaid is twenty−one.', 'context': 'She replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'A perfect little fairy!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'How could I be grateful enough for such a kindness!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'She would be most fortunate if she could be your servant,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'You promised Diao Chan to me and now you have given her to the Prime Minister: what foolery is this?', 'context': 'Seeing Wang Yun, Lu Bu at once reined in, stopped, seized him by the sleeve, and said angrily, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'This is no place to talk; I pray you come to my house.', 'context': 'Wang Yun checked him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Why do you find fault with me, General?', 'context': 'After the usual exchange of polite greetings, Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 118, 'talk': "Somebody told me that you had sent Diao Chan to the Prime Minister's palace in a covered carriage: what does it mean?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 657, 'talk': "Of course you do not understand. Yesterday when I was at court, the Prime Minister told me he had something to talk to me about in my own house. So naturally I prepared for his coming, and while we were at dinner he said, 'I have heard something of a girl named Diao Chan whom you have promised to my son Lu Bu. I thought it was mere rumor so I wanted to ask if it was true. Beside I should like to see her.' I could not say no, so she came in and made her bow to the lord of lords. Then he said that it was a lucky day and he would take her away with him and betroth her to you. Just think, Sir: when the Prime Minister had come himself, could I stop him?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'You were not so very wrong;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'but for a time I had misunderstood you. I owe you an apology.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'The girl has a small trousseau, which I will send as soon as she has gone over to your dwelling.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Nothing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'If there is nothing, you may go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 449, 'iend': 481, 'talk': 'Dare you make love to my beauty?', 'context': "One day Lu Bu went to inquire after his father's health. Dong Zhuo was asleep, and Diao Chan was sitting at the head of his couch. Leaning forward she gazed at the visitor, with one hand pointed to her heart, the other at Dong Zhuo asleep, and her tears fell. Lu Bu felt heartbroken. Dong Zhuo drowsily opened his eyes; and seeing his son's gaze fixed on something behind him, he turned over and saw who it was. He angrily rebuked his son, saying, “"},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Never let him enter here again!', 'context': 'He told the servants to turn Lu Bu out, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Then what can I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Recall him tomorrow; treat him well; overwhelm him with gifts and fair words; and all will be well.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'I was irritable and hasty yesterday owing to my illness and I wronged you, I know. Forget it.', 'context': 'So Dong Zhuo did so. He sent for Lu Bu and was very gracious and said, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 607, 'talk': "Though I am not the Minister's real daughter, yet he treated me as his own child. The desire of my life was fulfilled when he plighted me to you. But oh! to think of the wickedness of the Prime Minister, stealing my poor self as he did. I suffered so much. I longed to die, only that I had not told you the real truth. So I lived on, bearing my shame as best as I could but feeling it mean still to live. Now that I have seen you, I can end it all. My poor sullied body is no longer fit to serve a hero. I can die before your eyes and so prove how true I am!", 'context': 'Tears were in her eyes as she came up and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I knew it; I always knew your heart,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Only we never had a chance to speak.', 'context': ' he sobbed. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'If I cannot be your wife in this life, I will in the ages to come,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'If I do not marry you in this life, I am no hero,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Every day is a year long. O pity me! Rescue me! My lord!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'If you fear the old thief so much, I shall never see another sunrise.', 'context': 'Diao Chan clung to his robe, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Give me a little time to think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'In the deep seclusion of the harem, I heard the stories of your prowess; you were the one man who excelled all others. Little did I think that you of all heroes would rest content under the dominion of another.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'What were you coming about?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 318, 'talk': 'Happening to be passing your gates, I heard that you had gone into your private garden to look for your adopted son. Then came Lu Bu running and crying out that you wanted to kill him, and I was coming in as fast as I could to intercede for him when I accidentally collided with you. I am very sorry. I deserve death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'The wretch! How could I bear to see him toying with my fair one? I will be the death of his yet.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 713, 'talk': "Your Graciousness is making a mistake. It is the 'plucked tassel' story over again. But if you remember the banquet of old time where all guests were to tear the tassels of their hats. In that banquet, King Zhuang of Chu made no fuss about the liberties taken with his queen, although the hat−tassel in her hand betrayed the culprit Jiang Xiong. His restraint stood him good stead, for the same Jiang Xiong saved his life when he was hemmed in by the soldiers of Qin. After all Diao Chan is only a handmaid, but Lu Bu is your trustiest friend and most dreaded commander. If you took this chance of making the girl over to him, your kindness would win his undying gratitude. I beg you, Sir, to think over it well.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'What you say is right. I must think over it.', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo hesitated a long time; he sat murmuring to himself. Presently he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'What were you doing there with Lu Bu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 512, 'talk': 'Thy handmaid was in the garden among the flowers, when he rushed in on me. I was frightened and ran away. He asked why I ran away from a son of the family and pursued me right to the pavilion, where you saw us. He had that halberd in his hand all the time. I felt he was a vicious man and would force me to his will, so I tried to throw myself into the lily pond, but he caught me in his arms and held me so that I was helpless. Luckily just at that moment you came and saved my life.', 'context': 'She began to weep, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Suppose I send you to him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I was only joking.', 'context': 'her hand and, throwing his arms about her, and cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'This is the doing of that Li Ru,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 197, 'talk': "He is much too thick with Lu Bu. He suggested that, I know. Little he cares for the Imperial Rector's reputation or my life. Oh! I could eat him alive.", 'context': ' said she. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Do you think I could bear to lose you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Though you love me yet I must not stay here. That Lu Bu will try to ruin me if I do. I fear him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'We will go to Meiwo tomorrow, you and I, and we will be happy together and have no cares.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'This is a propitious day,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'He and I standing in the relation of father and son. I cannot very well do that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'But I will say no more about his fault. You may tell him so and soothe him as well as you can.', 'context': ' said Dong Zhuo. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You are not being beguiled by the woman, are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'Would you like to give your wife to some body else? Do not talk about this any further. It would be better not to.', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo colored, saying, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'We are dead people, slain by the hand of this girl!', 'context': 'Li Ru left the chamber. When he got outside, he cast his eyes up to heaven, saying, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Why do you not accompany the Prime Minister, General, instead of standing here and sighing?', 'context': 'Suddenly a voice said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'I have been confined to the house by illness these few days,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 226, 'talk': 'so I have not seen you. But I had to struggle out today to see the Prime Minister set off. This meeting is most fortunate. But why were you sighing?', 'context': ' continued he, “'},
{'istart': 229, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Just on account of that daughter of yours,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'So long a time and yet not given to you!', 'context': 'Feigning great astonishment Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'The old ruffian has fallen in love with her himself.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Surely this cannot be true.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 159, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'I did not think he was such a beast.', 'context': 'Lu Bu related the whole story while Wang Yun listened, silent, but stamping on the ground as with irritation and perplexity. After a long time Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'Come to my house, and we will talk it over.', 'context': 'Taking Lu Bu by the hand, Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 415, 'talk': 'He seems to have corrupted my little girl and has stolen your wife. He will be an object of shame and ridicule to the whole world. And those who do not laugh at him will laugh at you and me. Alas! I am old and powerless and can do nothing. More pitied than blamed! But you, General, you are a warrior, the greatest hero in the world. Yet you have been put to this shame and exposed to this contempt.', 'context': 'Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 136, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'I forgot myself. I should not have spoken like that. Do not be so angry, I pray.', 'context': 'A wave of fierce wrath rolled up in Lu Bu. Banging the table he shouted and roared. His host ostentatiously tried to calm him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'I will kill the wretch, I swear it. In no other way can I wash away my shame.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'No, no! Do not say such a thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': "When one is born great, one cannot be patient for long under another person's domination,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'It needs some one greater than the Prime Minister to limit the scope of such talents as yours.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'I had been misled if you had not said that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'I have decided,', 'context': 'Lu Bu rose from his place and bowed to Wang Yun. “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'You need not fear, Sir.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'But yet you may fail and bring upon yourself misfortune,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'But who would dare to go?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'Li Su, General of the Imperial Tiger Army, would go. He belongs to the same region as Lu Bu and is very angry with the Prime Minister for not advancing him. His going would assure us the plan would be completed.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Let us see what Lu Bu thinks of it.', 'context': ' said Wang Yun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'If Li Su refuses this mission, I will kill him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 509, 'talk': 'Formerly you talked me into killing Ding Yuan and going over to Dong Zhuo. Now we find Dong Zhuo means evil for the Emperor and is an oppressor of the people. His iniquities are many, and he is hated by gods and humans. You go to Meiwo, say you have a command from the Emperor to summon the Prime Minister to the Palace. He will come, and he will be put to death. You will have the credit of being loyal and restoring the Hans. Will you undertake this?', 'context': 'So they sent for Li Su. When Li Su arrived, Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I also wish to slay him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'But I could not find anyone to assist me. How can I hesitate? Your intervention is directly from Heaven.', 'context': ' was the reply. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'If this succeeds, what glorious rank will be yours!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'His Majesty has recovered and wishes his ministers to meet him in the Palace to consider the question of his abdication in your favor. That is what this summons means.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'What does Wang Yun think of the scheme?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 150, 'talk': "Wang Yun has already begun the construction of the Terrace of Abdication and only awaits my lord's arrival.", 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Last night I dreamed a dragon coiled round my body,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'and now I get this happy tidings! I must not neglect the opportunity.', 'context': ' said Dong Zhuo greatly pleased, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'When I am Emperor, you shall be Commander of the Capital District,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Your minister thanks you,', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Whither are you going, my son?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I go to receive the abdication of Han; and soon you will be the Empress.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I have been feeling nervous and creepy these few days. It is a bad sign.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Any one about to become the Mother of the State must have premonitions,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'When I am Emperor, you shall be Lady of the Palace.', 'context': 'Just before starting, he said to Diao Chan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'It means that you are going to receive the abdication of the Hans, which is to renew all things, to mount the jeweled chariot and sit in the golden saddle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'What does this mean?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'You are ascending to the place of the dragon; there must be bright light and lurid vapor to dignify your majestic approach.', 'context': 'The wily Li Su had an interpretation for this also, saying, “'},
{'istart': 264, 'iend': 355, 'talk': 'When I sit on the throne, you shall command the whole armies of the empire, horse and foot,', 'context': 'Dong Zhuo had no more doubts. He presently arrived and found many officials waiting without the city gate to receive him, all but Li Ru who was ill and unable to leave his chamber. He entered and proceeded to his own palace, where Lu Bu came to congratulate him. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'What is the meaning of this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'He is a madman,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Why are they all armed?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'The rebel is here! Where are the executioners?', 'context': 'Suddenly Wang Yun shouted, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Where is Lu Bu?', 'context': 'had not put on the breastplate he usually wore, and a spear pierced his breast. He sank down in the carriage calling loudly for his son, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Here, and with a decree to deal with a rebel,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'father.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu, as he appeared in front of his “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'The decree was to slay the rebel Dong Zhuo; no other.', 'context': 'decree, crying, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Live forever! O Emperor.', 'context': ' The whole assembly shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo has been put to death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Every body is glad to be rid of him, and yet one is found to lament over him. Who is this?', 'context': ' said Wang Yun, angrily. “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo has been put to death as a rebel, and all the land rejoices. You, a Han minister, instead of rejoicing, weep for him. Why?', 'context': 'Wang Yun spoke to Cai Yong angrily, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 455, 'talk': 'I am without talent, yet know what is right. I am the man to turn my back on my country and toward Dong Zhuo. Yet once I experienced his kindness, and I could not help mourning for him. I know my fault is grave, but I pray you regard the reasons. If you will leave my head and only cut off my feet, you may use me to continue the History of Han, whereby I may have the good fortune to be allowed to expiate my fault.', 'context': 'Cai Yong confessed his fault, saying, “'},
{'istart': 175, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'Cai Yong is famous as a scholar, and he can write glorious history, and it is inadvisable to put to death a man renowned for rectitude without consideration.', 'context': 'All were sorry for Cai Yong, for he was a man of great talents, and they begged that he might be spared. The Imperial Guardian, Ma Midi, secretly interceded for him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 355, 'talk': 'Centuries ago, Emperor Wu spared Sima Qian and employed him on the annals, with the result that many slanderous stories have been handed down to us. This is a trying period of great perplexity, and we dare not let a specious fellow like this wield his pen in criticism of those about the court of a youthful prince and abuse us as he will.', 'context': 'Wang Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'Is Wang Yun then careless of the future? Worthy people are the mainstay of the state; laws are the canons of action. To destroy the mainstay and nullify the laws is to hasten destruction.', 'context': 'Remonstrance and appeal being vain, Ma Midi retired. But he said to his colleagues, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 161, 'talk': "Four of them were the chief instruments of Dong Zhuo's aggressions. Now though a general amnesty were proclaimed, these men should be excluded from its benefit,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 388, 'talk': 'If we throw away our arms and flee singly, then we shall fall easy victims to any village beadle who may seize us. Rather let us cajole the Shanxi people to throw in their lot with us and make a sudden onslaught on the capital and so avenge Dong Zhuo. If we succeed, we control the court and the empire. There will be enough time to run away if we fail.', 'context': 'Then their adviser, Jia Xu, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'They are a lot of rats,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'You have sullied my reputation as a warrior and destroyed our fighting spirit.', 'context': 'Li Su reported the defeat, and Lu Bu raged at him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is too doughty a fighter for us to hope to overcome him. Our case is hopeless. Our best course is to desert these four generals, secrete their valuables, and leave the army with just a few of our followers.', 'context': 'Hu Chier said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 504, 'talk': 'Lu Bu though brave in battle is no strategist and so not really formidable. I will lead my troops to hold the mouth of the gorge, and every day I will incite him to attack; and when he comes toward me, General Guo Si can smite his rear, after the manner of Peng Yue when he fought against Chu. While thus I am alternating attack and retreat, Generals Fan Chou and Zhang Ji will march off in different directions toward Changan. Such an attack at two points must end both Wang Yun and Lu Bu.', 'context': 'Li Jue said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'The case is desperate now. Ride with me to a place of safety.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 507, 'iend': 527, 'talk': 'Long life O Emperor!', 'context': 'Li Jue, Guo Si, and his fellow leaders gave full license to their ruffians, who robbed and murdered their fill. Many high officers perished. Ministers Chong Fu, Lu Kui, and Zhou Huan, Imperial Commanders Cui Lie and Wang Qi all died in the fighting. In time the rebels penetrated to the inner palace, and the courtiers begged the Emperor to proceed to the Gate of Pervading Peace to try to quell the rioting. At sight of the yellow umbrella, Li Jue and Fan Chou checked their armies, and they all shouted, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Nobles, what means it that you enter the capital in this unruly manner and without my summons?', 'context': 'The Emperor stood by the tower and addressed them, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 216, 'talk': "Dong Zhuo, Your Majesty's Prime Minister, has been slain by Wang Yun, and we are here to avenge him. We are no rebels, Sire. Let us only have Wang Yun, and we draw off our troops.", 'context': 'The two leaders looked up and said, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 288, 'talk': 'The plan was made for the benefit of the Throne; but as this evil has grown therefrom, Your Majesty will not grudge losing me. I have brought about evil, and I will go down to these rebels.', 'context': "Wang Yun was actually among the courtiers and at the Emperor's side. Hearing this demand he said, “"},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Wang Yun is here.', 'context': 'The Emperor was torn with sorrow and wavered. But the faithful minister leaped from the wall, crying, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'For what crime was our master slain?', 'context': 'The two leaders drew their swords, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'His crimes filled the heavens and covered the earth; no tongue can tell them. The day he died was a day of rejoicing in the whole city as you well know,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'And if he was guilty of some crime, what had we done not to be forgiven?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'Seditious rebels, why bandy words? I am ready to die.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 215, 'talk': "No; the people will not approve of his death now. Restore him to power, and get the leaguers inside Changan's control. Remove his supporters, and then we can compass his death. And the empire shall be in our hands.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Why do you still remain? You have slain Wang Yun; now withdraw these soldiers.', 'context': 'So they ceased the attack. The Emperor again spoke from the tower, saying, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Your servants desire rank us a reward for their good service to your dynasty.', 'context': 'Then Li Jue and Guo Si replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'And what rank, Sirs?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'This plan is bad. Give us ten thousand troops, and we will put an end to both of them and offer their heads before your ensign.', 'context': 'Li Meng and Wang Fang rose and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'To fight forthwith means defeat,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'If we fail, we are willing to lose our heads; but if we win, then your head is forfeit.', 'context': 'Li Meng and Wang Fang cried with one voice, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 287, 'talk': 'Seventy miles west of the capital stand the Zhouzhi Hills. The passes are narrow and difficult. Send Generals Zhang Ji and Fan Chou to occupy this point of vantage and fortify themselves so that they may support Li Meng and Wang Fang.', 'context': 'Jia Xu then suggested to Li Jue and Guo Si, saying, “'},
{'istart': 275, 'iend': 317, 'talk': 'Those are traitors; who will capture them?', 'context': 'The force from the west arrived; Ma Teng and Han Sui led out their troops to the attack. They found their opponents Li Meng and Wang Fang in battle array. Ma Teng and Han Sui rode to the front side by side. Pointing to the rebel leaders, the commanders abused them, crying, “'},
{'istart': 398, 'iend': 415, 'talk': 'You are followed!', 'context': "Though young he was a supreme valiance. Wang Fang, despising him on account of his youth, galloped forth to fight him. Before they had exchanged many passes Wang Fang was disabled and fell to a thrust of the young Ma Chao's spear. The victor turned to retire into the formation, but Li Meng rode after Ma Chao to avenge his fallen colleague. Ma Chao did not see Li Meng, but his father called out “"},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'You and I, Sir, are fellow villagers. Why then behave so unfriendly?', 'context': 'Fan Chou pursued the other army; and when he had come close, Han Sui rode boldly up and addressed him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I must obey the commands of my chief.', 'context': 'Fan Chou replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'I am here for the service of the state; why do you press me so hard?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 374, 'iend': 559, 'talk': 'The people are yet unsettled, it was dangerous to provoke another war. Instead, invite Fan Chou to a banquet and, while the feast was in progress, executing him for dereliction of duty.', 'context': 'At this Fan Chou turned his horse, called in his troops, and left Han Sui in peace. Unwittingly a nephew of Li Jue had been a witness of this scene; and when he saw the enemy allowed to go free, he returned and told his uncle. Angry that his enemy had escaped, Li Jue would have sent an army to wreak vengeance on his general, but his adviser Jia Xu again came in, saying, “'},
{'istart': 249, 'iend': 320, 'talk': 'Why have you been intriguing with Han Sui? You are turning traitor, eh?', 'context': 'This seemed good to Li Jue, so the banquet was prepared. Zhang Ji and Fan Chou accepted their invitations and went cheerfully. Toward the latter part of the entertainment a sudden change came over their host Li Jue, and he suddenly asked Fan Chou, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Fan Chou was a traitor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'and he has his deserts; you are my friend and need not fear.', 'context': ' said the host, raising Zhang Ji by the arm, “'},
{'istart': 332, 'iend': 427, 'talk': 'You want to destroy this horde of rebels; you will fail unless you get the services of Cao Cao.', 'context': 'However, a new trouble arose in the shape of a resurgence of Yellow Scarves in Qingzhou. They came, under numerous chieftains, in the number of hundreds of thousand and plundered any place they reached. Minister Zhu Jun said he knew of one who could destroy this sedition, and when asked who was the man he proposed, Zhu Jun said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'And where is he?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'He is Governor of Dongjun. He has a large army, and you have only to order him to act; the rising will be broken.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Xun Yu is my Zhang Liang.', 'context': 'Cao Cao rejoiced when he had won the elder Xun to his side, saying, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'There is a certain wise person of Yanzhou somewhere, but I do not know in whose service he is.', 'context': 'Xun Yu said to Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Who is he?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'Cheng Yu; he belongs to the eastern region of Yanzhou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Yes; I have heard of him,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I shall prove unworthy of your recommendation,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'for I am rough and ignorant. But have you forgotten a fellow villager of yours, Guo Jia? He is really able. Why not spread the net to catch him?', 'context': ' said Cheng Yu to his friend Xun Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I had nearly forgotten,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Who is he?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I see he is no ordinary man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'He is fine and straight and looks very powerful and bold.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'This is old E Lai again,', 'context': 'clear out and held the staff quite steady with one hand, keeping it perfectly upright in spite of the strong wind. “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 220, 'talk': "Tao Qian's people have slain my father: no longer can the same sky cover us. I will sweep Xuzhou off the face of the earth. Only thus can I satisfy my vengeance.", 'context': 'a great cry. They raised him. With set teeth he muttered, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 447, 'talk': "They say you go to avenge your father's death on Xuzhou, to destroy its people. I have come to say a word. Imperial Protector Tao Qian is humane and a good man. He is not looking out for his own advantage, careless of the means and of others. Your worthy father met his unhappy death at the hands of Zhang Kai. Tao Qian is guiltless. Still more innocent are the people, and to slay them would be an evil. I pray you think over it.", 'context': 'Chen Gong said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'You once abandoned me and now you have the impudence to come to see me! Tao Qian slew my whole family, and I will tear his heart out in revenge. I swear it. You may speak for your friend and say what you will. I shall be as if I heard not.', 'context': 'Cao Cao retorted angrily, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Alas! I cannot go to Tao Qian and look upon his face.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Vengeance', 'context': 'and rushed far and wide like snow. In their midst was a large white flag and on both sides was written “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 277, 'talk': 'I wished to make friends with you, Illustrious Sir, and so I sent Zhang Kai to escort your family. I knew not that his rebel heart was still unchanged. The fault does not lie at my door as you must see.', 'context': 'But Tao Qian advanced, and from beneath his ensign he bowed low and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'You old wretch, you killed my father and now you dare to mumble this nonsense,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'The force against us is too strong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 553, 'iend': 817, 'talk': 'I am the Goddess of Fire from the Southern Land. I am on my way to execute a decree of the Supreme God to burn your dwelling, but your extreme courtesy has so deeply touched me that I now warn you. Hasten homeward, remove your valuables, for I must arrive tonight.', 'context': 'It was one Mi Zhu who said he knew how to defeat Cao Cao utterly. Mi Zhu came of a wealthy family of merchants in Donghai and trading in Luoyang. One day traveling homeward from that city in a carriage, he met an exquisitely beautiful lady trudging along the road, who asked him to let her ride. He stopped and yielded his place to her. She invited him to share the seat with her. He mounted, but sat rigidly upright, never even glancing in her direction. They traveled thus for some miles when she thanked him and alighted. Just as she left she said, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'I will go to Beihai and beg Governor Kong Rong to help. Another should go to Qingzhou on a similar mission to get the help from Imperial Protector Tien Kai. If the armies of these two places march on Cao Cao, he will certainly retire.', 'context': 'The plan Mi Zhu proposed was this: “'},
{'istart': 355, 'iend': 395, 'talk': "I am Minister Li Ying's intimate friend,", 'context': 'Kong Rong was a native of Qufu in the old state of Lu. He was one of the twentieth generation in descent from the great Teacher Confucius. Kong Rong had been noted as a very intelligent lad, somewhat precocious. When ten years old he had gone to see Li Ying, the Governor of Henan, but the doorkeeper demurred to letting him in. But when Kong Rong said, “'},
{'istart': 544, 'iend': 704, 'talk': 'Of old my ancestor Confucius questioned your ancestor, the Taoist sage Laozi, concerning ceremonies. So our families have known each other for many generations.', 'context': ' he was admitted. Li Ying asked Kong Rong what relations had existed between their families that might justify the term intimate. The boy replied, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'He is a wonder, this boy,', 'context': 'Presently High Minister Chen Wei visited, to whom Li Ying told the story of his youthful guest. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'It does not follow that a clever boy grows up into a clever man.', 'context': 'Chen Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'By what you say, Sir, you were certainly one of the clever boys.', 'context': 'The lad took him up at once saying, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'The boy is going to be a noble vessel.', 'context': 'The minister adviser and the governor all laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Your master and I are good friends, and your presence here constrains me to go to his aid. However, I have no quarrel with Cao Cao either, so I will first write to him to try to make peace. If he refuses my offer, then I must set the army in motion.', 'context': 'Then said Kong Rong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Cao Cao will not listen to proposals of peace; he is too certain of his strength,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'And who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 338, 'iend': 352, 'talk': 'Open the gate!', 'context': 'The sight from the city wall was exceeding sad, for the rebels were there in enormous numbers. One day standing on the wall, Kong Rong saw afar a man armed with a spear riding hard in among the Yellow Scarves and scattering them before him like chaff before the wind. Before long the man had reached the foot of the wall and called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'My name is Taishi Ci, and I am from the county of Laihuang. I only returned home yesterday from the north to see my mother, and then I heard that your city was in danger from a rebel attack. My mother said you had been very kind to her and told me I should try to help. So I set out all alone and here I am.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Give me a thousand soldiers, and I will go out and drive off these fellows.', 'context': 'Presently said Taishi Ci, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'You are a bold warrior, but these are very numerous. It is a serious matter to go out among them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'My mother sent me because of your goodness to her. How shall I be able to look her in the face if I do not raise the siege? I would prefer to conquer or perish.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'I have heard Liu Bei is one of the heroes in the world; and if we could get his help, there would be no doubt of the result. But there is no one to send.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'I will go as soon as I have received your letter.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 493, 'talk': 'I am Taishi Ci, a fellow from Laihuang. I am not related by ties of kin to Kong Rong, nor even by ties of neighborhood, but I am by the bonds of sentiment and I share his sorrows and misfortunes. The Yellow Scarves have invested his city, and he is distressed with none to turn to, and destruction is very near. You are known as humane, righteous, and eager to help the distressed. Therefore at his command I have braved all dangers and fought my way through his enemies to pray you save him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'And does he know there is a Liu Bei in this world?', 'context': 'Liu Bei smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Imperial Protector Tao Qian is a kindly man of high character, and it is a pity that he should suffer this wrong for no fault of his own.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'You are a scion of the imperial family,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'and this Cao Cao is injuring the people, a strong man abusing his strength. Why not go with me to rescue the sufferers?', 'context': ' said Governor Kong Rong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I dare not refuse, but my force is weak and I must act cautiously,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'You surely will not break your promise?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'What manner of man think you that I am?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'Cao Cao and you are not enemies; why do you spend yourself for the sake of another?', 'context': 'Liu Bei went away to his friend Gongsun Zan and laid before Gongsun Zan his design to help Xuzhou. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'I have promised,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'and dare not break faith.', 'context': ' Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Also I wish to have the services of Zhao Yun,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'The enemy is very powerful, and Cao Cao handles his army skillfully. We must be cautious. Let us make most careful observations before we strike a blow.', 'context': 'Presently Liu Bei came up and went to see Kong Rong, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'What I fear is famine in the city,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'They cannot hold out very long. I will put my troops with yours under your command, while I with Zhang Fei make a dash through to see Tao Qian and consult with him.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 304, 'iend': 352, 'talk': 'You mad men from somewhere, where are you going?', 'context': "When Liu Bei and Zhang Fei leading one thousand troops made their dash to get through Cao Cao's army, they got as far as the flank of his camp when there arose a great beating of drums, and horse and foot rolled out like billows on the ocean. The leader was Yu Jin. He checked his steed and called out, “"},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'Liu Bei of Pingyuan,', 'context': 'From the city wall the besieged saw a huge banner embroidered in white “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'What does this mean?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'There is trouble on every side, and the kingly rule is no longer maintained. You, Sir, are a member of the family and eminently fitted to support them and their prerogatives. I am verging on senility, and I wish to retire in your favor. I pray you not to decline, and I will report my action to the court.', 'context': 'Tao Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 387, 'talk': 'Scion of the family I may be, but my merit is small and my virtue meager. I doubt my fitness even for my present post, and only a feeling of doing right sent me to your assistance. To hear such speech makes me doubt. Surely you think I came with greed in my heart. May God help me no more if I cherished such a thought.', 'context': 'Liu Bei started up from his seat and bowed before his host saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': "It is a poor old man's real sentiment,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'The enemies had reached the wall, and something must be done to drive them off. The present matter could await a more tranquil time.', 'context': 'In the midst of this came Mi Zhu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'I ought to write to Cao Cao to press him to raise the siege. If he refuses, we will attack forthwith.', 'context': 'Said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Who is this Liu Bei that he dares write and exhort me? Beside, he means to be satirical.', 'context': 'Cao Cao gave vent to a torrent of abuse: “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 382, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has come from afar to help Tao Qian, and he is trying the effect of politeness before resorting to arms. I pray you, my lord, reply with fair words that his heart may be lulled with a feeling of safety. Then attack with vigor and the city will fall.', 'context': 'Cao Cao issued orders to put the bearer of the letter to death and to press on the siege. But Guo Jia remonstrated, saying, “'},
{'istart': 172, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'Lu Bu has invaded Yanzhou, now holding Puyang. The three counties left—Juancheng, Fanxia, and Dongjun—are under severe attacks.', 'context': 'Cao Cao found this advice good, so he spared the messenger, telling him to wait to carry back his reply. While this was going on, a horseman came with news of misfortune: “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 455, 'talk': 'The rupture of the empire has begun, and warriors are seizing what they can. It is strange that you, with all the advantages of population and provisions you enjoy, do not strike for independence. Cao Cao has gone on an expedition against the east, leaving his own territory defenseless. Lu Bu is one of the fighting people of the day. If you and he together attacked and got Yanzhou, you could then proceed to the dominion.', 'context': 'Chen Gong said to Zhang Miao, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'If my own region be lost, I have no home to return to. I must do something at once.', 'context': 'Cao Cao was greatly disturbed by this and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'The best thing would be to become friends with Liu Bei at any cost and return to Yanzhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 213, 'iend': 525, 'talk': 'I am old and feeble, and my two sons lack the ability to hold so important an office as this. The noble Liu Bei is a descendant of the imperial house. He is of lofty virtue and great talent. Let him then take over the rule of this region, and only too willingly I shall retire to have leisure to nurse my health.', 'context': 'At one of these, when the feasting was over, he proceeded with his wish of retirement in favor of Liu Bei. Placing Liu Bei in the seat of highest honor, Tao Qian bowed before him and then addressed the assembly, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'I came at the request of Governor Kong Rong, because it was the right thing to do. Xuzhou is saved; but if I take it, surely the world will say I am a wicked man.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'You may not refuse. The House of Han is falling; their realm is crumbling, and now is the time for doughty deeds and signal services. This is a fertile region, well populated and rich, and you are the man to rule over it.', 'context': 'Mi Zhu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'But I cannot accept,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Imperial Protector Tao Qian is a great sufferer,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'and cannot see to matters. You may not decline, Sir.', 'context': ' said Chen Deng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Brother, you should accept the offer thus made,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Why so much fuss?', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'We have not taken the place; it is he who wishes to give it you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'You all persuade me to do what is wrong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is very powerful, and he has Chen Gong as adviser. Yanzhou is as good as lost, with the exception of three counties which have been vigorously and desperately defended by Xun Yu and Cheng Yu.', 'context': 'In the meantime Cao Cao had marched toward his own region. Cao Ren met and told him, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'I own that Lu Bu is a bold fighter but nothing more; he has no craft. So we need not fear him seriously.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 175, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'I have long waited for opportunity to employ your skill; now I give you ten thousand soldiers, and you are to hold the city while I go forth to attack Cao Cao.', 'context': "Lu Bu, knowing of Cao Cao's return, called two of his subordinate generals, Xue Lan and Li Feng, to him and assigned to them the task of holding the city of Yanzhou, saying, “"},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'General, you are going away; whither?', 'context': 'They accepted. But Chen Gong, the strategist, came in hastily, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'I am going to camp my troops at Puyang, that vantage point.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'You are making a mistake,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 471, 'talk': 'The two you have chosen to defend this city are unequal to the task. For this expedition remember that about sixty miles due south, on the treacherous road to the Taishan Mountains, is a very advantageous position where you should place your best men in ambush. Cao Cao will hasten homeward by double marches when he hears what has happened; and if you strike when half his troops have gone past this point, you may seize him.', 'context': ' said Chen Gong. “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I am going to occupy Puyang and see what develops. How can you guess my big plan?', 'context': 'Said Lu Bu, “'},
{'istart': 183, 'iend': 351, 'talk': "We know all Lu Bu's dispositions. Xue Lan is keeping the city. Do you think Lu Bu has laid an ambush? I shall tell Cao Ren to besiege Yanzhou, and I shall go to Puyang.", 'context': 'Now when Cao Cao approached the dangerous part of the road near the Taishan Mountains, Guo Jia warned him to take care as there was doubtless an ambush. But Cao Cao laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'The enemy will be fatigued with long marches so attack quickly before they have time to recover.', 'context': "In Puyang, when Chen Gong heard of the enemy's approach he spoke, saying, “"},
{'istart': 189, 'iend': 338, 'talk': 'I, a single horseman, am afraid of none. I go and come as I will. Think you I fear this Cao Cao? Let him settle his camp; I will take him after that.', 'context': ' Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'You and I had no quarrel, why then did you invade my land?', 'context': 'The drums began their thunderous roll; and Cao Cao, pointing to his opponent, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'The empire of Han is the possession of all; what is your special claim?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 356, 'talk': "From the hill tops today I saw a camp of our enemies on the west of Puyang. They were but few men therein, and tonight after today's victory, it will not be defended. Let us attack; and if we can take the camp, we shall strike fear into the heart of Lu Bu. This is our best plan.", 'context': 'The day having gone against him, Cao Cao called a council, and Yu Jin said, “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'The western camp is importance point, and it might be attacked.', 'context': "In his camp Lu Bu was rejoicing for that day's victory, when Chen Gong reminded him, saying, “"},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 74, 'talk': "The enemy will not dare approach after today's defeat.", 'context': 'But Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is a very able commander,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'You must keep a good lookout for him lest he attack our weak spot.', 'context': ' replied Chen Gong. “'},
{'istart': 206, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'Who can save me?', 'context': "The fight became desperate. Cao Cao dashed at the enemy's array. The din was terrible. Arrows fell like pelting rain upon them, and they could make no headway. Cao Cao was desperate and cried out in fear, “"},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Fear not, my master.', 'context': 'Then from the crush dashed out Dian Wei with his double spears, crying, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'When the ruffians are at ten paces, call out to me.', 'context': 'battle−axes. Turning to his followers he said, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Ten paces!', 'context': "followed, and when they got near, Dian Wei's followers shouted, “"},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Five, then call!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Five paces!', 'context': 'Presently, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Cao Cao, you rebel, do not flee!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 603, 'talk': "In Puyang there is a rich, leading family, Tian by name, who number thousands, enough to populate a whole county in themselves. Make one of these people go to Cao Cao's camp with a pretended secret letter about Lu Bu's ferocity, and the hatred of the people, and their desire to be rid of him. End by saying that only Gao Shun is left to guard the city, and they would help any one who would come to save them. Thus our enemy Cao Cao will be inveigled into the city, and we will destroy him either by fire or ambush. His skill may be equal to encompassing the universe, but he will not escape.", 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 201, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'Rectitude', 'context': 'Coming soon after the defeat, when Cao Cao felt uncertain what step to take next, the secret letter was read with joy. It promised interior help and said the sign should be a white flag with the word “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Heaven is going to give me Puyang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is no strategist, but Chen Gong is full of guile; I fear treachery in this letter, and you must be careful. If you will go, then enter with only one third your army, leaving the others outside the city as a reserve.', 'context': 'So he rewarded the messenger very liberally and began to prepare for the expedition. Then came Liu Ye, saying, “'},
{'istart': 515, 'iend': 549, 'talk': 'We are clients of the Tian family,', 'context': 'That day, just about noon, the city gates opened, and two bodies of soldiers appeared as if to fight. Gao Shun was the front commander, and Hou Cheng the rear commander. Cao Cao told off his general, Dian Wei, to oppose them. Neither body, however, came on to full engagement but fell back into the city. By this move Dian Wei and his troops had been drawn close up to the drawbridge. From within the city several soldiers were seen taking any chance of confusion to escape and come outside. To Cao Cao they said, “'},
{'istart': 236, 'iend': 293, 'talk': 'My lord should stay outside the city; let us go in first.', 'context': 'be opened.” So Cao Cao ordered Xiahou Dun to march to the left and Cao Hong to the right. Cao Cao led the main army—together with Xiahou Yuan, Li Dian, and Yue Jin—into the city. Li Dian pressed upon his master the precaution, saying, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'If I do not go, who will advance?', 'context': 'But Cao Cao bade him be silent, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Where is our lord?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'I am looking for him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Quick! Get help from outside,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I will seek him.', 'context': ' shouted Dian Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'I have entered the city twice in search of him, but cannot find him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Let us go in together,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 457, 'iend': 474, 'talk': 'Where is Cao Cao?', 'context': 'When Cao Cao saw his sturdy protector Dian Wei cut his way out and disappear leaving him surrounded, he again made an attempt to reach the north gate. On the way, sharply outlined against the glow, he saw the figure of Lu Bu coming toward him with his trident halberd ready to kill. Cao Cao covered his face with his hand, whipped up his steed and galloped past. But Lu Bu came galloping up behind him and tapping him on the helmet with the halberd cried, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 94, 'talk': "There; on that dun! That's he.", 'context': 'Cao Cao turned and, pointing to a dun horse well ahead, cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': "I blundered into that fool's trap, but I will have my revenge,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Let us have a new plan soon,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Really a fine stratagem!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 136, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'strings', 'context': 'This year locusts suddenly appeared, and they consumed every green blade. There was a famine, and in the northeast grain rose to fifty “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 414, 'talk': "Cao Cao abandoned his attack on this place because of his enemy's seizure of Yanzhou; and now they are both keeping the peace solely because of the famine. But Cao Cao will surely renew the attack in the spring. When Liu Bei refused to allow you to vacate office in his favor, you were in full vigor. Now you are ill and weak, and you can make this a reason for retirement. He will not refuse again.", 'context': 'adviser said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'Sir, I asked you to come for the sole reason that I am dangerously ill and likely to die at any time. I look to you, Illustrious Sir, to consider the Hans and their empire as more important than anything else, and so to take over the symbols of office of this region, the commission and the seal, that I may close my eyes in peace.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'You have two sons, why not depute them to relieve you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Both lack the requisite talents. I trust you will instruct them after I have gone, but do not let them have the guidance of affairs.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'But I am unequal to so great a charge.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'I will recommend to you one who could assist you. He is Sun Qian from Beihai who could be appointed to some post.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'The noble Liu Bei here is the most prominent man of the time, and you should serve him well.', 'context': 'Turning to Mi Zhu, Tao Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'If you do not, we cannot live in pence,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 367, 'talk': "I have missed my revenge. This Liu Bei has simply stepped into command of the region without expending half an arrow; he sat still and attained his desire. But I will put him to death and then dig up Tao Qian's corpse in revenge for the death of my noble father.", 'context': 'The news of the events in Xuzhou duly reached the ears of Cao Cao, then in Juancheng. Said he, angrily, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 748, 'talk': 'Illustrious Sir, your Land Within the Pass and your Henei are Yanzhou and the Yellow River, which you had first, and which is of the utmost strategic point of the empire. If you undertake this expedition against Xuzhou leaving many troops here for defense, you will not accomplish your design; if you leave too few, Lu Bu will fall upon us. And finally if you lose this and fail to gain Xuzhou, whither will you retire? That region is not vacant. Although Tao Qian has gone, Liu Bei holds it; and since the people support him, they will fight to the death for him. To abandon this place for that is to exchange the great for the small, to barter the trunk for the branches, to leave safety and run into danger. I would implore you to reflect well.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'It is not a good plan to keep soldiers idle here during such scarcity.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 247, 'iend': 320, 'talk': 'I am He Man, the devil who shoots across the sky; who dare fight with me?', 'context': 'The following day the rebel Huang Shao himself led forth his army and made his battle array along a circle. A leader advanced on foot to offer combat. He wore a yellow turban on his head and a green robe. His weapon was an iron mace. He shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Are you also a Yellow Scarf?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'I have some hundreds of them prisoners in an enclosure here.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Why not bring them out?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'I will if you win this sword from my hand.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Why does the defeated leader venture forth again?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 796, 'talk': 'I am named Xu Chu. I am from Qiao. When the rebellion broke out, I and my relations of some hundreds built a stronghold within a rampart for protection. One day the robbers came, but I had stones ready for them. I told my relatives to keep on bringing them up to me and I threw them, hitting somebody every time I threw. This drove off the robbers. Another day they came and we were short of grain. So I agreed with them to an exchange of plow oxen against grain. They delivered the grain and were driving away the oxen when the beasts took fright and tore off to their pens. I seized two of oxen by the tail, one with each hand, and hauled them backwards a hundred or so paces. The robbers were so amazed that they thought no more about oxen but went their way. So they never troubled us again.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I have heard of your mighty exploits,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Will you join my army?', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'That is my strongest desire,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'With our soldiers fresh from victory the city will fall at a tap of the drum,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'General, you should not go out until the arrival of the other officers.', 'context': 'When they approached Puyang, Lu Bu wished to go out in person and alone to attack, but his adviser Chen Gong protested, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Whom do I fear?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'He is not the sort that one man can overcome,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Open the gates! Let me in!', 'context': 'But when the members of the Tian family saw him coming back beaten, they raised the drawbridge. Lu Bu shouted, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'We have gone over to Cao Cao.', 'context': 'But the Tians said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is a savage beast. If let alive, he will be a great danger. Hunt him down!', 'context': 'previous fault. However, Liu Ye said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'He fears an ambush in the wood,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'We will set up flags there and deceive him. There is a long embankment near the camp but behind it there is no water. There we will lay an ambush to fall upon Lu Bu when he comes to burn the wood.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'This Cao Cao is very crafty and full of wiles,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Do not act.', 'context': ' said the adviser. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'I will use fire this time and burn out his ambush,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'We would better leave,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'An empty city cannot be held.', 'context': ' said Chen Gong. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I have but small army,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'but still enough to break Cao Cao.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is too strong right now; seek some place where we can rest a time before trying.', 'context': 'Said Chen Gong, who was opposed to this course, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Suppose I went to Yuan Shao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Send first to make inquiries.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is a savage beast. If he gets possession of Yanzhou, he will certainly attempt to add this region to it. For your own safety you should help to crush him.', 'context': "Shao's advisers, Shen Pei, warned him, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Go over to Liu Bei, who has lately succeeded to Xuzhou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is a hero, and we will receive him with honor.', 'context': 'Hearing this, Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'He was a cruel, bloodthirsty beast.', 'context': 'But Mi Zhu was strongly against receiving him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'How would misfortune have been averted from Xuzhou if he had not attacked Yanzhou? He cannot be our enemy now that he comes seeking an asylum.', 'context': 'But Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Brother, your heart is really too good. Although it may be as you say, yet it would be well to prepare,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 596, 'talk': "After Wang Yun and I plotted to slay Dong Zhuo and my misfortune in the Li Jue and Guo Si's sedition, I drifted about from one place to another, and none of the nobles east of the Huashang Mountains seemed willing to receive me. When Cao Cao with wicked ambition invaded this region and you, Sir, came to its rescue, I aided you by attacking Yanzhou and thus diverting a portion of his force. I did not think then that I should be the victim of a vile plot and lose my leaders and my soldiers. But now if you will, I offer myself to you that we may together accomplish great designs.", 'context': 'Said Lu Bu, “'},
{'istart': 616, 'iend': 807, 'talk': 'When the late Tao Qian died, there was no one to administer Xuzhou, and so I assumed that task for a time. Now since you are here, General, it is most suitable that I step down in your favor.', 'context': ' Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'I may be something of a fighting man, but I could not rule a great region like this.', 'context': 'So Lu Bu put on a smile and said, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'The strong guest does not oppress his host. You need not fear, Lord Liu Bei.', 'context': 'Liu Bei repeated his offer. But Chen Gong said, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Good Younger Brother, you need not be so very modest.', 'context': 'Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'My poor brother talks wildly after he has been drinking. I hope you will not blame him.', 'context': 'Liu Bei hastily checked the impulsive one, and Guan Yu persuaded him to go away. Then Liu Bei apologized, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Lu Bu, you and I will fight that duel of three hundred bouts!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 518, 'iend': 731, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has two hundred thousand troops and many capable advisers and leaders; it would be well for the empire if he would lend his support to the imperial family and help to rid the government of this evil party.', 'context': 'That Cao Cao had subdued the east of the Huashang Mountains has been stated before. He memorialized the Throne and was rewarded with the title of General Who Exhibits Firm Virtue and Lord of Feiting. At this time the rebellious Li Jue was commanding the court, and he had made himself Regent Marshal, and his colleague Guo Si styled himself Grand Commander. Their conduct was abominable but no one dared to criticize them. Imperial Guardian Yang Biao and Minister Zhu Jun privately talked with Emperor Xian and said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'I am weary of the insults and contempt of these wretches and should be very glad to have them removed.', 'context': 'His Majesty wept, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'I have thought of a plan to estrange Li Jue and Guo Si and so make them destroy each other. Then Cao Cao could come and cleanse the court,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'How will you manage it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': "Guo Si's wife, Lady Qiong, is very jealous, and we can take advantage of her weakness to bring about a quarrel.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 197, 'iend': 447, 'talk': 'There is talk of secret liaison between the General, your husband, and the wife of Minister Li Jue. It is a great secret, but if Minister Li Jue knew it, he might try to harm your husband. I think you ought to have very little to do with that family.', 'context': "So Yang Biao received instruction to act, with a secret edict to support him. Yang Biao's wife, Lady Kai, made an excuse to visit Lady Qiong at her palace and, in the course of conversation, said “"},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'I have wondered why he has been sleeping away from home lately, but I did not think there was anything shameful connected with it. I should never have known if you had not spoken. I must put a stop to it.', 'context': 'Lady Qiong was surprised but said, “'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'This Li Jue is very deep, and one cannot fathom his designs. You two are not of equal rank, and if he made away with you, what would become of your poor handmaid?', 'context': 'Some days passed, and Guo Si was going over to the dwelling of Li Jue to a dinner. Lady Qiong did not wish him to go and she said, “'},
{'istart': 288, 'iend': 369, 'talk': 'It is unwise to consume things that come from outside. Let us try on a dog first.', 'context': "Guo Si paid no attention, and his wife could not prevail on him to stay at home. Late in the afternoon some presents arrived from Li Jue's palace, and Lady Qiong secretly put poison into the delicacies before she set them before her lord. Guo Si was going to taste at once but she said, “"},
{'istart': 320, 'iend': 466, 'talk': 'We did everything together and helped each other always. Now he wants to injure me. If I do not get in the first blow, I shall suffer some injury.', 'context': 'One day, at the close of business at court, Li Jue invited Guo Si to his palace. After Guo Si arrived home in the evening, rather the worse for too much wine, he was seized with a colic. His wife said she suspected poison and hastily administered an emetic, which relieved the pain. Guo Si began to feel angry, saying, “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'So Guo Si is doing so and so.', 'context': 'So Guo Si began to prepare his guards for any sudden emergency. This was told to Li Jue, and he in turn grew angry, saying, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'The court gets food morning and evening; why do they ask for more?', 'context': 'Li Jue angrily replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'I treated you well and why did you try to kill me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You call me rebel when I am guarding the Emperor?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You have abducted him; do you call that guarding?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Rest a while, O Commanders! For I have invited a party of officers to arrange a peace.', 'context': 'Then they saw Yang Biao come riding up to them, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'We came with good intentions,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'and we are treated like this.', 'context': ' they moaned, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Li Jue has run off with the Emperor; I have to have the officers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'What does it mean? One has the Emperor, the other his officers. What do you want?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Here are we two officers of the Throne, and we cannot help our lord. We have been born in vain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'That Jia Xu, although a friend of Li Jue, never seems to have lost the sense of loyalty to Your Majesty.', 'context': 'Yang Qi said to the Emperor, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Can you not pity the Hans and help me?', 'context': 'Soon after Jia Xu himself arrived. The Emperor sent away his attendants and said to Jia Xu, weeping the while, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'That is my dearest wish. But, Sire, say no more; let thy servant work out a plan.', 'context': 'Jia Xu prostrated himself, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'Guo Si has failed in his duty and imprisoned the court officers. He wished to slay Your Majesty, and you would have been captured but for me.', 'context': 'Then Li Jue spoke, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'I would release the officers if Li Jue would restore the Emperor to full liberty.', 'context': 'Huangfu Li accepted the mission and first went to Guo Si, who said, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'Since I am a Xiliang man, the Emperor and the officers have selected me to make peace between you and your adversary. Guo Si has consented to cease the quarrel; will you agree to peace?', 'context': 'Huangfu Li then went to the other side. To Li Jue he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 336, 'talk': 'I overthrew Lu Bu; I have upheld the government for four years and have many great services to my credit as all the world knows. That other fellow, that horse−thief, has dared to seize the officers of state and to set himself up against me. I have sworn to slay him. Look around you. Do you not think my army large enough to break him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'It does not follow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Did the Son of Heaven send you to mock and shame me?', 'context': 'Li Jue angrily drew his sword and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Guo Si is still alive,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 180, 'talk': "Li Jue will not obey the Emperor's command. He will kill his prince to set up himself.", 'context': 'Huangfu Li would not be satisfied with failure. As he went out of the camp, he cried loudly, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Do not utter such words. You will only bring hurt upon yourself.', 'context': "Counselor Hu Miao tried to shut Huangfu Li's mouth, saying, “"},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'You also are an officer of state, and yet you even back up the rebel. When the prince is put to shame, the minister dies. That is our code. If it be my lot to suffer death at the hands of Li Jue, so be it!', 'context': 'But Huangfu Li shrieked at him also, saying, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'The Son of Heaven knows you are loyal to him and have bravely fought and suffered. He has issued a secret command for you to go home, and then he will reward you.', 'context': 'Jia Xu tried to work on the feelings of the barbarian tribes. He said to them, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Li Jue is covetous in nature. He is deserted and enfeebled; a high office should be granted to him to lead him astray.', 'context': 'Then Jia Xu advised the Emperor, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'We have taken all the risks and exposed ourselves to stones and arrows in his service, yet instead of giving us any reward he ascribes all the credit to those witches of his.', 'context': 'But his army was forgotten. Wherefore his commander, Yang Feng, was angry; and he said to General Song Guo, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Let us put him out of the way and rescue the Emperor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'You explode a bomb within as signal and I will attack from outside.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I have longed to go back to the east.', 'context': 'The Emperor was delighted, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Who comes?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'The Imperial Chariot is passing, and who dares stop it?', 'context': ' cried a voice. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'General Guo Si has ordered us to guard the bridge and stop all spies. You say the Emperor is here; we must see him, and then we will let you pass.', 'context': 'Two leaders of the barring party advanced to Yang Qi, saying, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'I, the Emperor, am here. Why do you not retire to let me pass, Gentlemen?', 'context': 'So the pearl curtain was raised and the Emperor said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Long Life! Long Life!', 'context': 'They all shouted, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'I meant to outwit Zhang Ji, seize the Emperor, and hold him in Meiwo. Why have you let him get away?', 'context': 'But when they reported what they had done, Guo Si was very angry, saying, “'},
{'istart': 201, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'Stop the train!', 'context': 'He put the two officers to death, set out to pursue the cavalcade, and overtook it just at the county of Huaying. The noise of a great shouting arose behind the travelers, and a loud voice commanded, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': "Out of the wolf's den into the tiger's mouth!", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'Han General Yang Feng', 'context': 'heard the beating of drums and from behind some hills came into the open a cohort of one thousand soldiers preceded by a great flag bearing the name “'},
{'istart': 315, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'Where is Xu Huang?', 'context': "Having defeated by Li Jue, Yang Feng fled to the foothills of the Xian; and he came up to offer his services as soon as he heard the Emperor's journey. Seeing it was necessary to fight now, he drew up his line of battle. Guo Si's general, Cui Yong, rode out and began a volley of abuse. Yang Feng turned and said, “"},
{'istart': 338, 'iend': 402, 'talk': 'It is a great service you have rendered; you have saved my life.', 'context': 'In response out came a valiant warrior gripping a heavy battle−ax. He galloped up on his fleet bay, making directly for Cui Yong, whom he felled at the first blow. At this the whole force dashed forward and routed Guo Si. The defeated army went back some seven miles, while Yang Feng rode forward to see the Emperor who graciously said, “'},
{'istart': 173, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'Xu Huang of Hedong.', 'context': 'Yang Feng bowed and thanked him, and the Emperor asked to see the actual slayer of the rebel leader. So Xu Huang was led to the chariot where he bowed and was presented as “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'State Uncle.', 'context': 'When they had time to see their helper, they found him to be Dong Cheng, the uncle of the Emperor or the “'},
{'istart': 194, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'Be of good courage, Sire. General Yang Feng and I have pledged ourselves to kill both the rebels Li Jue and Guo Si and so purify the world.', 'context': ' The Emperor wept as he related his sorrows and dangers. Said Dong Cheng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'If they reach the Huashang Mountains and get settled in the east, they will send out proclamations to the whole country, calling up the nobles to attack us and we and our families will be in danger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'Zhang Ji is holding Changan, and we must be careful. There is nothing to prevent a joint attack on Hongnong, when we can kill the Emperor and divide the empire between us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 439, 'iend': 450, 'talk': 'Dare−to−Die', 'context': 'These three, being promised pardon for their faults and crimes and a grant of official rank, naturally responded to the call, and thus the loyal side was strengthened so that Hongnong was recaptured. But meanwhile Li Jue and Guo Si laid waste whatever place they reached, slaying the aged and weakly, forcing the strong to join their ranks. When going into a fight they forced these people−soldiers to the front, and they called them the “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'The danger is grave. I pray Your Majesty mount a horse and go in advance.', 'context': 'Li Yue said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I cannot bear to abandon my officers.', 'context': 'The Emperor replied, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'The rebels have confidence in my words. You stay as guard of the Emperor, and I will take my life in my hands and try to bring about peace.', 'context': 'Said Han Rong to his colleague, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Luoyang is the original capital as opposed to the paltry town of Anyi. Removal would be but reasonable.', 'context': 'Dong Cheng argued, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'You may get the court to remove, but I shall remain here.', 'context': 'Li Yue wound up by saying, “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Stop those carriages! Li Jue and Guo Si are here.', 'context': 'About the fourth watch, just as the cavalcade was passing Zhiguan Hills, a voice was heard shouting, “'},
{'istart': 286, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'palace', 'context': 'Capital Luoyang was presently entered. Within the walls all was destruction. The palaces and halls had been burned, the streets were overgrown with grass and brambles and obstructed by heaps of ruins. The palaces and courts were represented by broken roofs and toppling walls. A small “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'There was no need to refer to the matter again. Send a messenger when you will.', 'context': 'The Emperor replied, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 538, 'talk': 'Eight hundred years ago, Lord Wen of Yin supported Prince Xiang of the declining Shang Dynasty, and all the feudal lords backed Lord Wen. The Founder of the Hans, Liu Bang, won the popular favor by wearing mourning for Emperor Yi of Qin. Now Emperor Xian has been a fugitive on the dusty roads. To take the lead in offering an army to restore him to honor is to have an unrivaled opportunity to win universal regard. But you must act quickly or some one will get in before you.', 'context': 'Xun Yu laid the matter before Cao Cao and the council thus: “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'What can be done? There is no answer from the East of Huashang, and our enemies are near.', 'context': 'The frightened Emperor spoke with Yang Feng, saying, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'We, your ministers, will fight to the death for you.', 'context': 'Then Yang Feng and Han Xian said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'The fortifications are weak and our military resources small, so that we cannot hope for victory, and what does defeat mean? I see nothing better to propose than a move into the east of Huashang Mountains.', 'context': 'But Dong Cheng said, “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 364, 'talk': 'General Cao Cao, as commanded, is coming with all the military force of the East of Huashang; but hearing that Li Jue and Guo Si had again approached the capital, he has sent Xiahou Dun in advance. With Xiahou Dun are many capable leaders and fifty thousand of proved soldiers. They will guard Your Majesty.', 'context': 'He rode up to the chariot, made an obeisance, and said, “'},
{'istart': 139, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'When my brother, Cao Cao, heard of the approach of the rebels, he feared that the advance guard he had sent might be too weak, so he sent me to march quickly for reinforcement.', 'context': 'In a short time Cao Hong, Li Dian, and Yue Jin came to the imperial chariot and their names having been duly communicated. Cao Hong said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'General Cao Cao is indeed a trusty servant!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 232, 'iend': 585, 'talk': 'Having been the recipient of great bounty, thy servant owes the state much gratitude. The measure of evil of the two rebels is full, I have two hundred thousand of good soldiers to oppose them, and those soldiers are fully equal to securing the safety of Your Majesty and the Throne. The preservation of the state sacrifice is the matter of real moment.', 'context': 'Next day Cao Cao came with his great army, and having got them duly camped he went into the city to audience. He knelt at the foot of the steps, but was called up hither to stand beside the Emperor and be thanked. Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 153, 'iend': 262, 'talk': 'There was no hope of victory. He has both strong soldiers and brave leaders. Submission may bring us amnesty.', 'context': "The two rebels, Li Jue and Guo Si, wished to attack Cao Cao's army while fatigued from its long march. But their adviser, Jia Xu, opposed this, saying, “"},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Do you wish to dishearten the army?', 'context': 'Li Jue was angry at the suggestion, crying, “'},
{'istart': 335, 'iend': 362, 'talk': 'You are really my Fan Kuai!', 'context': "Then Li Xian and Li Bie, nephews of Li Jue, rode out. At once from Cao Cao's side dashed out Xu Chu and cut down Li Xian. Li Bie was so startled that he fell out of the saddle. He too was slain. The victor Xu Chu rode back to his own side with the two heads. When he offered them to the chief, Cao Cao patted him on the back, crying, “"},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'This Cao Cao has done a great service, and he will be the man in power. There will be no place for us.', 'context': "Cao Cao's army returned and camped again near the capital. Then Yang Feng and Han Xian said one to another, “"},
{'istart': 250, 'iend': 301, 'talk': 'You look plump and well, Sir, how do you manage it?', 'context': 'One day the Emperor sent to summon Cao Cao to audience. The messenger was called in. Cao Cao noticed that the messenger looked remarkably well and could not understand it seeing that everyone else looked hungry and famine stricken. So Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Only this; I have lived meager for thirty years.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'What office do you hold?', 'context': ' Cao Cao nodded, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'I am a graduate recommended for filial piety and honesty. I had offices under Yuan Shao and Zhang Yang, but came here when the Emperor returned. Now I am one of the secretaries. I am a native of Dingtao, and my name is Dong Zhao.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 289, 'iend': 337, 'talk': 'I have heard of you. How happy I am to meet you!', 'context': ' Cao Cao got up from his place and crossed over, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'They are old leaders under the rebels, Yang Feng and the White Wave General Han Xian. They are running off because you have come, Illustrious Sir!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Do they mistrust me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'They are not worthy of your attention. They are a poor lot.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'What of this departure of Li Jue and Guo Si?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Tigers without claws, birds without wings—they will not escape you very long. They are not worth thinking about.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 725, 'talk': 'You, Illustrious Sir, with your noble army have swept away rebellion and have become the mainstay of the Throne, an achievement worthy of the ancient Five Protectors. But the officials will look at it in very different ways and not all favorably to you. I think you would not be wise to remain here, and I advise a change of capital to Xuchang. However, it must be remembered that the restoration of the capital has been published far and wide and the attention of all the people is concentrated on Luoyang, hoping for a period of rest and tranquillity. Another move will displease many. However, the performance of extraordinary deed may mean the acquisition of extraordinary merit. It is for you to decide.', 'context': 'Said Dong Zhao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Exactly my own inclination!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'But are there not dangers? Yang Feng at Daliang and the court officials!', 'context': " said Cao Cao, seizing his guest's hand. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'That is easily managed. Write to Yang Feng and set his mind at rest. Then say to the high officials plainly that there is no food in the capital here, and so you are going to another place where there is, and where there is no danger of scarcity. When they hear it they will approve.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I shall need your advice in future affairs.', 'context': 'Cao Cao had now decided; and as his guest took leave, Cao Cao seized his hands once more, saying, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'The capital is deserted and cannot be restored nor can it be supplied easily with food. Xuchang is a noble city, resourceful and close to Luyang, a grain basin. It is everything that a capital should be. I venture to request that the court move thither.', 'context': 'Next day at court he said, “'},
{'istart': 420, 'iend': 457, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is stealing away the Emperor!', 'context': 'The Emperor dared not oppose and the officials were too overawed to have any independent opinion, so they chose a day to set out. Cao Cao commanded the escort, and the officials all followed. When they had traveled a few stages they saw before them a high mound and from behind this there arose the beating of drums. Then Yang Feng and Han Xian came out and barred the way. In front of all stood Xu Huang, who shouted, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'The two rebels themselves need not be discussed; but Xu Huang is a fine general, and I was unwilling to use any great force against him. I want to win him over to our side.', 'context': 'In the camp a council was called. Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 235, 'talk': "Do not let that trouble you; I will have a word with him. I shall disguise myself as a soldier this evening and steal over to the enemy's camp to talk to him. I shall incline his heart toward you.", 'context': 'Then stepped out Man Chong, replying, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'You have been well since we parted, old friend?', 'context': 'Suddenly Man Chong ran out in front and saluted, saying, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'What! You are Man Chong of Shanyang? What are you doing here?', 'context': 'Xu Huang jumped up in surprise, gazed into the face of the speaker a long time and presently said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 189, 'talk': "I am an officer in General Cao Cao's army. Seeing my old friend out in front of the army today, I wanted to say a word to him. So I took the risk of stealing in this evening and here I am.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 565, 'talk': 'There are very few as bold as you on the earth; why then do you serve such as your present chiefs, Yang Feng and Han Xian? My master is the most prominent man in the world—a man who delights in wise people and appreciates soldiers as every one knows. Your valor today won his entire admiration, and so he took care that the attack was not vigorous enough to sacrifice you. Now he has sent me to invite you to join him. Will you not leave darkness for light and help him in his magnificent task?', 'context': 'Xu Huang invited Man Chong in and they sat down. Then said Man Chong, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'I know my masters are doomed to failure, but I have followed their fortunes a long time and do not like to leave them.', 'context': 'Xu Huang sat a long time pondering over the offer. Then he said, with a sigh, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'But you know the prudent bird selects its tree, and the wise servant chooses his master. When one meets a worthy master and lets him go, one is very reckless.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I am willing to do what you say,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Why not put these two to death as an introductory gift?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'It is very wrong for a servant to slay his master. I will not do that.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'True; you are really a good man.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Betrayer! Stop there!', 'context': 'As they drew close, Yang Feng called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'I have been waiting here a long time; do not run away,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has his army at Xuzhou, and he carries on the administration of the region. Lu Bu fled to Liu Bei when defeated, and Liu Bei gave Lu Bu Xiaopei to live in. If these two agreed to join forces and attack, my position would be most serious. What precautions can be taken?', 'context': 'Then Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Give me fifty thousand of picked soldiers, and I will give the Prime Minister both their heads.', 'context': 'Then rose Xu Chu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 709, 'talk': "O Leader, you are brave, but we must consider the present circumstance. We cannot start sudden war just as the capital has been changed. However, there is a certain ruse known as 'Rival Tigers and One Prey.' Liu Bei has no decree authorizing him to govern the region. You, Sir Prime Minister, can procure one for him, and when sending it, and so conferring upon him right in addition to his might, you can enclose a private note telling him to get rid of Lu Bu. If he does, then he will have lost a vigorous warrior from his side, and he could be dealt with as occasions serve. Should he fail, then Lu Bu will slay him. This is 'Rival Tigers and One Prey' ruse; they wrangle and bite each other.", 'context': 'Xun Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'This decree was obtained for you by Prime Minister Cao Cao.', 'context': 'The messenger said, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'This matter can be easily arranged.', 'context': 'Liu Bei thanked him. Then the messenger drew forth his secret letter. After reading it, Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'There need be no compunction about putting him to death;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is a bad man.', 'context': ' said Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'But he came to me for protection in his weakness; how can I put him to death? That would be immoral,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'If he was a good man; it would be difficult,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'I have come to felicitate you on the receipt of the imperial bounty.', 'context': 'Liu Bei would not consent. Next day, when Lu Bu came to offer congratulations, he was received as usual. He said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Why do you wish to slay me, Zhang Fei?', 'context': 'Lu Bu was surprised and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Cao Cao says you are immoral and tells my brother to kill you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 98, 'talk': "This is that miscreant's scheme for sowing discord between us.", 'context': 'Lu Bu wept as he finished reading, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Be not anxious, Elder Brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'I pledge myself not to be guilty of such an infamous crime.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Why not kill him?', 'context': 'Said Guan Yu and Zhang Fei later, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Because Cao Cao fears that Lu Bu and I may attack him, he is trying to separate us and get us to swallow each other, while he steps in and takes the advantage. Is there any other reason?', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'I want to get him out of the way lest he trouble us later.', 'context': 'Guan Yu nodded assent, but Zhang Fei said, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'That is not what a noble man should do,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'The plan has failed; what next?', 'context': 'Then said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 115, 'talk': "I have another trick called 'Tiger against Wolf' in which the tiger is made to gobble up the wolf.", 'context': 'Xun Yu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Let us hear it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'It may be,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'but the royal command is not to be disobeyed.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'A trusty man must be left on guard of the city.', 'context': 'Sun Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I will guard the city,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'I am constantly in need of your advice, so how can we part?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I will guard the city,', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'You will fail,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 200, 'talk': "After one of your drinking bouts you will get savage and flog the soldiers. Beside you are rash and will not listen to any one's advice. I shall be uneasy all the time.", 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Henceforth I drink no more wine. I will not beat the soldiers and I will always listen to advice,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'I fear the mouth does not correspond to the heart,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 170, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'Liu Bei, you rustic bumpkin, how dare you invade this land?', 'context': 'Ji Ling was a native of the East of Huashang. He used a very heavy three−edged sword. After he had made his camp, he rode out and began abusing his opponents, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I have a decree ordering me to destroy the Governor who behaves improperly. If you oppose, you will be assuredly punished,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Fool, do not attempt to fight!', 'context': 'But Guan Yu cried, “'},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'Tell Ji Ling to come; I must settle with him who shall be tiger and who shall be deer.', 'context': 'When the moment came to renew the combat, Ji Ling sent out one of his officers, Xun Zheng, to take his place. But Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'You, a reputationless leader and unworthy to fight with our general,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 352, 'iend': 566, 'talk': 'Before my brother left, he bade me keep clear of the wine cup for fear of accidents. Now, gentlemen, you may drink deep today; but from tomorrow wine is forbidden, for we must keep the city safe. So take your fill.', 'context': 'In Xuzhou, after Liu Bei had started on his expedition, Zhang Fei placed his colleague and helper, Chen Deng, in charge of the administration of the region, keeping military affairs under his own supervision. After thinking over the matter or some time, he gave a banquet to all the military officers; and when they were all seated, he made a speech: “'},
{'istart': 118, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'I never drink as I am forbidden of heaven.', 'context': 'And with this he and all his guests rose to drink together. The wine bearer came to Cao Bao who declined it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'What! A fighting man does not drink wine!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I want you to take just one cup.', 'context': ' said the host. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Really, I cannot drink,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'You drank just now; why refuse this time?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'If you disobey the orders of your general, you shall be beaten one hundred strokes.', 'context': 'his temper and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'You civilians attend to your civil business and leave us alone,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 138, 'talk': "Sir, if you saw my son−in−law's face, you would pardon me.", 'context': 'The only way of escape for the guest was to beg remission; and Cao Bao did so, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Who is your son−in−law?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 7, 'talk': 'Lu Bu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Xiaopei is only a place to occupy temporarily,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 131, 'talk': "Liu Bei's secret messenger has arrived.", 'context': 'moonlight. No one on the ramparts saw him. Lu Bu came up close to the wall and called out, “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Lu Bu got in, and there is fighting in the city.', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Success is not worth rejoicing over; failure is not worth grieving over,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Where are our sisters?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei with a sigh. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'They shared the fate of the city.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'What did you say when you promised to guard the city and what orders did our brother give you? Now the city is lost and therewith our sisters−in−law. Have you done well?', 'context': 'Guan Yu with an effort controlled his reproaches and said, “'},
{'istart': 228, 'iend': 738, 'talk': 'Brothers are as hands and feet; wives and children are as clothing. You may mend your torn dress, but who can reattach a lost limb? We three, by the Oath of the Peach Garden, swore to seek the same death day. The city is lost, it is true, and my wives and little ones, but I could not bear that we should die ere our course be run. Beside, Xuzhou was not really ours, and Lu Bu will not harm my family but will rather seek to preserve them. You made a mistake, Worthy Brother, but is it one deserving of death?', 'context': 'In the last chapter it was recorded that Zhang Fei was about to end his life with his own weapon in Xuyi. But Liu Bei rushed forward and caught Zhang Fei in his arms, snatched away the sword, and threw it on the earth, saying, “'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'My lord has gone away; I will settle this as soon as I can see him and get his decision.', 'context': 'However, Gao Shun demanded the promised reward through Ji Ling, who put Gao Shun off, saying, “'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'Although Gao Shun had gone to attack Liu Bei, yet Liu Bei had not been destroyed and no reward could be given till he was actually taken.', 'context': 'With this answer Gao Shun returned to Lu Bu, who could not decide what to do. Then came a letter from Yuan Shu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Such a dishonorable man must have a motive,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Since he treats me kindly, I cannot but trust him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'I knew he would not harm my family,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'I did not wish to take the city, but your brother behaved very badly, drinking and flogging the soldiers, and I came to guard it lest some evil should befall.', 'context': 'At the interview Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'But I had long wished to yield it to you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 105, 'talk': "One must bow to one's lot. It is the will of Heaven, and one cannot struggle against fate.", 'context': 'Said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'If I had a son like Sun Ce,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'I should die without regret.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Here am I, a mere nobody and yet my father was such a hero!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': "I was weeping from regret at being unable to continue my father's work,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 361, 'talk': 'Why stay here bound to the service of a master? The Governor of Dangyang is in distress. Why not get command of an army under the pretense of an expedition to relieve Wu Jing? Escape the shadow of Yuan Shu and take control of Dangyang, then you can accomplish great things.', 'context': ' said Sun Ce. “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'I know what you two are planning, Noble Sirs. Under my hand is a band of one hundred bold fellows ready to help Sun Ce in whatever he wishes to do.', 'context': 'While these two were talking, another man suddenly entered, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'The one fear is that Yuan Shu will refuse to give you the troops,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'I still have the Imperial Hereditary Seal that my father left me; that should be good security.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Yuan Shu earnestly desires that jewel,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'He will certainly lend you troops on that pledge.', 'context': ' said Zhu Zhi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Let me see it if you have it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 394, 'talk': 'I do not want the jewel really, but you may as well leave it with me. I will lend you three thousand troops and five hundred horses. Return as soon as peace can be made. As your rank is hardly sufficient for such powers, I will memorialize to obtain for you higher rank with the title of General Who Exterminates Brigands, and you can soon start.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Now that you have come, the design is as good as accomplished,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'Do you know of the two Zhangs of Guangling? They would be most useful people in working out your schemes.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu was introduced to Zhu Zhi and Lu Fan. Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Who are they, the two Zhangs?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'And let me lead the van!', 'context': 'Zhang Ying was interrupted by another who shouted, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Is there a temple of Liu Xiu the Founder of Latter Hans in the vicinity?', 'context': 'Sun Ce inquired the natives, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'There is a temple to the south on the summit of the hills.', 'context': ' They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'I dreamed last night that Liu Xiu called me, so I will go and pray there,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'My lord, you should not go as the enemy is on the other side, and you may fall into an ambush.', 'context': 'But Counselor Zhang Zhao advised, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'The spirit will help me; what need I fear?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'If I, Sun Ce, succeed in my task and restore the authority of my late father, then will I restore this temple and order sacrifices at the four seasons.', 'context': 'Then Sun Ce knelt and made a vow, saying, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 111, 'talk': "I am going to ride along the ridge and reconnoiter the enemy's position.", 'context': 'When they had remounted, Sun Ce said, “'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'It is certainly Sun Ce trying to inveigle us to battle. But do not go out.', 'context': 'A soldier of the other side going along a bye road quickly reported the presence of horsemen on the ridge, and Liu Yao said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'What better chance to capture him?', 'context': 'Taishi Ci jumped up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'He is a valiant man and I will go with him.', 'context': 'No one moved save a subaltern who said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Stay, Sun Ce!', 'context': 'was going over the summit, some one shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Which is Sun Ce?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'I, Taishi Ci of Laihuang, come to take him prisoner.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Then I am he,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'You and all your crowd come on and I will not blench,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 582, 'iend': 619, 'talk': 'He who retreats is no worthy soldier!', 'context': "setting his spear. Sun Ce braced himself for the shock and the battle began. Fifty bouts were fought and still neither combatant had the advantage. Sun Ce's commanders whispered to each other their admiration and amazement. Taishi Ci saw that the spearmanship of his opponent showed no weak point whereby he could gain the advantage, so he decided to resort to guile. Feigning defeat he would lead Sun Ce to pursue. Taishi Ci however did not retire along the road by which he had come, but took a path leading around the hill instead of over it. His antagonist followed, shouting, “"},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'He has twelve others at his back and I only one. If I capture him, the others will retake him. I will inveigle him into some secret spot and then try.', 'context': 'But Taishi Ci thought within himself, “'},
{'istart': 280, 'iend': 351, 'talk': 'If the owner of this had not fled, he would have been stabbed to death.', 'context': "Next day Sun Ce led his army to the front of Liu Yao's camp, and the challenge was accepted. The armies were drawn up. Sun Ce hung the short lance he had seized from Taishi Ci at the end of his spear and waved it in front of the line of battle and ordered his soldiers to shout, “"},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 111, 'talk': "Sun Ce's head is here already.", 'context': "On the other side they hung out Sun Ce's helmet, and the soldiers shouted back, “"},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'My lord should not trouble himself; I will take him.', 'context': 'out challenging Sun Ce to a duel to the death, and Sun Ce would have accepted, but Cheng Pu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'You are no antagonist for me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Tell your master to come out.', 'context': ' said Taishi Ci. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Why did you sound the retreat?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'I was just going to capture the wretch.', 'context': ' said Taishi Ci. “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 225, 'talk': "Zhou Yu's attack is the cause of this move; they are in no mood to fight. A night raid on their camp would finish them.", 'context': 'The army retired, Taishi Ci with it, without being pursued. On the other side Zhang Zhao said to Sun Ce, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I am here;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'you would better give in.', 'context': ' said Sun Ce, “'},
{'istart': 321, 'iend': 372, 'talk': 'There is a man behind you going to strike secretly!', 'context': "A general came out from behind Liu Yao to accept the challenge. It was Yu Mi. But in the third bout Sun Ce made him prisoner and carried him off to the other side. Seeing his colleague thus captured, Fan Neng rode out to the rescue and got quite close. But just as he was going to thrust, all Sun Ce's soldiers shouted, “"},
{'istart': 311, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'Sun Ce is here still!', 'context': "By Sun Ce's command the story was spread abroad that the hurt had been fatal, and all the soldiers set up cries of lamentation. The camp was broken up. Xue Li, Zhang Ying, and Chen Heng made a night sortie but fell into a carefully prepared ambush, and presently Sun Ce himself appeared on horseback shouting: “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I knew you were a real hero,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'If you had taken me at that fight we had near the shrine, would you have killed me?', 'context': 'hand and said, laughing, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who can say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'Exactly what I most desire. I will make an agreement with you that at midday tomorrow you will return.', 'context': 'late master. Under the smart of this defeat they will turn against him, and they would be a great help to you.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'He is trustworthy and will not break his word,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 205, 'talk': "For as much as my lord's fate is bound up with that of the army, he should not risk a conflict with a mere robber. I wish that you should remember your own value.", 'context': 'Zhang Hong tried to dissuade him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Your words, O Wise One, are as gold and precious stones, but I fear that my soldiers will not carry out my commands unless I myself share their dangers.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': "See me hit that fellow's hand,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'How can we hope to withstand an army with such people as this in it?', 'context': 'The wounded man was taken away. When Yan Baihu the White Tiger heard of the exploit, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'And what does your brother propose?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'He is willing to share this region with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'The rat! How dare he put himself on a level with me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'No! No! Sun Ce as a leader is humane and upright, while the White Tiger is a savage ruffian. Rather capture him and offer his person as a peace offering to Sun Ce.', 'context': 'But, when Wang Lang proposed this, one of his officers stood forth, saying, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'Mine is an army of good soldiers, and my aim is to restore peace to this region, but you give your support to a rebel!', 'context': 'Sun Ce came up. When both sides were arrayed, Sun Ce rode out and addressed Wang Lang, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Your greed is insatiable. Having got possession of Wujun, you want also my territory. I shall revenge for the Yans.', 'context': 'Wang Lang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'We can only strengthen our position and remain behind the shelter of the ramparts until hunger forces the besiegers to retire,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 136, 'iend': 427, 'talk': 'Since they are holding the city with such resolution, it will be difficult to dislodge them. But the bulk of their supplies is stored at Chadu, distant only some ten miles. Our best plan is to seize this place, thus attacking where the enemy is unprepared, and doing what they do not expect.', 'context': 'For several days a vigorous attack was maintained, but with little success. In a council, Sun Jing, who was the uncle of Sun Ce, said, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 81, 'talk': "My uncle's plan is admirable and will crush the rebels.", 'context': 'Sun Ce approved, saying, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'When you, my lord, go away, the besieged will surely come out and follow you. We might prepare a surprise for them.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu came to utter a warning, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'My preparations are complete, and the city will be captured tonight.', 'context': 'Sun Ce replied, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'He has gone and this is only a strategy. Let us go out and smite them.', 'context': 'Zhou Xin said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'If he has gone, it is to attack Chadu. Let us pursue.', 'context': 'Yan Baihu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'The place is our base of supply,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 181, 'iend': 347, 'talk': 'Once in an engagement with some coastal pirates, I received many spear wounds, but a certain wise man named Yu Fan recommended a surgeon who cured me in half a month.', 'context': "These wounds being due to metal would not heal but swelled enormously, and the brave soldier's life hung in the balance. Sun Ce returned and was deeply grieved. Then Dong Xi said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Surely this must be Yu Fan of Kuaiji,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'That is he; he is so called.', 'context': ' replied Sun Ce. “'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Yes, truly a wise man; I would employ him.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'The case is not difficult,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'Sun Ce borrowed an army from me and set out on an expedition which has made him master of the South Land. Now he says nothing of repayment but demands the token of his pledge. Truly he is a boor, and what steps can I take to destroy him?', 'context': 'Yuan Shu said, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'You cannot do any thing against him, for he is too strongly placed, the Great River as the shield. You must first remove Liu Bei in revenge for having attacked you without cause, and then you may think about Sun Ce. I have a scheme to put the former into your hands in a very short time.', 'context': 'Yang Dajiang replied, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'What is your plan of attack on Liu Bei?', 'context': 'Adviser Yang Dajiang knew how to remove Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 489, 'talk': 'Though Liu Bei, now camped at Xiaopei, could easily be taken, yet Lu Bu is strongly posted at the chief city near. And I think Lu Bu would help Liu Bei if it was only for the grudge he bears against you for not having given him the gold and studs, grain and horses you promised. First of all you should send Lu Bu a present whereby to engage his affections and keep him quiet while you deal with Liu Bei. You can see to Lu Bu after this is done, and Xuzhou is yours.', 'context': 'Yang Dajiang replied, “'},
{'istart': 130, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'Our resources were too small; therefore, we must lay the position before Lu Bu and ask help.', 'context': 'When Liu Bei heard these things he called his officers to take counsel. Zhang Fei was for open war forthwith. But Sun Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Do you think that fellow will do anything?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 581, 'talk': 'I have just received gifts from Yuan Shu and a letter, with the intent of restraining me from helping Liu Bei. Now comes a letter from Liu Bei asking help. It seems to me that Liu Bei where he is can do me no harm; but if Yuan Shu overcomes Liu Bei and comes to an understanding with the leaders around the Huashang Mountains, then the power of the north is so much nearer, and I should be unable to resist the attacks of so many leaders and should never sleep secure. I will aid Liu Bei; that is the better course for me.', 'context': 'Receiving this Lu Bu called in Chen Gong to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I know how to make both of them love me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'I have treated him too well for him to do me any harm,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'You two are invited for the particular purpose of a discussion,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Do not take it amiss.', 'context': ' said the host. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Do you wish to slay me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Not at all,', 'context': ' asked Ji Ling. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Then you are going to slay Long−Ears?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'No; not that.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Then what does it mean?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Liu Bei and I are brothers. Now, General, you are besieging him, and so I have come to the rescue.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Then slay me,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'May I ask how you think of doing so?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'I have a means and one approved of Heaven itself.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'I wish you two gentlemen to listen to me and put an end to your strife.', 'context': 'The banquet began. After a number of courses almost in silence, Lu Bu spoke, saying, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'I have come with an army of one hundred thousand at the express bidding of my master to take Liu Bei. How can I cease the strife? I must fight.', 'context': 'Liu Bei made no reply, but Ji Ling said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'What!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Few as we are, we regard you no more than a lot of children. What are you compared with a million Yellow Scarves? You dare hurt our brother!', 'context': ' exclaimed Zhang Fei drawing his sword. “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Let us see what General Lu Bu has to say first; after that there will be time to go to our tents and fight.', 'context': 'Guan Yu urged him to be silent, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I beg you both to come to an understanding. I cannot let you fight,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 219, 'iend': 244, 'talk': 'Bring my trident halberd!', 'context': 'Now on one side Ji Ling was discontented and angry; on the other Zhang Fei was dying for a fight; and neither of the two chiefly concerned would signify assent. Then suddenly the host turned to his attendants, saying, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'I have tried to persuade you to make peace, for that is the command of the Most High. It shall be put to the test.', 'context': 'Lu Bu went on, saying, “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 406, 'talk': 'That gate is one hundred and fifty paces distant. If I can hit that left branch of the halberd−head with an arrow, you will both withdraw your armies. If I miss, you can go away and prepare for immediate battle. I shall stand against either of you who does not abide by what I say.', 'context': 'He then bade his servants take the halberd outside beyond the gate and set it up. Then speaking to his two guests, he said, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'That small mark at that distance! How could any one hit it?', 'context': 'Ji Ling thought to himself, “'},
{'istart': 212, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'Twang!', 'context': 'Lu Bu turned back his sleeves, carefully fitted an arrow to the string and pulled the bow to its utmost stretch. A slight exclamation escaped him as the bow curved like the harvest moon sailing through the sky. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'The command of Heaven indeed! And now you cease from fighting!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'I cannot disobey your command, General, but let me depart. What will my master say and will he believe me?', 'context': 'heart felt rather lucky; his fellow guest sat silent, nodding his head. Presently he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I will write a letter and confirm it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 181, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'Do not forget I have delivered you today!', 'context': 'After a few more rounds of the wine, Ji Ling asked that he might have the letter and after that departed. When the brothers took their leave, Lu Bu again reminded Liu Bei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Lu Bu repays me for all my grain with this bit of play acting!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'He has saved Liu Bei, but I will lead a large army myself and settle both Liu Bei and him.', 'context': ' cried Yuan Shu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Be careful, my lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 492, 'talk': "Lu Bu is braver and stronger than most leaders and has wide territory. He and Liu Bei together make a powerful combination, not easy to break. But there is another course. I have found out that his wife, Lady Yan, has a daughter just of marriageable age; and as you have a son, you could arrange a marriage alliance with Lu Bu. If his daughter wedded your son, Lu Bu would certainly slay your enemy for you. This is called 'Relative−above−Stranger' plan.", 'context': ' said Ji Ling. “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 247, 'talk': 'My master has an immense respect for you, Illustrious Sir, and he desires to ensure perpetual alliance between the two families by a marriage, an alliance such as existed between the ancient states of Qin and Jin.', 'context': 'When Han Yin saw Lu Bu, he said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 282, 'talk': 'The Yuans have dominated the regions around the River Huai these many years. They have a large army and are very prosperous. One day a Yuan will become emperor, and our daughter may hope to be an empress. But how many sons has Yuan Shu?', 'context': 'When he broached the subject, his wife said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Only this one.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Then we should accept the offer. Even if our daughter does not become an Empress, Xuzhou has a new ally.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 220, 'iend': 350, 'talk': "Who originated this scheme by which Yuan Shu and Lu Bu are to become connections by this marriage so that Liu Bei's head may fall?", 'context': 'Next day Chen Gong went to see the messenger in his lodging, and when the usual ceremonies and greetings had been exchanged, the two men sat down to talk. When the servants had been sent out of earshot, Chen Gong said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I pray you not to let it get abroad,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'I certainly shall keep it secret. But if there be any delay, some other person will find it out and that spells failure,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'What would best be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'I will see Lu Bu and get him to send the girl immediately so that the marriage may be concluded quickly.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'If it happened thus, my master would indeed hold you in high respect.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': "I hear your daughter is to be married to Yuan Shu's son. That is capital, but no one knows when.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'That has yet to be considered.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'There were certain fixed rules as to the period between sending presents and consummation of the marriage; emperors, a year; nobles, half a year; high officers, three months; and common people, one month.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'As to Yuan Shu, Heaven has already put into his hands the Imperial Hereditary Seal and he will surely arrive at the dignity one day. So, I should think the imperial rule would apply.', 'context': 'Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'No; it will not.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': "The nobles' rule, then?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'No; nor that.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': "The high officers'?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Not even that.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Then you mean me to go by the rule for common people.', 'context': 'Lu Bu laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Nor that either.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Then what do you mean?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'What you say is quite to the point,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': "They are working on the 'Relative−above−Stranger' device, then,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is in danger.', 'context': ' said Chen Gui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Noble Sir, what brings you here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'I heard you were dead and I came to mourn,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Who said that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 748, 'talk': "Once upon a time you received grand presents from Yuan Shu that you might slay Liu Bei, but you got out by that clever shot at your halberd. Now they suddenly seek a marriage alliance thinking to get hold of your daughter as a pledge. The next move will be an attack on Xiaopei and, that gone, where are you? Whatever they ask in future, grain or troops or anything else, and you yield, will bring your own end nearer, and make you hated all round. If you refuse, then you are false to the duties of a relative, and that will be an excuse to attack you openly. Beside this Yuan Shu intends to call himself emperor, which would be rebellion, and you would be of the rebel's family; something abominable, which the multitude people would not suffer.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'I have been misled!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'He is simply doing his duty; there is nothing to be surprised at,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 423, 'talk': 'As you ordered us, we went into the Huashang Mountains to purchase horses. We had got three hundred when, on our way back, on the borders of Xiaopei some robbers stole half of them. We hear that the real robbers were Zhang Fei and his soldiers, who took on the guise of brigands.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu at first. Then came two officers, Song Xian and Wei Xu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 231, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'Elder Brother, why have you brought an army against me?', 'context': 'Lu Bu was very angry at this and began to prepare an expedition against Xiaopei. When Liu Bei heard that an attack threatened, he led out his army to oppose it, and the two armies were arrayed. Liu Bei rode to the front and said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'That shot of mine at the Archery Feast saved you from grave danger; why then did you steal my horses?', 'context': 'Lu Bu began abusing him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I wanted horses and I sent out to buy them. Should I dare to take yours?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'You goggled−eyed thief! You are always treating me with contempt.', 'context': 'Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': "Yes; I took your horses and you get angry. You did not say any thing when you stole my brother's Xuzhou.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Where are the horses?', 'context': 'Liu Bei called his brother and chided him as the cause of all this misfortune. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'In some of the temples and courts,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'You will suffer by and by if you do not remove this Liu Bei.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'The one person that Cao Cao detests is Lu Bu. Let us then abandon the city and take refuge with Cao Cao, from whom we may borrow troops to destroy him.', 'context': 'Said Sun Qian, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'If we try to get away, who will lead the van?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'I will do my best,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 180, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is as my brother.', 'context': 'Liu Bei approached Xuchang and encamped outside the city, whence he sent Sun Qian to see Cao Cao and relate the events that brought him there. Cao Cao was very friendly and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'He has no sense of right,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'You and I, my brother, will attack him together.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'If you are not on your guard, Liu Bei will be your undoing. You ought to destroy him. He is too much of a hero.', 'context': 'Xun Yu then had an interview with his master and said, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'I have been advised to kill Liu Bei; what of such a scheme?', 'context': 'Cao Cao made no reply and his adviser retired. Presently Guo Jia came, and Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'A bad scheme,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 675, 'talk': 'You are the popular champion, pledged to relieve the people from oppression, and only by truth and rectitude can you secure the support of the noble−minded. Your only fear is lest they stay away. Now Liu Bei is clearly a hero. He has come to you for help and protection, and to put him to death would be to alienate all good people and put fear into the hearts of all the able advisers. Hampered by these difficulties, where will you find those whose help you need? To remove the dangers represented by one man and thereby injure yourself in the eyes of all humankind is a sure means of destruction. These conditions need careful consideration.', 'context': ' said Guo Jia. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'What you say exactly fits in with what I think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 297, 'talk': 'Lu Bu has no notion of a policy. He is led astray by any little advantage that presents itself to his eyes. All you need do is to obtain promotion for him, giving him some additional title, and tell him to make peace with Liu Bei, and he will do it. The south is no threat then.', 'context': 'Said the Adviser, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': "You would do well to surrender, since Cao Cao's army is too large for you to oppose,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 201, 'iend': 390, 'talk': "Peeping through one of the partitions last evening, I saw a perfectly beautiful woman in one of the courts. They told me she was the wife of Zhang Ji, Zhang Xiu's uncle. She is very lovely.", 'context': 'One day, when Cao Cao returned to his quarters in a more than usual merry mood, he asked the attendants if there were any singing girls in the city. His nephew, Cao Amin, heard the question and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Do you know who I am?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Indeed, then, I owe my very life to you; I am very grateful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'But Zhang Xiu will greatly wonder at my prolonged absence, and gossips will begin to talk,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'If you like, you can leave the city tomorrow.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 147, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'Keep this secret, wait till he appears again to carry on business, and then do so and so.', 'context': 'But people told Zhang Xiu what had gone amiss, and he was angry at the shame brought upon the family. He confided his trouble to Jia Xu who said, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'Since the surrendered troops are deserting in great number, it would be well to camp them in the center of your camp to prevent this.', 'context': "A plan was arranged quite secretly. Next day Zhang Xiu went into Cao Cao's tent, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'One of the soldiers has dropped a spark; there is nothing to be alarmed at,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'The Qingzhou soldiers say you have turned traitor; why do you not explain now that the Prime Minister has arrived? Why first make a camp?', 'context': 'An officer asked him, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'Our enemies are coming up in our rear and are very close. It is necessary to prepare for defense or we shall not withstand them. Explanation is a small matter, but defense is very important.', 'context': 'Yu Jin replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Why did you not tell me before you made the camp?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'When the first thought of a leader in the time of greatest stress is to maintain order and to strengthen his defenses, giving no thought to slander but shouldering his burdens bravely, and when he thereby turns a defeat into a victory, who, even of the ancient leaders, can excel Yu Jin?', 'context': 'Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 153, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'I have lost my first born son, but I grieve not so heavily for him as for Dian Wei. I weep for him.', 'context': 'Sacrifices in honor of the dead warrior Dian Wei were instituted. Cao Cao himself led the wailing and paid due honors. Turning to his officers he said, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 350, 'talk': "My master's project of declaring himself emperor is advancing. He has already built a palace and will speedily choose Empress and concubines and would come to the South of River Huai. He is looking forward to receiving the fiancee of the Heir Apparent.", 'context': 'Next came news that a messenger from Yuan Shu had arrived. When he had been introduced, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Has the rebel gone so far?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is cruel, stupid, and facile. The longer he remains, the worse.', 'context': 'However, Chen Deng secretly told Cao Cao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I know Lu Bu quite well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 250, 'talk': 'He is a wolf with a savage heart, and it will be hard to feed him for long. If it had not been for you and your father, I should not have known all the circumstances and you must help me to get rid of him.', 'context': ' replied Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Anything the Prime Minister wishes to do shall have my assistance,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'My father received a generous annuity, and I was made Governor of Guangling.', 'context': 'Chen Deng told him, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'O General, how unwary you are!', 'context': 'Chen Deng only laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I, unwary?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Yes; he understands me.', 'context': 'Lu Bu threw aside his sword and laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 610, 'talk': 'The Supreme Ancestor, the Founder of Han Dynasty, was only a very minor official, and yet he became ruler of the empire. The dynasty has endured four centuries, and its measure of fortune has run out. It no longer possesses authority; the cauldron is on the point of boiling over. My family has held the highest offices of state for four generations and is universally respected. Wherefore I wish, in response to the will of Heaven and the desire of the people, to assume the Imperial Dignity. What think ye of the proposal, my officers?', 'context': 'As a preliminary he assembled all his officers and addressed them thus: “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 512, 'talk': 'You may not do this. Prince Wen, the Ancestor of the Zhou, was of distinguished virtue and held many offices; till the last years of Shang Dynasty, he had two thirds of the empire. Still he served and was loyal to the ruling house. Your house is honorable, but it is not so glorious as that of Zhou. The Hans may be reduced, but they are not so abominably cruel as those of the Shang Dynasty that they are to be overthrown. Indeed this should not be done.', 'context': 'Secretary Yan Xiang rose in opposition at once, saying, “'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 402, 'talk': 'This misfortune that has come to us is due to the two Chens, who fawned upon the central government in order to obtain rank and appointments. Now remove the evil by putting these two to death and sending their heads to Yuan Shu. Then he will retire and leave us in peace.', 'context': 'Lu Bu summoned his advisers to a council to which came Chen Gong, Chen Deng, and Chen Gui. When all had assembled Chen Gong said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'If you can show us how to overcome them, I will spare your life,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'General, if you will listen to poor me, the region will be perfectly safe.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Let us hear what you have to say.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Let us have it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 402, 'talk': 'Han Xian and Yang Feng, two of the leaders of our enemies, are old servants of the Han Dynasty who fled from fear of Cao Cao and, being homeless, sought refuge with Yuan Shu. He despises them, and they are dissatisfied with his service. A little letter from the court will secure their help as our allies, and with Liu Bei to help us on the outside, we can certainly overcome Yuan Shu.', 'context': 'Chen Deng said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'You shall take the letters yourself,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'What are you here for? You belong to Lu Bu.', 'context': "When Han Xian's army had halted and pitched camp, Chen Deng went to see Han Xian who said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 390, 'talk': "I am a noble of the court of the great Hans. Why do you call me a Lu Bu's man? If you, General, hitherto a minister of state, now serve a traitor, you will nullify the grand services you rendered in protecting the Emperor in the flight from Changan. Beside, the suspicious Yuan Shu will assuredly do you some harm, and you will regret not having taken this opportunity to work against him.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'I would return to my allegiance if there should be any opportunity.', 'context': 'Han Xian sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'Yes; I know. You may return to your master and say General Yang Feng and I will turn our weapons and smite Yuan Shu. Look out for a signal flare, and let your master come to our aid.', 'context': "Thereupon Chen Deng gave him Lu Bu's letter asking for cooperation. Han Xian read it and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Traitor! Why have they not slain you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'Let them hold those places in Huashang Mountains, which will be all yours within a year.', 'context': 'There had been a question of keeping these two in Xuzhou City, but Chen Gui opposed it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Why not retain them here?', 'context': 'So Han Xian and Yang Feng were sent to these two cities in the meantime to await orders. “'},
{'istart': 158, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'They would be a basis for our conspiracy against Lu Bu.', 'context': ' asked Chen Deng secretly of his father. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': "But if they helped him, on the other hand, we should lengthen the tiger's claws and teeth,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'On the strength of holding the State Seal, he secretly calls himself emperor and rebels against the Hans. I would rather punish such a renegade than help him.', 'context': 'from Sun Ce. But Sun Ce said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'What next from this callow youth?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'I will smite him before I deal with the others.', 'context': ' cried Yuan Shu. “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 361, 'talk': 'Although recently defeated, Yuan Shu has large army and ample supplies. He is not to be attacked lightly. You would better write to Cao Cao persuading him to attack the South of River Huai and we will be auxiliaries. Between the two armies, Yuan Shu must certainly be defeated. If by the remotest chance we lose, we have Cao Cao to come to our rescue.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Whose are these?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'The heads of Han Xian and Yang Feng.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Why did this happen?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'You have removed an evil, which is a grand service: why talk of a fault?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 557, 'talk': "Shouchun has suffered from drought for several years and the people are on the verge of famine. Sending an army would add to the distress and anger the people, and victory would be uncertain. I advise not to send any more soldiers there, but to hold on till the besiegers are conquered by lack of supplies. Meanwhile, Your Highness, with regiment of guards, will move over to the other side of River Huai, which is quite ready, and we shall also escape the enemy's ferocity.", 'context': 'At this juncture Yuan Shu summoned his officers. Yang Dajiang explained the case, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Serve out with a smaller measure,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'That will save us for a time.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'But if the soldiers murmur, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I shall have another device.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 208, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'I want to ask you to lend me something to pacify the soldiers with. You must not refuse.', 'context': 'took this; and when he found that complaints were general and the soldiers were saying that the Prime Minister was fooling them, he sent a secret summons to the controller. When Wang Hou came, Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 299, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'What does the Prime Minister wish?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I want the loan of your head to expose to the soldiery.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'But I have done nothing wrong!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'I know that, but if I do not put you to death there will be a mutiny. After you are gone, your wife and children shall be my care. So you need not grieve on their account.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 187, 'iend': 314, 'talk': 'In accordance with military law, Wang Hou had been put to death for peculation and the use of a short measure in issuing grain.', 'context': 'Wang Hou was about to remonstrate further, but Cao Cao gave a signal. The executioners hustled Wang Hou out, and he was beheaded. His head was exposed on a tall pole, and a notice said, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 329, 'talk': 'Zhang Xiu, with the support of Liu Biao, was ravaging the country all round. There were rebellions in Nanyang and Jiangling, and Cao Hong could not cope with it. Cao Hong had been worsted already in several engagements and was in sore straits.', 'context': 'Cao Cao hesitated; and before he had made up his mind, there came an urgent message: “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 258, 'talk': "I am leaving you at Xiaopei to dig a 'pitfall for the tiger.' You will only take advice from Chen Deng and Chen Gui, and there can be no mishap. You will find so−and−so your ally when needed.", 'context': 'When Lu Bu had left for Xuzhou, Cao Cao said secretly to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 240, 'iend': 520, 'talk': 'I am sent on the expedition by command of the Emperor to capture a rebel and save the people. I cannot avoid moving in the harvest season; but if any one trample down the corn, he shall be put to death. Military law is strict without exception, and the people need fear no damage.', 'context': 'The army marched away. In the course of the march they passed through a wheat region, and the grain was ready for harvesting but the peasants had fled for fear, and the corn was uncut. Cao Cao sent proclamations to all villages and towns: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'How can I deal with your crime?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'I made the rule and I have broken it. Can I otherwise satisfy public opinion?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'In ancient days, the days of the Spring and Autumn history, the laws were not applied to the persons of the most important. You are the supreme leader of a mighty army and must not wound yourself.', 'context': 'Guo Jia said, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'Since there exists the reason just quoted, I may perhaps escape the death penalty.', 'context': 'Cao Cao pondered for a long time. At last he said, “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'I cut off the hair as touching the head.', 'context': 'Then with his sword he cut off his hair and threw it on the ground, saying, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister, having trodden down some corn, ought to have lost his head by the terms of the order; now here is his hair cut off as an attack on the head.', 'context': 'Then he sent messengers to exhibit the hair throughout the whole army, saying, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'O false and pretended supporter of benevolence and justice! O shameless one! You are just a beast of the forest, and absolutely devoid of humanity.', 'context': 'When the array was complete Zhang Xiu took his station in front and pointing at Cao Cao railed at him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 285, 'iend': 352, 'talk': 'I know what Cao Cao intends, and I can defeat him by a countermove.', 'context': 'Cao Cao rode round the city closely inspecting the defenses. Three days later he issued an order to make a mound of earth and brushwood at the northwest corner, as he would mount the walls at that point. He was observed from within the city by Jia Xu, who went to Zhang Xiu and said, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 692, 'talk': 'I saw Cao Cao very carefully reconnoitering round about the city. He certainly noticed that the southeast corner of the wall had been lately restored with mud bricks of a different kind, and that the fencing barrier is badly out of repair. He will try to effect an entrance there. Wherefore he is making a feint attack at the opposite point. He is piling up straw and making ostentatious preparations whereby to cajole us into withdrawing from the real point of attack to defend the northwest. His troops will scale the walls in the darkness and try to enter at the southeast.', 'context': "Jia Xu, as he had guessed the enemy's intention, had also devised a countermove. So he went to his chief and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Supposing your surmise correct, what do you advise?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 498, 'talk': 'The countermove is plain. You issue an order for our best and bravest soldiers to fill their bellies, to take only the lightest outfit and conceal themselves in the houses near the southeast corner. Then disguise the townspeople as soldiers and send them to pretend to defend the northwest. Tonight we will let the enemy climb up the walls and enter the city and, once they are fairly within, give the signal and the concealed soldiers will rush out upon them. We may even capture Cao Cao himself.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'The defenders of the city have moved to the northwest where noisy preparations for defense are going on. The opposite corner is left undefended.', 'context': 'The stratagem was decided upon. Soon the scouts told Cao Cao: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'They have fallen into my trap!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 190, 'talk': "This move of Sun Ce in the river is part of Cao Cao's strategy, and there will be never−ending regret if Cao Cao is allowed to escape. An immediate expedition is necessary.", 'context': 'Kuai Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'I remembered that here, only a year ago, I lost my great general: Dian Wei. Is that not a reason to grieve?', 'context': 'Walking one day beside River Yu, he suddenly uttered a great cry, and when his officers asked the reason thereof he replied, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'I have been marching only a short distance each day and of course knew of the pursuit. But my plans are laid and, as I am near Anzhong, my enemy will be broken. You need not have any fears.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied to the letter, saying, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'How could we have foreseen such a wicked ruse?', 'context': 'The two leaders on the other side restored order among their beaten troops and then held a conference. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Let us try again,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'It will lead to a defeat.', 'context': 'Jia Xu opposed it and said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'It is wrong to lose such a chance.', 'context': 'However, Liu Biao said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'This defeat comes from my not following your advice.', 'context': 'Zhang Xiu said to Jia Xu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Now set your army in order and pursue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'But we have just suffered defeat!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Do you now counsel pursuit?', 'context': ' cried both leaders. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Yes, and the result will be a great victory if you go now. I will venture my head on that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 340, 'talk': 'When our veteran and brave soldiers were going to pursue those who retreated, you said our men would lose the day; and when defeated men pursued the victors, you foretold victory. You were right in both cases, but we wish you would enlighten us.', 'context': 'The other general, Liu Biao, asked the adviser to explain his apparent inconsistency, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 496, 'talk': "It is easy to explain. You, Generals, although skilled leaders, are not a match for our enemy. Though Cao Cao had lost a battle, he had able generals to keep the rear and guard against pursuit. Our soldiers are good, but not a match for them. That is how I knew. For as much as Cao Cao's hurried retreat was due to trouble in the capital, and he had beaten off our attack, I knew he would retire at his utmost speed and not take his usual precautions. I ventured to take advantage of his laxity.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Had it not been for the troops that came out of the hills, we should all have been lost.', 'context': 'The soldiers of the beaten rearguard said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'What troops?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'You, Sir, marched very leisurely to Anzhong; how came it that you felt certain of victory?', 'context': 'Cao Cao went to his palace and there received the ceremonial calls of congratulation. These finished, Xun Yu asked, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 260, 'talk': 'My soldiers, who retire and find their retreat cut off, fight vigorously and desperately. I retired slowly to entice the enemy into following whereby I could do as I wished with them. Basing my movements on these considerations I felt secure.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Why so late, Sir?', 'context': 'When Guo Jia entered, Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao is so exceedingly rude that I will attack him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Only I think I am not quite strong enough. What should be done?', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 352, 'talk': 'My lord, you know well who lost, and why, in the conflict between Liu Bang, the Supreme Ancestor, and Xiang Yu, his rival; the former won only by superior wisdom. Xiang Yu was the stronger, but in the end he was overcome. Your rival has ten weak points whereas you have ten strong ones, and, though his army is large, it is not terrible.', 'context': 'Guo Jia said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 1596, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao is overmuch devoted to ceremony and deportment; while you are sympathetic and natural; this is an excellence in conduct. He is antagonistic and drives; you are conciliatory and lead; so you have the advantage of popular approval. For many years the government has been lax, and he makes it more so; you strive vigorously after efficiency; this is the excellence of able administration. He is outwardly liberal but grudging at heart, and too given to nepotism; you appear exacting, but you understand and use people after their ability; this is the advantage of correct appreciation. He is a visionary but lacking in decision; you are a man of prompt decision and direct action; this is an advantage in policy. He loves to gather about him people of renown; you treat people as you find them regardless of their reputation; this is where you excel in moral virtue. He is compassionate to those at hand, but careless about those out of sight; your care is all−embracing; this is where you excel in humanity. He lends a ready ear to calumny and is misled; you may be flooded with evil counsel, but you preserve independence; this is where you excel in perspicacity. His sense of right and wrong is confused; your appreciation is accurate and clear; this is where you excel in administrative capacity. He loves the make−believe force, but is ignorant of military essentials; you would overcome with far inferior numbers as you possess military genius; this is where you excel in war. With your ten superiorities, you will have no difficulty in overcoming Yuan Shao.', 'context': 'Then Guo Jia continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'How can I be worth as much as you say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'What Guo Jia has said about the ten points in your favor agrees exactly with what I think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 163, 'talk': "Yuan Shao's army is not formidable in spite of its size.", 'context': ' said Xun Yu. “'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'The real and dangerous enemy is Lu Bu,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 221, 'iend': 475, 'talk': 'When Yuan Shao has gone north to destroy Gongsun Zan, we ought to sweep away Lu Bu and so clear away our danger from that side; for if this is not done, our attack on Yuan Shao will be the signal for an attempt on the capital. That would be most serious.', 'context': ' said Guo Jia. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'They flatter you to your face, but what is in their hearts? You ought to be most carefully on your guard.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Hold your tongue!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'You are simply slandering them without the slightest excuse. You want to harm good people.', 'context': ' was the angry reply. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'No ears for loyal words;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'and we shall suffer.', 'context': ' said Chen Gong, as he went away sad at heart, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Where are you from? Who sent you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 267, 'iend': 445, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister sent me to bear a letter to Imperial Protector Liu Bei. I was now taking back the reply. I know nothing more, and I am ignorant of the contents of the letters.', 'context': "The messenger made no reply for he knew to what party his captors belonged. But they searched him and found a letter, the secret reply to Cao Cao's letter from Liu Bei. The messenger and the letter were both taken straight to Lu Bu. He questioned the man, who said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'The wretches!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'To dare to act thus!', 'context': ' cried he, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'I have no quarrel with your master, why do you come here with an army?', 'context': 'In due course Gao Shun came to the south gate. Liu Bei ascended the tower and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'You have plotted with Cao Cao to injure my master as we know now; why should I not bind you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'You are too good a man to waste yourself on rebels,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'He is afraid and so has gone away; it would be best to pursue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'As a warrior he is not inferior to either of us, but I have spoken a few straight words, and he has sunk deep. He is repentant and that is why he will not meet us.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'I wish to attack Lu Bu. I fear not Yuan Shao, but Liu Biao and Zhang Xiu may attack me in the rear.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'Both these latter have been too recently defeated to do anything so rash. But Lu Bu is a bold fighting man, and if he joined forces with Yuan Shu and they set themselves to conquer River Huai and River Si, the problem would he difficult.', 'context': 'Xun You, the nephew of Xun Yu, replied, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Let us take advantage of the moment before they have fully made up their mind. Smite before they are fully prepared.', 'context': 'Then spoke Guo Jia, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Essence of my father, blood of my mother, I cannot throw this away!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 325, 'talk': "The hero does not destroy a person's family. Your rival for the empire is Cao Cao, and my master, always mindful of the good turn you did him at the Archery Feast, would not be ungrateful. But he could not help going to Cao Cao, and I think you will pity him.", 'context': 'When Lu Bu reached the residence, he was met by Mi Zhu who said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'We two are old friends; how could I bear to harm his wives and children?', 'context': 'Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'Alas! I know not the fate of my brothers, whether they be alive or dead, and my wife and children are lost to me! What can I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'I see nothing better than getting away to Cao Cao, whence we may be able to plan our future moves.', 'context': 'Sun Qian replied, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'What flesh is it?', 'context': 'While eating Liu Bei asked, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Wolf.', 'context': 'Liu An told him: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'I wish I could go with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'but as my mother still lives I cannot go so far from home.', 'context': ' said Liu An, “'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Lu Bu has allied himself with the bandits in the east, and they are attacking Yanzhou.', 'context': 'Presently scouts, sent out particularly for tidings of Lu Bu, returned, saying, “'},
{'istart': 232, 'iend': 365, 'talk': 'Remember the words of Cao Cao, that the business of the east is in our hands. Now is our moment, for Lu Bu is about to suffer defeat.', 'context': 'The scouts told Lu Bu, who was then in Xuzhou, whither he had gone to start an expedition to save Xiaopei. He left the protection of Xuzhou to Chen Gui and set out with Chen Deng. As this latter was starting, Chen Gui said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'Father, I can look after the outside. But when Lu Bu returns beaten, you must arrange with Mi Zhu to keep him out of the city. I shall find a means of escape,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'His family is here, and he has many friends. How about them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I also have a scheme to settle them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 188, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'Your words are indeed wise. I will also send my wives and little ones thither,', 'context': 'attacked. We ought to provide for possible retreat, and I advise storing grain and money in Xiapi. We could retreat there if the day went adversely. Why not see about this in good time?” “'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'Let me go first to reconnoiter so that you, my lord, may advance with confidence.', 'context': 'And then the soldiers marched to the relief of the pass. About half way there Chen Deng said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'The General greatly wonders why you do not advance. He is going to inquire into it.', 'context': 'Chen Deng said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'The enemy is in great force, and we cannot be too careful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'We are holding the pass, and you should persuade our master to take steps to guard Xiaopei.', 'context': ' said Chen Gong. “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Your words are true.', 'context': 'Chen Deng said, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'Those bandits are about to give up the pass to the enemy, but I have left Chen Gong to hold it. You would better make an attack tonight and hold him.', 'context': 'Next day he left and hastened back to Lu Bu and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Had it not been for you, the pass would have been lost,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 146, 'iend': 269, 'talk': "Cao Cao's troops have found a secret way through the pass, and I fear Xuzhou is already lost. You ought to go back at once.", 'context': 'Then he sent Chen Deng back to arrange a fire signal with Chen Gong for simultaneous action. So Chen Deng returned to Chen Gong to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 203, 'talk': "You stole our master's city, and now we are going to give it back to him. You will not enter here again.", 'context': 'with a thick flight of arrows. At the same time Mi Zhu appeared on the defense tower and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Where is Chen Gui?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'We have slain him!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Where is Chen Deng?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Chen Deng came to us saying you, General, was surrounded and wanted help, so we came at once.', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Another trick of that false rogue!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Surely he shall die for this.', 'context': ' said Lu Bu. “'},
{'istart': 136, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'Did you think that I, a minister of the dynasty, would serve a rebel like you?', 'context': 'While Lu Bu stood at the foot of the rampart reviling the traitor, Chen Deng himself appeared on the wall and pointing to Lu Bu cried, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Do not flee, O Lu Bu! Guan Yu is waiting for you.', 'context': 'Then appeared a new force under Guan Yu. Holding his sword ready to strike, Guan Yu called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I was on the Haizhou Road when I heard of you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'I lost no time in starting.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'And I had been camped in the Mangdang Hills for a long time. It is happiness to be together again.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 422, 'talk': 'If Lu Bu be pressed too hard, he may get clear by a desperate effort and throw himself into the arms of our especial enemy, Yuan Shu. These two as allies would be difficult to overcome. Rather send a capable man to guard the South of River Huai, one able to secure you against Lu Bu on one hand and to hold Yuan Shu on the other. Moreover the bandits are in Huashang Mountains and still our enemies. They must be watched.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'I can keep the whole of Huashang Mountains, and I will request Liu Bei to take the south.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Could I dare withstand your command?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 206, 'talk': "You ought to attack Cao Cao's army as they come up, before they have time to make camps and defenses. They will only have a fatigued army to oppose to your fresh troops, and you will certainly defeat them.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'I have suffered too many defeats lately to take any risk. Wait till they actually attack, and you will see them floating away on the waters.', 'context': 'So said Chen Gong, but Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 486, 'talk': 'When I heard that your family and that of Yuan Shu were likely to be united by marriage, I sent an army against you. Yuan Shu was guilty of treason, while you had to your credit on the destruction of Dong Zhuo. For what reason have you sacrificed all your merits to throw in your lot with a rebel? It will be over late to regret when this city shall have fallen. But if you surrender and help me to support the ruling house, you shall not lose your rank.', 'context': 'Cao Cao addressed him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'If the Prime Minister will retire, we may be able to discuss the matter.', 'context': 'Lu Bu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'My oath, but I will slay you at least!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'They have come from far and cannot maintain this for long,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'The advice seems good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'My lord, you are leaving an undamaged city, abandoning your wife and little ones, and going with a paltry force. Should any untoward event happen, will your handmaid and her lord ever meet again?', 'context': 'She said, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'The enemy are all round the city, and unless you go out soon you will be quite hemmed in.', 'context': 'Lu Bu hesitated and for three days made no move. Then Chen Gong came to see him again and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'I am thinking it would be better to maintain a stubborn defense,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'You are my lord and my life; you must not be careless and ride out alone.', 'context': 'And she wept bitterly. Lu Bu very sadly went to take leave of Diao Chan who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'You need not fear; with my mighty trident halberd and Red−Hare, who dare come near me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'That story about supplies for Cao Cao is all false, one of his many ruses. I am not going to stir.', 'context': 'He went out. But when he met Chen Gong, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'We shall die, and no person shall know our burial place,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'You ought to send a strong escort with us to force a way through.', 'context': 'Xu Si said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'How is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Formerly he slew my messenger and repudiated the marriage; now he sends to ask for it.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'It is all due to the vile plans of that monster Cao Cao. If pray you, Illustrious Sir, consider it carefully,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'But if your master was not hemmed in by his enemy and in imminent danger, he would never have thought of renewing this proposal of marriage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'You may decide not to help him, but the teeth are cold when the lips are gone. It will not make for your happiness and comfort.', 'context': 'The messengers said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Lu Bu is unreliable; tell him that I will send soldiers after the girl has arrived here.', 'context': 'Said Yuan Shu, “'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'We must wait the night falls, and Wang Kai and I will try to get through in the darkness; the escort of He Meng remaining behind to protect our rear.', 'context': "This was final, and the two messengers took leave and headed back to Xiapi. When the party reached Liu Bei's camp, Xu Si decided, “"},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'We are in the most important place with regard to the South of River Huai, and you must be very careful not to allow any breach of this command.', 'context': 'Every soldier felt mightily afraid. Liu Bei returned to camp and cautioned his brothers, saying, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 204, 'talk': "We have just captured one of the enemy's leaders, and there is no word of praise or reward for us; nothing but new orders and threats. What do you make of that?", 'context': 'Zhang Fei was inclined to grumble, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'You are wrong to complain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'These are orders of the Commander−in−Chief, and what would happen were there no orders? Do not disobey them, Brother.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'But how can she be sent?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 225, 'talk': "That is the difficulty. He Meng's capture means that Cao Cao knows the whole plan of getting help from the South of River Huai. I do not see how any one but you yourself could hope to get through the close siege.", 'context': 'Xu Si said, “'},
{'istart': 228, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'Suppose we tried, today?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'This is an ill−omened day; you must not try today. Tomorrow is a very lucky day, especially in the evening, for any military action.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'Get ready three thousand troops for the venture, and prepare a light carriage. I will lead the first seventy miles; thence you can escort the bride−elect the remainder of the way to her new home.', 'context': 'Then Lu Bu ordered Zhang Liao and Gao Shun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Stop!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 329, 'talk': 'Though Zhang Yang, who meant to hurt us, is happily no more, yet we are threatened on the north by Yuan Shao, and on the east Liu Biao and Zhang Xiu are a menace. Here we meet with no success against the city of Xiapi. We are for leaving Lu Bu to his fate and returning home. What do you think?', 'context': 'Then he called a counsel, saying, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 370, 'talk': 'You must not act like this. Lu Bu has lost much, and his spirit is broken. The spirit of the leader expresses that of his army; and when the leader fails, his soldiers do not fight. Chen Gong is clever, but nothing is done. Lu Bu broken, Chen Gong without decision, it only needs a sharp attack, and we shall succeed.', 'context': 'Among them Xun You fought against the idea, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I have a plan to propose—', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'a plan to overcome the city at once; it is better than two hundred thousand troops.', 'context': ' said Guo Jia, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'I suppose you mean drowning the city by River Si and River Yi,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'That is it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Why should I fear? My good horse can go as well through the water as over the land.', 'context': 'Lu Bu said, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I am injuring myself with wine; no more from this day forward.', 'context': 'one day, he was startled at the change and said to himself, “'},
{'istart': 530, 'iend': 771, 'talk': 'By your virtue of warlike renown, I have recovered my horses; and as my comrades come with their congratulations, I brew some bottles of wine, first to offer Your Lordship and second to ask your permission to have a little wine at the feast.', 'context': "Now one of his generals, Hou Cheng, lost fifteen horses, stolen by one of his subordinates, Hou Cao, who intended to resell them to Liu Bei. Hou Cheng found out where the horses were, went out after them, and recovered them after killing Hou Cao. And Hou Cheng's colleagues congratulated him on his success. To celebrate the occasion, Hou Cheng brewed a few barrels of wine to be drunk at the feast, But thinking his chief might find him in fault, Hou Cheng sent the bottles of wine to Lu Bu's palace with a petition explaining, “"},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'When I have forbidden all wine, you brew some and begin to give feasts; you are simply defying me!', 'context': 'Lu Bu took it very angrily, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'You ought to lose your head for this disobedience; but for the sake of your colleagues, the punishment shall be reduced to a hundred strokes.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Had it not been for you I should have been put to death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'He is a beast, with neither a sense of humanity nor of right. Let us leave him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'He is not worth fighting for. The best we could do would be to seize him and hand him over to Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 208, 'talk': "I was punished because I got my horses back again, yet all he trusts in is his own Red−Hare. If you two will betray the gate and seize Lu Bu, I will steal the horse and go out to Cao Cao's camp.", 'context': 'said Wei Xu. “'},
{'istart': 552, 'iend': 582, 'talk': 'Lu Bu has been captured alive!', 'context': "Lu Bu was taking a rest in the tower and fell asleep in his chair. Song Xian sent away Lu Bu's attendants; and when they had gone, he stole Lu Bu's weapon, the trident halberd in which he trusted. Then Song Xian and Wei Xu fell upon Lu Bu together and before he was well awake had bound him with cords, trussing him so that he could not move. Lu Bu shouted for his guards, but they were driven off by the two traitor generals and could not come near. Then a white flag was shown, and the besiegers again approached the city. The traitors shouted out, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'The bonds are very tight,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I beseech you to loosen them!', 'context': ' cried he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Bindings a tiger must binding tight, of course,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'What have you to say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I hope you have been well since we last saw each other, Chen Gong?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Your ways were crooked, and so I left you,', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'You say I was crooked; and what of your serving Lu Bu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Though he was a fool, he did not resemble you in deceit and wickedness.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'You say you are able enough and clever, but what about your position today?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': "What think you ought to be done about this day's work?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'There is death for me today, and that is the end!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Very well for you; but what of your mother and wife and children?', 'context': ' said Chen Gong undauntedly. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 324, 'talk': "It is said that one who rules with due regard to filial piety does not harm a person's family; one who would show benevolence does not cut off the sacrifices at a person's tomb. My mother and wife and children are in your hands. But since I am your prisoner, I pray you slay me quickly and not to try to harrow my feelings.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Let his mother and family be taken to Xuchang and looked after immediately. Any postponement will be punished!', 'context': 'Turning to his guards Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'What do you think?', 'context': 'myself, and I am on your side now. You take the lead, I will help you, and together the world is at our feet.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'You are willing to forget the episodes of Ding Yuan and Dong Zhuo?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Truly the lout is not to be trusted!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Strangle and expose!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'You long−eared lout, you forget now the service I rendered you that day at my camp gate, when my arrow hit the mark!', 'context': 'As he was led away, Lu Bu turned once more to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Lu Bu, O fool! Death is but death, and why are you scared at it?', 'context': 'Just then some one shouted, “'},
{'istart': 123, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'He has a familiar face.', 'context': 'It was recorded earlier that the executioners were hustling Zhang Liao forward. Pointing to him from above, Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'You were not likely to forget me; you saw me before in Puyang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'O, so you remember me, eh?', 'context': ' said Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Yes; more is the pity.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Pity for what?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'That the fire that day was not fierce enough to burn you up, rebel that you are.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'How dare you insult me?', 'context': 'Cao Cao began to get angry. “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, I pray thee stay thy hand!', 'context': 'behind Cao Cao caught his arm, and in front of him another dropped on his knees, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'A man as generous−hearted as he is should be saved,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'I know him well as loyal and righteous. I will vouch for him with my own life!', 'context': 'Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'I also know Zhang Liao to be loyal and good; I was just testing him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has rendered great services. You must wait till he has been received in audience and obtained his reward. After that he shall be sent here.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
