{'istart': 18, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'I have been a bird in a cage, a fish in a net. This is like the fish regaining the open sea and the bird soaring into the blue sky. I suffered much from the confinement.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'He is going to cut off Yuan Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'Formerly, when he was Imperial Protector of Yuzhou, we recommended that he should be put to death, but you would not hear of it. Now you have given him an army. You have allowed the dragon to reach the sea, the tiger to return to the mountains. What control will you have in future?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 250, 'talk': "Even if you would not put him to death, you need not have let him go. As the proverb says, 'Relax opposition for one day and age−long harm ensues.' You must admit the truth of this.", 'context': 'So spoke Cheng Yu; and Guo Jia followed in the same strain, saying, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Surely they are pursuing us.', 'context': 'Liu Bei was marching as rapidly as possible when he noticed a cloud of dust in the rear and remarked to his brothers, “'},
{'istart': 250, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'Sir, on what business have you come?', 'context': 'He halted and made a stockade, and ordered his brothers to be in readiness, one on each flank. Presently the messenger arrived and found himself in the midst of an army ready for battle. Xu Chu dismounted and entered the camp to speak with Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister has sent me to request you to return as he has further matters to discuss with you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 255, 'talk': "When a general has once taken the field, even the royal command is of no effect. I bade farewell to the Emperor, I received the Prime Minister's commands, and there can be nothing further to talk about. You may return forthwith and take that as my reply.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister cherishes a friendship with Liu Bei, and I have no orders to kill. I can only return with this reply and ask further instructions.', 'context': 'Xu Chu was undecided what action to take. He thought, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'This refusal to return means enmity,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Still, two of my people are with him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 484, 'talk': "Yuan Shu's arrogance had driven away his generals, Lei Bo and Chen Lan, who had returned to their mountain fastness in Mount Song. His forces thus reduced, he wrote resigning the imperial style he had assumed in favor of his brother Yuan Shao, who at once commanded his presence. Thereupon he packed up the palace fittings he had made, got the remnants of his army in order, and marched west.", 'context': 'Scouts were sent out to see what Yuan Shu was doing. They came back with the intelligence: “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'O rebellious one, and wicked, I have a command to destroy you. Yield, then, with good grace and so escape your punishment!', 'context': 'As soon as the enemy came near, Liu Bei began to abuse him, crying, “'},
{'istart': 194, 'iend': 277, 'talk': 'Base weaver of mats and mean maker of straw sandals! How dare you make light of me?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'There is no water, save that tainted with blood,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Where can I get honeyed water?', 'context': ' replied the cook. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': "The power was in Liu Bei's hands, and so these two had no alternative,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'You should instruct Che Zhou, the Imperial Protector Deputy, to try to destroy him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'If I do not receive them, they will suspect my loyalty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Yet if I go out, I may be victim of a ruse.', 'context': ' said Che Zhou. “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'It is too dark to distinguish friends from foes. You must wait till daylight.', 'context': 'So he went up on the wall and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'If Liu Bei know our presence, he will attack,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 145, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Where is Zhang Liao?', 'context': 'Presently Che Zhou girded on his armor, placed himself at the head of one thousand cavalry and went out. He galloped over the bridge, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Wretch!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'You would plot to slay my brother, would you?', 'context': ' cried Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 285, 'iend': 358, 'talk': 'I have slain the traitor. You others need not fear if you only surrender.', 'context': 'the drawbridge, Chen Deng shot out flights of arrows, wherefore Che Zhou turned aside and galloped along under the wall. But Guan Yu came quickly in pursuit. His sword was raised aloft, and as it came down, Che Zhou fell to the earth. Guan Yu cut off his head and returned, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'But what will Cao Cao think of this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'And he may come.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'If he does, we can meet him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 88, 'talk': "We have slain one of Cao Cao's best officers, and how will he stand that?", 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Never mind!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 122, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'I have a plan.', 'context': ' cried Chen Deng. “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 276, 'talk': "Yuan Shao is Cao Cao's terror. He is strongly posted in an extensive territory of four regions—Jizhou, Qingzhou, Youzhou, and Bingzhou—with one million fighting soldiers and numerous able officers. Write letters and pray him rescue you.", 'context': 'This was the plan proposed to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'But we have never had any dealings with each other, and he is unlikely to do such a thing for one who has just destroyed his brother.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'There is some one here whose family have been on intimate terms with the Yuans for a hundred years. Yuan Shao would surely come if he wrote.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'And who is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'A man you know well and respect greatly; can you not guess?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'You surely mean Zheng Xuan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'That is he,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 141, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'Only one man has penetrated the inner meaning of my instructions, and that one is Zheng Xuan.', 'context': 'Naturally the master admired his pupil. After Zheng Xuan had finished his studies and gone home, Ma Rong praised him to the others, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'What are you doing there in the mire?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Liu Bei destroyed my brother, and I ought not to help him, but out of consideration for the writer of this letter I must.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 462, 'talk': 'Do not raise an army. The people are worn out, and the granaries are empty with these constant wars. Let us rather report the recent victory of Gongsun Zan to the Throne. If that does not reach the Emperor, then memorialize that Cao Cao is hindering the government. Then raise an army: occupy Liyang, assemble a Yellow River fleet in Henan, prepare weapons, send out your various divisions, and within three years you will win all round.', 'context': 'Adviser Tian Feng said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 215, 'talk': "I do not agree. The military genius of our illustrious lord having overcome the hordes of the north, to dispose of Cao Cao is as simple as turning one's hand; it is not a matter of months.", 'context': 'Adviser Shen Pei replied, “'},
{'istart': 178, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'You two have wide experience, how would you decide?', 'context': 'Thus the four advisers differed and wrangled, and Yuan Shao could not decide which to follow. Then there came two others, Xu You and Xun Shen, and, seeing them, Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'A letter from Zheng Xuan the Chair has arrived, counseling me to support Liu Bei in an attack on Cao Cao. Now am I to send an army or not send an army?', 'context': 'The two made their obeisance, and Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Send! Your armies are numerous enough and strong enough; you will destroy a traitor and help the dynasty.', 'context': 'They both cried with one voice, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Your words just express my desire,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'In order to manifest the righteousness of your attack on Cao Cao, it would be well to issue a manifesto with a summary of his various crimes.', 'context': 'When the arrangements were complete, Guo Tu went to his chief, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 344, 'talk': 'The rank of lordship, with feudal rights over five thousand households and a money reward of five millions, will be the reward of the one who brings the head of Cao Cao. No questions will be asked of those who surrender. I publish abroad this notice of my bounty and the rewards offered that you may realize that the dynasty is in real danger.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 248, 'iend': 263, 'talk': 'Who wrote this?', 'context': "servants took the paper to the sick man's room. He read it and was frightened from the tips of his hair to the marrow of his very bones. He broke out into a cold perspiration, and his headache vanished. He bounded out of bed and said to Cao Hong, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': "They say it is Chen Lin's brush,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 198, 'talk': "They have the literary gift; they would rather have the military too to back it up. This fellow may be a very elegant writer, but what if Yuan Shao's fighting capacity falls short?", 'context': 'Cao Cao laughed, “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'You should not fight with Yuan Shao; he is too strong. Make peace.', 'context': 'Cao Cao called his advisers together to consider the next move. Kong Rong heard of the summons and went to Cao Cao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'He is despicable; do not make peace.', 'context': 'Xun Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'His land is wide and his people strong. He has many skillful strategists like Guo Tu, Xu You, Peng Ji, and Shen Pei; loyal leaders like Tian Feng and Ju Shou; and formidable generals like Yan Liang and Wen Chou; able commanders like Gao Lan, Zhang He, Han Meng, and Chunyu Qiong. You cannot say he is despicable.', 'context': 'Kong Rong replied, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 549, 'talk': 'His army is a rabble. One general, Tian Feng, is bold but treacherous; another, Xu You, is greedy and ignorant; Shen Pei is devoted but stupid; Peng Ji is steady but useless. And these four of such different temperaments, mutually incompatible, will make for confusion rather than efficiency. The brave Yan Liang and Wen Chou are worthless and can be disposed of in the first battle; and the others such as Gao Lan, Zhang He, Han Meng, and Chunyu Qiong are poor, rough stuff. What is the use even of their hundred thousands?', 'context': 'Xun Yu laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'They are even as Xun Yu describes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'The two Liu Dai and Wang Zhong sent against Liu Bei are unequal to their task.', 'context': 'Adviser Cheng Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'I know,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister orders an attack; you advance.', 'context': "Suddenly orders came for the Cao Cao's army to attack, and then discord showed itself. Liu Dai said, “"},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'You were named first.', 'context': 'Wang Zhong replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'I am the Commander−in−Chief; it is not my place to go first.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I will go with you in joint command,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Let us cast lots, and he upon whom the lot falls must go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 207, 'talk': "There is dissension in Yuan Shao's camp at Liyang, so they do not advance. We do not know where Cao Cao is, but his own banner is not displayed in his Liyang's camp. Why then is it shown here?", 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'His tricks take a hundred forms. It must be that he regards the north as more important and has gone there to look after its defense. He dares not show his flag there, and I feel sure it is only meant to mislead us. He is not here.', 'context': 'Chen Deng replied, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'I fear you are unsuited for this,', 'context': 'Liu Bei then asked whether one of his brothers would find out the truth, and Zhang Fei volunteered to go. “'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'You are too impetuous.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'If Cao Cao is there, I will haul him over here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Let me go first and find out,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'If you go, I shall feel more at ease,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is here; why do you not surrender?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'Beg him to come to the front, for I would speak with him,', 'context': ' said Wang Zhong. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Is he likely to come out to see such as you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Who are you? What office do you hold? How dare you falsely display the ensigns of the Prime Minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'What do you mean by falsely when I simply obeyed my orders?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'My master wanted to produce the impression that he was present. Really he was not there.', 'context': ' said Wang Zhong. “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'I knew you had peaceful intentions in your mind; therefore, I captured Wang Zhong instead of slaying him.', 'context': 'Guan Yu said to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': "I was afraid of Zhang Fei's hasty and impulsive temper,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'He would have slain this man. So I could not send him. There is no advantage in killing persons of this sort, and while alive they are often useful in amicable settlements.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'You have got this Wang Zhong; now I will go and get the other man.', 'context': 'Here Zhang Fei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'Be careful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'Liu Dai was once Imperial Protector of Yanzhou, and he was one of the nobles who met at Tiger Trap Pass to destroy Dong Zhuo. He is not to be despised.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I do not think him worth talking about so much. I will bring him in alive just as Second Brother did this other.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I fear that if his life be lost, it may upset our designs,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'If I kill him, I will forfeit my own life,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 337, 'iend': 412, 'talk': 'Wait till I am ready to start tonight; you shall be sacrificed to the flag.', 'context': "After some days Zhang Fei evolved a ruse. He issued orders to prepare to rush the enemy's camp at night, but he himself spent the day drinking. Pretending to be very intoxicated, he held a court−martial, and one soldier was severely flogged for a breach of discipline. The man was left bound in the midst of the camp, Zhang Fei saying, “"},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'Hitherto Zhang Fei has been rather violent, but this time he has acted wisely, and I am very pleased.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'You said I was too rough; how now?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'If I had not put you on your mettle, you would not have evolved this stratagem,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'My young brother was rather hasty, but you must pardon him.', 'context': 'the cords, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'We are deeply grateful that you spare our lives, and we will certainly do so in gratitude for what our wives and children owe you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'My brother made a mistake in letting you go; he did not understand. How could he give freedom to two rebels?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 169, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'Do not behave so disgracefully!', 'context': 'This made the two men quake with fear, but as the fierce eyed warrior with uplifted sword was bearing down upon them, they heard another man galloping up and shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Why do you stop them since our brother set them free?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'If they are let go today, they will surely come back,', 'context': ' cried Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 145, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Wait till they do, then you may kill them,', 'context': ' cried Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'Even if the Prime Minister slay our whole clans, we will never come again. We pray you pardon us.', 'context': 'The two leaders with one voice cried, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'If Cao Cao himself had come, I would have slain him. Not a breastplate should have gone back. But for this time I leave you your heads.', 'context': 'Said Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Cao Cao will certainly come,', 'context': 'Clapping their hands to their heads the two men scuttled off while the two brothers returned to the city. “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'You shameful traitors, what use are you?', 'context': 'Liu Bei was not disaffected. But their master was exceeding angry with them, crying, “'},
{'istart': 167, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'You knew these two were no match for Liu Bei, and if you put them to death because they failed, you will lose the hearts of your people.', 'context': 'At the close of the last chapter the two unsuccessful leaders, Liu Dai and Wang Zhong, were in danger of death. However, Kong Rong remonstrated with Cao Cao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 179, 'iend': 376, 'talk': 'The weather is too inclement. We must wait the return of spring. In the interval, we better use the time to arrange peace with Zhang Xiu and Liu Biao, before launching an expedition against Xuzhou.', 'context': 'Wherefore the death sentence was not executed, but they were deprived of rank and status. Cao Cao next proposed to lead an army himself to attack Liu Bei, but Kong Rong advised, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'The war had ceased for the moment on account of the winter,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'As you, General, and Liu Biao are both well reputed officers of the state, I have been sent to request your help.', 'context': ' replied the messenger. “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'You can return to your master and say that as he could not brook rivalry of his brother, he certainly would be sorely put to it with that of all the officers of the state.', 'context': 'Jia Xu laughed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'But his master, Yuan Shao, is stronger than Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'You have torn up his letter and are dismissing his man. What shall we say about such an insult should Yuan Shao come?', 'context': ' protested Zhang Xiu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Better join hands with Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'But there is still between us an unavenged enmity; we could not suffer each other.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 261, 'talk': 'If the Prime Minister had any thought of the old quarrel, he would hardly have sent me to make friendly engagements, would he?', 'context': 'Zhang Xiu, now convinced, became more reasonable and recalled Liu Ye, who, at the interview, extolled the many virtues of his master. “'},
{'istart': 217, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Forget that little fault of mine, I pray you, General!', 'context': 'So Zhang Xiu and his adviser proceeded to the capital where formal submission was made. At the interview Zhang Xiu bowed low at the steps, but Cao Cao, hastening forward, took him by the hand and raised him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'A scholar of reputation is required to aid as a messenger of state; can you undertake this task?', 'context': 'Kong Rong. Cao Cao agreed and sent Xun You to speak with this officer. So he went to Kong Rong, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'I have a certain friend, Mi Heng, whose talents are ten times mine. He ought to be constantly at the court of the Emperor and not merely be sent as a state messenger. I will recommend him to the Emperor.', 'context': 'Kong Rong replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 1107, 'talk': "In our day Lu Cui and Yan Xiang, remarkable for their talents, have been appointed among the secretaries. And Mi Heng is no less capable. Should he be got, then all possibilities may be realized; the dragon may curvet through the celestial streets and soar along the Milky Way; fame will extend to the poles of the universe and hang in the firmament with rainbow glory. He would be the glory of all the present Ministers and enhance the majesty of the Palace itself. The Music will acquire new beauties, and the Palace will contain an excellent treasure. People like Mi Heng are but few. As in the recitation of 'Ji Chu Songs' and the singing of 'Yang E Poems,' the most skillful performers are sought; and such fleet horses as 'Fei Tu Broncos' and 'Yao Miao Mustangs' were looked for by the famous judges of horses, Wang Liang and Bo Le; so I, the humble one, dare not conceal this man. Your Majesty is careful in the selection of servants and should try him. Let him be summoned as he is, simply clad in his serge dress; and should he not appear worthy, then may I be punished for the fault of deception.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 246, 'iend': 300, 'talk': 'Wide as is the universe, it cannot produce the person.', 'context': 'The Emperor read the memorial and passed it to his Prime Minister, who duly summoned Mi Heng. He came, but after his formal salutations were over, he was left standing and not invited to sit down. Looking up to heaven, he sighed deeply, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Under my orders are scores of people whom the world call heroes. What do you mean by saying there is not the person,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I should be glad to hear who they are,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 434, 'talk': "Xun Yu, Xun You, Guo Jia, and Cheng Yu are all people of profound skill and long views, superior to Xiao He and Chen Ping. Zhang Liao, Xu Chu, Li Dian, and Yue Jin are bravest of the brave, better than Cen Peng and Ma Wu. Lu Qian and Man Chong are my secretaries; Yu Jin and Xu Huang are my van leaders; Xiahou Dun is one of the world's marvels, Cao Ren is the most successful leader of the age. Now say you there are not the people?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Sir, you are quite mistaken,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 864, 'talk': "I know all these things you call people. Xun Yu is qualified to pose at a funeral or ask after a sick man; Xun You is fit to be a tomb guardian; Cheng Yu might be sent to shut doors and bolt windows; and Guo Jia is a reciter of poems; Zhang Liao might beat drums and clang gongs; Xu Chu might lead cattle to pasture; Yue Jin would make a fair reader of elegy; Li Dian could carry dispatches and notices; Lu Qian would be a fair armorer; Man Chong could be sent to drink wine and eat brewers' grains; Yu Jin might be of use to carry planks and build walls; Xu Huang might be employed to kill pigs and slay dogs; Xiahou Dun should be styled 'Whole Body General,' and Cao Ren should be called 'Money−grubbing Governor.' As for the remainder, they are mere clothes shelves, rice sacks, wine vases, flesh bags.", 'context': ' said Mi Heng with a smile. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'And what special gifts have you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 350, 'talk': 'I know everything in heaven above and the earth beneath. I am conversant with the Three Religions and the Nine Systems of Philosophy. I could make my prince the rival of Kings Yao and Shun ((two ideal kings)), and I myself could compare in virtue with Confucius and Mencius ((two great philosophers)). Can I discuss on even terms with common people?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 137, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'I want another drummer boy to play on occasions of congratulation in the court. I will confer this office upon him.', 'context': 'Now Zhang Liao was present, and he raised his sword to strike down the impudent visitor who spoke thus to his master, but Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'He spoke very impertinently;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'why did you not put him to death?', 'context': ' said Zhang Liao, “'},
{'istart': 295, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'Tolling of Yuyang,', 'context': 'Soon after Cao Cao instituted a banquet in the capital at which the guests were many. The drums were to be played, and the old drummers were ordered to wear new clothes. But the new drummer Mi Heng took his place with the other musicians clad in old and worn garments. The piece chosen was the “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Why did you not put on your new uniform?', 'context': 'on the shabby performer, the attendants said, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Why do you behave so rudely at court?', 'context': 'born. The assembled guests covered their faces. Then the drummer composedly drew on his nether garments. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': "To flout one's prince and insult one's superiors is the real rudeness,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'So you are pure! And who is foul?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': "Mi Heng is only guilty of a misdemeanor like Fu Yue',", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'He is not a man likely to disturb your dreams, Illustrious Sir.', 'context': ' cried Kong Rong. “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'I will send you to Jingzhou as my messenger; and if Liu Biao surrender to me, I will give you a post at court.', 'context': 'Pointing to Mi Heng, the Prime Minister said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'When Mi Heng comes, we will not rise to salute him.', 'context': 'Xun Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'What is that for?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Should not one cry out when one enters a coffin?', 'context': ' said Xun Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'We may be corpses,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'but you are a wandering headless ghost.', 'context': ' shouted they altogether, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': "I am a minister of Han and not a partisan of Cao Cao's,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'You cannot say I have no head.', 'context': ' cried Mi Heng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'I am paltry, and yet I have the soul of a man, and you are mere worms,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Why did you not put the fellow to death for lampooning you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'You see he shamed Cao Cao, but Cao Cao did not kill him as Cao Cao feared to lose popular favor. So Cao Cao sent him to me, thinking to borrow my hand to slay him and so suffer the loss of my good name. I have sent him on to Huang Zu to let Cao Cao see that I understood.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 483, 'talk': 'As you have now two offers, you can please yourself and choose your own way to destroy your enemies; for if one refuses, you can follow the other. Now Cao Cao is an able general and has many capable officers in his train. It looks as though he may destroy Yuan Shao and then move his armies across the river. I fear, my lord, you would be unable then to withstand him. That being so it would be wise to support Cao Cao, who will treat you with respect.', 'context': 'Then Commander Han Song said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'You go to the capital and see how things tend. That will help me to decide.', 'context': 'Liu Biao replied, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'The positions of master and servant are clearly defined. Now I am your man prepared to go all lengths for you and obey you to the last, whether in serving the Emperor or in following Cao Cao. But lest there should be any doubt you must remember that if the Emperor gives me any office, then I shall become his servant and shall not be ready to face death for you.', 'context': 'Han Song said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'You go and find out what you can. I have ideas in my mind.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 290, 'talk': 'This man came to spy out how things were moving. He has done nothing to deserve reward, and yet you give him an office like this. There were no such suspicious rumors connected with poor Mi Heng, and yet you sent him off and would never test his power.', 'context': 'Adviser Xun Yu remonstrated, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 129, 'talk': "Mi Heng shamed me too deeply before all the world. I am going to borrow Liu Biao's hand to remove him. And you need say no more,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'You turn your back on me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I did not betray you.', 'context': ' cried Han Song. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Han Song had foretold this possibility before he left; it is only what he expected.', 'context': 'Kuai Liang remarked, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'You were in Xuchang,', 'context': 'over the wine cups. Both being worse for liquor they had begun to discuss the worth of people. “'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Who was there of worth?', 'context': ' said Huang Zu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'The big boy was Kong Rong and the little one Yang Xiu. There was no one else to count.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'What am I like?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'You are like a god in a temple; you sit still and receive sacrifice, but the lack of intelligence is pitiful.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Do you regard me as a mere image?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Alas!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'The putrid bookworm has just cut himself up with his own sharp tongue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Our business is settled!', 'context': 'Presently Wang Zifu and the others were announced. As they were coming in, Wang Zifu cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I should be glad to hear how,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 554, 'talk': 'Liu Biao has joined Yuan Shao, and five hundred thousand troops in fifty legions are on their way here by different routes. More than this, Ma Teng and Han Sui are coming from the northwest with seven hundred thousand Xiliang troops. Cao Cao has moved every soldier outside Xuchang to meet the combined armies. There is a great banquet in the Palace tonight; and if we get together our young men and servants, we can muster more than a thousand, and we can surround the Palace, while Cao Cao is at the banquet, and finish him off. We must not miss this.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Cao Cao, you rebel, stay!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Do you really wish to destroy Cao Cao?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Do not be frightened, O Uncle,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'I fear you may not be true to me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 146, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'I am afraid our schemes will come to nought,', 'context': 'Ji Ping at once bit off a finger as a pledge of his faith. And then his host and patient brought forth the decree he had received in the girdle. “'},
{'istart': 210, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'Liu Bei and Ma Teng are gone, and there is nothing we can do. That was the real reason I fell ill.', 'context': ' said Dong Cheng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': "It is not worth troubling you gentlemen with; for Cao Cao's life lies in these hands of mine,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'How can that be?', 'context': ' said Ji Ping. “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'If only you could do it! You would be the savior of the dynasty; it depends upon you.', 'context': 'next he calls me, I only have to give him one dose and he will certainly die. We do not want any weapons.” “'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 392, 'talk': 'Wang Zifu, Wu Zilan, Chong Ji, Wu Shi, Ma Teng, and my master have been meeting secretly. My master has a roll of white silk, with writing on it, but I do not know what it means. Yesterday, Ji Ping bit off one of his fingers as a pledge of fidelity. I saw that.', 'context': 'Cao Cao at once had him taken into a secret chamber and questioned him. Quin Quington gave the names of the conspirators, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'The rebel is done for,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'One draught will cure this disease,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'You should take it hot,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Then there will be a gentle perspiration, and you will be better.', 'context': ' said the doctor. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'You are a scholar,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'and know what is the correct thing to do. When the master is ill and takes drugs, the attendant first tastes them; when a man is ill, his son first tastes the medicine. You are my confidant and should drink first. Then I will swallow the remainder.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, sitting up, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': "Medicine is to treat disease; what is the use of any one's tasting it?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 328, 'iend': 404, 'talk': 'I am not ill; I only wanted to test you. So you really thought to poison me!', 'context': 'But he guessed now the conspiracy had been discovered, so he dashed forward, seized Cao Cao by the ear, and tried to pour the potion down his throat. Cao Cao pushed it away, and it spilt. The bricks upon which it fell were split asunder. Before Cao Cao could speak, his servants had already seized the assailant. Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'I thought you were a physician; how dared you try to poison me? Some one incited you to this crime; and if you tell me, I will pardon you.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'You are a rebel; you flout your Prince and injure your betters. The whole empire wishes to kill you. Do you think I am the only one?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'I have failed, and I can but die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'There is not much to amuse us today, but I have a man to show you that will sober you.', 'context': 'Tables were laid in the private apartments, and after several courses the host said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Bring him in!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Cao Cao, you rebel! What are you waiting for? Why not kill me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'The conspirators were only six at first; you made the seventh. Is that true?', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'Still there is something I want to speak about, so I have asked you to stay for a time longer. I do not know what you four have been arranging with Dong Cheng.', 'context': 'Presently Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Nothing at all,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'And what is written on the white silk?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 7, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Well, what have you seen and where?', 'context': 'said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Ji Ping tried to pour poison down my throat. Who told him to do that if it was not Dong Cheng?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'So far,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Why did you not come last night?', 'context': 'Cheng came out to receive his visitor, who at once said, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'I am not quite well yet and have to be very careful about going out,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 184, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'One might say you were suffering from national sorrow, eh?', 'context': ' replied Dong Cheng. “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Have you heard of the Ji Ping affair?', 'context': 'Dong Cheng started. Cao Cao continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'No; what is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'How can it be you do not know?', 'context': 'Cao Cao smiled coldly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 189, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'This man,', 'context': 'Dong Cheng was much put about and knew not what to do. Soon the gaolers led in the physician to the steps of the hall. At once the bound man began to rail at Cao Cao as rebel and traitor. “'},
{'istart': 236, 'iend': 358, 'talk': 'has implicated Wang Zifu and three others, all of whom are now under arrest. There is one more whom I have not caught yet.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, pointing to Ji Ping, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Who sent you to poison me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Quick, tell me!', 'context': ' continued Cao Cao, turning toward the physician. “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Heaven sent me to slay a traitor!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'You were born with ten fingers; how is it you have now only nine?', 'context': 'Dong Cheng sat looking at him, his heart feeling as if transfixed with a dagger. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'I bit off one as a pledge when I swore to slay a traitor.', 'context': 'Ji Ping replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Now they are all off; that will teach you to make pledges.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Still I have a mouth that can swallow a traitor and a tongue that can curse him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Do not. I cannot endure any more punishment, I shall have to speak out. Loosen my bonds.', 'context': 'Ji Ping said, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Loose them. There is no reason why not,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 88, 'talk': "It is Heaven's will that thy servant has been unable to remove the evil.", 'context': 'bowed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Do you know this man, Uncle?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Yes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'So the runaway servant is here; he ought to be put to death.', 'context': ' cried Dong Cheng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'He just told me of your treachery; he is my witness,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Who would dare kill him?', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'How can you, the First Minister of State, heed the unsupported tale of an absconding servant?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'And how can you rebut their evidence?', 'context': 'have Wang Zifu and the others in prison,” said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'You mean rat!', 'context': 'did so and found the decree that had been given him in the girdle and the pledge signed by the conspirators. “'},
{'istart': 141, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'You dared do this?', 'context': ' cried Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'girdle', 'context': 'The last chapter closed with the discovery of the “'},
{'istart': 196, 'iend': 481, 'talk': 'Illustrious Sir, the means by which you impress the world and direct the government is the command of the House of Han. In these times of turmoil and rivalry among the nobles, such a step as the deposition of the ruler will certainly bring about civil war and is much to be deprecated.', 'context': " decree and the assembly of Cao Cao's advisers to consider the deposition of Emperor Xian. Cheng Yu spoke strongly against this, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Does Your Majesty know that Dong Cheng conspired against me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Dong Zhuo died long ago,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Not Dong Zhuo—Dong Cheng!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Really I did not know!', 'context': "The Emperor's heart trembled but he gasped out, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'So the cut finger and the blood written decree are all forgotten, eh?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Immure her in one of the palaces till her confinement. Do not harm her now!', 'context': 'Said the Emperor, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Do you wish me to spare her offspring to avenge the mother?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I pray that my body may be spared mutilation and not put to shame,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Do not hate me in the below realms of the Nine Golden Springs,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'Any one of the imperial relatives by marriage who enter the Palace will be put to death, and the guards will share the same punishment for lack of zeal.', 'context': 'When leaving the Palace, Cao Cao gave strict orders to the keepers, saying “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'The conspirators in the capital have been removed, it is true, but there are yet two others, Ma Teng and Liu Bei. These must not be left.', 'context': 'Then said Cao Cao to his counselor Cheng Yu, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 482, 'talk': 'Ma Teng is strong in the west and would not be easily captured. He might be enticed to the capital by suave words and kindly praises, when he would be at your mercy. Liu Bei is at Xuzhou, strongly posted in an ox−horn formation, and not to be lightly attacked. More than this, Yuan Shao is at Guandu, and his one desire is to attack you. Any attempt on the east will send Liu Bei to Yuan Shao for help, and Yuan Shao will come here at once. Then what will you do?', 'context': 'Cheng Yu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'You are at fault,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is a bold warrior; and if we wait till he is fully fledged and winged, he will be more difficult to deal with. Yuan Shao may be strong, but he is not to be feared. He is too undeciding to act.', 'context': ' replied Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'If I attack Liu Bei, then Yuan Shao is to be feared; what do you think of it?', 'context': 'As they were discussing these things, Guo Jia came in, and Cao Cao suddenly referred the matter to him. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'This advice is in harmony with my thinking,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Why this disarray, my lord?', 'context': 'But Yuan Shao was of melancholy countenance, and his dress was all awry. Tian Feng said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'I am about to die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'But why do you utter such words?', 'context': ' replied Yuan Shao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'I have three sons, but only the youngest is clever enough to understand my ideas. Now he is suffering from scabies which places his life in jeopardy. Think you that I have any heart to talk over any other affairs?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'But,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'the present combination of circumstances is unparalleled. Cao Cao is going to attack the east, and Xuchang will be empty. You can enter it with a few volunteers and so perform good service to the Emperor and save the people from sorrow. You have only to make up your mind to act.', 'context': ' said Tian Feng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'I know the chance is excellent, but I am worried and distressed and fear failure.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'What are you distressed about?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Among my sons only this special one is remarkable; and if anything happens, I am done.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 7, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Go home and tell Liu Bei the real reason, and say that if anything untoward happen, he can come over to me, and I will find some means of helping him.', 'context': 'Qian, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'It is such a pity!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Do not be troubled, Brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'That would be according to the rules of war,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'From what direction was the wind at the time, and what was the color of the flag?', 'context': 'Xun Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'The wind was from the southeast, and the flag was blue and red.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'There is only one interpretation: A raid on the camp will occur tonight.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'My thinking tells me it means a night raid,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'This is evidently providence,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 161, 'talk': "Guan Yu is there, in charge of his brother's family, and he will defend the city to the last. If you do not take it quickly, Yuan Shao will get it.", 'context': 'Xun Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'I have always loved Guan Yu, both for his warlike abilities and his principles. I would engage him to enter my service. I would rather send some one to talk him into surrender.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'He will not do that;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'his sense of right is too solid. I fear any one who went to speak with him would suffer.', 'context': ' said Guo Jia, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'I know him slightly and I will go.', 'context': 'Then suddenly a man stepped out, saying, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 288, 'talk': 'Though you are an old acquaintance, I do not think you are equal to talking over Guan Yu. But I have a scheme that will so entangle him that he will have no alternative; he will have to enter the service of the Prime Minister.', 'context': 'The speaker was Zhang Liao. Cheng Yu looked at him and said, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 486, 'talk': "Since Guan Yu is far braver than ordinary warriors, he can only be overreached by superior cunning. Now send some of the captured soldiers who have lately been of Liu Bei's army into Xiapi, where they shall say they have come back. They shall thus be our allies on the inside. Then an attack and a feigned defeat will entice Guan Yu to a distance from the city. And his return road shall be cut.", 'context': 'The plan to seduce Guan Yu from allegiance to his brothers was now announced by Cheng Yu, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Are you come to fight me, Zhang Liao?', 'context': 'When within speaking distance, Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'I am come to see you because of our old friendship.', 'context': ' replied Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Then naturally you have come to talk me over,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Not so.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Then you desire to help me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Not exactly that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Then what are you doing here if you have not come to help me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'This is certainly talking me over,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Though escape is impossible yet I am not perturbed. I look upon death as going home. You would better depart quickly and let me go down and begin the struggle again.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Surely you must know everybody will ridicule you when they hear of this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'I shall die for loyalty and righteousness. Who will laugh?', 'context': ' said Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'You would be guilty of three faults if you died.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Tell me them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 864, 'talk': "First of all, you and your elder brother pledged yourselves in the Peach Garden to die or to live together. Now your brother has been defeated, and you want to fight to the death. Therefore, if your brother appear again by and by and wants your help, he will seek it in vain. Is this anything else than betraying the Peach Garden Oath? Secondly, you are in charge of your brother's family and, if you fought and died, the two women would be left forlorn and without a protector. That would be a betrayal of trust. Thirdly, your military skill stands out conspicuous and will go down in history. If you do not aid your brother in his noble attempt to maintain the dynasty, then all your labors and sufferings will have been spent to win a worthless reputation as a valiant fool. Where is the sense in that? I feel it my duty to point out these three faults to you.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'You have spoken of my three faults. What do you desire?', 'context': 'Then he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 386, 'talk': 'You are surrounded with the certainty of death if you do not yield. There is no advantage in a useless death. Wherefore your best course is to yield to Cao Cao till you hear news of Liu Bei and can rejoin him. Thus you will ensure the safety of the two ladies and also keep inviolate the Peach Garden compact. You will preserve a useful life. Brother, you must reflect on these things.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'Brother, you have spoken of three advantages; now I have three conditions. If the Prime Minister concede these, then will I doff my armor. If he refuses, then I prefer to be guilty of the three faults and die.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Why should the Prime Minister not concede them? He is most liberal and large minded. I pray you let me hear your conditions.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 564, 'talk': 'The first is that as I and the Imperial Uncle have sworn to support the Hans, I now submit to the Emperor and not to His Prime Minister Cao Cao. The second condition is that suitable provision be made for the two ladies under my care and that no one shall be allowed to approach them. The third is that I shall be allowed to set off to rejoin Uncle Liu Bei so soon as I shall hear where he is, whether it be far or near. I require all these to be satisfied; failing a single one, I will not submit. Wherefore, Zhang Liao, I pray you hasten back and announce them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 158, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'As I am the Minister of Han, so am I Han. I grant that.', 'context': "Zhang Liao lost no time but rode back to Cao Cao. When he spoke of Guan Yu's intention to submit to the Hans but not to Cao Cao, the latter laughed, saying, “"},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 319, 'talk': 'I will give them twice the regular amount for an Uncle of the Emperor; as for securing them from molestation, that is simple. The ordinary domestic law is enough. Why should there be any doubt?', 'context': 'Zhang Liao then spoke of provision due to their rank and security from molestation for the ladies, to which Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Whenever he shall get news of the whereabouts of Liu Bei, he must go to him.', 'context': 'Then said Zhang Liao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'What you say is much to the point. I will grant the three conditions,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Now I expect the army to withdraw so that I may enter the city to tell the two ladies what has been arranged. After that I submit at once.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Do not do this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'I fear treachery.', 'context': ' said Xun Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'He will certainly not break faith,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'He is too high principled.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I apologize for having caused you to feel alarmed.', 'context': 'He bowed to them below the steps and said, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'Where is the Uncle?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'I know not whither he has gone.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'What do you intend to do, Brother−in−Law?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'I went out of the city to try a last battle. I was surrounded on a hill top, and Zhang Liao has urged me to yield. I proposed three conditions, all of which were conceded, and the enemy drew off to allow me to return to the city. Unless I have your decision, Sisters−in−Law, I scarcely dare to take any final step.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 384, 'iend': 735, 'talk': "When Cao Cao's army came in, we took it to mean certain death. But it is scarcely credible that not a hair of our heads has been disturbed; not a soldier has dared enter our doors. You have accepted the conditions, Brother−in−Law, and there is no need to ask our consent. Our only fear is that he will not let you go by and by to search for the Uncle.", 'context': ' They asked what were the conditions and were told. Lady Gan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Sisters−in−Law, you need not be anxious. I will see to that.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'You must decide everything and need not ask us.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'The leader of a defeated army is grateful for the graciousness that has preserved his life,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'I have so long admired your loyalty and high principles that this happy meeting gratifies the desire of my whole life,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'As the Prime Minister has granted the three requests which my friend petitioned for on my behalf, there is now but little to discuss,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'As I have spoken, so be it; I could not break faith,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'Whenever I hear where Uncle Liu Bei is, I must certainly go to him, even if through fire and water. It may be that there will be no time nor opportunity of saying farewell. I trust you will understand the reason.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'If Liu Bei should prove to be alive, you must certainly be allowed to go to him. But I fear that in the confusion he may have lost his life. You may set your mind at rest and let me make inquiries.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 324, 'iend': 369, 'talk': 'Brother−in−Law, you may retire when you wish.', 'context': "Cao Cao also presented him with ten most lovely serving girls; Guan Yu sent these also within to wait upon his two sisters−in−law. Every third day Guan Yu went to the door of the women's quarters to inquire after their welfare, and then they asked if any news of the wanderer had come. This ceremony closed with the words: “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Why so very thrifty?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'It is not thrift,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'How very high principled!', 'context': 'me of him. I could not allow the new gift to eclipse his old one.” “'},
{'istart': 142, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Why this grief, Sisters−in−Law?', 'context': 'themselves on the ground and were weeping. They would not say why. Guan Yu set his dress in order, went over, and knelt by the door, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'In the night I dreamed that the Uncle had fallen into a pit. I woke up and told Lady Mi, and we think he must be dead. So we weep.', 'context': 'Lady Gan replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Dreams are not to be credited,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'You dreamed of him because you were thinking of him. Pray do not grieve.', 'context': ' he replied. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'My sisters−in−law have been weeping for my brother, and I cannot help being sad in sympathy.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'How many hairs in your beard?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'My beard is rather long, Your Majesty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Really a most beautiful beard!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Why is it so thin?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'My worthless body is rather heavy and really too much for it. It is always out of condition.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Do you recognize it?', 'context': 'glowing charcoal, and a handsome creature in every way. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Why, it is no other than Red−Hare!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Yes; it is Red−Hare,', 'context': ' cried Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 172, 'iend': 412, 'talk': 'I have given you many things, lovely handmaids and gold and silks and never won a bow of gratitude from you before. This horse seems to please you better than all the rest. Why do you think so poorly of the damsels and so much of the steed?', 'context': 'And he presented the horse, all fully caparisoned, to his guest. Guan Yu bowed many times and thanked him again and again, till Cao Cao began to feel displeased and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'I know the horse; it can travel five hundred miles a day, and I am very lucky to get him. Now as soon as I find out where my brother is, I can get to him in a single day,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I will try to find out,', 'context': 'leave me. Do you know if it is really so?” “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'I recommended you to the Prime Minister, and you have not lost much by that.', 'context': 'So Zhang Liao took an early opportunity of seeing Guan Yu, and when the politeness of the visit were over, Zhang Liao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'I am deeply affected by his kindness and bounty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'but, though my body is here, yet I am always thinking of my brother.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'I know only too well that he has been most kind, but I have also received great kindness from Uncle Liu Bei. Beside we have sworn to die together, and I cannot remain here; but before I go, I must try to render the Prime Minister some signal service to prove my gratitude.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Supposing Liu Bei should have left the world, whither will you go?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'I will follow him to the below realms of Nine Golden Springs.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': "To serve one's chief with unswerving fidelity is a proof of the highest principle of all,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Why should I not be sad when I have failed towards my country and my family?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I have long wished to attack Xuchang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'When Cao Cao attacked Xuzhou and Xuchang was undefended, you let the chance slip by. Now that Xuzhou has been captured, and their soldiers are flushed with victory, it would be madness to attempt it. It is necessary to await another chance.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Let me think about it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is a rebel. I think you are failing in your duty if you do not attack him.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Your words are good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 102, 'talk': "Neglect your servant's wise words, and you will fail in the field.", 'context': 'Tian Feng bowed his head and said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'I go with the army. If we succeed, then nothing can exceed our glory, but if we are defeated, the risk I run is great.', 'context': 'all his possessions, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'You are not the sort of man to measure my best generals,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'Illustrious Sir, the army is mobilized; I volunteer for the van leader.', 'context': 'Cao Cao moved his armies hastily. As soon as the news of battle got about, Guan Yu went to see the Prime Minister and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'I scarcely dare put you to such inconvenience, but presently, if need arises, I will call upon you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 120, 'talk': "You are one of Lu Bu's famous veteran generals; can you give battle to this Yan Liang?", 'context': 'once served under Lu Bu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'What a terrible leader!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'He has slain my comrade, I want to go and avenge him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Now, who again dares face him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'I can produce a man the equal of Yan Liang.', 'context': 'Then Cheng Yu went to see his chief, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Who?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'No other than Guan Yu.', 'context': ' cried Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'I am afraid that if he is given an opportunity to perform that return service he spoke of, he will leave me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 254, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'You may get news of the Uncle on the journey,', 'context': 'will look askance at Liu Bei and put him to death. Liu Bei gone, where can Guan Yu go?” This argument appealed to Cao Cao at once, and he sent to request Guan Yu to come. Previous to obeying the call, Guan Yu went to say farewell to his sisters−in−law. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Yes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Let me look at him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'See how formidable these soldiers of the North of Yellow River are,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'I regard them as so many clay fowls and mud dogs,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'His head looks as though it was stuck on a pole for sale,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'He is very terrible. You must not despise him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'I am a poor thing but I will go over and bring you his head if you like.', 'context': 'Guan Yu rose, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Joking is not allowed in this army,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Please be careful what you say, General.', 'context': ' interposed Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'You are more than human, General!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'What have I done to talk about?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'My brother, Zhang Fei, did the same thing in an army of a hundred legions, and did it as easily as picking something from his own pocket.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'If you meet this Zhang Fei, be careful.', 'context': 'Cao Cao marveled at the statement and turning to those about him said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Who was this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 85, 'talk': "It must have been Liu Bei's brother, Guan Yu; it could be nobody else.", 'context': 'Ju Shou said, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 408, 'talk': 'Pray hear one word, Illustrious Sir, before you decide. I have lost sight of my brother since my misfortune at Xuzhou and know not whether Guan Yu be dead or alive. There are many men in the world who resemble him. Is every red−faced man with a beard named Guan Yu? Should you not rather seek some evidence?', 'context': 'As the last chapter closed, Liu Bei had been condemned to die. Liu Bei spoke up, however, and said, “'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'By wrongly regarding what you said, I nearly killed an innocent person.', 'context': 'Now Yuan Shao was impulsive and facile by nature, and when Liu Bei spoke thus, he suddenly turned upon Ju Shou, saying, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Yan Liang and I were as brothers, and can I allow any other to avenge his death?', 'context': 'Soon from the lower end a voice was heard, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'You cannot do it; he will fail,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'The proper course is to hold Yenjin and detach a force to Guandu. If you rashly cross the river and anything goes wrong, not a soul will return.', 'context': ' said Ju Shou. “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'That is always the way with you fellows, always delaying and taking the dash out of the army. You put off today and postpone tomorrow till success has become impossible. Do you forget that promptitude is what each soldier honors?', 'context': 'Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'Superiors do not curb their ambitions; inferiors crave for achievements; things are undone. Eternal is the course of Yellow River, shall I change it?', 'context': 'The adviser withdrew sadly, saying. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'I have received much kindness at your hands and have been unable to show my gratitude. I would accompany General Wen Chou that I may repay your bounty and also that I may hear news of my brother.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has been so often defeated that it will augur ill for success this time. Since you wish, I will give Liu Bei command of the rear guard of thirty thousand soldiers.', 'context': 'But the former objected, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What is this reversal for?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'When the supplies are in rear, they are liable to be plundered. So I have put them first.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'But if you meet the enemy and they steal them?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Wait till the enemy appears; I shall know what to do.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 262, 'iend': 419, 'talk': "Wen Chou's army is approaching, and the supply train has been abandoned and is at the mercy of the enemy. The main body is still far behind; what to do next?", 'context': 'Lu Qian was much exercised at this new move of the Prime Minister. In the meantime the supply train moved along the river toward Yenjin. Presently the foremost troops raised a great shout, and Cao Cao sent to see what it meant. The messenger came back, saying, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'We will take refuge here for the present.', 'context': 'Thereupon Cao Cao pointed to two mounds, saying, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'The rebels are near; we ought to catch the horses and go back to Baima.', 'context': "Wen Chou's soldiers approached under cover. As they drew near, the officers told Cao Cao, saying, “"},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'These are a bait for the enemy; why retire?', 'context': 'But Adviser Xun You checked them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'He understands; do not say anything.', 'context': 'Cao Cao glanced across at him and said, “'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'There is one of the most famous generals of the north; who can capture him?', 'context': 'Then standing on the top of a mound Cao Cao pointed to the flying leader, calling out, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Wen Chou, do not run away!', 'context': 'Zhang Liao and Xu Huang both mounted and dashed after him, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Cease shooting, you rebel!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Stop!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 349, 'iend': 373, 'talk': 'Guan Yu, Lord of Hanshou', 'context': 'Liu Bei, with the thirty thousand reserve troops, appeared on the battle field on the other bank of the river. At once they told him that the red−faced, long−bearded warrior was there and had slain Wen Chou. Liu Bei hastily pressed forward to try to get a look at the warrior. He saw across the river a body of horse and the banners bore the words “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Then it is my brother, and he is really with Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'Again that fellow Guan Yu has been in the battle; he killed Wen Chou. Liu Bei pretends ignorance of him.', 'context': 'Yuan Shao, bringing reinforcements, reached Guandu and built a stockade. Two advisers, Guo Tu and Shen Pei, went in to see him and said, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'The long−cared rebel! How dare he do such a thing?', 'context': 'Their master was angry and railed at Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'What crime have I committed?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'You sent your brother to slay one of my generals. Is that no crime?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'Pray let me explain before I die. Cao Cao hated me and has always done so. Now he has found out where I am and, fearing that I may help you, has got my brother to destroy your two generals, feeling sure that when you heard of it, you would be angry and put me to death. You cannot fail to see this.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 302, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'What he says is sense,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'If I got Guan Yu, he would be ten times better than the Yan Liang and Wen Chou that I have lost,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Only Xun You understood that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'I should like to have the opportunity of performing some service by destroying these rebels.', 'context': 'Guan Yu hearing this said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'You have already rendered noble services for which you have not been properly requited. I could hardly trouble you again,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'I have been idle too long; I shall get ill,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'He always cherishes the idea of returning to Liu Bei. He will leave you if he hears any news. Do not let him go on this expedition.', 'context': 'Then Xun Yu said privily to his master, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'If he does well this time, I will not let him go into battle again,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'After we lost sight of each other, I have heard not a word of you; what are you doing here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 243, 'talk': 'After I escaped, I drifted hither and thither till I had the good fortune to reach Runan, and Liu Pi and Gong Du, the Yellow Scarves leaders, took me in. But why are you with Cao Cao, General? And where are your sisters−in−law? Are they well?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 468, 'talk': 'I have heard lately that Liu Bei is with Yuan Shao. I would have liked to go and join him, but I have not found a convenient opportunity. Now the two men I am with have taken the side of Yuan Shao against Cao Cao. By good luck you were coming here so I got command of a small party of scouts to be able to see you and tell you. Presently our two leaders will pretend to be defeated and you, and the two ladies, can go over to Yuan Shao. And you will see your brother.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 164, 'talk': "Since he is there, I certainly must go at once to see him. But it is a misfortune that I have slain two of Yuan Shao's generals. I fear things are not in my favor,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'Let me go first and see how the land lies; I will come back and tell you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'I would risk a myriad deaths to see my brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'You people, why have you risen against the government?', 'context': 'armor, went out to the front of the line of battle, and Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Why do you blame us when you have turned your back on your own lord?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'How have I turned my back on my lord?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is with Yuan Shao, and you are with Cao Cao; what is that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 150, 'talk': "Do not forget your old chief's kindness. Now attack as soon as you can, and I will give up the defense.", 'context': 'followed. Gong Du turned and said to Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Have you been able to get any news of Uncle Liu Bei in your two expeditions?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'None,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Alas! He is dead,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 7, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'Do not weep, ladies; your lord is with Yuan Shao in the North of Yellow River.', 'context': 'said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'How do you know that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I went out with General Guan Yu, and one of the soldiers told me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Brother−in−Law, you should hasten,', 'context': 'you, lest it should become known. Something must be done, but done carefully, and it needs time.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'My lord was there indeed, but I met him not. I see nothing to be glad about.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Is there any difference between the relationship of you two and that of any other two brothers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'Well, now that you know where your brother is, are you going to him?', 'context': 'beside, and prince and minister in addition to both. Our relationship cannot be discussed in usual terms.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'How can I go back on what I said before? I am sure you will explain fully to the Prime Minister.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 151, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'I must find a way to keep him here.', 'context': ' Zhang Liao went back and told his master who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I am Chen Zhen of Nanyang, in the service of Yuan Shao.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'I always wanted to find my brother, but I did not know where he was. How can he think such evil of me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Liu Bei looks for you very eagerly; and if you are still bound by the old pledge, you should go quickly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 291, 'talk': 'Any one born into the world without the essential virtue of sincerity is no true human. I came here openly and can go in no other way. Now will I write a letter which I will ask you to bear to my brother, that as soon as I can take leave of Cao Cao, I will bring the ladies and come to him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'But what if Cao Cao refuse to let you go?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Then would I rather die; I will not remain here.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Then, Sir, quickly write your letter and relieve your brother from his anxiety.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'This means Cao Cao will not let me go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'But I am going, and I shall hesitate no longer.', 'context': ' thought Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'So he has left!', 'context': "In the city, Guan Yu's letter reached the Prime Minister while he was consulting about what to do. He read it and exclaimed, “"},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'With three thousand of mailed horse, I will bring him back alive.', 'context': 'Suddenly from the assembly of officers rose a voice, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'He does not forget his old leader, and he was perfectly open in all his actions. He is a gentleman, and you would do well to follow his example,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'You were exceedingly good to Guan Yu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 329, 'talk': 'but he went off very rudely. He certainly left a screed behind with his reasons, but he affronted you, and that is no light matter. Now to let him join Yuan Shao is to add wings to a tiger. You would better catch him and put him to death so as to guard against future evil.', 'context': ' said Cheng Yu, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'But he had my promise, and can I break my word? Each has his master. Do not pursue.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 162, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'Go slowly, Guan Yu!', 'context': "him but that there was the ladies' carriage to escort, and so Red−Hare had to be held in and go slow. Suddenly Guan Yu heard a shout behind him, a voice crying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Of course you have come to take me back, Zhang Liao?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'No; the Prime Minister, seeing that you are going a long journey, wishes to see you on your way and told me to hasten forward and beg you to wait till he can come up. That is the only thing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Seeing that he is coming along with mailed men, I shall fight to the very last,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Why do you go in such haste, Guan Yu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 386, 'talk': 'I informed you in writing that since my lord was in the North of Yellow River, I had to leave at once. I went to your palace again and again but was refused admittance. So I wrote a letter of farewell, sealed up the treasure, resigned my lordship seal, and left everything for you. I hope you recall the promise you once made me.', 'context': 'Guan Yu inclined his head but did not dismount, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'My desire is to keep my troth with all people; I cannot go back on my word. However, you may find the journey expensive and therefore I have here prepared a sum of money to help you.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'I have sufficient left from your former bounty; keep that for presents to your soldiers.', 'context': 'Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Why should you refuse this? It is but an insignificant return for great services.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'My services have been all trifling, not worth mentioning.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'Really, Guan Yu, you are the most high−principled of humans. I am very sorry my luck is too poor to retain you at my side. Pray accept just this robe to show you I am not quite ungrateful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 177, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'I thank you, Sir Prime Minister, for the robe and trust we shall meet again.', 'context': 'what might happen, would not dismount, but he reached down his sword and took the robe on its point. Then he threw it over his shoulders and turned to thank the giver, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'He is a very rude man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Why do you not take him prisoner?', 'context': ' said Xu Chu, who was of the escort. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 177, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'Sir, I desire you to tell me your name.', 'context': 'The young man dropped his spear, dismounted, and made a low bow. Guan Yu feared this was some ruse, so he only checked his horse and gripped his sword the more firmly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 628, 'talk': 'My name is Liao Hua. I belong to a Xiangyang family. Since these troubled times began I have been an outlaw among the rivers and lakes, and I and my comrades have lived by plunder. We are about five hundred in all. By chance my friend Du Yuan came across two ladies in a carriage just now; and, quite wrongly, he took them prisoners and brought them to the hold in the hills. I questioned the servants and so found out who they were and who was escorting them. So I wished them to be set free to pursue their journey. Du Yuan opposed this and spoke so ill−mannerly that I killed him. And here is his head. I pray you pardon me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Where are the two ladies?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'They are among the hills,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Bring them down here, at once,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Sisters, have you been alarmed?', 'context': 'Then Guan Yu dismounted, laid aside his sword, and stood respectfully before them with his arms crossed. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'We should have suffered at the hands of Du Yuan had it not been for Liao Hua.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'How did Liao Hua come to save the ladies?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Surely you are no other than the slayer of Yan Liang and Wen Chou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'That is so,', 'context': ' said the venerable host. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Come in,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'My two sisters−in−law are in the carriage;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'will you let your women folks go out to receive them?', 'context': ' said Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 289, 'talk': 'I am called Hu Hua. In the days of the Emperor Huan, I was an officer of the court, but I resigned and retired into private life. I have a son, Hu Ban, with Governor Wang Zhi of Yingyang; and if you should be going that way, General, I should like to send him a letter by you.', 'context': 'He replied, “'},
{'istart': 327, 'iend': 349, 'talk': 'Whither are you going?', 'context': "Presently they approached a pass known as the Dongling Pass, guarded by Commander Kong Xiu and five hundred soldiers. When the soldiers saw a carriage being pushed toward the pass, they ran to tell their commander, who came out to accost the travelers. Guan Yu dismounted and returned the officer's salute, and Kong Xiu said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'I have left the Prime Minister to go into the North of Yellow River to find my brother.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 169, 'talk': "But Yuan Shao is my master's rival. You have authority from him to go thither?", 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I left hurriedly and could not get it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'If you have no authority, you must wait while I send to request orders.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'To remain while you send and receive an answer will delay me greatly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'I must stand by my instructions; that is the only thing to do,', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Then you refuse to let me pass?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'If you want to go through, leave the family as a gage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 243, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'Dare you go through, eh?', 'context': 'At this Guan Yu got very angry and made to cut at the commander on the spot, but Kong Xiu withdrew into the gate and beat the drums for an attack. Thereupon the soldiers armed themselves, mounted, and came down to oppose the passage, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Soldiers, do not flee!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'I killed him because I could do no otherwise. I have nothing against you, but I would ask you to tell the Prime Minister how this thing came to pass, that Kong Xiu wished to kill me, and so I slew him in self defense.', 'context': ' cried Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'This Guan Yu must be a fugitive, or he would have a safe conduct. Our only course is to stop him, or we shall incur blame.', 'context': 'Meng Tan, one of his generals, said, “'},
{'istart': 163, 'iend': 318, 'talk': 'The man is fierce and brave. Remember the fate of Yan Liang and Wen Chou. It seems vain to oppose him by force, and so we must think out some trap for him,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'I have a ruse ready,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 300, 'talk': 'I will close the gate with thorny blockades, and I will go to fight with him. I will engage and then flee, and you can shoot him from an ambush along the road. If we can get him and his party and send them prisoners to the capital, we ought to be well rewarded.', 'context': ' said Meng Tan. “'},
{'istart': 247, 'iend': 277, 'talk': 'Who is the traveler who comes?', 'context': 'This course was determined upon, and soon they heard that Guan Yu was approaching. Han Fu strung his bow and filled his quiver with arrows and with one thousand soldiers took up position along the pass. Then as the party approached, Han Fu said, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'He is a certain Guan Yu, Lord of Hanshou, and he wishes to go through the pass.', 'context': 'Guan Yu bowed low and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Have you a letter from the Prime Minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'In the hurry of departure I did not get any.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Who will capture him for me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Your name, General, makes the very earth tremble, and every one looks up to you. This return to the Imperial Uncle proves you to be noble and true.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'it is many a long year since you left Pudong.', 'context': ' said Transverse−Peace, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Yes,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'nearly twenty years.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Do you recognize this poor priest?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I left the village many years ago; I do not recognize you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'My house and yours were only separated by a rivulet,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'I want to invite the General to a feast. You priest fellows seem to have a lot to say,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Not too much,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'Naturally when fellow villagers meet, they talk of old times.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Is this invitation with good intention or evil?', 'context': 'When Bian Xi invited Guan Yu to go into the Hall of the Laws for some refreshment, Guan Yu turned to him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 179, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'What means this? I thought you an honorable man. How dare you?', 'context': 'Bian Xi was so taken aback that he could make no reply, and then Guan Yu saw that many armed men were concealed behind the arras. Then Guan Yu shouted loudly at Bian Xi, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I cannot remain here after this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'I shall pack up my few garments and my alms bowl and take to the road, vague in my wanderings as the clouds in the sky. But we shall meet again and till then take care of yourself.', 'context': ' said Transverse−Peace. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 260, 'talk': "You, General, have been able to get some exercise on the road, but the ladies in their carriage must be cramped and fatigued. I pray you come into the city, and all of you remain the night in the official travelers' quarters. Tomorrow you can set forth again.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 510, 'talk': 'This Guan Yu is a traitor to the Prime Minister and a fugitive. On the road he has murdered several Commanders of Passes and is guilty of serious crimes. But he is too strong and valiant for any ordinary soldier to overcome. So this evening a whole company of a thousand troops will surround his lodging, each one armed with a torch, and we will burn him. They will start the fire about midnight. Every one of the party will perish. I will come with a force to stand by and assist if necessary.', 'context': 'Said Wang Zhi, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'The General is the man in the main hall reading,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Really a god!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Who is there?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 120, 'talk': "I am the Governor's secretary, Hu Ban.", 'context': ' suddenly asked the reader at the sound. Hu Ban entered and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Surely you are the son of Hu Hua, who lives outside Xuchang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'I am he,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'I very nearly caused the death of a good man.', 'context': 'brought. Guan Yu handed it to the secretary, who read it and then breathed long, saying, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 264, 'talk': 'This Wang Zhi is a wicked man, who wanted to kill you. At this moment you are surrounded, and at the third watch they will set fire to this place. Now I will go and open the city gates while you hastily prepare for flight.', 'context': 'Then he betrayed the whole plot, saying, “'},
{'istart': 183, 'iend': 261, 'talk': 'Worthless fellow! What had you against me that you wished to burn me to death?', 'context': 'The fugitives pressed on; but before long they saw lights coming up behind them, and Wang Zhi called out to them to stop. Guan Yu reined in his horse and began to abuse him, crying, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Have you been quite well since we parted?', 'context': 'Guan Yu did not dismount but bowed from horseback, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Whither are you going, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I have left the Prime Minister and am on my way to find my brother.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'That matter was settled long ago.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'But suppose then you provide boats for me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Though there are boats, I dare not give them to you.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Well, formerly I slew Yan Liang and Wen Chou and saved you a grave danger. Now you refuse me a ferry boat!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'I am afraid Xiahou Dun will know of it and make it a fault against me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I am one Guan Yu, Lord of Hanshou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Whither are you bound?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Where is the authority of the Prime Minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'I am not on a mission from the Prime Minister, so why should I have such an authority?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Do you know that I have been the death of all those who have hitherto tried to stop me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'You have only slain a few officers of no rank or reputation; but you dare not kill me!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Where would you stand beside Yan Liang and Wen Chou?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'He who opposed me is dead; you others need not be afraid,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I did not willingly slay a single one of them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'There was no help for it. Nevertheless when Cao Cao hears of it, he will regard me as ungrateful for his bounty.', 'context': ' mused Guan Yu as he rode along. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I have never heard a word from you since we lost sight of each other at Runan; how have you fared?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 793, 'talk': "After your departure Liu Pi and Gong Du retook the city. I was sent by them to Yuan Shao to try to make peace with him and succeeded, so that Yuan Shao invited Liu Bei to go to him and share in the deliberations for a concerted attack on Cao Cao. But to my disgust the leaders of Yuan Shao's army showed great jealousy of each other so that Tian Feng got into gaol, Ju Shou was degraded, and others quarreled. Then Yuan Shao vacillated and hesitated, so that your brother and I consulted how we might get away from them all. Now the Uncle is at Runan with Liu Pi and, thinking you could not know that and might suffer some harm if you unwillingly went to Yuan Shao, I have come to warn you. It is good fortune to find you like this. Now we can hasten to Runan, and you will meet your brother.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 307, 'talk': "Uncle Liu Bei were nearly executed due to Yuan Shao's sudden bursts of anger after the deaths of Yan Liang and Wen Chou. Now, however, he is out of his way and safe at Runan, and you will meet him soon.", 'context': 'Guan Yu took Sun Qian to make his bow to the ladies, who asked after his adventures, and Sun Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'In coming after me thus you do not reinforce the magnanimity of your master!', 'context': 'When they were near enough, Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 250, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister has sent no definite instructions. You have caused the death of several people, among them one of my commanders, and so I have come to capture you! You have behaved most grossly. The Prime Minister will decide.', 'context': 'Replied Xiahou Dun, “'},
{'istart': 139, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'You must not fight with Guan Yu!', 'context': 'Thereupon Xiahou Dun dashed forward with his spear ready to thrust. But at that moment a rider came up behind him at full gallop, crying, “'},
{'istart': 133, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister loves General Guan Yu for his loyalty and honor, and fearing lest Guan Yu might be stopped at the various passes, he sent me with this letter to show when necessary at any point on the road.', 'context': 'Guan Yu stayed his steed at once and waited. The messenger came up, drew from his bosom an official letter, and said to Xiahou Dun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'But this Guan Yu has slain several commanders of the passes; does the Prime Minister know that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Then,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'I will arrest him and take him to the Prime Minister, who may set him free or not as he wills.', 'context': ' said Xiahou Dun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Do you think I fear anything you can do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 186, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'Generals, wait a little!', 'context': 'And he rode forward. Xiahou Dun, nothing loth, set his spear and prepared for battle. They met and had reached the tenth encounter when a second horseman came up at full speed, crying, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Am I to arrest him?', 'context': 'Xiahou Dun stayed his hand and asked the messenger, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'Fearing lest he should have difficulties at the passes, the Prime Minister has sent me with a dispatch to say he is to be released.', 'context': ' replied the messenger. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Did the Prime Minister know that he had slain several commanders on the way?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'He did not know!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Since he was ignorant of that, I may not let this Guan Yu go,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 130, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Guan Yu, give way and do not fight!', 'context': 'But Guan Yu flourished his sword and made to attack them and a fight was again imminent, when a third rider appeared, who cried, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 282, 'talk': "I bring the Prime Minister's order that since he has heard that Guan Yu has slain certain commanders on the way, he fears that some will hinder his passage. Wherefore he has sent me to deliver his command at each gate that Guan Yu is to be suffered to pass freely.", 'context': 'Zhang Liao said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 154, 'talk': "Qin Qi was the son of Cai Yang's sister, and he was confided to my especial care. Now this Guan Yu has killed him and how can I refrain?", 'context': 'Xiahou Dun said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 169, 'talk': "When I see his uncle Cai Yang, I will explain. But now the main point is that you have the Prime Minister's orders to let Guan Yu pass and you may not despise his wish.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Whither are you going?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I fear my brother is no longer with Yuan Shao, and now I am going to find him wherever he is.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'As you do not know where to go, why not return to the Prime Minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Where is the sense of that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'My name is Guo Chang, and I have lived here many years. I am very pleased to greet the man whom I have known so long by reputation.', 'context': 'When they had finished, the old fellow said, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'My son is come to pay his respects.', 'context': 'As the day closed in, they saw several youths come along, and their host said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'This is my humble son,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'What has he been doing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'He has just come in from hunting.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Why unhappily?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'In these days of disorder a good soldier can make a name for himself.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'The young fellow had tried to steal Red−Hare, but had been badly kicked. We heard shouting and went to see what it meant when his men had set on us.', 'context': 'Guan Yu asked what it was all about, and his guards told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'You mean thieves! Would you steal my horse?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Really he is unworthy of his father,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'What you told me shows he is a degenerate. For your sake I pardon him.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'My son has insulted your tiger dignity, I know, and I am deeply affected by your kindness in not punishing him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Bring him here and I will talk to him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'He went out before daylight with a lot of his fellow rogues, and I know not where he is.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'I have heard of the ruddy long beard called Guan Yu, but I have never seen him. Who may you be?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'You did not recognize me; how then did you know my name?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Zhou Cang renders obeisance,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'O Warrior, where have you known me?', 'context': 'Said Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'But if you follow me, what of your companions?', 'context': 'As he seemed thoroughly in earnest, Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'They may do as they please; follow me or go their ways.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'We will follow!', 'context': 'Thereupon they all shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'Brother−in−Law, you have traveled thus far alone and without fighters; you have safely passed many dangers and never wanted their assistance. You refused the service of Liao Hua, why then suffer this crowd? But this is only a my view and you must decide.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'What you say, Sister−in−Law, is to the point.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'It is not that I am lacking in gratitude, but my sisters−in−law do not care for a large following. Wherefore return to the mountains till I shall have found my brother, when I will surely call you.', 'context': 'Therefore returning to Zhou Cang, he said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 357, 'talk': 'I am only a rough uncouth fellow, wasting his life as a brigand. Meeting you, General, is like seeing the full sun in the skies, and I feel that I can never bear to miss you again. As it might be inconvenient for all my people to follow you, I will bid my companion lead them away, but I will come and follow you on foot wherever you go.', 'context': 'Zhou Cang replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'If you do not stay with the band, they will disperse and be lost. You must take command for the moment and let me accompany General Guan Yu. As soon as he has a fixed abode, I will come to fetch you.', 'context': 'Zhou Cang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'To think that I should find my brother like this!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'I have had never a word of him, nor knew I where he was since Xuzhou fell.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu, delighted. “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has left Yuan Shao and gone to Runan; and Guan Yu, with your sisters−in−law, is at the gates. He wishes you to go out and receive them.', 'context': 'As directed by Guan Yu, Sun Qian entered the city and, after the usual ceremonies, told Zhang Fei the news, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Brother, what does this mean? Is the Peach Garden Pledge quite forgotten?', 'context': 'Guan Yu was entirely taken aback and called out anxiously, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'What impudence is this that you come to see me since your disgraceful behavior?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'What disgraceful behavior has been mine?', 'context': ' shouted Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'Brother, why is this?', 'context': 'At this the ladies lifted the curtain of the carriage and called out: “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'When your brother went to Xuchang, no other course was open to him.', 'context': 'Lady Mi also chimed in, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Sisters, do not let him blind you to the truth. Real loyalty prefers death to dishonor. No good person can serve two masters.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Brother, cease to wrench me I pray you.', 'context': 'Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Guan Yu came expressly to seek you.', 'context': 'Sun Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'How much more nonsense will you talk?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Had I come to capture you, I should have come with troops and horses,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'And are there not troops and horses?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Now will you try to cajole me further?', 'context': "soon they were near enough, and from their trumpets and banners they showed themselves to be of Cao Cao's army. “"},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Brother, wait a while; see me slay the leader of these that I may prove myself no traitor.', 'context': 'He set his octane−serpent halberd and was just coming on when Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 350, 'talk': 'The fact is the Prime Minister had not given an order. Incensed at the loss of his nephew, Cai Yang wished to cross the river to pursue and attack you, General, although the Prime Minister refused permission. To satisfy him, the Prime Minister had sent Cai Yang to attack Runan, and the meeting at this place is entirely an accident.', 'context': 'The youth said, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Some scores of horsemen has arrived at the south gate. They seem in a great hurry but no one know them.', 'context': 'Just then messengers came from the city to Zhang Fei to say: “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 613, 'talk': 'After the dispersal at Xuzhou when we lost sight of you, we returned to our village whence we sent all around for news of you. We heard that Guan Yu had surrendered to Cao Cao and our lord was in the North of Yellow River with Yuan Shao. The one of whom we could hear nothing was yourself. But yesterday, while on our way, we fell in with some travelers who told us a certain General Zhang Fei, of such and such an appearance, had suddenly occupied Gucheng, and we felt it must be you. So we came to inquire, and we happily fell in with you here.', 'context': 'Quickly slipping out of the saddle, they came up and Mi Zhu said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Guan Yu and Sun Qian are here, and my two sisters are with them. They had heard where my elder brother was.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei replied, “'},
{'istart': 162, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'No; you take care of the ladies here while Sun Qian and I go to get news.', 'context': 'A day was spent in banquets, and next day Zhang Fei wished his newly found brother to go with him to Runan to see their elder brother Liu Bei. But Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is no longer in the city. After waiting some days, he has come to the conclusion that the soldiers are too few, and has gone back to Yuan Shao to consult with him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'Do not be sorrowful; it only means the trouble of another journey into the North of Yellow River to tell Uncle Liu Bei, and then we can all meet at Gucheng.', 'context': 'Guan Yu was greatly disappointed, and Sun Qian did his best to console him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 289, 'talk': 'Seeing you have this city, it makes a rallying point for us and a resting place. We must not abandon it lightly. Sun Qian and I will go; and while sway we look to you to keep the city safe.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei wanted to go with them into the North of Yellow River, but Guan Yu opposed this, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'How can you go after killing the two generals, Yan Liang and Wen Chou?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'That will not stop me. And after I am there, I can act according to circumstances.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'How many followers are there with Pei Yuanshao at Sleeping Bull Mountain?', 'context': 'Then Guan Yu summoned Zhou Cang and asked him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I should think four or five hundred.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Now,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'What is his age?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'My family name is also Guan, my personal name being Ding,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Jian Yong also is here. We will send for him secretly to talk over this matter.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'My lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'That seems best,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'but will you go with me?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I have another plan to extricate myself,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'I have sent messengers repeatedly to ask his help,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'but he is unwilling.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'As he and I are of the same family, he will not refuse me if I go and ask him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Certainly he is worth much more than Liu Pi; you shall go.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'I have just heard,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Really I like him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'May I send Sun Qian for him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Certainly.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'If Liu Bei goes, he will not come back. I would better go to speak to Liu Biao. And I can keep a watch on Liu Bei.', 'context': 'After Liu Bei had gone, Jian Yong came in and said to Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Do not be too suspicious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Jian Yong is clever enough.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shao. “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'These are of the same name as myself,', 'context': 'Presently the two sons of their host came to bow to the visitors. Liu Bei asked their names. “'},
{'istart': 148, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'The sons are Guan Ning, who is a student, and Guan Ping, who is to be a soldier.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I have been thinking of sending the younger in your train, General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Would you take him?', 'context': ' said old Guan Ding, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'He is eighteen.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Since, O Senior, you are so kind, I venture to suggest that your son should be adopted by my brother, who has no son of his own. What think you of that?', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'Uncle.', 'context': "Guan Ding was perfectly willing, so he called Guan Ping and bade him make a son's obeisance to Guan Yu and to style Liu Bei “"},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 424, 'talk': 'Before I reached the hill, a certain warrior all alone, had fought with my friend Pei Yuanshao and killed him. Then many of our troops surrendered to him, and he occupied our old camp. When I reached it, I tried to allure the soldiers back to my side but only succeeded with a few. The others were too afraid. I got angry and engaged the interloper, who however worsted me time after time and wounded me thrice.', 'context': 'He replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Who is the warrior? What does he look like?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'All I know he is a doughty fighter, I do not know his name.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'O Zhao Yun, I am here to look for you!', 'context': 'Suddenly Liu Bei rode out waving his whip and shouting, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'The first time I saw you, I felt drawn to you and did not want to part from you. I am very happy to meet you again.', 'context': 'Liu Bei told Zhao Yun all that had happened to him since they parted, and so did Guan Yu. Said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'In all my wanderings, trying to find a lord worth serving, I have seen no one like you. Now I have reached your side, that is enough for all my life. I care not what may happen to me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 363, 'talk': 'Liu Bei needs cause you no anxiety; Cao Cao is your one enemy and must be destroyed. Even Liu Biao, though strongly posted on the river, is none too terrible. There is Sun Ce on the southeast of the Great River, strong, feared, with wide domain of six territories, a large army, and able counselors and leaders; you should make an alliance there against Cao Cao.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'He is a lion difficult to contend with.', 'context': 'Cao Cao saw in Sun Ce a powerful rival and said, “'},
{'istart': 285, 'iend': 336, 'talk': 'So you wish to send me to the land of the dead, eh?', 'context': 'But the bearer of this letter was captured on the Great River and sent to Sun Ce, who immediately put him to death. Then Sun Ce treacherously sent to ask the author of the letter to come and consult over some affair. The unsuspecting Xu Gong came. Sun Ce produced the letter, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': "We belong to Han Dang's army and are shooting deer,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 522, 'iend': 560, 'talk': "We are Xu Gong's men and his avengers!", 'context': 'So Sun Ce shook his bridle to proceed. But just as he did so, one of the men thrust at him with a spear and wounded his thigh. Sun Ce drew the sword at his side, dashed forward, and tried to cut down the aggressor. The blade of his sword suddenly fell to the ground, only the hilt remaining in his hand. Then one of the assassins drew his bow, and an arrow wounded Sun Ce in the cheek. Sun Ce plucked out the arrow and shot at the offender, who fell, but the other two attacked him furiously with their spears, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'The arrowheads were poisoned,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Cao Cao fears you, my lord, very greatly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'and his advisers have exceeding respect for you; all except Guo Jia.', 'context': ' said Zhang Hong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'What did Guo Jia say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'The fool, how dare he say this of me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'I will take Xuchang from Cao Cao, I swear.', 'context': ' cried Sun Ce. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': "You are risking your priceless self in a moment's anger,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'My master wishes to ally himself with the South Land in an attack on Cao Cao.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Saint Yu Ji has just gone by, and the officers have gone down to pay their respects to him.', 'context': 'They told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'What wizard fellow is this? Bring him here!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'This is Yu Ji,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'You madman! How dare you incite humans to evil?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 481, 'talk': "I am but a poor priest of the Langye Mountains. More than half a century ago, when gathering simples in the woods, I found near the Diamond Spring a book called 'The Way of Peace.' It contains a hundred and more chapters and taught me how to cure the diseases of humans. With this in my possession I had only one thing to do: to devote myself to spreading its teachings and saving humankind. I have never taken any thing from the people. Can you say I incite people to evil deeds?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'You say you take nothing; whence came your clothes and your food? The fact is you are one of the Yellow Scarves, and you will work mischief if you are left alive.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Take him away and put him to death.', 'context': 'Then turning to his attendants, Sun Ce ordered, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'The Taoist Saint has been here in the east these many years. He has never done any harm and does not deserve death or punishment.', 'context': 'Zhang Zhao interceded, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I tell you I will kill these wizard fellows just as I would cattle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'They tell me you have put Saint Yu Ji in bonds. He has cured many sick people, and the common folk hold him in great reverence. Do not harm him!', 'context': "mother. Lady Wu sent for her son to the ladies' apartments and said to him, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'He is simply a wizard who upsets the multitude with his spells and craft. He must be put to death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Do not heed the gossip of the streets, Mother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I must be judge of these matters.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 537, 'talk': 'Gentlemen, you are all great scholars, but why do you not understand reason? Formerly in Jiaozhou was Imperial Protector Zhang Jing, who was deluded by these vicious doctrines into beating drums, twanging lyres, burning incense, and such things. He wore a red turban and represented himself as able to ensure victory to an army. But he was slain by the enemy. There is nothing in all this, only none of you will see it. I am going to put this fellow to death in order to stop the spread of this pernicious doctrine.', 'context': 'Sun Ce said to them, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'I know very well this Yu Ji can control the weather. It is very dry just now, why not make him pray for rain as an amercement?', 'context': 'Lu Fan interposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'We will see what sort of witchcraft he is equal to,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I will pray for three spans high of refreshing rain for the benefit of the people, nevertheless I shall not escape death thereby.', 'context': 'Said Yu Ji, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'But if your prayer be efficacious, our lord must believe in your powers.', 'context': 'The people said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'The day of fate has come for me, and there is no escape.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'It is near noon,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Clouds are of no account without rain. He is only an impostor.', 'context': ' said Sun Ce. “'},
{'istart': 488, 'iend': 546, 'talk': 'O Clouds, cease thy rain, and let the glorious sun appear!', 'context': 'Sun Ce bade his attendants lay the priest on the pyre and pile wood around him and apply the torch. Fanned by the gale the flames rose rapidly. Then appeared in the sky above a wreath of black vapor, followed by roaring thunder and vivid lightning, peal on peal and flash on flash. And the rain fell in a perfect deluge. In a short time the streets became rivers and torrents. It was indeed a three−span fall. Yu Ji, who was still lying upon the pile of firewood, cried in a loud voice, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Rain or shine are as nature appoints them, and the wizard has happened to hit upon a moment of change; what are you making all this fuss about?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You want to follow Yu Ji in rebellion, I suppose,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'My son, you have done wrong to slay the holy one, and this is your retribution.', 'context': 'They carried him to his chamber, and in a short time he recovered consciousness. His mother, Lady Wu, came to visit him and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 247, 'talk': 'Mother, when I was a boy, I went with Father to wars, where people are cut down as one cuts reed stalks. There is not much retribution about such doings. I have put this fellow to death and so checked a great evil. Where does retribution come in?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'This comes of want of faith,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Now you must avert the evil by meritorious deeds.', 'context': ' she replied. “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'My fate depends on Heaven; wizards can do me no harm, so why avert anything?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'I am the sworn foe of witchcraft, and I will purge the world of all such as deal in magic. You are a spirit, and how dare you approach me?', 'context': 'Sun Ce said, “'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 412, 'talk': "Confucius the Teacher says: 'How abundantly do spiritual beings display the powers that belong to them!' and 'Prayer has been made to the spirits of the upper and lower worlds.' You must have faith. You sinned in putting Saint Yu Ji to death, and retribution is sure. I have already sent to have sacrifices performed at the Jade−Pure Monastery, and you should go in person to pray. May all come right!", 'context': 'She said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Do you see that wizard fellow?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'This temple is nothing more than a lurking place for sorcerers and wizards and such people,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'My son,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'how wasted you are!', 'context': ' said Lady Wu, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'How do I come to look so haggard?', 'context': 'frightened and exclaimed, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'This is the end; I shall die.', 'context': 'reopened and he fainted. He was raised and borne within. When he recovered consciousness, he said, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'In the disordered state of the empire, the domains of Wu and Yue ((two ancient states in the South Land)), with its strong defense of the three rivers and resourceful lands, has a brilliant future. You, Zhang Zhao, must assist my brother.', 'context': 'He gave them his dying charge, saying, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 474, 'talk': 'For manipulating the might of Wu so as to make it the deciding force among the factions and then obtaining the whole empire, you are not so suited as I; but in encouraging the wise and confiding in the able and getting the best out of every one for the preservation of this land, I should not succeed as you will. Remember with what toil and labor your father and I have won what we possess, and take good care thereof.', 'context': 'So saying Sun Ce handed his seal to Sun Quan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'Mother, the days allotted of Heaven have run out, and I can no longer serve my tender mother. I have given over the seal to my brother and trust that you will advise him early and late, and see that he lives worthy of his predecessors.', 'context': 'Sun Quan wept as he knelt to receive the seal, and the dying Sun Ce turned to his mother, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Alas! Your brother is full young for such a task,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'I know not what may happen.', 'context': ' said his mother, weeping. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'He is far abler than I and fully equal to the task of ruling. Should he have doubts upon internal affairs, he must turn to Zhang Zhao; for outer matters he must consult Zhou Yu. It is a pity Zhou Yu is absent so that I cannot give him my charge face to face.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'When I am gone, you must help your brother. Should any discord arise in the family, let the others punish the wrongdoer and let not his ashes mingle with those of his ancestors in the family vaults.', 'context': 'To his brothers Sun Ce said, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 337, 'talk': 'Unhappily we have to part while still in the full vigor of life. You must care for my mother. Your sister will come to see you presently, and you can ask her to tell her husband, Zhou Yu, to help my brother in all things and make my brother keep to the way I have taught him to walk in.', 'context': 'Then he called for his wife, Lady Qiao, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'This is not the time to mourn,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 312, 'talk': 'I have looked well at them all, and they are all clever and perspicacious, but none of them have the very ultimate degree of good fortune. Only the second, Sun Quan, has the look of a deep thinker. His face is remarkable, and his build unusual, and he has the look of one who will come to great honor.', 'context': 'brothers, “'},
{'istart': 200, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'I need have no anxiety now that you have come.', 'context': "When Sun Quan succeeded to his brother and his brother's might, there was still some reorganization to be done. Soon Zhou Yu had arrived Wujun. The young ruler received him very graciously and said, “"},
{'istart': 215, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'I shall exert the puny powers I have in your service as long as I live.', 'context': "When Zhou Yu went to wail at the coffin of his late chief, Lady Wu, the dead man's mother, came out to deliver her son's last injunctions. When she had told him the last charge, Zhou Yu bowed to the earth, saying, “"},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 136, 'talk': "I trust you will not forget my brother's charge to you.", 'context': "Shortly after Sun Quan came in, and, after receiving Zhou Yu's obeisance, said, “"},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'I would willingly suffer any form of death for you.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu bowed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'How best can I maintain this great charge which I have inherited from my father and brother?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'My brother bade me consult Zhang Zhao for internal administration, and yourself on external matters,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 344, 'talk': 'He has always been fond of fencing and horse archery. He was living in Que. His grandmother died while he was there, and he went to bury her in Dongcheng, and then his friend, Liu Ziyang, wished to engage him to go to Chaohu and join Zheng Bao. However, he hesitated about that and has not gone yet. You should invite him without loss of time.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'I have been engaged by Liu Ziyang to go to Chaohu, and I am just starting thither.', 'context': 'Lu Su replied, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 344, 'talk': 'The dynasty is failing, and everything is at sixes and sevens. I have received a great charge from my father and brother, and I am thinking of imitating the actions of the celebrated Protectors of Reign, Wen and Huan, and becoming the leader of the feudal lords, and I pray you instruct me.', 'context': 'In the dead of night Sun Quan said to his bedfellow, “'},
{'istart': 123, 'iend': 322, 'talk': 'It would be mean to take advantage of the period of mourning. And if you should not overcome him, you will make him an enemy instead of being a friend. It would be preferable to treat him generously.', 'context': "Hearing of Sun Ce's death, Cao Cao was for sending an expedition against the south. But Zhang Hong dissuaded him, saying, “"},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'My lord, a hasty attack in full scale will bring disaster to our army. It is best now to wait upon such times as Heaven should appoint.', 'context': "Just as Yuan Shao's army was starting, Tian Feng sent out a remonstrance from his prison cell, saying, “"},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Why does this Tian Feng utter ill−omened words? My lord is sending forth an army in the cause of humanity and justice.', 'context': 'Peng Ji said to Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 177, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'I will punish Tian Feng when I return from conquering Cao Cao.', 'context': 'Easily moved to anger, Yuan Shao was going to execute Tian Feng, but this time he forbore at the entreaties of many of his officers. However, he was not appeased, for he said, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 386, 'talk': 'Though our soldiers are many, they are not so bold as the enemy; however, veterans as are the enemy, they have not ample supplies. Therefore they will wish to force on a speedy battle, while our policy is to hold them off and delay. If we can keep from a decisive battle long enough, the victory will be ours without fighting.', 'context': 'Then Ju Shou once more opposed any hasty movement, saying, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Tian Feng spoke discouraging words to my armies, and I will assuredly put him to death on my return. How dare you follow in the same way?', 'context': 'Said he, threateningly, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'The enemy are many but not terrible. Ours is an army of veterans, every soldier of ours worth ten of theirs; but our advantage lies in a speedy battle, for unhappily our stores are insufficient for a long campaign.', 'context': 'Then said Adviser Xun You, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'You speak to the point,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'I think the same.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'In the presence of the Emperor, I pressed your claims to consideration and obtained for you the title of Regent Marshal; why do you now plan rebellion?', 'context': 'Pointing with his whip at Yuan Shao, Cao Cao cried, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'You take the title of a minister of Han, but you are really a rebel against the House. Your crimes and evil deeds reach to the heavens, and you are worse than the usurper Wang Mang and the rebel Dong Zhuo. What are these slanderous words about rebellion that dare you address to me?', 'context': 'Yuan Shao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I have a command to make you prisoner!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'I have the Girdle Decree to arrest rebels!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 374, 'talk': "Now send one hundred thousand soldiers to guard Guandu, and get near Cao Cao's camp; then build up observation mounds to get a clear view of the enemy, and choose vantage points whence to shoot arrows into the midst of their host. If we can force him to evacuate this place, we shall have gained a strategic point whence Capital Xuchang can be attacked.", 'context': 'Then Shen Pei said, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Let us make catapults and so destroy them.', 'context': 'Liu Ye spoke up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 342, 'iend': 351, 'talk': 'Rumblers,', 'context': "Then Cao Cao's troops watched for Yuan Shao's archers to ascend the towers. As soon as the archers began to shoot, all the catapults began to heave stone balls into the skies and they wrought great havoc. There was no shelter from the falling stones, and enormous numbers of the archers were killed. Yuan Shao's troops called these machines “"},
{'istart': 153, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'The Sappers.', 'context': "Then Shen Pei, the strategist, thought out another plan. He set troops to tunnel under the walls into the midst of Cao Cao's camp and called this corps “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'As Yuan Shao can no longer attack openly, he is attacking secretly and is tunneling a road under ground into the midst of our camp,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'But how to meet it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'We can surround the camp with a deep moat which renders their tunnel useless.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 227, 'talk': "That fellow is a valiant fool. A few thousand light horse sent to intercept him can capture the whole train and cause much trouble in the enemy's camp.", 'context': 'When Xun You heard that the commander of the convoy was Han Meng, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Whom should I send?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'You might send Xu Huang; he is capable of such a task.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'Food is very important for an army in the field and must be defended with the greatest diligence. Wuchao is our main depot and must be carefully guarded.', 'context': 'Then said Shen Pei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'My plans being complete;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'you may as well return to Capital Yejun of Jizhou and undertake the control of the supplies. Let there be no shortage.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shao, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 376, 'talk': 'Cao Cao and we have been at grips here for a long time, and Capital Xuchang must be undefended. A small army sent quickly could take it, and at the same moment an attack here would deliver Cao Cao into our hands. Now is the moment to strike, for his supplies are short.', 'context': 'Seeing from the letter that Cao Cao was short of supplies, Xu You went to Yuan Shao and told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 398, 'iend': 501, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is full of ruses, and this letter is artfully designed to bring about a battle to suit himself.', 'context': ' Yuan Shao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'If you do not take this chance, he will do you some injury by and by.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 423, 'talk': 'How can you have the face to stand before me and propose plans, you extortionate fellow? You and Cao Cao have old liking for each other, and he has bribed you to do his dirty work for him and help his base schemes. Now you want to betray my army. I ought to take off your head, but temporarily I will let your neck carry it away. Get out and never let me see you again.', 'context': 'At this Yuan Shao turned on Xu You angrily and said, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'Faithful words offend his ear. He is a pest and unworthy of advice from me. And now that Shen Pei has injured my son and nephew, how can I look my fellow folks in the face again?', 'context': 'The discredited adviser sighed and went out, saying, “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 175, 'talk': "If Yuan Shao rejects your honest words, then assuredly he will be taken by Cao Cao. You are an old friend of Cao Cao's; why not abandon the shade for the sunlight?", 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'I am an old friend of the Prime Minister; go and tell the Prime Minister that Xu You of Nanyang wishes to see him.', 'context': 'captors: “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Sir, you, a great minister, should not thus salute a simple civilian like me.', 'context': 'Xu You hastened to help him rise, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'But you are my old friend and no name or office makes any difference to us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'If Xu You is willing to come, then have I indeed a helper,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'I counseled him to send a light force to take Capital Xuchang and at the same time attack here in full scale so that head and tail be both attacked.', 'context': 'scheme for the destruction of Yuan Shao.” “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'If he does so, I am lost!', 'context': 'Cao Cao was alarmed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'How much grain have you in store?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'Enough for a year.', 'context': ' said the new adviser. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'I think not quite,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Well, half a year.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'I offer him good counsel and he repays me with deceit. Could I have expected it?', 'context': 'The visitor shook out his sleeves, rose and hurried toward the door of the tent, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Do not be angry,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'I will tell you the truth. Really I have here only enough for three months.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'Everybody says you are a marvel of wickedness, and indeed it is true,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'But who does not know that in war there is no objection to deceit?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 99, 'talk': "Actually here I have only supplies for this month's use.", 'context': "Then whispering in Xu You's ear, he said, “"},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'O do not throw dust in my eyes any more. Your grain is exhausted and I know it.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'How did you find that out?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Who wrote that?', 'context': 'Xu You produced the captured letter, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Where did you get it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Since our old friendship has brought you to me, I hope you have some plan to suggest to me.', 'context': 'Cao Cao seized him by the hand, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 257, 'talk': 'To oppose a great army with a small one is to walk in the way of destruction, unless you inflict quick defeat. I can propose a plan which will defeat the innumerable hordes of Yuan Shao without fighting a battle. But will you follow my advice?', 'context': 'Xu You said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I very much desire to know your plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'The enterprise will be futile as the grain depot will certainly be well guarded. Without caution, we may be victims of the treachery on the part of the newly arrived Xu You.', 'context': 'Zhang Liao protested, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Xu You is no traitor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 370, 'talk': 'He has come sent by Heaven to defeat Yuan Shao. If we do not get grain, it will be hard to hold out; and I have either to follow his advice or sit still and be hemmed in. If he were a traitor, he would hardly remain in my camp. Moreover this raid has been my desire for a long time. Have no doubts; the raid will certainly succeed.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Well, then, you must look out for an attack here while the camp is undefended.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'That is already well provided for,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Some misfortune is near,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'While I happened to be studying the aspect of the heavens,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 439, 'talk': 'I saw Venus, then between Hydra and Cancer, suddenly shoot into the neighborhood of the Bear and Lyra. There is danger of a robber raid, and special precautions must be taken at the grain depot. Lose no time in sending good soldiers and vigorous leaders thither, and keep a lookout on the byways among the hills that you may escape the wiles of Cao Cao.', 'context': ' said the night visitor, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'You are a criminal,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'How dare you come with such wild nonsense to upset my armies.', 'context': ' said Yuan Shao. “'},
{'istart': 151, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'I bade you confine him; why did you let him come?', 'context': ' And turning to the gaolers Yuan Shao continued, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 166, 'talk': "Our soldiers' destruction is at hand, and I know not where our poor corpses may find a resting place.", 'context': 'Ju Shou went away, wiping his falling tears and sighing deeply, “'},
{'istart': 154, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'Jiang Qi has orders to go to Wuchao to guard the grain stores.', 'context': "Cao Cao's raiding party went along through the night. Passing one of Yuan Shao's outpost camps, they were challenged. Cao Cao sent forward a man to say, “"},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'The enemy is coming up in the rear. Send reinforcements.', 'context': "Some of Cao Cao's soldiers ran to him, saying, “"},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Press on to the front till the enemy is actually close at hand and then face about.', 'context': 'But Cao Cao only replied, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 317, 'talk': 'You may not go; it is certain that Cao Cao is there in person, wherefore his camp is undefended. Let loose our soldiers on the camp, and that will speedily bring Cao Cao back again. This is how Sun Bin besieged Wei and thereby rescued Hao ((two ancient states)).', 'context': 'Zhang He offered to go with Gao Lan, but Guo Tu said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'Not so; Cao Cao is too wily not to have fully prepared against a chance attack. If we attack his camp and fail and Chunyu Qiong should be caught, we shall all be captured too.', 'context': 'But Zhang He said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Cao Cao will be too intent on the destruction of the grain to think of leaving a guard. I entreat you to attack his camp.', 'context': 'Guo Tu said, “'},
{'istart': 487, 'iend': 492, 'talk': 'Stop!', 'context': "Now after overcoming Chunyu Qiong, Cao Cao's troops dressed themselves in the armor and clothing of the defeated soldiers and put out their emblems, thus posing as defeated force running back to their own headquarters. And when they happened upon Jiang Qi's rescue body, they said they had been beaten at Wuchao and were retreating. So Cao Cao's troops were suffered to pass without molestation while Jiang Qi hastened on. But soon Jiang Qi came to Zhang Liao and Xu Chu who cried out, “"},
{'istart': 273, 'iend': 327, 'talk': 'The General was intoxicated at the time of the attack.', 'context': "When the remains of the defenders of the grain stores reached their master's camp, they were mustered. Seeing the mutilated state of their one time leader, Yuan Shao asked how Chunyu Qiong had come to betray his trust and to suffer thus, and the soldiers told their lord, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Why do you say this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'O they have long cherished a desire to go over to Cao Cao; so when you sent them on the duty of destroying his camp, they did not do their best and so brought about this disaster.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 293, 'iend': 325, 'talk': 'For what reason are we recalled?', 'context': 'Yuan Shao accordingly sent to recall these two to be interrogated as to their faults. But Guo Tu sent a messenger in advance to warn them, as though in friendly guise, of the adverse fate that awaited them. So when the orders reached them to return to answer for their faults, Gao Lan asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Indeed I do not know,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'Our lord has allowed some one to malign us and say we have been bought by Cao Cao. What is the sense in our sitting still and awaiting destruction? Rather let us surrender to Cao Cao in reality and save our lives.', 'context': 'Gao Lan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'I have been wanting to do this for some time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'If Yuan Shao had listened to you, he would not have suffered defeat. Now you two coming to surrender are like Wei Zi leaving the falling House of Shang to go to Yin and Han Xin leaving Xiang Yu to go over to the rising House of Han.', 'context': 'weapons, removed their armor, and bowed to the ground before Cao Cao, who said, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 398, 'talk': "Now is the moment to spread a report that an army will go to take Suanzao and attack Yejun, and another to take Liyang and intercept the enemy's retreat. Yuan Shao, when he hears of this, will be alarmed and tell off his troops to meet this new turn of affairs; and while he is making these new dispositions, we can have him at great disadvantage.", 'context': 'Then Xun You suggested a plan to Cao Cao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao was so strong that even I could not be sure of safety; how much less other people?', 'context': "Cao Cao's personal staff suggested that the names of those concerned should be abstracted and the persons arrested, but their lord said, “"},
{'istart': 162, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'I will not surrender!', 'context': "Now when Yuan Shao's soldiers ran away, Ju Shou, being a prisoner, could not get away and was captured. Taken before Cao Cao, who knew him, Ju Shou cried aloud, “"},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao was foolish and neglected your advice; why still cling to the path of delusion? Had I had you to help me, I should have been sure of the empire.', 'context': 'Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'I have slain a faithful and righteous man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 400, 'iend': 463, 'talk': 'Had he but listened to Tian Feng, we had not met this disaster.', 'context': 'That evening, sitting in his tent, Yuan Shao seemed to hear a far off sound of lamentation. He crept out quietly to listen and found it was his own soldiers telling each other tales of woe. This one lamented an elder brother lost, that one grieved for his younger brother abandoned, a third mourned a companion missing, a fourth, a relative cut off. And each beat his breast and wept. And all said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'I did not hearken unto Tian Feng, and now my soldiers have been beaten and I was nearly lost. How can I return and look him in the face?', 'context': 'And Yuan Shao, very remorseful, said, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 220, 'talk': "I disregarded Tian Feng's advice and have brought myself to defeat. Now shall I be greatly ashamed to look him in the face.", 'context': 'Next day the march was resumed, and Yuan Shao met Peng Ji with reinforcements, to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'How dare he laugh at me, the blockhead? Assuredly he shall die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Above all humans I felicitate you.', 'context': "Meanwhile Tian Feng's gaoler came to him one day, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'What is the joyful occasion and why felicitate?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Now am I a dead man!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Why say you that, Sir, when all people give you joy?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'The Imperial Protector appears liberal, but he is jealous and forgetful of honest advice. Had he been victorious, he might have pardoned me; now that he has been defeated and put to shame, I may not hope to live.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 153, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'I knew all too well that I should have to die.', 'context': 'But the gaoler did not believe Tian Feng. Before long came the letter and the sword with the fatal order. The gaoler was dismayed, but the victim said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'An able person born into this world who does not recognize and serve the right lord is ignorant. Today I die, but I am not deserving of pity.', 'context': 'The gaoler wept. Tian Feng said, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 432, 'talk': 'As there is nought but war and trouble outside our borders, it is necessary that tranquillity within be early provided for, and I wish to appoint my successor. My eldest son is hard and cruel, my second is mild and unfit. The third has the outward form of a hero, appreciates the wise, and is courteous to his subordinates. I wish him to succeed, but I wish that you tell me your opinions.', 'context': 'When they met to consult, Yuan Shao said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 463, 'talk': 'Yuan Tan is your first born, and he is in a position of authority beyond your control. If you pass over the eldest in favor of the youngest, you sow the seeds of turbulence. The prestige of the army has been somewhat lowered and enemies are on our border. Should you add to our weakness by making strife between father and son, elder and younger brothers? Rather consider how the enemy may be repulsed and turn to the question of the heirship later.', 'context': 'Guo Tu said, “'},
{'istart': 288, 'iend': 325, 'talk': 'Venerable Sirs, what may be your age?', 'context': 'When Cao Cao drew up his victorious army on the banks of Yellow River, the aged natives brought an offering of food and sauce to bid him welcome. Their venerable and hoary appearances led Cao Cao to treat them with the highest respect, and he invited them to be seated and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'We are nearly a hundred,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'I should be very sorry if my army had disturbed your village,', 'context': ' replied the old villagers. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 744, 'talk': 'In the days of the Emperor Huan a yellow star was seen over by way of the ancient states of Chu and Song in the southwest. Yin Kui of Liaodong, who was learned in astrology, happened to be passing the night here, and he told us that the star foretold the arrival in these parts, fifty years hence, of a true and honest man here in the Yellow River. Lo! That is exactly fifty years ago. Now Yuan Shao is very hard on the people and they hate him. You, Sir, having raised this army in the cause of humanity and righteousness, out of pity for the people and to punish crimes, and having destroyed the hordes of Yuan Shao at Guandu, just fulfill the prophecy of Yin Kui and the millions of the land may look now for tranquillity.', 'context': 'One of them said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'How dare I presume that I am he?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Yuan Shao, your schemes are poor, your strength is exhausted, why still refuse to think of surrender? Are you waiting till the sword shall be upon your neck? Then it will be too late.', 'context': 'Cao Cao spoke first, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Who dares go out?', 'context': 'Yuan Shao turned to those about him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 189, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'Any one knows him?', 'context': 'His son Yuan Shang was anxious to exhibit his prowess in the presence of his father, so he flourished his pair of swords and rode forth. Cao Cao pointed him out to his officers and asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'He is the youngest son of Yuan Shao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'Ten Ambushes', 'context': 'When he had returned to camp, Cao Cao took counsel to find a plan to overcome Yuan Shao. Then Cheng Yu proposed the plan of the “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'There is no road in front, so all must fight or die.', 'context': 'Then Cao Cao shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'If we do not make most desperate efforts, we are all captives,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Many battles have I fought, and little did I think to be driven to this. Heaven is afflicting me. You would better return each to his own and swear to fight this Cao Cao to the end.', 'context': 'He sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 381, 'iend': 589, 'talk': 'Jizhou is large and well supplied; Shen Pei is an able strategist and it behooves me to be careful. I would rather wait till the autumn when the crops have been gathered in so that the people will not suffer.', 'context': "Meanwhile Cao Cao was distributing rewards to his army for the late victory, and his spies were scouting all about Jizhou. He soon learned that Yuan Shao was ill, and that the youngest son Yuan Shang and Shen Pei were in command of the city, while his brothers and cousin had returned each to his own. Cao Cao's advisers were in favor of a speedy attack. But he objected, saying, “"},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'I treated you as a guest of the highest consideration; why then do you turn your back on righteousness and forget kindness?', 'context': 'Cao Cao called Liu Bei to a parley, and when the latter appeared under his great standard, Cao Cao pointed his whip at him and railed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Under the name of Prime Minister you are really a rebel. I am a direct descendant of the family, and I have a secret decree from the Throne to take such offenders as you.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Girdle Mandate.', 'context': 'As he said these words, he produced and recited the decree which is known as the “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'If this be true, I have enemies in front and rear and have no place to go.', 'context': 'Quite dismayed, Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'Xu Chu is at the camp gate offering a challenge.', 'context': 'Liu Bei tried to withdraw his troops, fearing all the time an attack from Cao Cao. Suddenly the sentinels came in, saying: “'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'Do not let Liu Bei run away; I, the Prime Minister, am here awaiting you.', 'context': 'After traveling a some miles, they passed some mounds. Suddenly torches blazed out, and on the summit stood one who shouted, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Fear not, my lord, only follow me!', 'context': 'Zhao Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 197, 'talk': "The attack on us was too strong to be resisted, and so we were compelled to abandon the defense, and the enemy followed, and only Guan Yu's timely arrival saved us from destruction.", 'context': 'They told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I do not know where my brother is,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'All will come right if you will push on,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Liu Bei, quickly dismount and surrender!', 'context': 'He with a thousand soldiers. He cried, “'},
{'istart': 133, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'O Heaven, why am I brought to this state of misery? Nothing is left me now but death.', 'context': 'rushing another body of troops under Gao Lan. Thus checked in front and his retreat cut off, Liu Bei looked up to Heaven and cried, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Let me try to fight a way out and save you. Death is nothing to me.', 'context': 'But Liu Pi stayed his hand, saying, “'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 484, 'talk': 'All you, Fair Sirs, have talents fitting you to be advisers to a monarch, but your destiny has led you to follow poor me. My fate is distressful and full of misery. Today I have not a spot to call my own, and I am indeed leading you astray. Therefore I say you should abandon me and go to some illustrious lord where you may be able to become famous.', 'context': 'A feast was given upon a sandy bank of the Han River. After they had drunk awhile, Liu Bei addressed his faithful followers, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Success and failure both have their seasons,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'and we are not to grieve. Jingzhou, which your illustrious relative, Liu Biao, commands, is a rich and prosperous country. Liu Biao is of your house, why not go to him?', 'context': ' said Sun Qian, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Only that I fear he may not receive me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Then let me go and prepare the way. I will make Liu Biao come out to his borders to welcome you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'He is my brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'and I have long desired to see him, but no opportunity has occurred. I should be very happy if he would come.', 'context': ' said Liu Biao, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 414, 'talk': "No, no! Liu Bei first followed Lu Bu, then he served Cao Cao, and next he joined himself to Yuan Shao. And he stayed with none of these, so that you can see what manner of man he is. If he comes here, Cao Cao will assuredly come against us and fight. Better cut off this messenger's head and send it as an offering to Cao Cao, who would reward you well for the service.", 'context': 'Cai Mao, who was sitting by, here broke in, “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 464, 'talk': 'I am not afraid of death. Liu Bei, the Princely One, is true and loyal to the state and so out of sympathy with Lu Bu, or Cao Cao, or Yuan Shao. It is true he followed these three, but there was no help for it. Now he knows your chief is a member of the family, so that both are of the same ancestry, and that is why he has come far to join him. How can you slander a good man like that?', 'context': 'Sun Qian sat unmoved while this harangue was pronounced, saying at the end, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'I have decided, and you need say no more.', 'context': 'Liu Biao bade Cai Mao be silent and said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'My lord should return to the capital to refresh the soldiers so that they may be ready for a north and south campaign in the mild spring weather.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 174, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'You are not yet recovered from the fatigues of last year. It would be better to make your position impregnable and set to improving the army.', 'context': 'As to Yuan Shao, who had been suffering from blood−spitting but was now in better health, he began to think of measures against Xuchang, but Shen Pei dissuaded him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'If we allow the foe to get close to the city before we march to the river, we shall have missed our opportunity; I must go out to repel this army.', 'context': "When the news of Cao Cao's approach arrived, Yuan Shao said, “"},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'Father, you are not sufficiently recovered for a campaign and should not go so far. Let me lead the army against this enemy.', 'context': 'Here his son Yuan Shang interposed, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Is Yuan Shang to succeed?', 'context': 'When his wife put the formal question, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'In your absence, my lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'the two advisers of your younger brother will certainly set him up as lord, wherefore you must act quickly.', 'context': ' said Guo Tu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Those two, Shen Pei and Peng Ji, have already laid their plans,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'If you go, you will meet with some misfortune.', 'context': ' said Xin Ping. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Then what should I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Go and camp near the city, and watch what is taking place while I enter and inquire.', 'context': 'Guo Tu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Why did not my brother come?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'He cannot come as he is in the camp unwell.', 'context': 'Guo Tu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'There is no one in our camp to give advice,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'I wish to have the services of Shen Pei and Peng Ji.', 'context': ' said Guo Tu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I also need the help of these two,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Then let one of these two go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 298, 'talk': "Cao Cao is on the borders, and Peng Ji must be kept here to allay your brother's suspicions. After we have beaten Cao Cao, we can at once make an attempt on Jizhou.", 'context': 'Yuan Tan angrily refused to accept his resignation and was disposed to put him to death, but Guo Tu privately dissuaded him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Let me write to my lord and pray him to come himself.', 'context': 'Peng Ji replied, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 387, 'talk': "Guo Tu, your elder brother's adviser, is very guileful. Formerly he left without discussion because Cao Cao was on the border. If Cao Cao be defeated, there will certainly be an attempt on you. The better plan is to withhold assistance and use Cao Cao's hand to destroy your rival.", 'context': 'So Peng Ji wrote and the letter was sent. When it arrived, Yuan Shang again consulted Shen Pei who said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'If Yuan Tan goes over to Cao Cao, they will both attack Jizhou, and we shall be in great danger.', 'context': 'Yuan Shang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Who dares lead the van?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 455, 'talk': 'There is dissension among the Yuans because the elder has been superseded in the succession. The brothers are about equally strong and each has his party. If we oppose them; they unite to assist each other; but if we have patience, they will be weakened by family strife. Wherefore send first a force to reduce Liu Biao in Jingzhou, and let the fraternal quarrels develop. When they have fully developed, we can smite them and settle the matter.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 487, 'talk': "Brothers are as one's limbs. How can you possibly succeed if at a moment of conflict with an enemy you cut off one of your hands? If you abandon your brother and sever relationship, whom will you take in all the world as a relation? That fellow Guo Tu is a dangerous mischief−maker, who would sow dissension between brothers for a momentary advantage, and I beg you to shut your ears and not listen to his persuasions.", 'context': 'took into his confidence. Wang Xiu opposed the murder plan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 147, 'talk': "I recognize one of Guo Tu's stratagems and if you go, my lord, you will be the victim of their plot. Rather strike at them at once.", 'context': 'Shen Pei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'You poisoned my father and usurped the succession; now you come out to slay your elder brother?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 630, 'talk': "The city is short of food, the enemy is flushed with victory, and we cannot stand against them. My idea is to send some one to offer surrender to Cao Cao and thus get him to attack Jizhou. Your brother will be forced to return thither, which will leave you free to join in the attack. We may capture Yuan Shang. Should Cao Cao begin to get the better of your brother's army, we will lend our force to help Yuan Shang against Cao Cao; and as Cao Cao's base of supply is distant, we shall drive him off. And we can seize on Jizhou and begin our great design.", 'context': 'Yuan Tan asked his strategist what should be done next, and Guo Tu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Supposing this scheme be attempted, who is the man for a messenger?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 161, 'talk': "I have one Xin Pi, Xin Ping's younger brother; he is the magistrate here in this very place. He is a fluent speaker and good scholar and suited to your purpose.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 150, 'talk': "Yuan Tan has been forced into making this offer because of the pressure of his brother's attack. Put no trust in him.", 'context': 'The council met. Cheng Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Gentlemen, not one of you is giving good advice,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 144, 'talk': "But is this surrender of Yuan Tan real or false? Do you really think that Yuan Shang's army is sure to overcome him?", 'context': 'At a banquet Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 1129, 'talk': "Illustrious Sir, do not inquire into the degree of sincerity; rather regard the situation. The Yuans have been suffering military losses for years and are powerless without, while their strategists are put to death within. The brothers seize every chance to speak evil of each other and their country is divided. Add to this famine, supplemented by calamities and general exhaustion, and everybody, wise as well as simple, can see that the catastrophe is near and the time ordained of Heaven for the destruction of the Yuans is at hand. Now you have a force attacking the capital of Jizhou—Yejun—and if Yuan Shang will not return to give aid, the place of refuge is lost. If he helps, then Yuan Tan will follow up and smite him, making use of your power to destroy the remnant of his brother's army, just as the autumn gale sweeps away the fallen leaves. Now Liu Biao's Jingzhou is rich, the government peaceful, the people submissive, and it cannot be shaken. Moreover, there is no greater threat to it than the North of Yellow River. If that be reduced, then the task is complete. I pray you, Sir, think of it.", 'context': 'Xin Pi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'I am sorry that I did not meet you earlier,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'While my father lived, I never treated you badly; why do you support my brother and try to injure me?', 'context': 'Yuan Tan reined in and addressed them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Do not surrender to me but to the Prime Minister.', 'context': 'Yuan Tan said, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Supplies are short and difficult to transport. I must turn the waters of River Ji into the White River whereby to convey my grain and afterwards I can advance.', 'context': 'When Yuan Tan asked Cao Cao to attack Jizhou, the reply was “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 524, 'talk': "He has promised you a daughter to wife. I fear that bodes no good. Now he has given titles of nobility to the two Lus and taken them with him. This is a bait for the northern people, and at the same time he intends evil toward us. You, my lord, should have two generals' seals engraved and send them secretly to the brothers so that you may have friends at court ready for the day when Cao Cao shall have broken your brother's power, and we can begin to work against him.", 'context': 'Guo Tu noted this advancement and said to Yuan Tan, “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'I am going to get Jizhou this time.', 'context': "When Yuan Tan heard of the approach of his brother's army, he sent urgent messages to Cao Cao, who said to himself, “"},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 260, 'talk': "You, Sir, sit here on guard; are you waiting till Heaven's thunder shall strike the two Yuans?", 'context': 'Just at this time it happened that Xun You came down from the capital. When he heard that Yuan Shang was attacking his brother Yuan Tan, he sought Cao Cao and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I have thought it all out,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'The earth within the Pearly Gate is solid enough to be tunneled, and entrance can be effected there,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Feng Li is certain to try to come into the city by an underground road.', 'context': 'So he said to himself, “'},
{'istart': 161, 'iend': 342, 'talk': "The high road will surely be ambushed; we must find some other way. We can take a by−road from the Western Hills and get through by River Fu, whence we can fall upon Cao Cao's camp.", 'context': 'Yuan Shang heard of the defeat of Yin Kai and Ju Gu, and the siege of his own city, and bethought himself of relieving it. One of his commanders, Ma Yan, said, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 341, 'talk': "If Yuan Shang comes by the high road, I shall have to keep out of the way; if by the Western Hills' by−road, I can settle him in one battle. And I think he will show a blaze as a signal to the besieged that they may make a sortie. I shall prepare to attack both.", 'context': "Cao Cao's spies soon found out this move, and when they reported it, he said, “"},
{'istart': 366, 'iend': 567, 'talk': 'As your food supply is short, it would be well for the old people, the feeble soldiers and the women to surrender. This will come upon them as a surprise, and we will send the soldiers out behind them.', 'context': "Li Fu reached the city wall safely and called out to the guards to open. Shen Pei recognized his voice and let him in. Thus Shen Pei knew of the arrangements for his relief, and it was agreed that a blaze should be raised within the city so that the sortie could be simultaneous with Yuan Shang's attack. Orders were given to collect inflammables. Then said Li Fu, “"},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'The populace of Jizhou surrender!', 'context': 'Shen Pei promised to do all this, and next day they hoisted on the wall a white flag with the words “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Ho ho! This means no food,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'They are sending away the non−combatants to escape feeding them. And the soldiers will follow behind them.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'What is the use of such a channel to drown out the city from a deep river?', 'context': 'Shen Pei saw the diggers from the city wall and noticed that they made only a shallow channel. He chuckled, saying to himself, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'The family of the Yuans should be spared when the city should be taken and that no one who surrendered should be put to death.', 'context': 'Cao Cao issued an order: “'},
{'istart': 396, 'iend': 444, 'talk': 'Murder! Blood drinker! You will meet your death.', 'context': 'When Shen Pei, who was on the southeast of the city, saw the enemy within the gates, he placed himself at the head of some horsemen and dashed toward them. He was met and captured by Xu Huang who bound him and led him outside the city. On the road they met Xin Pi, who ground his teeth with rage at the murderer of his relatives and then struck the prisoner over the head with his whip, crying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Traitor! Seller of the city! I am very sorry I was not to have slain you before.', 'context': 'Shen Pei retorted, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Do you know who opened the gate to let me in?', 'context': "When the captive was taken into Cao Cao's presence, Cao Cao said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'No; I know not.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'It was your nephew Shen Rong who gave up the gate,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'He was always unprincipled; and it has come to this!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'The other day when I approached the city, why did you shoot so hard at me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I am sorry we shot too little.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'As a faithful adherent of the Yuans, you could do no otherwise. Now will you come over to me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Never; I will never surrender.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Eighty of my people murdered by this ruffian; I pray you slay him, O Prime Minister!', 'context': 'Xin Pi threw himself on the ground with lamentations, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Alive, I have served the Yuans;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'dead, I will be their ghost. I am no flattering time−server as you are. Kill me!', 'context': ' said Shen Pei, “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'My lord is in the north, I pray you not to make me face the south.', 'context': 'Cao Cao gave the order; they led him away to put him to death. On the execution ground he said to the executioners, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'When the arrow is on the string, it must fly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 196, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': "As was said, Cao Pi, having made his way into the Yuans' palace, saw two women there whom he was about to kill. Suddenly a red light shone in his eyes, and he paused. Lowering his sword he said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Thy handmaid is the widow of the late Yuan Shao, Lady Liu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'and this is the wife of Yuan Xi, his second son. She was of the Zhen family. When Yuan Xi was sent to command in Youzhou, her family objected to her going so far from home and she stayed behind.', 'context': ' said the elder of the two, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'I am the son of the Prime Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'I will guarantee your safety, so you need fear nothing.', 'context': ' said he turning to the elder woman. “'},
{'istart': 154, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Sir Prime Minister, you would not have been here but for my plans.', 'context': 'As Cao Cao was entering the gate of the conquered city of Yejun, Xu You rode up very quickly, passed him, and pointed with his whip at the gate, saying, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'Has anyone had gone in?', 'context': 'Cao Cao laughed, but his generals were very annoyed. When he reached the residence, he stopped at the gate and asked, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Your son is within.', 'context': 'The guard at the gate said, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'But not for your son we had not been saved. I desire to present to you a lady, of the Zhen family, as a handmaid to your son.', 'context': 'Cao Cao called him out and chided him, but the wife of the late Imperial Protector interposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Just the wife for him!', 'context': 'Cao Cao bade them bring out the girl and she bowed before him. After looking at her intently, he said, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Would you fellows be riding through here if it had not been for me?', 'context': 'One day Xu Chu, riding in at the east gate, met Xu You, who called out to him, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'We fellows, those who survive and those who perished, risked our lives in bloody battle to get this city, so do not brag of your deeds!', 'context': 'Xu Chu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'You are a lot of blockheads, not worth talking about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'He and I were old friends and we could joke together. Why did you kill him?', 'context': 'Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 7, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'Commander Cui Yan, of Dongwu, who had on many occasions given valuable advice to Yuan Shao. As the advice was not followed, he had pleaded indisposition and remained at home.', 'context': 'told: “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'According to the former registers, there are three hundred thousand households in the region so that one may well call it a major region.', 'context': 'Cao Cao sent for this man, gave him an office and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 349, 'talk': 'The empire is rent and the country is torn; the Yuan brothers are at war, and the people have been stripped naked. Yet, Sir, you do not hasten to inquire after local conditions and how to rescue the people from misery, but first compute the possibilities of taxation. Can you expect to gain the support of our people by such means?', 'context': 'Cui Yan replied, “'},
{'istart': 342, 'iend': 659, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is very strong now that he has overcome Jizhou, and the Yuans will be unable to hold out for long. Nothing is to be gained by helping Yuan Tan and it may give Cao Cao the loophole he is always looking for to attack this place. My advice is to keep the army in condition and devote all our energies to defense.', 'context': 'Whereupon Cao Cao summoned him. Yuan Tan refused to come, and Cao Cao sent letters breaking off the marriage between Yuan Tan and his daughter. Soon after Cao Cao led an expedition against Yuan Tan and marched to Pingyuan, whereupon Yuan Tan sent to Liu Biao to beg assistance. Liu Biao sent for Liu Bei to consult about this. Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Agreed; but what shall we say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Write to both the brothers as peacemaker in gracious terms.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'If I do not kill you, my order will not be obeyed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Yet supposing I cut off your heads, but I cannot bear to do that severity. Quickly flee to the hills and hide so that my soldiers do not capture you.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'He is nothing but a tickle−minded child,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 248, 'talk': 'He is never of the same mind two days running, and I cannot depend upon what he says. Now your brother Xin Pi is in my employ and has a post of importance, you would better remain here also.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Sir Prime Minister, you are in error,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 215, 'talk': "It is said that the lord's honor is the servant's glory; the lord's sadness is the servant's shame. How can I turn my back on the family I have so long served?", 'context': ' said Xin Ping. “'},
{'istart': 393, 'iend': 454, 'talk': 'Your brother is with Cao Cao, and you want to betray me also!', 'context': ' Cao Cao felt he could not be persuaded and sent him back. Xin Ping returned and told Yuan Tan the surrender could not be arranged, and Yuan Tan turned on him angrily, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Tomorrow when we go out to battle, we will drive the people out in front as a screen for the soldiers, and we must fight a winning battle.', 'context': 'Then Guo Tu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Did you know of my command?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I knew it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Yet you were not afraid?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 123, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'And there were many such as this in the north. What a pity that the Yuan family could not make the best of them! But if they had done so, I should never have dared to turn my eyes toward this place.', 'context': 'one stand in the world if one forgets duty through fear? If I could bury his body, I would not mind death.” Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'He is indeed loyal!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 128, 'talk': "Give Yuan Xi's former generals the command and ask them to attack Youzhou.", 'context': 'Then he questioned Guo Jia, who advised him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 193, 'iend': 339, 'talk': 'I understand that Cao Cao is the most powerful man of the day, and I am going to support him and those who do not go with me I shall put to death.', 'context': 'Then Wuhuan Chu, new Imperial Protector of Youzhou, was not disposed to incur the enmity of the powerful Cao Cao, so he called his subordinates together to swear them to support him and said, “'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 461, 'talk': 'I have received great promotions and benefits from the Yuans. Now my lord has been vanquished; my knowledge was powerless to save him, my bravery insufficient to cause me to die for him; I have failed in my duty. But I refuse to commit the crowning act of treachery and ally myself with Cao Cao.', 'context': 'Each in turn smeared his lips with the blood of sacrifice and took the oath till it came to the turn of Han Heng. Instead he dashed his sword to the ground, crying, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'Generals Li Dian, Yue Jin, and Zhang Yan had marched to Bingzhou, but that Gao Gan had occupied Wine Jar Pass and could not be dislodged.', 'context': 'Then the scouts came to report: “'},
{'istart': 362, 'iend': 573, 'talk': "We are old officers in Yuan Shao's armies forced into surrender to Cao Cao. We find him so false and he treats us so meanly that we want to return to help our old master. Wherefore quickly open your gates to us.", 'context': 'So Cao Cao marched thither himself. The defender still maintaining his position, Cao Cao asked for plans. Xun You proposed that a band should go over pretending to be deserters. Cao Cao assented and then called the two Lu Xiang and Lu Kuang, to whom he gave whispered orders. They left with their companies. Soon they came near the pass and called out, saying, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 177, 'talk': "Cao Cao's troops are new to the country and not settled; you ought to fall upon their camp this very evening. If you approve, we will lead the attack.", 'context': 'And they said to Gao Gan, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'I have no quarrel with Cao Cao; why then should he invade my land? Do you desire to embroil me with him?', 'context': 'Ce Xian the Khan replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'You are wrong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'You speak well, O Guo Jia,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'My friend, you are suffering for my ambition to subdue the Gobi Desert. I cannot bear to think you should be ill.', 'context': "Cao Cao's tears fell as he said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'You have always been very good to me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'and I can never repay what I owe you.', 'context': ' said the sick man, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'The country is exceedingly precipitous, and I am thinking of going back; what think you?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 385, 'talk': 'Between autumn and summer this route is under water, the shallow places too heavy for wheeled traffic, the deep parts insufficient for boats. It is always difficult. Therefore you would do better to return and at Lulong cross the Baitan Pass into the desert. Then advance to Liucheng and smite before there is time to prepare. One sudden rush will settle King Mao Dun.', 'context': 'Tian Chou said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'They have no formation, we can easily rout them.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 225, 'talk': 'I am a renegade and a fugitive. It is my good fortune that you spared my life and how can I accept a rank for betraying Lulong? I would rather die than accept the lordship.', 'context': 'But Tian Chou declined the rank, saying with tears, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 325, 'talk': 'I took some risk in going so far, but by good fortune I have succeeded; with the aid of Heaven I have secured victory. I could not be guided by your advice, but still they were counsels of safety, and therefore I reward you to prove my appreciation of advice and that hereafter you may not fear to speak your minds.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Alas! Heaven has smitten me; Guo Jia is dead.', 'context': 'Cao Cao mourned for him, crying, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'If the Prime Minister shall follow the advice given herein, then Liaodong will be secure.', 'context': 'and he had told them to say, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'For a long time the Governor of Liaodong, Gongsun Kang, has been contumacious, and it bodes ill for peace that the Yuan brothers have fled to him. Would it not be well to attack before they move against you?', 'context': 'Shortly after, Xiahou Dun at the head of a delegation presented a petition, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I need not trouble your tiger courage, Sirs,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Wait a few days and you will see the heads of our two enemies sent to me.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao smiling. “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 455, 'talk': "When Yuan Shao was alive, he nourished the plan of adding this territory to his own. Now his sons, homeless, with a broken army and no officers, are coming here; it seems to me like the dove stealing the magpie's nest. If we offer them shelter, they will assuredly intrigue against us. I advise that they be inveigled into the city, put to death, and their heads sent to Cao Cao, who will be most grateful to us.", 'context': 'At the council Gongsun Gong rose, saying, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'I have one fear; Cao Cao will come against us. If so, it would be better to have the help of the Yuans against him.', 'context': 'Said the Governor Gongsun Kang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 155, 'talk': "Then you can send spies to ascertain whether Cao Cao's army is preparing to attack us. If it is, then save the Yuans alive; if not, then follow my advice.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 154, 'iend': 366, 'talk': 'Liaodong has a large army strong enough to oppose Cao Cao. We will go thither and submit till we can slay the Governor and take possession. Then when we are strong enough, we will attack and recover our own land.', 'context': 'It was decided to wait till the spies came back. In the meantime, Yuan Xi and Yuan Shang had taken counsel together as they approached Liaodong, saying, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'May we have cushions?', 'context': 'Now it was bitterly cold and on the couches where they were sitting were no coverings. So Yuan Shang said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'When your heads take that long, long journey, will there be any cushions?', 'context': 'The host said, “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Why do you not begin?', 'context': 'Before Yuan Shang could recover from his fright, Gongsun Kang shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': "Let's march to the capital to ward off Liu Biao's threat if we are not going to attack the east.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'I am waiting for the heads of the enemy. We will go as soon as the heads arrive.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 118, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Just as Guo Jia said!', 'context': "the heads. Then they were greatly surprised; and when the messenger presented Gongsun Kang's letters, Cao Cao cried, “"},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'As the north has been overcome, it is time to settle the south.', 'context': 'Then Cheng Yu and others said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'That has long occupied my thoughts.', 'context': 'Cao Cao was pleased and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'What is there that can oppose your heaven−high prestige?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Surely a treasure is buried there,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'What is the portent?', 'context': 'The diggers at the spot whence the golden light proceeded presently unearthed a bronze bird. Looking at it, Cao Cao turned to his companion, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'You will remember that the mother of the praiseworthy King Shun 1 dreamed of a jade bird before his birth, so certainly it is a felicitous omen,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'If you build a terraced tower, you should add two others, one on each side. The center tower as the tallest should be called the Bronze Bird Tower; the side towers named Jade Dragon Tower and Golden Phoenix Tower. Then connect these by flying bridges and the effect will be noble.', 'context': 'His younger son, Cao Zhi, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'My son, your words are very good; and by and bye when the building is complete, I can solace my old age therein.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'The Grand Army has only just returned from the north and needs rest. Wait half a year that the soldiers may recover from the fatigue of the campaign, and both Liu Biao and Sun Quan will fall at the first roll of the drums.', 'context': 'Xun You said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'If they really rebel, it will cause a lot of trouble,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Do not let that trouble you; I will go and settle it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'He certainly has a fine steed.', 'context': 'Zhang Wu was riding a handsome prancing horse, and Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'With such heroism as my brother has shown, Jingzhou has one upon whom to rely. But a source of sorrow is the borders with the lands of Yue, Wu, and Shu ((three ancient states)), from which a raid may come at any time. Zhang Lu of Shu and Sun Quan of Yue and Wu are to be feared.', 'context': 'At one of these banquets the Imperial Protector said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'But I have three bold generals,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 304, 'talk': 'quite equal to any task you can set them. Send Zhang Fei to keep ward on the southern border of Yue, Guan Yu to guard the city of Guzi against Zhang Lu in the west, and Zhao Yun holding the Three Gorges will protect you from Sun Quan. Why need you grieve?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is putting his troops in such commanding positions all round the region. That is the danger.', 'context': "The scheme appealed strongly to the Imperial Protector, but Cai Mao did not approve. So he spoke to his sister, Liu Biao's wife, saying, “"},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'The Jingzhou army seem to have a great liking for Liu Bei; they are always coming and going. You ought to take precautions. I do not think you should let them stay in the city. Why not send them on some mission?', 'context': 'Lady Cai, thus influenced by her brother, undertook to remonstrate, and that night began by saying to Liu Biao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is a good man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'I think others differ from you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 312, 'talk': 'My passed−away brother, Kuai Liang, knew horses very well, and I am not a bad judge. This horse has tear−tracks running down from its eyes and a white blaze on its forehead. It is called a Dilu horse, and it is a danger to his master. That is why Zhang Wu was killed. I advise you not to ride it.', 'context': 'Kuai Yue said, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'You kindly presented me with a horse lately, and I am most grateful; but you may need it on some of your expeditions and, if you do not mind, I would like to return it.', 'context': 'Liu Biao began to think. Soon after he asked Liu Bei to a banquet and in the course of it said, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'You have been here a long time, and I fear I am spoiling your career as a warrior. Now Xinye in Xiangyang is no poverty−stricken town; how would you like to garrison it with your own troops?', 'context': 'Liu Bei rose and thanked him. The Imperial Protector continued, “'},
{'istart': 122, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'You should not ride that horse.', 'context': 'When he left Jingzhou City, he noticed in the gate a person making him emphatic salutations, and the man presently said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'Yesterday I heard that Kuai Yue told the Imperial Protector that that horse was a Dilu horse and brought disaster to its owner. That is why it was returned to you. How can you mount it again?', 'context': 'Yi Ji replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I am deeply touched by your affection,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 140, 'talk': "but a person's life is governed by fate and what a horse can interfere with that?", 'context': ' replied Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'Why do you not take this opportunity to march against the capital? An empire might follow from that.', 'context': 'While Cao Cao was absent from the capital on his northern expedition, Liu Bei went to Liu Biao and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I am well placed here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Why should I attempt other things?', 'context': ' was the reply. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'O Brother, why do you sigh thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'I have a secret sorrow that is difficult to speak about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has returned, and he is stronger than ever. I am afraid he means to absorb this region. I am sorry I did not follow your advice for I have missed an opportunity.', 'context': 'Presently Liu Biao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'In this period of disruption, with strife on every side, one cannot pretend that there will be no more opportunities. If you only take what that offers, there will be nothing to regret.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'What you say, Brother, is quite to the point,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 146, 'iend': 257, 'talk': 'It is that secret sorrow I spoke of to you before; I wished to tell you, but there was no opportunity that day.', 'context': 'They drank on for a time till presently Liu Bei noticed that his host was weeping, and when he asked the cause of these tears, Liu Biao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'O Brother, what difficulty have you, and can I assist you? I am entirely at your service.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 543, 'talk': 'My first wife, of the Chen family, bore me a son Liu Qi, my eldest. He grew up virtuous but weakly and unfitted to succeed me in my office. Later I took a wife of the Cai family, who bore me a son named Liu Zong, fairly intelligent. If I pass over the elder in favor of the younger, there is the breach of the rule of primogeniture; and if I follow law and custom, there are the intrigues of the Cai family and clan to be reckoned with. Further, the army is in the hollow of their hands. There will be trouble, and I cannot decide what to do.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'All experience proves that to set aside the elder for the younger is to take the way of confusion. If you fear the power of the Cai faction, then gradually reduce its power and influence, but do not let doting affection lead you into making the younger your heir.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'In the past I was always in the saddle and I was slender and lithe. Now it is so long since I rode that I am getting stout, and the days and months are slipping by, wasted; I shall have old age on me in no time, and I have accomplished nothing. So I am sad.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 460, 'talk': 'I have heard a story that when you were at Xuchang at the season of green plums, you and Cao Cao were discussing heroes. You mentioned this name and that to him as humans of parts, and he rejected every one of them. Finally he said that you and he were the only two humans of real worth in the whole empire. If he with all his power and authority did not dare to place himself in front of you, I do not think you need grieve about having accomplished nothing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 575, 'iend': 670, 'talk': 'If I only had a starting point, then I would not be afraid of any one in a world full of fools.', 'context': ' At this flattering speech Liu Bei, as wine was getting the better of him and in a half maudlin manner, replied, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Let me go to the guest−house and slay him forthwith, and we can report what we have done.', 'context': 'Her husband made no reply, but only shook his head. Then Lady Cai took counsel with her kinsman Cai Mao, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I have not said farewell to my host; how can I go away?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'If you go to bid him farewell, you will fall a victim to the Cai faction,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 202, 'iend': 330, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has treacherous intentions, as can be seen from some lines written on the wall. And his hurried departure is suspicious.', 'context': 'Naturally the failure of the plot chagrined the treacherous Cai Mao, but he took the occasion to scribble some calumnious verses on one of the partitions. Then he went to see Liu Biao to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'I have seen much of the man, but have never known him write verses. This is the handiwork of some one who wishes to sow discord between us.', 'context': 'sword and swore to slay the writer. But before he had gone many paces, his anger had already died down, and he said to himself, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'The soldiers are awaiting your orders to go to Xinye and arrest Liu Bei.', 'context': 'By and bye Cai Mao reminded him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'Soon there is to be the great gathering at Xiangyang, and we can arrange something for that day.', 'context': "Cai Mao saw his brother−in−law's hesitation and again sought his sister. She said, “"},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'We have had several fruitful harvests recently. I pray you, Sir, attend the Full Harvest Festival at Xiangyang; it would be an encouragement to the people.', 'context': 'Next day Cai Mao petitioned the Imperial Protector, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I have been feeling my old trouble lately; I certainly cannot go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'but my two sons can go to represent me and to receive the guests.', 'context': ' replied he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'They are full young,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'They may make some mistakes.', 'context': ' replied Cai Mao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Then go to Xinye and request Liu Bei to receive the guests,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'You have seemed worried and preoccupied lately, and I think something untoward happened at Jingzhou. You should consider well before you accept this invitation.', 'context': 'Sun Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'You speak well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'Banquets are no good; gatherings are no better; it is best not to go.', 'context': 'Said Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Let me take three hundred horse and foot as escort; there will be no trouble then,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'That is the best course,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'My father is feeling unwell and could not come, wherefore he begs you, Uncle Liu Bei, to preside at the various ceremonies and give encouragement to the officers who administer the region.', 'context': 'Liu Qi said to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Really I am unfit for such responsibilities,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 102, 'talk': "But my brother's command must be obeyed.", 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'This Liu Bei is the villain of the age and if left alive will certainly work harm to us. He must be got rid of now.', 'context': 'Then Cai Mao said to Kuai Yue, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': "I fear you would forfeit everybody's favor if you harmed him,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'I have already secretly spoken in these terms to Imperial Protector Liu Biao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'and I have his word here.', 'context': ' said Cai Mao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'So it may be regarded as settled; then we can prepare.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 285, 'talk': 'My brothers are ready. Cai He is posted on the road to the Xian Hills from the east gate; Cai Zhong and Cai Xun are on the north and south roads. No guard is needed on the west as the Tan Torrent is quite safeguard enough. Even with legions, he could not get over that.', 'context': 'Cai Mao added, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'I notice that Zhao Yun never leaves him. I feel sure he expects some attack.', 'context': 'Kuai Yue replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'I have placed five hundred men in ambush in the city.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 203, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'Make an excuse to get sway.', 'context': 'All were ready and awaiting the signal. At the third course, Yi Ji took a goblet of wine in his hands and approached Liu Bei, at the same time giving him a meaningful look. Then in a low voice he said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Cai Mao plots to kill you, and all the roads have been guarded except that to the west. My lord must to lose no time to depart.', 'context': 'Yi Ji then told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Dilu, Dilu, why betray me?', 'context': 'Then he plied the whip furiously, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Now leap, my steed!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Why did you run sway from the feast?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Why did you wish to harm one who has done you no injury?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I have never thought of such a thing; do not listen to what people say to you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'What spirits aided him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'And where does your master live?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Where is my lord?', 'context': 'Meeting Cai Mao near the gate, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'He left the banquet−hall quite suddenly, and I know not whither he has gone,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'You invited my lord to a feast; what means this going after him with a squadron of horse?', 'context': 'he came to the river. There he was checked by a torrent without ford or bridge. At once he turned back and shouted after Cai Mao, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'It is my duty to guard the officials of forty−one counties who have assembled here as I am the Chief Commander.', 'context': 'Cai Mao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Whither have you driven my lord?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'They tell me he rode quite alone out through the west gate, but I have not seen him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'My safety is due to an especial interposition of Providence.', 'context': 'After that marvelous life−saving leap over the Tan Torrent, Liu Bei felt elated but rather dazed. He could not help telling himself, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'If I were only as happy!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'You must be Liu Bei, the general who fought the Yellow Scarves,', 'context': 'He checked his horse and looked at the lad, who stopped his beast, ceased playing on the pipe, and stared fixedly at the stranger. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'How can you know my name, a young rustic like you living in such a secluded place?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Well, who is your master?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': "My master's name is Sima Hui. He belongs to Yingchuan and his Taoist appellation is Water−Mirror.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 150, 'talk': "Who are your master's friends that you mentioned?", 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'They are Pang Degong and Pang Tong of Xiangyang.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'And who are they?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'In that wood there, in front,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'There he has a farmstead.', 'context': ' said the cowherd pointing to it. “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'I really am Liu Bei, and you might lead me to your master that I may salute him.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'Amidst the clear and subtle sounds of the lute, there suddenly rang out a high note as though some noble man was near.', 'context': 'Suddenly the music ceased. He heard a deep laugh and a man appeared, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'That is my master,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'chosen vessel.', 'context': 'Liu Bei saw before him a tall figure, slender and straight as a pine tree, a very “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'You have escaped from a grave danger today, Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'This is Liu Bei.', 'context': 'Liu Bei was startled into silence, and the cowherd said to his master, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Whence come you, Illustrious Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'By chance I was passing this way and the lad pointed you out to me. So I came to bow in your honored presence. I cannot tell what pleasure it gives me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Why this mystery? Why must you conceal the truth? You have certainly just escaped from a grave danger.', 'context': 'Water−Mirror laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'I knew it all from your appearance,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'Your name has long been familiar, but whence comes it that, up to the present, you are only a homeless devil?', 'context': ' said his host. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I have suffered many a check during my life,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'and through one of them am I here now.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'It should not be so; but the reason is that you still lack the one person to aid you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'Your fighting generals are good: fit to oppose a legion. The pity is you have no really able adviser. Your civilians are but pallid students of books, not humans fitted to weave and control destiny.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'I have always yearned to find one of those marvelous recluses who live among the hills till their day arrive. So far I have sought in vain.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': "You know what the Teacher Confucius said, 'In a hamlet of ten households there must be one true human.' Can you say there is no one?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'I am simple and uninstructed; I pray you enlighten me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'How could such a thing be?', 'context': 'Liu Bei started up in surprise, crying, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'At this moment the marvelously clever ones of the earth are all here and you, Sir, ought to seek them.', 'context': 'Water−Mirror continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Where are they? Who are they?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'If you could find either Sleeping−Dragon or Blooming−Phoenix, you could restore order in the empire.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'But who are these two?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Good; very good!', 'context': 'His host clapped his hands, smiled and said, “'},
{'istart': 118, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Where are you from?', 'context': 'Suddenly he became fully awake at the sound of a knock at the door and a person entering. And he heard his host say, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 462, 'talk': 'It has long been said that Liu Biao treated good humans as good humans should be treated and bad humans as they should be treated. So I went to see for myself. But that reputation is undeserved. He does treat good people correctly but he cannot use them, and he treats wicked people in the right way, all but dismissing them. So I left a letter for him and went away; and here I am.', 'context': 'Liu Bei rose from his couch and listened secretly. He heard the visitor reply, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'You, capable enough to be the adviser of a king, ought to be able to find some one fit to serve. Why did you cheapen yourself so far as to go to Liu Biao? Beside, there is a real hero right under your eyes and you do not know him.', 'context': 'Water−Mirror replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'It is just as you say,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 273, 'iend': 300, 'talk': 'Who was it came last night?', 'context': 'Liu Bei listened with great joy for he thought this visitor was certainly one of the two he was advised to look for. Liu Bei would have shown himself then and there, but he thought that would look strange. So he waited till daylight, when he sought out his host and said. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'A friend of mine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'He wants to find an enlightened master, and so he has gone elsewhere.', 'context': 'Liu Bei begged for an introduction. Water−Mirror said, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Good, good!', 'context': 'When Liu Bei asked his name, his host only replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Last night, on my return to Xinye,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'I could not find my lord, so I followed at once and traced you here. I pray you return quickly as I fear an attack on the city.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'You ought first of all to indite a letter to Liu Biao telling him all these things.', 'context': 'As soon as they reached the city, a council was called and Zhao Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'How dare you try to hurt my brother?', 'context': 'Liu Biao was very angry, sent for Cai Mao, and berated him soundly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'I owe my life to this horse; had it not been for him, I had been already below the Nine Golden Springs.', 'context': 'Liu Bei escorted Liu Qi well on his way and, pointing to his steed, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'It was not the strength of the horse, but your noble fortune, Uncle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Surely this is one of the people Water−Mirror spoke of,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Is not this a Dilu horse?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'But though it is a good steed, it risks his master. You must not ride it.', 'context': ' said San Fu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'It has already fulfilled the omens,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'But that was saving his master, not risking him; it will surely harm some one in the end. But I can tell you how to avert the omen.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I should be glad to hear it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'If you have an enemy against whom you bear a grudge, give him this horse and wait till it has fulfilled the evil omens on this person, then you can ride it in safety.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'What, Sir! You are but a new acquaintance, and you would advise me to take an evil course and to harm another for my own advantage? No, Sir! I cannot listen.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'People said you were virtuous. I could not ask you directly, so I put it that way to test you.', 'context': 'His guest smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'But how can I be virtuous while I lack your teaching?', 'context': "Liu Bei's expression changed. He rose and returned the compliment, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'So you see, the effects of your virtue extend to the ordinary people.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 348, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is strengthening his position at Xinye and laying in large supplies. Some great scheme is afoot, and he should be checked. Since our surrender we have performed no noteworthy service and, if you will give us five thousand soldiers, we promise to bring you the head of Liu Bei.', 'context': 'Then the two Lu Xiang and Lu Kuang petitioned Cao Ren, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'They must not be permitted to cross the boundary. Send Guan Yu and Zhang Fei left and right, each with one thousand troops, one to attack the enemy on the march, the other to cut off the retreat. You and Zhao Yun will make a front attack.', 'context': 'San Fu said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Who are you who thus would encroach on my territory?', 'context': 'He called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'I am the great General Lu Kuang, and I have the order of the Prime Minister to make you prisoner,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 158, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'Zhang Fei is waiting!', 'context': 'About three miles farther on they found their retreat barred by an army under Zhang Fei, who stood in the way with a long spear ready to thrust, crying out, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'The loss is due to our underestimation of our enemy. Now we should stay where we are, hold on, and request reinforcements.', 'context': 'Cao Ren, much distressed, consulted Li Dian who advised, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Not so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 226, 'talk': 'We cannot support calmly the death of two leaders and the loss of so many soldiers. We must avenge them quickly. Xinye is but a crossbow−slug of a place and not worth disturbing the Prime Minister for.', 'context': ' said Cao Ren. “'},
{'istart': 229, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is a man of metal,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 272, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'Do not esteem him lightly.', 'context': ' said Li Dian. “'},
