{'istart': 104, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'How could I make him come?', 'context': ' replied Cheng Yu. “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'I hear you have a very talented son, who is now at Xinye helping on that rebel Liu Bei against the government. There he is like a jewel in a muck−heap; it is a pity. Supposing you were to call him, I could speak of him before the Emperor, and he might get an important office.', 'context': 'Presently he said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'four precious things of the study,', 'context': 'Cao Cao bade his secretaries bring along the “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'What sort of a man is Liu Bei?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 718, 'talk': 'Why do you malign him so bitterly? Every one knows he is a descendant of one of the Han princes and so related to the House. He has condescended to take a lowly office and is respectful to all people. He has a reputation for benevolence. Every one, young and old, cowherds and firewood cutters, all know him by name and know that he is the finest and noblest man in the world. If my son is in his service, then has he found a fitting master. You, under the name of a Han minister, are really nothing but a Han rebel. Contrary to all truth you tell me Liu Bei is a rebel, whereby you try to induce me to make my son leave the light for darkness. Are you devoid of all sense of shame?', 'context': 'Lady Xun answered in a hard voice, “'},
{'istart': 401, 'iend': 405, 'talk': 'home', 'context': "So the outspoken old lady was saved. She was given quarters and cared for. Daily Cheng Yu went to ask after her health, falsely claiming to being a sworn brother of her son's, and so entitled to serve her and treat her as a filial son would have done. He often sent her gifts and wrote letters to her so that she had to write in reply. And thereby he learned her handwriting so that he could forge a “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'The bond between mother and son is divine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 463, 'talk': "Xu Shu is indeed a genius, but he has been here long enough to know all our secrets. If you let him go over to Cao Cao, he will be in his confidence and that will be to our detriment. You ought to keep him at all costs and not let him go. When Cao Cao sees Xu Shu does not come, he will put the mother to death, and that will make Xu Shu the more zealous in your service, for he will burn to avenge his mother's death.", 'context': 'Then Sun Qian said privately to his master, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 245, 'talk': "I cannot do that. It would be very cruel and vile to procure the death of his mother that I might retain the son's services. If I kept him, it would lead to a rupture of the parental lien, and that would be a sin I would rather die than commit.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'With my mother a prisoner I can swallow nothing, nay, though it were brewed from gold or distilled from jewels.', 'context': 'Both were grieved and sighed. Liu Bei asked the parting guest to a banquet, but he declined, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Alas! Your departure is as if I lost both my hands,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Even the liver of a dragon or the marrow of a phoenix would be bitter in my mouth.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'It is my mean fortune that separates me from you, but I hope that you may serve well your new lord and become famous.', 'context': 'Liu Bei lifted the goblet and said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 274, 'talk': 'I am but a poor ignorant person whom you have kindly employed. Unhappily I have to break our intercourse in the middle, but my venerable mother is the real cause. Though Cao Cao use all manner of means to coerce me, yet will I never plan for him.', 'context': 'Xu Shu wept as he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'After you are gone, I shall only bury myself in the hills and hide in the forests,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'I shall find none to help better than you, my master.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'How can I permit such extravagant praise?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'I am only a useless blockhead.', 'context': ' said Xu Shu. “'},
{'istart': 167, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'I will not trouble you, O Princely One, to come further. Let us say our farewell here.', 'context': 'They were all deeply affected. Liu Bei could not bring himself to part from his friend. He escorted him a little further, and yet a little further, till Xu Shu said, “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Alas! We part. Each goes his way and who knows if we shall meet again?', 'context': 'Liu Bei dismounted, took Xu Shu by the hands, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'He is gone! What shall I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Wish that I could cut down every tree in the countryside!', 'context': 'One of the trees shut out the traveler from his sight, and Liu Bei pointed at it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Why?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Because they hinder my sight of Xu Shu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'He is returning; can it he that he is going to stay?', 'context': 'Said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'This return is surely for no slight reason.', 'context': 'So he hastened forward to meet Xu Shu, and when they got near enough, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'In the turmoil of my feelings I forgot to say one word. There is a person of wonderful skill living about seven miles from the city of Xiangyang; why not seek him?', 'context': 'Checking his horse, Xu Shu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Can I trouble you to ask him to visit me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'He will not condescend to visit you; you must go to him. But if he consents, you will be as fortunate as the Zhou when they got the aid of Lu Wang, or the Han when Zhang Liang came to help.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'How does the unknown compare with yourself?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 335, 'talk': 'With me? Compared with him I am as a worn−out carthorse to a palomino, an old crow to a phoenix. This man often compares himself with the ancient sages Guan Zhong and Yue Yi but, in my opinion, he is far their superior. He has the talent to measure the heavens and mete the earth; he is a man who overshadows every other in the world.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I would know his name.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 311, 'talk': 'On their land was a ridge of hills called the Sleeping Dragon, and the elder of the brothers took it as a name and called himself Master Sleeping−Dragon. This is your man; he is a veritable genius. You ought really to visit him; and if he will help you, you need feel no more anxiety about peace in the empire.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Water−Mirror spoke that time of two persons, Sleeping−Dragon and Blooming−Phoenix, and said if only one of them could be got to help me all would be well. Surely he, whom you speak of, is one of them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Blooming−Phoenix is Pang Tong of Xiangyang, and Sleeping−Dragon is Zhuge Liang.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 357, 'talk': 'I wished to serve Liu Bei of Yuzhou, but my mother has been imprisoned by Cao Cao, and has sent to call me. Therefore I have had to leave him. At the moment of parting I commended you to him. You may expect him speedily and I hope, Sir, you will not refuse your aid but will consent to use your great talents to help him.', 'context': 'Asked why he had come, he replied, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'And so you have made me the victim of the world sacrifice.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang showed annoyance and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Why did such an illustrious scholar as you bow the knee to Liu Bei?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'I am young and I fled to avoid the results of certain escapades. I spent some time as a wanderer and so came to Xinye where I became good friends with him. But my mother is here, and when I thought of all her affection, I could no longer remain absent.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Now you will be able to take care of your mother at all times. And I may have the privilege of receiving your instructions.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'What have you come here for?', 'context': 'But she was greatly surprised to see him and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'I was at Xinye, in the service of Liu Bei of Yuzhou, when I received your letter. I came immediately.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'The winter is not favorable for this campaign. My lord should await milder weather.', 'context': 'At that time Cao Cao was contemplating an attack on the south. His adviser Xun Yu dissuaded him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Surely this is he', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 326, 'talk': 'Since leaving you that day in the mountains I have been overwhelmed with military preparations and so have failed to visit you as courtesy demanded. Now that the brightness has descended upon me, I hope this dereliction of duty may be pardoned.', 'context': 'There Liu Bei conducted him to the seat of honor and made his obeisance, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'I hear Xu Shu is here. I have come expressly to see him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'But how?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Why do you speak like that?', 'context': 'provoke Zhuge Liang into coming out and showing compassion for some one else?” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'When they asked him what was his ambition, he would only smile and always compared himself with the great ancient scholars Guan Zhong and Yue Yi. No one could gauge his talents.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'How comes it that Yingchuan produces so many able humans?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'That old astrologer, Yin Kui, used to say that the stars clustered thick over the region and so there were many wise humans.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 323, 'talk': 'Guan Zhong and Yue Yi are the two most famous leaders mentioned in the Spring and Autumn and the Warring States Periods. They well overtopped the rest of humankind. Is it not a little too much to say that Zhuge Liang compares with these two?', 'context': 'Now Guan Yu was there; and when he heard Zhuge Liang so highly praised, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'In my opinion he should not be compared with these two, but rather with two others,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Who are these two?', 'context': ' said Water−Mirror. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'What a wise hermit!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'It was made by Master Sleeping−Dragon,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Then he lives hereabout. Where?', 'context': '“'},
