{'istart': 23, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'A simple denizen of the mountain wilds is unfitted to discuss the affairs of empire. But you bade me speak and I have spoken; perhaps somewhat madly.', 'context': 'Cui Zhouping replied, “'},
{'istart': 175, 'iend': 261, 'talk': 'Master, I am grateful for your instruction. But know you whither Zhuge Liang has gone?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'I also came to see him and I know not where he is,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'If I asked you, Master, to accompany me to my poor bit of territory, would you come?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'I am too dilatory, too fond of leisure and ease, and no longer have any ambitions. But I will see you another time.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'We have not found Zhuge Liang, and we have had to listen to the wild ravings of this so−called scholar. There is the whole result of this journey.', 'context': 'Presently Zhang Fei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'His words were those of a deep thinker,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Why must you go hunting after this villager? Send and tell him to come.', 'context': 'Again Zhang Fei showed his irritation by remarking, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Silence!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 207, 'talk': "The Teacher Mencius said, 'To try to see the sage without going his way is like barring a door you wish to enter.' Zhuge Liang is the greatest sage of the day; how can I summon him?", 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'It is very cold and the earth is frozen hard, no fighting is possible now.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'Yet we are going all this way to get advice which will be useless to us. Where is the sense of it? Let us rather get back to Xinye out of the cold.', 'context': ' Said Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'I am set upon proving my zeal to Zhuge Liang, but if you, my brother, do not like the cold, you can return.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': "I do not fear death; do you think I care for the cold? But I do care about wasting my brother's energies,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Say no more,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Which of you is Master Sleeping−Dragon?', 'context': 'Liu Bei saluted them and said, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Who are you, Sir?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 122, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'What business have you with Sleeping−Dragon?', 'context': ' asked the long−bearded one. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'I am Liu Bei. I want to inquire of him how to restore tranquillity to the world.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Well, neither of us is your man, but we are friends of his. My name is Shi Guangyuan and my friend here is Meng Gongwei.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I know you both by reputation,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 207, 'talk': "I am indeed fortunate to meet you in this haphazard way. Will you not come to Sleeping−Dragon's retreat and talk for a time? I have horses here for you.", 'context': ' said Liu Bei gladly. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'We idle folks of the wilds know nothing of tranquilizing states. Please do not trouble to ask. Pray mount again and continue searching Sleeping−Dragon.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'He is in his room reading,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'General, you must be that Liu Bei of Yuzhou who wishes to see my brother.', 'context': 'The young man hastily returned the salute and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Then, Master, you are not Sleeping−Dragon!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'I am his younger brother, Zhuge Jun. He has another elder brother, Zhuge Jin, now with Sun Quan in the South Land as a counselor. Zhuge Liang is the second of our family.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Is your brother at home?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Only yesterday he arranged to go a jaunt with Cui Zhouping.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'Whither have they gone?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'What very poor luck have I! Twice have I failed to meet the great sage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Pray sit a few moments and let me offer you some tea.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Brother, since the master is not here, I pray you remount and go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Since I am here, why not a little talk before we go home again.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Can you tell me if your worthy brother is skilled in strategy and studies works on war?', 'context': 'Then turning to his host he continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'I do not know.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'This is worse than the other,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'And the wind and snow are getting worse; we ought to go back.', 'context': ' grumbled Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Since my brother is absent, I will not presume to detain you longer. I will return your call soon.', 'context': 'Zhuge Jun said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'Please do not take that trouble. In a few days I will come again. But if I could borrow paper and ink, I would leave a note to show your worthy brother that I am zealous and earnest.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'four treasures', 'context': 'Zhuge Jun produced the “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'This is written to tell you that, after purification of mind with fasting; and of body with fragrant baths, Liu Bei will come again to prostrate himself in your honored presence and receive enlightenment', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 218, 'iend': 243, 'talk': 'The old Master is coming.', 'context': 'The letter written and given to Zhuge Jun, Liu Bei took his leave, exceedingly disappointed at this second failure. As he was mounting, he saw the serving lad waving his hand outside the hedge and heard him call out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Here at last is Sleeping−Dragon,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'I chanced to hear the song you were singing; it is very beautiful.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'Have you seen your son−in−law lately?', 'context': 'the bridge and saw the plum trees in the hedge. And so it happened to catch your ear, Noble Sir.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'That is just what I have come to do now.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'Brother, you have sought him twice; surely this is showing even too much deference. I do not believe in this fame of his for learning; he is avoiding you and dare not submit to the test. Why so obstinately hold this idea?', 'context': 'His brothers disapproved, and Guan Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 222, 'talk': "You are wrong, my brother. In the Spring and Autumn Period Prince Huan of Qi paid five visits to the 'Hermit of the Eastern Suburb' before he got to see his face. And my desire to see Zhuge Liang is even greater than his.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I think you are mistaken,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'How can this villager be such a marvel of wisdom? You should not go again and, if he will not come, I will bring him with a hempen rope.', 'context': ' said Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 225, 'talk': "Have you forgotten the great King Wen's visit to Lu Wang, the old man of the Eastern Sea? If he could show such deference to a wise man, where am I too deferential? If you will not go, your brother and I will go without you,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'If you two go, how can I hang back?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'If you go, then you must be polite.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'He returned last evening; you can see him today, General.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Fortune favors me this time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'I am going to see the Master.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'That was a rude fellow;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Each one has his own affairs,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'What power have we over him?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'I would trouble the servant of the genius, gentle page, to inform the Master that Liu Bei wishes to pay his respects to him.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said very deferentially, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'My master is at home, but he is asleep.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'In that case do not announce me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'What an arrogant fellow is this Master?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'There is our brother waiting, while he sleeps on perfectly carelessly. I will go to the back of the place and let off a bomb and see if that will rouse him.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'No, no; you must do nothing of the kind,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Have any of the usual people come?', 'context': 'As he finished he turned to the lad, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Liu Bei, the Uncle of the Emperor is here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'He has been waiting a long time.', 'context': ' said the boy. “'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Why did you not tell me?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 154, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'I must dress.', 'context': ' said he, rising from the couch. “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 284, 'talk': "I am one of the offshoots of the Han family, a simple person from Zhuo. I have long known the Master's fame, which has indeed thundered in my ear. Twice I have come to visit you, without success. Once I left my name on your writing table; you may have my note.", 'context': 'Liu Bei bowed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'This hermit is but a dilatory person by temperament. I know I have to thank you for more than one vain visit and I am ashamed to think of them.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'From your letter I know that you grieve for both people and government. If I were not so young and if I possessed any talent, I would venture to question you.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'Sima Hui and Xu Shu have both spoken of you; can it be that their words were vain? I trust, O Master, that you will not despise my worthlessness but will condescend to instruct me.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'The two men you speak of are very profound scholars. I am but a peasant, a mere farmer, and who am I that I should talk of empire politics? Those two misled you when they spoke of me. Why do you reject the beautiful jewel for a worthless pebble?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'But your abilities are world embracing and marvelous. How can you be content to allow time to pass while you idle away life in these secluded haunts? I conjure you, O Master, to remember the inhabitants of the world and remove my crass ignorance by bestowing instruction upon me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'But what is your ambition, General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 386, 'talk': 'The Hans are sinking; designing ministers steal away their authority. I am weak, yet I desire to restore the state to its right mind. But my ignorance is too vast, my means are too slender, and I know not where to turn. Only you, Master, can lighten my darkness and preserve me from falling. How happy should I be if you would do so!', 'context': 'Liu Bei moved his seat nearer to his host and said, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 596, 'talk': 'There you see the fifty−four counties of the west. Should you wish to take the overlordship, you will yield to Cao Cao in the north till the time of Heaven be come, to Sun Quan in the south till the Earth may become favorable. You, General, will be the lord of Human and complete the trinity. Jingzhou is to be taken first as a home, the Western Land of Rivers next for the foundation of domination. When you are firmly established, you can lay your plans for the attainment of the whole empire.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang paused while he bade the lad bring out a map. As this was unrolled Zhuge Liang went on, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 319, 'talk': 'Your words, O Master, render everything so clear that the clouds are swept aside and I see the clear sky. But Jingzhou belongs to Liu Biao, my kinsman, and Yiazhou to another kinsman Liu Zhang; I could hardly take the lands from them.', 'context': 'As Zhuge Liang ceased his harangue, Liu Bei left his place and saluted him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'I have studied the stars and I know Liu Biao is not long for this world; the other is not the sort of man to endure. Both places will certainly fall to you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Though I be of small repute and scanty virtue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'I have long been happy on my farm and am fond of my leisure. I fear I cannot obey your command.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'If you will not, O Master, what will become of the people?', 'context': 'Liu Bei wept. “'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'General, if you will accept me, I will render what trifling service I can.', 'context': "The tears rolled down unchecked upon the lapel and sleeves of Liu Bei's robe. This proved to Zhuge Liang the sincerity of his desire, and Zhuge Liang said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'These are not gifts to engage your services, but mere proof of my regard,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 335, 'talk': 'Uncle Liu Bei has come thrice to see me, and now I must go with him. Keep up the farm in my absence and do not let the place go to ruin for, as soon as my work is accomplished, I will certainly return.', 'context': 'Then the presents were accepted. They all remained that night at the farm. Next day Zhuge Jun returned, and his brother said to him, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is training his troops for naval service in Aquamarine Lake and hence certainly intends to invade the country south of the Great River. We ought to send our spies to ascertain what Cao Cao and Sun Quan are really doing.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 462, 'talk': 'Our lord has succeeded to the heritage and has a large army of veterans and ample supplies. He has able officers ready to do his bidding, and why should he be compelled to send a hostage to any perosn? To send a hostage is to be forced into joining Cao Cao, and to carry out his behests, whatever they be. Then we shall be in his power. It would be better not to send, but rather to wait patiently the course of events and prepare plans to attack.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'That is also my opinion,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 221, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'I had avenged the death of your husband, and you must go with me.', 'context': "The two prime movers at once seized Bian Hong and beheaded him in the market place. Then they went to Sun Yi's residence, which they plundered. Gui Lan was taken with the beauty of the dead Governor's wife and told her, “"},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 166, 'talk': "It is too soon after my husband's death to think of remarriage; but as soon as the thirty−day mourning sacrifices are over, I will be yours.", 'context': 'Lady Xu pleaded, saying, “'},
{'istart': 158, 'iend': 632, 'talk': "My husband had great faith in you. Now Gui Lan and Dai Yuan have compassed his death and have laid the crime on Bian Hong. They have plundered my house and carried off my servants. Worse than this, Gui Lan insists that I shall be his wife. To gain time I have pretended to favor this proposal, and I pray you now send the news to my husband's brother and beg him to slay these two miscreants and avenge this wrong. I will never forget your kindness in this life or the next.", 'context': 'She thus obtained a respite, which she utilized to send for two old generals of her husband, Sun Gao and Fu Ying. They came and she tearfully told her tale. “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'We were much attached to our master; and now that he has come to an untimely end, we must avenge him. Dare we not carry out your behests?', 'context': 'They wept also and said, “'},
{'istart': 324, 'iend': 348, 'talk': 'Where are you, Generals?', 'context': 'When night came she sent a servant girl to call her suitor to the Palace, where she entertained him at supper. When he had well drunk, she suggested that they should retire and led him to the chamber where her friends were waiting. He followed without the least hesitation. As soon as she entered the room, she called out, “'},
{'istart': 146, 'iend': 685, 'talk': 'I came of a family of the old Wu, but losing my parents in early life; my brother Wu Jing and I went into the old Yue, and then I married into this family. I bore my husband four sons, not without premonitions of the greatness to be theirs. With my first, Sun Ce, I dreamed of the moon and with my second, Sun Quan, of the sun, which omens were interpreted by the soothsayer as signs of their great honor. Unhappy Sun Ce died young, but Sun Quan inherited, and it is he whom I pray you both assist with one accord. Then may I die in peace.', 'context': 'In the twelfth year (AD 207), the Dowager Wu, feeling her end approaching, called to her the two advisers Zhou Yu and Zhang Zhao and spoke thus: “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 349, 'talk': 'These two you are to serve as they were your teachers and treat them with all respect. My younger sister and I both were wives to your father, and so she is also a mother to you, and you are to serve her after I am gone as you now serve me. And you must treat your sister with affection and find a handsome husband for her.', 'context': 'And to her son she said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'The armies should not move during the period of mourning.', 'context': 'Zhang Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 431, 'talk': 'So Gan Ning got away from Xiakou and would have come to you then, but he feared that he would not be welcomed, since he had assisted Huang Zu and killed Ling Cao. I told him you were always ready to welcome able people and would nourish no resentment for former deeds. After all, every person was bound to do his best for his master. He would come with alacrity if he only felt sure of a welcome. I pray you express your pleasure.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'With his help I could destroy Huang Zu.', 'context': 'This was good news for Sun Quan and he said, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 260, 'talk': 'My heart is entirely captivated by your coming; I feel no resentment against you. I hope you will have no doubts on that score, and I may as well tell you that I desire some plan for the destruction of Huang Zu.', 'context': 'When the salutations were over, the chief said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 711, 'talk': 'The dynasty is decadent and without influence. Cao Cao will finally absorb the country down to the river unless he is opposed. Liu Biao provides nothing against the future, and his sons are quite unfitted to succeed him. You should lay your plans to oust him at once before Cao Cao anticipates you. The first attack should be made on Huang Zu, who is getting old and avaricious, so that every one hates him. He is totally unprepared for a fight and his army is undisciplined. He would fall at the first blow. If he were gone, you would control the western passes and could conquer the lands of Ba and Shu [0 Lands of two ancient states in the empire.]}. And you would be securely established.', 'context': 'Gan Ning replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'The advice is most valuable,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'We must go forward,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'I treated you well in the past; why do you now press me so hard?', 'context': 'From horseback, Huang Zu said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'I did good service for you, and yet you treated me as a pirate. Now what have you to say?', 'context': 'Gan Ning angrily shouted, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'It is impossible to try to hold one distant city alone. It is better to return home and prepare for the expedition that Liu Biao will surely send in revenge. We will meet and defeat his worn army, push home the attack, and capture his whole region.', 'context': 'But his adviser, Zhang Zhao, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'I should not have forgotten him even if he had said nothing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 353, 'talk': 'Long ago, if it had not been for Su Fei, my bones would have been rotting in some ditch and how then could I have rendered service under your banner? Now he deserves death, but I cannot forget his kindness to me, and I pray you take away the honors you have bestowed on me as a set−off to his crime.', 'context': 'Then Gan Ning went in to his lord and said, weeping, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Since he once showed kindness to you, I will pardon him for your sake. But what can be done if he run away?', 'context': 'Sun Quan replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'If he be pardoned and escape death, he will be immeasurably grateful and will not go away. If he should, then will I offer my life in exchange.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 343, 'talk': 'If he slew your noble father, then remember each was fighting for his lord for whom he was bound to exert himself to the utmost. But now that you both are under one flag and are of one house, you may not recall an ancient injury. You must regard my interests continually.', 'context': 'Hastily leaving his place, Sun Quan checked the angry officer, saying, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'But how can I not avenge this? It is a blood feud and we may not both live under the same sky.', 'context': 'Ling Tong beat his head upon the floor and cried, saying, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'This call is to consult you about avenging Huang Zu. You must take me with you and let me act as the circumstances direct. There are advantages to be got.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang advised him to go and said, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 320, 'talk': 'First you must thank Liu Biao for having saved you from the evil that Cai Mao planned against you at Xiangyang. However, you must not undertake any expedition against the South Land but say you must return to Xinye to put your army in good order.', 'context': 'On the way he discussed the course of action with his adviser, who said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 260, 'talk': 'Worthy Brother, I know you were the victim of a vile plot; and I should have put the prime mover to death for it, had there not been so universal a prayer for mercy. However, I remitted that penalty. I hope you do not consider that I was wrong.', 'context': 'The host said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Cai Mao hall little to do with it; I think it was due to his subordinates,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Why do you say this, my brother? Think you that I am equal to such a task?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'But give me a little time to think it over.', 'context': 'Here Zhuge Liang glanced at Liu Bei who continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'He has always been most kind and courteous. I could not take advantage of his weakness.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'A perfectly kind and gracious lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'My worthy nephew, this is a family affair. You should not come to me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'This is a family affair; I cannot touch it!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 173, 'iend': 245, 'talk': "I am an object of my stepmother's dislike; can you advise me what to do?", 'context': 'The adviser went, and when he had reached the Palace, dismounted, and was led in, Liu Qi conducted him into one of the inner rooms and when the tea had been brought, said, “'},
{'istart': 248, 'iend': 405, 'talk': "As a mere stranger guest, I can hardly have anything to do with your own 'bone and flesh' matters. If I did, and the story got abroad, much harm might ensue.", 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'Your glory has turned in my direction; you cannot mean to go away so pointlessly.', 'context': 'With this he rose to take leave. But Liu Qi was unwilling to say farewell. He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'It is not the sort of thing I can advise in,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Master, if you will not reply, that is well. But why incontinently leave me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Where is the writing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Sow not dissension among relatives,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Is it possible for me to make any plan for you?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Then is my life indeed in danger,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 163, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'I will die at your feet.', 'context': ' said the young man. “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'There is a way.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang checked him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'I pray you tell me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 231, 'iend': 403, 'talk': 'Jiangxia is important, and your son is the most suitable man to defend it. You must let him go. The southeast will be defended by your son; the northwest I will look after.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang returned to Liu Bei and related the whole interview. The young man soon acted on the advice given him, but his father would not at first consent to let him go. To settle his doubts Liu Biao sent for Liu Bei, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'I hear that Cao Cao has been training a naval force, and I am afraid he has intentions against us. We must be on our guard.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I know all about it; you need feel no anxiety,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is drilling his army at Xinye, and is a source of danger. He should be destroyed.', 'context': 'Xiahou Dun opened the debate, saying, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is a mean rat. I will certainly take him prisoner.', 'context': 'Xiahou Dun replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Do not despise him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Who is this Zhuge Liang?', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'How does he stand as compared with you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'There is no comparison. I am a mere glow−worm spark; he is the glory of the full moon,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'You are mistaken,', 'context': ' replied Xu Shu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Hasten to comfort me with news of victory,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 306, 'talk': 'He is very young, although he is clever and learned. Our brother really treats him too well. We have not seen any evidence of his wonderful skill.', 'context': "Xiahou Dun hastened to depart. The advent of Zhuge Liang and the extravagant deference shown him did not please Liu Bei's sworn brothers who grumbled, saying, “"},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'You do not know his worth. I have him as if the fish has got into the water again. Pray do not discuss this matter further, my brothers.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Then you have renounced all ambitions, my lord; you are just going to attend to this sort of thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'I was only amusing myself with the thing.', 'context': 'Liu Bei snatched off his cap and flung it away, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'How do you think you stand compared with Cao Cao?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Inferior.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'I am greatly distressed about it; but I see no way.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'You might recruit and I will train them. Then we might be able to oppose him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 156, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'We will get this Zhuge Liang to go and fight them.', 'context': 'Soon they heard that Xiahou Dun was leading an army of one hundred thousand troops against them. When he heard it, Zhang Fei said to his brother, Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': "Why not send the 'Water,' Brother?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I fear your brothers will not obey me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'We will go just to see what he will do,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'All of us are to go out to meet the enemy, but I have not yet heard what you are going to do.', 'context': 'Then said Guan Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I am going to guard the city.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'We are to go out to bloody battle, and you are to stay quietly at home quite comfortable.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei burst into a laugh, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Here is the sword and here the seal!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Disobedience of orders will be death.', 'context': ' replied the strategist, displaying the emblems of authority. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'Do you not understand that the plans elaborated in a little chamber decide success over thousands of miles? Do not disobey the command, my brothers.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Let us await the result. If he fails, then we can look to it.', 'context': 'Guan Yu remarked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'The place in front is Bowang Slope, and behind us is the River Luo,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'You lot, followers of Liu Bei, are only like wraiths following devils.', 'context': 'Then he rode forward at full speed. Zhao Yun rode to meet him, and Xiahou Dun opened a volley of abuse, “'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'I fear he is trying to lead us into an ambush.', 'context': "Seeing these tactics Han Hao, one of Xiahou Dun's generals, rode up to his chief and urged him to use caution, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'With such antagonists as these, I should not fear even Ten Ambushes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Here is your ambush,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'I will get to Xinye this evening before I have done.', 'context': ' said Xiahou Dun, laughing. “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Those who despise the enemy are beaten,', 'context': 'The two generals in the rear came to a narrow part of the road with reeds and rushes thick all round them. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'You are right,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'I will get on and warn the Commanding General; perhaps he will stop. You can halt those who come up.', 'context': ' replied Yu Jin. “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Halt the train!', 'context': 'Yu Jin rode forward shouting at the top of his voice, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'The roads here are narrow and difficult. Around us are thick forests. What if they use fire?', 'context': 'Xiahou Dun saw him coming up and asked what was the matter. Yu Jin said, “'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'the four quarters and the eight sides,', 'context': 'Then there arose a shout behind him. A rushing noise came from in the reeds and great tongues of flame shot up here and there. These spread and soon the fire was in “'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is really a fine strategist!', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang ordered his armies to collect; and as Guan Yu and Zhang Fei rode homeward they confessed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'We owe our lives to the Prince,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Xiahou Dun has been driven off, but Cao Cao will come with a stronger force.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'And what shall we do?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'My plan is quite ready,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 264, 'talk': 'Xinye is a small city and unfitted for our lengthy occupation. Liu Biao is ill and failing fast, so this is the time to take his region as a base where we may be safe against Cao Cao.', 'context': 'When Liu Bei asked how his adviser hoped to repel Cao Cao, Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'You speak well, but Liu Biao has shown me great kindness, and I could not bear to serve him an ill turn.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'If you do not take this opportunity, you will regret it ever after,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I would rather perish than do what is wrong.', 'context': '“'},
