{'istart': 166, 'iend': 241, 'talk': "I was the victim of Zhuge Liang's evil machinations; he attacked with fire.", 'context': 'When Xiahou Dun reached the capital, he presented himself to his master in bonds and craved death. But his master loosed him and let him tell his tale. And he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'As a soldier from your youth, you should have remembered that fire was a likely weapon in narrow roads.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'Li Dian and Yu Jin reminded me; I am sorry enough now.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Liu Bei as strong as he is now certainly is a menace to our existence, and he must be quickly destroyed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'He is one of my anxieties,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 294, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'horse', 'context': 'legions each. Each division had two leaders: Cao Ren and Cao Hong were in command of the first division; Zhang Liao and Zhang He, the second; Xiahou Dun and Xiahou Yuan, the third; Yu Jin and Li Dian, the fourth. The fifth body was led by Cao Cao himself. The van was commanded by Xu Chu. The “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 375, 'talk': 'Liu Bei and Liu Biao are both of the Imperial House and should not be attacked without grave reasons. Sun Quan in the six territories of the South Land is terrible as a crouching tiger and, with the Great River as his defense, he is very secure. If, Sir Prime Minister, you undertake this unjustifiable expedition, you will forfeit the respect of the world, I fear.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 378, 'iend': 468, 'talk': 'All three of them are disobedient ministers and rebels, and how can I fail to punish them?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'Where is the chance of success when the perfectly inhumane attacks the perfectly humane? He must be defeated.', 'context': 'Kong Rong went forth from the Palace sadly. Casting his eyes up to heaven, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Your father has just been carried off for execution; why do you not run away?', 'context': 'servants ran in and said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'When the nest is pulled down, are the eggs left unbroken?', 'context': 'The youths replied, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 262, 'talk': "You should not slay a righteous man who came to mourn over his friend's corpse. Zhi Xi had often warned Kong Rong against the danger Kong Rong's severe rectitude might lead him into.", 'context': 'However, this additional punishment was prevented by Adviser Xun Yu, who said, “'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 343, 'talk': 'The disease has attacked my very vitals and my time is short. I confide my orphans to your guardianship. My sons is unfit to succeed to my place, and I pray you, my brother, administer the region after my death.', 'context': 'chamber. Liu Bei went accompanied by his two brothers, Guan Yu and Zhang Fei, and Directing Instructor Zhuge Liang. Liu Biao said, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I will do my utmost to help my nephews; what else could I do, indeed?', 'context': 'Liu Bei wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 368, 'talk': 'Your father sent you to guard Jiangxia. Such a very responsible post should by no means have been quitted without orders. Suppose it was attacked, what might not happen? If your father sees you, he will be very angry, and it will make him worse. That would be most undutiful, and you should return to your command at once.', 'context': 'But Cai Mao refused him admittance and said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Who are you to speak thus wildly and oppose the testament of our late lord?', 'context': 'But Cai Mao replied harshly, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'You and your party have fabricated this testament, setting aside the rightful heir. Now the whole region is in the hands of the Cai family; and if our dead lord knew your doings, he would slay you!', 'context': 'Li Gui began to abuse him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 500, 'talk': "Not only are we threatened by a great army from the north, but the elder son, who is the real heir, at Jiangxia, and his uncle at Xinye, are to be reckoned with. These two have not been notified of the death, and they will resent that. We shall be in sad case if they also march against us. But if you will adopt my suggestion, then our people will be as steady as Taishan Mountains and our young lord's position and rank will be assured.", 'context': 'One of the secretaries, Fu Xuan, offered his advice, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'What is your plan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'To offer the whole region to Cao Cao, who will treat our young master most liberally.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'What advice!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Am I to yield my heritage to another before I have even fairly succeeded to it?', 'context': ' said Liu Zong angrily. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'The advice is good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 482, 'talk': 'Opportunism is a policy, and possibilities need consideration. In the name of government, Cao Cao is fighting against his neighbors. If our lord opposes him, he will be termed contumacious. Beside, any misfortune on our borders before our young lord is well established will react upon the internal administration, and our people will be panic−stricken at the mere news of the approach of a hostile army. How could we then offer any resistance?', 'context': ' said Kuai Yue. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'It is not that I disagree with you, but I should be a laughing stock to the whole world were I to abandon my heritage without an effort.', 'context': 'Liu Zong replied, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'If their advice is good, why not follow it?', 'context': 'He was interrupted by a speaker who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'He is a young man with the highest gifts,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'General, how do you compare with Cao Cao?', 'context': 'What he said was this, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Inferior,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 514, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has many soldiers and bold leaders; he is able and resourceful. He took Lu Bu at Xiapi and broke the power of Yuan Shao at Guandu. He pursued Liu Bei into Longyou and destroyed Mao Dun at White Wolf Hills. The destruction of such firmly established men shows his invincible character. Now he is on the way here, and it will be very difficult to withstand him. The plan proposed is the best you can expect, and you should not delay and hesitate till it is too late for ought but regret.', 'context': 'Wang Can continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Worthy Sir, you indeed speak to the point; I must inform my mother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'Why refer to me when three such gentlemen coincide in their opinions?', 'context': 'But just then they saw his mother appear from behind a screen; she had been listening to all that was said. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Tell Liu Zong to go out to meet me in the open country, and he will be in perpetual tenure of his land.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Hold on. I have something more to say.', 'context': 'But Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Yes; you know that the younger son has usurped the lordship, but you have not heard that he has already sent to offer Jingzhou to Cao Cao.', 'context': 'Then he said, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'How know you this?', 'context': 'This news shocked Yi Ji, who asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Your advice is good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'and my lord ought to take it.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'If you do not act in this way now, how will you repel Cao Cao, who has already reached Wancheng?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Our best plan is to take refuge in Fankou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'My lord should not worry. We have burned the army of Cao Cao at Bowang Slope, so we will see them fallen into another ruse in Xinye. This is no place to live in; we will move over to Fankou.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'After the battle, all generals shall gather at Fankou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 400, 'iend': 447, 'talk': 'It could be an ambush; it is unwise to advance.', 'context': 'Cao Hong and Cao Ren, with their one hundred thousand troops, preceded by Xu Chu leading three thousand of mailed men, marched toward Xinye. They formed a mighty host and reached Magpie Tail Slope about noon. Looking ahead, they saw what seemed a goodly army with many blue and red flags. Xu Chu pressed forward. As he neared, the flags moved from side to side, and he hesitated. He began to think, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Those troops are only make−believe,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Advance, there is no ambush. I will hasten up the supports.', 'context': ' said Cao Ren. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'This shows they are done,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'They have all run away, people and all. We may as well occupy the city and rest our soldiers ready for tomorrow.', 'context': ' said Cao Hong. “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'The careless men have let sparks fly about,', 'context': 'After the first watch the wind began to blow. Soon after the gate guards reported that a fire had started. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'You Cao Cao brigands!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Come and receive your fate!', 'context': ' shouted Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'How dare he, this rustic Zhuge Liang!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 422, 'talk': "Sir, you are new to this region, and you should win over the people's hearts. Liu Bei has moved all the people from Xinye to Fankou. If we march through the country, the people will be ground to powder. It would be well to call upon Liu Bei first to surrender, which will prove to the people that you have a care for them. If he yields, then we get Jingzhou without fighting.", 'context': 'Then Liu Ye came in to see his lord and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'He is a close friend of Liu Bei, and he is here with the army,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'But he will not come back,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'If he does not return, he will be a laughing stock to the whole world; he will come back.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 322, 'talk': "Cao Cao has sent me to invite you to surrender, thereby making a bid for popularity. But you ought also to know that he intends to attack the city from every point, that he is damming up the White River's waters to be sent against you, and I fear you will not be able to hold the city. You ought to prepare.", 'context': 'Then he said, “'},
{'istart': 384, 'iend': 715, 'talk': 'That is impossible, for all the world would ridicule me if I stayed. My old mother is dead, and I never forget my resentment. My body may be over there, but I swear never to form a plan for Cao Cao. You have the Sleeping−Dragon to help you and need have no anxiety about the ultimate achievement of your undertaking. But I must go.', 'context': ' Liu Bei asked Xu Shu to remain with them, but Xu Shu said, “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'We shall abandon Fankou and take Xiangyang.', 'context': 'When Liu Bei asked what Zhuge Liang meant to do, Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'But what of the people who have followed us? They cannot be abandoned.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'You can tell them to do as they wish. They may come if they like, or remain here.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 127, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'We will follow the Prince even if it be to death!', 'context': 'that the city could not be defended, and those who wished to do so might cross the river with the army. All the people cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Why was I ever born,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'to be the cause of all this misery to the people?', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 165, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Liu Zong, Good Nephew, I only wish to save the people and nothing more. I pray you quickly open the gates.', 'context': 'When Xiangyang came in sight, they saw many flags flying on the walls and that the moat was protected by barbed barriers. Liu Bei checked his horse and called out, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'Cai Mao and Zhang Yun are two traitors. The princely Liu Bei is a most upright man and has come here to preserve his people. Why do you repulse him?', 'context': 'Suddenly there appeared a general, with a small following, who cried out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Come in, Uncle Liu Bei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'and bring your army to slay these traitors!', 'context': ' cried Wei Yan, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Do not frighten the people!', 'context': 'Zhang Fei plunged forward to take Cai Mao and Zhang Yun, but he was checked by his brother, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I wanted to preserve the people, and I am only causing them injury,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Jiangling is an important point; we will first take that as a place to dwell in,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'That pleases me greatly,', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 256, 'talk': 'Shameful is thy brother, lacking both in virtue and in talents. I refused to bear the burden you wished to lay upon me, wherein I was wrong. But the people committed no sin. I pray your glorious spirit descend and rescue these people.', 'context': 'He lamented, saying, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 287, 'talk': 'Jiangling is a defensible shelter, but with this crowd we can only advance very slowly and when can we reach the city? If Cao Cao pursue, we shall be in a parlous state. Our counsel is to leave the people to their fate for a time and press on to Jiangling.', 'context': 'The generals of Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'The success of every great enterprise depends upon humanity; how can I abandon these people who have joined me?', 'context': 'But Liu Bei wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'The pursuers will be upon us quickly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'Let us send Guan Yu to Jiangxia for succor. Liu Qi should be told to bring soldiers and prepare boats for us at Jiangling.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 208, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'You are mad! You know nothing and understand nothing of destiny,', 'context': 'would be yours for the taking. This is a sort of opportunity that does not recur and you should not miss it.” The young man consulted Cai Mao, who called Wang Wei an evil counselor and spoke to him harshly. “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Cai Mao is the betrayer of the country, and I wish I could eat him alive!', 'context': 'Wang Wei angrily retorted, saying, “'},
{'istart': 182, 'iend': 405, 'talk': 'There are fifty thousand of horse, one hundred fifty thousand of foot, and eighty thousand of marines. Most of the money and grain are at Jiangling; the rest is stored at various places. There are ample supplies for a year.', 'context': 'Then Cai Mao and Zhang Yun went to Fankou to see Cao Cao. Cai Mao was by instinct specious and flattering, and when his host asked concerning the resources of Jingzhou, he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'How many war vessels are there? Who is in command?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'The ships, of all sizes, number seven thousands, and we two are the commanders.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 213, 'talk': "I am about to propose to the Throne that Liu Biao's son should be perpetual Imperial Protector of Jingzhou in succession to his late father.", 'context': 'When they went to thank Cao Cao for these honors, he told them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Why these two evident self−seekers and flatterers have been treated so generously?', 'context': 'Then Xun You asked Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'Do I not know all about them? Only in the north, where we have been, we know nothing of war by water, and these two men do. I want their help for the present. When my end is achieved, I can do as I like with them.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'I do not rejoice so much at gaining Jingzhou as at meeting you, friend Kuai Yue.', 'context': 'Cao Cao presently entered the city and took his seat in the residence in state. Then he summoned Kuai Yue and said to him graciously, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'I cannot do that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Follow Liu Zong and put him and his mother to death. Our worries are thus removed.', 'context': 'Then Cao Cao called his trusty officer Yu Jin and said, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'I have an order from the great Prime Minister to put you both to death, mother and son; you may as well submit quietly.', 'context': 'Yu Jin followed the small party. When he drew near he shouted, “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Jiangling is an important place, and very rich. If Liu Bei gets it, it will be difficult to dislodge him.', 'context': 'So Xiangyang was settled. Then Xun You proposed a further advance. He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'How could I have overlooked that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Why are you late?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'There is as yet no news from Jiangxia; there must be some difficulties.', 'context': 'One day Zhuge Liang came in and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I wish that you yourself would go there,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Liu Qi would remember your former kindness to him and consent to anything you proposed.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'What might that portend?', 'context': 'Liu Bei was frightened and asked, “'},
{'istart': 147, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'A calamity is threatening this very night. My lord must leave the people to their fate and flee quickly.', 'context': 'Jian Yong, who knew something of the mysteries of nature, took the auspices by counting secretly on his fingers. Pale and trembling he announced, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'If you allow your pity to overcome your judgment, then misfortune is very near,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Turncoat! Can you still look humans in the face?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 251, 'iend': 403, 'talk': 'Myriads of living souls are suffering from love of me, and my officers and my loved ones are lost. One would be a graven image not to weep at such loss.', 'context': 'By that time Liu Bei had got beyond the sound of battle and there was time to rest. Only a few of his followers had been able to keep near him. He knew nothing of the fate of his officers or the people. He lifted up his voice in lamentation, saying, “'},
{'istart': 137, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun has gone over to Cao Cao!', 'context': "Still plunged in sadness, presently he saw hurrying toward him Mi Fang, with an enemy's arrow still sticking in his face. He exclaimed, “"},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Do you think I can believe that of my old friend?', 'context': 'Liu Bei angrily bade him be silent, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Perhaps he has gone over,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'He must see that we are nearly lost and there are riches and honors on the other side.', 'context': ' said Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'He has followed me faithfully through all my misfortunes. His heart is firm as a rock. No riches or honors would move him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I saw him go away northwest,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Wait till I meet him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'If I run against him, I will kill him!', 'context': ' said Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Beware how you doubt him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 255, 'talk': "Have you forgotten the circumstances under which your brother Guan Yu had to slay Cai Yang to ease your doubts of him? Zhao Yun's absence is due to good reason wherever he has gone, and he would never abandon me.", 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 191, 'iend': 415, 'talk': "My master confided to me his family and the child lord Liu Shan; and I have lost them. How can I look him in the face? I can only go now and fight to the death. Whatever happen, I must go to seek the women and my lord's son.", 'context': "Now Zhao Yun, after fighting with the enemy from the fourth watch till daylight, could see no sign of his lord and, moreover, had lost his lord's family. He thought bitterly within himself, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Have you seen the two mothers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Say,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': "One of the Princely One's carriage guards. I am wounded.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Do you know anything of the two ladies?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Is Lady Gan among you!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'It was my fault that you were lost. But where are Lady Mi and our child lord?', 'context': 'spear in the sand and wept, “'},
{'istart': 233, 'iend': 274, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun, why have you betrayed our lord?', 'context': 'free. Then taking two of the horses, Zhao Yun set Lady Gan on one and Mi Zhu took the other. They rode away toward Long Slope Bridge. But there, standing grim on the bridge, was Zhang Fei. As soon as he saw Zhao Yun, he called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I fell behind because I was seeking the ladies and our child lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'What do you mean by talking of betrayal?', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'If it had not been that Jian Yong arrived before you and told me the story, I should hardly have spared you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Where is the master?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Not far away, in front there.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Conduct Lady Gan to him; I am going to look for Lady Mi,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 193, 'iend': 327, 'talk': 'A woman with a child in her arms, and wounded in the thigh so that she cannot walk, is lying over there through that hole in the wall.', 'context': 'Nevertheless not for a single instant thought he of turning back; he was too intent upon his quest. To and fro, back and forth, he rode questioning this person and that. At length a man said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'My child will live then since you are here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 197, 'talk': "Pity him, O General; protect him, for he is the only son of his father's flesh and blood. Take him to his father and I can die content.", 'context': ' cried Lady Mi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'It is my fault that you have suffered,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'But it is useless to say more. I pray you take my horse while I will walk beside and protect you till we get clear.', 'context': ' replied Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'I may not do that. What would you do without a steed? But the boy here I confide to your care. I am badly wounded and cannot hope to live. Pray take him and go your way. Do not trouble more about me.', 'context': 'She replied, “'},
{'istart': 216, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'I hear shouting,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 250, 'iend': 317, 'talk': 'The soldiers will be upon us again in a moment. Pray mount quickly.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'But really I cannot move,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Do not let there be a double loss!', 'context': ' she said. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Take the child,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'His life and safety are in your hands.', 'context': ' cried Lady Mi. “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'If you will not do what I say, what will happen when the soldiers come up?', 'context': 'and nearer, Zhao Yun spoke harshly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 165, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'Zhang He of Hejian', 'context': 'As the road cleared before him, Zhao Yun saw another detachment barring his way. At the head of this was a general exalted enough to display a banner with his name “'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun, Zhao Yun, stop!', 'context': 'This apparition frightened Zhang He, who abandoned the pursuit forthwith, and Zhao Yun rode off. Presently he heard shouts behind, “'},
{'istart': 604, 'iend': 643, 'talk': 'We should hear the name of the warrior!', 'context': "As the men of Cao Cao came pressing on, Zhao Yun drew Cao Cao's own sword to beat them off. Nothing could resist the Blue Blade Sword. Armor, clothing, it went through without effort and blood gushed forth in fountains wherever it struck. So the four generals were soon beaten off, and Zhao Yun was once again free. Now Cao Cao from a hilltop of the Prospect Mountain saw these deeds of derring−do and a general showing such valor that none could withstand him, so Cao Cao asked of his followers whether any knew the man. No one recognized him, so Cao Hong galloped down into the plain and shouted out, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'I am Zhao Yun of Changshan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'A very tiger of a leader! I must get him alive.', 'context': 'Cao Hong returned and told his lord, who said, “'},
{'istart': 137, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Quickly dismount and be bound!', 'context': 'and Zhong Shen. One of these was armed with a massive ax, the other a halberd. As soon as they saw Zhao Yun, they knew him and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Help me, Zhang Fei!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Hasten!', 'context': ' he cried and crossed the bridge. “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I will keep back the pursuers.', 'context': ' cried Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 565, 'talk': "My fault—death is too light a punishment. Lady Mi was severely wounded; she refused my horse and threw herself into a well. She is dead, and all I could do was to fill in the well with the rubbish that lay around. But I placed the babe in the breast of my fighting robe and have won my way out of the press of battle. Thanks to the little lord's grand luck I have escaped. At first he cried a good deal, but for some time now he has not stirred or made a sound. I fear I may not have saved his life after all.", 'context': 'Still panting from his exertions, Zhao Yun gasped out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Happily, Sir, your son is unhurt,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'To preserve that suckling I very nearly lost a great commander!', 'context': 'Liu Bei took the child but threw it aside angrily, saying, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Were I ground to powder, I could not prove my gratitude.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun picked up the child again and, weeping, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Too great the risk you ran to save This child,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'I am Zhang Fei of Yan ((an ancient state)); who dares fight with me?', 'context': 'So in a mighty voice he shouted: “'},
{'istart': 161, 'iend': 394, 'talk': 'Guan Yu had said that his brother Zhang Fei was the sort of man to go through an army of a hundred legions and take the head of its commander−in−chief, and do it easily. Now here is this terror in front of us, and we must be careful.', 'context': 'At the sound of this thunderous voice, a terrible quaking fear seized upon Cao Cao, and he bade them take the umbrella away. Turning to his followers, he said, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'I am Zhang Fei of Yan; who dares fight with me?', 'context': 'As he finished speaking, again that terrible voice was heard, “'},
{'istart': 198, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'What mean you? You will not fight nor do you run away!', 'context': 'Cao Cao, seeing his enemy so fierce and resolute, was too frightened to think of anything but retreat; and Zhang Fei, seeing a movement going on in the rear, once again shook his spear and roared, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Do not be frightened,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'After all Zhang Fei is but one man and not worthy of extravagant fear. If you will only return and attack, you will capture your enemy.', 'context': ' said Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Brave as you are, Brother, and no one is braver; but you are no strategist,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'What mean you, Brother?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is very deep. You are no match for him. The destruction of the bridge will bring him in pursuit.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'If he ran away at a yell of mine, think you he will dare return?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'The bridge has been destroyed; Zhang Fei has left.', 'context': 'The two generals sent by Cao Cao to reconnoiter near Long Slope Bridge returned, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Then he is afraid,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'I fear this is one of the wiles of Zhuge Liang; so be careful.', 'context': 'Li Dian said, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Zhang Fei is just a bold warrior, but there is no guile about him,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 178, 'iend': 260, 'talk': 'Before us rolls the Great River; behind is the pursuer. What hope is there for us?', 'context': 'Liu Bei was making all speed to Hanjin. Suddenly there appeared in his track a great cloud of dust whence came loud rolls of drums and shoutings. Liu Bei was dismayed and said, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 264, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is a fish in the fish kettle, a tiger in the pit. Catch him this time, or the fish will get back to the sea and the tiger escape to the mountains. Therefore every general must use his best efforts to press on.', 'context': 'Now Cao Cao in an order to his army had said, “'},
{'istart': 183, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'I have waited here a long time.', 'context': 'In consequence every leader bade those under him hasten forward. And they were pressing on at great speed when suddenly a body of soldiers appeared from the hills and a voice cried, “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Here we are, tricked again by that Zhuge Liang!', 'context': 'As soon as Guan Yu appeared, Cao Cao stopped and said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Alas!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'Had you taken my advice that day of the hunting in Xutian, we should have escaped the misery of this day.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'But,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Are you all right, my uncle; I am very guilty.', 'context': 'stood in the prow of the foremost ship. The leader cried, “'},
{'istart': 272, 'iend': 437, 'talk': "The Directing Instructor's words are excellent, but I wish rather my uncle stayed awhile in Jiangxia till the army was in thorough order. Then he could go to Xiakou.", 'context': 'I would ask you, my lord, to make it a permanent camp. Your nephew can go to Jiangxia to get the fleet in order and prepare weapons. Thus we can create two threatening angles for our position. If we all return to Jiangxia, the position will be weakened.” Liu Qi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'You speak to the point, Nephew,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has gone to Jiangxia and may ally himself with the South Land, and the opposition to me will be greater. Can he be destroyed?', 'context': 'Then said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'The splendor of your achievements has spread wide. Therefore you might send a messenger to invite Sun Quan to a grand hunting party at Jiangxia, and you two could seize Liu Bei, share Jingzhou with Sun Quan, and make a solemn treaty. Sun Quan will be too frightened not to come over to you, and your end will be gained.', 'context': 'Xun You said, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 433, 'talk': "Jingzhou is contiguous to our borders. It is strong and defensive, its people are rich. It is the sort of country that an emperor or a king should have. Liu Biao's recent death gives an excuse for me to be sent to convey condolence and, once there, I shall be able to talk over Liu Bei and the officers of the late Imperial Protector to combine with you against Cao Cao. If Liu Bei does as I wish, then success is yours.", 'context': 'Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 256, 'talk': "Cao Cao's power is too great for us to cope with. Let us go over to the South Land and ask help from Sun Quan. If we can set north and south at grips, we ought to be able to get some advantage from our intermediate position between them.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 259, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'But will they be willing to have anything to do with us?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 332, 'iend': 418, 'talk': 'The South Land is a large and populous country, and Sun Quan has ambitions of his own.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 553, 'talk': "Cao Cao with his army of a million holds the Han River and the Great River. The South Land will certainly send to find out all possible about the position. Should any messenger come, I shall borrow a little boat and make a little trip over the river and trust to my little lithe tongue to set north and south at each other's throats. If the south wins, we will assist in destroying Cao Cao in order to get Jingzhou; if the north wins, we shall profit by the victory to get the South Land. So we shall get some advantage either way.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'That is a very fine view to take,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'But how are you going to get hold of any one from the South Land to talk to?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 147, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'It is done!', 'context': "Liu Bei's question was answered by the arrival of Lu Su, and as the ship touched the bank and the envoy came ashore, Zhuge Liang laughed, saying, “"},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'When Sun Ce died, did your country send any condolences?', 'context': 'Turning to Liu Qi he asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'It is impossible there would be any mourning courtesies between them and us; we had caused the death of his father, Sun Jian.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Then it is certain that this envoy does not come to present condolences but to spy out the land.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'When Lu Su asks about the movements of Cao Cao, you will know nothing. If he presses the matter, say he can ask me.', 'context': 'So he said to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'My army was so small that we fled whenever we heard of his approach; so I do not know how many he had.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'You had the advice of Zhuge Liang, and you used fire on Cao Cao twice. You burned him almost to death so that you can hardly say you know nothing about his soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Without asking my adviser, I really do not know the details.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Where is Zhuge Liang? I should like to see him,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'I have long admired your genius but have never been fortunate enough to meet you. Now that I have met you, I hope I may speak of present politics.', 'context': 'So they sent for him and he was introduced. When the ceremonies were over, Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 158, 'talk': "I know all Cao Cao's infamies and wickednesses, but to my regret we were not strong enough to withstand him. That is why we avoided him.", 'context': 'Replied Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Is the Imperial Uncle going to stay here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'The Princely One is an old friend of Wu Ju, Governor of Changwu, and intends to go to him.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Wu Ju has few troops and insufficient supplies; he cannot ensure safety for himself. How can he receive the Uncle?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Changwu is not one to remain in long, but it is good enough for the present. We can make other plans for the future.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'Sun Quan is strongly posted in the six southern territories and is exceedingly well supplied. He treats able people and scholars with the greatest courtesy and so they gather round him. Now if you are seeking a plan for your Prince, you cannot do better than send some friend to confer with him.', 'context': 'Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'There have never been any relations between my master and yours,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'I fear there would be nothing but a waste of words. Besides, we have no one to send.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'Your elder brother Zhuge Jin is there as adviser and is longing to see you. I am but a simple wight, but I should be pleased to discuss affairs with my master and you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'But Zhuge Liang is my Directing Instructor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'and I cannot do without him. He cannot go.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'It is important; I pray you give me leave to go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 226, 'talk': "When you see my master, do not reveal the truth about the magnitude of Cao Cao's army.", 'context': 'In the boat on the way to Chaisang, the two travelers beguiled the time by discussing affairs. Lu Su impressed upon his companion, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'You do not have to remind me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'but I shall know how to reply.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'I know the general outline, but I want a little time to prepare my report,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'That came yesterday. I have sent the bearer of it back, and this gathering is to consider the reply,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'What have you decided upon, my lord?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'I have not yet decided.', 'context': ' asked Lu Su as he finished the letter. “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 363, 'talk': "It would be imprudent to withstand Cao Cao's hundred legions backed by the imperial authority. Moreover, your most important defense against him is the Great River; and since Cao Cao has gained possession of Jingzhou, the river is his ally against us. We cannot withstand him, and the only way to tranquillity, in my opinion, is submission.", 'context': 'Then Zhang Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'The words of the speaker accord with the manifest decree of providence,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'What do you desire?', 'context': 'the door, and Lu Su followed him. Outside he took Lu Su by the hand, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'What they have all been saying is very derogatory to you. A common person might submit; you cannot.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Why? How do you explain that?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 347, 'talk': "They all talk and talk; they miss my point of view. Now you have just spoken of a bold game, and your view is the same as mine. Surely God has expressly sent you to me. Still Cao Cao is now the stronger by all Yuan Shao's and Liu Biao's armies, and he has possession of Jingzhou. I fear he is almost too powerful to contend with.", 'context': 'Sun Quan sighed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'I have brought back with me Zhuge Liang, the younger brother of our Zhuge Jin. If you questioned him, he would explain clearly.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Is Master Sleeping−Dragon really here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Really here; in the guest−house.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 116, 'talk': "When you see my master, say nothing of the magnitude of Cao Cao's army.", 'context': 'commands to the guest, particularly saying, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'I shall act as circumstances dictate; you may be sure I shall make no mistakes.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'Here is a persuader fitted for discourse.', 'context': "They, on their part, noted with interest Zhuge Liang's refined and elegant manner and his commanding figure, thinking within themselves, “"},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'You will pardon the most insignificant of our official circle, myself, if I mention that people say you compare yourself with those two famous men of talent, Guan Zhong and Yue Yi. Is there any truth in this?', 'context': 'Zhang Zhao led the way in trying to bait the visitor. He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'To a trifling extent I have compared myself with them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 475, 'talk': 'I have heard that Liu Bei made three journeys to visit you when you lived in retirement in your simple dwelling in the Sleeping Dragon Ridge, and that when you consented to serve him, he said he was as lucky as a fish in getting home to the ocean. Then he desired to possess the region about Jingzhou. Yet today all that country belongs to Cao Cao. I should like to hear your account of all that.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 141, 'talk': "This Zhang Zhao is Sun Quan's first adviser; and unless I can nonplus him, I shall never have a chance with his master.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang thought, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 490, 'talk': "In my opinion the taking of the region around the Han River was as simple as turning over one's hand. But my master Liu Bei is both righteous and humane and would not stoop to filching the possession of a member of his own house. So he refused the offer of succession. But Liu Zong, a stupid lad, misled by specious words, submitted to Cao Cao and fell victim to his ferocity. My master is in camp at Jiangxia, but what his future plans may be cannot be divulged at present.", 'context': 'So he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 521, 'talk': "Why then, when you went to Xinye, did not Cao Cao's army throw aside their arms and armors and flee like rats? Why could you not have told Liu Biao how to give tranquillity to his people? Why could you not aid his orphan son to protect his frontiers? Instead you abandoned Xinye and fled to Fankou; you were defeated at Dangyang and fled to Xiakou with no place to rest in. Thus, after you had joined Liu Bei, he was worse off than before. Was it thus with Guan Zhong and Yue Yi? I trust you do not mind my blunt speech.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 860, 'talk': 'Small forces are no match for large armies. Victory and defeat are common episodes in every campaign. The great Founder of the Hans suffered many defeats at the hands of Xiang Yu, but Liu Bang finally conquered at Gaixia, and that battle was decisive. Was not this due to the strategy of Han Xin who, though he had long served his master Liu Bang, had never won a victory. Indeed real statesmanship and the restoration of stable government is a master plan far removed from the vapid discourses and debates of a lot of bragging babblers and specious and deceitful talkers, who, as they themselves say, are immeasureably superior to the rest of humankind but who, when it comes to deeds and decisions to meet the infinite and constant vicissitudes of affairs, fail to throw up a single capable person. Truly such people are the laughing stock of all the world.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 331, 'talk': "But what of Cao Cao's present position? There he is, encamped with one hundred legions and a thousand leaders. Whither he goes he is invincible as wriggling dragon, and whither he looks he is as fearsome as roaring tiger. He seems to have taken Jiangxia already, as we see.", 'context': 'But another in the assembly lifted up his voice, saying, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has acquired the swarms of Yuan Shao and stolen the crowds of Liu Biao. Yet I care not for all his mob legions.', 'context': 'The speaker was Yu Fan; and Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'When you got thrashed at Dangyang and in desperation sent this way and that to ask help, even then did you not care? But do you think big talk really takes people in?', 'context': 'Yu Fan smiled icily, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 462, 'talk': 'Liu Bei had a few thousand of scrupulous soldiers to oppose to a million of fierce brutes. He retired to Xiakou for breathing space. The South Land have strong and good soldiers, and there are ample supplies, and the Great River is a defense. Is now a time for you to convince your lord to bend the knee before a renegade, to be careless of his honor and reputation? As a fact Liu Bei is not the sort of man to fear such a rebel as Cao Cao.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Will you talk of our southern land with a tongue like the tongues of the persuaders Zhang Yi and Su Qin in the ancient time?', 'context': 'Next, Bu Zhi, who was among those seated, said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 616, 'talk': "You regard those two as mere speculative talkers; you do not recognize them also as heroes. Su Qin bore the Prime Ministers' seals of six federated states; Zhang Yi was twice Prime Minister of the state of Qin. Both were men of conspicuous ability who brought about the reformation of their governments. They are not to be compared with those who quail before the strong and overbear the weak, who fear the dagger and run away from the sword. You, Sir, have listened to Cao Cao's crafty and empty threat, and it has frightened you into advising surrender. Dare you ridicule Su Qin and Zhang Yi?", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'What do you think of Cao Cao?', 'context': 'Bu Zhi was silenced. Then suddenly another interjected the question, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'You are mistaken,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 677, 'talk': "Why do you speak so undutiful words, as if you knew neither father nor prince? Loyalty and filial duty are the essentials of a person's being. For a minister of Han, correct conduct demands that one is pledged to the destruction of any one who does not follow the canon of a minister's duty. Cao Cao's forbears enjoyed the bounty of Han, but instead of showing gratitude, he nourishes in his bosom thoughts of rebellion. The whole world is incensed against him, and yet you would claim for him the indication of destiny. Truly you are a man who knows neither father nor prince, a man unworthy of any words, and I decline to argue with you farther.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang angrily replied, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 980, 'talk': "Are you not that Lu Ji who pocketed the orange when you were sitting among Yuan Shu's guests?2 Listen to me; I have a word to say to you. Inasmuch as Cao Cao is a descendant of a minister of state, he is by heredity a servant of the Hans. But now he has monopolized all state authority and knows only his own arbitrary will, heaping every indignity upon his lord. Not only does he forget his prince, but he ignores his ancestors; not only is he a rebellious servant of Han, but the renegade of his family. Liu Bei of Yuzhou 3 is a noble scion of the imperial family upon whom the Emperor has conferred rank, as is recorded in the annals. How then can you say there is no evidence of his imperial origin? Beside, the very founder of the dynasty was himself of lowly origin, and yet he became emperor. Where is the shame in weaving mats and selling shoes? Your mean, immature views are unfit to be mentioned in the presence of scholars of standing.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang laughed and replied, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 207, 'talk': "Zhuge Liang's words are overbearing, and he distorts reason. It is not proper argument, and he had better say no more. But I would ask him what classical canon he studied.", 'context': 'But another of those present said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 694, 'talk': 'The dryasdusts of every age select passages and choose phrases; what else are they good for? Do they ever initiate a policy or manage an affair? Yi Yin, who was a farmer in the state of Shen, and Lu Wang, the fisherman of the River Wei, Zhang Liang and Chen Ping, Zheng Yu and Geng Yan—all were men of transcendent ability, but I have never inquired what classical canon they followed or on whose essays they formed their style. Would you liken them to your rusty students of books, whose journeyings are comprised between their brush and their inkstone, who spend their days in literary futilities, wasting both time and ink?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang looked at his interlocutor, who was Yan Jun, and said, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'You are mightily fond of big words, Sir, but they do not give any proof of your scholarship after all. I am inclined to think that a real scholar would just laugh at you.', 'context': 'But another disputant, Cheng Deshu by name, suddenly shouted, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 818, 'talk': 'There is the noble scholar, loyal and patriotic, of perfect rectitude and a hater of any crookedness. The concern of such a scholar is to act in full sympathy with his day and leave to future ages a fine reputation. There is the scholar of the mean type, a pedant and nothing more. He labors constantly with his pen, in his callow youth composing odes and in hoary age still striving to understand the classical books completely. Thousands of words flow from his pen, but there is not a solid idea in his breast. He may, as did Yang Xiong, glorify the age with his writings and yet stoop to serve a tyrant such as Wang Mang. No wonder Yang Xiong threw himself out of a window; he had to. That is the way of the scholar of mean type. Though he composes odes by the hundred, what is the use of him?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 368, 'talk': 'This is not paying fit respect to a guest. You have among you the most wonderful man of the day, and you all sit there trying to entangle him in speech while our archenemy Cao Cao is nearing our borders. Instead of discussing how to oppose Cao Cao, you are all wrangling and disputing.', 'context': 'to pose Zhuge Liang, suddenly some one appeared from without and angrily shouted, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'There is a saying that though something may be gained by talk, there is more to be got by silence. Why not give my lord the advantage of your valuable advice instead of wasting time in discussion with this crowd?', 'context': 'He turned to address Zhuge Liang, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'They did not understand,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'and it was necessary to enlighten them, so I had to speak.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 192, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'Why have you not been to see me, Brother?', 'context': "As Huang Gai and Lu Su led the guest toward their master's apartments; they met his brother Zhuge Jin. Zhuge Liang saluted him with the deference due to an elder brother, and Zhuge Jin said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'I am now in the service of Liu Bei of Yuzhou, and it is right that public affairs precede private obligations. I cannot attend to any private matters till my work is done. You must pardon me, Brother.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'After you have seen Marquis Sun Quan, you will come and tell me your news,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 175, 'talk': "Do not tell the magnitude of Cao Cao's forces; please remember.", 'context': 'As they went along to the audience chamber, Lu Su again cautioned Zhuge Liang against any rash speech, saying, “'},
{'istart': 184, 'iend': 378, 'talk': 'Certainly in appearance this is no common man. He is one to be incited perhaps, but not to be persuaded. It will be better to see what he has to say first, then I will try to stir him to action.', 'context': "As Zhuge Liang spoke of Liu Bei's intentions, he glanced up at his host. He noted the green eyes and red beard and the dignified commanding air of the man and thought within himself, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Lu Su has often spoken of your genius;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'it is a great pleasure to meet you. I trust you will confer upon me the advantage of your instruction.', 'context': ' said the host, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I am neither clever nor learned;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'it humiliates me to hear such words.', 'context': ' was the reply, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'You have been at Xinye lately, and you helped your master to fight that decisive battle with Cao Cao, so you must know exactly the measure of his military strength.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 161, 'talk': "My master's army was small and his generals were few; the city was paltry and lacked supplies. Hence no stand could be made against such a force as Cao Cao had.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'How many has he in all?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Horse and foot, land and marine, he has a million.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Is there not some doubt about that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has enough administrators and strategists to control such a host, and his capable and veteran leaders are more than a thousand; perhaps more than two thousand.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': "What will be Cao Cao's next move now that he has overcome Jingzhou?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'He is camped along the river, and he has collected a fleet. If he does not intend to invade the South Land, what can be his intentions?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Since that is his intention, it is a case of fight or not fight. I wish you would decide that for me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'I have something I could say, but I fear, Sir, you would not care to hear it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'I am desirous of hearing your most valuable opinion.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 726, 'talk': 'Strife has prevailed for a long time; and so you have raised your army in the South Land and Liu Bei collected his forces south of the Han River to act in contest for the empire against Cao Cao. Now Cao Cao has overcome most of his difficulties, and his recent conquest of Jingzhou has won him great and wide renown. Though there might be one bold enough to tackle him, yet there is no foothold for such. That is how Liu Bei has been forced to come here. But, General, I wish you to measure your forces and decide whether you can venture to meet Cao Cao and that without loss of time. If you cannot, then follow the advice of your councilors: cease your military preparations and yield, turn your face to the north and serve.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'You have the reputation of being reasonable, but I know also you are inclined to hesitate. Still this matter is most important, and evil will be quickly upon you if you do not decide.', 'context': 'Sun Quan did not reply. But his guest went on, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'If what you say represents the actual conditions, why does not Liu Bei yield?', 'context': 'Then replied Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 370, 'talk': 'Well, you know Tian Heng, that hero of the state of Qi; his character was too noble for him to submit to any shame. It is necessary to remember that Liu Bei also is an off−shoot from the Dynastic Family, beside being a man of great renown. Every one looks up to him. His lack of success is simply the will of Heaven, but manifestly he could not bow the knee to any one.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'Luckily for you, my lord is too large−minded to rebuke you to your face, for you spoke to him most contemptuously.', 'context': 'But Lu Su was annoyed and reproached Zhuge Liang for his maladroit way of talking to Sun Quan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'What a sensitive fellow it is!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'I know how Cao Cao could be destroyed, but he never asked me; so I said nothing.', 'context': ' cried he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'If you really do know how that could be done, I will certainly beg my lord to ask you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang insulted me too deeply,', 'context': "Lu Su at once went into his master's private room, where he found Sun Quan still very irritable and angry. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I have already reproached him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'So he had a plan ready, and his words were meant to provoke me. I did despise him for a moment, and it has very nearly lost me.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I offended you just now; I hope you are not implacable.', 'context': 'Sun Quan spoke courteously, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'And I also was rude,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'I entreat pardon.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 361, 'talk': 'The enemies of Cao Cao were Lu Bu, Liu Biao, Yuan Shao, Yuan Shu, Liu Bei, and my poor self. Now most of these are gone, and only Liu Bei and I remain. I will never allow the land of Wu to be dictated to by another. The only one who could have withstood Cao Cao was Liu Bei, but he has been defeated lately and what can he do now against such force?', 'context': 'Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Your words, Master, open up the road clearly. I have decided and shall have no further doubts.', 'context': 'Sun Quan joyfully replied, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Our master has fallen into the trap set by this Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'When Zhang Zhao heard of the decision he met his colleagues and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 382, 'talk': "We hear you are going to attack Cao Cao; but how do you stand when compared with Yuan Shao? In those days Cao Cao was comparatively weak, and yet he overcame. What is he like today with his countless legions? He is not to be lightly attacked, and to listen to Zhuge Liang's advice to engage in a conflict is like carrying fuel to a fire.", 'context': 'They went in a body to their lord and said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 174, 'talk': "Liu Bei has been defeated, and he wants to borrow our help to beat his enemy. Why must our lord lend himself to his schemes? Pray listen to our leader's words.", 'context': 'Gu Yong said, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'They came to exhort you not to fight, but to compel you to surrender simply because they wish to secure the safety of their families. They distort their sense of duty to serve their own ends, and I hope you will not take their advice.', 'context': 'When the troop of advisers had retired, Lu Su came in, saying, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'If you hesitate, you will certainly be led astray by the majority and—', 'context': 'Sun Quan being sunk in thought and saying nothing, Lu Su went on, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Retire for a time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'I must think it over carefully.', 'context': ' said his master. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'If I fight, I might fail; and if I offer to surrender, perhaps Cao Cao will reject my proposal,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Have you forgotten the last words of my sister?', 'context': 'Then she replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': "In Zhou Yu's counsels you safety find.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'For internal matters consult Zhang Zhao; for external policy Zhou Yu.', 'context': "The dying message which Lady Wu recalled to Sun Quan's memory was, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Have no anxiety;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'I shall be able to decide this. But go quickly and beg Zhuge Liang to come to see me.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Have you heard of our terrible danger?', 'context': 'They were received, and after the exchange of the usual commonplaces, Zhang Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'I have heard nothing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 595, 'talk': "Cao Cao and his hordes are encamped up the Han River. He has just sent letters asking our lord to hunt with him in Jiangxia. He may have a desire to absorb this country but, if so, the details of his designs are still secret. We prayed our master to give in his submission and so avoid the horrors of war, but now Lu Su has returned bringing with him the Directing Instructor of Liu Bei's army, Zhuge Liang. Zhuge Liang, desiring to avenge himself for the recent defeat, has talked our lord into a mind for war, and Lu Su persists in supporting that policy. They only await your final decision.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Are you all unanimous in your opinions?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'We are perfectly unanimous,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'No; I have heard nothing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'And are you unanimous, Generals?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'They may take my head, but I swear never to surrender.', 'context': 'Huang Gai suddenly started up and smote his forehead, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Not one of us is willing to surrender,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'My desire also is to decide matters with Cao Cao on the battlefield. How could we think of submission? Now I pray you retire, Generals, and when I see our lord, I will settle his doubts.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 375, 'talk': 'My brother has come down the river saying that Liu Bei desires to ally himself with our lord against Cao Cao. The civil and military hold different opinions as to the course to be pursued, but as my brother is so deeply concerned, I am unwilling to say much on either side. We are awaiting your decision.', 'context': 'They were brought in and, after the usual courtesies, Zhuge Jin said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'And what do you think about it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Submission is an easy road to tranquillity, while the result of war is hard to foretell.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'I shall have my mind made up. Come tomorrow to the palace, and the decision shall be announced.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu smiled, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I must not say much now,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'but you will see tomorrow in the palace, when the matter will be fully debated.', 'context': ' replied Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'We may not oppose Cao Cao when he acts at the command of the Emperor. Moreover, he is very strong, and to attack him is to take serious risks. In my opinion, opposition would mean defeat and, since submission means peace, I have decided to advise our lord to write and offer surrender.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu replied, “'},
{'istart': 306, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'But you are wrong!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 344, 'iend': 724, 'talk': 'This country has been under the same rule for three generations and cannot be suddenly abandoned to some other. Our late lord Sun Ce said that you were to be consulted on matters beyond the border, and we depended upon you to keep the country as secure and solid as the Taishan Mountains. Now you adopt the view of the weaklings and propose to yield! I cannot believe you mean it.', 'context': ' stammered Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'The six territories contain countless people. If I am the means of bringing upon them the misery of war, they will hate me. So I have decided to advise submission.', 'context': 'Replied Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 151, 'talk': "But do you not realize our lord's might and the strength of our country? If Cao Cao does attack, it is very uncertain that he will realize his desire.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Why do you smile thus, Master?', 'context': 'Presently Zhou Yu asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Master,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'what do you mean?', 'context': ' said Lu Su, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Why, this intention to submit is perfectly reasonable; it is the one proper thing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 7, 'talk': 'There!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang knows the times perfectly well, and he agrees with me.', 'context': ' exclaimed Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'But, both of you, why do you say this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Would you make our lord crook the knee to such a rebel as Cao Cao?', 'context': 'Lu Su interrupted angrily, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'What two persons could cause Cao Cao to go away as you say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'But who are the two?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'How do you know Cao Cao so greatly desires these two?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Try,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'You old rebel; this insult is too deep!', 'context': 'Turning to the north and pointing with his finger, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'You do not know, Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'Of those two women of the Qiao family you mentioned, Elder Qiao is the widow of Sun Ce, our late ruler, and Younger Qiao is my wife!', 'context': ' replied Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'No indeed; I did not know. I blundered; a deadly fault; a deadly fault!', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang feigned the greatest astonishment and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'One of us two has to go, either the old rebel or I; we shall not both live. I swear that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'However, such a matter needs a good deal of thought,', 'context': ' cried Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Should I be happy enough not to be rejected, I would render such humble service as I could. Perhaps presently I might be able to offer a plan to oppose him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I am going to see my lord tomorrow to discuss this matter,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'I hear that Cao Cao is encamped on the river and has sent a dispatch to you, my lord; I would ask what your opinion is.', 'context': 'Soon Zhou Yu entered and, when Sun Quan had finished the usual gracious remarks, Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'What do you think, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Who advise surrender?', 'context': 'and therefore I have asked you to come and decide the point.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Zhang Zhao and his party are firmly set in this opinion.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'I should be pleased to hear why you are for surrender, Master.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu then turned to Zhang Zhao and said, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 430, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has been attacking all opponents in the name of the Emperor, who is entirely in his hands. He does everything in the name of the government. Lately he has taken Jingzhou and thereby increased his prestige. Our defense against him was the Great River, but now he also has a large fleet and can attack by water. How can we withstand him? Wherefore I counsel submission till some chance shall offer.', 'context': 'Then Zhang Zhao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'This is but the opinion of an ill−advised student,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'How can you think of abandoning this country that we have held for three generations?', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'That being so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'where is a plan to come from?', 'context': ' said Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 960, 'talk': "Moreover, Cao Cao has undertaken this expedition in defiance of all the rules of war. The north is unsubdued; Ma Teng and Han Sui threaten his rear, and yet he persists in his southern march. This is the first point against Cao Cao. The northern soldiers are unused to fighting on the water; Cao Cao is relinquishing his well−tried cavalry and trusting to ships. That is the second point against him. Again, we are now in full winter and the weather is at its coldest so there is no food for the horses. That is the third point against. Soldiers from the central state marching in a wet country among lakes and rivers will find themselves in an unaccustomed climate and suffer from malaria. That is the fourth point against. Now when Cao Cao's armies have all these points against them, defeat is certain, however numerous they may be, and you can take Cao Cao captive just as soon as you wish. Give me a few legions of veterans and I will go and destroy him.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 371, 'talk': 'The rebellious old rascal has been wanting to overthrow the Hans and set up himself for years. He has rid himself of all those he feared, save only myself, and I swear that one of us two shall go now. Both of us cannot live. What you say, Noble Friend, is just what I think, and Heaven has certainly sent you to my assistance.', 'context': 'Sun Quan started up from his place, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Thy servant will fight a decisive battle,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'and shrink not from any sacrifice. Only, General, do not hesitate.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Let any other person mention surrender, and he shall be served as I have served this table.', 'context': 'Sun Quan drew the sword that hung at his side and slashed off a corner of the table in front of him, exclaiming, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'With this sword you will slay any officer who may disobey your commands.', 'context': 'In conclusion Sun Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 362, 'talk': "You have heard our lord's charge to me to lead you to destroy Cao Cao; you will all assemble tomorrow at the river−side camp to receive my orders. Should any be late or fail, then the full rigor of military law—the seven prohibitions and the fifty−four capital penalties—there provided, will be enforced.", 'context': 'Zhou Yu took the sword and turning to the assembly said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'But your master has not yet made up his mind,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Till he has, no plan can be decided upon.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'What do you mean?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 221, 'talk': "In his heart, Sun Quan is still fearful of Cao Cao's numbers and frets over the inequality of the two armies. You will have to explain away those numbers and bring him to a final decision before anything can be effected.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What you say is excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'You must have something of real importance to say if you come like this at night.', 'context': 'Sun Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'I am making my dispositions tomorrow; you have quite made up your mind?', 'context': 'Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'The fact is,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 217, 'talk': "If that Zhuge Liang can gauge my master's thoughts so very accurately, he is too clever for me and will be a danger. He will have to be put out of the way.", 'context': 'Zhou Yu left; but in his innermost heart he said to himself, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'it is self−destruction to make away with your ablest officer before Cao Cao shall have been destroyed.', 'context': ' said Lu Su, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'But Zhuge Liang will certainly help Liu Bei to our disadvantage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Try what his brother Zhuge Jin can do to persuade him. It would be an excellent thing to have these two in our service.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Yes, indeed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 484, 'talk': 'The law knows no partiality, and you will all have to attend to your several duties. Cao Cao is now more absolute than ever was Dong Zhuo, and the Emperor is really a prisoner in Xuchang, guarded by the most cruel soldiers. We have a command to destroy Cao Cao, and with your willing help we shall advance. The army must cause no hardship to the people anywhere. Rewards for good service and punishments for faults shall be given impartially.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu addressed the gathering, saying, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 154, 'talk': "I have always despised Zhou Yu as a mere student who would never be a general, but this shows that he has a leader's talent. I must support him.", 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 375, 'talk': "Evidently your brother is a genius, a man born to be a king's counselor. Why then does he serve Liu Bei? Now that he is here, I wish you to use every effort to persuade him to stay with us. Thus our lord would gain able support and you two brothers would be together, which would be pleasant for you both. I wish you success.", 'context': 'Next Zhou Yu sent for Zhuge Jin and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'I am ashamed of the little service I have rendered since I came here, and I can do no other than obey your command to the best of my ability.', 'context': 'Zhuge Jin replied, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Brother, do you remember the story of Bo Yi and Shu Qi, the brothers who would not be separated?', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Jin, weeping also, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Ah, Zhou Yu has sent him to talk me over,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 467, 'talk': 'You are talking now of love, but what I stand for is duty. We are both men of Han, and Liu Bei is of the family. If you, Brother, could leave the South Land and join me in serving the rightful branch, then on the one side we should be honored as Ministers of Han, and on the other we should be together as people of the same flesh and blood should be. Thus love and duty would both receive their proper meed. What do you think of it, my brother?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'I came to persuade him and lo! It is I who is being talked over,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'What do you think?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'General Sun Quan has treated me with great kindness, and I could not turn my back on him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'You go on first, Noble Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I will then march to support you.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 771, 'talk': "Cao Cao, though he had fewer troops than Yuan Shao, nevertheless overcame Yuan Shao because he followed the advice given by Xun You to destroy Yuan Shao's supplies at Wuchao. Now Cao Cao has over eight hundred thousand troops while I have but fifty or sixty thousand. In order to defeat him, his supplies must be destroyed first. I have found out that the main depot is at the Iron Pile Mountains. As you have lived hereabout, you know the topography quite well, and I wish to entrust the task of cutting off supplies to you and your colleagues Guan Yu, Zhang Fei, and Zhao Yun. I will assist you with a thousand soldiers. I wish you to start without delay. In this way we can best serve our masters.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang came; and after the salutations were ended, Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 290, 'talk': 'This is a ruse in revenge for my not having been persuaded to enter the service of the South Land. If I refuse, I shall be laughed at. So I will do as he asks and trust to find some means of deliverance from the evil he intends.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang saw through this at once. He thought to himself, “'},
{'istart': 149, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Do you think this expedition will succeed?', 'context': 'quite unconcerned and getting the soldiers ready to march. Unable to let Zhuge Liang go without a warning, however, Lu Su put a tentative question, “'},
{'istart': 226, 'iend': 429, 'talk': 'I am an adept at all sorts of fighting, with foot, horse, and chariots on land and marines on the water. There is no doubt of my success. I am not like you and your friend, only capable in one direction.', 'context': ' Zhuge Liang laughingly replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'What do you mean by our being capable only in one direction?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 169, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'This man is far too clever; he beats me ten to one. He will have to be done away with or my country will suffer.', 'context': 'Without loss of time, Lu Su went to Zhou Yu to relate what Zhuge Liang had told him. Zhou Yu shook his head when he heard it and beat the ground with his foot, saying, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 154, 'talk': "This is the moment to use people; you must think of the country's good first of all. When once Cao Cao is defeated, you may do as you please.", 'context': 'Said Lu Su, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang went to Wu some time ago, and no word has come from him, so I know not how the business stands. Will any one volunteer to go to find out?', 'context': 'Then he assembled his officers and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I will go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang has been here a long time, and I desire that he may return with me.', 'context': 'Mi Zhu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is making plans with me, and I could not let him return,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'I also wish to see Liu Bei that we may make joint plans; but when one is at the head of a great army, one cannot get away even for a moment. If your master would only come here, it would be very gracious on his part.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'What is your reason for desiring Liu Bei to come?', 'context': 'Then Lu Su asked Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'If you have finally decided to go, then will I go with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'And I also,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'How many ships has he?', 'context': 'As soon as he arrived, the guards ran to tell Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Only one; and the escort is only about a score.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'His fate is sealed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'General, you are famous through all the empire, while I am a nobody. Do not overwhelm me with too great deference.', 'context': 'After the salutations, Zhou Yu wished Liu Bei to take the upper seat, but he declined saying, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'What is to be done now?', 'context': 'Commander−in−Chief. The news gave Zhuge Liang a great shock, and he said to himself, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'My lord faces no danger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'That is my brother, Guan Yu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Is he the slayer of Yan Liang and Wen Chou?', 'context': 'Zhou Yu, quite startled, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Exactly; he it is,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Wait till we have defeated Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'then you shall see him.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'I would take leave now; I will come again to congratulate you when the enemy has been defeated and your success shall be complete.', 'context': 'and rose, saying, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Sir, do you know in how great danger you were today?', 'context': 'Liu Bei was exceedingly pleased, but Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'No; I did not think of danger.', 'context': 'Suddenly sobered, Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'If Guan Yu had not been there, you would have been killed,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'I am quite safe,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 322, 'talk': "Although I am living in the tiger's mouth, I am as steady as the Taishan Mountains. Now, my lord, return and prepare your ships and soldiers. On the twentieth day of the eleventh month, send Zhao Yun with a small ship to the south bank to wait for me. Be sure there is no miscarriage.", 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'What are your intentions?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'When the southeast wind begins, I shall return.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Then you had cajoled Liu Bei into coming, why did you not carry out your plan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'To death with this fellow!', 'context': 'he fell into a frenzy of rage, tore the letter to fragments, and threw them on the ground. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'When two countries are at war, their emissaries are not slain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 138, 'talk': "Messengers are slain to show one's dignity and independence,", 'context': ' said Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 460, 'iend': 505, 'talk': 'I am Gan Ning; I challenge any one to combat.', 'context': 'Cao Cao was greatly angered when he heard that his letter had been torn to fragments, and he resolved to attack forthwith. His advance was led by the Supreme Admiral Cai Mao, the Vice−Admiral Zhang Yun, and others of the Jingzhou officers who had joined his side. Cao Cao went as hastily as possible to the meeting of the three rivers and saw the ships of the South Land sailing up. In the bow of the foremost ship stood a fine figure of a warrior who cried, “'},
{'istart': 171, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'You did not do your best. You let an inferior force overcome you.', 'context': 'Cao Cao was worsted, but his ships returned to the bank, where a camp was made and order was restored. Cao Cao sent for his defeated leaders and reproached them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 317, 'talk': 'The Jingzhou marines have not been exercised for a long time, and the others have never been trained for naval warfare at all. A naval camp must be instituted, the northern soldiers trained and the Jingzhou force drilled. When they have been made efficient, they will win victories.', 'context': 'Cai Mao defended himself, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'If you know what should be done, why have you not done it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'What is the use of telling me this? Get to work.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Water Gates,', 'context': 'So Cai Mao and Zhang Yun organized a naval camp on the river bank. They established twenty−four “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'How well and correctly built is that naval base! Any one knows the names of those in command?', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'They are Cai Mao and Zhang Yun,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'They have lived in our country a long time,', 'context': ' said his officers. “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'and are thoroughly experienced in naval warfare. I must find some means of removing them before I can effect anything.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'The other day you lost a battle, and the soldiers were greatly dispirited. Now the enemy have spied out our camp. What can be done?', 'context': 'Again Cao Cao found fault with his officers and said, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'When I was a youth, Zhou Yu and I were fellow students and pledged friends. My three−inch tongue is still good, and I will go over and persuade him to surrender.', 'context': 'In eager response to his question one stepped out, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Are you a good friend of Zhou Yu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Rest content, O Prime Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'What preparations are necessary?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Just a youth as my servant and a couple of rowers; nothing else.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'A persuader is coming.', 'context': 'about him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'You have been well I hope since last we met,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': "You have wandered far and suffered much in this task of emissary in Cao Cao's cause,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I have not seen you for a very long time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'As you choose to treat your old friend like this, I think I will take my leave,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 145, 'iend': 317, 'talk': 'Jiang Gan is an old fellow student of mine, and we are pledged friends. Though he has arrived here from the north, he is no artful pleader so you need not be afraid of him.', 'context': "musicians played songs of victory and the wine circulated merrily. Under its mellowing influence, Zhou Yu's reserve seemed to thaw and he said, “"},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 354, 'talk': 'You take this and wear it for the day as master of the feast. This day we meet only as friends and speak only of friendship, and if any one shall begin a discussion of the questions at issue between Cao Cao and our country, just slay him.', 'context': 'Then Zhou Yu took off the commanding sword which he wore as Commander−in−Chief and handed it to Taishi Ci, saying, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'Since I assumed command, I have tasted no drop of wine, but today as an old friend is present and there is no reason to fear him; I am going to drink freely.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Do you not think my soldiers a fine lot of fellows?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Strong as bears and bold as tigers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Do you not think I have a fairly good store of grain and forage?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': "Your troops are brave and your supplies ample; the world's rumor is not unfounded.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'For a genius like you, it is nothing extraordinary,', 'context': 'looked forward to a day like this, did we?” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 509, 'talk': 'A man of the time, I have found a proper lord to serve. In his service, we rely upon the right feeling between minister and prince outside, and at home we are firm in the kindly feeling of relatives. He listens to my words and follows my plans. We share the same good or evil fortune. Even when the great old persuaders like Su Qin, Zhang Yi, Lu Jia, and Li Yiji lived again, even when their words poured forth like a rushing river, their tongues were as a sharp sword, it is impossible to move such as I am!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'The wine is too much for me,', 'context': 'A burst of applause greeted the song. By this time it was getting late, and the guest begged to be excused. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Those two were connected with the South Land in the beginning,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 326, 'iend': 391, 'talk': "Friend, I am going to let you see Cao Cao's head in a day or two.", 'context': ' thought Jiang Gan, so he secreted the letter in his dress and began to examine the others. But at that moment Zhou Yu turned over, and so Jiang Gan hastily blew out the light and went to his couch. Zhou Yu was muttering as he lay there as if dreaming, saying, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 140, 'talk': "Wait a few days; you will see Cao Cao's head. The old wretch!", 'context': 'Jiang Gan hastily made some reply to load on his host to say more. Then came, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'General, are you awake?', 'context': 'Then some one came in, saying, “'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Who is this on the couch?', 'context': 'At that moment as if suddenly awakened from the deepest slumber, Zhou Yu started up and said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Do you not remember, General? You asked your old friend to stay the night with you; it is he, of course.', 'context': 'The voice replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I drank too much last night,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'and I forgot. I seldom indulge to excess and am not used to it. Perhaps I said many things I ought not.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu in a regretful tone, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'A man has arrived from the north.', 'context': 'The voice went on, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Speak lower,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Whither are you going, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I fear I am in the way here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'and so I have taken leave of the Commander−in−Chief for a time. So do not stop me.', 'context': ' replied Jiang Gan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Zhou Yu is very clever and perfectly high−minded,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Nothing that I could say moved him in the least.', 'context': ' said Jiang Gan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Your failure makes me look ridiculous,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Well, if I did not win over Zhou Yu, I found out something for you. Send away these people and I will tell you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 229, 'iend': 254, 'talk': 'I want you two to attack.', 'context': "The servants were dismissed, and then Jiang Gan produced the letter he had stolen from Zhou Yu's tent. He gave it to Cao Cao. Cao Cao was very angry and sent for Cai Mao and Zhang Yun at once. As soon as they appeared, he said, “"},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'But the soldiers are not yet sufficiently trained.', 'context': 'Cai Mao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'The soldiers will be well enough trained when you have sent my head to Zhou Yu, eh?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'These two had been remiss, and so had been put to death.', 'context': 'So he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Those two Cai Mao and Zhang Yun were my only source of anxiety,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Now they are gone; I am quite happy.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'General, if you can continue like this, you need not fear Cao Cao.', 'context': 'Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'I do not think any of them saw my game,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'There has been so much to do that I have not been able to come to listen to your instructions,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'That is truly so,', 'context': ' said Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 148, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'and I have not yet congratulated the Commander−in−Chief.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'What have you wished to congratulate him upon?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Why Sir, the matter upon which he sent you to find out whether I knew about it or not. Indeed I can congratulate him on that.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'But how did you know, Master?', 'context': 'Lu Su turned pale and gasped, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 417, 'talk': 'The ruse succeeded well thus played off on Jiang Gan. Cao Cao has been taken in this once, but he will soon rise to it. Only he will not confess his mistake. However, the two men are gone, and your country is freed from a grave anxiety. Do you not think that is a matter for congratulation? I hear Mao Jie and Yu Jin are the new admirals, and in their hands lie both good and evil for the fate of the northern fleet.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Do not let Zhou Yu know that I know his ruse. If you let him know, he will seek some chance to do me harm.', 'context': 'As he was going away, Zhuge Liang cautioned him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Really he must be got rid of;', 'context': 'Lu Su promised; nevertheless he went straight to his chief and related the whole thing just as it happened. “'},
{'istart': 155, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'I have quite decided to put the man out of the way.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'If you slay him, will not Cao Cao laugh at you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Oh, no; I will find a legitimate way of getting rid of him so that he shall go to his death without resentment.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'But how can you find a legitimate way of assassinating him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Do not ask too much; you will see presently.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'On a great river arrows are the best,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Whatever task the Commander−in−Chief lays upon me, I must certainly try to perform,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'May I inquire by what date you require the hundred thousand arrows?', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Could you have them ready in ten days?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'The enemy will be here very soon; ten days will be too late,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'In how many days do you estimate the arrows can be ready?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Let me have three days; then you may send for your hundred thousand.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'No joking, remember!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'There is no joking in war time.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'I shall have to congratulate you most heartily when this is accomplished.', 'context': 'drank to the success of the undertaking and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'This day is too late to count,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'On the third from tomorrow morning send five hundred small boats to the river side to convey the arrows.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Do you not think there is some deceit about this?', 'context': 'After he had gone, Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Clearly it is not I! It is he who has signed his own death warrant,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 494, 'talk': 'Without being pressed in the least, he asked for a formal order in the face of the whole assembly. Even if he grew a pair of wings, he could not escape. Only I will just order the workers to delay him as much as they can, and not supply him with materials, so that he is sure to fail. And then, when the certain penalty is incurred, who can criticize? You can go and inquire about it all and keep me informed.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 250, 'talk': 'He wants to hurt me, as you know, and I did not think you could not keep my secret. And now there is what you saw today and how do you think I can get a hundred thousand arrows made in three days? You will simply have to rescue me.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'You brought the misfortune on yourself, and how can I rescue you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'I look to you for the loan of twenty vessels, manned each by thirty people. I want blue cotton screens and bundles of straw lashed to the sides of the boats. I have good use for them. On the third day, I have undertaken to deliver the fixed number of arrows. But on no account must you let Zhou Yu know, or my scheme will be wrecked.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 141, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is not using bamboo or feathers or glue or varnish, but has some other way of getting arrows.', 'context': 'Lu Su consented and this time he kept his word. He went to report to his chief as usual, but he said nothing about the boats. He only said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': "Let us await the three days' limit,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Why have you sent for me, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I want you to go with me to get those arrows.', 'context': ' asked Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Whither are you going?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Do not ask; you will see.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'But what shall we do if they attack us?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Coming up in a fog like this means that they have prepared an ambush for us. Do not go out, but get all the force together and shoot at them.', 'context': 'Jin, ran off to report to Cao Cao, who said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'We thank you, Sir Prime Minister, for the arrows.', 'context': 'As they left, Zhuge Liang asked all the crews to shout derisively, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 281, 'talk': "Every boat must have five or six thousand arrows and so, without the expenditure of an ounce of energy, we must have more than ten myriad arrows, which tomorrow can be shot back again at Cao Cao's army to his great inconvenience.", 'context': 'On the way down Zhuge Liang said to his companion, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'You are really superhuman,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'But how did you know there would be a thick fog today?', 'context': ' said Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'He is better than I; his methods are more than human.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu was amazed and sighed sadly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 156, 'iend': 204, 'talk': "Your superhuman predictions compel one's esteem.", 'context': 'When, shortly after his return, Zhuge Liang went to the tent of the Commander−in−Chief, he was welcomed by Zhou Yu, who came forward to greet him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'There is nothing remarkable in that trifling trick,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'My lord sent yesterday to urge me to advance, but I have no master plan ready; I wish you would assist me, Master.', 'context': 'Then Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 137, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'But where should I, a man of poor everyday ability, find such a plan as you desire?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 235, 'talk': "I saw the enemy's naval camp just lately, and it looked very complete and well organized. It is not an ordinary place to attack. I have thought of a plan, but I am not sure it will answer. I should be happy if you would decide for me.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'do not say what your plan is, but each of us will write in the palm of his hand and see whether our opinions agree.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Fire.', 'context': 'other, and both burst out laughing, for both had written the same word, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Since we are of the same opinion,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I had thought of that myself,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'Whom do you think the best person to send?', 'context': ' replied Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 261, 'talk': 'Cai Mao has been put to death, but all his clan and family are in the army, and his two younger brothers are junior generals. You have them most securely in your power and may send them to surrender. The ruler of the South Land will never suspect deceit there.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 301, 'talk': 'I want you two pretend to surrender to the South Land so that you can gather intelligence and sent it back. When all done, you will be richly rewarded. But do not betray me.', 'context': 'Cao Cao decided to act on this plan, and in the evening summoned Cai Zhong and Cai He to his tent, where he told them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'Our families are in Jingzhou, and that place is yours,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'Should we dare betray? You need have no doubts, Sir. You will soon see the heads of both Zhou Yu and Zhuge Liang at your feet.', 'context': ' replied they. “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Our innocent brother has been put to death, and we desire vengeance. So we have come to offer allegiance to you. We pray you appoint us to the vanguard.', 'context': 'They were led in and, bowing before the general, said, weeping, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 450, 'talk': 'They have come without their families, and so I know their desertion is only pretense. They have been sent as spies, and I am going to meet their ruse with one of my own. They shall have some information to send. You will treat them well, but keep a careful guard over them. On the day our soldiers start the offense, they shall be sacrificed to the flag. But be very careful that nothing goes wrong.', 'context': 'But Zhou Yu gave Gan Ning secret orders, saying, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Every one agrees in thinking the surrender of Cai Zhong and Cai He feigned and they should be rejected.', 'context': 'Gan Ning went away; and Lu Su came to tell Zhou Yu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'But they wish to revenge the death of their brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Where is the pretense? If you are so suspicious, you will receive nobody at all.', 'context': ' said the General. “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Why do you smile?', 'context': 'Lu Su left much piqued and went to see Zhuge Liang to whom he told the story. Zhuge Liang only smiled. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'You have surely some wise plan to propose that you come at night like this.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'The enemy are more numerous than we, and it is wrong to delay. Why not burn them out?', 'context': 'Huang Gai replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Who suggested that to you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I thought of it myself, nobody suggested it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'I just wanted something like this, and that is why I kept those two pretended deserters. I want them to give some false news. The pity is that I have no one to feign desertion to the other side and work my plan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'But I will carry out your plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'But if you cannot show some injury, you will not be believed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Kill me; I do not mind,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 324, 'talk': "Our lord's orders were to destroy Cao Cao, and whoever mentioned the word surrender should be put to death. Now, the very moment when the two armies are to engage, you dare talk of surrender and damp the ardor of my army! If I do not slay you, how can I support the others?", 'context': "Zhou Yu's anger flared up and he flushed, crying, “"},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'This is the third generation since I went with General Sun Jian, and we overran the southeast; whence have you sprung up?', 'context': 'Huang Gai then flamed up in turn, saying, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'He is a veteran officer of the South Land; pray pardon him!', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'What are you prating about?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Dare you come between me and my duty?', 'context': ' cried Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'If you dare flout me again, you shall have the other fifty. If you are guilty of any disrespect, you shall be punished for both faults!', 'context': 'Zhou Yu sprang from his chair and pointing his finger at Huang Gai said, “'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 361, 'talk': "Though the other officers have been cowed into silence, I think thought you, Sir, might have interceded. You are a guest and not under Zhou Yu's orders. Why did you stand by with your hands up your sleeves and say never a word?", 'context': 'Lu Su went to see the suffering officer and then called on Zhuge Liang in his boat. Lu Su related the story of the beating and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'You insult me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Why do you say that? I have never insulted you; never since the day we came here together.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'Do you not know that terrible beating was but a ruse? How could I try to dissuade Zhou Yu?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 398, 'talk': "Cao Cao would not be taken in unless there was some real bodily suffering. Zhou Yu is going to send Huang Gai over as a deserter, and Zhou Yu will see to it that the two Cao Cao's spies duly tell the tale. But when you see the General, you must not tell him that I saw through the ruse. You say that I am very angry like the others.", 'context': 'Then Lu Su began to perceive, and Zhuge Liang continued, saying, “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Why have you so cruelly beaten a proved and trusty officer?', 'context': 'Lu Su went to see Zhou Yu and asked, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Do the officers resent it?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'They are all upset about it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'And what does your friend think?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang also resents it in his heart, and thinks you have made a mistake.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Then I have deceived him for once,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'What mean you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Surely you must have some serious quarrel with the General.', 'context': 'bade the servants go away, and Kan Ze said, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'I have none,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Then this beating is just part of a ruse?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'How did you guess?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Because I watched the General, and I guessed about nine tenths of the truth.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 361, 'talk': 'You see I have been very generously treated by the Sun family, all three of them, and have no means of showing my gratitude except by offering to help in this ruse. True I suffer, but I do not regret that. Among all those I know in the army, there is not one I am intimate with except yourself. You are true and I can talk with you as a friend.', 'context': 'Huang Gai said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I suppose you wish me to present your surrender letter to Cao Cao; is that it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Just that; will you do it?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 365, 'talk': 'When you, my friend, have suffered so much for our lord, could I spare myself? No; while a person lives, he must go on fulfilling his mission, or he is no better than the herbs that rot in the field.', 'context': "Now Huang Gai had thought of Kan Ze to present the treacherous letter to Cao Cao, as Kan Ze's gifts made him most suitable. Kan Ze accepted with enthusiasm, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'However, this matter must speed;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'there is no time to lose.', 'context': ' continued Kan Ze, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'The letter is already written,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Is he not just a spy?', 'context': 'informed Cao Cao, who said at once, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Bring him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'You are an adviser of East Wu; what then are you doing here?', 'context': 'prisoner, he said harshly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'You know I am fighting against East Wu and you come here privately. Why should I not question you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 385, 'talk': 'You, O Prime Minister, treat people with sincerity and are ready to welcome ability and so I, and those under my leadership, desire to enter your service whereby to acquire reputation and remove the shameful stigma. The commissariat, weapons, and the supply ships that I am commanding will also come over to you. In perfect sincerity I state these matters; I pray you not to doubt me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'Huang Gai is trying to play the personal injury trick on me, is he? And you are in it as the intermediary to present the letter. How dare you come to sport with me?', 'context': 'Then he smacked the table, opened his eyes wide with anger, saying, “'},
{'istart': 122, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'What do you find to laugh at now that I have foiled you and your ruse has failed?', 'context': 'face untroubled. On the contrary, he laughed aloud. At this Cao Cao told them to bring him back and harshly said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': "I was not laughing at you; I was laughing at my friend's simplicity.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'What do you mean by his simplicity?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'If you want to slay, slay; do not trouble me with a multitude of questions.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'And so you say that the letter is a vicious trick?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'What mean you? I, ignorant?', 'context': 'fight, Zhou Yu will certainly capture you. But how sad to think I die at the hand of such an ignorant fellow!” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'You are ignorant of any strategy and a victim of unreason; is not that sufficient?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Well then, tell me where is any fault.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'You treat wise people too badly for me to talk to you. You can finish me and let there be an end of it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'If you can speak with any show of reason, I will treat you differently.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 479, 'talk': "Do you not know that when one is going to desert one's master and become a renegade, one cannot say exactly when the chance will occur? If one binds one's self to a fixed moment and the thing cannot be done just then, the secret will be discovered. One must watch for an opportunity and take it when it comes. Think: is it possible to know exactly when? But you know nothing of common sense; all you know is how to put good humans to death. So you really are an ignorant fellow!", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'I did not see clearly; that is quite true. I offended you, and I hope you will forget it.', 'context': 'At this Cao Cao changed his manner, got up, and came over to the prisoner bowing, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'The fact is that Huang Gai and I are both inclined to desert to you; we even yearn for it as a child desires its parents. Is it possible that we should play you false?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'If you two could render me so great a service, you shall certainly be richly rewarded.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'We do not desire rank or riches; we come because it is the will of Heaven and the plain way of duty.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Let me see the letter.', 'context': "came in and whispered in Cao Cao's ear. He replied, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'That is from the two Cai brothers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'I cannot return; pray, Sir, send some other one you can trust.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'If some one else should go, the secret would be discovered.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'If it had not been for your persuasive tongue, then had I undergone this suffering in vain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'I will now go to get news of the two Cai brothers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Why, Sir, do you anger him? Why not be silent about your injuries?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'What know you of our bitterness?', 'context': ' said they. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'We think you seem much inclined to go over to Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'They have found out; they must die to keep their mouths shut.', 'context': 'Kan Ze at this lost color; Gan Ning started up and drew his sword, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Let us tell you something quite secret.', 'context': ' cried the two in a flurry. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Quick, then,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'But are you speaking the truth?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Is it likely we should say such a thing if it were untrue?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Then this is the very heaven−given chance.', 'context': 'Gan Ning put on a pleased look and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'You know we have already told Cao Cao of the Huang Gai affair and how you were insulted.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'When an honest person happens upon an enlightened master, his heart will always be drawn toward him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 328, 'talk': 'On the other side Gan Ning has been put to shame by the Commander−in−Chief whom he is prepared to betray for the sake of revenge. Huang Gai has been punished and sent Kan Ze to propose that he should come over to our side. Only I still distrust the whole thing. Who will go over to the camp to find out the real truth?', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'I failed in my mission the other day and am greatly mortified. I will risk my life again and, this time, I shall surely bring good news.', 'context': 'Then Jiang Gan spoke up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 237, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'Success depends upon this man.', 'context': 'Cao Cao approved of him as messenger and bade him start. Jiang Gan set out in a small craft and speedily arrived in the Three Gorges, landing near the naval camp. Then he sent to inform Zhou Yu, who hearing who it was chuckled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 300, 'iend': 514, 'talk': 'You must use fire against him. But the river is wide and if one ship is set on fire, the others will scatter unless they are fastened together so that they must remain in one place. That is the one road to success.', 'context': 'This Pang Tong was from Xiangyang. And he had gone to the east of the river to get away from the strife. Lu Su had recommended him to Zhou Yu, but he had not yet presented himself. When Zhou Yu sent Lu Su to ask what scheme of attack he would recommend against Cao Cao, Pang Tong had said to Lu Su, “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'The only person who can manage this is Pang Tong himself.', 'context': 'Lu Su took this message to the General, who pondered over it and then said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is very wily;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'how can Pang Tong go?', 'context': ' said Lu Su, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'My friend, why did you treat me so badly?', 'context': 'When Zhou Yu saw Jiang Gan, Zhou Yu put on an angry face and said, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'I remembered the old days when we were as brothers, and I came expressly to pour out my heart to you. Why do you say I treated you badly?', 'context': 'Jiang Gan laughed and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 869, 'talk': 'You came to persuade me to betray my master, which I would never do unless the sea dried up and the rocks perished. Remembering the old times, I filled you with wine and kept you to sleep with me. And you, you plundered my private letters and stole away with never a word of farewell. You betrayed me to Cao Cao and caused the death of my two friends on the other side and so caused all my plans to miscarry. Now what have you come for? Certainly, it is not out of kindness to me. I would cut you in two, but I still care for our old friendship. I would send you back again, but within a day or two I shall attack that rebel; and if I let you stay in my camp, my plans will leak out. So I am going to tell my attendants to conduct you to a certain retired hut in the Western Hills, and keep you there till I shall have won the victory. Then I will send you back again.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 570, 'iend': 585, 'talk': 'The Art of War.', 'context': "When Jiang Gan found himself in the lonely hut, he was very depressed and had no desire to eat or sleep. But one night, when the stars were very brilliant, he strolled out to enjoy them. Presently he came to the rear of his lonely habitation and heard, near by, some one crooning over a book. Approaching with stealthy steps, he saw a tiny cabin half hidden in a cliff whence a slender beam or two of light stole out between the rafters. He went nearer and peeping in, saw a man reading by the light of a lamp near which hung a sword. And the book was Sun Zi's classic “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'This is no common person,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'I am Pang Tong.', 'context': 'The host replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Then you are surely the Master known as Blooming−Phoenix, are you not?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Yes; I am he.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'How often have I heard you talked about! You are famous. But why are you hidden away in this spot?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'I am Jiang Gan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'With your gifts, you would succeed anywhere,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I, too, know well that you are a model of military strategy,', 'context': 'to turn my way, I pray you not to be thrifty of your advice.” “'},
{'istart': 142, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'but I should like to have one look at your disposition.', 'context': ' said Pang Tong, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 402, 'talk': 'Wu Qi the Great General, came to life again, could not do better, nor Sun Zi the Famed Strategist if he reappeared! All accords with the precepts. The camp is beside the hills and is flanked by a forest. The front and rear are within sight of each other. Gates of egress and ingress are provided, and the roads of advance and retirement are bent and broken.', 'context': 'After looking all round Pang Tong remarked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Master, I entreat you not to overpraise me, but to advise me where I can make further improvements,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'Sir Prime Minister, if this is your method of warfare, you enjoy no empty reputation.', 'context': 'Pang Tong surveying all this smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Zhou Yu! Zhou Yu! You are finished; you will have to die.', 'context': 'Then pointing to the southern shore, he went on, “'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'Have you any capable medical people in your army?', 'context': 'By and bye the guest seemed to have succumbed to the influence of many cups and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What are they for, Master?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'There is a lot of illness among the marines, and you ought to find some remedy.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Your marine force is excellent, but there is just one defect; it is not quite perfect.', 'context': 'Pang Tong said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'I have a plan to overcome the ailment of the soldiers so that no one shall be sick and all fit for service.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'What is this excellent scheme?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'I could never defeat the land of the south without this scheme of yours.', 'context': 'Coming down from his seat, Cao Cao thanked his guest, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'That is my idea;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'it is for you to decide about it.', 'context': ' said Pang Tong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'Certainly if you could render me so great a service, I would memorialize the Throne and obtain for you one of the highest offices,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': "I am Heaven's means of doing right and could not bear to slay the people.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Where do they live?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'All are near the river bank.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'You should attack as soon as I have gone, but do not let Zhou Yu doubt anything.', 'context': 'who said, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'It would be a pity if you upset my plan; the fate of the people of all the eighty−one southern counties is in your hands.', 'context': 'Looking around and seeing no one near, Pang Tong said, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'And what of the fate of these eight hundred thirty thousand soldiers and horse of the north?', 'context': 'Xu Shu smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Do you intend to wreck my scheme, Xu Shu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 421, 'talk': "I have never forgotten the kindness of Uncle Liu Bei, nor my oath to avenge the death of my mother at Cao Cao's hands. I have said I would never think out a plan for him. So am I likely to wreck yours now, Brother? But I have followed Cao Cao's army thus far; and after they shall have been defeated, good and bad will suffer alike and how can I escape? Tell me how I can secure safety, and I sew up my lips and go away.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'If you are as high−minded as that, there is no great difficulty.', 'context': 'Pang Tong smiled, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Still I wish you would instruct me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'You have been kind enough to give me an office, Sir, and I have really done nothing in return. If I may have three thousand troops, I will march at once to San Pass and guard this entrance. If there be any pressing matter, I will report at once.', 'context': 'At this point Xu Shu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'If you would do this, I should be quite at my ease. There are already troops beyond the Pass, who will be under your command, and now I will give you three thousand of horse and foot, and Zang Ba shall lead the van and march quickly.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 552, 'talk': 'My one aim since I enlisted my first small band of volunteers has been the removal of evil from the state, and I have sworn to cleanse the country and restore tranquillity. Now there is only left this land of the south to withstand me. I am at the head of a hundred legions. I depend upon you, gentlemen, and have no doubt of my final success. After I have subdued the South Land, there will be no trouble in all the country. Then we shall enjoy wealth and honor and revel in peace.', 'context': "Cao Cao's heart was jubilant, and he harangued the assembly, saying, “"},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'We trust that you may soon report complete victory, and we shall all repose in the shade of your good fortune.', 'context': 'They rose in a body and expressed their appreciation, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, say nothing of these things lest they become known to the enemy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'You are all my trusty friends,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'both officers and humble attendants. Why should I refrain?', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Why does the raven thus cry in the night?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'The moon is so bright that it thinks it is day,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'and so it leaves its tree.', 'context': ' said they, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'When the great army is on the point of battle and lives are about to be risked, why do you, O Prime Minister, speak such ill words?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'What ill−omened words did I use?', 'context': 'When Liu Fu spoke, Cao Cao dropped his spear to the level and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'You spoke of the moon paling the stars and the raven flying southward without finding a resting place. These are ill−omened words.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'How dare you try to belittle my endeavor?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'If Heaven had not been on my side, should I have got this excellent plan from the Blooming−Phoenix? Now that the ships are attached firmly to each other, one may traverse the river as easily as walking on firm earth.', 'context': 'Then Cao Cao went to his tent and summoned his advisers. He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'The ships are firmly attached to each other,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'but you should be prepared for an attack by fire so that they can scatter to avoid it.', 'context': ' said Cheng Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'You look a long way ahead,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'but you see what cannot happen.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Cheng Yu speaks much to the point;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'why do you laugh at him?', 'context': ' said Xun You, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is indeed wise,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'None can equal him.', 'context': ' said the others in chorus. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'With northern troops unused to shipboard, I could never have crossed the river but for this chaining plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 255, 'talk': "We are from the north, but we are also sailors. Pray give us a small squadron, and we will seize some of the enemy's flags and drums for you that we may prove ourselves adepts on the water.", 'context': 'Then he saw two of the secondary leaders stand up and they said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'I do not think naval work would suit you two, born and brought up in the north,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 211, 'talk': "The southern soldiers are thoroughly accustomed to ships. You should not regard your lives as a child's plaything.", 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 226, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'If we fail, treat us according to army laws!', 'context': ' They cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'I will let you have the twenty ships and five hundred of good, vigorous troops with long spears and stiff crossbows. Early tomorrow the main fleet shall make a demonstration on the river, and I will also tell Wen Ping to support you with thirty ships.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'The masts of the northern ships stand thick as reeds; Cao Cao himself is full of wiles; how can we destroy him?', 'context': 'To his officers Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'That is a bad omen,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 218, 'iend': 345, 'talk': "What a pity our general should be taken ill when Cao Cao's legions threaten so terribly! What would happen if Cao Cao attacked?", 'context': 'In the last chapter Zhou Yu was seized with sudden illness as he watched the fleets of his enemy. He was borne to his tent, and his officers came in multitudes to inquire after him. They looked at each other, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'What do you make of it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Good luck for Cao Cao; bad for us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'I could cure him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'If you could, Wu would be very fortunate,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'How are you, General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'My heart pains me; every now and again I feel faint and dizzy.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Have you taken any remedies?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'My gorge rises at the thought; I could not.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Ask him to come in.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I have not seen you for days,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'How could I guess that you were unwell?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'How can any one feel secure? We are constantly the playthings of luck, good or bad.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'That is exactly how I feel.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'You need cooling medicine to dissipate this sense of oppression.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'I have taken a cooling draught, but it has done no good.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'You must get the humors into good order before the drugs will have any effect.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'What should be taken to produce a favorable temper?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'I know one means of producing a favorable temper,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I wish you would tell me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'That is the origin of your illness.', 'context': 'This he gave to the sick general, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I have no great talent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Never mind three whole days;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'one day of strong wind will serve my purpose. But it must be done at once and without delay.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I will sacrifice for a wind for three days from the twentieth day of the moon; will that suit you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 384, 'iend': 390, 'talk': 'houses', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang took his leave, went forth, and rode off with Lu Su to the mountains where they measured out the ground. He bade the soldiers build the altar of red earth from the southeast quarter. It was two hundred and forty spans in circuit, square in shape, and of three tiers, each of three spans, in all nine spans high. On the lowest tier he placed the flags of the twenty−eight “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Return to the camp and assist the General in setting out his forces. Should my prayers avail not, do not wonder.', 'context': 'He bade Lu Su retire, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'We have been cajoled,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang would not use vain and deceitful words,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'Each of you take a party of one hundred troops, one along the river, the other along the road, to the altar on the mountains. As soon as you get there, without asking questions or giving reasons, you are to seize and behead Zhuge Liang. Rich reward will be given when you bring his head back.', 'context': 'guard, Ding Feng and Xu Sheng, and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 199, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'He has just gone down.', 'context': 'Ding Feng first arrived. He saw the guards with their flags, dropped off his steed, and marched to the altar, sword in hand. But he found no Zhuge Liang. He asked the guards; they told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'The evening before a small, fast boat anchored there near a sand spit, and Zhuge Liang was seen to go on board. Then the boat went up river.', 'context': 'Ding Feng ran down the hill to search. There he met his fellow Xu Sheng, and they joined forces. Presently a simple soldier told them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 196, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'Do not flee, O Instructor of the Army! The General requests your presence.', 'context': "Xu Sheng bade his boatmen put on all sail and take every advantage of the wind. Before very long he saw the fugitive's boat ahead, and when near enough, stood in the prow of his own and shouted, “"},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'Return and tell the General to make good use of his soldiers. Tell him I am going up river for a spell and will see him again another day.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang, who was seated in the stern of his boat, just laughed aloud, saying, “'},
{'istart': 224, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'Pray wait a little while,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 268, 'iend': 312, 'talk': 'I have something most important to tell you.', 'context': ' cried Xu Sheng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'I knew all about it, that Zhou Yu would not let me go and that he wanted to kill me. That is why Zhao Yun was waiting for me. You would better not approach nearer.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 367, 'talk': 'You know who I am, and I came expressly to escort the Directing Instructor. Why are you pursuing him? One arrow would kill you, only that would cause a breach of the peace between two houses. I will shoot and just give you a specimen of my skill.', 'context': 'Then when he got too close, Zhao Yun fitted an arrow to the bowstring and, standing up in the stern of his boat, cried, “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I shall have no peace day or night while he lives,', 'context': "safety. Zhou Yu was indeed puzzled at the depth of his rival's insight. “"},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'At least wait till Cao Cao is done with,', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu. “'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 448, 'talk': "Take with you the false deserter Cai Zhong and his soldiers, and go along the south bank, showing the flags of Cao Cao, till you reach the Black Forest just opposite the enemy's main store of grain and forage. Then you are to penetrate as deeply as possible into the enemy's lines and light a torch as a signal. Cai He is to be kept in camp for another purpose.", 'context': 'Having summoned the leaders to receive orders, first Zhou Yu gave orders to Gan Ning: “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 286, 'talk': "Taishi Ci is to lead two thousand troops as quickly as possible to Huangzhou and cut the enemy's communications with Hefei. When near the enemy, he is to give a signal; and if he sees a red flag, he will know that our lord, Sun Quan, is at hand with reinforcements.", 'context': 'The next order was: “'},
{'istart': 217, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'The southeast wind had begun to blow, and that Zhao Yun had gone to meet Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'Liu Bei was at Xiakou anxiously awaiting the return of his adviser. Then appeared a fleet, led by Liu Qi, who had come to find out how matters were progressing. Liu Bei sent to call him to the battle tower and said, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'There is no time to tell of any other things now. Are the soldiers and ships ready?', 'context': "Liu Bei was very glad, and after they had inquired after each other's well−being, Zhuge Liang said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'They have long been ready,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'They only await you to direct how they are to be used.', 'context': ' replied Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 443, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun, with three thousand troops is to cross the river and go to the Black Forest by the minor road. He will choose a dense jungle and prepare an ambush. Tonight, after the fourth watch, Cao Cao will hurry along that way. When half his troops have passed, the jungle is to be fired. Cao Cao will not be wholly destroyed but many will perish.', 'context': 'The three then went to the tent and took their seats. Zhuge Liang at once began to issue orders: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'There are two roads,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'One leads to the southern regions and the other to Jingzhou. I do not know by which he will come.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'The south road is too dangerous; Cao Cao will certainly pass along the Jingzhou road, so that he may get away to Xuchang.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 316, 'talk': 'The country around Wuchang is very important, and I wish you to take command of your own troops and station them at strategic points. Cao Cao, being defeated, will flee thither, and you will capture him. But you are not to leave the city without the best of reasons.', 'context': 'The three left. Then Zhuge Liang said to Liu Qi, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'I wish you to remain quietly and calmly in Fankou, in a high tower, to watch Zhou Yu work out his great scheme this night.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Since I first followed my brother to battle many years ago, I have never been left behind. Now that great things are afoot, is there no work for me? What is meant by it?', 'context': 'When Guan Yu could bear this no longer, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'You should not be surprised. I wanted you for service at a most important point, only that there was a something standing in the way that prevented me from sending you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'What could stand in the way? I wish you would tell me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'You see Cao Cao was once very kind to you, and you cannot help feeling grateful. Now when his soldiers have been beaten, he will have to flee along the Huarong Road; and if I sent you to guard it, you would have to let him pass. So I will not send you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'You are most considerate, Instructor. But though it is true that he treated me well, yet I slew two of his most redoubtable opponents, Yan Liang and Wen Chou, by way of repayment, beside raising a siege. If I happened upon him on this occasion, I should hardly let him go.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'But what if you did?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'You could deal with me by military rules.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Then put that in writing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'What happens if Cao Cao does not pass that way?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I will give you a written engagement that he will pass.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'If Cao Cao sees a smoke, he will suspect an ambush and will not come.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'You are very simple,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 288, 'talk': "Do you not know more of war's ruses than that? Cao Cao is an able leader, but you can deceive him this time. When he sees the smoke, he will take it as a subterfuge and risk going that way. But do not let your kindness of heart rule your conduct.", 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'His sense of rectitude is very profound; I fear if Cao Cao should come that way, my brother will let him pass.', 'context': 'Said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'I have consulted the stars lately, and the rebel Cao Cao is not fated to come to his end yet. I have purposely designed this manifestation of kindly feeling for Guan Yu to accomplish and so act handsomely.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Indeed there are few such far−seeing humans as you are,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'The Winter Solstice depends upon the sun and nothing else; there is sure to be a southeast wind at some one or other of its recurrences. I see nothing to wonder at.', 'context': 'southeast wind was very strong that day, and Cheng Yu was insisting on the necessity for precaution. But Cao Cao laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 130, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'I have committed no crime.', 'context': 'In the South Land, when evening fell, Zhou Yu sent for Cai He and bade the soldiers bind him. The unhappy man protested, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'What sort of a fellow are you, think you, to come and pretend to desert to my side? I need a small sacrifice for my flag, and your head will serve my purpose. So I am going to use it.', 'context': 'But Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Two of your own side, Kan Ze and Gan Ning, are also in the plot!', 'context': 'Cai He being at the end of his tether unable to deny the charge suddenly cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Under my directions,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 189, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'Van Leader Huang Gai', 'context': 'This ceremony over, the ships started, and Huang Gai took his place on the third ship. He merely wore breast armor and carried a keen blade. On his flag were written four large characters “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'The whole south is one mass of sails, and they are coming up on the wind.', 'context': 'Then a soldier pointing to the river said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'That is my friend, the deserter,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Heaven is on my side today.', 'context': ' said he joyfully. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'How know you that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'I am well used to the waters.', 'context': 'Cao Cao began to understand. Then he asked who would go out to stop the approaching fleet, and Wen Ping volunteered, saying, “'},
{'istart': 205, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'You southern ships are not to approach; such are the orders of the Prime Minister. Stop there in mid stream!', 'context': 'Thereupon Wen Ping sprang into a small light craft and sailed out, followed by ten cruisers which came at his signal. Standing in the prow of his ship, Wen Ping called out to those advancing toward them, “'},
{'istart': 182, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'You rebel! Do not flee. I am Huang Gai.', 'context': 'Huang Gai, seeing a handsomely robed person get into a small boat, guessed it must be Cao Cao and pursued. He drew very near and he held his keen blade ready to strike, crying out, “'},
{'istart': 8, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Cao Cao, stop!', 'context': 'cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'That is my friend Huang Gai!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'The only suitable road is through the Black Forest.', 'context': 'Zhang Liao pointed out, saying, “'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Ling Tong is here!', 'context': 'Soon after Cao Cao saw the light of torches in front, and from a gorge there rushed out another force. And the leader cried, “'},
{'istart': 152, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'Fear not, O Prime Minister, I am here to rescue you!', 'context': 'Cao Cao was scared; his liver and gall both seemed torn from within. But just then on his half right, he saw another company approach and heard a cry, “'},
{'istart': 143, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'I am Gan Ning of Wu!', 'context': 'The two went forward, but before they had gone very far, they heard a shouting and a party of soldiers came out, the leader of them shouting, “'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'What is this place?', 'context': 'At the fifth watch he was a long way from the glare and he felt safer. He asked, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'It is west of the Black Forest and north of Yidu.', 'context': ' They told him, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Why are you, Sir, so merry?', 'context': 'Those about him asked, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'I am only laughing at the stupidity of Zhou Yu and the ignorance of Zhuge Liang. If they have only set an ambush there, as I would have done, why, there is no escape.', 'context': 'And he said, “'},
{'istart': 256, 'iend': 305, 'talk': 'I am Zhao Yun, and long have I been waiting here!', 'context': 'Cao Cao had scarcely finished his explanation when from both sides came a deafening roll of drums and flames sprang up to heaven. Cao Cao nearly fell off his horse—he was so startled. And from the side dashed in a troop, with Zhao Yun leading, who cried, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'What places lay ahead?', 'context': 'When giving the order to advance again, Cao Cao asked, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'There are two roads; one was the highway to South Yiling, and the other a mountain road to North Yiling.', 'context': 'They told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Which is the shorter way to Jiangling?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'The best way is to take the south road through Hulu Valley,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Not long since, Sir, you laughed at Zhou Yu and Zhuge Liang; that resulted in the arrival of Zhao Yun and great loss of troops to us. Why do you now laugh?', 'context': 'His companions, remembering the sequel of his last laugh, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 322, 'talk': 'I am laughing again at the ignorance of the same two men. If I were in their place, and conducting their campaign, I should have had an ambush here, just to meet us when we were tired out. Then, even if we escaped with our lives, we should suffer very severely. They did not see this, and therefore I am laughing at them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Whither would you flee, O rebel?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'There are two roads before us; which shall we take?', 'context': 'But many had received wounds. As they were going. the soldiers said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Which is the shorter?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Where smoke arises there are surely soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Why go this way?', 'context': ' remarked the officers. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, your conclusions are most admirable. None other can equal you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'What are you howling for?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'The number of your days is fixed by fate. Any one who howls shall be put to death.', 'context': ' cried Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'Press on to Jingzhou and there we shall find repose.', 'context': 'But he pressed on, and when the officers told him the horses were quite spent and must rest, he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What is there to laugh at?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'People say those two, Zhou Yu and Zhuge Liang, are able and crafty; I do not see it. They are a couple of incapables. If an ambush had been placed here, we should all be prisoners.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Now we have but one course;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'we must fight to the death.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'How can we?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Though the leaders are not scared, the horses are spent.', 'context': ' said the officers. “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'General, I trust you have enjoyed good health.', 'context': 'Cao Cao agreed to try. He rode out to the front, bowed low and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I had orders to await you, O Prime Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'and I have been expecting you these many days.', 'context': ' replied Guan Yu, bowing in return, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'You see before you Cao Cao, defeated and weak. I have reached a sad pass, and I trust you, O General, will not forget the kindness of former days.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 349, 'talk': 'Though indeed you were kind to me in those days, yet I slew your enemies for you and relieved the siege of Baima. As to the business of today, I cannot allow private feelings to outweigh public duty.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 278, 'talk': "Do you remember my six generals, slain at the five passes? The noble person values righteousness. You are well versed in the histories and must recall the action of Yu Gong, the archer, when he released his master Zi Zhuo, for he determined not to use Zi's teaching to kill Zi.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 420, 'iend': 443, 'talk': 'Break up the formation!', 'context': "Guan Yu was indeed a very mountain of goodness and could not forget the great kindness he had received at Cao Cao's hands, and the magnanimity Cao Cao had shown over the deeds at the five passes. He saw the desperate straits to which his benefactor was reduced, and tears were very near to the eyes of both. He could not press Cao Cao hard. He pulled at the bridle of his steed and turned away saying to his followers, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I thought I would never see you again,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, when you were in the cave of the tiger and trying to escape, you showed no sign of sorrow; now that you are safe in a city, where you have food and the horses have forage, where all you have to do is to prepare for revenge, suddenly you lose heart and grieve; why thus?', 'context': 'Wherefore they said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'I am thinking of my friend Guo Jia; had he been alive, he would not have let me suffer this loss.', 'context': 'Replied Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Alas for Guo Jia! I grieve for Guo Jia! I sorrow for Guo Jia!', 'context': 'He beat his breast and wept, saying “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 361, 'talk': 'I am going to the capital to prepare another army for revenge. You are to guard this region and, in case of necessity, I leave with you a sealed plan. You are only to open the cover when hard−pressed, and then you are to act as directed. The South Land will not dare to look this way.', 'context': 'The reproach shamed the advisers. Next day Cao Cao called Cao Ren and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Who is to guard Hefei and Xiangyang?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'Jingzhou is particularly your care, and Xiahou Dun is to hold Xiangyang. As Hefei is most important, I am sending Zhang Liao thither with good aids of Li Dian and Yue Jin. If you get into difficulties, send at once to tell me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Joy! O General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 180, 'talk': "You have done a deed that overtops the world. You have removed the empire's worst foe and ought to have been met at a distance and felicitated.", 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I hope it is not because we have omitted to welcome you on the road that you seem sad.', 'context': 'Guan Yu muttered inaudibly, and Zhuge Liang continued, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Why did you not tell us Guan Yu was coming?', 'context': 'Turning to those about him, Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'I am here to ask for death,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Surely Cao Cao came through the valley?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Yes; he came that way, and I could not help it; I let him go.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Then whom have you captured?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No one.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'We three pledged ourselves to live and die together. Although my brother Guan Yu has offended, I cannot bear to break our oath. I hope you will only record this against him and let him atone later for the fault by some specially meritorious service.', 'context': 'Guan Yu would have died there but for his elder brother, who said to Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'My lord sent me on this special mission to felicitate the General on his great virtue and offer some unworthy gifts.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu received him and, having saluted in proper form, Sun Qian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Where is Liu Bei?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'He is now encamped at Youkou, the mouth of River You.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Is Zhuge Liang there?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Both are there,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Then return quickly, and I will come in person to thank them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Because,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'How can you prevent them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'I will go myself and speak with them. If all goes well, then, let it be so; in case it does not, then I shall immediately settle up with Liu Bei without waiting for Nanjun to be taken.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'I should like to accompany you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Why has he come?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'He is not likely to come out of simple politeness. Surely he has come in connection with Nanjun.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'But if he brings an army, can we stand against it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'When he comes, you may reply thus and thus.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 159, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'Of course you are camped here with no other idea than to take Nanjun?', 'context': 'Presently Liu Bei raised his cup in felicitation on the recent victory gained by his guest. The banquet proceeded, and after a few more courses Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'We heard you were going to take the place and came to assist. Should you not take it, then we will occupy it.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'Well, if we do not take it then, Sir, you may have it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Here are witnesses to your words,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'I hope you will never repent what you have just said.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, naming Lu Su, Zhuge Liang, and those at table. “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'When the word of a noble person has gone forth, it is ended; he never regrets.', 'context': 'Lu Su stammered and seemed unwilling to be cited as one of the witnesses, but Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'This speech of yours, Sir, is very generous,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'The South Land shall try first; but if the place does not fall, there is no reason why my lord should not capture it.', 'context': ' interjected Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 483, 'talk': 'O Master, you bade me thus reply to Zhou Yu; but though I did so, I have turned it over and over in my mind without finding any reason in what I said. I am alone and weak, without a single foot of land to call my own. I desired to get possession of Nanjun that I might have, at least, a temporary shelter, yet I have said that Zhou Yu may attack it first, and if it falls to the South Land, how can I get possession?', 'context': 'As soon as they had left, Liu Bei turned to Zhuge Liang and said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'First I advised you to attack Jingzhou, but you would not listen; do you remember?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang laughed and replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'But it belonged to Liu Biao, and I could not bear to attack it then. Now it belongs to Cao Cao I might do so.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Do not be anxious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Let Zhou Yu go and attack it; some day, my lord, I shall make you sit in the high place thereof.', 'context': ' replied the adviser. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'But what design have you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'So and so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I can take it with a flick of my finger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 195, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'We will defend and not offer battle.', 'context': "On the other side Cao Ren ordered Cao Hong to guard Yiling, and so hold one corner of an ox−horn defense. When the news came that the South Land's force had crossed the River Han, Cao Ren said, “"},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 248, 'talk': 'To let the enemy approach the walls and not offer battle is timidity. Our troops, lately worsted, need heartening and must show their mettle. Let me have five hundred of veterans, and I will fight to a finish.', 'context': 'But General Niu Jin said impetuously, “'},
{'istart': 302, 'iend': 470, 'talk': 'General, do not be in too great hurry; let me go first and attack Yiling, the supporting angle of the ox−horn formation. After that the conquest of Nanjun will be easy.', 'context': 'So Cao Ren went back victor, while the unhappy Jiang Qin returned to report his failure. Zhou Yu was very angry and would have put to death his hapless subordinate but for the intervention of the other officers. Then Zhou Yu prepared for another attack where he himself would lead. But Gan Ning said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Let us hasten to his rescue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Our place is of the greatest importance,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'and I am afraid to leave it undefended lest Cao Ren should attack.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'But Gan Ning is one of our first leaders and must be rescued,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'I should like to go myself to his aid, but whom can I leave here in my place?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Leave Ling Tong here;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Are you willing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'If the ten−day period is not exceeded, I may be able to carry on for that time; I am unequal to more than that.', 'context': 'Ling Tong said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 325, 'talk': 'South of Yiling is a little−used road that may prove very useful in an attack on Nanjun. Let us send a party to fell trees and barricade this road so that horses cannot pass. In case of defeat, the defeated will take this road and will be compelled to abandon their horses, which we shall capture.', 'context': 'Lu Meng said to his chief, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 263, 'talk': 'The loss of Yiling has brought us to a dangerous pass; now it seems the time to open the guide−letter of the Prime Minister, and see what plans he arranged for our salvation in this peril.', 'context': 'During the night he called his officers to a council. Then said Cao Hong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'You but say what I think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Cao Ren must be prepared for a long march.', 'context': 'Thought Zhou Yu to himself, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'The missile had been poisoned, and the wound will require a long time to heal. You, General, must be kept quiet and especially free from any irritation, which will cause the wound to reopen.', 'context': 'The physician said, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'What mean the drums and the shouting?', 'context': 'Then Zhou Yu summoned the officers to his bedside and said, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'The soldiers are drilling,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Why do you deceive me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'And if you do not fight, what think you should be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Zhou Yu, you babe! I think your fate has met you. You dare not face my army.', 'context': 'At sight of the opponents, Cao Ren flourished his whip and began to hurl abuse at them, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Here I am, base churl; look at me!', 'context': 'The stream of insult never ceased. Presently Zhou Yu could stand it no longer. Riding out to the front he cried, “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'Let us all revile him!', 'context': "The whole Cao Ren's army were taken aback. But Cao Ren turned to those about him and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Do you feel better?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'It was a ruse of mine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'But what avails it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'The plan seems excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'The General is dead of his wound,', 'context': 'Soon from the tent there arose the sound of wailing as for the dead. The soldiers around took up the cry and said one to another, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 225, 'talk': 'Zhou Yu lost his temper, and that has caused his wound to reopen and brought on that flow of blood. You saw him fall to the ground, and he will assuredly die soon.', 'context': 'Meanwhile Cao Ren was consulting with his officers. Said he, “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 273, 'talk': "Zhou Yu's wound reopened at his anger, and he died in the camp that day. The leaders are all clothing in white and in mourning. We desert because we have been put to shame by the second in command.", 'context': 'Cao Ren sent for the deserters and questioned them. They told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Success depends upon promptitude, so act without delay,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'Pardon, General; I had orders from the Directing Instructor to take this city. I am Zhao Yun of Changshan.', 'context': 'Before they had recovered from their surprise, there appeared one who cried, “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'After Nanjun fell, Zhuge Liang, suddenly forging a military commission, induced the guards of Jingzhou to leave it and go to the rescue of Cao Ren. Whereupon Zhang Fei occupied the town.', 'context': 'But even as these orders were being given, the scouts came in hurriedly to report, saying, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 261, 'talk': 'Xiahou Dun, at Xiangyang, received from Zhuge Liang dispatches, supported by a commission in due form, saying that Cao Ren was in danger and needed help, whereupon Xiahou Dun marched off, and Guan Yu seized that city.', 'context': 'Soon after another messenger came, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'How did Zhuge Liang get this military commission with which he has imposed on the generals?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'He seized that of Chen Jiao and so has got all this region into his power.', 'context': 'Cheng Pu replied, “'},
{'istart': 303, 'iend': 465, 'talk': 'What but the death of that bumpkin Zhuge Liang will assuage my anger? If Cheng Pu can but aid me in an attack on Nanjun, I can certainly restore it to my country.', 'context': "Zhou Yu's anger at seeing that his rival, Zhuge Liang, had surprised Nanjun, and at hearing the same news of Jingzhou and Xiangyang, was but natural. And this sudden fit of rage caused his wound to reopen. However, he soon recovered. All his officers besought him to accept the situation, but he said, “"},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'I simply must fight Liu Bei and Zhuge Liang till it is decided which shall have the upper hand. I must also recapture the city. Perhaps you can assist me.', 'context': 'Soon Lu Su came in, to whom Zhou Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'It cannot be done,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 640, 'talk': 'We are now at grips with Cao Cao, and victory or defeat is undecided. Our lord has not been successful in overcoming Hefei. Do not fight near home, or it will be like people of the same household destroying each other; and should Cao Cao take advantage of this position to make a sudden descent, we should be in a parlous condition. Further, you must remember that Liu Bei and Cao Cao are united by the bonds of old friendship; if the pressure becomes too great, Liu Bei may relinquish these cities, offer them to Cao Cao, and join forces with him to attack our country. That would be a real misfortune.', 'context': ' replied Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I cannot help being angry', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'to think that we should have used our resources for their benefit. They get all the advantage.', 'context': ' said Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'Well, let me go and see Liu Bei and talk reason to him. If I can arrive at no understanding, then attack at once.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Excellent proposal!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'I have something to say to Liu Bei;', 'context': 'reached the city wall and summoned the gate, whereat Zhao Yun came out to speak with him. “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'I wish to see him.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'My lord and Zhuge Liang are in Jingzhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 720, 'talk': 'My master, Marquis Sun Quan, and the commander of his army, Zhou Yu, have sent me to lay before the Imperial Uncle their views. When Cao Cao led his huge host southward, he gave out that it was for the conquest of the South Land; really his intention was to destroy Liu Bei. Happily our army was able to repulse that mighty host and so saved him. Wherefore Jingzhou with its nine territories of forty−one counties ought to belong to us. But by a treacherous move, your master has occupied Jingzhou and Xiangyang, so that we have spent our treasure in vain and our armies have fought to no purpose. The Imperial Uncle has reaped the benefits to the full. This is not as it should be.', 'context': 'Having finished the tea, Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 375, 'talk': 'Lu Su, you are a man of high intelligence; why do you hold such language? You know the saying that all things turn to their owner. These places have never belonged to the South Land, but were of the patrimony of Liu Biao, and though he is dead, his son remains. Should not the uncle assist the nephew to recover his own? Could my master have refrained ?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'If the nephew Liu Qi, the rightful heir, had occupied these cities there would have been something to say. But he is at Jiangxia and not here.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Would you like to see him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'I am too weak to perform the correct ceremonies; I pray you pardon me, Lu Su.', 'context': 'Addressing Lu Su he said, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'But if the heir had not been here, what then?', 'context': 'Lu Su said not a word; he was too much taken aback. However, he recovered himself presently and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'The heir is living but from day to day; should he go, then—there will be something to talk about.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'Should he die, then you ought to return these cities to us.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'You state the exact facts,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': "But what is there for us in the chance of Liu Qi's death?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Rest content, General; let me guarantee the return of these places.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'But how can you?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 242, 'talk': "Liu Qi has indulged too freely in wine and women; he is a wreck and rotten to the core, miserably emaciated and panting for breath. I will not give him half a year's life. Then I will go to Liu Bei, and he will be unable to deny the request.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'Our lord is laying siege to Hefei but in several battles has had no victory. He now orders you to withdraw from here and go to Hefei to help him.', 'context': 'But Zhou Yu was still unmollified. Suddenly came a messenger from Sun Quan, who said, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'You wish for a plan to accomplish yet greater deeds; why not seek wise people and ask them?', 'context': 'When Yi Ji was seated, and his host had asked what he proposed, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Where are these wise people to be found?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 403, 'talk': "In this region there is a certain family named Ma, five brothers, all of whom are known as men of ability. The youngest is called Ma Su. The ablest is Ma Liang, who has white hairs in his eyebrows, and the villagers have a little rhyming couplet that means 'There are five sons in the family Ma, but white eyebrows is the best of them.' You should get this man to draw up a plan for you.", 'context': 'Yi Ji replied, “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 607, 'talk': 'Attacked as it is on all sides, this region is not one in which one is permanently secure. You should let Liu Qi remain here till he is recovered from his present illness; the actual protection of the place being left in the hands of trusty friends. Obtain an edict appointing him Imperial Protector of Jingzhou, and the people will be content. Then conquer Wuling, Changsha, Guiyang, and Lingling; and with the resources you will thus acquire, you will have the means for further plans. That should be your policy.', 'context': 'He was asked to suggest a plan for the security of the newly acquired region, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Which of the four territories should be first taken?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'The nearest, Lingling, which lies in the west of River Xiang. The next is Wuling, and after these the other two.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'Have no anxiety. They may have the known and famous warriors, Zhang Fei and Zhao Yun, but we have our leader, Xing Darong, who is match for any number of men. He can withstand them.', 'context': 'The son was very self−confident and said to his father, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Rebels, how comes it that you have dared to enter our territory?', 'context': 'In his hand he held a battle−ax called Cleaver of Mountains. In a mighty voice he cried, “'},
{'istart': 321, 'iend': 558, 'talk': 'I am Zhuge Liang of Nanyang, whose plans broke up the countless legions of Cao Cao so that nothing of them returned whence they started. How then can you hope to oppose me? I now offer you peace, and it will be well for you to surrender.', 'context': 'From the center of the opposing army, where appeared a cluster of yellow flags, there came out a small four−wheeled carriage in which sat, very erect, a certain man dressed in white, with a turban on his head. In one hand he held a feather fan, with which he signed to the warrior to approach. At the same time he said, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Their defeat was owing to the plan of Zhou Yu; you had nothing to do with it. How dare you try to deceive me?', 'context': 'Xing Darong laughed derisively, saying, “'},
{'istart': 163, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'Do you know me? I am Zhao Yun of Changshan.', 'context': 'Then the ambushing troops appeared. Xing Darong, nothing daunted, rushed into their midst. But in front appeared another warrior barring the way, who called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'We will accept your submission if you capture Liu Xian for us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 127, 'iend': 377, 'talk': 'If you will set me free, I shall be cunning of speech. If you raid the camp this evening, you will find me your helper on the inside. I will make Liu Xian a prisoner and will hand him over to you. He being captured, his father will surrender at once.', 'context': 'The captive accepted the offer without the least hesitation, and when Zhuge Liang asked how he intended to do it, he replied, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Xing Darong is not deceiving.', 'context': 'Liu Bei doubted the good faith of the man, but Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'What can we do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 224, 'talk': "Do not enter the burning camp, but to go to attack Zhuge Liang's stockade.", 'context': 'It was still burning for no one had extinguished the flames. Soon from behind them came out Zhang Fei. Liu Xian called out to his companion, saying, “'},
{'istart': 355, 'iend': 419, 'talk': "The ruse was Xing Darong's evil counsel; I was forced to follow.", 'context': 'Thereupon they turned again, but at a distance of three miles Zhao Yun and an army suddenly debouched upon their road. Zhao Yun attacked and slew Xing Darong by a spear thrust. Liu Xian turned to flee, but Zhang Fei was close upon him and made him prisoner. He was thrown across a horse, bound, and taken to camp. When he saw Zhuge Liang, Liu Xian said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'And if he does not, the city shall be destroyed and every one put to death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Undoubtedly Zhao Yun was first to volunteer, wherefore he is to go.', 'context': 'Then said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'I would not have wanted any helpers: just three thousand soldiers and I would have done it.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei was still very angry and grumbled, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I also only want three thousand soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'And if I fail, I am willing to suffer the penalties.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Flying Fork,', 'context': 'These two warriors belonged to Guiyang and had made themselves famous as hunters. Chen Ying used a “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'We will lead the way against Liu Bei.', 'context': 'They stood before Zhao Fan and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Let me go out to fight,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'If I cannot capture Zhao Yun, then you can yield.', 'context': ' said Chen Ying. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'We are supporters of the Prime Minister Cao Cao and are no followers of your master,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I thought you would not dare a combat with me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'However, I am not going to put you to death. You are free. But persuade your master to yield.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun to the prisoner when they had returned to camp. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'My original desire was to yield, but you insisted on fighting, and this is what it has brought you to.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 314, 'talk': 'General, your surname is the same as mine, and five centuries ago we were one family. You are from Changshan, and so am I. Moreover we are from the same village. If you do not mind, we might swear brotherhood. I should be very happy.', 'context': 'After the wine had gone round several times, Zhao Fan became talkative, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'Who is she?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'My sister−in−law; she is of the Fan family.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Why did you trouble your sister−in−law to present wine to me, Brother?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'There is a reason,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 872, 'talk': "I pray you let me tell you. My brother died three years ago and left her a widow. But this cannot be regarded as the end of the story. I have often advised her to marry again, but she said she would only do so if three conditions were satisfied in one man's person. The suitor must be famous for literary grace and warlike exploits, secondly, handsome and highly esteemed and, thirdly, of the same name as our own. Now where in all the world was such a combination likely to be found? Yet here are you, Brother, dignified, handsome, and prepossessing, a man whose name is known all over the wide world and of the desired name. You exactly fulfill my sister's ambitions. If you do not find her too plain, I should like her to marry you and I will provide a dowry. What think you of such an alliance, such a bond of relationship?", 'context': ' said the host smiling. “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'As I have just sworn brotherhood with you, is not your sister−in−law my sister−in−law? How could you think of bringing such confusion into the relationship?', 'context': 'But Zhao Yun rose in anger, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'I only thought of being kind to you; why are you so very rude to me?', 'context': "Shame suffused Zhao Fan's face, and he said, “"},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'He has gone away in a rage, which means that we shall have to fight him.', 'context': 'Chen Ying said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I greatly fear you will lose,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'We will pretend to be deserters,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'We shall have to take some others with us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Five hundred troops will be ample,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Those who wanted to harm me are your leaders and not you. If you do as I tell you, you shall be well rewarded.', 'context': 'Then he gave the soldiers wine and said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'But this seems a fine project; why did you receive the proposal so roughly?', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang to Zhao Yun, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 484, 'talk': 'Zhao Fan and I had just sworn brotherhood, and so marriage with his sister−in−law would have called down on my head universal blame. That is one reason. Another is that I should have made his sister fail to keep her dutiful chastity. And thirdly, I did not know whether I might trust such a proposal from one who had just yielded to force. My lord, your position as a recent victor was one of danger, and could I risk the failure of your plans for the sake of a woman?', 'context': 'Zhao Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'But now that the plan has been carried out, and we are victors, would you care to marry her?', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'There are other women in the world. All my fear is for the building of a reputation. What is a family to me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'You are indeed right honorable,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'So Zhao Yun gets all the praise, and I am worth nothing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'There is no reason why you should not go, but I will only require one condition of you.', 'context': 'and I will take Wuling and bring you the Governor.” This pleased Zhuge Liang, who said, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'When Zhao Yun went on his expedition, he gave written guarantee of being responsible for success, and you ought to do the same now that you are starting for Wuling. In that case you may have men and start.', 'context': 'What Zhuge Liang required from Zhang Fei was a formal recognition of responsibility for success. Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 370, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is of the Hans, and recognized as an uncle of the Emperor. All the world knows he is kindly and righteous. Added to that his brother Zhang Fei is extraordinarily bold. We cannot face them in battle with hope of success. Our best course is to give in.', 'context': 'A certain secretary, Gong Zhi, remonstrated with his chief for opposing a scion of the imperial house, saying, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Do you want to play the traitor and take the side of the rebels and help them?', 'context': 'But his master angrily replied, “'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'It augers ill to start an expedition by slaying your own officer.', 'context': 'Jin Xuan called in the lictors and told them to put Gong Zhi to death. The other officers interceded for Gong Zhi, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'You brought defeat upon yourself because you opposed the will of God,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'I and the people with me are determined to yield to Liu Bei.', 'context': ' cried the traitor. “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Changsha is yet to be taken; and if I am not thought too feeble, I would like to be sent to attack it.', 'context': 'Guan Yu at once wrote back and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 371, 'talk': "Huang Zhong is a native of Nanyang. He used to be in the service of Liu Biao and was a colleague Liu Biao's nephew, Liu Pan, when he was in command of Changsha. After Liu Biao's death, he joined Han Xuan when he took command of the city. Now, although he is nearly sixty, he is a man to be feared and a warrior of a thousand. You ought to take a larger number of troops.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'The horse is too old,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 351, 'talk': "Instructor, what makes you damp another man's ardor to fight and do away with your own dignity? I do not think the old leader need be discussed, and I do not think I require three companies of soldiers. Give me my own five hundred of swordsmen, and I will have the heads of both Han Xuan and Huang Zhong to sacrifice to our standard.", 'context': 'Guan Yu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'If he is not careful how he attacks Huang Zhong, there will be a mishap,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'You must go to support him.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Do not be distressed; this sword of mine and my bow are equal to the slaughter of all who may come.', 'context': 'The latter said, “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'Let not the veteran General go out to battle. Trust to my right arm, and you shall have this Guan Yu a prisoner in your hands.', 'context': 'When Huang Zhong referred to his prowess, a certain man spoke up and said, “'},
{'istart': 288, 'iend': 327, 'talk': 'He who comes is surely Huang Zhong, eh?', 'context': 'Huang Zhong took his sword and crossed the drawbridge of Changsha at the head of his force. Guan Yu, seeing an old leader riding out, knew it must be Huang Zhong. Guan Yu halted his troops and placed them in line with their swords at the point. Then sitting there on horseback, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Since you know me, how dare you come within my boundaries?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'I have come expressly to get your head!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 212, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'swinging−horse stab', 'context': 'Guan Yu thought in his heart that the fame of the veteran opposed to him was well merited. He had fought a hundred bouts and discovered never a weak spot. He determined that in the next encounter he would use a “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'I spare your life, but quick! Get another horse and come again to battle.', 'context': 'Guan Yu turned, raised his sword in both hands, and cried in a fierce tone, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Why did you not shoot since your aim is so perfect?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I will try again tomorrow,', 'context': '“'},
