{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Then what further can I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'I want to see your authority and virtue spread over the four seas and enfold the nine regions, and you yourself playing your part as emperor. Then will my name be inscribed in the annals, and I shall indeed be known.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'This Zhang Liao has insulted me grossly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'He hears that Cheng Pu has arrived and sends a challenge. Tomorrow, O newly−come warriors, you shall see me fight with him. You shall have no share in the battle.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'He there opposite us with the golden helm is Sun Quan; could we but capture him, the loss of our eight hundred thirty thousand soldiers at the Red Cliffs would be amply avenged.', 'context': 'Then said Li Dian to Yue Jin, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 734, 'talk': 'My lord, you relied too much upon your martial prowess and lightly engaged in battle with a formidable enemy. Every person in the army was chilled with fear, and you lost a general and some of your banners. It is not for you to exhibit prowess on the actual battlefield and encroach upon the duties of a general. Rather curb and repress such physical feats as those ancient Xia Yu and Meng Ben, and contemplate schemes of exercising princely virtues with the hegemony of all the feudal states. It is because of your ill−regulated action in engaging in battle that Song Qian perished at the hands of your enemies. Hereafter you should regard as most important your personal safety.', 'context': 'But Zhang Hong, the adviser, reproached him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Yes; it is indeed a fault,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I will reform.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 360, 'iend': 377, 'talk': 'Where is Ge Ding?', 'context': 'groom in the army of Zhang Liao. This servant is deeply resentful on account of a punishment inflicted upon him and is anxious to be revenged. He has sent over to say that he will show a signal tonight when he has assassinated Zhang Liao in revenge for the death of your late leader Song Qian. I wish to take some troops over to await this signal to attack.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Ge Ding has mingled with the enemy and gone into the city. Let me have five thousand soldiers.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'Taishi Ci will come over tonight to help us; what need to be done now?', 'context': 'made his way into the city without detection, found his brother, and the two had arranged their plot. Ge Ding also told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 269, 'talk': 'As the troops of Sun Quan are far away, I fear they cannot be here tonight, so we will make a huge bonfire of straw and then you can rush out and cry treachery. That will throw all into confusion and will give a chance to kill Zhang Liao.', 'context': 'His brother, the groom, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'This is an excellent plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 169, 'iend': 282, 'talk': 'You have gained a great victory today, and the enemy are far away. You might doff your armor and get some repose.', 'context': 'Now after the victory, Zhang Liao returned to the city and rewarded his soldiers, but he issued orders that no one was to doff his armor or sleep. His attendants said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'That is not the way of a leader. A victory is no reason for rejoicing, nor should a defeat cause sadness. If those of the South Land suspect that I am unprepared, they will attack; and we must be ready to repel them. Be ready tonight and be doubly careful.', 'context': 'But Zhang Liao replied, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Treachery!', 'context': 'Scarcely had he said this than a fire started and cries of “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'The shouts are insistent; you ought to go and see what it means.', 'context': 'Those about him said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'A whole city cannot be traitors,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Some discontented person has frightened the soldiers. If I see any one doing so, I will slay him.', 'context': ' said Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'That means the troops of South Land are there to help,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'But we will destroy them by a simple ruse.', 'context': ' said Zhang Liao. “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Treachery! Rebellion!', 'context': 'He bade them light torches and yell “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'When a worthy person is born into a turbulent world, he has to be a soldier and gird on a three−span sword to step on the mountains to mend the sky. I have not rendered great service. Why must I die before I have attained my desire?', 'context': 'When his lord went to ask how he fared, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I was studying the sky and saw a falling star in the northwest. The imperial family is to suffer a loss.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 282, 'talk': 'Life and death are beyond our control, wherefore weep not, my lord, for grief harms the body. Rather consider what is necessary to be done. Send some one to assume control and make arrangements for the interment.', 'context': 'Liu Bei at once began to wail bitterly. But his adviser said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'Who can go?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'No other than Guan Yu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'I will have somewhat to say to any one who comes to ask fulfillment of the promise.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 156, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'Hearing of the death of your nephew, my lord Sun Quan has prepared some gifts and sent me to take his place at the funeral sacrifices. General Zhou Yu also sends regards to the Imperial Uncle and to you, Master Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'Liu Bei and Zhuge Liang went out of the city to welcome the envoy of the South Land and led him to the guest−house. After the usual greetings, Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'You said, Sir, that Jingzhou should be returned to us after the death of Liu Qi. Now that that event has happened, rendition becomes due, and I should be glad to know when the transfer can take place.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'We will discuss that later; in the meantime let us go on with our wine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 1249, 'talk': 'What is your master? The son of a petty official on the banks of the River Qiantang, absolutely without merit so far as the state is concerned. Just because he is powerful, he holds actual possession of six territories and eighty−one counties, which has whetted his insatiable appetite till he now desires to swallow the whole empire. The land is the estate of the Liu family and my lord, who is of that name, has no share thereof, while your master, whose name is Sun, would dispute with, and even fight him. Beside, at the battle at the Red Cliffs my lord did good service and acquired great merit while his commanders risked their lives. Was it solely the strength of your southern soldiers that won that fight? Had I not brought that southeast wind that meant so much for Zhou Yu, could he have done anything? Had the South Land been conquered, it is needless to say that the two paramount beauties would now be gracing the Bronze Bird Palace, and as for yourself and other officers, insignificant though your families be, could you have been sure to survive? Just now my lord did not reply because he was willing to believe rather that a scholar of your abilities would understand without a detailed explanation, and I trust now that you will.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'What you say, Zhuge Liang, I think is devoid of reason, and means much unpleasantness for me.', 'context': "This speech absolutely shut the guest's mouth for a time, and he said no word in reply. But after an interval he said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'What unpleasantness?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 663, 'talk': 'When Liu Bei was in serious straits at Dangyang, I conducted you across the river and introduced you to my lord. I opposed Zhou Yu when he was going to capture Jingzhou, and then it came to agreement that the place was to be ours when the young man died. And I pledged myself to that. Now how can I go back and say you break your promise? Both my lord and Zhou Yu will hold me guilty. I would not mind death so much, but I fear that my master will be very wrathful and make war on the Imperial Uncle, who will have no place of refuge and he will look ridiculous in the eyes of the world for no reason.', 'context': ' asked Zhuge Liang. The guest replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 499, 'talk': 'I care not for Cao Cao with his million troops and the Emperor in name at his back, and do you think I fear such a youngster as Zhou Yu? However, as it may cause you some loss of consideration, I will try to persuade my master to put the matter in writing and give you a paper to the effect that he is temporarily occupying Jingzhou as a base; and when he can obtain possession of some other city, this shall be returned to you. What think you the South Land would say to this?', 'context': 'Replied Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Wait till what other place was obtained?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 123, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'I know that your master is perfectly honorable and will adhere to the bargain.', 'context': 'trouble you, Lu Su, also to sign. It will look better when you reach the South Land again,” said Zhuge Liang. Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Here is the document,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'You have been victimized by Zhuge Liang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'I think Liu Bei will be true to me.', 'context': 'Lu Su was dumbfounded. When he had somewhat recovered his self−possession, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'You, my friend, are simple and sincere; Liu Bei is a scoundrel adventurer; and Zhuge Liang is a slippery customer. They and you are utterly different.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 154, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'What then is to be done?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'You are my dear friend, and your kindness in freely offering your store of grain to relieve my army is still fresh in my memory. Of course I will save you. Do not be anxious, but wait a few days till we get news of what is doing on the north of the river, and then we can decide upon a plan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'My scheme is made. You will see Liu Bei just stand still to be bound, and we shall get Jingzhou like turning a hand.', 'context': 'When Zhou Yu knew who was dead, he said to Lu Su, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'What is the main spring of your plan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'What is the use of such nonsense as this?', 'context': 'After the lending of Jingzhou had been discussed, Lu Su presented the document given him by Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'I have it; Lu Fan is the man to send.', 'context': 'send. Suddenly he cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': "One of Zhou Yu's devices,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'and it is all on account of this region. I will just retire behind the screen and listen. But you, my lord, agree to whatever the messenger proposes. Then let the messenger be taken to the guest−house while we arrange what is to be done.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang smiling, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'You must have some commands for me, Sir, since you come thus.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': "To lose one's wife in middle age is truly a great misfortune,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'While her body is still warm, I cannot listen to proposals for another marriage.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 716, 'talk': "A man without a wife is like a house without a ridge pole. At your age, one should not live an incomplete life. I am come on the part of Marquis Sun Quan, who has a sister, beautiful as she is, accomplished and well fitted to be a mate for you. Should the two families become allied as formerly were Qin and Jin, then that ruffian Cao Cao would never dare so much as look this way. Such an alliance would be to the benefit of both our houses and of the state. I hope, O Imperial Uncle, that you will fairly consider the proposal. However, since the young girl's mother is dotingly fond of her, the mother does not wish her to go far away, and so I must ask you to come into our country for the wedding.", 'context': 'Lu Fan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Does the Marquis know of your coming?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'How dare I come without his knowledge?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'I am no longer young,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Sir, stay here awhile and I will give you a reply tomorrow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I knew what he had come about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 329, 'talk': 'While he was talking, I consulted the oracle and obtained an excellent sign. Wherefore you may accept the proposal and send Sun Qian back with this envoy to arrange the details. When the promise has been ratified, we will choose a day and you shall go to complete the ceremony.', 'context': ' said the adviser. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'How can I thus go into enemy territory? Zhou Yu has wanted to slay me for a long time.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'I wish my sister could induce Liu Bei to live here with us. He would come to no harm.', 'context': 'instructions, and traveled thither with Lu Fan. At the interview Sun Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 167, 'talk': "Sun Quan's sole desire is for our lord to go over and complete the marriage.", 'context': 'Sun Qian took his leave; and returning to Jingzhou, he told the bridegroom elect, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'I have prepared three plans, but I need Zhao Yun to carry them out. He will be sent as your guard.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'What happy event?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'The betrothal of your beloved daughter to Liu Bei. And he has arrived too, as surely you know.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'My poor old self does not know;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'I have heard nothing of all this.', 'context': ' said the Dowager, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 364, 'talk': 'The whole city know of the coming wedding, and the bridegroom is now at the guest−house. Moreover, he has come with a large escort, and they are spending freely, buying pork and mutton and fruits, all in readiness for the wedding feasting. Lu Fan and Sun Qian are the intermediaries on each side, and they are in the guest−house too.', 'context': 'They quickly returned to say: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'What has disturbed you, Mother?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'What you have just done,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'You have treated me as a nonentity. When my elder sister lay dying, what did she tell you?', 'context': ' said she. “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'Please speak out plainly, Mother; what is this great sorrow?', 'context': 'Sun Quan began to be frightened, but he said boldly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'When a son is grown he takes a wife, and when a girl is old enough she goes to her husband. And that is right and proper. But I am the mother, and you ought to have told me that your sister was to become the wife of Liu Bei. Why did you keep me in the dark? It was my place to promise her in marriage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Whence comes this story?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Do you pretend ignorance? There is not a soul in the city who does not know! But you have succeeded in keeping me in the dark.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I heard it several days ago,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'And I came just now to offer my felicitations.', 'context': ' said the State Patriarch Qiao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'There is no such thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 322, 'talk': 'It is just one of the ruses of Zhou Yu to get hold of Jingzhou. He has used this means to inveigle Liu Bei here and hold him captive till Jingzhou is restored to us. And if they will not give it back, then Liu Bei will be put to death. That is the plot. There is no real marriage.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 11, 'iend': 416, 'talk': "Zhou Yu is a pretty sort of governor over the six territories and eighty−one counties if he cannot find any means of recovering one region except making use of my child as a decoy. Truly this is a fine deed, to spoil the whole of my child's life and condemn her to perpetual widowhood, because he wants to use the fair damsel ruse to slay a man! Who will ever come to talk of marriage with her after this?", 'context': 'She said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I am afraid their ages do not match,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is a very famous man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'There can be no shame in having such a son−in−law.', 'context': ' said the State Patriarch Qiao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I have never seen him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'Arrange that I may get a look at him tomorrow at the Sweet Dew Temple. If he displeases me, you may work your will on him. But if I am satisfied with him, then I shall simply let the girl marry him.', 'context': ' said the Dowager. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Why not order Jia Hua to station some men in the wings of the temple? Then if the Dowager be not pleased, we can call them out and fall upon him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Tomorrow the Marquis and the Dowager Marchioness wished to see you. So be careful!', 'context': 'When the State Patriarch Qiao took his leave and had reached his house, he sent to tell Liu Bei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'The morrow bodes rather ill than well. However, your escort shall be there.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Just the son−in−law for me!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'He has the air of an emperor and a look like the sun,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'This is Zhao Yun of Changshan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Then he must be the hero of Dangyang, who saved the little Liu Shan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Yes; this is he,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'A fine general!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'I have seen a lot of armed ruffians hidden away in the purlieus of the temple. They can be there for no good, and you should ask the Dowager to get them sent away.', 'context': 'Presently Zhao Yun said to his master, “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'If you would slay me, let it be here.', 'context': 'Thereupon Liu Bei knelt at the feet of the Dowager and, weeping, said, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Why do you say this?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Because there are assassins in hiding in the wings of the temple; what are they there for if not to kill me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'What are armed men doing there today when Liu Bei is to become my son−in−law and the pair are my son and daughter?', 'context': 'The Dowager wrathfully turned on Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 114, 'talk': "The general's death will do me harm and make it hard for me to stay at your side.", 'context': 'But Liu Bei interceded, saying, “'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 376, 'talk': 'If I am to return to Jingzhou and achieve my intent to become a chief ruler, then may I cleave this boulder asunder with my sword; but if I am to meet my doom in this place, then may the sword fail to cut this stone.', 'context': 'By and bye, strolling out of the banquet room into the temple grounds, Liu Bei came to a boulder. Drawing his sword he looked up to heaven and prayed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Why do you thus hate that stone?', 'context': 'It happened that Sun Quan had seen the blow, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'That is only to blind me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'And I also ask of Heaven an omen, that if I am to destroy Cao Cao, I may also cut this rock.', 'context': ' thought Sun Quan. Drawing his own sword, he said, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'If I am to recover Jingzhou and extend my borders, may the stone be cut in twain.', 'context': 'So he spoke. But in his secret heart he prayed, “'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'I pray you excuse me as my drinking powers are very small.', 'context': 'Both put up their swords and returned hand in hand to the banquet hall. After some more courses, Sun Qian gave his master a warning look, and Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 174, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'Really this is the finest scene in the whole world! 1', 'context': 'Wherefore Sun Quan escorted him to the gate. As they walked down looking at high land and rolling river spreading in glorious panorama before their eyes, Liu Bei exclaimed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'The northern people are riders and the southern people sailors; it is said quite true,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'So the southerners cannot ride, eh?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Slope Where the Horses Stood,', 'context': 'Thence forward that hillside was known as the “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'It should be fixed as early as possible so that no further complications could arise.', 'context': 'Sun Qian advised, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Do not be anxious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Who would dare harm my son−in−law?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 305, 'talk': 'Do not be frightened, O Honorable One. My lady has always had a taste for warlike things, and her maids have all been taught fencing as a pastime. That is all it is.', 'context': 'The bridegroom turned pale: bridal apartments lined with weapons of war and waiting maids armed! But the housekeeper of the princess said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Not the sort of thing a wife should ever look at,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'It makes me feel cold and you may have them removed for a time.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'The weapons in your chamber displease the handsome one; may we remove them?', 'context': 'The housekeeper went to her mistress and said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Afraid of a few weapons after half a life time spent in slaughter!', 'context': 'Lady Sun laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 518, 'talk': 'My idea is identical with his. Liu Bei began life in a humble position and for years has been a wanderer. He has never tasted the delights of wealth. Give him the means of luxury, a beautiful dwelling, fair women, gold and silken attire; and as he enjoys them, the thoughts of Zhuge Liang and his brothers will fade away and they, on their side, will be filled with rancor. Thus can we lay our plans for recovering Jingzhou. I recommend action as Zhou Yu says and quickly.', 'context': 'The letter was shown to Zhang Zhao who said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun has some important matter on which to see the master.', 'context': 'The maid in attendance went within and said, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'My lord, you are living happily secluded in these beautiful apartments; do you never think of Jingzhou?', 'context': 'Liu Bei called him in and asked what the business was. Zhao Yun assumed an attitude of great concern and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'But what is the matter that you seem so disturbed?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 219, 'talk': 'Today early Zhuge Liang sent a messenger to say that Cao Cao was trying to avenge his last defeat and was leading five hundred thousand troops to attack Jingzhou, which was in great danger. And he wished you to return.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I must speak to my wife,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'If you consult her, she will be unwilling for you to return. It would be better to say nothing but to start this evening. Delay may do great damage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Retire for a time; I must act discreetly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Do not try to deceive me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'I heard and I know all. Just now Zhao Yun came to tell you Jingzhou was threatened and you wish to return home. That is why you put forward this excuse.', 'context': ' said Lady Sun. “'},
{'istart': 240, 'iend': 453, 'talk': 'Why should I dissemble, O Wife, since you know? I do not wish to go, but if Jingzhou be lost, I shall be an object of ridicule to everyone. I do desire to go, but I cannot leave you. Now you know why I am grieved.', 'context': ' Then Liu Bei fell on his knees and said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'I am your handmaid, and whithersoever you go, it is my duty to follow.', 'context': 'She replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Yes; your heart is right, but the difficulty is your mother and the Marquis; they will be unwilling. If you would have pity on me and let me go for a time——', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Do not be so sad, my husband,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'I will implore my mother to let us go, and she will surely allow it.', 'context': ' said Lady Sun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Even supposing the Dowager permits, I am sure the Marquis will hinder.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I should be never so grateful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'A very filial proceeding,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 207, 'talk': "I should not think of stopping you. Although you have never known your husband's parents, yet you may go with him to sacrifice as it is proper for a wife to do.", 'context': ' said the Dowager. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'They have got away today, but trouble will surely come of it; therefore, pursue after them without loss of time.', 'context': 'Zhang Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'My lord, your wrath is in vain, for I do not think your generals will catch the runaways.', 'context': 'Said Cheng Pu, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Will they dare to disobey my order?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 142, 'iend': 260, 'talk': 'You two take this sword and bring back the heads of my sister and Liu Bei. And if you do not, I will put you to death.', 'context': "Sun Quan's wrath burned the more fiercely at these words. He drew the sword girded at his side and called up Jiang Qin and Zhou Tai, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'What shall we do if they come up with us?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'My lord, you go on in front and I will prevent pursuit.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Liu Bei, dismount and yield yourself captive. We are here by order of Commander Zhou Yu, and you have kept us waiting long.', 'context': 'were there and they bellowed, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'In front a force barring the road; in rear pursuers. There is no escape. What can we do?', 'context': 'Greatly fearing, Liu Bei rode back to consult Zhao Yun, to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 301, 'talk': 'Do not be alarmed, my lord. The Directing Instructor gave me three plans enclosed in three silken bags. Two have been used and have answered admirably. There is yet the third, and my orders were to open the bag in such a strait as this. This is a day of great danger such as calls me to open the bag.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 165, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'I have something private to say, and I must tell you.', 'context': "Thereupon Zhao Yun opened the bag and handed it to Liu Bei. As soon as Liu Bei had seen the contents, he hastened to Lady Sun's carriage and began to weep, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'What have you to tell me, my husband? Tell me the whole truth,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 734, 'talk': "Your brother and Zhou Yu formerly made a plot for you to marry me, not for your sake, but to get me into their power and hold me so that they might recover Jingzhou. They were set on my murder, and you were the bait with which to hook me. Careless of consequences I came, for I knew that the spirit of a heroine dwelt in your bosom and you would pity me. Lately I heard that harm was intended me, and so I made danger to Jingzhou the excuse to escape. Happily for me you have remained true and come with me. But now the Marquis is pursuing us, and Zhou Yu's soldiers are in front. Only you, my wife, can extricate us from this danger; and if you refuse, then slay me where I stand that I may thus show my gratitude for your kindness.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'Then does my brother forget that I am his sister? How will he ever look me in the face? I can extricate us from this danger.', 'context': 'Lady Sun grew angry and said, “'},
{'istart': 6, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Xu Sheng, Ding Feng, are you turned traitors then?', 'context': 'out, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'We are no traitors,', 'context': 'The two generals slid out of their saddles, dropped their arms, and stood meekly in front of the carriage. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Zhou Yu is an interfering scoundrel,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': "We pray you, O Lady, stay your anger. This is no plan of ours; we do but obey our General's orders.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'So you fear Zhou Yu and not me!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'You were wrong to let them pass,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'They are again pursuing us; what now?', 'context': 'said to his wife, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Husband, go on in front. Zhao Yun and I will keep them off.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 236, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'What are you doing here, Generals?', 'context': "So Liu Bei and a small company went on toward the river bank, while Zhao Yun reined up beside the lady's carriage and set out his troops ready for battle. And when the four generals came up, they dismounted and stood with folded arms. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'We have orders from our lord to request you and Liu Bei to return.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 416, 'talk': "Say what one will, after all they two are brother and sister and the Dowager Marchioness is the controlling power. Sun Quan is most obedient and would never dare oppose his mother's decision. When the reaction comes, then indeed we shall certainly be found in the wrong. We would better be kind.", 'context': 'She abused the four men to their faces so that they looked from one to another in shame. And each in his heart thought, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'We four will go to see the Commander−in−Chief and report,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Have you fellows seen Liu Bei ?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'He has just passed along.', 'context': ' they cried as they rushed up. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Why did you not arrest him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Because of what Lady Sun said.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'That is just as the Marquis feared, and so he gave us this sword and told us first to slay his sister and then Liu Bei. And if we disobey, he will put us to death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'What can be done? They are far away by now.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 185, 'talk': "My lord, you have just escaped from the tiger's jaws and had not far to go. Moreover, I suspect Zhuge Liang has something prepared for us.", 'context': 'Zhao Yun bade him be of good courage, saying, “'},
{'istart': 283, 'iend': 400, 'talk': 'We have fled before them now for days, worn out our soldiers and jaded our horses, and all to die in a strange place.', 'context': 'Liu Bei bade Zhao Yun go along the bank to seek some boats. Then the soldiers told him there was a huge cloud of dust on the road. Ascending one of the hills, he looked back whence they had come and saw the whole earth as it were covered with an advancing host. He sighed and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'By good luck here are some ships,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Let us get on board, row to the further bank, and see what can be done.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 194, 'iend': 256, 'talk': 'My lord, again you see Zhuge Liang. He has waited a long time.', 'context': 'Liu Bei and his bride hastened down the bank and went into a ship. The soldiers were embarked. Then they saw in the hold of the ship some one in Taoist dress, who came up with a smile, saying, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 210, 'talk': "I foresaw this a long time ago. You may return and tell Zhou Yu not to use the 'Fair Damsel Trick' again.", 'context': 'Before long the four pursuer leaders reached the bank. Zhuge Liang pointed to them and laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'My schemes are a failure and a defeat, and how can I face my master again?', 'context': 'him. He uttered, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has never forgotten his defeat at the Red Cliffs, but he dares not attempt to avenge himself while the Sun family are friendly with Liu Bei. If in any moment of anger you two fall upon each other, Cao Cao will certainly seize the opportunity and your position will be dangerous.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 858, 'talk': 'Beyond all doubt Cao Cao has his spies here. As soon as he hears of any rift in the friendship between the Sun and Liu families, he will desire to come to an understanding with the latter, and Liu Bei, who fears your power, will accept his offer and take his side. Such an alliance will be a continual menace to the land south of the river. No; the plan for the occasion is to secure the friendship of Liu Bei by memorializing that he be made Imperial Protector of Jingzhou. This will make Cao Cao afraid to send any army against the South Land. At the same time it will raise kindly feelings in the heart of Liu Bei and win his support. You will be able to find some one who will provoke a quarrel between Cao Cao and Liu Bei and set them at each other, and that will be your opportunity. In this way you will succeed.', 'context': 'Gu Yong supported Zhang Zhao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'These are good words,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'but have I a messenger who can accomplish such a mission?', 'context': ' said Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'There is such a man, one whom Cao Cao respects and loves.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Who is he?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'What prevents you from employing Hua Xin? He is ready to hand.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'A very promising colt of my own,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 208, 'talk': "It were more fitting to let outsiders compete for the Prime Minister's silken robe; it is not right that members of the family monopolize the contest.", 'context': 'But suddenly from the green side rode out one who cried, “'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Let us see what his shooting is like!', 'context': 'Cao Cao looked at the speaker, who was Wen Ping. And some of the officers cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Quickly bring me the robe,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'How can you win what has been already won? But let me show you how I can shoot an arrow that shall overcome both your shots.', 'context': 'But at once from the ranks of the red−robed another competitor dashed forward, shouting fiercely, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'What is there amazing in your shooting, you three? See how I can shoot.', 'context': 'However, yet another archer came forth from the green−robed ranks, playing with his bow and crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I think the robe should be mine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'You shot backwards; but that is commonplace enough. Look while I shoot better than you all.', 'context': 'Before he could finish speaking, a fifth competitor came out from the red robes and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'Is not that a better shot than any of its predecessors?', 'context': 'As the gongs and drums broke out, Xiahou Yuan put aside his bow and rode up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Leave the robe there for me, Xu Huang, to win.', 'context': 'Then came out another from the greens who cried, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'What can you do that is better than my shot?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': "That you hit the bull's eye is no great feat. You will see me win the silken robe after all.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 394, 'iend': 453, 'talk': 'Where would you go with that robe? Quickly leave it for me!', 'context': 'which the robe hung down and shot thereat so true that his arrow cut it through, and the robe fluttered to the ground. At once Xu Huang dashed along, picked up the robe and slipped it on. Then riding swiftly to the terrace, he thanked the Prime Minister. No one present could withhold unstinted praise, and Xu Huang was turning to ride away when another green clad general leaped out, saying, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'The robe has already been adjudged to me; would you dare take it by forces', 'context': 'Xu Huang cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Never mind the robe; I see only your magnificent courage,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'What does a robe more or less matter?', 'context': ' said Cao Cao smiling. “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'Since the military officers have competed in mounted archery for our enjoyment and displayed their boldness and their skill, you, Gentlemen Scholars, stuffed full of learning as you are, can surely mount the terrace and present some complimentary odes to make the occasion a perfect success.', 'context': 'Cao Cao looked around to those about him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 345, 'iend': 387, 'talk': 'We are most willing to obey your commands,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 263, 'iend': 307, 'talk': 'Lord Cao Cao Who Restores Order in the West.', 'context': '“To my surprise, I was chosen for a small military office which changed my intentions, and I determined to repress the rebellion and so make a name for myself. I thought that I might win an inscription on my tomb to the effect that it covered the remains of the “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 841, 'talk': 'As a minister of state I have attained the topmost pinnacle of honor, and I have no more to hope for. Were it not for poor me, I know not how many there would be styling themselves emperors and dubbing themselves princes. Certain there be who, seeing my great authority, think I have some ulterior aim. But they are quite wrong. I ever bear in mind what Confucius said of King Wen of Zhou, that he was perfectly virtuous, and this saying is ever engraved on my mind1. If I could, I would do away with my armies and retire to my fief with my simple title of Lord of Wuping. Alas! I cannot. I am afraid to lay down my military powers lest I should come to harm. Should I be defeated, the state would totter; and so I may not risk real misfortune for the sake of an empty reputation for kindness. There be some of you who do not know my heart.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'None are your equals, O Prime Minister, not even Duke Zhou or the great Minister Yi Yin2.', 'context': 'As he closed, they all rose and bowed their heads, saying, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 304, 'talk': "The Marquis of Wu has sent Hua Xin as an envoy and presented a memorial to appoint Liu Bei Imperial Protector of Jingzhou. Sun Quan's sister is now Liu Bei's wife, while on the River Han, the greater part of the nine territories is under Liu Bei's rule.", 'context': 'But as he was beginning to write, they announced, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, you have been among fighting soldiers by myriads and in danger from stones and arrows many a time and never quailed. Now the news that Liu Bei has got possession of a small tract of country throws you into a panic. Why is it thus?', 'context': 'Cheng Yu said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Do you know the reason of the coming of Hua Xin?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'No; I know not,', 'context': ' said Cheng Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 330, 'talk': "Liu Bei is Sun Quan's one terror, and Sun Quan would attack Liu Bei were it not for you, O Prime Minister. Sun Quan feels you would fall upon him while he was smiting his enemy. Wherefore he has taken this means of calming Liu Bei's suspicions and fears and at the same time directing your enmity toward Liu Bei and from himself.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Yes,', 'context': 'Cao Cao nodded; “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Now this is my plan to set Sun Quan and Liu Bei at one another and give you the opportunity to destroy both; it can be done easily.', 'context': 'Cheng Yu continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'What is your plan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Friend Cheng Yu, you are a man after my own heart.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'You are the guarantor in the loan of Jingzhou to Liu Bei. He still delays to return it, and how long am I to wait?', 'context': 'Wherefore Lu Su was summoned, and his master said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'The writing said plainly that the rendition would follow the occupation of Yiazhou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Yes it said so. But so far they have not moved a soldier to the attack. I will not wait till old age has come to us all.', 'context': 'Sun Quan shouted back, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I will go and inquire?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 465, 'talk': 'Just lately Sun Quan concerned himself with getting you appointed Imperial Protector of Jingzhou; that was calculated to inspire Cao Cao with fear. Cao Cao obtained for Zhou Yu the governorship of Nanjun; that was designed to stir up strife between our two houses and set us fighting so that he might accomplish his own ends. This visit of Lu Su means that Zhou Yu, having taken over his new governorship, wishes to force us out of this place.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Then how shall we reply?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'If Lu Su introduces the subject, you will at once set up loud lamentations. When the sound of lamentation is at its height, I will appear and talk over your visitor.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 151, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'Sir, now that you are the husband of a daughter of Wu, you have become my lord, and I dare not sit in your presence.', 'context': 'Thus they planned, and Lu Su was duly received with all honor. When the salutations were over and host and guest were about to be seated, Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'You are an old friend,', 'context': 'Liu Bei laughed. “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Why this excessive humility?', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'What is the matter?', 'context': 'you two, and you should hand it back to my master.” At this Liu Bei covered his face and began to cry. “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Really I know not.', 'context': 'lord weeps so bitterly?” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 572, 'talk': "But it is easy to see. When my lord got the temporary occupation of Jingzhou, he gave the promise to return it when he had got the Western Land of Rivers. But reflect. Liu Zhang of Yiazhou is my lord's younger brother, and both of them are blood relations of the ruling family. If my lord were to move an army to capture another region, he fears the blame of the ignorant. And if he yields this place before he has another, where could he rest? Yet, while he retains this place it seems to shame you. The thing is hard on both sides, and that is why he weeps so bitterly.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Be not so distressed, O Uncle; let us hear what Zhuge Liang can propose.', 'context': 'Lu Su attempted to console him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'I would beg you to return to your master and tell him all. Tell him of this great trouble and entreat him to let us stay here a little longer.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 164, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'But suppose he refuses; what then?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'How can he refuse since he is related by marriage to my master ?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'I shall expect to hear glad tidings through you.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 118, 'iend': 500, 'talk': 'My friend, you have been fooled again. Long ago when Liu Bei was dependent on Liu Biao, he always cherished the intention to supplant him; think you that he really pities Liu Zhang? This sort of evasive policy will certainly cause you much trouble. However, I have a scheme which I think Zhuge Liang will not be able to get the better of. Only you will have to make another journey.', 'context': 'On the way Lu Su called in to see Zhou Yu at Chaisang and told him. But Zhou Yu stamped his foot with rage and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'I should be pleased to hear your fine scheme,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 589, 'talk': 'Do not go to see our master. Return to Jingzhou and say to Liu Bei that since his family and the Suns are related by marriage, they really form but one house, and since he has qualms about attacking the west, we will do it for him. Thus, the South Land will march an army under this pretext, but really go to Jingzhou, and we shall take him unprepared. The road to the west runs through his city, and we will call upon him for supplies. He will come out to thank the army, and we will assassinate him whereby we shall revenge ourselves and at the same time remove a source of future evil.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'Lu Su has not seen the Marquis of Wu, he has called in at Chaisang, and he and Zhou Yu have decided upon some scheme, which he is to talk you into accepting. However, let him talk; you, my lord, only watch me; and when I nod my head, then you agree to whatever he may propose.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 397, 'talk': "The Marquis of Wu praises the noble virtue of the Imperial Uncle; and after consultation with his officers, he has determined to take the western country on the Imperial Uncle's behalf and, that done, Jingzhou can be exchanged for it without further delay. However, when the army marches through, it will be expected of you to contribute some necessary supplies.", 'context': 'Lu Su was then admitted and said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'We could hardly have hoped for such kindness.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang here nodded his head rapidly, at the same time saying, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'This is due to your friendly efforts on our behalf.', 'context': 'And Liu Bei saluted with joined hands and said, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'When the brave army arrives, we shall certainly come out to meet it and entertain the soldiers,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'What is their intention?', 'context': 'Liu Bei as yet did not understand. “'},
{'istart': 9, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Why?', 'context': 'child.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'And what are we to do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'Have no anxiety; all we have to do is to prepare a hidden bow to get the fierce tiger; to spread the enticing bait to hook the great leviathan. Wait till Zhou Yu comes; if he is not killed, he will be nine−tenths a corpse. We will call in Zhao Yun for orders and give him secret instructions, and I will dispose the others.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'At last! Now they will fall into my trap.', 'context': 'Zhou Yu laughed with glee, saying, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Is there any one to welcome the brave army?', 'context': 'At Xiakou he inquired, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'The Imperial Uncle has sent Mi Zhu to greet us.', 'context': 'They told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'What of the preparations for the army?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'My master has seen to that; all is prepared,', 'context': ' asked Zhou Yu as soon as Mi Zhu came. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Where is the Imperial Uncle?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'He is at the city of Jingzhou, waiting outside the walls to offer you the cup of greeting.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'This expedition is on your account,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 155, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'Who is there?', 'context': 'By and bye he came to the city wall. There was no sign of life. Reining in his steed, he bade them challenge the gate. Then some one from the wall asked, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'The Commander−in−Chief of the South Land, Zhou Yu, in person.', 'context': 'The soldiers of the South Land replied, “'},
{'istart': 139, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Why are you here, General?', 'context': 'Immediately was heard the thud of a club, and the wall became alive with troops all armed. And from the tower came out Zhao Yun who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I am going to take the west for you;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'do you not know?', 'context': ' replied Zhou Yu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 481, 'talk': "The Directing Instructor knows that you want to try the ruse of 'Borrowing a Road to Destroy the Host.' And so he stationed me here. And my master bade me say that he and the ruler of the Western Land of Rivers are both members of the reigning family so that he could not think of such baseness as attacking Yiazhou. If you people of the South Land do so, he will be forced to go away into the mountains and become a recluse. He could not bear to lose the confidence of humankind.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 328, 'talk': 'Armed bands are moving toward us from all four sides, led by Guan Yu, Zhang Fei, Huang Zhong, and Wei Yan. Their number is unknown, but the sound of their tramping shakes the heavens. They say they want to capture the Commander−in−Chief.', 'context': 'At this Zhou Yu turned his horse as if to return. Just then his scouts came up to report: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'They say I shall never be able to get Yiazhou! But I will; I swear I will.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'My brother sent me to assist you,', 'context': "Soon after Sun Quan's brother Sun Shao arrived, and Zhou Yu told him his vexations. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 606, 'talk': 'Now indeed, General, you would go far and you would render great services, yet can any one foretell the final result? No; not even Wu Qi the Great General could say for certain, nor could Sun Zi the Famed Strategist be sure of a successful issue. Cao Cao suffered severe defeat at the Red Cliffs; think you he will ever cease to hope for revenge? Now if you undertake a long expedition, will he not seize the occasion to fall upon the South Land and grind it to powder? Such a deed would be more than I could bear, and I venture to warn you of the possible danger if haply you may condescend to regard it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 185, 'iend': 367, 'talk': 'I have honestly tried to do my best for my country, but my end is at hand. The number of my days is accomplished. You must continue to aid our master till his end shall be achieved——', 'context': 'The letter made Zhou Yu feel very sorrowful, and he sighed deeply. He called for paper and ink and wrote to the Marquis of Wu and, having done this, he said to his assembled officers, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'O God, since thou made Zhou Yu, why did thou also create Zhuge Liang?', 'context': 'Slowly he regained consciousness; and as he looked up to heaven, he sighed heavily, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'Lu Su is most loyal, careful in all matters and a fitting man to succeed to my office. When a person is near death, his words are wise; and if I may haply retain your regard, I may die but I shall not decay.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': "Zhou Yu should have been a king's counselor,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'He has left me alas! too soon, and whom have I to lean upon? But he recommends Lu Su, and I can do nothing better than take that advice.', 'context': ' cried Sun Quan, amid his tears. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Zhou Yu is dead,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Now that this has come to pass, what should we do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Lu Su will succeed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 244, 'talk': 'And I see in the heavens signs of an assembly of generals in the southeast, so I shall go there. The mourning for Zhou Yu will serve as a pretext. I may find some able leaders there to be of help to you.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'I am afraid lest the generals of the South Land harm you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'While Zhou Yu lived, I did not fear; is there anything to dread now that he is gone?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Deign to accept this my sacrifice.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'Plainly Zhuge Liang loved Zhou Yu much, but Zhou Yu was not broadminded enough and would have done Zhuge Liang to death.', 'context': 'And Lu Su was particularly affected by the display of feeling and thought, “'},
{'istart': 173, 'iend': 353, 'talk': 'You exasperated literally to death the man whose body lies up there; to come here as a mourner is an open insult to the South Land. It is as good as to say they have no other left.', 'context': 'Lu Su gave a banquet for Zhuge Liang after which the guest left. Just as Zhuge Liang was embarking, his arm was clutched by a person in Taoist dress who said with a smile, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 306, 'talk': 'I do not think that Sun Quan will use you as you merit. If you find life here distasteful, then you may come to Jingzhou and help to support my master. He is liberal and virtuous and will not disdain what you have spent your life in learning.', 'context': 'Before leaving, Zhuge Liang gave his friend a letter and said, “'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'Yes; I know him by reputation; let him come.', 'context': "This was good news for Sun Quan, who asked the man's name, and when he heard it was Pang Tong or Blooming−Phoenix, he replied, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'What have you studied,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'and what are you master of?', 'context': ' asked Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'One must not be narrow and obstinate; one must change with circumstances.', 'context': 'Pang Tong replied, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'How does your learning compare with that of Zhou Yu?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'My learning is not to be compared with his in the least; mine is far greater.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'You may retire, Sir; I will send for you when I can employ you.', 'context': 'Now Sun Quan had always loved his late general, and he could not bear to hear him disparaged. This speech of Pang Tong only increased his dislike. So he said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'My lord, why not employ him?', 'context': 'When he had gone, Lu Su said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'What good would result; he is just one of those mad fellows.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'It was simply that Cao Cao wished to chain his ships together. No credit was due to this fellow. In any case I give you my word that I will not employ him. That much is certain.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'I fear you are doomed to constant disappointment here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'There is nothing you can hope for, eh?', 'context': ' said Lu Su. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'With your wonderful gifts, of course you will be successful whithersoever you may go. You may take my word for that. But to whom will you go?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I think I will join Cao Cao,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'That would be hinging a gleaming pearl into darkness. Rather go to Liu Bei, who would appreciate you and employ you fittingly.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'The truth is that I have been thinking of this for a long time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'I was only joking just now.', 'context': ' said Pang Tong. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'I will give you a letter to Liu Bei; and if you go to him, you must try to maintain peace between him and my lord and get them to act together against Cao Cao.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'That has been the one desire of my life.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'You have come a long and arduous journey,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'I hear, O Imperial Uncle, that you are welcoming the wise and receiving scholars, wherefore I have come to join your service.', 'context': 'At this point the suitor should have produced his letters from Zhuge Liang and Lu Su, but did not. Instead he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'The country is decently peaceful now, and unfortunately there is no office vacant. But away to the northeast there is a small magistracy, Leiyang, which needs a chief. I can offer you that post until there should be something more fitting.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Here is this stiff−necked pedant throwing my administration into disorder.', 'context': 'News of this reaching Liu Bei, who was angry and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Where is the Magistrate?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'Ever since his arrival, a hundred days ago and more, he has attended to no business, but spends his days from morn to night in wine−bobbing and is always intoxicated. Just now he is sleeping off a debauch and is not yet risen.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 282, 'talk': 'Pang Tong is a man of great ability, and it would be wrong to deal with him thus summarily. Let us inquire into it. If he is really so guilty, we will punish his offense.', 'context': "This raised Zhang Fei's choler, and he would have dismissed the offender forthwith had not his colleague said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'My brother took you for a decent person,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Do you think I have done as you say, General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'What affairs have I disordered?', 'context': ' said Pang Tong. “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'You have been here over a hundred days and spent the whole time in dissipation. Is not that disorderly?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Where would be the difficulty in dealing with the business of a trifling county like this? I pray you, General, sit down for a while till I have settled the cases.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 256, 'talk': 'Where is the disorder? When I can take on Cao Cao and Sun Quan as easily as I can read this paper, what attention from me is needed for the business of this paltry place?', 'context': 'This done, the Magistrate threw aside his pen and turned to the inquisitors, saying, “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'You are indeed a marvel, Master. I have not treated you respectfully enough, but now I shall commend you to my brother with all my might.', 'context': "Zhang Fei was astonished at the man's ability, rose from his seat, and crossed over, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Why did you not show this to my brother when you first saw him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'You just saved a wise man for us.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei turned to his colleague and said, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I have been wrong; I have behaved unjustly to a sage.', 'context': 'Liu Bei then seemed to be conscious of his error and said, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Is Directing−Instructor Pang Tong quite well?', 'context': 'Soon Zhuge Liang entered the hall, and the first question he put after the formal salutations was: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'He is in charge of Leiyang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'where he is given to wine and neglects his business.', 'context': ' replied Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'This very day I have received a letter, but from Lu Su. I have had no letter written by you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'When a person of transcendent abilities is sent to a paltry post, he always turns to wine out of simple ennui,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'If it had not been for what my brother said, I should have lost a great person,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 318, 'iend': 401, 'talk': 'As soon as the Blooming−Phoenix shall arrive, he should be given an important post.', 'context': 'Then he lost no time, but sent Zhang Fei off to the northeast to request Pang Tong to come to Jingzhou City. When he arrived, Liu Bei went out to meet him and at the foot of the steps asked pardon for his mistake. Then Pang Tong produced the letter that Zhuge Liang had given him. What Liu Bei read therein was this: “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 275, 'talk': 'Water−Mirror said of the two men, Sleeping−Dragon and Blooming−Phoenix, that any man who obtained the help of either of them could restore the empire when he would. As I now have them both, surely the Hans will rise again.', 'context': 'Liu Bei rejoiced indeed as he read it, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Sun Quan should be first attacked. because of the recent death of their ablest general Zhou Yu. Liu Bei will follow.', 'context': 'Said Xun Yu, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'If I go on such a distant expedition, Ma Teng will fall upon the capital. While I was at the Red Cliffs, there were sinister rumors of this, and I must guard against it.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 261, 'talk': 'The best thing that occurs to stupid me is to obtain for Ma Teng the title of General Who Subdues the South and send him against the South Land. Thus he can be enticed to the capital and got rid of. Then you can have no fear of marching southward.', 'context': 'Xun Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 425, 'talk': 'When Dong Cheng got the Girdle Edict from the Emperor, we formed a society, of which Liu Bei was one, pledged to put down rebellion. However, we accomplished nothing, for Dong Cheng was put to death and Liu Bei was unfortunate, while I escaped to the west. However, I hear that Liu Bei now holds Jingzhou, and I am inclined to carry out the plan we made so long ago. But here I am summoned by Cao Cao and what is to be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'Cao Cao has the command of the Emperor to call you; and if you do not go, that will mean disobeying an imperial command and you will be punished. Obey the summons in so far as to go to the capital, where you may be able to arrange to carry out your original intention.', 'context': 'Ma Chao replied, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 91, 'talk': "Cao Cao's designs are unfathomable; and if you go, Uncle, I fear you will suffer.", 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Let me lead the army against the capital,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 152, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Can we not purge the empire of evil?', 'context': ' said Ma Chao. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'You must take command of the Qiang troops for the defense of our territory here. I will take with me your two brothers and your cousin. When Cao Cao knows that you have the Qiangs at your call and that Han Sui is prepared to assist, he will hardly dare to work any harm to me.', 'context': 'But his father said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Father, if you must go, be careful not to enter the city till you know exactly what plots and machinations are afoot.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'I will certainly take great care, so do not be too anxious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 474, 'talk': 'Ma Teng is to be sent against the south, and I shall send you as Adviser. You are first to go to his camp and express my congratulations on his arrival and say that as Xiliang is so distant and transport very difficult, he is not to take too large an army of his own. I will send a large force. Also tell him to come in soon for audience of the Emperor. I will send him supplies.', 'context': "When Cao Cao heard of Ma Teng's arrival, he called to him Minister Huang Kui and said to him, “"},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'My father perished at the hands of Li Jue and Guo Si, and I have always nourished resentment. Now there is another rebel in power wronging our Prince.', 'context': 'In his cups the messenger grew confidential and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who is that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'The wrong doer is that rebel Cao Cao, of course. Do you mean to say you do not know?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Then you have quite forgotten the Girdle Edict, eh?', 'context': 'But Huang Kui cared not, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'Cao Cao wants you to go in to audience; there is no good intention there. Do not go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'You lead your army up close to the city and get Cao Cao to come and review them; and when he comes, assassinate him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 441, 'iend': 525, 'talk': 'Ask him what is the truth about two men, Liu Bei and Cao Cao? Who is the wicked one.', 'context': "Seeing Huang Kui so disturbed in mind, his wife, Lady Zhi, asked him what was wrong. But he would tell her nothing. However, he had a concubine, Li Chunxiang. And it happened that she had an intrigue with the wife's younger brother, Miao Ze, who much desired to marry her. The concubine who also saw her lord's displeasure, spoke of it to her paramour, and he told her she could probably draw from him what was wrong by a leading question. “"},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'You are a woman; still you know right from wrong as well as I. My enemy and the man I would slay if I could, is Cao Cao.', 'context': 'Her lord, still rather intoxicated, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'But why? And if you wish to slay him, why do you not do something?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'I have done something. I have settled with General Ma Teng to assassinate Cao Cao at the review.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'That worthless scoundrel has spoiled all my plans!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Now I cannot slay the rebel and purge my country. But it is the will of God.', 'context': ' cried Ma Teng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'I desire no other reward than Li Chunxiang as wife,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'For the sake of a woman then you have brought a whole household to death. What advantage would there be in preserving such a miscreant?', 'context': 'Cao Cao smiled and said, “'},
{'istart': 239, 'iend': 331, 'talk': "The bird's wings will be fully grown if he obtains possession of the Western Land of Rivers.", 'context': 'Having slain Ma Teng, Cao Cao decided to set out on his expedition to the south. But then came the disquieting news of the military preparations of Liu Bei, whose objective was said to be the west. This caused him alarm, for, as he said, “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'I know how to prevent Liu Bei and Sun Quan from helping each other, and both the south and the west will be yours.', 'context': 'Cao Cao recognized the difficulty, but from among his counselors there arose one who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'What is this good plan of yours, friend Chen Qun?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 539, 'talk': 'Your two principal enemies—Liu Bei and Sun Quan—are now firm allies, close as lips and teeth. But Liu Bei wants the Western Land of Rivers and if you, O Prime Minister, send a mighty host against Sun Quan, Sun Quan must ask help from his friend Liu Bei, who, having his heart set on the west, will refuse it. Sun Quan without this aid cannot stand and will become so weak that the South Land will be yours for the taking, and Jingzhou will follow in a tap of the drum. The west will follow and the whole empire is yours.', 'context': 'Chen Qun replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Those are my thoughts put into words,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'Let us send to Lu Su to tell him to write at once to Liu Bei that he may help us. They are good friends, and Liu Bei will certainly respond favorably. Beside, since Liu Bei and our lord are now connected by marriage, there is no risk of refusal. With the support of Liu Bei, there is no danger to our country.', 'context': 'At the council Zhang Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 173, 'talk': "It is not necessary for the South Land's troops to move, nor need we send ours. I can prevent Cao Cao from even daring to look in the southeast direction.", 'context': 'The adviser said, “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'How could the Instructor hope to roll back the huge army of three hundred thousand troops that Cao Cao is preparing to bring south?', 'context': 'The letter was given to the messenger, and then Liu Bei asked his adviser, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 311, 'talk': "Cao Cao's chief fear is Xiliang. Now just lately he has slain Ma Teng and his sons as well, and the people of Xiliang are grinding their teeth with rage. Now you must write and ask Ma Chao to march through the pass, and Cao Cao will have no leisure to think of any expedition to the south.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'What is your interpretation?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Bind us both, Uncle, and send us thither; you need not move a single spear,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Your father and I were sworn brothers; think you I would harm you? Rather will I help if you are going to fight.', 'context': 'But Han Sui raised him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 343, 'talk': 'Since the land about the city is barren and the water bitter, the people must have communication with the country around in order to live. Further they have no fuel. Ten days of siege must have exhausted the supplies in the city, wherefore if we relax for a time—well, you will see. We shall capture the city without moving a finger.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Your plan seems excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 326, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'Here is Pang De!', 'context': 'The General of the west gate was Zhong Jin, brother of Zhong Yao. About the third watch of the night, a torch was seen moving just inside the gate; and when the General went to see what was wrong, and was passing the gateway, a man suddenly galloped up and slashed at him with a sword. At the same time the attacker shouted, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'Cao Hong and Xu Huang are to march your ten thousand troops to Tong Pass to support Zhong Yao. You are to hold the Pass at all costs for ten days, or you will pay for its loss with your heads. After ten days the Pass will be no concern of yours, for I will be there with the main army.', 'context': 'He at once gave orders, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Cao Hong short of temper is unfitted to hold the Pass. Everything could happen.', 'context': 'Cao Ren said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'You will go to reinforce him.', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Ma Chao only wishes to provoke you to come out, but remember our orders and go not. The Prime Minister has some master plan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'When I gave you the limit of ten days, why did you leave the Pass on the ninth?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Those soldiers from Xiliang hurled every sort of insult at us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'You are young and impetuous. But, Xu Huang, you ought to have known.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'We should establish a strong stockade before attacking.', 'context': 'Cao Ren said, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'Why are you arrayed against the Hans, whom your father and grandfather served faithfully?', 'context': 'However, Cao Cao urged forward his steed and shouted to Ma Chao, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 276, 'talk': 'Rebel! Betrayer of both prince and people! Murderer of my father and brothers! My hate for you is to the death: the same sky shall not continue to cover us, for I will take you captive and satiate my appetite on your living flesh.', 'context': 'Ma Chao ground his teeth and cursed Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is he in the red dress!', 'context': 'They came close. Cao Cao heard one of his pursuers shout to another, “'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is he with the long beard!', 'context': 'So he hastily tore off his red robe and threw it away. He also heard one say “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Cao Cao, do not flee!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 531, 'iend': 551, 'talk': 'Do not hurt my lord!', 'context': "The whip dropped from Cao Cao's nerveless hand as he saw his enemy coming closer and closer. But just as Ma Chao had leveled his spear for a thrust, Cao Cao slipped behind a tree, changed the direction of his flight and so escaped, while Ma Chao struck the tree. He quickly pulled out his spear, but the delay gave the fugitive an advantage, although it did not quite free him from pursuit, for Ma Chao was soon again galloping on his track. As they drew near the slope of some hills, a bold general suddenly appeared, who cried, “"},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'Had I not spared Cao Hong, I should have fallen at the hands of Ma Chao today.', 'context': 'As he sat in his tent, Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Our enemies use long spears,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'We will meet them with bows and crossbows.', 'context': ' said the officers. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'They may have long spears,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'but whether I give battle or not depends on my decision. How can they thrust at us if we do not go out? All you have to do is to take no notice of them, and they will speedily retire.', 'context': ' replied Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister came out on this expedition of his own will and was foremost in the fight; why does he accept defeat so easily?', 'context': 'The officers wondered. They said one to another, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'Ma Chao has been reinforced by twenty thousand Qiangs, the tribespeople beyond the frontier.', 'context': 'After some days the spies reported: “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'Wait till I have defeated them and I will explain.', 'context': 'Cao Cao took the news gleefully. His officers asked him why the news pleased him, and he replied, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'You gentlemen laugh because I cannot destroy Ma Chao. Well then, can any one of you propose a plan?', 'context': 'Then said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 400, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, you have a large force here, and the enemy are strongly posted beyond the Pass. This means that on the west side of River Wei they are unprepared. If you can get an army secretly across the river and block the ferry, you will cut off their retreat; and if you can smite them on the north side of the river, they can get no reinforcements and must fail.', 'context': 'Then rose Xu Huang and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'What you propose is just what I think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 421, 'talk': 'I understand. The Pass is left, rafts are being prepared; that means that he is going to cross to the north side and cut off my retreat. I must coast along the river and keep him off. If I can do that, his food will run short within twenty days, and that will cause a mutiny. I will travel along the south bank and attack.', 'context': 'Cao Cao himself crossed River Wei, and when Ma Chao heard of the new military movements, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Attack from the south bank when his army is in the act of crossing, and his army will be drowned in the river,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Uncle, your words are good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'A general dressed all in white is approaching.', 'context': 'Very soon the sentinels reported, “'},
{'istart': 455, 'iend': 511, 'talk': 'The rebels are close! Get into a boat, O Prime Minister.', 'context': 'Everyone knew it must be Ma Chao. This terrified them and they made a rush to get into the boats. The river bank became a scene of shouting men struggling who could first embark. Cao Cao sat watching and never stirred. He only issued orders to stop the confusion. Meanwhile, the yelling of the troops and the neighing of the horses of the approaching army came nearer and nearer. Suddenly a general jumped out of one of the boats and shouted to Cao Cao: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'The rebels are near; why not?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'The rebels very nearly caught me today,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Who was it that drew them off?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'I should have been a prisoner but for your happy thought,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Though they have gone, yet they will assuredly return tomorrow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'My preparations are all made,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'I would have captured Cao Cao, but a certain bold general had taken him on his back and leaped with him into a boat.', 'context': 'Ma Chao returned to Han Sui and told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 335, 'talk': 'I have heard that Cao Cao had a body guard of the bravest and strongest soldiers under the command of Dian Wei and Xu Chu. They are called the Tiger Guards. Now as Dian Wei is dead, the man you saw must have been Xu Chu. He is both brave and powerful and goes by the name of Tiger−Lust. You will do well to avoid him.', 'context': 'Han Sui replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'I know his name, too,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Cao Cao now means to attack our rear;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'let us attack first, before he can establish camps and stockades. If once he can do that, it will be difficult to dislodge him.', 'context': ' continued Han Sui, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'My idea is that we should hold the north bank and prevent him from crossing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Worthy nephew, keep guard here while I go along the bank of the river and fight Cao Cao.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'If you will take Pang De as your van leader, I am content,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'If we give the enemy time, he will make himself strong on the north bank. I think we can do no better than to raid his camp tonight,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'We must have a force and supports for it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'The rebels will try to surprise us as they are deceived by my not having set up stockades. You will place your soldiers in ambush. At the bomb signal, you will rush out from four directions to capture them.', 'context': "Now Cao Cao's troops were on the north bank of the River Wei, and he gave his generals orders, saying, “"},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, you have long been striving to make a camp on the river. Now is your opportunity; why not begin?', 'context': 'Cao Cao received him with great courtesy, and presently the venerable one began, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'The soil is too sandy to stand,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'But if you have some other plan to propose, pray tell me what it is, O Hermit.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 341, 'talk': 'You are more than human, O Prime Minister, in the art of war, and you surely know the times and seasons. It has been overcast for many days, and these clouds foretell a north wind and intense cold. When the wind begins to blow, you should hurry your army to carry up the earth and sprinkle it with water. By dawn your wall will be complete.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 234, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'I, Cao Cao, am here alone, and I beg Ma Chao to come out to parley with me.', 'context': 'However, very soon after, he got his whole army together and sounded an attack. Cao Cao himself rode out of the camp, with only the redoubtable Xu Chu in attendance, and advanced toward the enemy. Flourishing his whip he called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'You despised me because I had no wall to my camp, but lo! in one single night, God has made me a wall. Do you not think it time to give in?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 307, 'iend': 376, 'talk': "Where is the noble 'Marquis Tiger' that I hear you have in your camp?", 'context': 'Ma Chao was so enraged that he almost rushed at Cao Cao, but he was not too angry to notice the henchman behind him, glaring in angry fashion, who held a gleaming sword in his grip. Ma Chao thought this man could be no other than Xu Chu, so he determined to find out. With a flourish of his whip, he said, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'I am Xu Chu of Qiao!', 'context': 'At this Xu Chu lifted his sword and roared, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'They know our friend Xu Chu over there as Marquis Tiger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I will capture that fellow Ma Chao tomorrow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Ma Chao is very bold,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Be careful!', 'context': ' said his master. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I swear to fight him to the death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Dare he insult me so?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 217, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'Where is the Tiger−Lust?', 'context': 'Next day both armies moved out and arrayed in order of battle. Ma Chao gave Pang De and Ma Dai command of the two wings, while Han Sui took the center. Ma Chao took up his station in front of the center and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Ma Chao is no less bold than Lu Bu!', 'context': 'Cao Cao, who was on horseback by the standard, turned and said, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'I have seen some wicked fighters, but none to match that Xu Chu. He is aptly nicknamed Tiger−Lust', 'context': 'Ma Chao went down to the river. When he saw Han Sui, he said, “'},
{'istart': 239, 'iend': 306, 'talk': 'If that Ma Chao is not killed, may I never know my place of burial!', 'context': 'One day from his ramparts, Cao Cao saw Ma Chao and a few horsemen ride close up to the walls and then gallop to and fro like the wind. After gazing at them for a long time, Cao Cao tore off his helmet and dashed it on the ground, saying, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'May I die here at once if I do not destroy that rebel!', 'context': 'Xiahou Yuan heard his master, and his heart burned within him. He cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'What now? Cao Cao has went to the west of the river, and we can be attacked in the rear,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'He is wise,', 'context': 'the spring warmth.” “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'and I advise the same.', 'context': ' said Han Sui, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'You may return; I will send my reply,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'What is your opinion, O Prime Minister?', 'context': 'Then Jia Xu said to Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'What is yours?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'Although he agrees to peace, yet he is evil and crafty. We must remain prepared against his machinations. Uncle, you and I will take turns in watching Cao Cao and Xu Huang on alternate days. So shall we be safe against his treachery.', 'context': 'When the reply arrived, Ma Chao said to Han Sui, “'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'I am succeeding.', 'context': 'They agreed and began the regular alternate watch. Soon Cao Cao got to know what they were doing, and he turned to Jia Xu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Who keeps the look−out on this side tomorrow?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Han Sui,', 'context': ' asked Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Do any of you soldiers want to see Cao Cao? Here I am quite alone. I have not four eyes nor a couple of mouths, but I am very knowing.', 'context': 'Presently Cao Cao called out, “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'Sir, the Prime Minister humbly asks you to come and confer with him.', 'context': 'The soldiers turned pale with fright. Then Cao Cao called up a man and told him to go and see Han Sui and say, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'Your father and I were granted filial degrees at the same time, and I used to treat him as an uncle. You and I set out on our careers at the same time, too, and yet we have not met for years. How old may you be now?', 'context': 'Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'I am forty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'In those old days in the capital, we were both very young and never thought about middle age. If we could only restore tranquillity to the state, that would be a matter of rejoicing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'What was it Cao Cao came out to discuss today ?', 'context': 'It was not long before some one told Ma Chao of this meeting, and he went over to his ally to ask about it. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'He just recalled the old days when we were together in the capital.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Did he say nothing about military matters?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Not a word; and I could not talk about them alone.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'It may be an excellent idea,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'What is your scheme?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'The scheme looks excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Why are all these alterations here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'It came like that; I do not know.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Does any one send a rough draft like this? It seems to me, Uncle, that you are afraid I shall know something or other too well, and so you have changed the wording.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'It must be that Cao Cao has sealed up the rough draft by mistake.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'I do not think so. He is a careful man and would not make such a mistake. You and I, Uncle, have been allies in trying to slay the rebel; why are you turning against me now ?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'If you doubt my word, I will tell you what you can do. Tomorrow, in full view of the army, I will get Cao Cao to come out and talk. You can hide in behind the ranks ready to kill me if I am false.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'That being so, I shall know that you are true, Uncle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 170, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'Last night the Prime Minister quite understood. Let there be no mistake.', 'context': 'Thereupon at his command, Cao Hong, with a train of ten horsemen rode out, advanced straight to Han Sui, leaned over to him and said, loudly enough to be heard plainly, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Nephew, trust me, really I have no evil intentions.', 'context': 'When Han Sui saw him, he said, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'How can this be cleared up?', 'context': 'But Ma Chao, burning with rage, went away. Then Han Sui talked over the matter with his five generals. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Ma Chao trusts too much to his strength,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': "I was his father's pledged brother and could not bear to desert him,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'It seems to me that as things have come to this pass: you simply have to now.', 'context': ' said Han Sui. “'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'Who would act as go−between?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'I will,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 438, 'iend': 473, 'talk': 'We must not delay, now is the time.', 'context': "All this was done, but not without some hesitation and delay, and some news of the plot reached Ma Chao. He found out the careful preparations that had been made and resolved to act first. Leaving Ma Dai and Pang De in reserve, he chose a few trusted leaders and with stealthy steps made his way into Han Sui's tent. There he found Han Sui and his five confederates deep in conversation. He just caught a word or two that Yang Qiu said, “"},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'You herd of rebels! Would you dare to plot against me?', 'context': 'In burst Ma Chao raging and yelling, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'Pursue him day and night, and rich rewards are for him dead or alive. For his head the rewards are a thousand ounces of gold and the lordship of a fief of ten thousand families. If any one captures Ma Chao, the reward is the rank of general.', 'context': 'Hearing that his enemy had got away, Cao Cao gave order to his generals, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 224, 'talk': 'I would be quite willing to finish the subjugation, but there is much to do in the capital and the south is still to conquer. So I cannot remain. But you, Sir, might secure this country for me. Do you consents', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 187, 'iend': 269, 'talk': 'A strong force ought to be left in Changan, as a reserve in case they be required.', 'context': "Yang Fu did consent. And he brought to Cao Cao's notice Wei Kang, who was made Imperial Protector of Liangzhou, with joint military powers. Just before Yang Fu left, he said to Cao Cao, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'That has been already dealt with,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 913, 'talk': "The rebels first held the Pass. Had I forthwith taken the east of the river, the rebels would have defended the camps one by one and mustered at all the ferries, and I should never have got across the river to the north bank. So I massed troops against Tong Pass and made the rebels guard the south bank so that the west of the river was left open. Thus Xu Huang and Zhu Ling could move there, and I was able later to cross over to the north. Then I made the raised road and the mud rampart to deceive the enemy and cause them to think I was weak and thus embolden them up to the point of attacking without proper preparation. Then I used the clever device of causing dissension in their ranks and was able in one day to destroy the stored up energy of all their forces. 'It was a thunder clap before you could cover your ears.' Yes indeed; the mutations of the art of war can be called infinite.", 'context': 'And he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'But one thing more puzzled us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'and we ask you to explain it. When you heard the enemy was reinforced, you seemed to grow happier. Why was that?', 'context': ' said the officers, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 384, 'talk': 'Because Tong Pass is distant from Xuchang; and if the rebels had taken advantage of all defensible points and held them, they could not have been quelled in less than a couple of years. When they came on altogether, they made a multitude but they were not unanimous. They easily quarreled and, disunited, were easily overcome. So I had reason to rejoice that they came on altogether.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Indeed no one can equal you in strategy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Still, remember that I rely on you,', 'context': ' said his officers, bowing low before him. “'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'The writing of the Three Gods.', 'context': 'When praying for a person, they wrote his name on a slip and his confession and made three copies thereof, called “'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 412, 'talk': "Ma Teng has died, and Ma Chao defeated, thus the northwest has fallen. Cao Cao's next ambition will be the southwest, and Hanzhong will be his first attack. I should act first by assuming the title of Prince of Hanzhong and superintending the defense.1", 'context': "When the reports of Cao Cao's success against the west, and his prestige and influence, reached the Hanzhong people, Zhang Lu met with his counselors, saying, “"},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 559, 'talk': "The army of this region counts one hundred thousand, and there are ample supplies of everything. The Eastern Land of Rivers is a natural stronghold with its mountains and rivers. Now Ma Chao's soldiers are newly defeated, and the fugitives from the Ziwu Valley are very numerous. We can add them to our army by several ten−thousands more. My advice is that as Liu Zhang of Yiazhou is weak, we should take possession of the forty−one counties of the Western Land of Rivers, and then you may set up your sovereign as soon as you like.", 'context': 'In reply one Yan Pu said, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'My Master, be not alarmed; I am no genius, but I have a bit of a healthy tongue, and with that I will make Zhang Lu afraid even to look this way.', 'context': 'At the council one haughtily said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'What proposal have you to offer that may avert this danger?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Your master Liu Zhang has sent no tribute for several years; why?', 'context': 'Cao Cao was seated in the high place, and after his visitor had finished his salutations, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Because the roads are dangerous and thieves and robbers infest them. Intercourse is restricted.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'How can you behave so rudely when you come on a mission? Your whole attitude was blunt and discourteous. Happily for you, our lord remembered you had come from afar and did not take open notice of your fault. The best thing for you is to go home again as quickly as you can.', 'context': 'Those in attendance were annoyed with Zhang Song and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'We have no plausible flatterers and glib talkers in our western country,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Your roads are precipitous and wearisome,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': "But at our lord's command we travel, even through fire and water; we never decline,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'What sort of a country is this Yiazhou?', 'context': ' replied Zhang Song. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'But what of the people?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'Our administrators are talented as Sima Xiangru; our soldiers able as Ma Yuan; our physicians are expert as Zhang Ji; our diviners are profound as Yan Zun. Our schools of philosophy and our culture stand forth as models, and we have more remarkable people than I can enumerate. How should I ever finish the tale of them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'And how many such as you, Sir, do you think there are at the orders of your Imperial Protector?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'Our officers are all geniuses: wise, bold, loyal, righteous, and magnanimous. As for poor simpletons like me, they are counted by hundreds; there are cartloads of them, bushels of them. No one could count them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'What office may you hold then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'Mine can hardly be called an office. I am a Supernumerary Charioteer. But, Sir, what state affairs may you control?', 'context': ' Zhang Song replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'I am the First Secretary in the Palace of the Prime Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'They say that members of your family held office for many generations, and I do not understand why you are not in court service actually assisting the Emperor, instead of filling the post of a mere clerk in the private palace of the Prime Minister.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 280, 'talk': "Though I am among the minor officials, yet my duties are of great importance, and I am gaining experience under the Prime Minister's guidance. I hold the office for the sake of the training.", 'context': "Yang Xiu's face suffused with shame at this rebuke, but he mastered himself and replied, “"},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 390, 'talk': "If what I have heard is true, Cao Cao's learning throws no gleaming light on the way of Confucius or Mencius, nor does his military skill illumine the art of Sun Zi or Wu Qi. He seems to understand the doctrine of brute force and holding on to what advantages he can seize, but I see not how he can give you any valuable training or enlighten your understanding.", 'context': 'Zhang Song smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'Ah, Sir; that comes of dwelling in out−of−the−way parts. How could you know of the magnificent talents of the great Prime Minister? But I will show you something.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'The New Book of Cao Cao', 'context': 'Yang Xiu called up an attendant and bade him bring a book from a certain case. He showed this to his guest, who read the title “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'What do you take this to be?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 240, 'talk': "This is the great Prime Minister's discussion of the art of ancient and modern war composed on the model of Sun Zi's Treatise on the Art of War. You may be disdainful of the Prime Minister's talents, but will this not go down to posterity?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 244, 'talk': 'This book! Every child in Yiazhou knows this by heart. What do you mean by calling it a new book? It was written by some obscure person of the time of the Warring States, and Cao Cao has plagiarized it. But he has deceived no one but you, Sir.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'But what is the use of your sarcastic insult in saying that your school children know the book by rote? It has never been given to the world, although copies have been made. It belongs to his private library.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Do you disbelieve me? Why, I know it and could repeat it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'You remember it like this after only one reading! Really you are marvelous.', 'context': 'Yang Xiu said, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'Remain a while in your lodgings till I can petition our Prime Minister to give you another interview.', 'context': 'Once read, his memory held fast. At leave−taking Yang Xiu said, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'Sir, why did you formerly treat Zhang Song so off−hand?', 'context': 'Zhang Song thanked him and left. By and bye Yang Xiu went to see Cao Cao on the matter of receiving the emissary from the west and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'He spoke very rudely; that is why.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'But you bore with Mi Heng; why not with this man?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'It only shows that the ancients and I are in secret sympathy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Then may I bring him to see you, Sir, that he may see the glory of our court.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'Have you ever seen such fine bold fellows in Yiazhou?', 'context': 'Zhang Song glanced at them contemptuously. After a long time Cao Cao called up Zhang Song and, pointing to his army, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'We never see this military parade in Yiazhou; we govern the people by righteousness.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 337, 'talk': 'I regard the rat−class of the world as of no more importance than so many weeds, and for my army to reach a place is to overcome it, to give battle is to conquer, to besiege is to take. Those who are with me, live; but those who oppose me, die. Do you understand?', 'context': 'Yang Xiu shot a quick glance at Zhang Song, but Cao Cao went on, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 470, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister, I know well that when you march out your army, you always conquer. I knew it when you attacked Lu Bu at Puyang; and when you fought Zhang Xiu at Wancheng; and when you met Zhou Yu at the Red Cliffs; and when in Huarong Valley encountered Guan Yu; and on that day when you cut off your beard and threw away your robe at Tong Pass; and when you hid in a boat to escape the arrows on the River Wei. On all these occasions, no one could stand against you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'You stuck−up pedant! How dare you thus bring up all my failures?', 'context': 'It made Cao Cao very angry to be thus twitted with his misfortunes and he said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'You may behead him, but he came from the west bearing tribute, and his death would have a very evil effect on all distant peoples.', 'context': 'Yang Xiu ventured to argue with him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 395, 'talk': 'I did not expect such arrogance when I came with the intention of giving him a region. When I get back, Liu Zhang will expect great things. Now I am returning empty handed and a failure to endure the laughter of my fellow country people. I will not go back. I have heard of the virtues of Liu Bei, and I will go to him and see what manner of man he is. Then I can decide what to do.', 'context': 'Thought he, “'},
{'istart': 213, 'iend': 254, 'talk': 'Surely you are the Charioteer Zhang Song.', 'context': 'So with his little escort and following he made for Jingzhou. He had reached the boundaries of Wuchang when he met a body of horsemen, at the head of whom rode a general in simple undress, who pulled up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'I am he,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'I have expected you these many days. I am Zhao Yun.', 'context': 'The general quickly dismounted and humbly said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'No other,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'I am come because the world says Liu Bei is liberal and kindly disposed.', 'context': 'Zhang Song said, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'My brother sent me to meet you after your long and dusty journey and prepare the guest−house for your reception. My name is Guan Yu.', 'context': 'And the officer in command, bowing low, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Your exalted name has been long known to me;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 486, 'talk': 'it has reverberated through my ears. My one regret is that cloudy hills and long distances have hitherto prevented me from enjoying the advantage of your instruction. Hearing that you were passing through, I have come to meet you; and if you would be willing to notice me and condescend to rest for a time in my city, thus allowing me to satisfy my long disappointed desire to see you, I should indeed hold myself fortunate.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'How many counties are there in Jingzhou, where you are now, O Imperial Uncle?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'The South Land is large,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'yet their six territories and their eighty−one counties do not satisfy them. The people are strong and the land is fruitful.', 'context': ' said Zhang Song, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 274, 'talk': "Our lord, being of the dynastic family, has never occupied a territory of the empire. Those others, thievish as they are, may indeed seize upon as much territory as they are strong enough to hold, but such deeds are not according to the wise person's heart.", 'context': 'Said Pang Tong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Noble Sirs, pray say no more; what virtue have I that I should expect anything from the future?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Not so, indeed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Sir, you go too far; this really is too much.', 'context': 'Liu Bei deprecated such a suggestion, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'parting road', 'context': 'Western Land of Rivers. And when, at the end of that time, Zhang Song took leave, his host was at the three−mile “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'I am sincerely grateful that you deigned to come here. You have prolonged your visit to three days, but now the moment of parting has come. Who knows when I may have the privilege of receiving your instructions again?', 'context': 'When the moment came for the parting, Liu Bei raised his wine−cup and said, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'I have thought that I, too, would come to you one day, but so far I have found no way. In Jingzhou I see Sun Quan on the east, always ready to pounce; I see Cao Cao on the north, greedy to swallow. So this is not a wholly desirable place for you to remain in.', 'context': 'So he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I know this but too well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'but I have no secure place to go to.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'Yiazhou is well protected, has much fertile soil, is populous and well governed. Its scholars are attracted by your virtue. If you marched your armies westward, you could easily become a real power there and restore the glory of the Hans.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'But how dare I attempt this? The ruler is also of the Imperial House. The whole region is devoted to him for his good deeds, and no other person could attain such a hold.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'I am no traitor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 886, 'talk': 'but in your presence I feel constrained to be perfectly open and plain. Liu Zhang, the Imperial Protector of Yiazhou, is naturally weak and can neither use the wise nor employ the capable. Then again Zhang Lu threatens the north. People are distracted and would gladly welcome an appreciative ruler. The journey I have just made was to propose to support Cao Cao and place the region under him, but I found him rebellious and set on evil, proud and arrogant. So I have turned aside to you. If you will take Yiazhou, you will have a base from which to deal with Hanzhong when you will, and the whole country beside. You will continue the rightful line, and your name will live in history. Would not that be real fame? If then you think of taking our country, I am willing to do what little I can as an ally within. But do you contemplate such a step?', 'context': ' said Zhang Song, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'I am deeply grateful that you think so well of me. But the Imperial Protector being a member of the family, I should lay myself open to general execration, were I to attack him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 325, 'talk': 'When a hero finds himself in the world, his duty is to work out his destiny, to exert himself and perform his task as best as he can, to press forward among the foremost. At the moment the position is that, if you fail to seize this opportunity, some other will take possession of Yiazhou, and you will regret when too late.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'And I have heard much of the difficult nature of the country, its many high mountains and numerous streams, and its narrow roads. How could such a country be invaded?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'I am so deeply affected by your virtue that I offer you this map of the country, whereby its roads and rivers may be known.', 'context': 'Then Zhang Song drew the map from his sleeve, saying, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Sir, you can prepare your plans promptly. I have two friends who will certainly help you. And when they come to see you, you may be perfectly frank with them. Their names are Fa Zheng and Meng Da.', 'context': 'Zhang Song went on, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'As the blue mountains grow not old and the green waters always remain, so shall I never forget. And when I shall have accomplished my task, you shall have no mean reward.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'I look for no reward. Having met with an enlightened lord, I felt compelled to unbosom myself to him.', 'context': 'Replied Zhang Song, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'As for the man himself,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'he is a man to grieve with but not a person to rejoice with. I have promised Yiazhou to Liu Bei, the Imperial Uncle, and I want your especial advice and assistance.', 'context': ' said Zhang Song, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'I think Liu Zhang is incapable,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'and I have felt drawn to Liu Bei for some time past. So we are in sympathy here.', 'context': ' said Fa Zheng, “'},
{'istart': 172, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'I know what you two are about; you are scheming to hand over Yiazhou to somebody.', 'context': 'Shortly after Meng Da arrived. Meng Da and Fa Zheng were fellow townsmen. When Meng Da entered the room and saw the other two in earnest and secret conversation, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'It is really so; you have guessed right,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'But to whom ought it to go?', 'context': ' said Zhang Song. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'There is but one: Liu Bei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'You will see our lord tomorrow; what about that?', 'context': 'Then said Fa Zheng to Zhang Song, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'I shall recommend that you two be sent to Jingzhou on a mission.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is a rebel who desires to get the whole empire into his hands. I need hardly tell you that. But he also hankers after this region.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Then what will become of us?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'I have been thinking thus for a long−time; can you recommend a suitable emissary?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'The only ones are Fa Zheng and Meng Da.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 127, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'My lord, your land of forty−one counties will be lost to you and pass to another if you listen to Zhang Song.', 'context': 'While still discussing the details of the policy, a person forced his way in, his face all running with sweat, and cried out, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Why do you use such language? Liu Bei is of my family, and so I am seeking his support.', 'context': 'The Imperial Protector said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 798, 'talk': "I know all about him; he is liberal minded to gain people to his side, and his softness can overcome the hardest. He is bolder than any other. He gains humans' hearts from afar off, and those near him look up to him. He also has the wisest advisers and the boldest warriors. But if you call him here as a soldier, think you that he will be content to remain in a lowly condition? And if you treat him as an honored guest, can a state stand two rulers? Hear me, my lord, and you stand secure as Taishan Mountains; be deaf to my words, and your position is as precarious as a pile of eggs. This Zhang Song has lately come home through Jingzhou where he has certainly been plotting with Liu Bei. Slay this man; and make an end of Liu Bei. That will be for the happiness of this land.", 'context': 'Said Huang Quan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'But how else am I to fend off my two enemies?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Fortify your country, dig out your moats, and raise your ramparts. Then you can wait on events.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Not so; I make an alliance with Liu Bei in order to withstand Zhang Lu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 372, 'talk': "Zhang Lu's invasion would be but a skin disease. Liu Bei's entry into this country would be a mortal malady. Liu Bei is an unscrupulous brave; he was once in Cao Cao's service and plotted against him. Then he hung on to Sun Quan and seized Jingzhou. This shows his character and his designs. Think you that you two can dwell together? If you invite him, then Shu is lost!", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'No more wild talk!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is of my clan and family and will not ravish me of my possessions.', 'context': ' cried Liu Zhang angrily. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Friend, I have long admired you, and Zhang Song extolled your virtues. I shall always feel grateful for this opportunity of hearing you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 291, 'talk': "That is too great praise for a humble emissary from Shu. But they say that horses always neighed in recognition of Bo Le, the supreme judge of horses, and when a person has found his lord, he dies for him. Have you thought further of Zhang Song's proposals, General?", 'context': 'Fa Zheng bowed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 378, 'talk': 'I have always been a wanderer, often in suffering and sorrow. I have often thought of the wren for even that tiny bird has a twig to rest on; and of the cunning hare, that secures safety with three openings to its burrow. Does not a person need at least a shelter? Your land of the west is fertile and a temptation, but its ruler is of my family, and I cannot plot against him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 363, 'talk': 'Yes; Yiazhou is a very paradise. But without a ruler it cannot exist. Liu Zhang knows not how to use the wise people, and his heritage must speedily pass to another. Today it is offered to your hands, and you must not miss the opportunity. You know the saying, that the leader in the hunt gets the quarry. If you will only consent, I will serve you to the death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Let me reflect for a time and take advice.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'You must decide; not to decide is foolish. You are of high intelligence, my lord, and why do you hesitate?', 'context': 'Then Pang Tong said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'What should my reply be?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 346, 'talk': 'Now there are two men in the world as mutually antagonistic as fire and water. My opposite is Cao Cao. He is impetuous and I am long suffering; he is cruel and I am humane; he feigns while I am true. In all particulars I act the direct contrary to him. I refuse to risk the loss of the confidence and trust of the world for a trifling advantage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'These words are as jewels; they should be engraved on my very heart.', 'context': 'Liu Bei, a prey to confused emotions, replied, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'This is an important place and must be very well defended.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'I, Pang Tong, and my two generals Huang Zhong and Wei Yan will go into the west; you and our three best generals—Guan Yu, Zhang Fei, and Zhao Yun—can defend Jingzhou.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 185, 'talk': "My lord, if you go out, you will be exposed to danger. I have been in your service for many years, and I would prevent you from being the victim of another's wiles. I pray you reflect.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'His words are those of one who would sow discord in a family and encourage the power of the robbers who threaten you. Assuredly such action is to your detriment.', 'context': 'Zhang Song said, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I have decided, and why do you oppose me?', 'context': 'Liu Zhang then spoke angrily to Huang Quan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'My lord, do you neglect the loyal words of your faithful Huang Quan to go to your death?', 'context': 'As Liu Zhang was starting, another man cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'The prince may have ministers who remonstrate with him, and the father may have children who oppose,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'Huang Quan has spoken faithfully, and you ought to listen. To let Liu Bei into this land is to welcome the tiger into your gates.', 'context': ' said Li Hui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is my brother and will not harm me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'And any other who shall oppose me shall suffer death.', 'context': ' said the Imperial Protector. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'The officers of Shu regard the safety of their families and no longer render you service. The generals are arrogant, and each has some scheme of his own to further. If you do not get Liu Bei to oppose the enemy without and your own people oppose you within, surely you are on the road to ruin.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I know the plan is for my advantage.', 'context': 'So spoke Zhang Song, and the Imperial Protector replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Say nothing about this; after the two Lius have met, there may be opportunities, but this is too early to talk. Any plot would leak out.', 'context': 'Pang Tong said, “'},
{'istart': 503, 'iend': 772, 'talk': 'How ridiculous have been proved the fears of Huang Quan and Wang Lei! They do not understand the force of family affection. I see he is really a kindly and noble man, and with him as a support I shall fear neither Cao Cao nor Zhang Lu. And I owe all this to Zhang Song.', 'context': 'So nothing was said. Fucheng, where the meeting was to take place, was one hundred twenty miles from Capital Chengdu. Liu Zhang arrived first and sent messengers to welcome Liu Bei. The two armies camped on the bank of River Fu. Liu Bei went into the city to see the Imperial Protector, and they met cordially as brothers should. Both shed a few tears, and by and bye they began a heart−to−heart talk. Then followed a banquet, and after this each returned to his own camp. The Imperial Protector said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Do not rejoice too soon, O Master,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'You are all too anxious;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'my brother is no double−dealer, I am sure.', 'context': ' said Liu Zhang, laughing, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'He seems a very honest man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 436, 'talk': 'He is good enough, but some of his servants are discontented at this turn of affairs, and I would not guarantee there will be no murders. If you took my advice, you would have Liu Zhang assassinated at the return banquet. A hundred ruffians behind the arras, a signal from you, and the deed would be accomplished. All that would be needed, then would be a rush on Capital Chengdu. No sword need be drawn, no arrow fitted to the string.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'He is a brother of my house and has treated me with sincerity. I am a new−comer and so far unknown in this land. Such a deed would be abhorrent to all the world, and these people would resent it. I will not establish myself by such means.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'The scheme is not mine; it originated in a private letter from Zhang Song, who says it will have to be done some time.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'This is not for ourselves; it is the will of heaven.', 'context': 'At this moment Fa Zheng came in and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Liu Zhang and I are of the same house, and I would shudder at harming him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 233, 'talk': "Since our master will have nothing to do with our scheme, we would better set Wei Yan's sword−play to work and take advantage of the confusion to kill Liu Zhang.", 'context': 'All were mellow with wine, and Pang Tong, talking with Fa Zheng, said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'There being no other entertainment at this banquet, may I show you a little fencing to amuse you?', 'context': 'Wei Yan came in shortly afterward, with his sword drawn, and said, “'},
{'istart': 171, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'An opponent is needed to make fencing a success, so he and I will display our skill at the same time.', 'context': 'At these preparations the officers of Liu Zhang stared with questioning eyes toward the chief seats at the upper end, and one of them, Zhang Ren, drew his sword, saying, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'And we three will come in too; it may add to your amusement and help to raise a laugh.', 'context': 'At once three of the commanders of the west followed suit, saying, “'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 337, 'talk': 'We brothers have perhaps honored our meeting with a little too much wine; there is nothing to say against that, but this is no Hongmen Banquet, where murder was done. Put up your swords, or I will slay you!', 'context': 'But to Liu Bei matters began to take on a serious look. Drawing a sword of a servant, he stood out in the banquet hall and cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Why wear swords at all at a meeting of two brothers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 152, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'You need have no doubts; we two brothers, of the same bone and blood, have talked over the great design, and we are one in purpose.', 'context': 'Disarmed, they sulkily withdrew, and then Liu Bei called all the generals of Liu Zhang to the upper end of the banquet hall, gave them wine, and said, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Brother, I shall never forget your kindness.', 'context': 'Liu Zhang took his guest by the hand, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Why did you endeavor to force me into committing a great wrong?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'There must be no repetition of this.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'My brother is different from ordinary humans,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'He may not incline toward murder himself, but those about him have but one desire—that is to exploit this land of ours to their own advantage.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Do not try to sow dissension between us and make us quarrel,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 344, 'talk': 'I have an infallible plan to propose. Liu Bei and his army are now far away and separated from us by difficult country. Therefore he cannot return quickly, and my advice is to occupy the passes so that he cannot get through. Then send all your force against Jingzhou and Xiangyang, and they will surely fall to you.', 'context': 'Then Gu Yong spoke, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'The plan seems excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'You may just put to death the man who proposed that scheme for trying to compass the death of my daughter.', 'context': 'But just then a voice was heard from behind the screen, crying, “'},
{'istart': 132, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'What is to become of my only daughter, who is the wife of Liu Bei?', 'context': "Every one started with surprise. It was the Dowager Marchioness' voice. Further, Lady Wu looked very angry as she entered, saying, “"},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'You were heir to your father and brother and obtained possession of all these lands without the least effort. Yet you are dissatisfied and would forget the claims of your own flesh and blood and sacrifice your sister for the sake of adding a little to your lands.', 'context': 'She turned her wrathful eyes to Sun Quan and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 110, 'talk': "I would never think of going contrary to my mother's wishes and orders.", 'context': ' murmured Sun Quan, ashamed. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'This chance missed! When will Jingzhou be mine?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'What grieves my lord?', 'context': 'While still deep in reverie, Zhang Zhao came up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'No great matter; only this last failure to gain my ends.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'The difficulty may be easily removed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'That sounds like a good plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'Further, I have the man to carry it out successfully. He is that Zhou Shan, who was a bold one. He used to accompany my brother in his youth. He is the man to go.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Keep it a secret, then,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'and let Zhou Shan start quickly.', 'context': ' said Zhang Zhao, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'The Dowager Marchioness is really fretting for a sight of yours; and if you do not go quickly, it will be too late. The Dowager Marchioness also wants to see little Liu Shan once before she dies.', 'context': 'Zhou Shan invented a story, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'You know that the Imperial Uncle is far away on military service, and I ought to inform the chief of the army before returning home.', 'context': 'Lady Sun replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'But what will you do if the chief says he must inform your husband and await his consent?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'If I went without asking permission—but I fear that is impossible.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Do not start yet; let me bid my lady farewell.', 'context': 'But just as the ships were starting, a voice was heard, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Who are you that you dare hinder the movements of your mistress?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'My lady may go or not as she pleases,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'but I have one word to say to her.', 'context': ' cried he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Why this rude intrusion?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Whither may my mistress be going, and why goes she privily?', 'context': 'The warrior sheathed his sword and said humbly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'My mother is ill and on the point of death; I had no time to inform any person of my departure,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'But why take the young master if you are going merely to see a sick person?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Liu Shan is my son, and I would not leave him behind to be neglected.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'You leave my family affairs alone, you common soldier!', 'context': 'Lady Sun took refuge in anger. “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'My lady, if you will go, then go, but leave the young master behind.', 'context': ' cried she. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'You are a rebel, jumping on board the ship like that!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'If you will not leave the young lord behind, I refuse to let you go, come what may,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Sister−in−Law! Leave the child lord.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei also shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Why this very unseemly behavior?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Sister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'you thought very little of my brother when you set out on this mad journey. That was behaving rudely.', 'context': ' said Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'My mother is very ill; it is a matter of life and death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 217, 'talk': "If I had waited for your brother's permission to go, I should have been too late. If you do not let me go now, I will throw myself into the river.", 'context': ' cried she. “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 216, 'talk': "It is hardly the correct thing for servants to force their lord's wife into committing suicide. Suppose we keep the child and let the vessel go.", 'context': 'Zhao Yun and Zhang Fei took counsel together. They said to each other, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'O Lady, we cannot allow the wife of our exalted brother to die a death of shame, and so we will take our leave. We trust you will not forget our brother and that you will return quickly.', 'context': 'Then they said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Now that my sister has returned home, there is no longer any family tie to prevent the attack, and I will take full measure of revenge for the death of my general,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Zhang Hong was sincere till his death. I cannot withstand his last advice!', 'context': 'He told them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 257, 'talk': "One must prepare against possibilities. Soldiers vary in keenness and sometimes lose battles. If an urgent occasion arises, the soldiers may be unable to reach the water's edge, and how then are they to embark? They will then need shelter.", 'context': 'Lu Meng replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'How can we disappoint the hopes of many because of the words of one?', 'context': 'Dong Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I did not think to see this day!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 88, 'talk': "The enemy's fleet blankets the river, but no sign of movements.", 'context': 'Soon Cao Hong reported: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'That is the sort of son to have;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 106, 'talk': "not such piglets and puppies as Liu Biao'.", 'context': ' said Cao Cao in admiration, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'You blunt the keen spirits of the army; and if you do such a thing again, I will put you to death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'O Prime Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 371, 'talk': 'you who know so thoroughly the art of war, have you forgotten the maxim to strike quickly? You had your army ready, but you postponed action and allowed your enemies to build the ramparts at River Ruxu. Now you will find it hard to capture the place. It would be better now to retreat on the capital and await a more propitious moment.', 'context': ' said Cheng Yu, “'},
{'istart': 149, 'iend': 361, 'talk': 'Behold the all−powerful minister who holds the capital in the hollow of his hand! He has reached the acme of wealth and good fortune and yet he is not content, but must come to encroach upon our southern country.', 'context': 'Seeing his chief enemy, Sun Quan showed no sign of haste or dismay, but reined in his steed on a rise and, pointing with his whip at Cao Cao, said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'You are disobedient, and the command of the Emperor is to exterminate you!', 'context': 'Cao Cao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'What words!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'This Sun Quan certainly is no ordinary man, and by the presage of the sun in my dream he will become an emperor.', 'context': 'Alone in his camp, Cao Cao thought, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'But spring with its heavy rains is at hand, and you would be wise to retire while you can. If not, you may expect a repetition of the misfortune at the Red Cliffs. It would be well to consider this.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'No tranquillity for me while you live!', 'context': 'And on the back of the letter was a note in two lines running thus: “'},
{'istart': 147, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Sun Quan speaks the truth!', 'context': ' Cao Cao read the letter and laughed. “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 542, 'talk': 'If you undertake any expedition farther west, Cao Cao will undoubtedly return to the attack. Rather write two letters, one to Liu Zhang saying that Liu Bei has leagued himself with you against the west, which will raise suspicions in the mind of Liu Zhang and cause him to attack his guest, and another letter persuading Zhang Lu to march upon Jingzhou, which will uproot Liu Bei. Between these two conflicting matters, Liu Bei cannot give supports to all fronts, and we can march against Jingzhou.', 'context': 'Zhang Zhao proceeded to unfold his device: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'The victor, whoever it is, will assuredly possess himself of our region of Jingzhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'You need not trouble about that region,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 839, 'talk': "I do not think the South Land or the Middle Land will try to take it so long as Zhuge Liang is there. But, my lord, write to Liu Zhang telling him you wish to return on account of this threatening danger. It will be a plausible excuse. You may say that on account of Cao Cao's attack, Sun Quan has sent to you for help, and that as his country and yours are neighbors and dependent upon each other for safety you cannot refuse. Further, you will assure him that there is no danger of any invasion by Zhang Lu. However, we have too few troops for our purpose and insufficient grain, so you must also urge your relative to send you thirty or forty thousand of veterans and a plentiful supply of food. He will not refuse, and with more soldiers and provisions we can do as we please.", 'context': ' said Pang Tong. “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Why did you come with the messenger?', 'context': 'After reading the letter, the Imperial Protector asked Yang Huai, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Only because of that letter,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 339, 'talk': 'This Liu Bei, from the day he first entered Yiazhou, has been trying to win over the hearts of your people by a display of kindness and virtue. He certainly intends no good, and I think you should refuse both the troops and the supplies he asks. To help him is like adding fuel to a fire.', 'context': ' Yang Huai replied. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'We are affectionate brothers, and I must help him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is nothing but a vagabond swashbuckler,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'and if you keep him here in the west, you are loosing a tiger in your household. If you give him the troops and supplies he asks, you are adding wings to your tiger.', 'context': ' some one cried, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'I have been spending myself in your defense, and this is my reward! You are mean and greedy enough to stint my supplies. How can you expect generous service?', 'context': "When Liu Bei read the letter that accompanied the Imperial Protector's miserable contribution to his strength, he was furious and cried, “"},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'You have hitherto laid too much stress on humanity and righteousness. However, that is all over now, and all affection between you two is at an end, now that you have torn up that letter.', 'context': 'Then said Pang Tong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Yes. And since that is so, what next?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I have three schemes ready in my mind. You may choose which pleases you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'What are your three schemes?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 604, 'talk': 'The first, and best, is to send an army forthwith and seize Chengdu. The second is to capture and put to death the two generals of the River Fu Pass. They are the two most famous fighting men in this land. If you give out that you are returning to Jingzhou, they will assuredly come to say farewell. Seize and put them to death, and the Pass and Fucheng are both yours. Chengdu will follow soon. The third plan is to drop this role you have been playing, go back to Jingzhou and make a regular invasion. But if you ponder these schemes too long, you will get into such straits that nothing can save you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Of your three schemes, O Instructor, I find the first too summary and the last too slow. I choose the second scheme, which is neither.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I knew that the real desire of Liu Bei was to return to Jingzhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': "This plot of my brother's will end in the destruction of the whole family,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'I must get in the first word.', 'context': ' said Zhang Su. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'I have always treated your brother so well!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'What is the real meaning of this retirement?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'This Liu Bei ought to die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 157, 'talk': "Let us hide daggers under our dress and stab him at the place of farewell. That will end all our lord's troubles.", 'context': ' said Gao Pei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'A most excellent plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'That means a surprise; those two intend to assassinate you, so be on your guard.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'We hear, O Imperial Uncle, that you contemplate a long march, and therefore we come to offer a few poor gifts to speed you on your way.', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'You have a heavy responsibility to defend the Pass, Generals. I pray you drink first.', 'context': 'The cups of farewell were duly filled. Then Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'I have a secret matter to talk over with you.', 'context': 'They drank. Then Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'My generals, lay hands upon these two rebels!', 'context': 'As soon as they had gone, Liu Bei shouted, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'Your lord and I are of the same house;', 'context': 'taken aback, but began to struggle. However, Liu Feng and Guan Ping each seized one man and held him. “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'Your leaders conspired to sow dissension between brothers and were found with daggers hidden beneath their clothing. They were assassins in intent and have met the fate they merited. You have committed no crime and need feel no alarm.', 'context': 'Liu Bei summoned the soldiers of the escort to his tent, gave them wine to comfort them, and said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'If you will now show the way so that our troops may capture the Pass, you shall even be rewarded.', 'context': 'Then said Pang Tong, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'This is what one might call a joyful occasion.', 'context': 'At one of these feasts, Liu Bei turned to his adviser, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'To employ warlike weapons in making an attack upon the possession of another is not using them in the best way,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'Nor is such attack the most proper occasion for rejoicing.', 'context': ' replied Pang Tong. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'The success of King Wu of Zhou was celebrated with music; I suppose weapons were not well used on that occasion either. Why do you talk so wide of reason? You would better retire.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'I drank too much last night and spoke rudely; pray forget it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Really I was the only one to blame yesterday.', 'context': 'Pang Tong, who had taken the whole episode in very good part from the first, laughed and talked as usual. But Liu Bei went on, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'We both slipped up; it was not only you, my lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 7, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Let us send without delay a force to hold Luocheng, which is the very throat of the road he must take. He may have veteran soldiers and fiery generals, but he will not be able to pass.', 'context': 'said, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 237, 'talk': "In the Silky Hills there is a wonderful Taoist who calls himself 'The Super Human of the Dark Void.' He has the gift of second sight, so let us visit him as we pass and inquire what our fortunes are to be.", 'context': 'As they marched, Liu Gui said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'What should one seek of a hermit when one is out to repulse an enemy?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Your view is wrong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'The Holy One ((Confucius)) has said that it is characteristic of the most entire sincerity to be able to foreknow. So let us inquire of this man of high intelligence that we may know what to do and what to avoid.', 'context': ' said Liu Gui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'How can a poor Taoist recluse know ought of fortunes, good or evil?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'One must have faith in such as he says,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'What is to be gained by listening to the sayings of a daft old man?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'Liu Zhang has sent four generals to the defense of that city, and two camps has been established twenty miles away to form an ox horn.', 'context': 'The scouts reported: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Veteran General, take your own troops and go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'A goodly reward shall be yours if you capture the two camps.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'The General is too old to go on such an expedition; I am of poor ability, but I wish to take his place.', 'context': 'Huang Zhong thanked his lord and was just leading away his troops when suddenly up spoke a youthful leader, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'I already have my commission; why should you wish to supplant me?', 'context': 'Huang Zhong replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': "Because the task is beyond an old man's strength,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 353, 'talk': "The two generals in those camps we know are the best and boldest in the country. They are strong, and, veteran as you are, I fear you will be unable to overcome them. If you fail, our lord's great design will be hindered. Therefore I ask that I may replace you, and my intent is kindly.", 'context': ' said Wei Yan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Old, am I? Dare you compete with me in the use of warlike weapons?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Yes; I dare. And our lord shall be the judge. The winner shall undertake this expedition. Do you agree?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'You two must not quarrel,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 279, 'talk': 'But as there are two camps to be taken and two generals to fight, take one each and let each lead his own troops. The first to capture his camp shall be held to have rendered the greater service and to have acquired the greater merit.', 'context': ' said Pang Tong. “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'You, my lord, should follow them lest they should quarrel on the way.', 'context': 'But after they had marched away, Pang Tong recommended, “'},
{'istart': 149, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'General Huang Zhong is here!', 'context': "Ling Bao, Deng Xian's colleague, rode up quickly to his rescue, but just then a body of horse came dashing down the hill, and their leader shouted, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Whither would you come?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'The camp is ours; I have captured it.', 'context': ' cried Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 284, 'iend': 454, 'talk': 'You soldiers have parents and wives and little ones at home, and those who wish to return to them are free to go. If any wish to join my army, they also will be received.', 'context': 'Liu Bei had hoisted the flag of amnesty for his enemies, and whenever any soldier of the Western Land of Rivers laid down his weapons and stripped off his armor he was spared. Also all the wounded were granted life. Liu Bei told his enemies that they had liberty of choice. He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Since you give me my life, I can do no other,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'Moreover, my two companions, Liu Gui and Zhang Ren, and I are sworn to live or die together. If you will release me, I will return and bring them also to you and therewith you will get possession of Luocheng.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Do not let him go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'If you do, you will never see him again.', 'context': ' said Wei Yan. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'If I treat humans with kindness and justice, they will not betray my trust.', 'context': 'Liu Bei replied, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'I slew many of the enemy and escaped by mounting the steed of one of them.', 'context': 'So the prisoner was set free. When Ling Bao reached the city and saw his two friends, he told them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'Father, let me go to defend Luocheng.', 'context': 'Then his eldest son, Liu Xun, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'You may go, my son, but who is there to go with you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'If the enemy draw near to the walls, it will be hard to drive them off again. What do you two think should be done?', 'context': 'Wu Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'The city lies along River Fu and the current is strong. The enemy camp lies low at the foot of the hills; and with five thousand people I can cut the river banks, flood their camp, and drown Liu Bei and his army with him.', 'context': 'Ling Bao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'If they do that, I am taken in the rear and helpless in both advance and retreat,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'What do you counsel, O Instructor?', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'You are a native of Shu and well skilled in its topography; what can be done to make the Pass secure?', 'context': 'Pang Tong turned to Meng Da, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Let me take a certain man with me, and I will defend it myself and answer for its safety.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Who is he?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'He was formerly an officer under Liu Biao. His name is Huo Jun, and he is a native of Nanjun in the south.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Who may you be, Master?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Do let me rest a little; then I will talk with you about everything in the world.', 'context': 'Pressed again, the visitor said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Surely it can be no other than Peng Yang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'I hope you have been well since we parted last!', 'context': 'Fa Zheng went inside and looked. Immediately the visitor jumped up, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': "To save a myriad of your soldiers' lives. I will explain fully when I see General Liu Bei.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'How many troops have you, General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I treated you generously and set you free; you repaid me with ingratitude. I cannot forgive again.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'I will return myself to Jingzhou and discuss the matter.', 'context': 'Having read this and sent Ma Liang away, Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 193, 'iend': 410, 'talk': 'I also have made calculations, and I read the signs to mean that the time is favorable for you to get possession of this land, and no evil is foreshown. Therefore be not of doubtful heart, my lord, but advance boldly.', 'context': "But Pang Tong, who thought in his heart that Zhuge Liang's warning was due to a jealous desire to prevent him from winning the glory of conducting a victorious campaign, opposed this, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'There will be opposition on the high road, and you are the best to deal with it. Let me take the by−road.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'No; this does not suit me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'A spirit bearing a massive iron club appeared to me in a dream and struck my right arm, so that I suffered great pain. I feel sure this expedition will turn out badly.', 'context': ' replied Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'When a soldier goes into battle, he may be killed, or he may be wounded; he accepts whichever is his fate. But should one hesitate because of a dream?', 'context': 'Pang Tong replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'The real reason of my hesitation is the letter from Zhuge Liang. Wherefore I wish you to remain and guard River Fu Pass. Do you agree to that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 423, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang has indeed filled your mind with doubts. The real thing is that he is unwilling to let me have the merit of accomplishing a great undertaking alone. That is why he has written this. And your doubts and hesitations have produced the dream. But I see nothing ill−omened, and I am prepared for any sacrifice and mean just what I say. Pray, my lord, say no more, but prepare to set forth.', 'context': 'Pang Tong smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Why do you ride this wretched beast?', 'context': 'Liu Bei jumped down and seized the horse by the bridle, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I have ridden him a long time, and he has never done this before,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': "A shying steed risks a person's life,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I am deeply affected by your kindness,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'I know a by−road on the east which is of great importance, and I pray you let me guard it while you two hold the city.', 'context': "When the news of Ling Bao's capture and death reached Luocheng, Wu Yi and Liu Gui took counsel together. Their colleague, Zhang Ren, said, “"},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'That surely is Liu Bei on the white horse.', 'context': 'The soldiers in ambush saw a rider on a fine white horse and pointed him out to one another, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'I will rescue you, Wei Yan!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 263, 'talk': 'Now that our leader is no more, certainly the enemy will return to attack the Pass. What is to be done? I think we would better send to Jingzhou for Zhuge Liang and get him to lay plans for getting possession of the Western Land of Rivers.', 'context': 'Then said Huang Zhong, “'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'We have suffered a severe check, and the soldiers are low−spirited. Let us rather remain on the defensive until the Directing Instructor can arrive.', 'context': 'Huang Zhong and Wei Yan wished to go forth to fight, but Liu Bei disapproved, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'Alas! Alas!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'My lord has lost an arm!', 'context': 'Again he fell to weeping. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'We shall hear the sad news in a very few days,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'I must go to help our lord; he is hemmed in at the Pass and cannot move.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'If you go away, who will guard this region?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'It is of very great importance.', 'context': ' asked Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Our lord has not written plainly, but I know what was in his mind.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 417, 'talk': 'Provision for the defense of this region is laid upon me, and I am to find one equal to the task. I read the letter to mean that he desires Guan Yu to undertake the defense, and I know that Guan Yu will do it for the sake of the pledge taken long ago in the Peach Garden. The task is no light one.', 'context': ' Then he showed the letter to the others and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'All the future rests with you, General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'When a person of honor accepts such a task, he is only released by death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'death', 'context': 'But that ill−omened word “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Now if Cao Cao attack what is to be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Repel him with all my strength.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'But if Cao Cao and Sun Quan attack you together, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Fight both; half my force against each.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'In that case, Jingzhou would be in danger. I will give you my advice in a few words, and if you remember them the region is safe.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'What are these few words?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'North, fight Cao Cao; south, ally with Sun Quan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'These words, O Commander, are engraved on my heart.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 410, 'talk': 'Do not think lightly of the soldiers of Yiazhou, for there are many mighty warriors among them. On the march restrain your soldiers from plunder and license lest the ordinary people be against us. Wherever you halt, be compassionate and kindly and do not give way to anger and flog your soldiers. I shall expect you to reach Luocheng very soon.', 'context': 'Just before leaving, the Directing Instructor said to Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Tell the old fool to give in, or I will trample down his walls and leave no soul alive.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei said, “'},
{'istart': 130, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'This is like calling a tiger to protect one when one is alone on a bare hill side.', 'context': "Yan Yan had never favored inviting Liu Bei into Yiazhou. When he had first heard of the Imperial Protector's intention, he said, “"},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'Fool that you are! How dare you speak thus to me? Think you that I, General Yan Yan, will surrender to such as him. By your mouth indeed will I send a message.', 'context': 'But the Governor was exceedingly angry and said, “'},
{'istart': 282, 'iend': 354, 'talk': 'I will capture you yet, you old fool, and then I will devour your flesh!', 'context': "Next day Zhang Fei again led his troops to the foot of the wall and challenged; again the challenge was refused. But Yan Yan shot an arrow from the tower that struck Zhang Fei's helmet. This angered him still more, and pointing the finger of disdain at his enemy, Zhang Fei cried, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'The old fool! Assuredly I shall die of disappointed wrath,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'General, do not let your heart be hot within you. These last few days we have discovered a narrow road by which we can sneak past this city.', 'context': 'And one of them said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Why did you not come and tell me before?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Because we have only lately discovered it,', 'context': ' cried he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I will lose no time then,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'This very night let food be ready at the second watch, and we will break camp and steal away as silently as possible. I will lead the way, and you shall go with me as guides.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I guessed right, then,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 570, 'talk': "I cannot bear the fool. He will now try to sneak past with his commissariat following, and I will cut off his rear. How can he get through? He is very stupid to fall thus into my trap. All are to prepare for battle; the food is to be ready at the second watch, and the army is to move out at the third; we will hide in the woods and thickets till the greater part of the enemy's army has passed and Zhang Fei has arrived in the very throat of the road. Then the blow will be struck.", 'context': ' said Yan Yan gleefully when the spies reported their success. “'},
{'istart': 170, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'Old rebel, do not flee! I have been waiting for this chance a long time.', 'context': 'The western troops began to plunder. But suddenly a gong clanged and along came a company of soldiers Yan Yan had not seen. At the same time a voice was heard shouting, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Why did you not surrender at first?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'How dared you try to oppose me?', 'context': ' cried Zhang Fei, angrily grinding his teeth. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Because you are a lot of unrighteous and lawless invaders!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'You may behead me as you will, but I will not surrender to you.', 'context': ' replied Yan Yan without the least sign of fear. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Strike, if you want to, fool; why so angry?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'I have always known you were a hero. Now I pray you not remember against me the roughness of my speech.', 'context': 'When Yan Yan was seated, Zhang Fei made a low bow, saying, “'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 455, 'talk': 'All the fortified posts between this and Luocheng are under my control, and the commanders of all the garrisons owe to me their commissions. The only way for me to prove my gratitude is to make them all yield, as I myself have done. Let me lead the advance, and I will summon them one by one to surrender.', 'context': 'As stated in the last chapter, Zhang Fei asked Yan Yan to tell him how he might conquer the whole of the Western Land of Rivers. This was the reply: “'},
{'istart': 221, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'You see I have submitted; how much more ought you to do so?', 'context': 'Zhang Fei thanked him again and again, and the march on this plan began. Whenever the army arrived at a post, Yan Yan summoned the commander, and there it ended. Occasionally, one would hesitate, when Yan Yan would say, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Day after day the enemy has come to challenge us, and day after day we have refused. They must have grown lax, and I propose a night raid on their camp. We shall catch them unprepared and shall score a victory.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'An ambush in front; pursuers in rear! Surely Heaven wishes to destroy me!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 84, 'talk': "General, my brother's speedy arrival is certainly owing to your help.", 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'Tomorrow I will go and challenge them. If they accept and come out to fight, I will feign retreat and inveigle them round to the north side of the city. As they follow me, a sortie must be made when they pass the gate so as to cut their army in two. We ought to overcome them in this way.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Let me lead the sortie,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 110, 'talk': "General Liu Gui can stay to help our lord's son Liu Xun guard the city.", 'context': ' said Wu Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Where is the Directing Instructor?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'He has arrived; I think he has already seen our lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'How comes it that you arrived before me?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang was surprised, and said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Why not, seeing I am a prisoner?', 'context': 'Wu Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'The son of the Imperial Protector, Liu Xun, and his generals Liu Gui and Zhang Ren are the defenders. Liu Gui does not count for much, but Zhang Ren is a man to be avoided.', 'context': 'Wu Yi told him the names of the officers, saying, “'},
{'istart': 226, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'Then before we can get the city we must capture Zhang Ren,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 305, 'iend': 354, 'talk': 'There is a bridge on the east; what is it called?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 167, 'talk': "Dare you withstand me and not surrender when Cao Cao's million troops fled at my name?", 'context': 'Having crossed the bridge, Zhuge Liang halted and pointed to Zhang Ren, saying, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 126, 'talk': "People talk of Zhuge Liang's superhuman military genius; I say his reputation is false.", 'context': 'With a cynical smile, Zhang Ren said, “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 175, 'talk': 'Why have you held out so long after all the other generals of Yiazhou have yielded?', 'context': 'When the leader Zhang Ren was led in by Zhang Fei, Zhuge Liang was seated beside his lord. “'},
{'istart': 192, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'Can a loyal servant take a second master?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'You do not know the times; submission means life.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'I might submit today, but it would not endure. I should repent it. You would better slay me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Our next city is Chengdu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 478, 'talk': 'However, in the meantime there may be some trouble in pacifying the outlying counties, and hence it will be well for you to send Zhang Fei and Zhao Yun with Wu Yi, Zhang Yi, Yan Yan, and Zhuo Ying leading the way, into the country along the river and Changyang, Deyang, and Baxi to reassure the people and to repress any rising that may take place. There will be no need for any especial precautions in the neighborhood of Chengdu.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'The only place where you can expect any serious defense is Mianzhu. Once you have passed this, the capital lies at your mercy.', 'context': 'Those who had given in their allegiance to the invaders said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 269, 'talk': 'With the fall of Luocheng, the Western Land of Rivers passed to you. Let our lord only deal with the people kindly and justly, and there will be no need of weapons. I can write such a letter to Imperial Protector Liu Zhang as shall make him surrender at call.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'That would be most excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 597, 'talk': 'Although Liu Bei has been successful and captured cities and towns, yet his army is but small, his hosts are not near him, and he depends upon chance for his grain and has no proper supplies. Therefore our best plan is to remove the people of Baxi and Zitong to the farther side of River Fu, burn all the granaries, fortify the city, and let starvation defeat him. Let us reject all challenges to battle, and in a hundred days his troops will go off of their own accord. Then we can do with him as we will.', 'context': 'The Imperial Protector at once called his counselors together, and Adviser Zheng Du said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'I like not the plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 250, 'talk': 'Oppose invaders in order that tranquillity may prevail is a well−worn maxim, but till now I have never heard of disturbing the people in order to oppose the march of an enemy. Your words are not such as safety.', 'context': ' said Liu Zhang. “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'That traitor, ingrate, and renegade! How dares he talk thus to me?', 'context': 'Liu Zhang flew into a passion. He tore the letter to fragments and began to abuse its writer, crying, “'},
{'istart': 143, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'It will be useless to try to obtain help from a region under the influence of our relentless enemy Zhang Lu.', 'context': 'At this juncture Dong He, the Governor of Yiazhou City, wrote advising to borrow aid from Hanzhong, but Liu Zhang rejected this plan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'He may be an enemy, but Liu Bei is in possession of Luocheng, and the situation is extremely dangerous. When the lips are gone, the teeth are cold. If you clearly indicate the dangers to him, he must come to our help.', 'context': 'Dong He replied, “'},
{'istart': 145, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'We cannot surrender to a lot of rebels such as are Ma Chao and his colleagues.', 'context': 'Wei Kang was in despair, and at a council his officers advised him to yield. However, one of them, Yang Fu, earnestly opposed yielding, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What is there to hope for?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'You only yield now as the last resource,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'This is no real submission.', 'context': ' cried Ma Chao, angry at the delay he had suffered. “'},
{'istart': 197, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'Yang Fu had but done his duty.', 'context': 'But when one told Ma Chao that Yang Fu had been really responsible for the long delay, in that Yang Fu had urged his master to hold out, Ma Chao did not put him to death but praised him and said, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'My wife has died in Lintao; I wish to take leave for two months to bury her.', 'context': 'One day Yang Fu went to his new chief and said, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 363, 'talk': 'Behold an unfortunate man! The city I had to defend is lost; my master is dead; and I have survived him. I am ashamed to look you in the face. Now this Ma Chao ravages the countryside, and everyone hates him. Yet my cousin sits still and does nothing against Ma Chao. Is this fitting conduct for a state servant?', 'context': 'When Yang Fu saw her, he wept before her, saying, “'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'You are the cause of the evil that has come upon the noble Wei Kang.', 'context': 'Yang Fu wept bitterly. The old lady was moved by his grief, called in her son and said to him reproachfully, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'But what can now be done? You have surrendered and, more than that, you have accepted service under your late enemy.', 'context': 'Then turning once more toward Yang Fu, she said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'It is true,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'I have surrendered and I have accepted service, but it is with the desire to preserve my miserable life till I can avenge my master.', 'context': ' replied Yang Fu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'A bold man is Ma Chao, and difficult to destroy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'Not very difficult,', 'context': ' said Jiang Xu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'for though he is bold, yet he is unskillful. Already I have two friends Liang Kuan and Zhao Qu by his side, and they would help against him if you, my brother, would only supply a force.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'What is to be gained by delay?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 318, 'talk': 'Is there any who will not have to die? To perish in the way of loyalty and righteousness is to die in the right path. Do not think of me, for if you do, and heed not the call of your cousin, then will I die at once so that you may be free to make up your mind.', 'context': ' then said the old lady. “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 254, 'talk': "I have today been led into a scheme to destroy Ma Chao and avenge Wei Kang. But there is our son there in Ma Chao's service, and Ma Chao will certainly put our son to death as soon as he hears that we are arming against him. What is to be done?", 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'Should anyone grudge even his life to avenge his liege lord or his father? How much less a son? My lord, if you let the thought of your son stay your hand, then will I die forthwith.', 'context': 'But his wife replied angrily, “'},
{'istart': 430, 'iend': 452, 'talk': 'Wicked traitor! Rebel!', 'context': 'The fears of Zhao Ang concerning the fate of his son were only too soon justified. At the first news of the march of an army against him, Ma Chao beheaded the young Zhao Yue. Then Ma Chao marched his force, together with Pang De and Ma Dai, to Licheng, and the troops under Jiang Xu and Yang Fu went out to oppose it. The two leaders on the avenging side went to battle dressed in mourning white. They railed at Ma Chao, crying, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'I have neither the credit of a successful defense nor the merit of death with my master. Death should be my portion rather than honors. How could I accept the offer?', 'context': 'But Yang Fu declined the honor, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 151, 'talk': "The misfortune that befell Ma Chao's wife and family was entirely the fault of his own misconduct. Would you give your daughter to such as he to wife?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'The Eastern and Western Lands of Rivers, which stand next each other as the lips are close to the teeth, are interdependent. If Yiazhou is lost, Hanzhong has little chance to survive. On the other hand, once relieved by your help, Imperial Protector Liu Zhang will reward twenty counties to Hanzhong as compensation.', 'context': 'Huang Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 159, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Useless I may be, but if you will give me troops, I will capture this Liu Bei and you will retain all your land.', 'context': "Yan Pu, one of Zhang Lu's officers, tried to dissuade him by pointing out the old enmity between him and Liu Zhang, but another suddenly interjected, saying, “"},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 340, 'talk': 'I have been the recipient of much kindness from my lord, which I feel I can never repay adequately. Now let me lead an army to take Jiameng Pass and capture Liu Bei. Then, my lord, Liu Zhang will surely lose his twenty counties, and they shall be yours.', 'context': 'It was Yan Pu who thus opposed sending help to Liu Zhang. Then Ma Chao rose and said, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 274, 'talk': 'Zheng Du advised Liu Zhang to set fire to all the plains and valleys between the capital and the invaders, as well as the granaries, to move sway the people, and to stand solely on the defensive.', 'context': 'Meanwhile, the messenger sent by Fa Zheng had returned to Luocheng to report: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Do not be anxious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'the plan would be extremely harmful, but it will not be carried out. Liu Zhang will not do that.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Now let us capture Mianzhu quickly, for, that done, Chengdu is as good as ours.', 'context': 'Then said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'O Instructor, why did you sound the retirement just as I was getting the better of my opponent?', 'context': 'When Huang Zhong had got back to his side again, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'Because I saw that Li Yan was not to be overcome by mere force. Tomorrow you shall fight again, and then you shall lead him into the hills by the ruse of pretended defeat. There will be a surprise awaiting him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'You would better yield; if not, there are bows and crossbows on both sides of you—all ready to avenge the death of our Pang Tong.', 'context': "But he found Wei Yan's troops drawn up across his path, while Zhuge Liang from a hill top near by cried, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Though he is related to Liu Zhang, yet Fei Guan and I are very close friends. Let me go and persuade him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'We need both Zhang Fei and Zhao Yun for this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'But Zhao Yun is away,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'However, Zhang Fei is here. Let us send him quickly.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Do not say anything, my lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Let me stir him to fight his noblest.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Why do you despise me, O Instructor?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Did I not once drive back a whole army with my mere voice? Think you that I mind a stupid fool like Ma Chao?', 'context': ' cried Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 481, 'talk': 'Yes, Zhang Fei; but when you forced back the waters and broke the bridge in the Long Slope, you succeeded because your enemies were doubtful. If they had known, General, you would not have come off so easily. All the world knows this Ma Chao and has heard about his six battles at River Wei; and how he made Cao Cao cut off his beard and throw away his robe. Ma Chao very nearly slew Cao Cao too. This is no lightsome task like that, and even Guan Yu might fail.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'All I care for is to go, and if I do not overcome this fellow, I will take the consequences.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'Well, if you will put that in writing, you may lead the attack. And I will ask our lord to lead another army to back you up this time. He can leave the defense of this town to me till Zhao Yun returns.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'I also want to go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Who are you? Tell your name,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'then I may fight with you.', 'context': ' cried Zhang Fei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I am Ma Dai of Xiliang.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'How dare you treat me with contempt?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Do not pursue, my brother.', 'context': 'Zhang Fei was about to pursue when a rider came up to him hastily, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'He justifies what people say,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Handsome Ma Chao.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Do you know who I am?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I am Zhang Fei of Yan!', 'context': ' shouted Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'My family having been noble for many generations; I am not likely to know any rustic dolts!', 'context': 'Ma Chao replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'A veritable tiger of a leader,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'You would better retire for today; he is a terrible opponent. Try him again tomorrow.', 'context': 'It was then getting late, and Liu Bei said to his brother, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': "But Zhang Fei's spirit was roused, and was it likely that such advice would be palatable? “"},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'I will die and not come back!', 'context': ' shouted he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'But it is late; you cannot go on fighting,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Let them bring torches, and we will have a night battle,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Dare you try a night battle, Zhang Fei?', 'context': 'Ma Chao having mounted a fresh steed, now rode out and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'If I do not capture you, I will not go back to the Pass,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'And if I do not overcome you, I will not return to the camp,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Whither are you going?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'Note well, O Ma Chao, that I, who have never treated people other than with kindness and justice and truth and sincerity, swear that I will not take advantage of your period of repose to pursue or attack. Wherefore you may rest awhile in peace.', 'context': 'Then Liu Bei came out to the front of his battle line and called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 297, 'talk': 'He is the most terrible leader of the age; if he fights a desperate battle with Zhang Fei, loss of a general will ensue. So I have come as quickly as I could. I left Mianzhu in the safe hands of Zhao Yun and Huang Zhong. I think I have a little ruse left that will bring Ma Chao over to our side.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Now I have seen the man. I greatly admire him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'If we could only win him over!', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Then listen, my lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'He is an Imperial Uncle;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'with such a rank he could present such a memorial.', 'context': ' said Yang Song, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'This Ma Chao is untrustworthy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'He will not withdraw his soldiers because he contemplates rebellion. That is the real reason.', 'context': ' said Yang Song. “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'Ma Chao desires to make himself the ruler of the west and has said that he will no longer be content with subordinate rank. And he means to avenge the death of his father.', 'context': 'Yang Song set stories afloat rumoring: “'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 595, 'talk': "Give Ma Chao a limit of a month in order to accomplish his task, provided he consents to three conditions. And if he does not agree, he will have to be put to death. The three conditions are the capture of the Western Land of Rivers, the head of Liu Zhang, and the repulse of the Jingzhou troops. If he fails in any one of these, just bring his head. Meanwhile, Zhang Wei should be sent as guard at one of the strategic points which will control Ma Chao's army in case of rebellion.", 'context': 'The rumors came to the ear of Zhang Lu, and he asked Yang Song what should be done. Yang Song proposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'What can such a charge mean?', 'context': 'When Ma Chao heard the three demands made on him, he was greatly troubled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 210, 'talk': "Ma Chao's return with an army will be a danger, and hence all the points of vantage on the homeward road must be guarded so that to stop him.", 'context': 'But Yang Song had not yet attained his end, so he said to Zhang Lu, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Now is my chance to use my little three inches of unworn tongue; Ma Chao is in a fix. I am going to his camp to persuade him to come over to your side.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said to his lord, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'But I do not like you to run such a risk, Instructor. You are my most necessary support, and if anything happened to you, what should I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'You once pleaded with your master to keep me out; why are you here now?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 382, 'talk': 'Because the prudent bird chooses its perch and the wise person his master. I did attempt to dissuade Liu Zhang of Yiazhou from a course which I felt to be disastrous, and thereby fulfilled my duty as his servant. He rejected my counsel, and I knew he would fail. Your liberality, O General, has won over all the region, and success must be yours. I wish to serve under your banner.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Your services will surely be of great advantage to me, Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'I knew him when we were in Longxi together. He is now in great straits, and I may be able to talk him over. What say you?', 'context': 'Then Li Hui began to talk of Ma Chao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Just the man to go instead of me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'But what arguments will you use?', 'context': ' interjected Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'What are you come for?', 'context': 'spoke roughly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'I am here as persuader.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'This sword here in the scabbard is newly ground. You may try me by words, but if the words do not penetrate, I shall ask you to try the sword.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'O, General, evil is not far off. However, I am thinking the newly ground sword will not be tried on my head. You will want to try it on your own!', 'context': 'Li Hui smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'What evil were you talking about?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 790, 'talk': "The worst vilification could not hide the beauty of Lady Xi Shi of Yue, nor could the most fulsome praise gloze over the ugliness of Lady Wuyan of Qi ((two states of old)). The sun rises to the meridian and then declines; the moon waxes to the full and then wanes. All things obey the one law. Now, General, you are at enmity with Cao Cao for your father's death, and in Longxi you carry a stubborn, grinding hate for your family's death. You can neither rescue Liu Zhang by repulsing the army from Jingzhou, nor can you settle Yang Song by getting an interview with Zhang Lu. The whole world now holds no place for a person without a lord; and if you experience further defeats, like that one on River Wei, or the loss of Jicheng, will you not be too shamed to look any human in the face?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'You speak well, Sir. But I am helpless.', 'context': 'Ma Chao bowed his head, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Now that you listen to me, I would ask why those fearsome ruffians are in hiding by your tent?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Meeting you, O Illustrious Lord, is like seeing the clear sky when the clouds have been swept aside.', 'context': 'Ma Chao bowed his head, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Let not my lord attack,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'I will make Liu Zhang surrender of his own accord. Should he resist, my brother Ma Dai and I will take the city and offer it to you with both hands.', 'context': ' said Ma Chao. “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I wish to speak with Liu Zhang.', 'context': 'And Ma Chao called out, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'I am stupid and I am sorry. Better open the gates and end it. The city will be saved.', 'context': 'When he came to his senses, he muttered, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'There are thirty thousand of good soldiers in the city and ample money and stores for a year to come. Hold out!', 'context': ' cried Dong He. “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 357, 'talk': 'My father and I have ruled Shu for twenty years and have done no particular good for the people. And we have fought for three years; the grass has been be stained with the blood of my people; and the fault is mine. I could not bear it, and so I see no better way than to surrender, whereby I may bring peace to the people.', 'context': 'But Liu Zhang was broken, saying, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'You speak as Heaven guides you.', 'context': 'Those about him wept. One man spoke, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'None can withstand the decree of the Most High.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 224, 'iend': 373, 'talk': 'You have got your wish, wretched creature, and you seem to think there is no one to compare with you. But do not look so contemptuously at us of Shu.', 'context': 'and he was even then at the city gate. Jian Yong was admitted, and he entered, riding in a carriage and looking about him most haughtily. Suddenly he was hailed from the street by a man with a sword in his hand, who cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Worthy brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'I did not recognize you. I pray you not to be angry.', 'context': ' said Jian Yong, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'It is not that I wish to act cruelly or wrongly; I am the victim of circumstances and cannot help it.', 'context': 'Taking Liu Zhang by the hand, Liu Bei wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'We have vanquished, and all opposition in Yiazhou is at an end. But there cannot be two rulers, so you must remove Liu Zhang to Jingzhou.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang to Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'But I do not wish to exile him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'He lost his prestige through weakness. If you are weak and undecided, you also will not last long.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'The sufferings of the people have been severe and losses great; it would be wise policy to let them settle down to their occupations as soon as possible. It would be wrong to reward our own people at the expense of these people.', 'context': 'But here Zhao Yun and others dissuaded him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 974, 'talk': 'You only look at one side. The laws of Qin 1 were fiercely cruel and provoked resentment among the people; it was fitting that the Supreme Ancestor should temper them with kindness. Under the weak administration of Liu Zhang, there has never been an efficient government, and there is a lack of respect for the law. The proper relationship between ruler and minister has been gradually obscured. Favor has been the means of rising, and the highest in rank have been the basest; kindness has been extended into license, and the most benefited have been the most contemptuous. And thereby have crept in many evils. Now I mean to inculcate respect for the dignity of the law, and kindness shall follow its attainment: there shall be moderation in conferring rank, but honor shall really follow on such promotion. In the mutual cooperation of kindness and honor and in proper distinction between superiors and inferiors lies the efficiency of a government.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'When my lord was in Jingzhou, fearful of his enemy on the north and trembling lest he be attacked from the east, Fa Zheng was his sure support. In these prosperous days one can hardly begin to discipline him. Could we reasonably forbid him following somewhat his own way?', 'context': 'But Zhuge Liang referred to his meritorious services, saying, “'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'My father was anxious to come into Yiazhou to try conclusions with Ma Chao.', 'context': 'his father, thanking his elder brother for the handsome gifts. Making obeisance and handing in his letter, Guan Ping said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'If he were to come and fight, I fear they would not both survive.', 'context': 'Said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'There is nothing to be anxious about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'I will write to Guan Yu.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'The Instructor knows me thoroughly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 458, 'talk': "The one man upon whom Liu Bei relies most is Zhuge Liang. Now his brother is in your service and in your power. All you have to do is to seize Zhuge Jin's family and send him west to see Zhuge Liang and make Zhuge Liang persuade Liu Bei to return Jingzhou. If Liu Bei refuses, the family of Zhuge Jin will suffer, and Zhuge Liang will not be able to resist the claims of brotherhood.", 'context': 'The scheme, which Zhang Zhao had in mind, he laid before his master thus: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'But Zhuge Jin is a loyal and true gentleman. I could not lay hands upon his family!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'Explain the ruse to him; that will set his mind at rest,', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Why think you your brother has come?', 'context': 'Liu Bei at once sought the advice of Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'He has come to force the return of Jingzhou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'How shall I answer him?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'You must do so and so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'If you have any trouble, my brother, tell; why do you weep thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Alas! My family are lost!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 364, 'talk': 'He is related to me by marriage, and he has profited by my absence from Jingzhou to steal away his sister. That is a sort of kindliness I find it hard to bear. When I am just going to lead my army to the South Land to take vengeance, is it likely he will get Jingzhou out of me?', 'context': 'The letter of Sun Quan was presented, but when Liu Bei had read it he said, angrily, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 343, 'talk': "The Marquis of Wu has seized my brother's family, and he will put them all to death if the land be not given up. Can I remain alive if such a fate befall them? I pray my lord for my sake to give back the region and prevent any breach between my brother and me.", 'context': "At this point Zhuge Liang prostrated himself weeping at his lord's feet and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Since things are so, and the Instructor pleads for it, I will return half,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'I will give up three territories—Changsha, Lingling, and Guiyang.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Then, as you have consented, prepare letters ordering Guan Yu to yield these three territories,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'When you see my brother, you must use most gracious words to him, for his nature is as a fierce fire, and even I fear what he may do. So be very careful.', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'The Imperial Uncle has promised to return three territories to my master, and I hope, General, you will hand them over at once and let me return.', 'context': 'When both were seated in their respective places, the emissary produced the letter of Liu Bei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'But the Marquis of Wu has laid hands upon my family, and they will be slain if the land be not given up. I crave your pity, O General!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'This is but a ruse on his part, but it does not deceive me!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Why are you so pitiless?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Let us have no more. This sword is pitiless!', 'context': 'Guan Yu drew his sword, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'It will put the Instructor to shame,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I pray you not to be angry, my father.', 'context': ' said Guan Ping. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Were it not for my respect for the Instructor, you would never go back to the South Land,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'My brother is hasty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'It is difficult to argue with him. But return home for the present, and when I have finished my conquest of Hanzhong, I will transfer Guan Yu to another post, and then I may be able to return Jingzhou.', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 133, 'iend': 208, 'talk': "This running to and fro was nothing more than one of your brother's tricks.", 'context': 'Zhuge Jin had no choice but to accept this reply and carry the unsatisfactory news to his master, who was greatly annoyed and said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'No, no! Zhuge Liang had interceded with many tears and obtained the promise to return three territories from Liu Bei. It was the obstinacy of Guan Yu that spoiled all.', 'context': 'The unhappy messenger denied, saying, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'What you say, my lord, seems most proper.', 'context': 'administration. Think you that might be done?” said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 185, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'Guan Yu would have none of us, but had chased us away at once with threats to kill us if we did not hasten!', 'context': 'The family of Zhuge Jin were restored to liberty, and officers were sent to take charge of the three territories of Changsha, Lingling, and Guiyang. But they quickly returned, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I have thought out a plan and was just going to impart it to you,', 'context': '“'},
