{'istart': 145, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'Geng Ji and Jin Yi have raised a disturbance.', 'context': 'This was a shock, but it told Wang Bi that his quondam friend was now an enemy. Wherefore he fled further to the house of Cao Xiu and told him, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'Slay Cao Cao and restore the Hans!', 'context': 'In the city the crowd was shouting one to another: “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Living we have failed to slay you, Cao Cao; dead we will be malicious spirits smiting rebels in all places!', 'context': 'Xiahou Dun sent his two chief prisoners to the place of execution. They shouted against Cao Cao. “'},
{'istart': 213, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'How I hate him!', 'context': 'The executioner smote Geng Ji on the mouth with his sword, so that the blood gushed out, but he continued to shout as long as he could. Wei Huang, his fellow−conspirator, dashed his temples on the ground crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'In this late rebellion some of you went out to extinguish the fire, some of you stayed within doors. Let those who went forth to put out the fire take their stand by the red flag, and those who remained in their houses go to the white flag.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Certainly there can be nothing wrong in trying to put out a fire,', 'context': 'The officials thought within themselves, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'We are guiltless!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'At that time you intended not to put out the flames but to aid the rebels.', 'context': 'Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'The enemy are newly arrived, why not fight and take the keen edge off their pride? If we do not fight, how can we look our chief in the face when we return?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Why did you attack without orders and bring about this defeat?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'It was the fault of Ren Kui, who disobeyed orders.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Defend the Pass most carefully; do not engage,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'General, why did you retire after the successful attack and slaughter of one of the enemy leaders?', 'context': 'some ruse when Ma Chao remained so long inactive, and retired to Nanzheng. Here he was visited by Zhang He, who asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'Seeing that Ma Chao declined to come out to fight, I suspected some ruse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'Beside, when I was at Yejun that wonderful soothsayer, Guan Lu, foretold the loss of a leader here. I heeded what he said and so was careful.', 'context': ' replied Cao Hong. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'You have been a leader of soldiers for half your life, and yet you heed the sayings of a soothsayer! I may be of small wit, but I would take Baxi with my own troops, and the possession of Baxi would be the key to the whole of Shu.', 'context': 'Zhang He laughed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'The defender of Baxi is Zhang Fei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'But if you fail, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Then I shall be content to pay the penalty according to military rules.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Since that is so, let us send him fifty vessels of the best brew of Chengdu. He probably has but poor stuff in the camp.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang was jocular, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'But he has always had a weakness for wine, and he has failed because of it. Yet you would encourage him to drink by sending him more wine?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 500, 'talk': 'My lord, is it that you do not understand your brother even after all these years? He is brave and steady, yet when we first invaded the Western Land of Rivers, he released Yan Yan, which was not what a mere brave would have done. He is face to face with Zhang He, and has been for nearly two months, and day after day he drinks and rages and insults his enemy openly. He treats Zhang He with most perfect contempt. But this is not only the wine−cup; it is a deep plan to get the better of Zhang He.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'This may be so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'but let us not rely upon it too much. Let Wei Yan go to help him.', 'context': ' replied Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 126, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'Fine Wine for the Frontier Army', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang sent Wei Yan with the wine, and the carts set out, each flying a yellow flag with a writing in large characters: “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'He despises me too much,', 'context': 'saw his opponent drinking, and two of the soldiers were boxing before Zhang Fei for his amusement. “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'He disobeyed my orders and marched; he has lost an important point and now he sends to me for help!', 'context': 'Cao Hong angrily replied, “'},
{'istart': 215, 'iend': 297, 'talk': 'I will pretend defeat and fly. They will follow and you can cut off their retreat.', 'context': 'While refusing aid, Cao Hong sent to urge his colleague to go out and fight. But Zhang He too greatly feared. At length Zhang He decided upon a plan of action. He sent out two parties into ambush and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'Zhang He has compassed the death of Lei Tong by leading him into an ambush, and he wants to inveigle me into another. What say you to meeting trick with trick?', 'context': 'He said to Wei Yan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'But how?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 388, 'talk': "Tomorrow I will lead the army forward, you following me with some reliable soldiers. When his army come out from their ambush, you can smite them, sending half your men against each party. We will secretly fill the by−roads with loads of combustibles, entice the enemy among them and start a fire. In the confusion, I shall try to capture Zhang He. So will we avenge our comrade's death.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'That is the way to take Wakou Pass,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Whence come you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 287, 'talk': 'We belong to Hanzhong and are going home. We heard that you were out fighting and the high road to Langzhong was blockaded, and so we have come across the Mist Torrent and Zitong Mountains and down River Guijin. We are going to our homes in Hanzhong.', 'context': ' asked Zhang Fei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Can one reach Wakou Pass by this road? And how far is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'A small road leads past to the rear of the Pass from Zitong Mountains.', 'context': 'The country people replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'I told you not to go, but you were willful. And you gave in your written pledge. You have lost all your soldiers, yet you do not commit suicide. What will you do next?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 380, 'talk': 'An army is easily raised; a leader is hard to find. Though Zhang He is guilty, he is a great favorite with our prince. I think you should spare him. Rather give him command of another army and send him to take Jiameng Pass and so hold up the soldiers at all the stations. Hanzhong will be tranquil of its own accord. If he fails a second time, you can punish him for both faults.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Jiameng Pass is in danger; we must get Zhang Fei from Langzhong to drive off Zhang He,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'Zhang Fei is encamped at Wakou Pass, and Langzhong is no less important than Jiameng Pass. I do not think he should be recalled. Choose one among the generals to go and defeat Zhang He.', 'context': 'Fa Zheng replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Zhang He is renowned in Wei; no ordinary leader will avail. Zhang Fei is the only man to send, the only one equal to the task.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang laughed, “'},
{'istart': 206, 'iend': 353, 'talk': 'Instructor, why do you thus despise us? I will use what little skill I have in slaying our enemy and will lay his head at the foot of our standard.', 'context': ' Then among the generals one started up crying angrily, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Friend Huang Zhong, you are bold enough, but what about your age? I fear you are no match for Zhang He.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'General, you are nearly seventy; can you still hold you are not aged?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Well, if you will go, who will second you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'I would prefer Veteran General Yan Yan. And if there is the least anxiety, well, here is this hoary head.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang has slipped up in his calculations in sending such a pair of dotards on such an important mission.', 'context': 'defenders of the Pass, laughed in their hearts, thinking: “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'You see the behavior of these people? They are laughing at us because we are old. Now we will do something that will win admiration from all the world.', 'context': 'Huang Zhong said to Yan Yan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I should be glad to hear your orders,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'You must be very old, and yet you are unashamed to go into the battle, eh?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'You menial!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'If he is pressed too hard, he may take refuge in Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'Rather send him help. You will thus keep a hold over him and prevent his desertion.', 'context': ' said Guo Huai. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'That old man Huang Zhong is really a hero;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Hereabout there is a mountain named Tiandang Mountain wherein Cao Hong has stored his supplies. If we can gain its possession, we shall reduce the enemy to want and we shall get Hanzhong.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I think so, too, and so let us do so and so.', 'context': 'Huang Zhong replied, “'},
{'istart': 170, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'Disgraceful old ruffian!', 'context': 'At news of the coming of new armies, Huang Zhong marched out to meet them. He found Han Hao in front of his array, and Han Hao began to abuse the veteran, shouting out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Huang Zhong has retreated before you for two days; there is some deep stratagem behind this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'You are such a coward that you have been defeated many times. Now say no more, but let us accomplish something.', 'context': 'Xiahou Shang scoffed at him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 192, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'The old general is making the enemy over−confident—to their ultimate destruction.', 'context': 'Then Meng Da secretly wrote to Liu Bei that Huang Zhong had been repeatedly defeated and now was in the Pass and unable to go out. Liu Bei became alarmed and consulted Zhuge Liang, who said, “'},
{'istart': 198, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'General, what makes you come here?', 'context': 'But Zhao Yun did not share this opinion, nor did many others, and Liu Bei decided to send Liu Feng to reinforce his aged general. The young man came to the Pass and saw Huang Zhong, who asked him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'My father heard that you have sustained several defeats, and he has sent me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'But I am only employing the ruse of leading on the enemy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 425, 'talk': 'You will see tonight that in one battle I shall regain all the camps and capture their supplies and many horses. I have only lent the camps to them to store their supplies. Tonight I shall leave Huo Jun to guard the Pass, while General Meng Da will gather up the spoils for us. Now, young Sir, you shall see the destruction of the enemy.', 'context': ' said Huang Zhong, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Our soldiers need repose.', 'context': 'Huang Zhong pressed on his victory. Liu Feng ventured to say, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': "Can you seize the tiger's whelps without going into the tiger's den?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 306, 'talk': 'This is Tiandang Mountain, where our stores are. Close by is Micang Mountain. The two mountains are the very source of life of the Hanzhong army. Lose them and Hanzhong is gone too. We must see to their security.', 'context': 'Then Zhang He sought the two generals who had brought about the misfortune and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 275, 'talk': 'My uncle, Xiahou Yuan, will look out for the defense of Micang Mountain, which is next to his station at Dingjun Mountain; there need be no anxiety about that. And my brother, Xiahou De, guards Tiandang Mountain. Let us go to him and help to protect that.', 'context': 'Xiahou Shang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'I have one hundred thousand troops in camp here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'You may take some of them and recover your lost camps.', 'context': ' replied he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'The only proper course is to defend.', 'context': ' replied Zhang He. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'The old ruffian does not know much of the art of war; after all,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'he is only a brave.', 'context': ' said Xiahou De with a laugh, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Be not mistaken; he is crafty and not only bold,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Nevertheless, be careful how you attack,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Give me three thousand good soldiers, and I will cut him to pieces,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'The sun is setting, and our men are weary. Let us retire for the fight tomorrow.', 'context': 'Liu Feng put in a note of warning, saying, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'I do not hold with your objections. This is the one God−given opportunity to make good, and it would be a sin not to take it.', 'context': 'But Huang Zhong paid little attention, saying, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 649, 'talk': 'Not long ago Zhang Lu submitted to Cao Cao, and thereby Cao Cao got possession of Hanzhong quite easily. Instead of following up this by an advance westward, he left two generals to guard it and went south. That was a mistake. Now, my lord, do not make a mistake yourself, but take advantage of the present favorable position, with Zhang He newly defeated and Tiandang Mountain captured, to attack Hanzhong and you will have it at once. Once that is yours, you can train your army and amass supplies ready for a stroke against the arch−rebel himself. This God−given advantage will be confirmed to you and you should not miss it.', 'context': 'Then said Fa Zheng, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 438, 'talk': 'People said you were old, General, but the Directing Instructor of the army know you better than they, and you have rendered amazing service. Still, Dingjun Mountain is yet to be captured, and it is both a great central store and a major defense of Nanzheng. If we could get Dingjun Mountain, we could be quite easy about the whole region of Hanzhong. Think you that you are equal to taking Dingjun Mountain?', 'context': 'Liu Bei said to Huang Zhong, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 411, 'talk': "Old Lian Po was eighty years old and yet he ate a bushel of rice and ten pounds of flesh, so that his vigor frightened the nobles and not one dared encroach upon the borders of the state of Zhao. I am not yet seventy. You call me old, O Instructor; then I will not take any helper, but go out simply with my own three thousand troops, and we will lay Xiahou Yuan's head at your feet.", 'context': 'Huang Zhong hotly replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'If you are really determined to undertake this expedition, I shall send Fa Zheng with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'You will have to discuss everything with him. I shall also dispatch supports and reinforcements.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang to the veteran leader. “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 291, 'talk': 'Tiandang Mountain has been captured, and Xiahou De and Han Hao have died with the loss. Liu Bei is about to invade Hanzhong. Send a swift messenger to inform the Prince of Wei and ask for help.', 'context': "The refugees, Zhang He and Xiahou Shang, reached Xiahou Yuan's camp and told their doleful tale, “"},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'The loss of Hanzhong would shake the whole country. You, O Prince, must not shrink from toil and hardship, but must yourself go to lead the army.', 'context': 'Cao Cao lost no time in calling a council. Then High Minister Liu Ye said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'This state of things comes of my not heeding your words before, gentle Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'This place is the Indigo Field,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'And in that wood is the estate of the late Minister Cai Yong. His daughter, Cai Yan, and her present husband, Dong Si, live there.', 'context': ' they replied. “'},
{'istart': 263, 'iend': 305, 'talk': 'Eighteen Stanzas for the Mongol Flageolet,', 'context': "Now Cao Cao and Cai Yong had been excellent friends at one time. Cai Yong's daughter had been first married to Wei Zhongdao. Then she was abducted by the frontier tribes and taken away to the north, where she had borne two sons. She had composed a ballad called “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 673, 'talk': 'A later magistrate had the story inscribed by Handan Chun in memory of the event. At that time Handan Chun was only thirteen, but the composition of the inscription was so perfect that neither jot nor tittle could be added, and yet he had written it impromptu without revision. The stone was set up beside the grave, and both inscription and story were the admiration of all the people of that day. My father went to see it. It was evening, but in the obscurity he felt out the inscription with his fingers. He got hold of a pencil and wrote eight large characters on the reverse of the stone and, later, some person recutting the stone engraved these eight words as well.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 143, 'talk': "yellow silk, young wife, a daughter's child, pestle and mortar.", 'context': 'Cao Cao then read the eight words; they formed an enigma. Literally they read, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Can you explain?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': "No; although it is a writing of my father's, thy handmaid cannot interpret it,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'Can any one of you explain it?', 'context': 'Turning to the strategists of his staff, Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I have grasped the meaning of it.', 'context': 'reply. Suddenly, they heard one voice, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Do not tell me yet; let me think it out,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Now, you may try.', 'context': 'the meaning suddenly dawned upon Cao Cao, and he laughingly turned to Yang Xiu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'This is the solution of the enigma,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Just what I made it.', 'context': "Cao Cao was astonished at Yang Xiu's cleverness, and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'To suffer defeat is no crime;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'that and victory are things that happen constantly in war.', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has sent Huang Zhong to take Dingjun Mountain,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'But standing always on the defensive is showing weakness,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Xiahou Yuan is very stern and inflexible, and he may be carried too far and fall victim to some vile ruse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'The Prince has a great army at Nanzheng ready to destroy Liu Bei. We have been on the defense here long enough, and it is time we rendered some solid service. Tomorrow I am going out to battle, and hope to capture Huang Zhong.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Your opponent combines ready resource with boldness and prevision,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'Beside, he has Fa Zheng to aid him; and you must be cautious, for the country is very difficult and dangerous. You would better keep on the defensive.', 'context': ' said Zhang He. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'How shall we be able to look our prince in the face when other leaders render good services? However, you just keep the hill, and I will go out to battle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'You are not to make a real stand, but merely to begin the fight. You are to lose and not win, for a grand ruse is ready for the enemy.', 'context': 'Xiahou Yuan said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Do not trouble yourself to move, O General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'for I will go out to fight them.', 'context': ' said Chen Shi, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'This is a well known ruse, and you should remain on the defensive. You will lose if you fight.', 'context': ' said the prudent Zhang He. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Because we saw the banners of Shu through openings in the mountains in several places, and we feared an ambush,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'Now take up position half way up the hill, while I go to the top. When the enemy appears, I will show a white flag. But you will remain quiet till the enemy become tired and remiss, when I will hoist a red flag. That will be the signal for attack.', 'context': 'Then said Fa Zheng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'With Huang Zhong in occupation of that hill, I simply must give battle,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'The whole thing is but a ruse of Fa Zheng. General, you would better defend our position.', 'context': 'Zhang He strongly dissuaded him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'From the top of that hill the whole of our position is visible, our strength and our weakness; I must fight.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 280, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun of Changshan is here!', 'context': 'Mountain. Zhang He came out to oppose the army of Shu, but, attacked at two points by Huang Zhong and Chen Shi, he could not stand. He lost the day and fled. However, before he had gone far, another cohort flashed out from the hills and barred his way. And the leader cried out, “'},
{'istart': 376, 'iend': 385, 'talk': 'Army Halt', 'context': 'a great cry and then he understood the prediction of the soothsayer, Guan Lu, that the cast showed opposition: It was the twenty−fourth year of Rebuilt Tranquillity (three and eight cross); the yellow boar (the month Xiahou Yuan died) had met the tiger; the expedition had suffered a loss indeed by the death of a general, and the death had taken place at the mount known as “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Dingjun Mountain is lost. Before marching farther, the stores in Micang Mountain should be moved to the Northern Mountain.', 'context': 'They said to Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 231, 'talk': "Cao Cao's army of two hundred thousand troops is on the way to avenge Xiahou Yuan's loss; and the supplies on Micang Mountain are being moved to the Northern Mountain.", 'context': 'While these were going on, General Zhang Zhu brought the news: “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is certainly short of supplies. If we can burn what he has and destroy his baggage train, he will have but little spirit left to fight.', 'context': 'Then said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'I am willing to undertake the task,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Remember Cao Cao is a different sort of man from Xiahou Yuan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I will go and kill him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Then go with Zhao Yun;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'act in concert and see who can do best.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'I am going to lead,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'No wait; I am going first,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'But I am the senior leader; you are only my second,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Since you have won the right to make the first attempt, you must let me help you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'That suits me admirably,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 139, 'iend': 377, 'talk': 'My friend Huang Zhong is going to try to burn the stores tomorrow. If he has not returned at noon, I am to go to aid him. You are to guard our camp, which is in a dangerous place by the river, but you are not to move out unless compelled.', 'context': 'So they decided upon noon as the time; and Zhao Yun went back to his own camp, where he called in his Deputy General, Zhang Yi, and said, “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 422, 'talk': "I have slain Xiahou Yuan and cowed Zhang He. I am going to destroy the enemy's store of grain tomorrow, taking with me most of the troops. You are to come and assist me. A meal for the men is to be ready about midnight tonight, and we shall move at the fourth watch. We shall march to the foot of their hill, capture Zhang He, and then start the fire.", 'context': 'Huang Zhong went back to his camp and said to his general, Zhang Zhu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Guard the camp most carefully; see that you have archers and crossbowmen on both sides.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Yes, yes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Where are the soldiers of Shu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'All killed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'That is Zhao Yun of Changshan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'So the hero of Dangyang is still alive,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Let us bar the gates while we make preparation,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Do not bar the gates,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 209, 'talk': "Have you never heard of my exploit at Dangyang, when I laughed at Cao Cao's many legions? Now that I have an army at my back and generals to help, what is there to fear?", 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 346, 'iend': 382, 'talk': 'Truly, the man is brave all through!', 'context': "They sent news of the victory to Liu Bei, who came with Zhuge Liang to the scene of the victory, and there they heard the full story of Zhao Yun's prowess. Liu Bei was glad, and when he had seen the steepness and difficulties of the surrounding hills and understood the fine deeds of valor that had been done, he turned to Zhuge Liang and said, “"},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is coming again down through the Xie Valley to try to capture River Han.', 'context': 'Soon it was reported: “'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'He will not succeed, for I think that we shall gain command of the river.', 'context': ' But Liu Bei laughed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'I know the country well, and I wish to help General Xu Huang to destroy the army of Shu.', 'context': 'A General named Wang Ping said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'To cross the river is well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'but what if you have to retreat?', 'context': ' said Wang Ping, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'You may lead the footmen to hold the enemy while I destroy them with the horsemen,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'Xu Huang has been bold enough to come; we will not go out against him till evening, when his soldiers are fatigued. Then we will fall upon him one on either side.', 'context': 'Then said Huang Zhong, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'He must be thinking of retreat or he would not shoot thus. Now is our time to smite him.', 'context': 'Huang Zhong said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Had I done so, these camps would have been left unguarded,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'I tried to dissuade you from going, but you would not hear me, and you brought about this reverse yourself.', 'context': ' said Wang Ping. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'I shall surely capture Hanzhong now that you are here to help me, friend Wang Ping,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 156, 'iend': 440, 'talk': 'General, you lead five hundred troops, with drums and horns, and place them in ambush behind the hill, to await certain orders which will come some time during the night or at dawn. When you hear a detonation, you are not to appear, only give a long roll of the drums at every report.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang saw in the upper course of the stream a hill which might well screen a thousand soldiers, so he returned to camp, called in Zhao Yun and said, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Cao Cao is skilled in war, but still he is not proof against all deceitful tricks.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang was pleased at the result of his ruse. Said he, smiling, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Liu Bei, you have forgotten kindness and lost the sense of right; you are a rebel against the government.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'He who captures Liu Bei will be made Prince of Hanzhong.', 'context': 'Liu Bei retired within the ranks of his array. Liu Feng was no match for his opponent, and fled. Cao Cao issued an order to capture Liu Bei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Why did you call us off, O Prince, just as we were on the point of success?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 311, 'talk': 'Because I saw the enemy had encamped with the river in their rear, which was very suspicious. They also abandoned their steeds and weapons, which made me doubt. Wherefore I could only retire. But retain your armor. Let not a person take off his harness on pain of death. Now retire as quickly as you can march.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Cao Cao was exceedingly quickly overcome this time;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'how was that?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'He has always been of a suspicious nature,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'and that has led to many failures although he is a good leader of armies. I have defeated him by playing upon his doubts.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'He is rather weakened now,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Can you not devise a plan to drive him away finally?', 'context': ' said Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'That is all thought out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'The roads far and near are blocked by the troops of Shu, and every place seems to be burning. No soldier is seen.', 'context': "Cao Cao's scouts sent out from Yangping Pass returned to report: “"},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'Our stores are being plundered by Zhang Fei and Wei Yan.', 'context': 'Cao Cao knew not what to do. Then other scouts told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Except for you, O General, the grain could never reach Yangping Pass.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'The sun has nearly set,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I can face any danger;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Seller of shoes, you are always sending out this pretended son of yours to fight for you. If I only call my golden−bearded son Cao Zhang, your so−called son will be chopped to mincemeat!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'If that is an ambush, it is the last of me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'You do not study, but only love your bow and your horse; this is the courage of a mere person. Think you that this makes for an honorable career?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 288, 'talk': 'The really noble person ought to imitate such grand men as Wei Qing and Huo Qubing. They won their reputation in the Gobi Desert, where they led a mighty host of hundred thousand, able to overrun the whole world and go anywhere. What have I to do with scholarship?', 'context': 'But Cao Zhang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'But what should a leader be like?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'He should be endued with firmness and courage, never turn aside from a difficulty, but be in the van of his officers and troops. Rewards should be certain; and so should punishments.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'At home we are father and son, but when a task is given you, you have to consider your duty as a servant of your ruler. The law knows no kindness, and you must beware.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'Now that my golden−bearded son has arrived, we can destroy Liu Bei for certain.', 'context': 'His coming greatly pleased his father, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Vie with each other,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 543, 'iend': 558, 'talk': 'Chicken tendon.', 'context': 'After a great fight, Cao Cao ordered his army to retire into camp at the Xie Valley. Here he remained many days, prevented from advancing by Ma Chao and fearing the ridicule of Shu if he should retreat. One day, while he was anxiously trying to decide what to do, his cook sent in some chicken broth. He noticed in the broth some chicken tendons, and this simple fact led him into a train of reflection. He was still deep in thought when Xiahou Dun entered his tent to ask the watchword for that night. Cao Cao at once involuntarily replied, “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'chicken tendon,', 'context': 'The word was passed on in orders. When First Secretary Yang Xiu saw the order that the watchword was “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 473, 'talk': "By tonight's orders I see that the Prince of Wei is soon going to retire. 'Chicken tendons' are tasteless things to eat, and yet it is a pity to waste them. Now if we advance, we cannot conquer; and if we retire, we fear we shall look ridiculous. There being no advantage here, the best course is to retire. You will certainly see the Prince of Wei retreat before long. I have made my preparations so as not to be hurried and confused at the last moment.", 'context': 'Yang Xiu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': "You seem to know the Prince's inmost heart,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Why is everything in your camp packed as if ready for the march?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': "Yang Xiu, the First Secretary, seems to have private knowledge of the Prince's design to retire,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'How dare you invent such a story and disturb the hearts of my army?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 218, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'alive', 'context': "tongue had often wounded Cao Cao's susceptibilities. Once Cao Cao was having a pleasance laid out, and when it was completed, he went to inspect the work. He uttered no word of praise or blame; he just wrote the word “"},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister thinks the gates are too wide.', 'context': "“'Gate' with 'alive' inside it makes the word for 'wide,'“ said he. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'But who guessed what I meant?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Yang Xiu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'One Cream Box', 'context': 'Another time Cao Cao received a box of cream cheese from Mongolia. Cao Cao just scribbled three words “'},
{'istart': 463, 'iend': 486, 'talk': 'Each person a mouthful.', 'context': ' on the top and left it on the table. The words seemed to have no meaning. But Yang Xiu happened to come in, saw the box and at once handed a spoonful of the contents to each guest in the room. When Cao Cao asked why he did this, he explained that that was the interpretation of the words on the box, which, resolved into primary symbols, read, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Could I possibly disobey your orders?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 439, 'iend': 500, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister was in no dream, but only you were asleep.', 'context': 'him again. Cao Cao suddenly leaped from the couch, cut down the intruder with his sword, and lay down again to sleep. Some time after he awoke, simulated surprise and asked who had killed his attendant. When they told him, Cao Cao wept aloud for the dead man and had him buried in a fine grave. Most people thought that Cao Cao had slain the man while asleep, but Yang Xiu knew better, and at the funeral of the victim Yang Xiu remarked, “'},
{'istart': 585, 'iend': 696, 'talk': 'Be not afraid, but to fill a basket actually with rolls of silk on the morrow and have it carried in as before.', 'context': 'When Cao Cao was considering the nomination of his heir and desired to name Cao Zhi, Cao Pi got to hear of the proposal to set him aside in favor of his younger brother, so he secretly requested the Master of the Court Singers, Wu Zhi, to come and discuss this matter. Then fearing that someone might see his visitor, Cao Pi got a large basket made, in which his friend was smuggled into the Palace. Cao Pi gave out that the basket contained rolls of silk. Yang Xiu heard the truth and informed Cao Cao, who sent guards to watch at the gates. Cao Pi, in alarm, told Wu Zhi, who said, “'},
{'istart': 335, 'iend': 434, 'talk': 'You have received orders from the Prince to go out; simply cut down any who may try to prevent you.', 'context': 'Another time Cao Cao, wishing to compare the abilities of his two sons Cao Pi and Cao Zhi, told them both to go out of the city, at the same time ordering the gate wardens to forbid their exit. Cao Pi first came to the gate, was stopped by the wardens and returned to his palace. But his brother Cao Zhi consulted Yang Xiu, who said, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 133, 'talk': "I have the Prince's order to go out; dare you stop me?", 'context': 'When Cao Zhi went to the gate and was stopped, he shouted out to the wardens, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'How dare he throw dust in my eyes like this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 172, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Get out of this!', 'context': 'Cao Cao thus put to death the prime mover and simulated anger against Xiahou Dun. He threatened to execute Xiahou Dun, but listened to those who begged him to show mercy. “'},
{'istart': 299, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'Death for any officer who flinches!', 'context': "Pang De went out to fight Wei Yan; but while the combat was in progress, fires broke out in Cao Cao's camp, and a soldier came flying to say that the rear and center camps had been seized by Ma Chao. Fearing lest this should lead to a rout, he drew his sword and stood before the army, crying out, “"},
{'istart': 337, 'iend': 353, 'talk': 'Wei Yan is here!', 'context': 'Wherefore the men of Wei pressed forward valiantly, and Wei Yan, pretending defeat, retreated. Having driven back this army, Cao Cao gave the signal to turn toward camp and fight with Ma Chao. He took up his station on the top of a hill whence he could survey the field. Suddenly a cohort appeared just below him, and the leader cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Spare my lord!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Emperor,', 'context': 'It was after this that the general body of the officers decided to urge Liu Bei to assume the title of “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 460, 'talk': "Now that Cao Cao really holds the reins of authority, the people are without a true sovereign. Our lord, your kindness and sense of justice have spread throughout the empire. You have restored peace over the two Lands of Rivers, and your becoming an emperor would be according to God's will and the desire of the people. Then by right and title you could destroy rebels. This matter should not be delayed, and we pray you choose the auspicious day.", 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'Your words, O Instructor of the Army, are wrong. Although I am of the imperial house, yet I am but a minister; and to do this thing would be rebellion against Han.', 'context': 'But Liu Bei evinced great surprise, and replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 531, 'talk': 'Not so. Today the empire is riven, and many of the bolder spirits have seized upon and claim the rule of various portions. The talented of the empire and the virtuous among officers, who have risked death and lost their lives in serving those above them, all desire to have the opportunity of serving a true emperor and doing service for a true throne. Now, if you insist on modestly maintaining your righteous way, I fear that you will lose popular support. My lord, I wish that you should reflect upon this.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'But you desire me to usurp a place of great honor in the state, and I dare not. Let there be more delay and discussion.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Our lord, if you reject this, the hearts of the people will turn from you.', 'context': 'But with one voice they said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'My lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 236, 'iend': 377, 'talk': 'Gentlemen, though you may desire to honor me by the title of Prince, yet, without an edict from the Emperor, such action would be usurpation.', 'context': " said Zhuge Liang, “you have made rectitude your motto all your life. If you really object to the most honored title, then, since you have Jingzhou, Yiazhou, and Hanzhong, take temporarily the title of 'Prince of Hanzhong.'“ “"},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'The time demands recognition of the actual state of authority, and not a rigid adherence to all the rules of propriety.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'All sorts of people with all sorts of names are making themselves rulers; how much more ought you, O Brother, who are of the dynastic stock? It ought not to be Prince of Hanzhong but Emperor. What prevents it?', 'context': 'And Zhang Fei roared out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Brother, say no more,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'My lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 438, 'talk': 'Humbly I think of such a title and its exalted position and the favor vouchsafed me, and I would endeavor to show true gratitude. My anxiety is deep, for the responsibility is heavy. I am as one on the brink of a great gulf. I must surely exert myself to the utmost and encourage my armies and lead all disciples of rectitude, in accordance with the will of Heaven and as occasion serves, to smite rebellion so as to restore the dynasty.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'How dare this mean weaver of straw shoes behave thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Now I swear that I will destroy him.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 401, 'talk': 'Let not the great Prince of Wei trouble himself to go on a distant expedition because of a temporary annoyance. I can propose a plan of which the execution will need not the bending of a single bow, and yet it will make Liu Bei bring down disaster upon his own head. When his army shall have become exhausted, it will only be necessary to send one single general against him and victory will be ours.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'What is your exalted view, my friend?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'Wei and Wu are primarily enemies because of the dissension fomented by the words of Zhuge Liang. They have been fighting for several years and many lives have been lost. Now this messenger has surely come to discuss terms of friendship, and he should be welcomed.', 'context': 'Zhang Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 342, 'talk': "Wu and Wei have no fundamental quarrel, and their dissension has been brought about by Liu Bei. My master sends me to covenant with you for an attack on Jingzhou, while he goes against Hanzhong. This double attack being successful, the conquered country can be divided between us two, and we can both swear to respect each other's territory.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 311, 'talk': "Although the messenger's speech was all special pleading, it was correct in form. I propose that the messenger be allowed to return and that a covenant be made with Cao Cao for joint attack. In addition, let spies be sent over the Great River to find out Guan Yu's movements, and then we may act.", 'context': 'Said Gu Yong, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 380, 'talk': 'I hear that since Guan Yu has been in Jingzhou, Liu Bei has found him a wife, who has borne him a son and a daughter. The daughter is too young to have been betrothed, wherefore let me go to ask her in marriage with your heir. If Guan Yu agrees, then we can arrange with him to attack Cao Cao. If Guan Yu refuses, then let us aid Cao Cao in an attack on Jingzhou.', 'context': 'Zhuge Jin said, “'},
{'istart': 220, 'iend': 254, 'talk': 'What have you come for, Zhuge Jin?', 'context': 'Sun Quan took this advice. So he sent Man Chong away and sent Zhuge Jin to Jingzhou to try to arrange the betrothal. Zhuge Jin was received; and when the time came to state the reason for his coming, Guan Yu asked him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 300, 'talk': 'I have come seeking to ally the two houses. My master, the Marquis of Wu, has a son who is quite clever. Hearing that you have a daughter, General, I ask her in marriage, hereby the two houses may join in an attack on Cao Cao. This would be an admirable result, and I pray you consider the proposal.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 121, 'talk': "How can my tiger's daughter marry with a dog's whelp? Were it not for your brother, I would take your head. Say no more!", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'What ruffianism!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'But I also want the place,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I felt that Cao Cao would try to do this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'and most of the advisers in the South Land will persuade Cao Cao to order Cao Ren to begin the campaign.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'But what am I to do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'First send a special messenger to Guan Yu with his new title, telling him to capture Fankou, which will so damp the ardor of the enemy that they will break off themselves.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'The First of the Five Tiger Generals,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'And who are the five?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Their names are Guan Yu, Zhang Fei, Zhao Yun, Ma Chao, and Huang Zhong.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'The second is my brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'You do wrong to refuse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 763, 'talk': 'Of old, Xiao He and Cao Shen helped Liu Bang, the Founder of the Han Dynasty, in his great enterprise and were very dear friends, while Han Xin was but a runaway leader from Chu. Yet Liu Bang made Han Xin a prince, and so placed over the heads of the other two. I have never heard that these two resented it. The Prince of Hanzhong has his Five Tiger Generals, but he is still your brother and all that that means. As his brother, you are he and he is you. Is there any comparison with any other? The Prince has always treated you with the greatest kindness. You two are one in sorrow and joy, sharers of disaster and good fortune. No such question as that of a mere title ought to reckon at all. I pray you, Sir, reflect.', 'context': ' said Fei Shi. “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'You have prevented me from making a great mistake due to my ignorance.', 'context': 'Guan Yu understood, and thanked Fei Shi, saying, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'It is not well to put two leaders to death at the beginning of a campaign, before even the army has marched. You might reprieve them at least.', 'context': 'However, Fei Shi interceded for them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'Were it not that I have the greatest regard for Chairman Fei Shi here, I had let the sentence take its course. Now I will only flog you.', 'context': "Guan Yu's anger had by no means subsided, but he recalled the two generals and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Now be warned,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'If, when I return from my victories, there is the least sign of disorder on your part, you will suffer for both faults.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'The boar is a royal beast, like the dragon, and coming to your feet means a rise of your dignity.', 'context': 'The dream perplexed him, and he could not explain it. He related it to his son, who interpreted it happily, saying, “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'When a person nears sixty, he ought not to be greatly disturbed by the thought of death,', 'context': 'When the dream got noised abroad, for he told his officers, some interpreted it as auspicious and some the reverse. “'},
{'istart': 222, 'iend': 248, 'talk': 'After all, I am a warrior.', 'context': ' said Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'This shows what a dream of boars means.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'The Prince of Wei has ordered you to act in concert with Wu and take Jingzhou. For the other side to come against such a combination is to walk in the way of death; certainly we have no occasion to avoid a conflict.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Guan Yu is brave and cunning and one not to be met lightly. I think defense is best.', 'context': 'On the other hand the newly sent Adviser Man Chong inculcated caution. Said he, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'This is all the talk of a lot of book−folk. When the flood approaches, bank up to keep it out. Let the enemy come with their tired soldiers, and we shall go out, defeat them, and receive our reward, for we are sure of victory.', 'context': 'Then General Xiahou Cun said contemptuously, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'You have obtained this city very easily,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 331, 'talk': "but the task is not ended. Cao Cao's army have been beaten and their courage broken, but there is danger from the side of Wu. Lu Meng is at Lukou, and he has long cherished the desire to lay hands on Jingzhou. Suppose he now attacks; what will happen?", 'context': ' said the Marching General, Wang Fu, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 424, 'talk': 'I was even thinking of that myself. You may go and attend to this matter. You will certainly be able to find certain elevated spots on the river bank, about seven miles apart, suitable for alarm beacons, whence could be signaled any attempt of the marines of Wu to cross the river. Fifty soldiers could guard each station. Let there be a flame by night and a smoke by day. If they cross the river, I must go and smite them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Fu Shiren and Mi Fang are defending important places, but they may not be able to defend the Passes well. There ought to be a commander−in−chief over Jingzhou City.', 'context': 'Wang Fu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'There is no need for anxiety; Army Inspector Pan Jun is guarding the city.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 291, 'talk': 'The objection is the character of Pan Jun. He is jealous and selfish and not a fit person for the task. I think you would do well to replace him by Zhao Lei, now of the Chief of the Commissariat. Zhao Lei is loyal, trusty, clean−handed, and straight, a much more desirable man for the post.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'I know Pan Jun very well, but I have delegated him for that duty and cannot change now. The work Zhao Lei has to do in the supplies is also most important. I do not think you need be anxious. Just get along with those beacons for me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Neglecting your advice, I lost my soldiers, my two generals, and the city of Xiangyang. What am I to do now?', 'context': 'Now Cao Ren said to Man Chong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'Guan Yu is very dangerous, too brave and skillful for us to try to defeat. We would better remain on the defensive,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I ask for a few thousand troops,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'and I will meet the enemy on the way.', 'context': ' said Lu Chang, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'You cannot do any good,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 347, 'talk': 'According to the advice of you and the other bookish officials, there is only one thing to do. But will defense drive off the enemy? The proper way is to attack your enemy while he is crossing a river, and as Guan Yu is doing that now, why not attack? It will be quite another matter if you let him reach the walls and get possession of the moat.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'You go and defend Fankou!', 'context': 'The letter reached Cao Cao, who chose a certain general among his leaders and assigned the task, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Let me have another general to lead the van,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Who volunteers?', 'context': ' said Yu Jin. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'I do;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'I will give my poor services for what they are worth. And I will capture this fellow Guan Yu and bring him as an offering before your standard.', 'context': ' cried a man, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'That fellow Guan Yu has a great reputation, and in the whole country he has no rival. He has not met his match yet, but now you are going, he will find all his work cut out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'Sir General, the expedition you lead is for the relief of Fankou, and it can confidently expect victory, but is it not unwise to place such as Pang De in command of the van?', 'context': 'Dong Heng said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Why?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 444, 'talk': 'Because Pang De was once under the command of Ma Chao. He had no alternative but to surrender and fight for Wei. But his former chief is now in high honor in Shu, one of the Five Tiger Generals, and his own brother Pang Rou is there, too, as an officer. To send Pang De as Leader of the Van just now seems like trying to extinguish a fire with oil. Would it not be well to inform the Prince of Wei and ask him to exchange this man for another?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'O Prince, why do you reject my services? I was just about to do my best for you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'I do not doubt you, but Ma Chao is now in the west, and your brother also; both in the service of Liu Bei. I myself have no doubts, but it is what all the crowd are saying. What can I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'What can that inauspicious thing mean putting out on the eve of a campaign?', 'context': 'And they asked one another, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 359, 'talk': 'The Prince of Wei has been generous to me, and I am pledged to show my gratitude to the death. I am about to go out against this Guan Yu, and I have to kill him or he must kill me. If he does not kill me, I must commit suicide, and so I have prepared what is necessary. I will not return leaving my task unachieved.', 'context': 'By and by, drinking to them, Pang De said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'I have been appointed Leader of the Van of this new expedition against Guan Yu, and my duty bids me seek death or glory on the battlefield. If I die, our son is in your special care. Alas, the child has been born ill−starred, and when he grows up he will have to avenge a father.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'I will fight to the end with Guan Yu. Place my body therein if I fall in combat. And if I slay him, then will I bring his head in this coffin as an offering to our Prince.', 'context': 'He bade his officers, saying, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'If you are like this, O General, then we also will follow you to the end.', 'context': 'Then out spoke his five hundred veterans and said, “'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'I have no anxiety with such a general to lead my armies.', 'context': 'The vanguard then marched away. A certain man told the story of these happenings to Cao Cao, who was very pleased, saying, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 118, 'talk': "I am anxious for Pang De's safety. He is over−bold and imprudent to fight with Guan Yu to the death.", 'context': 'But Jia Xu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'This Guan Yu lacks neither cunning nor valor. You are to be most cautious in engaging him. If you can conquer, then conquer; but if there be any doubt, remain on the defensive.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'How highly does our Prince regard this fellow Guan Yu!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 123, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'But I think I shall be able to take the keen edge off his thirty−year reputation.', 'context': ' said the general to his officers when he heard this new command. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'The command of the Prince is to be obeyed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'Seven armies of the north under Yu Jin are approaching. They are ten miles away. The van leader is Pang De.', 'context': 'Guan Yu was sitting in his tent when his spies came to report: “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'There is never a fighting man in all the world who has heard my name without trembling. Does this fellow dare disdain me?', 'context': 'Rage took possession of Guan Yu. His face changed color, his beard shook, and he roared out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Father,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'Taishan Mountain in its majesty does not quarrel with a pebble. Let me go and fight this Pang De.', 'context': ' said Guan Ping, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Well, my son, go and try; I will support you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 190, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Pang De, Corrector of the West', 'context': 'So Guan Ping took his sword, mounted his steed, and went out with his troops. Both sides being drawn up for battle. On the side of Wei there flew a single black flag on which was inscribed “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Turncoat! Traitor!', 'context': 'Guan Ping was very angry, crying out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who is that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 65, 'talk': "That is Guan Yu's adopted son, Guan Ping.", 'context': 'A certain one replied, “'},
{'istart': 233, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'Come quickly and be slain!', 'context': 'He sent Liao Hua to assault the city while he went to do battle with Pang De. Guan Ping met his father and related the story of the indecisive fight. So Guan Yu rode out with his green−dragon saber ready, and he shouted to Pang De, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'The edict from the Prince of Wei tells me to take your head. In case you disbelieve it, here is the coffin ready to receive it. If you fear death, down from your horse and surrender.', 'context': 'The drums reechoed as Pang De rode out and replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I hold you for a simple fool,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'People rumor Guan Yu is a mighty man of war; today I really believe that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'O General, you fought the great combat of a hundred bouts, which ended indecisively. I think it would be prudent to retire out of his way.', 'context': 'Then his chief, Yu Jin, came to see him and said, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'What makes you so soft? Yet the Prince gave you the command of the seven armies! But tomorrow I will fight again and that to the death. I swear I will never give way.', 'context': 'But Pang De replied haughtily, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'His swordsmanship is perfect; he is my worthy enemy.', 'context': 'When Guan Yu had got back to his camp, he extolled Pang De, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'The new−born calf fears not the tiger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 269, 'talk': "But if you slay this fellow, my father, you have only killed a barbarian of the tribes beyond the frontier. If any accident occurs, then you will have the reproach of not having considered your brother's charge.", 'context': ' said Guan Ping. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'How can my resentment be assuaged save by the death of this man?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'I have decided to fight, so say no more.', 'context': ' returned Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 422, 'iend': 510, 'talk': "Traitor! You want to use the 'swinging−horse stab,' but here I am, never afraid of that.", 'context': 'Next day Guan Yu took the field first, but Pang De quickly came out. Both arrayed their troops and then went to the front at the same moment. This time neither spoke, but the combat began forthwith. It went on for fifty bouts, and then Pang De pulled his horse, sheathed his sword, and fled. Guan Yu went in pursuit, and Guan Ping followed lest there should be need of him. Guan Yu roared out reviling to his flying foe, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'The bandit is going to shoot!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Why did the gongs clang?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 114, 'talk': "Because of our Prince's warning. Though Guan Yu was wounded, I feared some trick on his part. He is very cunning.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'I should have killed him if you had not done that,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Haste makes slow going; you can postpone your fight with him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'I swear I will have my revenge for this arrow.', 'context': 'Guan Yu was very bitter against his enemy and declared, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Never mind anything but recovering now,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Zengkou Stream,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I shall capture Yu Jin,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Why, how can any fish last long in such a trap?', 'context': 'He replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Do you not know even?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 465, 'talk': 'Our enemies have camped in difficult ground instead of the open country and are crowded in the dangerous valley there. After some days of this rain, River Xiang will swell, and I shall send people to dam up all the outlets and so let the water rise very high. When at its highest, I shall open the dams and let the water out over Fankou. That valley will be flooded too, and all the soldiers will become aquatic animals.', 'context': ' replied his father. “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 472, 'talk': 'The army is camped near the mouth of a stream in a depression. There are hills around us, but they are too far off to keep the water away. Our soldiers are already suffering from these heavy rains, and, moreover, they say the Jingzhou troops have moved to higher ground. More than that, at River Han they are preparing boats and rafts so that they can take advantage of the floods if there are any. Our army will be in great danger, and something should be done.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'You fool! Do you want to injure the spirit of our soldiers? Talk no more, or your head will be fallen.', 'context': 'But Yu Jin scoffed at his words, saying, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'What you said is excellent. If Yu Jin will not move camp tomorrow, I myself will do so.', 'context': 'Then he went to Pang De, who saw the force of his words and said, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'We have lost more than half of our men. Surrender is the only course.', 'context': 'Dong Chao pressed their chief to give in, saying, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'I have received great kindness from the Prince; think you that I will bow the head to any other?', 'context': 'But Pang De only raged, saying, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Anyone who says surrender shall be as these two.', 'context': 'Pang De cut down Dong Heng and Dong Chao right in the battlefield and then shouted, “'},
{'istart': 272, 'iend': 381, 'talk': 'The valorous leader fears death less than desertion; the brave warrior does not break faith to save his life,', 'context': "So the survivors made a desperate effort to beat off their enemies, and they held their own up to midday. Then Guan Yu's marines redoubled their efforts, and the arrows and stones rained down upon the defenders, who fought desperately hand to hand with their assailants. “"},
{'istart': 399, 'iend': 509, 'talk': 'This is the day of my death, but I will fight on to the last. And you, General, should fight to your end, too.', 'context': ' cried Pang De. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I will decide your fate when I return,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Rather than surrender to you, I would perish beneath the sword,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 514, 'talk': 'No! No! Though the force of these mountainous waters is great, we only have to wait ten days or so, and the flood will have passed. Though Guan Yu has not assaulted this city, yet he has sent another army to Jiaxia, which indicates he dares not advance lest we should fall upon his rear. Remember, too, that to retire from this city means the abandonment of everything south of the Yellow River. Therefore I decide that you defend this place.', 'context': 'But Man Chong interposed before the boats could be got ready. He said, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'What a tremendous error I should have committed had it not been for you, Sir!', 'context': 'Cao Ren saluted Man Chong as he concluded his harangue, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 142, 'talk': "The Prince's command being to defend this city, I shall defend it to the last. And I shall put to death anyone who even mentions abandonment,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'And we desire to defend it to out last gasp,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 274, 'iend': 338, 'talk': 'You lot of rats will not give in then! What are you waiting for?', 'context': "After Guan Xing's departure, the army was divided into two halves, one under Guan Yu to attack Fankou, and the other to go to Jiaxia. One day Guan Yu rode over to the north gate. Halting his steed, he pointed with his whip toward the defenders on the wall, and called out, “"},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 179, 'talk': "As fighting is impossible for the moment, we should withdraw to Jingzhou, where my father's wound can be treated.", 'context': 'Guan Ping consulted with the other leaders and proposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'What have you come for?', 'context': 'Having decided upon this, they went to see the wounded warrior. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'Considering that you, Sir, have been wounded in the right arm, we fear the result of the excitement of battle. Moreover, you can hardly take part in a fight just now, and we therefore propose that the army retire till you are recovered.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'I am on the point of taking the city, and if I succeed, I must press forward to Capital Xuchang, and destroy that brigand Cao Cao, so that the Hans may be restored to their own. Think you that I can vitiate the whole campaign because of a slight wound? Would you dishearten the army?', 'context': 'Guan Yu replied angrily, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'My name is Hua Tuo, and I belong to Qiao. I have heard of the wound sustained by the famous general and have come to heal it.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Surely you must be the physician who treated Zhou Tai in the South Land,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'I am.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'This was caused by an arrow,', 'context': 'Hua Tuo was introduced, asked to take a seat and, after the tea of ceremony, was shown the injured arm. “'},
{'istart': 153, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'There is poison in the wound, and it has penetrated to the bone. Unless the wound is soon treated, the arm will become useless.', 'context': ' said the doctor. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What do you propose to do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'I know how to cure the wound, but I think you will be afraid of the remedy.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Am I likely to be afraid of that when I am not even afraid of death? Death is only a return home after all.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'It all sounds easy enough;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'but why the post and the ring?', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I am just going to cut; do not start,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'When I consented to undergo the treatment, did you think I was afraid of pain?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 363, 'iend': 454, 'talk': 'This arm is now as good as it ever was; there is no pain. Indeed, Master, you are a marvel.', 'context': 'but he scraped it clean. When the knife went over the surface of the bone and made horrible sounds, all those near covered their eyes and turned pale. But Guan Yu went on with his game, only drinking a cup of wine now and again, and his face betrayed no sign of pain. When the wound had been cleansed, sewn up and dressed, the patient stood up smiling and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I have spent my life in the art;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'but I have never seen such a patient as you, Sir. You are as if not from the earth but heaven.', 'context': ' said Hua Tuo, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 323, 'talk': 'I had come to treat you, O General, from admiration of your great virtue and not for money. Although your wound is cured, you must be careful of your health, and especially avoid all excitement for a hundred days, when you will be as well as ever you were.', 'context': 'fee of a hundred ounces of gold. But Hua Tuo declined it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 481, 'talk': 'I must acknowledge this Guan Yu as the one man who, in skill and valor, overtops the whole world. Lately he has obtained possession of Jingzhou and the territory near it, and has so become very terrible. He is a tiger with wings added. Pang De is no more; Yu Jin is his prisoner; the armies of Wei have lost their morale; and if he led his armies here, Xuchang, we should be helpless. I can only think of avoiding the peril by removal of the capital. What think you?', 'context': 'Said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'No; do not take that step,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 532, 'talk': 'Yu Jin and all the others you lost were victims of the flood and slain in battle. These losses do no harm at all to your great plan. The Suns and Lius are no longer friends since Guan Yu has accomplished his desire. You may send a messenger into Wu to foment the quarrel and cause Sun Quan to send his armies to attack the army of Guan Yu from the rear, promising that, when things are tranquil, you will reward the south to Sun Quan. In this way you will relieve Fankou.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi, rising to reply. “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Sima Yi speaks well, and the messenger should lose no time. Do not move the capital or send an army.', 'context': 'Here Minister Jiang Ji said, “'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'Yu Jin had followed me faithfully for thirty years, yet in that moment of truth he was less than Pang De.', 'context': 'Cao Cao therefore did not carry out his first proposal. But he was sad at the loss of Yu Jin, and spoke of him affectionately, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'We know Guan Yu has captured one leader and slain another. This has added greatly to his fame and reputation. Cao Cao was going to move the capital rather than risk an attack. We also know that Fankou is in imminent danger. Cao Cao has asked for our help; but when he has gained his end, I doubt whether he will hold to his promise.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'The armies of Guan Yu being absent at Fankou, the opportunity should be taken to attack Jingzhou.', 'context': 'Said Lu Meng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'But I wish to attack Xuzhou in the north; what of this plan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'It would be better to attack Jingzhou, and so get control of the Great River. Cao Cao is far away to the north and too occupied to regard the east. Xuzhou is weakly held and could be taken easily, but the lie of the land favors the use of an army rather than a navy force. If you capture it, it will not be easy to hold; but once you hold Jingzhou, you can evolve other schemes.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 382, 'iend': 540, 'talk': 'Really, my desire was to attack Jingzhou, but I wished to hear what you would say to the other plan. Now, Sir, make me a plan speedily and I will act upon it.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'If this is so, it is hard to make a plan that will ensure success,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'I have already advised my master to attack Jingzhou, but I am unable to meet this complication.', 'context': ' said Lu Meng. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'The illness is feigned; he is quite well.', 'context': 'Then said Lu Xun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'If you know that so well, go and see,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'The Marquis of Wu has sent me to inquire after your honorable complaint,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I have a little remedy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Do you think you might use it?', 'context': ' said Lu Xun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'My friend, you speak as if you saw into my inmost heart. Pray unfold your good scheme.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'The plan seems most excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'As to the appointment at Lukou, you know Zhou Yu recommended Lu Su, who at his last moment proposed you. Now you ought to be able to mention some other talented and well−known officer to succeed you.', 'context': 'Sun Quan said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'If you choose a well−known man, Guan Yu will certainly be on his guard against him. Now Lu Xun is deep and farseeing, but he has no widespread fame. Hence no particular notice would be taken of his appointment and no countermeasures taken. So he is the most suitable person to send.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'I am very young,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'and feel unequal to such a post.', 'context': ' said Lu Xun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Lu Meng has proposed you, and you will not make any mistakes. Pray do not decline,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Friend Sun Quan was not very prudent when he made a general out of a mere scholar,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'General Lu Xun sends this letter and some presents, which he hopes you will accept. He also sends his felicitations, and would rejoice if the two houses could become friends.', 'context': 'The messenger said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Now is the favorable moment to get possession of Jingzhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I propose to send you and my brother, Sun Jiao, to lead the army.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 688, 'talk': "My lord, if you think to employ me, then employ me only; if Sun Jiao, then Sun Jiao only. You cannot have forgotten that Zhou Yu and Cheng Pu were associate commanders, and although the final decision lay with Zhou Yu, yet the other presumed upon his seniority and there was some unfriendliness between the two. All ended well because Cheng Pu recognized the ability of his colleague and so supported him. I know I am not so clever as Zhou Yu, but Sun Jiao's consanguinity will be a greater obstacle than mere length of service, and I fear he may not be wholly with me.", 'context': "This Sun Jiao was really only a cousin, as he was the second son of Sun Quan's uncle, Sun Jing. But Lu Meng objected. “"},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'We are traders forced into the bank by contrary winds.', 'context': 'When the beacon−keepers came down to question them, the men of Wu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'You are an old acquaintance, but you knew my order; why did you disobey it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 293, 'talk': 'I thought the rain would spoil my uniform, and I took the hat to protect it. I did not take it for my own advantage, but to protect official property. Spare me, O General, for the sake of our common dwelling−place.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I know you were protecting your armor, but still it was disobedience to the order against taking anything from the people.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'We have got the city of Jingzhou, but now Fu Shiren is holding Gongan and Mi Fang Nanjun. How can we get these two territories?', 'context': 'Then said Sun Quan to Lu Meng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'You will need neither bows nor arrows,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'unless my little tongue is worn out. I can persuade Fu Shiren to surrender.', 'context': ' said Yu Fan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Friend Yu Fan, how will you do it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'Fu Shiren and I are very old friends, ever since we were boys; and if I explain the matter to him, I am sure he will come over to this side.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 350, 'iend': 445, 'talk': 'I think I should do well in surrender, for at his departure Guan Yu was very bitter against me.', 'context': 'Now when Fu Shiren heard of the capture of Jingzhou, he closed his gates. Yu Fan arrived, but was refused entrance. So Yu Fan wrote a letter, attached it to an arrow, and shot it over the city wall. A soldier picked it up and took it to his commander, who found therein much persuasion to surrender. Having read all this, he thought within himself, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 248, 'talk': 'Guan Yu is yet unconquered; we should not put Fu Shiren in Gongan. Instead, send him to Nanjun to induce his former colleague and fellow Mi Fang to join him in desertion to the enemy.', 'context': 'Lu Meng thought the appointment imprudent and said to Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Go to Nanjun and win over Mi Fang, and I will reward you richly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'I am faithful enough, but I got into difficulties and danger and could not hold on, so I have surrendered to Wu. And I advise you to do the same.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'You and I have both fed on the bounty of the Prince of Hanzhong, and I cannot understand how you can turn against him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Guan Yu went away hating both of us intensely; and even if he comes back victorious, I do not think he will forgive us. Just think it over.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'My brother and I have followed the Prince these many years, and I do not like leaving him like this.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Where am I to get the rice?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'Jingzhou is now in the hands of Wu.', 'context': ' said he despairingly to his friend and tempter. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Do not dilly−dally,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'What have you done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 455, 'talk': 'Now that the relief of Fankou is contemplated, it would be well to shoot letter into the city to let the besieged know, so that they may not yield to depression and to inform Guan Yu. If Guan Yu hears that Jingzhou is in the hands of Wu, he will come back to try to recover it. Then let Xu Huang take the chance to attack, and our victory will be complete.', 'context': 'At the meeting of advisers that Cao Cao summoned to consultation, First Secretary Dong Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'Guan Ping, my worthy nephew, it is strange that you do not recognize death when it stares you in the face. Your Jingzhou has fallen into the hands of Wu, and yet you act so madly.', 'context': 'Xu Huang shouted out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'People say that Jingzhou has fallen to Lu Meng, and the news has frightened the whole army; what is to be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'It is only a malicious rumor; do not let it spread. If any one repeats it, put him to death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'If that goes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'There is no danger here,', 'context': 'if the enemy came. “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'The camp is defended by a tenfold line of thorny barriers; even a bird could not get in.', 'context': ' said they. “'},
{'istart': 175, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'Those soldiers are stationed in an unsafe place; let us raid their camp tonight.', 'context': 'Guan Ping and Liao Hua mustered all the veterans they had and went away to the first stockade. Seeing the Wei soldiers camped on a low hill, Guan Ping said to his colleague, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'You take half the force, General, and I will remain to keep the camp,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'This is a fabrication of the enemy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Father, you are not strong enough to go into the battle,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 7, 'iend': 380, 'talk': 'Some years have passed since I met you, most excellent Marquis, but I had not expected to see you so gray. I have not forgotten the old brave days, when we were together and you taught me so much, and I am very grateful. Your new fame has spread throughout the whole empire, and your old friends cannot but praise you. I am indeed glad that I have the happiness to see you.', 'context': 'said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'We have been excellent friends, Xu Huang—better than most. But why have you pressed my son so hardly of late?', 'context': 'Guan Yu replied, “'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 135, 'talk': "I would give a thousand ounces of gold for this Guan Yu's head.", 'context': 'Xu Huang suddenly turned to the officers about him and cried fiercely, “'},
{'istart': 170, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'What did you say that for?', 'context': ' Guan Yu, greatly shocked, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Because today I am on state business, and I have no inclination to let private friendship override my public duty.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Jingzhou has been taken by Lu Meng. Your family is now in the hand of enemy.', 'context': 'Suddenly the scouts reported: “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Fu Shiren has yielded Gongan to the hands of Wu.', 'context': 'Guan Yu was shocked; thence he marched for Gongan. But the scouts told him: “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Fu Shiren murdered the officer and persuade Mi Fang to surrender to Wu.', 'context': 'Then some of the men he had dispatched for supplies came in and reported: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Wang Fu, you were right,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'How I regret that I did not heed what you said! And now.', 'context': ' said he when he recovered consciousness. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'But why were the beacon fires not lighted?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 183, 'talk': "Lu Meng's marines in the guise of traders came over the river. There were soldiers hidden in the ships, and they seized the beacon guards, so preventing them from kindling the fires.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Indeed I have fallen into their trap. How shall I look my brother in the face?', 'context': 'Guan Yu sighed. Beating the ground with his foot, he said, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'We are in straits. Send to Chengdu for help, and let us take the land road to Jingzhou to try to recover it.', 'context': 'Then outspoke Commissariat Commander Zhao Lei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'It was the will of heaven, and no fault of yours,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'Xu Huang was very clever to overcome these. With my thirty years of war, I should not have dared to penetrate such opposition. He is valiant and wise, and both in a high degree.', 'context': 'When he visited Sizhong and had inspected the captured stockades, he remarked on the defenses, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Aye,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'General Xu Huang has the spirit of the old Zhou Yafu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'What is to be done,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'You must understand the different circumstances. When your general and I were leagued together, it was a personal matter between us two. Now things have changed. I am sent here with certain orders and am not my own master. I would trouble you, O Messenger, to return and explain thus to your master and in good words.', 'context': 'When Lu Meng read the letter, he said to the bearer thereof, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'The brigand! If I cannot slay him while I live, I will after I am dead. My hate shall not go unappeased.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Why do you not surrender, friend Guan Yu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Could I give in to a rebel; I, a servant of the Hans and a leader of their army?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 172, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Natives of Jingzhou', 'context': 'Before he had gone very far, he saw signs of many people bivouacking among the hills, and presently made out, on a huge white banner that flapped in the breeze, the words “'},
{'istart': 234, 'iend': 285, 'talk': 'All the inhabitants of this place have surrendered.', 'context': ', and the people about were calling out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': "The soldiers' hearts are all melted,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Who will try to break through and go away to Shangyong for assistance?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I will go,', 'context': ' asked Guan Yu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'And I will escort you past the danger zone,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'Guan Yu is closely besieged in Maicheng. Help from the west will be a long time in coming, so I have been sent to beg your assistance. I hope you will march the Shangyong troops thither as quickly as possible, for any delay will be fatal.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Sir, go to the rest−house for a time till we can decide.', 'context': 'Liu Feng replied, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'This is bad news; what is to be done?', 'context': 'Liu Feng said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Wu is very powerful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'I know all this. But Guan Yu is my uncle, and I cannot bear to sit still and not try to save him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'So you hold him as an uncle!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Granted that what you say is true, still what reply can we give?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'Simply say that this city is still unsettled, and you dare not move lest it be lost.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'If you act thus, there is an end of Guan Yu!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Will a cup of water extinguish a wagon load of blazing wood?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Hasten back and await patiently for the coming of help from the west.', 'context': ' said Meng Da. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 584, 'talk': 'I come at the command of my master, the Marquis of Wu, to persuade you to a wise course. From of old it has always been recognized that the hero must bow to circumstances. The region with its nine territories and forty−one counties that you ruled have come under another, with the exception of this single city. Within, there is no food, without, no help, so that it must fall quickly. Wherefore, O General, why not hear me and join your fortunes to those of Wu? You shall be restored to your governorship, and you will preserve your family. If haply, Sir, you would reflect thereon.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 423, 'talk': "I am a simple soldier from the village of Jieliang. I am the 'hands and feet' of my lord. How can I betray him? The city may fall, and then I can but die. Jade may be shattered, but its whiteness remains; bamboo may be burned, but its joints stand straight. My body may be broken, but my fame shall live in history. Say no more, but leave the city, I beg. I will fight Sun Quan to the death.", 'context': 'Guan Yu replied, quite calmly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'My master desires to enter into such a league with you as did Jin and Qin in former days, that you may mutually assist to destroy Cao Cao and restore the Hans. That is his idea, and why do you persist in this wrong course?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'Remember his brother is in Shu, helping your uncle. If you hurt him, you will injure the principle of fraternity.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'He is indeed a loyal servant!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Still, what is to be done next?', 'context': ' said Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Take some casts in the Book of Changes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'If he flies to a distance, how can he be captured?', 'context': 'Then Sun Quan asked Lu Meng, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'The divination exactly fits in with my schemes;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 559, 'talk': 'This Guan Yu has very few soldiers left, and he will not venture along the high road. North of Maicheng is a risky path, and he will try to escape along that. Therefore you must lay an ambush for him seven miles away from the city, but do not stop him. Let him go by, and then harass his rear. Thus he will be forced into Linju. Set another small ambush near there, and you will capture your enemy. For the present, attack the city vigorously on all sides but one, leaving the north gate for escape.', 'context': 'Sun Quan having asked Lu Meng for a plan, Lu Meng replied, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'The enemy will flee toward the northwest, but will be caught that night before midnight.', 'context': 'Before carrying out this plan, Sun Quan bade Lu Fan consult the auspices. He did so, announcing, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'I regret that I have neglected your wise warning; in this danger what is to be done?', 'context': 'Again he bewailed to Wang Fu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'I think even if Lu Wang could come to life again, he would be helpless in this case,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'Liu Feng and Meng Da have surely decided not to send help from Shangyong. Let us abandon this miserable place, try to get to Yiazhou, and recover the army. We may then tempt our fortune once more.', 'context': 'Said Zhao Lei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I agree with you that that is the best plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'There are only paths there, but by them one may get into the Western Land of Rivers.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'We will go that way tonight,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'General, you will surely fall into an ambush. The main road will be safer.', 'context': 'Wang Fu opposed it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'There may be an ambush, but do I fear that?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'At least be very cautious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'I will defend this city to the very last; I only need a hundred troops. Never will we surrender. Only I hope, most noble General, that you will send me speedy help.', 'context': ' said Wang Fu. “'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'Guan Yu, do not run! Surrender and live!', 'context': 'Soon appeared a large force with Zhu Ran at their head. He came dashing forward, and summoned the small party, saying, “'},
{'istart': 451, 'iend': 484, 'talk': 'Zhao Lei has fallen in the melee!', 'context': "Still he struggled on. A few miles farther the drums rolled again, and torches lit up all round. This was Pan Zhang's ambush, and he appeared flourishing his sword. Guan Yu whirled his blade and went to meet him, but Pan Zhang ran away after a couple of bouts. However, Guan Yu saw they were too many for him, and sought refuge among the mountains. His son followed, and when he got within speaking distance, Guan Ping gave him the mournful tidings: “"},
{'istart': 223, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'I have long had a friendly feeling for you,', 'context': 'With great joy Sun Quan heard of the success of his plans. In the morning, he assembled all his officers in his tent to await the arrival of the prisoners. Before long, Ma Zhong came hustling his prisoner before his lord. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'He is a real hero, and I love him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'You are right,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 446, 'iend': 450, 'talk': 'Way.', 'context': 'certain spot in Dangyang on a famous hill known as the Mount of the Jade Spring. There lived a venerable Buddhist priest whose name in the faith was Transverse−Peace. He was originally of the Guardian Temple in the River Si Pass and abbot of that temple. In the course of roaming about the world, he had reached this place. Entranced with its natural beauty, he had built himself a shelter of boughs and grass, where he sat in meditation on the “'},
{'istart': 210, 'iend': 247, 'talk': 'Give back my head; give back my head.', 'context': 'This night, about the third watch, the moon was bright and the air serene. Transverse−Peace sat in his usual attitude in the silence of the mountains. Suddenly he heard a great voice calling in the upper air, “'},
{'istart': 130, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Where is Guan Yu?', 'context': "The recluse recognized the figure as that of Guan Yu, so with his yak's tail flagellum he smote the lintel of his hut and cried, “"},
{'istart': 175, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'Who is my teacher, and what is his name in the faith?', 'context': 'The spirit understood, and the figure dismounted, glided down, and came to rest at the door of the hut. Interlacing its fingers, it stood in a reverential attitude and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'In the state Guardian Temple in River Si Pass, I once saw you, O noble Sir, and I was not likely to forget your face,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'I am deeply grateful for the help you gave me. Misfortune has befallen me, and I have ceased to live. I would seek the pure instruction and beg you to indicate the obscure way.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 320, 'talk': 'Let us not discuss former wrongdoings nor present correct actions. Later events are the inevitable result of former causes. I know that Lu Meng has injured you. You call aloud for the return of your head; who will also return the heads of your several victims—Yan Liang, Wen Chou, and the commanders of the five passes?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'In the light of clear lamp, reading the histories, resting on the Green−Dragon saber curved as the young moon, heart pure as the azure heaven.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'After long waiting, the desire of my heart has come to me very easily through the magnificent efforts of my friend Lu Meng.', 'context': 'Sun Quan made a speech, saying, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 690, 'talk': 'My good Zhou Yu was superior to most humans, and he defeated Cao Cao at the Red Cliffs. Alas! He died too soon. My good Lu Su succeeded him. In his first interview, he inaugurated the general policy of creating a state. That was the first instance of his keen insight. When Cao Cao descended upon my country, and everyone counseled me to yield, he advised me to summon my good Zhou Yu to oppose and smite Cao Cao. That was the second instance of his keen insight. He made only one fault; he advised me to let Liu Bei occupy Jingzhou. Now today my good Lu Meng has succeeded, and in that he far surpasses both his predecessors.', 'context': 'Lu Meng bowed and bowed deprecatingly, but Sun Quan continued, “'},
{'istart': 220, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'O green−eyed boy! O red−bearded rat! Do you know me?', 'context': 'Then Sun Quan filled a goblet and in person presented it to the guest of the evening. Lu Meng took the cup, but as he raised it, a sudden change came over him. Dashing the cup to the ground, he seized Sun Quan, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'After I quelled the Yellow Scarves, I went hither and thither for thirty years. Now I have fallen victim to your base plots, and you have overcome me. If living, I have been unable to gorge upon the flesh of my enemy; dead, I will pursue the spirit of this bandit Lu Meng. I am the Lord of Hanshou, Guan Yu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Yes; I have made a little mistake,', 'context': 'Sun Quan started up in a fright. “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'But seeing it is so, what shall I do?', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'You need have no fear,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'I have a plan to fend off the armies of the west from our borders and keep Jingzhou quite safe.', 'context': ' replied Zhang Zhao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'What is your plan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 547, 'talk': "Cao Cao with his many legions is greedily aiming at the whole empire. If Liu Bei wants revenge, he will ally himself with Cao Cao, and, should they combine against this country, we should be in great danger. Therefore I advise you to send Guan Yu's head to Cao Cao to make it appear that Cao Cao was the prime cause of his destruction. This should divert Liu Bei's extreme hatred toward Cao Cao and send the armies of Shu against Wei instead of toward Wu. After carefully considering the whole matter, I counsel this as the best course of action.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 149, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'So Guan Yu is dead; now I can stick to my mat and sleep soundly at night.', 'context': "At this time Cao Cao's army had marched back from Mopo to Luoyang. When he heard of the coming of the gruesome gift, he was glad at heart and said, “"},
{'istart': 296, 'iend': 335, 'talk': 'This is a trick to divert evil from Wu.', 'context': ' But Sima Yi saw through the ruse and said from his place by the steps, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'What do you mean? How?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 392, 'talk': "The Peach Garden Oath bound the three brothers to live and die together. Now Wu is fearful of revenge for the execution of one of the three and sends the head to you to cause Liu Bei's wrath to fasten on you, O Prince. Sun Quan wishes Liu Bei to attack you instead of himself, the real perpetrator of the crime. Then he will find a way of accomplishing his ends while you two are quarreling.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'You are right, friend;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'and now how can we escape?', 'context': ' said Cao Cao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I hope you have been well since our last meeting, Guan Yu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'General Guan Yu is indeed a spirit,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 360, 'talk': 'O Prince, thy consort has passed away and the Lady Sun has returned to her maiden home, perhaps never to come again. Human relations should not be set at nought, wherefore a secondary consort should be sought, so that all things may be correctly ordered within the palace.', 'context': 'The Prince of Hanzhong returned to his capital Chengdu. Fa Zheng memorialized, saying, “'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'There is the sister of Wu Yi, comely and good, and declared by the physiognomist as destined to high honor. She was betrothed to Liu Mao, son of Liu Yan, but he died in youth, and she has remained unwedded. Take her as a wife.', 'context': 'The Prince having signified his acceptance of the principle, Fa Zheng continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'It is incompatible with propriety; Liu Mao and I are of the same ancestry.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'As to the degree of relationship, would it differ from the marriage of Duke Wen of Jin and Huai Ying?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Jingzhou is in danger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Recall and replace Guan Yu.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Who are you, who thus come by night to my chamber?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'Brother, there is nothing wrong, I hope. But surely something of great importance brings you here thus in the dead of the night. And why do you avoid me, your brother, who loves you as himself?', 'context': 'Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'Brother, send your armies to avenge me.', 'context': 'Then the figure wept and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'You have been thinking too deeply of Guan Yu lately, my lord,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'There is no need to be distressed.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'What is your secret?', 'context': 'very secret piece of news, and they told me to find you here.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'There is a report about that Wu has got possession of Jingzhou; Lu Meng has taken it. And more than that, Guan Yu is dead. I had to come to tell you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'I saw it in the sky some nights ago. A large star of a general fell over against Jingzhou, and I knew some evil had befallen Guan Yu. But I feared the effect upon our master, and I forbore to say anything.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'Why did you hide from me? Why, when you had such terrible news?', 'context': 'They did not know that Liu Bei was standing just within the door. Suddenly he rushed out, seized Zhuge Liang by the sleeve and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Because it is only a rumor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'It is too improbable for belief. We pray you not to be distressed.', 'context': ' replied they. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'By our oath we live or die together; how can I go on living if he is lost?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Jingzhou has indeed been lost, and Guan Yu begs for instant help.', 'context': 'attendants said that Ma Liang and Yi Ji had arrived. Liu Bei called them in and questioned them eagerly. They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Then is my brother lost!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'If those two have really behaved so badly, the offense is even too great for death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'But calm yourself, O Prince. I will see about an army and lead it to the rescue.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'If Guan Yu is gone, I cannot live,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Tomorrow I myself will set out with an army to rescue him.', 'context': ' moaned Liu Bei. “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'Guan Yu had cut his way to Linju at night and been captured by a general of Wu. He had refused to bend, and both father and son had gone to the Nine Springs.', 'context': 'Before day dawned other messengers arrived, giving step by step the sequence of the tragedy: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'My lord, control your grief,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'Life and death are fixed by fate. Guan Yu brought the evil upon himself by his harshness and haughtiness. You must now take care of your health and mature your vengeance.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'When we swore brotherhood in the Peach Garden, we pledged ourselves to live or die together. What enjoyment of riches and honors is there for me now that my brother is gone?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'I swear I will not live under the same heaven as Sun Quan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'It is said that the head of your brother has been sent to Cao Cao, but Cao Cao has buried the remains with the rites of a princely noble,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Why did he do that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 185, 'talk': 'Because Sun Quan thought thereby to bring evil upon Cao Cao. But Cao Cao saw through the subterfuge and has buried your brother with great honor so that your anger may burn against Wu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'I want to send my armies to punish Wu and appease my wrath,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 314, 'talk': 'No; you may not do that. Wu wishes to move you to smite Wei, and Wei wishes you to attack Wu, each harboring the malevolent design of taking advantage of the quarrel. You would do well, my lord, to keep your armies at home. Put on mourning for Guan Yu, and wait till Wei and Wu are at war. That will be your time.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'There is much witchcraft and malign influence in this old palace at Luoyang; build a new palace for your own occupation,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'But where is the good architect?', 'context': "“I would, and it should be called 'The Firm Foundation,'“ said he. “"},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'There is one Su Yue, a very cunning artificer in Luoyang.', 'context': ' Jia Xu said, “'},
