{'istart': 106, 'iend': 396, 'talk': 'I am doomed, I know. The pity is that my Black Bag treatise on medicine may be lost. You have been most kind to me, and as I have no other way of recompensing you, I will give you a letter to my wife telling her to send the Black Bag, and I will give it to you that you may carry on my art.', 'context': 'Hua Tuo and saw that he was well fed. Hua Tuo conceived a liking for his gaoler and said to him one day, “'},
{'istart': 438, 'iend': 552, 'talk': 'If you become such a learned person as Hua Tuo, you will only die in prison like him. What good did it all do him?', 'context': 'Ten days after this, Hua Tuo died in prison. Wu the Gaoler bought a coffin and had him buried. This done, he quitted the prison and went home. But when he asked for the book, he found that his wife had discovered it and was using it to light the fire. He snatched away what was left of it, but a whole volume was missing, and what was left amounted only to a few pages. He vented his anger in cursing his wife, and she retorted, saying, “'},
{'istart': 156, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'Treatise of the Black Bag', 'context': 'It struck Wu the Gaoler that there was something in what she said, and he ceased grumbling at her. But the upshot of all this was that the learning in the “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Is this youth trying to put me on a furnace?', 'context': 'Cao Cao laughed as he read this, and he said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 170, 'iend': 544, 'talk': 'O Prince, the Hans have been feeble too long, while your virtues and merits are like the mountains. All the people look to you, and when Sun Quan acknowledged himself as your minister, he is but responsive to the will of God and the desire of humans. It is wrong that you oppose when such contrary influences work to a common end, and you must soon ascend to the high place.', 'context': ' But Minister Chen Qun and the attendants seriously replied, “'},
{'istart': 151, 'iend': 301, 'talk': 'I saw three horses feeding on the same manger before the family of Ma Teng was harmed. Last night I saw the same dream again. How do you interpret it?', 'context': "Cao Cao's condition grew worse daily. One night he had a dream of three horses feeding out of the same manger. Next day he told it to Jia Xu, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'It is auspicious to dream of dignity,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'And naturally such an honor comes to the Caos. I do not think you need feel any misgivings.', 'context': ' replied Jia Xu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'O Prince, you should summon the Taoists to offer sacrifices and prayers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Take good care of your precious self, O Prince, that you may quickly recover.', 'context': 'Cao Hong, speaking for the four, said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 797, 'talk': 'Thirty and more years have I gone up and down, and many a bold leader has fallen before me. The only ones that remain are Sun Quan in the south and Liu Bei in the west. I have not yet slain them. Now I am very ill, and I shall never again stand before you; wherefore my family affairs must be settled. My first born—Cao Ang, son of Lady Liu—fell in battle at Wancheng, when he was young. The Lady Bian bore four sons to me, as you know. The third, Cao Zhi, was my favorite, but he was vain and unreliable, fond of wine and lax in morals. Therefore he is not my heir. My second son, Cao Zhang, is valiant, but imprudent. The fourth, Cao Xiong, is a weakly and may not live long. My eldest, Cao Pi, is steady and serious; he is fit to succeed me, and I look to you to support him.', 'context': 'But Cao Cao said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'After my death you must diligently attend to your womanly labors. You can make silken shoes for sale, and so earn your own living.', 'context': 'And he said to them, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'A Song of Yejun', 'context': 'A certain poet composed “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'I would request the heir to cease lamentation for the dead and devote himself to the present needs of state.', 'context': 'Suddenly one stood out from the ranks of the mourners and said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'The death of the Prince will cause an upheaval in the empire, and it is essential that the heir should assume his dignity without loss of time. There is not mourning alone to be seen to.', 'context': 'It was Sima Fu, and he continued, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'The Prince of Wei is dead and the world is in commotion; why do you not invest his successor quickly?', 'context': 'what his sudden arrival meant. Soon he entered the hall and said, “'},
