{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I have procured the Imperial edict here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'Cao Zhang, Lord of Yanling, with an army of one hundred thousand troops, is approaching from Changan.', 'context': 'However, all was not to pass too smoothly. While the banquet was in progress, the news came: “'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 264, 'talk': 'What shall I do? This young, golden−bearded brother of mine, always obstinate and determined and with no little military skill, is marching hither with an army to contest my inheritance.', 'context': 'In a state of consternation, the new Prince turned to his courtiers, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Let me go to see the Marquis; I can make him desist,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Only yourself, O Exalted One, can save us in this peril!', 'context': ' said one of the guests. The others cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': "Who has the late Prince's seal?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'You come as a mourner or as a rival claimant?', 'context': 'suddenly asked him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'I am come as a mourner; I never had any ulterior motive.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'That being so; why bring in your soldiers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'Cao Xiong, the Lord of Xiaohuai, had hanged himself rather than suffer for his fault.', 'context': 'Cao Pi took up the suggestion and sent commissioners to each. They who were sent to the younger quickly returned to report: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'And then Cao Zhi, in a fit of anger, had ordered his lictors to beat the chief envoy and turn him out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'Your brother has always had that weakness for wine, but we let him go his way out of consideration for his undoubted ability. I hope you will not forget he is your brother and that I bore you both. Spare his life that I may close my eyes in peace when I set out for the deep springs.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'I also admire his ability, Mother, and have no intention to hurt him. But I would reform him. Have no anxiety as to his fate,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Surely the Princess−Mother has just been interceding for your brother; is it not so?', 'context': 'Said Hua Xin, “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'It is so,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Then let me say that Cao Zhi is too clever to be content to remain in a humble station. If you do not remove him, he will do you harm.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 170, 'talk': "I must obey my mother's command.", 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'People say your brother simply talks in literature. I do not believe it myself, but he might be put to the test. If he bears a false reputation, you can slay him; if what they say is true, then degrade him, lest the scholars of the land should babble.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 487, 'talk': "Though we are brothers, yet the proper relation between us of prince and minister must not be overlooked. Why then did you behave indecorously? While the late Prince lived, you made a boast of your literary powers, but I am disposed to think you may have made use of another's pen. Now I require you to compose a poem within the time taken to walk seven paces, and I will spare your life if you succeed. If you fail, then I shall punish you with rigor.", 'context': 'The Prince addressed him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Will you suggest a theme?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'brother', 'context': 'so he bade his brother improvise on the theme of their fraternal relationship, the words “brotherhood" or “'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'Should the elder brother thus oppress the younger?', 'context': 'The mother of both men came out at this moment from her abiding place and said, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'My mother, the laws of the state cannot be nullified.', 'context': 'The Prince jumped from his seat, saying, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 384, 'talk': 'Since the death of Cao Cao and the accession of his son, the position of the Emperor has changed for the worse. Sun Quan acknowledges the lordship of Wei, and its influence is becoming too great. I am disposed to destroy Sun Quan in revenge for the death of my brother. That done. I will proceed to the Capital District and purge the whole land of rebellion. What think you?', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'Liu Feng and Meng Da were the true cause of the death of your brother and his adopted son; both these renegades deserve death.', 'context': 'Then Liao Hua stood out from the ranks of officers and threw himself upon the earth, saying with tears, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'That is not the way; go slowly or you may stir up strife. Promote these two and separate them. After that you may arrest.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 516, 'iend': 605, 'talk': 'The Prince of Hanzhong used to look on you with great favor; why does he do so no longer?', 'context': "Now Peng Yang and Meng Da were old friends. Hearing what was afoot, the former hastened home and wrote warning his friend. The letter was confided to a trusty messenger to bear to Meng Da. The messenger was caught as he went out of the city and carried before Ma Chao, who thus got wind of the business. He then went to Peng Yang's house, where, nothing being suspected, he was received kindly and wine was brought in. The two drank for some time. When Ma Chao thought his host sufficiently off his guard, he said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'The obstinate old leather−belly! But I will find some way to pay him out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'What you propose is very feasible, but we will talk it over again tomorrow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'That fellow Peng Yang meant to turn traitor; what shall I do with him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'The fellow is something of a scholar, but irresponsible,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 154, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'He is too dangerous to be left alive.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'My friend Peng Yang and I did much for the Prince of Hanzhong. But now Peng Yang is dead, and I am forgotten. More than that, the Prince wishes to put me to death. What can I do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'I think I can find a plan that will secure your safety.', 'context': 'Shen Dan replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'What is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'They say that dissolution of bonds should not occasion recrimination, and the dismissed servant should take leave without heart−burning. I have taken your orders many times, and now, O Prince, you must act yourself. I write this with extreme trepidation.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'The unmerited fellow!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'He turns traitor and dares to insult me by sending a letter of farewell.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'You would better send Liu Feng to capture him and let the two tigers worry each other to weakness. Whether Liu Feng succeeds or fails, he will have to come to the capital, and you can kill him. Thus will you cut off two evils.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'You seem to be true. Go then to Xiangyang and take Liu Feng. If you bring me his head, I shall no longer doubt.', 'context': 'large army, and had attacked Xiangyang and was challenging Meng Da to battle, Cao Pi said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I will convince him by argument; no soldiers will be needed. I will bring him to surrender too.', 'context': 'Meng Da replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'The renegade has already made me offend against my duty to my uncle, and now would sever me from my father so that I shall be reproached as disloyal and unfilial,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Death is very near you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'yet you continue blindly in the way of foolishness and will not understand.', 'context': ' replied Meng Da, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I have surrendered to Wei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'Shameful son! How are you come to see me at all?', 'context': 'Seeking an interview with his father, he found but scant sympathy, for in response to his petition, made prostrate, and weeping, Liu Bei said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 86, 'talk': "My uncle's mishap was not due to my refusal of help, but because Meng Da thwarted me.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'You eat as a man, you dress as a man; but you have no more the instincts of a man than an image of clay or wood. What mean you by saying another wretch thwarted you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 321, 'iend': 430, 'talk': 'Those splendid signs presage that Wei is about to supplant Han, and the altar of abdication should be set up.', 'context': 'In the late summer of this same year, it was reported that a phoenix had been seen to bow at Shiyi, and a linlion had appeared at Linzi, while a yellow dragon was observed in Yejun. Whereupon Imperial Commander Li Fu and Minister Xu Zhi discussed these appearances, and putting them all together they concluded, saying, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 1044, 'talk': 'Since the inauguration of the Prince of Wei, virtue has spread to the four corners of the empire and humanity has permeated all the earth to a degree unexcelled in all the ages, even in the days of the ancient rulers, King Tang and King Yu. We, your servants, have taken account of these things and have reached the conclusion that the fortunes of Han is worn out, wherefore we trust Your Majesty, in imitation of the great prototypes King Yao and King Shun, will yield the mountains, the rivers, and the peoples to a more able guardian and high priest of the sacrifices in the person of the Prince of Wei, thereby pleasing Heaven and satisfying the hearts of humans, and enabling Your Majesty to enjoy the happiness of freedom and repose from the exacting duties of the chief ruler. The happiness of your ancestors and of humanity at large would thereby be enhanced. Having thoroughly debated this matter, we have come to lay it before you.', 'context': 'Hua Xin was the spokesman of the deputation of officers that went into the palace, and he spoke thus: “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 458, 'talk': 'How can I abandon my empire for the sake of repose—the empire won by my Great Ancestor, its Founder, when, with a three−span sword, he slew the Snake and restored Right, and consolidated when he reduced Qin and overwhelmed Chu—the empire which has been handed down for four centuries? Though I possess not brilliant talents, yet I have done no wrong. Go back and debate this again in a just and moderate spirit.', 'context': 'Then, looking at the assembly, he said sadly, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'If Your Majesty thinks we may be mistaken, pray ask these two, who will explain.', 'context': 'Then Hua Xin led forward Xu Zhi and Li Fu nearer the throne, saying, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'Since the Prince of Wei has taken his seat, the Linlion has descended, the Phoenix has appeared, the yellow Dragon has come forth, the Grain of Felicity has flourished, and Sweet Dew has watered the earth. All these things augur that Heaven decrees a change and Wei must replace Han.', 'context': 'Said Li Fu, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 838, 'talk': "The astrologers, watching the aspect of the skies at night, have seen the blazing light of the star of Han gradually fade away and Your Majesty's own star become dim. On the other hand, the aspect of the sky and the attitude of the earth have been wholly bright in favor of Wei to a degree hard to state in words. Moreover, the lots have been cast, and they gave the word 'Devil, at the side, has been sent, there must be an inroad upon Han without word'; another lot, 'Word, in east, light moves west, two suns radiating as the air blows south.' These oracles gave two words which, joined, compose Xu; 'two suns, one on the other,' which is Chang. These signs are unmistakeable, for when put together the whole reads, 'Wei at Xuchang is to receive the abdication of Han.' If you consider, Your Majesty must admit this.", 'context': 'Xu Zhi continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'All empty words and madness, this talk of auguries and lots! Is it reasonable that I should suddenly abandon the great heritage for such nonsense?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 368, 'talk': 'Wax and wane has been the law of all things from the beginning; every period of glory is followed by one of obscurity. Has any rule endured forever or any House never failed? The rule of Han, handed down through four centuries to Yourself, has lost its vigor, and the time has come to yield. Retirement may not be delayed or confusion will ensue.', 'context': 'Then Wang Lang said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Why do Your Majesty not hold the court as usual, especially when you are requested to go out?', 'context': 'The Empress Cao asked him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'Because your brother wishes to depose me and become Emperor himself. He has set the whole host of officers against me to force me to abdicate, and I will not expose myself to this compulsion.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'But what can have induced my brother to do such a dreadfully rebellious thing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Your Majesty should act as was advised yesterday and so avoid any misfortune.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Who would dare to murder me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Is it consent or not?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'One word!', 'context': ' cried he angrily. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Where is the Keeper of the Seal?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'The Prince will always take care of Your Majesty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 329, 'talk': 'By all noble principles the empire is no private possession, but a public trust. Wherefore the great King Yao, to his eternal glory, passed over his own son. How I admire this deed! Now in imitation thereof I have resolved to abdicate in favor of my Chief Minister, the Prince of Wei, who will not, I hope, disappoint my wishes.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'By the hand of the Minister Zhang Yin, this is sent with the emblems and the seal.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'That is easily arranged,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 357, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'Founder of the Dynasty', 'context': 'Emperor. Then Jia Xu, at the head of the great concourse of officers, came to the foot of the terrace, and a court was held. The year of reign was changed from Prolonged Wealth, the First Year, to Yellow Dawn, the First Year (AD 220), and the government became that of Great Wei. An edict was then published proclaiming a general amnesty, and the title of “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'As heaven has but one sun, so the people can have but one ruler. The Hans have abdicated, and it is fitting that they withdraw to a distance. I pray for an edict naming the place of residence of the Liu family.', 'context': 'Then said Hua Xin, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 314, 'talk': 'It is an old rule that the setting up of one Emperor means the degradation of another. Now, through the gracious kindness of His Majesty, you are spared personal injury and created a duke. Proceed at once and return not to court without express command.', 'context': 'Thereupon Hua Xin drew his sword and in a harsh voice said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'Now I understand the story of Shun and Yu.', 'context': 'Said Cao Pi to his courtiers, “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'O ruler, may thy life be eternal!', 'context': ' Then they all shouted: “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 331, 'talk': 'There have been auspicious indications. A yellow vapor has been seen in the northwest of Chengdu rising to the clouds, and the star of emperor has greatly increased in splendor and shined like the moon. These signs mean that our Prince is to become Emperor in succession to the House of Han. There can be no doubt.', 'context': 'Qiao Zhou said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'O Nobles, do you desire to set my feet in the way of disloyalty and wrong−doing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Not so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Can I imitate the deeds of such a rebel?', 'context': 'But the Prince suddenly showed anger, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 353, 'talk': 'The late Emperor of the Hans has been slain by Cao Pi. You, O Prince, will fail both in loyalty and rectitude if you do not assume the succession and destroy the wrong−doers. The whole empire requests you to rule that you may avenge the death of the late Emperor, and the people will be disappointed if you do not accede to their wishes.', 'context': 'Xu Jing spoke, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 204, 'talk': "Although I am descended from the grandson of Emperor Myers, I have not been of the least advantage; and if I assumed the title of 'Emperor,' how would that act differ from usurpation?", 'context': 'The Prince replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'What illness affects you, my Commander−in−Chief?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'My heart is sad like unto burning, and I shall soon die.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'What is it that causes you such grief?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Unless I refused, the whole land would blame me; and I am afraid,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'When you have recovered, it shall be done,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'So you have consented. O Prince! Then choose the day for the ceremony.', 'context': 'high officers, who prostrated themselves, crying, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'You are committing me to doing what is dishonorable!', 'context': 'The Prince was greatly startled, and said, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'Since consent has been given, let a terrace be built and a day chosen for the great ceremony.', 'context': 'But Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 242, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'I, Liu Bei, am unfitted; I pray that another, more able, may be chosen.', 'context': 'When the reading was ended, and the sacrifice and the prayer, Zhuge Liang, in the name of all those assembled, presented the Imperial Seal. The Prince received it in both hands, laid it upon the altar, and again declined acceptance, saying, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 260, 'talk': 'Our lord has settled the empire, and his merits are manifest to the whole world. Moreover, he is of the Dynastic Family and it is fitting that he succeed. Now that the great announcement has been made, such self−abnegation is impossible.', 'context': 'But Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Eternal life to the Emperor!', 'context': 'So all the officers shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 390, 'talk': 'In the Peach Garden I and my brothers Guan Yu and Zhang Fei pledged ourselves to live and die together. Unhappily my brother Guan Yu came to his end at the hands of Sun Quan of Wu, and I must avenge him lest I fail to fulfill the oath. Therefore will I devote the whole force of my kingdom to the destruction of Wu and the capture of its rebellious chief, whereby to wipe away my reproach.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'It may not be so.', 'context': 'But just as he closed this oration, an officer threw himself down at the foot of the throne, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Dire vengeance will I wreak!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Do no such thing.', 'context': 'His minister replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 523, 'talk': 'The real rebel was not Sun Quan, but Cao Cao; and now it is his son who has usurped the Imperial Throne and called forth the anger of gods and men. You should first aim at the inside by camping on the River Wei, from which to attack the rebel. After that the right−thinking sort on the east of the Passes will do their utmost to help you. If you leave River Wei out of consideration in order to fight Wu, your military force will be engaged, and could you disengage it quickly in case of necessity? It is worth reflection.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'Sun Quan slew my brother. Furthermore, Fu Shiren, Mi Fang, Pan Zhang, and Ma Zhong are on his side, all of whom I hate so much that I could eat their flesh with gusto and devour their relatives, whereby I should have my vengeance. Why, Noble Sir, do you obstruct me?', 'context': 'The First Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 149, 'talk': "Because the enmity against Cao Cao is a public matter; vengeance for the manner of your brother's end is private. The empire should be placed first.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'What care I for myriads of square miles of territory as long as my brother is unavenged?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'My enmity for the death of my brother is deep as the sea. Why do not the officers at the court propose an avenging expedition?', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Most of them favor first the destruction of Wei; Wu is to follow.', 'context': 'The messenger replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What sort of talk is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 285, 'talk': "It is not in accordance with the importance due to the Emperor's position that he should go in personal command of this army, particularly as he has but lately assumed his throne. You, Sir, hold the weighty post of adviser in such a matter, and why do you not dissuade him?", 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'I have done so, most sincerely and repeatedly, but he will not listen. But now you all come with me to the drill ground, and we will try once more.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 429, 'talk': 'Your Majesty has but lately taken the imperial seat. If the expedition was one to march northward to destroy the rebels against Han and in the interest of rectitude, it would be perfectly correct for the Emperor to lead the army, but an officer of high rank should more properly be sent against Wu. Why should Your Majesty expose yourself to such fatigues?', 'context': 'So they proceeded thither, with Zhuge Liang at their head, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 120, 'talk': "Your Majesty is now ruler and too quickly forgets the oath in the Peach Garden; why is our brother's death not avenged?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'Many officers dissuade me from such a course; I cannot act rashly.', 'context': 'The First Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'What do others know of our oath? If Your Majesty will not go, then let me sacrifice myself to avenge our brother. If I cannot, then would I rather die and see your face no more.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Then will I go with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'Bring your own troops from Langzhong, and I will bring my veterans to meet you at Jiangzhou. We will both attack Wu and wipe out the reproach.', 'context': ' said the First Ruler. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 345, 'talk': 'I know that your weakness for wine leads you astray, and you become very cruel in your cups, and hog your people, and keep the beaten ones near you. They may be dangerous, and it is certainly the road to misfortune. Now you must be more kindly and not give way to passion as before.', 'context': 'As Zhang Fei rose to take leave, the First Ruler said to him, “'},
{'istart': 9, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'That Your Majesty, the Lord of a Myriad Chariots, should risk his person in what is not the way of perfect rectitude is not what the ancients would have done. I pray that this may be reflected upon.', 'context': 'saying, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Guan Yu and I were as one body, and the way of perfect rectitude is here. Have you forgotten?', 'context': 'But the First Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 112, 'talk': "I fear disaster if Your Majesty disregards your servant's words.", 'context': 'But the officer remained at his feet and said, “'},
{'istart': 148, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Why do you use such bad words when I desire to march?', 'context': ' The First Ruler replied angrily, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'I die without regret. It is a pity that this newly established state should be overturned ere it be well begun.', 'context': 'He only smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Your fate will be decided when the army of vengeance return,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'I have decided, and no remonstrance should be raised!', 'context': 'But having listened to the memorial, the First Ruler threw it to the floor, saying, “'},
{'istart': 754, 'iend': 759, 'talk': 'tiger', 'context': 'Then he appointed the Prime Minister to take care of his son and the two Lands of Rivers. Then the Generals of the Flying Cavalry—Ma Chao and Ma Dai—, together with the General Who Defends the North, Wei Yan, were ordered to guard Hanzhong against Wei. The Tiger General Zhao Yun was to be in reserve and to control the supplies; Huang Quan and Cheng Ji were made Counselors; Ma Liang and Chen Zhen, Recorders; Huang Zhong, the van leader, assisted by the Marching Generals Feng Xi and Zhang Nan; Fu Tong and Zhang Yi, Marching Commanders of the Center Army; Zhao Rong and Liao Chun, the rear guards. The whole army, including the borrowed foreign troops, numbered seven hundred fifty thousand, and high−rank officials amounted several hundred. And the “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'The time allowed is insufficient to make white flags and armors. Pray give us more time, General.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I am hot to avenge my brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': "We have been beaten today; what about tomorrow? This man's temper is unbearable; and if things are not ready, we shall suffer death.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Suppose we slay him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'since if we do not, he will kill us.', 'context': ' suddenly said Zhang Da, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'But how can we get near him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'If we are to have a chance to live, he will get drunk and go to bed; if we are to die, he will remain sober.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'I feel nervous and creepy and shivery and cannot not rest. What does it mean?', 'context': 'restless. He told some of his subordinates, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'This is due to too much brooding over the loss of your brother,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'This means the loss of a great leader, and there will be bad news in a few days.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang sent back the reply: “'},
{'istart': 186, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Alas! My other brother is gone!', 'context': "So the army was halted and did not march. Then the arrival of a message from Wu Ban of Langzhong was announced. The First Ruler's foreboding increased, and he stamped his foot, saying, “"},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 212, 'talk': "My father has been killed by Fan Jiang and Zhang Da. They have gone over to Wu, taking my father's head with them.", 'context': "As soon as he reached the First Ruler's presence, he dismounted and bowed to the earth, weeping, “"},
{'istart': 9, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Are you and Wu Ban willing to lead your troops to attack Wu and to avenge your father?', 'context': 'saying, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'For my country or for my father, I would shrink from no sacrifice,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'I think of the plain and simple days of long ago when we pledged ourselves one to the other. Now I am Emperor. How I should rejoice to share my good fortune with them! But they have met violent deaths, and the sight of these two youths wrings my heart to the very core.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Young gentlemen, please retire,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'and let our Sacred One repose his dragon body.', 'context': ' said the officers to the two youthful generals, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'Your Majesty is no longer young; you are over sixty, remember, and it is not fitting that you give way to such extreme sorrow.', 'context': 'They went. Said the attendants, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'But my brothers—dead,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'How can I live without them?', 'context': ' wailed the First Ruler. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'What can be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'He is in such trouble! How can we comfort him?', 'context': ' asked the officers one to another. “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Sire, it is bad for the army to spend whole days in wailing and tears when leading against the enemy.', 'context': 'Ma Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 351, 'talk': 'There is a certain hermit living among the Blue Mountains, near Chengdu, who is said to be three hundred years old. He is called Li Yi, and people say he is a seer. Let us tell His Majesty and let him send for this old man that he may know what the future may have in store. It will have more weight than anything we can say.', 'context': 'And then Chen Zhen said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'You are surely Chen Zhen.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Truly he is more than wise;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'and people have not believed him.', 'context': ' said Chen Zhen, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'This is no common man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'I am but an old man of the barren hill country, without learning or wisdom; you shame me, O Emperor, by calling me, and I know not why.', 'context': 'The seer said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'I and my two brothers, both now deceased, swore a mutual oath some thirty years ago. Both have gone, both by violent deaths. I would lead a great army to avenge them and wish to know how the expedition will end. Hearing that you, Venerable Sir, are learned in the deeper mysteries, I sent for you and beg you to tell me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'But this is fate; it is not for an old man like me to know.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Soldiers, horses, weapons', 'context': 'But the First Ruler pressed him to say. However, the aged one got paper and a brush and wrote: “'},
{'istart': 337, 'iend': 343, 'talk': 'White.', 'context': '—again and again on many sheets of paper. Having done this, he suddenly tore them into fragments. Further, he drew a picture of a tall man lying supine and another above him digging a grave. And over all he wrote: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'This is only a demented man; what he says is not worthy of confidence,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Leave that seal to me!', 'context': 'seal to his girdle, another youth boldly stepped forth and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I have already received my commission,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'What abilities have you for such a task?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'That I have been training as a soldier since my boyhood. I can shoot and never miss.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I should like to see your prowess,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'that I may decide who is the better.', 'context': ' said the First Ruler, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'What is it to hit such a mark?', 'context': 'Then Guan Xing seized his bow, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I will hit the third of the flying geese,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Fine!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Dare you try a real combat?', 'context': 'But Zhang Bao was enraged. Leaping on his steed, he seized the long octane−serpent halberd left him by his father, crying, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'You can use the spear, think you that I cannot wield a sword?', 'context': 'Guan Xing took up the challenge at once. He sprang into the saddle, took his great saber, and galloped out. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Do not behave so badly!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 444, 'talk': "Young men, from the time I left my native place Zhuo and swore brotherhood with your fathers, they were as my own flesh and blood. You two are also brothers, and you should help each other in vengeance rather than quarrel and dispute. You have lost the sense of rectitude while your fathers' deaths are still recent, and what will happen in future?", 'context': 'Both dropped out of the saddle, threw aside their weapons, ran to his feet, and begged pardon. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Which of you two is the elder?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I am the elder by a year,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'Liu Bei has declared himself Emperor and is leading against us in person a great host of more than seven hundred thousand. What shall we do, for the danger is imminent?', 'context': 'Then Sun Quan said to his assembled officers, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'I have been in your service these many years and have never justified the favor you have shown me. I will risk my life and go to this Liu Bei of Shu that I may talk to him plainly and prove to him the advantages of friendship and alliance against Cao Pi.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 351, 'talk': 'His brother being your Prime Minister, Zhuge Jin is certainly come on some important mission. Your Majesty ought to see him and hear what he says. If his proposals are admissible, then agree; if not, he can be made use of to take knowledge of your intentions to Sun Quan and let Sun Quan know that you intend to punish his crime.', 'context': 'But Huang Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Zhuge Jin, you have come a long journey; what is its object?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 429, 'talk': "My master is now very sorry for it, but it was Lu Meng's doing. However, Lu Meng is now dead and his enmity has died with him. Moreover, Lady Sun is always thinking over returning to you. My master now proposes to send back the lady, to bind and hand over to you those officers who surrendered, and to restore Jingzhou. If the two houses swear perpetual amity, then they may join forces against Cao Pi and punish his usurpation.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'You of Eastern Wu killed my brother; yet you dare to come with your artful talk!', 'context': 'To this harangue the First Ruler only replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 257, 'talk': 'All the world knows of your assumption of the dignity of Emperor and that you will assuredly restore the Hans and rescue their territory; only now you do not try to deal with Wei, you only desire to attack Wu. I venture to think you have made a bad choice.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 314, 'talk': 'The slayer of my brother shall not live in the same world as I. You ask me not to fight. I will cease when I have slain your master. Were it not for the sake of your brother, I would behead you at once. As it is, you may go; and you may tell your master to cleanse his neck ready for the blade of the executioner.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'He knows something of the strength of the armies of Shu, and he made this mission of his an excuse to get out of danger. He will not return.', 'context': 'But while Zhuge Jin had been absent, Zhang Zhao said to Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 538, 'talk': 'He and I are sworn friends—friends to the death. I shall not wrong him, nor will he betray me. When he was at Chaisang and Zhuge Liang came to our country, I wanted my friend Zhuge Jin to persuade his brother to remain with me. His reply was that his brother would not remain any more than he himself would go: each would be faithful to his salt. That was quite clear enough. How could he desert me after that? Our friendship has something of the divine in it, and no talk from outside can sow dissension between us.', 'context': 'The Marquis replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'What do you think now?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Then the South Land is in great danger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I have a way out of the difficulty.', 'context': 'But a certain man here interposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'What good scheme do you propose, friend Zhao Zi?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Though the suggestion is good, yet shall we not lose something of our dignity by that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Minister.', 'context': 'Sun Quan was satisfied and composed the memorial, styling himself “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Eastern Wu has sent a high officer, Zhao Zi, with a memorial.', 'context': 'Next day, Jia Xu stood forth one day at court and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Because he wants the armies of Shu driven off,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 238, 'iend': 279, 'talk': 'What sort of an over−lord is the Marquis?', 'context': ' said Cao Pi, smiling, and as if completing the sentence. But he summoned Zhao Zi, who, having prostrated himself in the outer court, handed in his memorial. After reading it, Cao Pi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Intelligent, clear−sighted, wise, brave, and perspicacious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Your praise is none too enthusiastic.', 'context': 'Cao Pi laughed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'I do not wish to overstate,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Is he at all learned?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 429, 'talk': 'Sire, remember he commands a large fleet of ten thousand battleships and a huge army of million armored soldiers. He endeavors to find wise and capable people to help him, and his mind is full of plans and projects. When he has a little leisure, he reads the histories and the annals, for the sake of the general lessons to be learned therefrom. He is no dryasdust pedant seeking remarkable passages and culling model sentences.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Do you think I could overcome Wu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'If a large state has military force to attack, a small one has also preparations for defense.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Does Wu fear Wei?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'How many such persons as high minister does Wu possess?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Prince of Wu', 'context': 'ambassador to Wu, bearing for Sun Quan the title of “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Nine Signs of Honors.', 'context': ' and allowing him to use the “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 408, 'talk': 'Sun Quan has done this for fear of the armies of Shu. In my opinion, if Shu and Wu fight, heaven will make an end of one country. If you will send an army across the river to attack, and Shu attack at the same time, Wu as a state will disappear. If Wu goes, then Shu will be left alone and can be dealt with when you will.', 'context': 'But when the messenger had gone out of the city, Liu Ye went to remonstrate, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'How do you think you can overcome them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'Not at all; I am helping neither Wu nor Shu. I am waiting till they are at grips, and if one goes under, there will be only one left to destroy. That will be easy. However, say no more, for I have decided.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 129, 'talk': "My lord, you should style yourself 'Supreme Ruler' and 'Lord' of the nine territories; you should not receive any rank from Wei.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'But on one occasion Liu Bang received the princedom of Han (Hanzhong) from Xiang Yu; it depends upon the times. Why refuse?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Everyone must obey the rules of courtesy as everyone must respect the laws. You, Sir, are behaving proudly as if there was no such thing as a sword in this country.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'Here we are prevented from risking our lives in smashing Wei and swallowing Shu; and our lord receives a title from another man. Are not such things shameful?', 'context': 'As the cavalcade proceeded, a loud voice was heard in the rear of the two carriages, crying, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'If all the leaders and ministers of the South Land are like this, the lord of the country will not long be content to obey another.', 'context': 'And the messenger sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 490, 'talk': 'The First Ruler, together with King Shamo Ke of the Mang nations, leads his own army and a large number of tribesmen from the east and south; furthermore, he is aided by the two Han generals of Dongxi, Liu Ning and Du Lu, with their cohorts. They advance both by land and by water, a mighty host, of which the shouting shakes the heavens. The naval force has already come out at Wukou, and the land force has reached Zigui.', 'context': 'Not long after came tidings of the forces under the ruler of Shu: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'Ah!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'After Zhou Yu I had Lu Su, and Lu Meng succeeded Lu Su. But now they have all three gone, and there is no one to share my troubles!', 'context': ' sighed he. “'},
{'istart': 117, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'Though I am young, I am not a little versed in the books of war, and with a few legions I could destroy the power of Shu.', 'context': 'But just then a very youthful general stepped out from the ranks of the officials and said, with a lowly obeisance, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'There are two able commanders under my command named Xie Jing and Li Yi, both very brave. With a few legions I will capture Liu Bei.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Though you are brave, nephew, yet you are young and ought to have an assistant.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Let me go.', 'context': ' Thereupon Tiger General Zhu Ran stepped forward, saying, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'So they think this youth is able to withstand me?', 'context': 'The First Ruler got angry, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Since this nephew of Sun Quan has been made a leader,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I was just wishing to see what you could do,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Then both go, my nephews,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'But you must be prudent and not hasty.', 'context': ' said the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Sun Huan, you tiny rascal, your time has come!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'How dare you stand against the forces of Heaven?', 'context': ' cried Zhang Bao abusively. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Your father is a headless devil,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 135, 'talk': "and you are going just now to join him; don't you see?", 'context': ' cried Sun Huan, no way backward in reviling, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'If something wrong happens to Guan Xing, I will not live!', 'context': 'But Guan Xing was missing. Zhang Bao was desperate, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'In the melee I met an enemy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'and I took him prisoner.', 'context': ' cried Guan Xing, “'},
{'istart': 337, 'iend': 393, 'talk': 'The power of Wu is broken; let us raid their encampment.', 'context': 'After this they drew up a report of the victory for the First Ruler. Sun Huan had lost his generals—Li Yi, Xie Jing, and Tan Xiong—as well as many other officers and many troops. His army was too weakened to continue the campaign, so he halted and sent back to Wu for reinforcements. Then Generals Zhang Nan and Feng Xi said to Wu Ban, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 258, 'talk': "Though so many have been lost, there are many left. Zhu Ran's marine force is in a strong position on the river and is untouched. If you carry out your plan and the marines land in force and cut off our retreat, we shall be in difficulties.", 'context': 'But Wu Ban said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'That is easily met,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Let each of the two leaders Guan Xing and Zhang Bao take five thousand troops and go into ambush in the valleys to guard against any such move.', 'context': ' said Zhang Nan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 224, 'talk': 'I think it better to send some persons to pretend to be deserters. Let them tell Zhu Ran of the plan to raid the camp, and Zhu Ran will come to the rescue as soon as he sees fire. Then the ambushing soldiers can attack him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'What secret can you betray?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'You cannot trust what those soldiers said,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'Is there any city ahead that has good defense and granary?', 'context': "The remnant of Sun Huan's troops ran away, following their leader. As they went, Sun Huan inquired, “"},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'To the north is Yiling, where we can camp.', 'context': 'They told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Sun Huan is besieged in Yiling, and Zhu Ran has been defeated on the river; what can be done?', 'context': 'So he called a great council, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 289, 'talk': 'The generals that have followed me since the early days have got aged, and thus no longer a big use. But now that I have such two valorous nephews, I have no fear for Sun Quan.', 'context': 'He was exceedingly pleased with his two nephews, who had distinguished themselves again and again, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Huang Zhong and a half dozen other officers have run off to Wu.', 'context': 'Then those near him reported: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Huang Zhong is no traitor;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'it is only that he heard what I happened to say about old and useless leaders. He will not confess he is old and wants to prove he is not.', 'context': ' said the First Ruler, smiling, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'Huang Zhong may fail in this enterprise of his, so I hope you two will not mind going to his assistance. As soon as there is some success to report, get him to return and do not let him come to grief.', 'context': 'Then he called Guan Xing and Zhang Bao and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'For what reason do you come, O Veteran General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 479, 'talk': 'I have followed the Emperor ever since he left Changsha, and I have done diligent service. I am now over seventy, but my appetite is still good for ten pounds of meat, and I can still stretch the strongest bow, and I can still ride five hundred miles without fatigue. I am not weak or worn out. But our master has been talking of old and useless leaders, and I am come to take part in the fight with Wu. If I slay one of their leaders, he will see I may be old but not worn out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Aged General, be careful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'We come by the sacred command to aid you if necessary. And now that you have scored so complete a victory, we pray you return to the main camp,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'Flee not, for now will I avenge the death of Guan Yu!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'It is my fault, O Veteran General, that you have been hurt in the battle!', 'context': 'The First Ruler came to visit him and patted his back and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'I am a soldier,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'I am glad that I could serve Your Majesty. But now I am seventy−five, and I have lived long enough. Be careful of your own safety for the good of the state.', 'context': ' said the old man. “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'My brave general is gone,', 'context': "The First Ruler was very sad when he heard of Huang Zhong's death and made him a grave in Chengdu. “"},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Your Majesty is now Ruler of Shu; why do you risk your life in the battlefield? It would be most regrettable if any untoward event happened.', 'context': 'Then Han Dang spoke, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'You rats of Wu bereft me of my brother, and I have sworn that you shall not live with me under the same sky!', 'context': 'The First Ruler pointed the finger of scorn at the speaker and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Who dares plunge in among the enemy?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'The tiger fathers have not begotten curs of sons,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'I am a leader of the army, and I have lost my way. I beg a meal, for I am starving,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Why do you wail thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'This is my father,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Why should you treat my father with such respect?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'Stay, you ruffian! Do not flee!', 'context': 'As Pan Zhang came in, Guan Xing recognized him and drew his sword, crying, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'Do not be hasty; we will do it presently when there is a chance.', 'context': 'Another said, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'The troops are mutinous, and we ourselves are in danger. Ma Zhong is an object of especial hatred to the Ruler of Shu; suppose we kill him and surrender. We can say we were compelled to give in to Wu, but as soon as the news of the Emperor came near we wanted to get back.', 'context': 'Mi Fang started as he heard this. He told Fu Shiren, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'It will not do,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'If we go, they will kill us.', 'context': ' said Fu Shiren. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'No; the Ruler of Shu is liberal and kind. And the heir, Liu Shan, is my nephew. They will surely not do any harm to a connection.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 340, 'talk': "We are not traitors. We were the victims of Lu Meng's wickedness. He said that Guan Yu was dead and tricked us into giving up the city. We could not help surrendering. When we heard the Sacred Chariot had come, we slew Ma Zhong to satisfy your vengeance, and we implore forgiveness.", 'context': 'And they threw themselves on the ground and wept, saying “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 328, 'talk': 'I left Chengdu a long time ago; why did you not come to confess your fault before? Now you find yourselves in danger and so you come with this specious tale to try to save your lives. If I pardon you, how shall I look my brother in the face when we meet beneath the Nine Golden Springs?', 'context': 'But the First Ruler was angry, and said, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'The two enemies of my uncle have been slain, but when will vengeance be taken upon those of my father?', 'context': 'Presently Zhang Bao came in and wailed before him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Do not grieve, my nephew,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'I am going to lay waste the South Land and slay the whole of the curs that live there. I will assuredly capture the two murderers of your father, and you shall hack them to pieces as a sacrifice.', 'context': ' said the First Ruler, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 438, 'talk': "There were five persons—Lu Meng, Pan Zhang, Ma Zhong, Mi Fang, and Fu Shiren—whom Liu Bei had a grudge against, and they are all dead. Now the objects of his hate are the murderers of Zhang Fei—Fan Jiang and Zhang Da. Why not send back Zhang Fei's head, and these two assassins, and give up Jingzhou and restore Lady Sun and ask for peace and alliance against Wei? This will make the army of Shu retire, and we shall have peace.", 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Your enemies are now all dead: you are avenged. Wu has sent a high officer with large concessions and awaits your reply.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'The one I would grind to pieces is Sun Quan. To act as he proposes and enter into alliance would be treachery to my two brothers and a breach of our oath. Now I will exterminate Wu, and Wei shall follow.', 'context': 'But the First Ruler angrily replied, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'The Ruler of Shu, not listening to words of peace, was determined to level Wu before attacking Wei. Those under him protested in vain. What is to be done?', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Since there is a sky−supporting pillar, why not use it?', 'context': 'Seeing this, Kan Ze stepped forward and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Whom do you refer to?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 522, 'talk': 'You once had perfect confidence in Zhou Yu, and he was followed by Lu Su, equally able. Lu Meng succeeded and you pinned your faith upon him. Though now Lu Meng is dead, yet there is Lu Xun. And he is quite near, in Jingzhou. He is reputed to be a scholar, but really he is a bold and capable man, no whit inferior to Zhou Yu, in my opinion. The plan that broke Guan Yu was his. If anyone can destroy Shu, it is he. If he fails, then I will stand the same punishment as may be his.', 'context': ' asked Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'If you had not spoken thus, my whole scheme might have gone amiss,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Lu Xun is a student,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'He is no match for Liu Bei. You may not use him.', 'context': ' said Zhang Zhao. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'He is well enough to control a region, but he is not fit for a big matter.', 'context': 'Bu Zhi also said, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'It is the only hope. I will guarantee him with the lives of all my house!', 'context': 'Kan Ze got desperate, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'I know he is able,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'I wish to send you in supreme command of all the forces against Shu.', 'context': 'When Lu Xun arrived at court and made his bow, Sun Quan said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Sir, you have numerous old and tried officers under your command; I am very young and not at all clever,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Kan Ze goes bail for you and pledges his whole house. Moreover, I know your abilities. You must be Commander−in−Chief and may not refuse the appointment.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'But what will happen if the officers do not support me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Here is authority!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Slay the disobedient and report afterwards.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan, taking his own sword from his side and giving it to Lu Xun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'I am grateful for this proof of confidence, but I dare not accept forthwith. I pray you assemble all the officers and confer the office upon me in their presence.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 399, 'talk': "The ancient fashion was to set up a platform and thereon present to the leader−elect a white yak's tail and a golden ax with the seal of office and commission. Thereafter his dignity and the reverence due from others were beyond all question. It would be well, O Prince, to follow the old rule. Choose a good day and appoint Lu Xun before all the world, and no one will refuse support.", 'context': 'Said Kan Ze, “'},
{'istart': 424, 'iend': 494, 'talk': 'Domestic affairs belong to me; outer affairs are under your direction.', 'context': 'assembly was called. Then Lu Xun was requested to ascend and make his bow on receiving his appointment as Commander−in−Chief, Leader of the Senior, General Who Guards the West, and Lord of Fenglou. The sword of authority and the seal of office were presented. His powers extended over the six territories and the eighty−one counties of the South Land, over the forces in Jingzhou and Wu. And in charging him Sun Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'Why did the Prince appoint a mere bookish student to the commandership of all armed forces?', 'context': 'When the dispatch reached Han Dang and Zhou Tai, who were camping near Xiaoting, they were alarmed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 327, 'talk': 'By order of my superior I am Commander−in−Chief, and my commission is to destroy Shu. You, gentlemen, all know the ordinary military rules, and you would do well to obey them. The law is no respecter of persons, as those who disobey will find out. Do not have to regret when it is too late.', 'context': 'Then Lu Xun addressed them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 255, 'talk': "There is Sun Huan, nephew of our Prince; he is surrounded at Yiling and is short of food. I venture to request you to send relief to him and get him out, so that the Prince's heart may be comforted.", 'context': 'They nodded in sullen acquiescence. Then Zhou Tai said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'I know all about him. His soldiers are faithful, and he can easily maintain his position. There is no need to go to his aid. When Shu is broken, he will be free to come out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'This will be the end of Wu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Did you note what he said?', 'context': ' said he to his colleague. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I tried him just to see what he would do,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'You see he had no plan ready; he destroys Shu indeed!', 'context': ' said Zhou Tai. “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'You know I am in command; yet the recent orders for defense have been disregarded. Why?', 'context': 'So once more Lu Xun assembled them and said, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'General Han Dang just says what we think: let us fight a decisive battle,', 'context': 'All the others applauded this speech and cried that the speaker had expressed their own ideas. “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 469, 'talk': 'That I am a student is true. But I have been entrusted with a great task, a task for which the Prince of Wu considers me competent and for the performance of which I am prepared to bear all the responsibilities. As for you, you will do well to act on the defensive as I ordered and not allow yourselves to be led astray into any attacks. And I shall put the disobedient to death!', 'context': 'The new general waited till the uproar had subsided; then drawing his sword, he shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'What sort of a man is this Lu Xun?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'He is a scholar among the people of Wu, and, though young, he is very talented,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'His crafty scheme caused the deaths of my brothers; but now I shall have him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Be very careful;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'this Lu Xun is no whit inferior to Zhou Yu.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I have grown old in the field,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 101, 'talk': "Don't you think me a match for this callow youth?", 'context': ' said the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'That must be Liu Bei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'I should like to kill him.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Careful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 239, 'talk': "Lu Xun is a deep and crafty fellow. He recognizes the disadvantages of Your Majesty's troops in being far from their base, and from spring to autumn he will not come out to fight till some move occurs that he may profit by.", 'context': 'Said Ma Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'What ruse can he be contemplate?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'The real fact is that he is afraid. Their army has suffered nothing but defeat times and again. They dare not meet us.', 'context': ' said the First Ruler. “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'The weather is scorching, and the troops are camped in the full glare of sun. Beside, water is scarce and hard to get.', 'context': 'One day the leader of the van, Feng Xi, memorialized the First Ruler, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'If our soldiers move, the enemy will rush out on us and we shall be hard set.', 'context': 'Ma Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I will provide for that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 388, 'talk': 'I will send Wu Ban with ten thousand of our inferior troops to camp near their lines. But I will choose eight thousand of veterans and place them in ambush. Wu Ban will have orders to flee before the soldiers of Wu and lead them into my ambush if they come out, and I will cut off their retreat. We ought to capture this precocious youth.', 'context': ' said the First Ruler. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'A genius in plans, a marvel of prevision!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'None of us can approach him in cleverness.', 'context': ' cried ail those about him as this plan was unfolded. “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'They say the Prime Minister is on a tour of inspection of the defenses in the eastern portion of Shu, seeing that they are in good order against any attack on the part of Wei. Why not send him a sketch of your present dispositions of troops and ask his opinion?', 'context': 'But Ma Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'I also am not entirely ignorant of the art of war, and I see no reason to seek advice,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'There is an old saying about hearing both sides,', 'context': ' was the cold reply. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Well, then you go round to all the camps and make a map and take it to the Prime Minister. If he finds any fault, you may come and tell me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 86, 'talk': "All the enemies' forty camps had been moved into the shade. Now, Sir, you can attack!", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 419, 'iend': 436, 'talk': 'Van Leader Wu Ban', 'context': 'The last chapter closed with the report that the First Ruler had shifted camp in search of cool shade, and the news was very welcome to Lu Xun. He went forthwith to assure himself of the truth of the report and observe the new position. A level plain lay at his feet, whereon he saw something short of ten thousand Shu troops, the greater part of whom appeared invalids. On the banner of their leader he read the name “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'We consider these troops children,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Let me and General Han Dang go out and smite them. I will give the formal guarantee of victory.', 'context': ' said Zhou Tai. “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'It seems to me that an air of slaughter is rising over there from that valley; surely there is an ambush there. These poor troops in the foreground are nothing but a bait. No, Gentlemen; do not leave your positions.', 'context': 'The Commander−in−Chief made no reply, but remained gazing out before him. Presently he said, “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Those Shu soldiers despise us so much. Let us go out and punish them!', 'context': "Xu Sheng and Ding Feng came to the commander's tent to complain, saying, “"},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 276, 'talk': 'You see everything from the point of view of brute courage. You seem not to know the principles of war laid down by Sun Zi and Wu Qi. This display is only meant to entice us into fight. You will see the pretense yourselves in about three days.', 'context': 'But Lu Xun only smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'In three days the change of camp will be complete, and the enemy will be too strongly posted for our success,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'I am just letting them move their camp.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'There is still a deadly look over the valley,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Liu Bei will soon appear.', 'context': ' said Lu Xun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'That is why I would not listen to those of you who wanted to fight Wu Ban,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'Now that the ambush has been withdrawn, we can settle them in about ten days.', 'context': ' said Lu Xun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'The proper time to attack was when they began to transfer their camp. Now they are fully established with encampments stretching two hundred miles. Having spent seven or eight months in strengthening where they might be attacked, will it not be difficult to destroy them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 337, 'talk': 'I see you do not understand how to carry on war. This man Liu Bei is a capable and crafty man. When he first started on this expedition his methods were of the best, and he kept to them for a long time, so we gave him no chance against us. When his troops are worn out and his thoughts cease to be clear, that will be our day to attack.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'We have found another remarkably able leader,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'and I have no further anxiety. They all said he was a useless pedant, and only I knew better. Reading this letter shows him nothing at all of a pedant.', 'context': ' said the Prince, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 244, 'talk': 'It is easy enough for the ships to go a down, but how about returning? Let me make the first advance, and Your Majesty may follow. That will make it more than probable that nothing will go wrong.', 'context': 'However, Huang Quan spoke against this, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Those Wu enemy are afraid,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'and I want to make a dash at them. Where is the difficulty?', 'context': ' objected the ruler, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 341, 'talk': "Shu marches against Wu, erecting forty base camps along two hundred miles of woods and hills. Moreover, the Ruler of Shu places Huang Quan in command of the North of the Great River. Huang Quan's marines patrolled as far as thirty miles daily. We do not know their intention.", 'context': 'The spies of Wei duly reported these doings to the Ruler of Wei: “'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is going to be defeated,', 'context': 'The Ruler of Wei laughed aloud when he heard the details of the long line of camps and the encampments among the trees and all this. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'How do you know?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'If successful, Lu Xun will lead all his force westward into the Western Land of Rivers, and his country will be defenseless. I shall pretend to send an army to help. I shall send them in three divisions, and I shall overcome Wu easily.', 'context': 'But the Ruler of Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 263, 'talk': "Now the forces are on both sides of the Great River extending along a front of two hundred miles, with forty stations, each beside a mountain stream or in a pleasantly shaded forest. At our lord's command, I prepared this map, and he sent me to ask your opinion.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Who advised such an arrangement? He ought to be put to death, whoever it was,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': "It is entirely our lord's own work; no other had any hand in it,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'The life and energy of the Hans are done indeed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 558, 'talk': 'He has committed those very faults which the rules of the Art of War lay down as to be particularly avoided. The camps are made where free movement is impossible, and nothing can save him if the enemy use fire. Beside, what defense is possible along a two−hundred−mile front? Disaster is at hand, and Lu Xun sees it all, which explains his obstinate refusal to come out into the open. Go back as quickly as you can and tell our lord that this will not do, that it must be changed at once.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'But if I am too late—if Wu has already attacked and won—, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'The enemy will not dare to follow up their victory by a march on Chengdu. So this capital is secure.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Why will they not?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Wei is behind their back; that is why. Our lord will be compelled to shelter in Baidicheng. I have already placed ten thousand troops in hiding at Fishbelly Creek.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Have you? I have been up and down that creek three or four times without seeing a soldier. I do not see the reason of telling lies to me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'You will see; do not ask so many questions.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 212, 'talk': "There has been no fighting since I received our lord's command. I have spent the time in acquiring a knowledge of the enemy. As a preliminary operation I want to capture a camp on the south bank. Who volunteers?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'You will take the fourth camp on the south side; you may have five thousand troops. The commander of the post is Fu Tong. I shall support you.', 'context': 'Then he called up the junior general, Chunyu Dan, and said, “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'Each of you will take three thousand troops and bivouac two miles from the camp, so that if your colleague is repulsed and pursued, you can rescue him.', 'context': 'When Chunyu Dan had gone, Lu Xun summoned Xu Sheng and Ding Feng and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'It was no fault of yours;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'I wanted to test the force of our enemy. My plan of attack is quite ready.', 'context': ' said the Commander−in−Chief, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'The enemy is very strong and will not be easily overcome,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'We have now suffered great loss to no purpose.', 'context': ' said Xu Sheng and Ding Feng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'This plan of mine would not hoodwink Zhuge Liang, but happily he is not here. His absence will allow me to score a great success.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 687, 'talk': 'Zhu Ran is to lead the marine force. He is to advance next day afternoon, when the southeast wind will serve. His ships are laden with reeds and straw, which are to be used as ordered. Han Dang is to attack the north bank, Zhou Tai the south. Each soldier, in addition to his weapons, is to carry a bundle of straw or reeds, with sulfur and saltpeter hidden therein, and each has a piece of tinder. They are to advance, and, when they reach the Shu camps, they are to start a conflagration. But they are to burn only alternate camps, twenty in all, leaving the others untouched. They are to advance and only stop if they capture Liu Bei.', 'context': 'Then he summoned his generals to receive orders: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'It means only one thing, that the troops of Wu will raid the camp tonight,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'They will not dare after the slaughter of yesterday.', 'context': ' said Cheng Ji. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'But suppose that was only a reconnaissance; what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'They are soldiers meant to put us in confusion,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Your Majesty, the fire is gaining all round, and this place is not safe. I request you to try to reach Baidicheng, and as many as possible will gather there.', 'context': 'Guan Xing quickly leapt down, prostrated himself and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Who will dare stay behind to keep off the enemy?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'I will fight to death to guard the rear!', 'context': 'Fu Tong volunteered, saying, “'},
{'istart': 197, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'This is the end!', 'context': 'Zhu Ran marched up from the river to try to intercept the flight, and the noise of his drums was terrifying. The First Ruler thought there was no possibility of escape from this force, and cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Though I am safe, how about the other generals and soldiers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'The pursuers are close upon us, and we cannot wait for anything,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 226, 'talk': 'I wish Your Majesty to get into the city as quickly as possible; and while you are reposing yourself, we may try to rescue some of the leaders.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Shall I, a servant of Han, give in to the cure of Wu?', 'context': 'But Fu Tong replied, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'The soldiers of Wu are upon us; let find a way to escape.', 'context': "One of Cheng Ji's generals shouted to him: “"},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Since I first followed my lord, I have never yet turned my back upon the foe.', 'context': 'But Cheng Ji shouted back, “'},
{'istart': 346, 'iend': 376, 'talk': 'The Shrine of the Bold Beauty,', 'context': 'When the story of the disaster to Shu reached the Southern Land, and with it the report that the First Ruler had been killed in battle, Lady Sun gave way to wild grief. She rode down to the river bank and, gazing westward, wept and lamented. Then she threw herself into the stream and was drowned. Posterity erected a temple on the shore called “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'We may not yet advance farther; I suspect an ambush.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 194, 'iend': 297, 'talk': 'There is not a single soldier, but I have noticed on the river bank nearly a hundred heaps of boulders.', 'context': 'Still, as the sun got lower and lower in the west, he saw the same appearance accentuated, and he began to feel grave doubts. He sent a confidant to look once more. This man came back, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Who put them there? Why did they look so ghastly?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'We do not know. This place is called Fishbelly Creek. When Zhuge Liang was going west into the Lands of Rivers, he came along here with a lot of soldiers and heaped up the boulders like that above the Sandy Rapid. We have seen vapors rising from the boulders; they seemed to come from inside them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'This looks likely to drive a person out of his senses;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'I wonder whether it is any good.', 'context': ' he said, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'The sun is setting; we ought to be returning to camp.', 'context': 'Presently one of the escort called attention to the increasing darkness and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'This is some trick of Zhuge Liang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'and I have been caught.', 'context': ' said Lu Xun in a scared voice, “'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'Does the General wish to go out?', 'context': 'He would go out, but he had quite lost his way and could find no exit. As he stopped to consider what he should do, an old man suddenly appeared, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'I greatly desire that you would pilot me out, O Elder,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Have you studied this matter, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'The variations are inexhaustible, and I could not learn them all.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'This Zhuge Liang is well named Sleeping−Dragon,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I am not his equal.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'I am not afraid of the stones, and it is not on their account that I retire. But I fear Cao Pi. He is no less resourceful than his father, and when he hears I am marching into Shu, he will certainly attack us. How could I return then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 311, 'iend': 521, 'talk': 'Three Wei generals with three armies are debouching at three different points and moving toward the borders of Wu—Cao Ren from Ruxu, Cao Xiu from Dongkou, and Cao Zhen from Nanjun. Their intentions are unclear.', 'context': ' The homeward march began. On the second day the scouts brought a report: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Just as I thought,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'But I am ready for them.', 'context': ' said Lu Xun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'And now the west is mine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 161, 'talk': "If I had listened to the Prime Minister's advice, the defeat would not have happened. Now how can I face a return to my capital?", 'context': 'The First Ruler sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'Huang Quan, who had been given command of the army on the north bank, had given in to Wei. Your Majesty should deliver his whole family to the authority and hold them responsible for the renegade.', 'context': 'Next he heard people say: “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'The army was quite cut off by Wu from the south bank, and he had no alternative but to surrender. Really, I betrayed him, not he me. Why should I take vengeance on his family?', 'context': 'But the First Ruler only said, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'You have surrendered to me because you desired to imitate the admirable conduct of Chen Ping and Han Xin of old.', 'context': 'When Huang Quan surrendered, he was led into the presence of Cao Pi, who said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 411, 'talk': 'The Ruler of Shu has been very kind to me, and he gave me the leadership of the army on the North of the Great River. Lu Xun cut me off so that I could not return to Shu, and I would not surrender to Wu, wherefore I have yielded to Your Majesty. Defeated as I am, I should be only too happy if my life were spared, but I have no claim to the credit of the virtuous ones of old.', 'context': 'But Huang Quan replied, weeping, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'A spy has reported that all of your family have been put to death by the Ruler of Shu.', 'context': 'Then one of the courtiers said, “'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 192, 'talk': 'I wish to bring the whole empire under my rule; which shall I first reduce, Shu or Wu?', 'context': 'Cao Pi sought advice from Jia Xu concerning his design of bringing the whole country under his own rule. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 531, 'talk': "Liu Bei is an able warrior, and Zhuge Liang is a most capable administrator; Sun Quan possesses discrimination, and his general, Lu Xun, occupies all the strategic positions of importance. The natural obstacles, the intervening rivers and spreading lakes, would be hard to overcome. I do not think you have any leader to match either of these two men. Even with the prestige of Your Majesty's own presence, no one could guarantee the result. The better course is to hold on and await the outcome of the struggle between those two.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'I have already dispatched three armies against Wu; can it be that they will fail?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Well; but I have decided to attack. So say no more,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'A force of Wu has been sent to oppose each of our three armies. Lu Fan leads an army against Cao Xiu at Dongkou, Zhuge Jin against Cao Zhen at Nanjun, and Zhu Huan against Cao Ren at Ruxu.', 'context': 'justifying the opinion of his advisers: “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Wu has prepared, and no success can be expected.', 'context': 'Liu Ye pointed this out and again said, “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 763, 'talk': 'Success depends upon the leader rather than on the number of soldiers. The Art of War says that the value of one soldier who inhabits the place equals that of two soldiers who come from afar; and those who are in possession, however in small number, can overcome those who come from afar. Now the enemy is weary from a long march, and I and you, my men, can hold this place together. We have the Great River to defend us on the south, and we are backed by the mountains on the north. Success should be ours easily, and we are as hosts at home awaiting the arrival of our weary visitors. This will give us victory in every fight. Even if Cao Pi comes, we need feel no anxiety. How much less care we for Cao Ren and his troops?', 'context': 'Drawing his sword, he made a speech, “'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'Cao Zhen and Xiahou Shang were besieging Nanjun when Zhuge Jin from within and Lu Xun from without attacked in concert. The two generals suffered a great loss.', 'context': 'And before the Ruler of Wei could decide what course to take in regard to this loss, the news came of the defeat of his another army: “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Cao Xiu has been defeated by Lu Fan at Dongkou.', 'context': 'Immediately, another report came: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I told you I was worried,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'and bade you leave me; why have you come back? Go!', 'context': ' said the First Ruler, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Are you still alive, then, brothers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'We are not men; we are shades,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I am not much longer for this world,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 417, 'talk': 'The attainment of emperorship was your work. Little thought you that I should prove so stupid as not to follow your advice and so bring about the late disasters. But I am deeply sorry, and now I shall not live long. My heir is a degenerate, but I must leave him to do the best he can with the great inheritance.', 'context': 'The dying Emperor bade him come near and sit beside him, and he patted his Minister on the back, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'I trust Your Majesty will fulfill the hopes of the people by a speedy recovery,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'Do you think Ma Su is clever?', 'context': "Turning his head, the First Ruler saw Ma Su, Ma Liang's brother, at the bedside. He bade him retire. When Ma Su had left the chamber, the First Ruler said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'He is one of the ablest people in the world,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'I do not think so. I think his words exceed his deeds. Do not make much use of him. Watch him carefully.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 593, 'talk': "I am no great scholar, and I only know the rough outlines of what should be known. But the Teacher has said: 'A bird's song is sad when death is near, and a dying person's words are good.' I was waiting that we might aid each other in the destruction of the Caos and the restoration of the Hans, but ere the work is complete I am called away, and this last command of mine I confide to you as Prime Minister to be handed to my son and heir, Liu Shan. My words are to be taken seriously. I trust that you will instruct and guide my son.", 'context': 'He handed it to the Prime Minister with a sigh and said, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'We pray Your Majesty repose yourself. We will do our utmost whereby to prove our gratitude for the kindness we have received.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang and all those present wept and prostrated themselves, saying, “'},
{'istart': 201, 'iend': 269, 'talk': 'The end is near; I have something more to say as to a close general.', 'context': "At the First Ruler's command the attendants raised Zhuge Liang from the earth. With one hand the dying man brushed away the falling tears, while with the other he grasped Zhuge Liang's hand and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'What holy command has Your Majesty to give?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'I could never do otherwise than wear myself to the bone in the service of your son, whom I will serve till death.', 'context': 'He fell on his knees, saying, “'},
{'istart': 168, 'iend': 351, 'talk': "My sons, remember your father's words. After my death you are to treat the Prime Minister as you would your father and be not remiss, for thereby you will fulfill your father's hopes.", 'context': 'He knocked his head upon the ground till blood ran down. The dying man called Zhuge Liang closer, and at the same time making his two sons come near, he said to them, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Were I destroyed and ground into the earth, I should be unable to repay the kindness I have experienced.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'As you have seen, I have confided my orphan son to the care of the Prime Minister and bidden my sons treat him as a father. You too, Sirs, are to treat him with deference. This is my dying request and charge to you.', 'context': 'Turning to the assembled officers, the First Ruler said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'You and I have gone together through many dangers and difficulties. Now comes the parting of our ways. You will not forget our old friendship, and you must see to it that my sons follow my precepts.', 'context': 'Turning to Zhao Yun, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I shall never dare to give other than my best,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'The fidelity of the dog and horse is mine to give and shall be theirs.', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'Noble Sirs, I am unable to speak to you one by one and lay a charge upon each individual; but I say to you: Maintain your self−respect.', 'context': 'Then the First Ruler turned to the others, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'After my death you are to conduct the affairs of the state with the Prime Minister. You are to treat him as a father and serve him without remissness. You and your brothers are to seek instructions. This is my final and simple command.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'The state cannot go a single day without a ruler, wherefore I beg you to install the heir as successor to the great line of the Hans.', 'context': 'When this had been read, Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'Beginning Prosperity.', 'context': 'Thereupon the ceremony was performed, and the new Emperor took his place. The style of the reign was changed to “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'Liu Bei is dead: I am no longer worried. An attack during the critical moment can bring a victory over Shu.', 'context': 'Cao Pi felt relieved and was glad of the death of his rival, saying, “'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'If you neglect this moment, can you expect a more favorable opportunity?', 'context': 'As Jia Xu tendered this remonstrance, a man suddenly stepped out from the serried ranks of courtiers and said fiercely, “'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 297, 'talk': 'It would be very difficult to obtain success with our own resources. Hence we must use five armies and attack all round at the same time, so as to divide Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'The interruption greatly pleased Cao Pi, who at once asked how it was to be done. He propounded his plan in the following speech: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Where are the five armies to come from?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'The daughter of the late General of the Chariot and Cavalry Zhang Fei prudent, and she is now seventeen. Your Majesty should make her Empress.', 'context': 'As the Latter Ruler had no consort, the courtiers, headed by Zhuge Liang, proposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'But his conduct puzzles us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'We do not know why he does not take some action instead of remaining shut up in his palace all the time.', 'context': ' said the informers. “'},
{'istart': 181, 'iend': 274, 'talk': 'The servants in the Prime Minister Palace said the Prime Minister was ill and not to be seen.', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler became really alarmed, and he sent one of his personal attendants to call the Prime Minister to court. The servant was gone a long time, and then returned to say: “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is rather better and will be at court in the morning.', 'context': 'After keeping them waiting a long time, the wardens returned, saying, “'},
{'istart': 282, 'iend': 369, 'talk': 'Your Majesty should go in person and try to get Zhuge Liang to say what should be done.', 'context': "Next morning a great crowd of officers assembled at the gate of the Prime Minister's residence to wait for him to appear. But he did not come out. It began to grow late, and many of them were tired of waiting, when at last Du Qiong went again to the Emperor and suggested, saying, “"},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'What can he mean?', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler then returned to his palace with the officials and told the Empress Dowager his trouble. She was also alarmed. “'},
{'istart': 159, 'iend': 270, 'talk': 'This does not look like acting in the spirit of the charge laid upon him by the late Emperor. Let me go myself.', 'context': ' said she. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 7, 'talk': 'Oh no,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'Your Majesty must not go. We think all is well, and the Prime Minister certainly understands and will do something. Beside, you must let His Majesty go first, and if the Prime Minister still shows remissness, then Your Majesty can summon him to the Temple of the Dynasty and ask him.', 'context': ' said Dong Yun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Where is the Prime Minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'We do not know. But we have orders not to let in the crowd of officers.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Is the Prime Minister really enjoying himself?', 'context': 'Presently the Latter Ruler said slowly and with dignity, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I ought to be put to death ten thousand times,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Cao Pi threatens immediate invasion from five points; why will you not come forth and attend to business?', 'context': 'But the Emperor put forth his hand and helped him to rise, saying, “'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'Could it be possible that I was ignorant of these five armies? I was not looking at the fishes; I was thinking.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang laughed. He conducted the Emperor into an inner room, and, when he was seated, Zhuge Liang addressed the Emperor, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'But, this being so, what shall we do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 509, 'talk': 'Now there is only Wu left to deal with. Had the other four armies succeeded and Shu been in danger, Sun Quan would have come to the attack. If the others fail, I know he will not budge, for he will remember that Cao Pi has just sent three armies to attack his country. And this being so, I want some one with a ready tongue and ingenious mind to go and talk plainly to Sun Quan. So far I have not found such a person, and I am perplexed. I regret that I have given Your Majesty occasion to make this journey.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'The Empress Dowager also wanted to come,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'But now you have spoken, O Minister Father, I am as one awakened from a dream; I shall grieve no more.', 'context': ' said the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'The three states have become a fact,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Now if our state wanted to absorb the other two and restore the condition of one rule, which country should it attack first?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 438, 'talk': 'Though Wei is the real rebel, yet Wei is strong and would be very difficult to overthrow. Any move against it would have to develop slowly. As our Emperor has but lately succeeded his father and the people are none too decided in his favor, I should propose a treaty of mutual defense with Wu. This would obliterate the enmity of His late Majesty and would have important results. However, you, Sir, may have another opinion. What is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'That is what I have been thinking of this long time, but I had not the person for the task. Now I have found him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'What do you want the person to do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 252, 'talk': "I want him to go as envoy to Wu to negotiate such a treaty. As you understand the position so well, you will surely do honor to your prince's commission as envoy. There is no other who would succeed.", 'context': ' said Deng Zhi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I fear I am not equal to such a task: I am not clever enough and too ignorant.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'I will inform the Emperor tomorrow and beg him to appoint you. Of course you will accept.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 371, 'talk': 'Recently Shu sent to Wei for help, and, the situation being misunderstood, the Ruler of Wei dispatched a force against Wu. Now this action is greatly regretted. In Wei it is thought desirable to set four armies in motion against Shu to capture it; and if Wu will assist, and success crown these efforts, Wei and Wu will share the conquered territory.', 'context': 'The messenger said, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'Lu Xun is the man of profound knowledge; he should be consulted.', 'context': 'Sun Quan listened, but was not prepared to give a decided answer. He betook himself to his counselors, Zhang Zhao and Gu Yong, who said, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 545, 'talk': 'Cao Pi is too firmly established in the Middle Land to be upset now; and if this offer of his be refused, we shall provoke his enmity. Neither Wei nor Wu, so far as I see, has any one fit to oppose Zhuge Liang. We must perforce consent and put our army in order. But we can wait till we see how the four armies speed. If Shu seems likely to fall and Zhuge Liang is outmaneuvered, then our army can be dispatched and we will take Capital Chengdu. If the four armies fail, we shall have to consider.', 'context': 'So Lu Xun was called, and his speech ran thus: “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'We are not ready at the moment, so we will choose a day to start later.', 'context': 'So Sun Quan said to the envoy of Wei, “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 186, 'talk': "Lu Xun's words were indeed prophetic; he made most perfect deductions. Any rash action on my part would place me on bad terms with Shu.", 'context': 'Knowing all this, Sun Quan said to his officials, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 122, 'talk': "This mission is also part of Zhuge Liang's scheme to divert danger from Shu. Deng Zhi has come as envoy.", 'context': 'Said Zhang Zhao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'That being so, how should I reply?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 530, 'talk': 'I will tell you. Set up a large cauldron and pour therein a quantity of oil. Light a fire beneath. When the oil is boiling, choose a goodly company of your tallest and brawniest fighting guards, arm them and draw them up in lines between the palace gate and your throne room. Then summon Deng Zhi; but before he can say a word, forewarn him that he will have the same fate of being boiled in oil if being guilty of the same sort of treachery as Li Yiji when he was a persuader to the state of Qi. Then see what Deng Zhi will say.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Why do you not make an obeisance?', 'context': 'The Prince bade his attendants roll up the curtain, and called out, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'The envoy of the superior state does not make an obeisance to the ruler of a smaller country.', 'context': 'Deng Zhi boldly replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'If you do not control that tongue of yours, but will let it wag, you will be like that fellow Li Yiji who went to talk to Qi. You will soon find yourself in the cauldron.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'People say there are many sages in Wu; no one would believe that they would be frightened of a simple scholar.', 'context': 'Then Deng Zhi laughed aloud, saying, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Who fears an unmerited fool like you?', 'context': "This reply only increased Sun Quan's anger, and he said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'If you fear not the envoy, why so anxious about what he may have to say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 142, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'What is the real matter between Wei and Wu? I desire that you would inform me.', 'context': 'As soon as Sun Quan heard these words, he bade the soldiers go, and called the envoy into the hall. There he invited him to a seat and said, “'},
{'istart': 246, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'Do you, great Prince, desire to discuss peace with Wei or with Shu?', 'context': ' Then Deng Zhi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I really desire to discuss peace with the Ruler of Shu. But he is young and inexperienced and ignorant, and unable to carry a matter through.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 815, 'talk': 'Prince, you are a valiant warrior, just as Zhuge Liang is a great minister. Now Shu has the strength of its mountainous geography just as Wu has the protection of its three rivers. If these two countries are at peace, they are mutually protective. They may swallow up the rest of the empire, or they may stand secure alone. If you send tribute to Wei and acknowledge yourself one of its ministers, you will be expected to attend at court, and your heir−apparent will become a servant in that court; and if you disobey, an army of Wei will be sent to attack you. Shu also will come down the river and invade your country. Then this country will be yours no longer. And if you listen not to these words of mine, and refuse my offer, I shall commit suicide before your face and so justify the post I have as an envoy.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Stop him!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'O Master,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'My mind is made up,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Do not doubt me, Master.', 'context': ' replied Sun Quan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Sir, I fear that when you reach Shu and are in the presence of Zhuge Liang, you will not explain my real sentiments,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'Think you that I shall fear him? He also is but a man.', 'context': 'Zhang Wen replied, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 572, 'talk': 'This mission to Wu will succeed, and of the many wise people in the east one will come as return envoy. Your Majesty should treat him with courtesy, and let him return to Wu to complete the league. For if we have an alliance with Wu, Wei will not dare to send an army against us. And if we are safe from those quarters, I will lead an expedition to subdue the Mangs in the south country. After that we can deal with Wei. If Wei is reduced, Wu will not last long, and the whole empire will again be under one ruler.', 'context': 'While Deng Zhi was absent, Zhuge Liang said to his lord, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 399, 'talk': 'Our First Ruler was not on friendly terms with Wu. But that is all changed, as is demonstrated by these banquets, and our present Emperor is disposed to be very friendly. It is hoped that the former enmity may be entirely forgotten and the two countries swear eternal friendship and alliance in their common end—the destruction of Wei. I look to you, Sir, to speak in favor of this league.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Who is the new comer, Sir Prime Minister?', 'context': 'His conduct seemed strange to Zhang Wen, who asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'He is a man named Qin Mi, a Doctorate Academician of Yiazhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'He may be that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'but I wonder if he has any learning at all inside him.', 'context': ' said Zhang Wen with a laugh, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'What may have been your special studies, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'Since you talk so big,', 'context': 'the philosophers, history all through, and all sacred books and traditions. There is nothing I have not read.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Yes; it has a head.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Where is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Well; has the sky ears?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Has the sky feet?', 'context': "crane calls from the midst of the marsh, its cry is heard by the sky.' How could the sky hear without ears?” “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': "It has; the Odes say, 'Heaven treads down difficulties.' If there were no feet, how could it tread?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'Has heaven a name?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Why not?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Then what is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Liu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'How do you know that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': "Because the Emperor's family name is Liu, and he is the Son of Heaven. That is how I know.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Does the sun spring from the east?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Though it does, yet it sets in the west.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 788, 'talk': "You are a famous scholar in your own land, Sir; and since you have asked so many questions about Heaven, I take it you are I well up in all celestial matters. When original chaos resolved into its two elements, negativity and positivity (yin and yang), the lighter portion rose and became sky, and the grosser sank and solidified into earth. When Gong Gong's rebellion was crushed, his head struck the Imperfect Mountain, the pillar, which upholds heaven, was broken and the bonds of earth were destroyed. Heaven fell over to the northwest, and earth sank into the southeast. Since heaven was ethereal and had floated to the top, how could it fall over? Another thing I do not know is what is beyond the ether. I should be glad if you would explain, Master.", 'context': "Then it became Qin Mi's turn, “"},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'I knew not that there was so much ability in this land. I am happy to have heard such a discourse. Now all obstructions have disappeared, and I see quite clearly.', 'context': 'Zhang Wen had no reply ready, but he rose from his place and bowed his acknowledgment, saying, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 276, 'talk': 'This is all play upon words, the sort of puzzles one propounds at a merry feast. You, honored Sir, know that the tranquillity and safety of states are no matters to joke with.', 'context': 'But Zhuge Liang, fearing lest the guest should feel mortified, soothed him with fair words, saying, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Would it not be a happy result if tranquillity should be restored to the empire by the destruction of Wei, and Wu and Shu should share its administration?', 'context': 'Turning to Deng Zhi, Sun Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'The sky knows not two suns,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 305, 'talk': 'nor can the people recognize two kings. If Wei be destroyed, no one can say upon whom the divine command will devolve. But one who becomes a prince must perfect his virtue, and those who become ministers must be wholly loyal. In this way strife will cease.', 'context': ' replied Deng Zhi, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'And your sincerity is beyond question.', 'context': 'Sun Quan smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'This is only the distorted opinion of a perverted pedant. Having made this league, Shu and Wu may fall upon us at any moment. This matter cannot be postponed for ten years,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'Battleships are necessary, as Wu is protected by the Great River. Your Majesty must lead small and big vessels. The navy can advance by way of River Huai, taking Shouchun. When you reach Guangling, the river is to be crossed and Nanxu is to be captured. Then Wu will be subdued.', 'context': 'Sima Yi then said, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Cao Pi is leading the dragon fleet and commanding three hundred thousand marines and ground forces against the South Land, and the danger is very great.', 'context': "The spies told the Prince of Wu's attendants of the dangers, and the latter hastened to inform the Prince. They said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'I shall have to recall Lu Xun,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'He is the only man to undertake this great task.', 'context': ' said the Prince. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Do not move him if you can help it; he is necessary for the protection of Jingzhou.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Yes, I know; but there is no other strong enough to help me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Noble Sir, what anxiety need I feel if I have your protection?', 'context': 'Sun Quan was pleased to find a willing volunteer, and replied, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 398, 'talk': 'My lord has laid upon you, O General, a heavy responsibility; but if you really desire to destroy the invading force and capture Cao Pi, you should send an army to meet him on the north side in the South of River Huai. I fear failure if you wait till the northern troops have come this far.', 'context': 'But another impetuous young leader was anxious to take more vigorous measures, and he stood forth, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 185, 'talk': "Cao Pi's army is strong and its leaders famous. I hold that we may not cross the river to meet him, but wait the arrival of his ships on the other side. Then I shall carry out my plan,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'I have three thousand troops of my own, and I know the country about Guangling thoroughly. Let me go across the river and fight a battle. I will willingly undergo the penalty if I fail,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 150, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'What control shall I have if you are allowed to disobey orders?', 'context': 'However, Xu Sheng refused, and all the pleadings of his impetuous general were vain. And when he still persisted, the Commander grew angry and said, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'I have been at Guangling, and if we do not attack the enemy there, but let him get down to the river, there will be an end of Wu.', 'context': 'Sun Shao began to press his claim to the Prince, saying, “'},
{'istart': 308, 'iend': 486, 'talk': 'O Prince, you placed me in command of the force to repulse Wei. Now this general of mine, Sun Shao, is disobedient and should suffer death. I would ask why he should be pardoned.', 'context': ' Sun Quan went into the camp, and Xu Sheng came to receive him. When the Prince was seated in his tent, Xu Sheng said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'He is naturally hot and impetuous. He has been guilty of disobedience, but I hope you will overlook his fault.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'The law is none of my making, nor is it yours, O Prince; it is a state penalty, and if relationship is enough to evade it, where is discipline?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'Since you have intervened, O Prince, I remit the death penalty.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'I can only lead my troops against Cao Pi and so die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'I cannot consent to the other plan.', 'context': ' cried Sun Shao. “'},
{'istart': 212, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'He will not be any loss,', 'context': " Xu Sheng's countenance changed. The recalcitrant young man was ordered to leave the tent by Sun Quan. “"},
{'istart': 254, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'and I will not employ him again.', 'context': ' said Sun Quan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'How many soldiers are on the other bank?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'I have not seen a single one; nor are there any flags or encampments.', 'context': 'Cao Zhen replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'That is a ruse; I will go and find out.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Do you think we should cross?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'So I think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'But as it is now late, we will pass the night on the river.', 'context': ' said the Ruler of Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'What do you think it means?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'A long wall by the Great River has grown up in a night and stood there with carts and masts of ships lying along it, stretching some one hundred miles from Shidou to Nanxu.', 'context': 'In just a short time several reports came: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'My hosts of troops are no use against such warriors; we can do nothing against those talents of the South Land,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun is marching out through Yangping Pass and threatening Changan.', 'context': 'Soon came a hasty messenger to report: “'},
{'istart': 141, 'iend': 912, 'talk': 'The Mang King, Meng Huo, leading one hundred thousand Mang tribesmen, has invaded the south and is laying waste the country; Yong Kai, the Governor of Jianning, a descent of the Han Lord Yong Chi of Shifang, had joined Meng Huo to rebel. Zhu Bao and Gao Ding, the Governors of Zangge and Yuesui, have yielded to the invaders; but the Governor of Yongchang, Wang Kang, is staunchly holding out. The three rebels—Yong Kai, Gao Ding, and Zhu Bao—, who had joined the invaders, are now acting as guides and assisting in the attack on Yongchang, which has remained faithful. Governor Wang Kang, ably assisted by Lu Kai, one of his subordinates, is making a desperate effort to defend the city with only its ordinary inhabitants as fighting men. The position is very desperate.', 'context': 'Such was the state of things when, in the third year of Beginning Prosperity (AD 225), the news came from Yiazhou to the capital to report: “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'The contumacy of the Mangs is a real danger to our state. I feel it incumbent upon me to lead an expedition to reduce the tribespeople to obedience.', 'context': 'When this news came, Zhuge Liang went into the palace and thus memorialized to his lord, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'Sun Quan is in the east, and Cao Pi the north; if you abandon me and either of them comes, what shall do?', 'context': 'But the Latter Ruler was afraid, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 296, 'talk': 'I am going to sweep clean the Mang country, so that we may have a free hand to attack Wei when the day comes. Thus I shall be enabled to requite the honor paid me by your father the First Ruler, who came thrice to seek me and who doubled my obligation when he confided to me the care of his son.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Indeed I am young and ignorant,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'and can only exist with you to decide for me.', 'context': ' replied the Latter Ruler, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 430, 'talk': 'No, no, Sir; you may not go! The South Mang is a wild country reeking with malaria. It is wrong that an officer of state in such an exalted and responsible position should go away on a distant expedition. These rebels and barbarians are but an irritation, not a disease, and an ordinary leader would be enough to send against them. He would not fail.', 'context': 'At that moment Counselor Wang Lian, a man of Nanyang, stepped forward, crying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'This country of the Mangs is distant and mostly uncivilized. To reduce them to reasonableness will be difficult, and I feel I ought to go. When to be harsh and when to show leniency are matters to be decided on at the moment, and instructions cannot be easily given to another.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'O Malcontent! Be quick to surrender!', 'context': 'The two sides drew up for battle; and, the arrays being complete, Wei Yan rode out and vilified the rebels, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Whom do you belong to?', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang asked, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'I am one of the generals under Gao Ding.', 'context': 'E Huan replied, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'How did E Huan manage to return?', 'context': "Next day, Yong Kai came over to Gao Ding's camp to visit him. After the exchange of salutations, Yong Kai asked, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang released him out of pure kindness,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'This is a ruse of his to separate you from me: he wishes to make us enemies.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Whose soldiers were you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': "Gao Ding's,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': "We all really belong to Gao Ding's command,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 425, 'talk': "Yong Kai has just sent a messenger to ask that he may surrender, and he offers to bring with him the heads of Gao Ding and Zhu Bao as a proof of merit. But I will not receive him, and you, since you are Gao Ding's soldiers, shall be released and allowed to return to him. But let there be no ingratitude and fighting again, for if there is, I certainly will not pardon you next time.", 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang addressed them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 296, 'iend': 446, 'talk': 'Why has your leader failed to send me the heads of Gao Ding and Zhu Bao as he promised? You lot are not very clever, and what are you come to spy out?', 'context': "Although this seemed very satisfactory, yet Gao Ding did not feel convinced, and he sent another man to Zhuge Liang's camp to try to verify the rumor. But this man was captured and taken before the Commander−in−Chief, who pretended that he thought the spy belonged to Yong Kai, and said to him, “"},
{'istart': 152, 'iend': 243, 'talk': 'You give this letter to your commander, Yong Kai, and tell him to get the job done quickly.', 'context': 'The soldier muttered and mumbled in confusion. But Zhuge Liang gave the man wine and food, and then wrote a letter which he handed to the spy, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'I have ever been true to him, and yet he wants to kill me. It is hard to be either friendly or reasonable.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 237, 'talk': "Zhuge Liang is a most benevolent man, and it would be ill to turn our backs upon him. It is Yong Kai's fault that we are now rebels, and our best course would be to slay him and betake ourselves to Zhuge Liang.", 'context': 'of Zhuge Liang, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'How could it be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'Invite him to a banquet. If he refuses, it means he is a traitor, and then you can attack him in front while I will lie in wait behind his camp to capture him as he runs away.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'Influenced by your kindness, Sir, I have brought the head of my colleague as a proof of the sincerity of my surrender; why should I die?', 'context': 'But Gao Ding said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'You come with false intent; do you think you can hoodwink me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'What proof have you that I am false?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, laughing. “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'Zhu Bao sent this secretly to say he wished to surrender, and he said you and Yong Kai were sworn friends to death. How could you suddenly change your feelings and slay him? That is how I know your treachery.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang drew a letter from his box, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Zhu Bao only tried to make trouble,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'I cannot believe you without more solid proof. If you would slay Zhu Bao, I could take that as proving you were sincere in your surrender.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang still refused to believe him, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Do not doubt me. What if I go and capture this man?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'If you did that, my doubts would be set at rest.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Why did you write a letter to the Prime Minister and so intrigue with him to get me killed?', 'context': 'But Gao Ding cried out to him, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'The soldiers should either yield or be slain!', 'context': 'Thereupon Gao Ding shouted, “'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'I have made you kill both these as a proof of loyalty.', 'context': 'Gao Ding then went back to Zhuge Liang and offered the head of the man just slain. Zhuge Liang laughed again. “'},
{'istart': 173, 'iend': 219, 'talk': 'Who has aided you in the defense of this city?', 'context': 'Governor Wang Kang of Yongchang then came out of the city and welcomed Zhuge Liang; and, when Zhuge Liang had made his entry into that city, he called Wang Kang and asked, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'The safety of this city is due entirely to Lu Kai.', 'context': 'The Governor said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'I come by special command of the Emperor with gifts of wine and silks for the soldiers.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 159, 'talk': "I have His Majesty's command to conquer these Mangs. I hear you have some advice to offer, and I should be pleased if you would instruct me.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 538, 'talk': 'Yes; I have one thing to say that may be worth thinking over. These people refuse to recognize our supremacy, because they think their country is distant and difficult. If you should overcome them today, tomorrow they would revolt. Wherever your army marches, they are overcome and submit; but the day you withdraw the army and attack Cao Pi, they will renew their attack. In arms even it is best to attack hearts rather than cities; to fight with sentiment is better than to fight with weapons. It will be well if you can win them over.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'You read my inmost thoughts,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Three Ravines', 'context': 'called together the leaders of the “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang and his Grand Army has invaded our country, and we must exert our united strength to drive out the invaders. You three must lead your forces, and whoever conquers the enemy shall be chief of chiefs.', 'context': "These having come to the King's place, he said to them, “"},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 290, 'talk': 'I cannot send Zhao Yun and Wei Yan against the Mangs because they do not know the country. You two are to go, one against each wing, and the two veteran warriors shall support you. Get your troops ready and start tomorrow at dawn.', 'context': 'Next he sent for Wang Ping and Ma Zhong, and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'You two are to march against the center army; you are to act with Wang Ping and Ma Zhong tomorrow. I want to send Zhao Yun and Wei Yan, but I am still afraid they do not know the country well.', 'context': 'Then Zhang Yi and Zhang Ni were given orders: “'},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 316, 'talk': 'I have no wish to pass you over, you two, but I fear that if you get too deeply into the country and should fall victims to the Mangs, it will have an ill effect on the others.', 'context': 'Zhang Yi and Zhang Ni also received the orders and went out. Zhao Yun and Wei Yan now began to feel hurt. Noticing this, Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'But what if we did know the geography of the country?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'All I say to you is to be careful how you do anything,', 'context': ' said Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'We are greatly ashamed at being put in the background because we do not know the country. We cannot bear this.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Then let us ride out and survey,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Let us capture a few natives and make them show us the road, and let us defeat these tribesmen.', 'context': ' said his colleague. “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'The camp of Chief Jinhua Sanjie is just in front, just by the entrance to the mountains. Near the camp, running east and west, is the Five Valleys. The camps of the other two chiefs—Dongtu Na and Ahui Nan—are behind.', 'context': 'Said they, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'The three parties of Mangs have fled, and Dongtu Na and Ahui Nan escaped; where is the head of Jinhua Sanjie?', 'context': 'They returned to headquarters, and Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 218, 'iend': 338, 'talk': 'Dongtu Na and Ahui Nan escaped by abandoning their horses and going over the hills. Therefore, we could not be followed.', 'context': ' Zhao Yun produced it. At the same time he reported: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'They are already prisoners,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 567, 'talk': 'I had studied the map and knew the positions of the camps. I taunted Zhao Yun and Wei Yan into making a supreme effort into the camp of Jinhua Sanjie; at the same time that I sent other forces under Wang Ping and Ma Zhong, with the purpose to support Zhao Yun and Wei Yan and to force Dongtu Na and Ahui Nan to flee. I felt certain the two chiefs would run away along those small roads, and I set soldiers under Zhang Ni and Zhang Yi on those roads to wait for them. They also were supported.', 'context': 'When the Shu leaders expressed surprise and admiration, Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 91, 'talk': "The Prime Minister's calculations are divine and incomprehensible.", 'context': 'They all bowed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Tomorrow Meng Huo will come in person to make an attack. We shall probably capture him again.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said to his generals, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 473, 'talk': 'It has always been said that Zhuge Liang is a wonderful soldier, but I see that is false. Look at this array with its banners all in confusion and the ranks in disorder. There is not a weapon among all the swords and spears better than ours. If I had only realized this before, I would have fought them long ago. Who dares go out and capture a Shu general to show them what sort of warriors we are?', 'context': 'He looked haughtily at his foes, and then, turning to his generals, said, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Why did you rebel after the generous treatment you have received from our Emperor?', 'context': 'knelt in front of the Commander−in−Chief, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'The two Lands of the Rivers belonged to others, and your lord took it from them by force, and gave himself the title of Emperor. My people have lived here for ages, and you and yours invaded my country without the least excuse. How can you talk of rebellion to me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'You are my prisoner; will you submit or are you still contumacious?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Why should I submit? You happened to find me in a narrow place; that is all.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'If I release you, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 122, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'Meng Huo is the most important personage of all the Mangs, and his capture is the key to restoring order in the south. Why then, O Minister, did you release him?', 'context': 'The officers did not approve of the release of the King of the Mangs, and they came to the tent of Zhuge Liang and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'I can capture him just as easily as I can get something out of my pocket. What I want to do is to overcome and win his heart, so that peace may follow of itself.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'How were Your Highness able to get back?', 'context': 'They were surprised, but glad, to see him, and asked, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'They confined me in a tent, and I broke out in the night. I slew more than ten guards and ran. And then I met one of their sentries, killed him, and that is how I got this horse.', 'context': 'The King lied, saying, “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 490, 'talk': 'I know Zhuge Liang is too full of ruses for us to conquer him in a fight; we should only fall victims to other base devices. However, we must remember that his soldiers have marched far and the weather is sultry, which are factors in our favor. Beside, River Lu is our rampart. We will have boats and rafts on the south side, and we will build a mud wall. With such good defenses we can afford to wait and see what the enemy intends.', 'context': 'When all had assembled, the King proclaimed as follows: “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'No boats or rafts can be found to cross, and the current is too strong to think of fording. Beside, we can see the formidable defenses on the farther bank, the mud wall and the turrets all fully manned.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang had advanced, and his leading division was now close to the river. Spies came back to report: “'},
{'istart': 253, 'iend': 490, 'talk': 'The enemy is securely established on the south bank ready to repel our attack. Yet, having come so far, we cannot return empty. For the present you will all seek what shelter you can find in the forests, and rest and refresh your people.', 'context': 'The weather was burning hot, for it was the fifth mouth, and the soldiers could not tolerate their armor nor even their clothing. When Zhuge Liang had inspected the river, he returned to his tent and assembled his officers, to whom he read this order: “'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 366, 'talk': 'These shelters of Lu Kai are very unsuitable. He has made the same mistake as that which led to the defeat of the First Ruler at the hands of Wu. He has not taken into account the surroundings of the stockades, and if the Mangs should come over and start a fire, there could be no rescue.', 'context': 'However, Jiang Wan, observed these shelters and went to Zhuge Liang, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Do not anticipate trouble,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'I have provided against all such dangers.', 'context': ' said the Commander−in−Chief, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'What force have you brought?', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Three thousand,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'My people are weary and worn out; I want to use yours. You have no objections?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Of course not; they are equally government troops. They are ready even to die for you if you wish.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'This Meng Huo is established on the river, and we have no means of crossing. But I am anxious to intercept his supplies, so that his troops may mutiny.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'How can you do it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 384, 'talk': 'It happens so every year. In the hot season, poisonous miasma collects over the waters of the River Lu, especially during the heat of the day. Anyone who drinks the water will surely die. Travelers who wish to cross have to wait till night, because the cooler waters do not breathe out the poisonous vapors. Further, the crossing should be attempted on a full stomach.', 'context': 'They told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 360, 'talk': 'If I attempt to oppose Zhuge Liang, I shall certainly fall a victim to some wile of his. However, my waiting policy is a safe one. With our defenses, and the river to back them, we can wait for the heat to overcome these men of Shu, who cannot stand the hot season. They will have to retreat, and then we can harass them. And we will capture this Zhuge Liang.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 244, 'talk': 'Remember the shallows at Shakou; it would be very serious if the soldiers of Shu got across there secretly. It ought to be guarded.', 'context': 'He lay back and laughed at the thought. However, one chief, more prudent than the others, stood forth and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'You belong to these areas. Do you not know that I want the enemy to try to get across there? Why, they will all perish in the water.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'But what if the natives tell them to cross only in the night?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Do not be so anxious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Our own people will not help the enemy that far.', 'context': ' said Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'This sort of fellow is not worth talking about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I will go,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'O you ingrate! How could you forget the debt to the Prime Minister? Have you known no shame?', 'context': 'So Ma Dai galloped toward him, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'You are a traitor! I know Zhuge Liang was good to you, and that is why you would not fight.', 'context': 'But Meng Huo was angry, and cried, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 657, 'talk': "Though we live in the Mang country, we have never had any thoughts of rebellion against the Imperial Government, nor has the Middle Empire ever encroached upon our land. We must own that Meng Huo's superior power forced us into this rising, and we could not help ourselves. Zhuge Liang is too clever for us, and no one can guess what he may do. Even Cao Cao and Sun Quan fear him; how much more must we? Moreover, we have received kindness at his hands and owe him our lives. We ought to show our gratitude. Now let us at all risks slay this Meng Huo and submit to Zhuge Liang so that our people may not suffer.", 'context': 'They went to the tent of Dongtu Na and said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'I do not know your inner sentiments.', 'context': 'Dongtu Na said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'You also received kindness from Zhuge Liang and ought to repay it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'You do not have to slay him; let us carry him a prisoner to the Prime Minister.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 299, 'iend': 371, 'talk': 'You said once before that if you were captured again, you would give in,', 'context': 'their weapons. All being ready, he told the chiefs to bring up their prisoner, and bade the others return to their camps. Dongtu Na went first and told the matter to Zhuge Liang, who praised his zeal and gave him presents. Then he retired with the chiefs, and the executioners brought in Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 401, 'iend': 420, 'talk': 'Now will you yield?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'This capture is not your work,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'It is the work of these minions of mine who want to hurt me. I will not yield on this.', 'context': ' replied Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'If I free you again, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 304, 'talk': 'I am only a Mang, I know, but I am not wholly ignorant of war. If you, O Minister, let me return to my ravines, I will muster another army and fight a decisive battle with you. If you capture me again, then I will incline my heart and own myself beaten and yield. I will not go back on my promise again.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'If you refuse to yield next time you are captured, I shall hardly pardon you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 95, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'Remember,', 'context': "At Zhuge Liang's orders the cords were loosed and refreshments were brought for the prisoner. “"},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 174, 'talk': "I know all the details of the enemy's force from what I saw in their camp.", 'context': 'Meng Huo then returned to his own ravine and discussed matters with his brother, Meng You, saying, “'},
{'istart': 791, 'iend': 822, 'talk': 'Know you why this man has come?', 'context': 'And Meng Huo gave his brother certain instructions, which Meng You at once began to carry out. Meng You loaded a hundred men with gold and jewels and pearls and ivory and rhinoceros horn, crossed River Lu, and was on his way to the main camp of the Shu army, when he heard the sound of drums and a cohort under Ma Dai poured out to stop him. Meng You did not expect to meet an enemy, and was surprised. But Ma Dai only asked what he had come for. And when he had heard, Meng You was detained while a message was sent to Zhuge Liang. The messenger arrived while a council was in progress, the matter under discussion being how to reduce the Mangs. When the messenger had announced that Meng You had come bearing gifts of gold and pearls and such things, Zhuge Liang turned to Ma Su, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'I dare not say plainly; but let me write it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Write it, then.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'What you say is exactly what I think. But you may know I have already made arrangements for the capture of Meng Huo.', 'context': 'with joy, crying, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 373, 'talk': 'The brother of my house, Meng Huo, having received great kindness at your hands in sparing his life, feels bound to offer a paltry gift. He has presumed to collect a few pearls and some gold and other trifling jewels by way of something to give your soldiers. And hereafter he will send tribute to your Emperor.', 'context': 'Meng You came and bowed low at the door of the tent, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Where is your brother at this moment?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'How many soldiers have you brought?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Only about a hundred; I should not dare to bring any large number. They are just porters.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 285, 'talk': 'The presents have been accepted, and even the porters have been invited to drink in the tent and have been regaled with beef and flesh in plenty. O King, your brother sends the news that all will be ready at the second watch for the attack. He will support you from within.', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'Let each army carry the means of making fire, and as soon as they arrive let a light be shown as a signal. I am coming to the main camp to capture Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'The King called up his chieftains and notables, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'That was but a shallow ruse of yours to send your brother with presents to pretend to submit to me; did you really think I should not see through it? But here you are once more in my power; now do you yield?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'I am a prisoner owing to the gluttony of my brother and the power of your poisonous drugs. If I had only played his part myself and left him to support me with soldiers, I should have succeeded. I am the victim of fate and not of my own incapacity. No; I will not yield.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Remember this is the third time; why not?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Ah, well; I will let you go once more,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'Certainly I shall scarcely pardon you next time,', 'context': 'once more. If I am caught that time, then I will confess myself beaten to the ground, and that shall be the end.” “'},
{'istart': 184, 'iend': 384, 'talk': 'You would better be careful. Diligently tackle your Book of Strategy; look over your list of confidants. If you can apply a good plan at the proper moment, you will not have any need for late regrets.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 309, 'iend': 355, 'talk': 'Next time you are caught, you will not escape.', 'context': 'By the time the released prisoners had got back to the river, the army of Shu had crossed to the farther side and had captured the Mang defenses, the Shu flags fluttering in the breeze. As Meng Huo passed the camp, he saw Ma Dai sitting in state. Ma Dai pointed his sword at the King as he passed, and said, “'},
{'istart': 193, 'iend': 287, 'talk': 'Do not presume on the kindness of the Prime Minister because you have been generously treated.', 'context': 'When Meng Huo came to his own camp, he found Zhao Yun in possession and all in order. Zhao Yun was seated beneath the large banner, with his sword drawn, and as the King passed, he also said, “'},
{'istart': 149, 'iend': 380, 'talk': 'See to it; we have got into the inmost recesses of your country and have taken all your defensive positions. Yet you are fool enough to hold out. Next time you are caught, you will be quite destroyed. There will be no more pardons.', 'context': 'Meng Huo grunted and passed on. Just as he was going over the frontier hills, he saw Wei Yan and a company drawn up on the slopes. Wei Yan shouted, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'O Minister, you are indeed perfect in every one of the three gifts: wisdom, benevolence, and valor. Not even Lu Wang or Zhang Liang can equal you!', 'context': 'They all bowed, and one said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'How can I expect to equal our men of old? But my trust is in your strength, and together we shall succeed.', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'This is what I was waiting for, that the Mangs should have an opportunity of knowing our might.', 'context': 'And the scouts knew it all, and they told Zhuge Liang, who said, “'},
{'istart': 293, 'iend': 463, 'talk': 'There is close by a mountain covered with bamboos. I have heard of these bamboos, and some are several spans in girth. We can make a bridge of them for the army to cross.', 'context': "Zhuge Liang's small carriage was escorted by only a few horsemen. Hearing that a sluggish river, the Western River, lay in the way, and having no boat, Zhuge Liang bade the escort cut down some trees and make a raft. They did so, but the raft sank. So Zhuge Liang turned to Lu Kai, who said, “"},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 293, 'talk': 'These men are not submissive to the Empire Government and are naturally fierce and turbulent. In that mood we are no match for them. But all we have to do is to remain on guard for a few days till their ferocity has spent itself. Then I have a plan that will overcome them.', 'context': 'Presently he said, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Dare you give battle now?', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang called together his generals and asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'They have abandoned the camp,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'But this is only a ruse.', 'context': ' said Meng You. “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 330, 'talk': 'I think that Zhuge Liang has important news from the capital that has made him leave without his baggage train like this. Either Wu has invaded or Wei has attacked. They left these lamps burning to make us think the camps were occupied, but they ran away leaving everything behind. If we pursue we cannot go wrong.', 'context': 'Said Meng Huo, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'This means that Zhuge Liang fears lest we may pursue. That is only a temporary halt, and they will retire in a couple of days.', 'context': 'Meng Huo said to his brother, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'So King of the Mangs has got here! How does Heaven make you defeated so? I have waited for you a long time.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang laughed, and said, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 265, 'talk': "Thrice have I been the victim of this man's base wiles and have been put to shame. Now chance has sent him across my path, and you must attack him with all your energy. Let us cut him to pieces and those with him.", 'context': 'Meng Huo angrily turned to his followers and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'Your brother is a misguided simpleton; you ought to remonstrate with him and persuade him to change his course. Here you are, a captive for the fourth time; are you not ashamed? How can you have the effrontery to look anyone in the face?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'If I put you to death, it shall not be today. This time I pardon you, but you are to talk to your brother.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'What can you say now? You see you are in my hands again.', 'context': 'Very soon Wei Yan brought up Meng Huo, and to him Zhuge Liang simulated great rage, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'I am again an unfortunate victim,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Once more I have blundered into your net, and now I shall die with no one to close my eyes.', 'context': ' said Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 148, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'If you freed me only once more, I would wipe out the shame of all four captures.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang shouted to the lictors to take him away and behead him. Meng Huo never blenched at the sentence, but he turned to his captor and said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Four times you have been treated generously and yet you are still defiant. Why?', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I have liberated you four times; do you think you can give battle again?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'We cannot stand against the enemy. We have been defeated several times. Now I think we would better go into the mountains and hide in some dark gully where they cannot find us. Those soldiers of Shu will never stand the summer heat; they must retire.', 'context': 'Meng You said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Where can we hide?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 140, 'talk': "I know a valley away southwest from us called 'Bald Dragon Ravine,' and the King, Duo Si, is a friend of mine. Let us take refuge with him.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Very well; go and arrange it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'O King, rest content. If those men from the Lands of Rivers come here, I will see to it that not one goes home. And Zhuge Liang will meet his death here too.', 'context': 'Duo Si said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 1079, 'talk': "Then again there are four streams actually poisonous. One is called 'The Dumb Spring.' Its water is pleasant to the palate, but it makes people dumb and they die in a few days. A second fountain is called 'The Spring of Destruction' and is hot. But if a person bathes therein, his flesh rots till his bones protrude and he dies. The third is 'The Black Spring.' Its waters are greenish. If it be sprinkled on a person's body, his limbs turn black and presently he dies. The fourth is 'The Spring of Weak Water,' ice cold. If a person drink of this water his breath is chilled, he becomes weak as a thread and soon dies. Neither birds nor insects are found in this region, and no one but the Han General Ma Yuan, who was styled General Who Quells the Waves for this exploit, has ever passed. Now the northeast road shall be blocked, and you may hide here perfectly safe from those troops of Shu, for, finding that way blocked, they will try the other road, which is waterless save for the four deadly springs. No matter how many they be, they will perish, and we need no weapons.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Now indeed I have found a place to live in,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 237, 'talk': "Even Zhuge Liang's wonderful cunning will be of no avail. The four springs alone will defeat him and avenge my army.", 'context': ' cried Meng Huo, striking his forehead. Then looking to the north he said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'The valley is garrisoned, the hills are precipitous and even impassable.', 'context': 'Dragon Ravine and the barricading of one entrance. They also said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 287, 'talk': "Meng Huo's repeated captures have broken his spirit so that he dare not take the field again. Our soldiers are exhausted with this intense heat, and little is to be gained by prolonging the campaign. The best move would be to return to our own country.", 'context': 'Then out spoke Jiang Wan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': "If we do this, we shall fall victims to Meng Huo's scheme,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'If we retreated, he would certainly follow. Beside, having advanced so far, it would be fruitless to turn back now.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 723, 'talk': 'Your humble servant received a sacred trust, the protection of the son of the First Ruler. That son, the present Emperor, sent him here to subdue the Mangs that the land might be free from peril when he decided to attack Wei and take possession of Wu and thereby restore the glory of the Hans. But the soldiers are ignorant of the country, and some of them have drunk of a poisonous spring so that they have become dumb. Your servant earnestly prays your honored spirit, out of regard for the kindness and justice of the present Emperor, to reveal your spiritual character and manifest your holiness by safeguarding and assisting the army.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang, much impressed, bowed before the image of the great leader, and said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'Sir Minister, I know you well by repute, and am happy to meet you. Many of the Mangs owe their lives to you, and all have been deeply impressed by your kindness.', 'context': 'The old gentleman replied, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 338, 'talk': 'That is the Dumb Spring that your soldiers have drunk, and they will die in a few days. Besides that, there are other three poisonous streams called Spring of Destruction, Black Spring, and Spring of Weak Water. All miasma gathers there in the four streams, and it only vaporizes during the two watch before sunset.', 'context': 'The old man told him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'In short, the Mangs cannot be conquered,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'And Wu cannot be repressed, nor Wei overcome. And the Hans cannot be restored. So, I fail in the task set me by my Prince. Wish that I might die?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang when the old man had finished. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Be not so cast down, O Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'I can lead you to a place where you may counteract all this.', 'context': ' said the aged one. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'I would ask for your instruction, Venerable One,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'What exalted advice have you to confer upon me? I hope you will instruct me.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 648, 'talk': "West of this, not far off, is a valley, and seven miles from its entrance is a stream called the 'Spring of Eternal Peace,' near which there lives a recluse known as the Hermit of the Stream. He has not left the valley these twenty years. Behind his hut there gushes out a spring of water, called the 'Spring of Peace and Joy.' This is the antidote to your poison. Bathing in its waters is a cure for skin diseases and for malaria. Moreover, near the hut grows an herb called the 'garlic−leaved fragrance.' Chewing a leaf of this safeguards one from malaria. You can do no better than go to the hut of the recluse forthwith and get these remedies.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Venerable Sir, I am profoundly affected by your merciful kindness and compassion. May I ask again by what name may call you?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang humbly thanked his aged counselor, and said, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I am the Spirit of this mountain, sent by Ma Yuan to guide you.', 'context': 'The old man rose and entered the temple, saying, “'},
{'istart': 180, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'Surely my visitor is the Prime Minister of the Han Dynasty?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang rejoiced to recognize the spot and at once knocked at the door. A lad answered his knock, and Zhuge Liang was telling his name when the host came out quickly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Great Scholar, how did you know who I was?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'How could I not have heard of your expedition to the south?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 689, 'talk': "My former Prince, the First Ruler, confided to me the care of his son and successor. That son, now Emperor, gave me a command to lead an army to this country, get the Mangs on our side and spread our culture among them. But now to my disappointment Meng Huo, the King, has hidden himself in the Bald Dragon Ravine, and some of my soldiers on the way to seek him drank of a certain fountain and are dumb. But last evening the former leader of an expedition, Ma Yuan, manifested his sacred presence and told me that you, Exalted Sir, had a remedy for this evil, and I pray you of your pity to give me of the potent fluid whereby my soldiers' lives may be saved.", 'context': 'and guest, Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'I am only a worthless old man of the wild woods and unworthy of the visit of such as you, O Minister. The water you desire flows out at the back of my cottage and you may take what you will of it.', 'context': 'The recluse replied, “'},
{'istart': 143, 'iend': 339, 'talk': 'In this region, the lands are full of serpents and scorpions, and the lily flowers blown into the springs by the wind make them unfit to drink. However, if you dig wells, you will find good water.', 'context': 'In the cottage the recluse regaled Zhuge Liang with tea made of cypress seeds and a conserve of pine flowers. He also told his guest, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': "I am Meng Huo's eldest brother,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'My name is Meng Jie.', 'context': ' said the recluse, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Do not be afraid,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'Now I believe that story of the robber Liu Zhi and the noble Liu Xiahui; this is the same thing over again. People renowned for villainy and virtue may come from the same stock.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 235, 'iend': 320, 'talk': 'Would you wish me to represent your merits to the Emperor and get you created a king?', 'context': ' Then he said to his host, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'How can you think I desire honors or wealth when I am here because of my contempt for all such things?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 209, 'iend': 276, 'talk': 'These troops do not appear to have suffered either thirst or fever,', 'context': "The soldiers' spirits revived with the supply of water, and the army soon advanced by hill paths to the Valley of the Bald Dragon, where they camped. When Meng Huo heard the news, he was greatly taken aback. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'These are not human soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'They must be sent from Heaven.', 'context': ' said he, shivering. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Our two brothers will fight one fierce battle with these troops of Shu and die therein,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'We cannot wait calmly to be put into bonds.', 'context': ' said Meng Huo, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 287, 'talk': 'But, O King, if your army should be beaten, my whole family will also perish. Let us encourage the people of the ravines. Let us kill bullocks and slaughter horses to feed them, and urge them to go through fire and water to rush right up to the camp of the enemy and seize upon victory.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 367, 'iend': 682, 'talk': 'I have with me thirty thousand troops in iron mail, brave and intrepid warriors, who can fly over mountains and bound across the peaks; they of themselves are a match for the enemy even if the enemy numbered a hundred legions. And, moreover, my five sons, all trained in arms, are with me, all to help you, O Kings.', 'context': 'So there was great feasting before the Mangs took the field. Just as this was going on, there arrived one Yang Feng, King of twenty−one ravines in the west, and he led thirty thousand troops. Meng Huo rejoiced exceedingly at this unexpected addition to his army and felt sure of victory. So he and Duo Si went out of their own valley to welcome Yang Feng, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'There is but scanty amusement in the field,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'and so I have brought along some native singing girls who have been taught fencing and such things. If you care for it, they might give an exhibition.', 'context': ' said Yang Feng, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'When the hare dies the fox mourns,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 173, 'talk': "One sympathizes with one's own as a rule. We are both chiefs and have been friends. I know not why you should injure me.", 'context': ' said Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'I had to repay Zhuge Liang the Minister for his compassion on me and my people, and there was no way till you rebelled. Why should I not offer up a rebel in propitiation?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'I and my sons and the sons of my brother are grateful to you for much kindness, wherefore we bring to you as an offering the persons of these rebels.', 'context': 'Yang Feng then took the prisoners to the camp of Shu, where he bowed at the tent door, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'This time are you prepared to yield?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'My fathers have long held the Silver Pit Hills, and the three rivers and the two forests are their ramparts. If you can take that stronghold, then will I and my heirs for ever acknowledge your power and yield.', 'context': 'Meng Huo replied, “'},
{'istart': 231, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'I am going to liberate you once more,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 289, 'iend': 493, 'talk': 'and you may put your army in order if you will and fight a decisive battle. But after that, if you are my prisoner and are still refractory and unsubmissive, I shall have to exterminate your whole family.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 441, 'iend': 452, 'talk': 'Silver Pit.', 'context': 'Outside this ravine were three rivers—River Lu, River Gannan, and River Xicheng. These three streams united to form Three Rivers. Close to the ravine on the north was a wide and fruitful plain; on the west were salt wells. The River Lu flowed about seventy miles to the southwest, and due south was a valley called the Liangdu Ravine. There were hills in, as well as surrounding, the ravine, and in these they found silver; whence the name “'},
{'istart': 149, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Family Spirits,', 'context': 'A palace complex had been built in the ravine, which the Mang kings had made their stronghold, and there was an ancestral temple, which they called “'},
{'istart': 270, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'Inquiring of the Spirits.', 'context': ' where they solemnized sacrifices of bulls and horses at the four seasons. They called these sacrifices “'},
{'istart': 468, 'iend': 479, 'talk': 'Drug Demon.', 'context': ' Human sacrifices were offered also, humans of Shu or of their own people belonging to other villages. The sick swallowed no drugs, but prayed to a chief sorcerer, called “'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'King of the Ravine,', 'context': 'All over the country the head of the family of greatest local consideration is termed “'},
{'istart': 148, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'Notable.', 'context': ' and the next in importance is called a “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'I have been put to shame by the leaders of Shu many times, and I have sworn to take revenge for the insults. Has anyone any proposal to make?', 'context': 'In his own ravine, Meng Huo gathered his family and clan to the number of a thousand or more and addressed them: “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'I can produce a man able to defeat Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'Thereupon a certain one replied, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Who is the man?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 224, 'iend': 331, 'talk': 'Every man should provide himself with a coat by the first watch. If any one lacks, he will be put to death.', 'context': 'The army of Shu made a strong camp in their new halting place and closed the gates for defense. For five days they gave no sign. One evening, just at sunset, a slight breeze began to blow. Then Zhuge Liang issued an order: “'},
{'istart': 229, 'iend': 326, 'talk': 'You are to carry the earth to the foot of the city wall, and the first arrivals will be rewarded.', 'context': 'None of the generals knew what was in the wind, but the order was obeyed. Next, each man was ordered to fill his coat with earth. This order appeared equally strange, but it was carried out. When all were ready, they were told: “'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'Though you are brave, how stupid you are! I am only a woman, but I want to go out and fight.', 'context': 'Just as he was in the very depths of distress, a laugh came from behind the screen, and a woman appeared, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 163, 'talk': 'No; five times has Zhuge Liang set me at liberty. It would be unjust to put these to death. Confine them till we have taken their chief; then we may execute them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'We have spent all our life in the battlefields, but we have never seen the like of that before,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'The fault is not yours,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'Long ago, when I was still in my rustic hut, I knew the Mangs possessed certain powers over beasts, and I provided against this adventure before we left Shu. You will find twenty big sealed carts in the baggage train. We will use half of them now.', 'context': ' he said. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'That is Zhuge Liang in that small chariot. If we can only capture him, our task is done.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 371, 'iend': 400, 'talk': 'Let my strong captors appear!', 'context': 'Hearing this, Zhang Ni and Ma Zhong were called and received certain orders, upon which they hid themselves in the wings of the tent with a large body of sturdy warriors. This done, Zhuge Liang ordered the keepers to open the gates, and in came Chief Dai Lai with Meng Huo and his people in custody. As Dai Lai bowed at the entrance of the hall, Zhuge Liang called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Did you think your paltry ruse would deceive me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Did you not say that if your family were taken prisoners you would yield? How now?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'We have come of our own will and at the risk of our lives; the credit is not yours. Still I refuse to yield,', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'This is the sixth time I have captured you, and yet you are obstinate; what do you expect?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'If you take me a seventh time, then I will turn to you and never rebel again.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Well, your stronghold is now destroyed. What have I to fear?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'If you are caught again and lie to me once more, I shall certainly not be inclined to let you off.', 'context': 'He ordered the bonds to be loosed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Whither can we go?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Our stronghold is in the hands of the enemy.', 'context': ' said Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 903, 'talk': 'There is but one country that can overcome these troops; that is the Wugo Kingdom. It lies two hundred miles to the southeast. The King of that state is named Wutu Gu. He is a giant of twelve spans. He does not eat grain, but lives on serpents and venomous beasts. He wears scaly armor, which is impenetrable to swords and arrows. His warriors wear rattan armor. This rattan grows in gullies, climbing over rocks and walls. The inhabitants cut the rattans and steep them in oil for half a year. Then they are dried in the sun. When dry they are steeped again, and so on many times. Then they are plaited into helmets and armor. Clad in this, the men float across rivers, and it does not get wet. No weapon can penetrate it. The soldiers are called the Rattan Army. You may seek aid from this king, and with his help you can take Zhuge Liang as easily as a sharp knife cleaves a bamboo.', 'context': 'Dai Lai replied, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 354, 'talk': 'I have heard of the Wugo Kingdom as perfectly barbarous, the people having no codes of law as they are understood in the Middle Empire. I have also heard of the rattan armor, which can withstand all thrusts, and the harmful River of Peach Flowers. The Southern Mangs are so untameable that victory will mean little. We would rather retreat.', 'context': 'Lu Kai said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'No, no,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'we have had too much difficulty in getting here to go back so easily. I shall have a counter−plan for these people tomorrow.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang merrily, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'What is the name of the valley?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'The very thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Surely this is providence. I shall score a great success here.', 'context': ' cried Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 426, 'talk': 'I will give you the ten black painted carts, and you are to get a thousand long bamboo poles. Open the carts, and follow my instructions there. Then you are to keep the two ends of the Coiled Serpent Valley. Half a month is the deadline, and all of these must be performed with the most perfect secrecy under military law and punishment.', 'context': 'Ma Dai was called and put in charge of the preparations. Zhuge Liang gave him an order: “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'This Zhuge Liang is exceedingly crafty. Ambush is one of his favorite ruses, so you should warn your soldiers that on no account should they enter a valley where the trees are thick.', 'context': 'Meng Huo had begun to have a real terror of Zhuge Liang, and he warned King Wutu Gu of Wugo, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Great King, you speak with reason,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 248, 'talk': 'I have always heard that the people of the Middle Empire are full of wiles, and I will see that your advice is followed. I will go in front to fight, and you may remain in the rear to give orders.', 'context': ' said Wutu Gu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Just as you foretold,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'The men of Shu like using ambush.', 'context': ' said Wutu Gu to Meng Huo. “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'The carts must be the commissariat wagons of the enemy, abandoned in their hasty flight when they heard of the coming of Your Majesty.', 'context': 'The soldiers said to each other, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 193, 'talk': 'The exit has been blocked with wood−laden carts, which on being broken open are found to contain gunpowder, and they are all on fire.', 'context': 'But he heard much shouting in the rear, and they told him: “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'Though I am rendering great service to my country, yet I have sacrificed many lives. My life may be shortened for this.', 'context': "Zhuge Liang's tears fell fast as he saw the slaughter, and he sighed, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'What now, rebel Meng Huo?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 213, 'iend': 406, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is ashamed and does not wish to see you again, Sir. He has sent me to release you. You may enlist another army if you can and once more try a decisive battle. Now you may go.', 'context': 'The chief prisoners were Meng Huo, Lady Zhurong, Meng You, and Dai Lai. There were many of his clan as well. As they were eating and drinking, a messenger appeared in the door of the tent and addressed the King: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Seven times a captive and seven times released!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 274, 'talk': 'Surely there was never anything like it in the whole world. I know I am a barbarian and beyond the pale, but I am not entirely devoid of a sense of propriety and rectitude. Does he think that I feel no shame?', 'context': ' said the King. “'},
{'istart': 135, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'O Minister, you are the majesty of Heaven. We people of the south will offer no more opposition.', 'context': 'Thereupon he and all his followers fell upon their knees and crawled to the tent of the Commander−in−Chief and begged pardon, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Then you yield?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'I and my children and grandchildren are deeply affected by your all−pervading and life−giving mercy. Now how can we not yield?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'You, O Minister, have led the army this long journey into the wilds and have reduced the Mang country, and have brought about the submission of the king; why not appoint officials to share in the administration and hold the land?', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 578, 'talk': 'There are three difficulties. To leave foreigners implies leaving a guard for them; there is the difficulty of feeding a guard. The Mangs have lost many of their relatives. To leave foreigners without a guard will invite a calamity; this is the second difficulty. Among the Mangs, dethronements and murders are frequent, and there will be enmities and suspicions. Foreigners and they will be mutually distrustful; this is the third difficulty. If I do not leave our people, I shall not have to send supplies, which makes for peace and freedom from trouble.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Wild spirits have always troubled those who would cross this river; it is necessary to propitiate them with sacrifices.', 'context': 'Meng Huo replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'What is the sacrifice?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 304, 'talk': 'In the old days when malicious spirits brought misfortune, they sacrificed humans to the number of seven sevens and offered their heads. They also slew a black ox and a white goat. Sacrifice thus; the wind will subside and the waters come to rest. The same used to be done to secure a plenteous harvest.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'How can I slay a single man without good reason now that fighting is done and peace has returned?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'We have heard the demons moaning every night since the army crossed the river. The cries begin at dusk and continued till dawn. There are many dark demons in the malarial vapors and no one dared cross.', 'context': 'They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'The sin is mine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'for more than a thousand soldiers of Ma Dai perished in these waters beside the southern people. Their poor distressed souls are not yet freed. Therefore I will come this night and sacrifice to them.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'According to the ancient rule the number of victims ought to be forty−nine; then the spirits will disperse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 185, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'mantou', 'context': 'By nightfall, an altar had been set up on the bank of the river with the sacrificial objects all arranged. There were also forty−nine lamps. Flags were flying to summon the souls. The “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Alas, ye dead! To you this offering!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Thy servant has offended in causing his master anxiety; but the conquest of the south was long.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang quickly descended from his chariot, prostrated himself and said, “'},
{'istart': 523, 'iend': 551, 'talk': 'She is the king among women,', 'context': 'The Ruler of Wei, Cao Pi, had now ruled seven years, and it was the fourth year of Beginning Prosperity in Shu−Han calendar. Cao Pi had taken to wife a lady of the Zhen family, formerly the wife of the second son of Yuan Shao. He had discovered Lady Zhen at the sack of Yejun and had married her. She bore him a son, Cao Rui, who was very clever and a great favorite with his father. Later Cao Pi took as Beloved Consort a daughter of Guo Yong in Guangzong. Lady Guo was a woman of exceeding beauty, whom her father said, “'},
{'istart': 567, 'iend': 578, 'talk': 'Female King', 'context': ' and the name “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 231, 'talk': "In the palace of the Empress has been dug up a wooden image with Your Majesty's date of birth written thereon. It is meant to exercise a maleficent influence.", 'context': 'At that time the Emperor was indisposed, and Zhang Tao alleged, saying, “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'Your Majesty has slain the mother; how can one kill the child as well?', 'context': "fawn's course led past his son's horse, Cao Pi called out to him to shoot it. Instead the youth bursts into tears. “"},
{'istart': 242, 'iend': 385, 'talk': 'I am grievously ill, and my end is near. I confide to your care and guidance this son of mine; you must support him out of good feeling for me.', 'context': "summoned to the bedside of the Emperor. They were Commander of the Central Army Cao Zhen, General Who Guards the West Chen Qun, and Grand Commander Sima Yi. When they had come, the Emperor's son was called, and the dying Emperor spoke thus: “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Why does Your Majesty talk thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'We will do our utmost to serve you for a thousand autumns and a myriad years.', 'context': ' said they. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'No; I know that I am about to die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'The sudden fall of the gates of Xuchang this year was the omen, as I well knew.', 'context': ' said the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'You and these three are the pillars and cornerstones of the state. If you will only uphold my son, I can close my eyes in peace.', 'context': 'When he had entered, Cao Pi said to him, “'},
{'istart': 187, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'Emperor Pi.', 'context': 'The four ministers raised the wailing for the dead and forthwith busied themselves with setting up Cao Rui as the Emperor of Great Wei. The late Emperor received the posthumous style of “'},
{'istart': 266, 'iend': 279, 'talk': 'Empress Zhen.', 'context': ' The late Empress, the consort who had suffered death, was styled “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'What plan have you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'The young emperor has no confidence in Sima Yi although Sima Yi is a high minister of state. Now send someone secretly to Luoyang and Yejun to disseminate reports that Sima Yi is about to rebel. Further, prepare a proclamation in his name and post it up so as to cause Cao Rui to mistrust him and put him to death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 360, 'talk': 'That was the reason for his having requested the governorship of Xizhou and Xiliang. Now Emperor Cao, the Founder of Great Wei, frequently said to me that Sima Yi was ambitious and hungry, and should not be entrusted with military authority lest he harm the state. This is the first beginning of rebellion, and the author should be put to death.', 'context': 'Hua Xin said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Sima Yi is a master of strategy and skilled in tactics. Moreover, he is ambitious and will cause mischief if he be allowed to live.', 'context': 'Wang Lang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Supposing Sima Yi really contemplates a revolt; what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 163, 'talk': "Sima Yi's defection is certain since such a large army can only mean that he is prepared to resist.", 'context': 'As Sima Yi approached, the courtiers told the Emperor, saying, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'Friend, His late Majesty entrusted you with the heavy responsibility of caring for his son; why are you in revolt?', 'context': 'Cao Xiu advanced and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'This is a vile plot on the part of our rivals, Shu and Wu, to cause dissension,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'It is a design to make the Emperor work evil upon his ministers that thereby another may profit. I must see the Son of Heaven and explain.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 381, 'talk': 'His late Majesty gave me charge of his son; could I betray him? This is a wile of the enemy. I crave permission to lead an army, first to destroy Shu and then to attack Wu, whereby to show my gratitude to the late Emperor and Your Majesty and manifest my own true heart.', 'context': "Ordering his army to retire, Sima Yi went forward alone to the Emperor's chariot, bowed low and said, weeping “"},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'In any case withdraw his military powers and let him go into retirement.', 'context': 'However, Cao Rui did not feel quite convinced, and Hua Xin said, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'I have studied the aspect of the stars; the northern quarter is brilliant and strong. The scheme will not speed.', 'context': 'Forth from the ranks of courtiers stood Minister Qiao Zhou and said, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'You, O Minister, understand the mysteries of the skies; why do you oppose the stars?', 'context': 'Then turning toward the Prime Minister, he continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'Because the stars are in infinite changes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'One may rely on the stars too much. Moreover, I have already sent the army into Hanzhong, where I shall act as soon as I have studied what is afoot.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'tiger.', 'context': 'All being ready, a day was chosen for the start: the fifth year, the third month, on the day of “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Old I may be,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 321, 'talk': 'I have lost my friend Ma Chao by illness since I returned from the Southern Expedition, and I feel as I had lost an arm. Now, General, you must own that the years are mounting up. Any slight lapse would not only shake the life−long reputation of yourself, but might have a bad effect on the whole army.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 287, 'talk': 'I have never quailed in the presence of the enemy from the day I first joined the First Ruler; I have ever pressed to the front. It is a happy ending for a person of valor to die on the frontier. Think you that I should resent it? Let me lead the van, I pray.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun replied bitterly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I will go to help the veteran leader,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'I am not worth much, but I will help lead the attack on the enemy.', 'context': " cried Deng Zhi, without a moment's hesitation. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'A report from the border stations says that Zhuge Liang has marched three hundred thousand troops into Hanzhong. Zhao Yun and Deng Zhi are leading the advanced guard.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Who can lead an army to repel the advance?', 'context': 'The report alarmed the Emperor, and he asked, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 277, 'talk': 'The appointment is wrong. Xiahou Mao, the Son−in−Law, has never seen a battle and is unsuitable for this post, especially when his opponent is the clever and crafty Zhuge Liang, a man thoroughly versed in strategy.', 'context': 'The Minister Wang Lang spoke against the appointment, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'I suppose you have arranged with Zhuge Liang to be his ally,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 295, 'talk': "Ever since I was a boy, I have studied strategy, and I am well acquainted with army matters. Why do you despise my youth? Unless I capture this Zhuge Liang, I pledge myself never again to see the Emperor's face.", 'context': ' sneered Xiahou Mao. “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'The Ruler of Wei, Cao Rui, has put in motion all western forces under Xiahou Mao.', 'context': 'After this ceremony, when the Commander−in−Chief was discussing his plans, the spies came in to report: “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 532, 'talk': 'Xiahou Mao is a child of a wealthy family, soft and stupid. Give me five thousand troops, and I will go out by Baozhong, follow the line of the Qinling Mountains east to the Ziwu Valley and then turn north. In ten days I can be at Changan. Hearing of my intent, Xiahou Mao will hasten to vacate the city. Then he must flee by way of Royal Gate. I will come in by the east, and you, Sir, can advance by the Xie Valley. In this way and all west of Xianyang will be ours in just one move.', 'context': 'Then Wei Yan went in to offer a plan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I do not think the plan quite perfect,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 328, 'talk': 'You are gambling by thinking there is no northerner worth considering guarding Changan. If anyone suggests sending a force across to block the exit of the mountains, I am afraid we should lose five thousand troops, to say nothing of the check to our elan. The plan will not do.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'If you, O Minister, march by the high road, they will bring against you the whole host within the passes and will thus hold you indefinitely; you will never get to the Middle Land.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'But I shall go along the level road on the right of Longyou. I cannot fail if I keep to the fixed rules of war.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'Mountain Splitter.', 'context': 'De, a man of great valor, whose weapon was a mighty battle−ax called “'},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'Rebels and raiders! How dare you invade our territory?', 'context': 'When the battle line was in order, the father, with his four sons, rode to the front and began to revile their enemy, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 855, 'iend': 868, 'talk': 'Sun and Moon.', 'context': " Zhao Yun quickly lost his temper, rode forward and challenged. The eldest son, Han Ying, accepted and galloped out; but he was slain in the third bout. Immediately his brother Han Yao went out, whirling his sword. But now Zhao Yun's blood was up, and the old dash and vigor came upon him so that the young man had no chance to win the battle. Then the third son, Han Qiong, took his great halberd and dashed out to his brother's aid. Zhao Yun had now two opponents; nevertheless he held his own, nor blenched nor failed a stroke. Seeing that his two brothers were nearing defeat, the fourth son Han Qi went to join in the fray with his pair of swords that he had named “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'For a man of seventy years, you are unique and wonderful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'You are as much the hero as you ever were. It is almost an incomparable feat to have slain four generals in one day.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Yet the Prime Minister thought me too old and did not wish to employ me. I had to give him a proof.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'Is it not mine to avenge my four sons?', 'context': 'standard, he saw Zhao Yun galloping to and fro. He was going out to give battle, when Han De checked him. “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'I have heard Zhao Yun long ago, but have never met face−to−face. Now though that warrior is old, he still has incredible prowess. The story of Dangyang where he alone fought against a whole host and came out victor is really not fabricated. But what to be done against such a champion?', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 412, 'talk': 'My opinion is that this Zhao Yun, though brave in the field, is lacking in the council chamber. Really he is not greatly to be feared. Give battle again soon, but first prepare a two−pronged ambush. You can retreat and so draw him into it. Then go up on the hill top and direct the attack from that point of vantage so that he may be hemmed in on all sides and be captured.', 'context': 'Then Cheng Wu, son of Cheng Yu, said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'The army of Wei were beaten only yesterday. This renewed attempt must mean that they are trying some trick. You should be cautious, General.', 'context': 'Deng Zhi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 134, 'talk': "I do not think this youth, with the smell of mother's milk still on his lips, worth talking about. We shall surely capture him today.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 257, 'iend': 299, 'talk': "Zhao Yun! Why don't dismount and be bound?", 'context': 'struggle when the moon should be up. But just as he had taken off his armor the moon rose and, with it, his enemies began to attack with fire as well, and the thunder of the drums was accompanied by showers of stones and arrows. The oncoming host shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'I refused the repose of age,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'and now my end will come to me here!', 'context': ' sighed he, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 256, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister feared some misfortune had befallen you, so he sent me to your help; I have five thousand troops here. We heard that you were surrounded. On the way I met Xue Ze and slew him.', 'context': "Soon Zhang Bao reached the veteran general's side and cried, “"},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister sent me with five thousand troops to your aid. On the way I encountered Dong Xi and slain him. Here is his head; and the Prime Minister is coming up too.', 'context': 'This was Guan Xing, and he cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'But why not press on to capture Xiahou Mao since you have had such wonderful success?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'They are as my own children,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister has stationed the rear army in Mianyang, the left army in Yangping Pass, the right army in Shicheng. He himself is leading the central army toward Nanan.', 'context': 'After vain efforts for ten days, they heard the news: “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'The moat is deep, the walls are steep; wherefore the city is well defended and difficult to take. My present plan omits this place. If you persist in the attack and the Wei armies march to try for Hanzhong, our army will be in danger.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Consider what the capture of Xiahou Mao would mean,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'He is an Imperial Son−in−Law, and worth more than slaying a hundred ordinary leaders. We have begun the siege, and I do not like to raise it.', 'context': ' said Deng Zhi. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'I have other plans. West of this lies Tianshui and north Anding; does any one know the governors of these two places?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'Ma Zun is the Governor of Tianshui, Cui Liang that of Anding,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 521, 'talk': "I am one of Xiahou Mao's trusted soldiers and named Pei Xu. I was sent to beg for help from Tianshui and Anding. The city of Nanan is hard pressed; every day we have raised fires to call the attention of your cities to our plight, but our signals have all failed. No one has come. I was ordered to fight my way through the besiegers and come to tell you. You are to give assistance immediately, and our General will open the gates to help you.", 'context': 'Cui Liang had him brought into the city, and, when questioned, the man said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Have you a letter from the General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'Governor Ma Zun of Tianshui with his troops have already started for Nanan. The troops of Anding should march at once to their aid.', 'context': 'Two days later a mounted messenger came to say: “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'If you do not go, and Nanan is taken, we shall he blamed for giving up the Imperial Son−in−Law. He must be rescued.', 'context': 'Cui Liang took the advice of his officers. Most of them said, “'},
{'istart': 297, 'iend': 343, 'talk': 'I have taken the city; you would better yield!', 'context': 'At this news the soldiers scattered in all directions. Cui Liang had a hundred men left with whom he tried to cut his way out that he might return to his own city. He got through. But when he came to his own city, a flight of arrows greeted him from the wall, and Wei Yan shouted to him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'Is the Govenor of Nanan a friend of yours?', 'context': 'After a time Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'He is one Yang Ling, a cousin of Yang Fu. Being neighboring counties, we are very good friends.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'After the kindness we have received from Wei, we cannot be traitors,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'But we will meet ruse with ruse.', 'context': ' said Yang Ling. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'What ruse do you propose?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Let us pretend to offer the city, and let the army of Shu in. Once they are in, we can massacre them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'That is simple enough,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 335, 'talk': "Your hundred troops are here. We can mix with them some of my generals dressed as your officers and so let them get into the city. They can hide in Xiahou Mao's dwelling and arrange with Yang Ling to open the gates in the night. And my grand army will come in to make the capture for you.", 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'If I do not take the Shu generals, they will arouse suspicion. I would rather take them and will kill them as soon as they get within the walls. Then, I will give the signal and beguile Zhuge Liang to enter, and so dispose of him.', 'context': 'Cui Liang thought within himself, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 302, 'talk': "I will send my trusty Guan Xing and Zhang Bao with you. You will pass them off as the rescuers just to set Xiahou Mao's mind at rest. But when you raise a fire, I shall take that as my signal and come in.", 'context': "So Cui Liang consented to Zhuge Liang's proposal, and Zhuge Liang gave him instructions, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'We are rescuers from Anding.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 304, 'talk': 'Then Zhuge Liang is going to be our victim. Put a company of ax and bill men in the palace, and as soon as these two generals get inside, shut the gates and fall on. Then give the signal. As soon as Zhuge Liang gets inside the gate, seize him.', 'context': 'Yang Ling went to show this letter to Xiahou Mao, who said, “'},
{'istart': 378, 'iend': 429, 'talk': 'Since you are Anding troops, you may be allowed in.', 'context': ' All arrangements being made, Yang Ling went back to the wall and said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Scoundrel! Did you think your vile plot would be hidden from the eyes of our Prime Minister?', 'context': 'Zhang Bao cried, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'O Minister, how did you know the treachery of Cui Liang?', 'context': 'Then Deng Zhi asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 567, 'talk': 'I knew the man was unwilling in his heart to yield, so I sent him into the city that he might have a chance to weave a counter plot with Xiahou Mao. I saw by his manner he was treacherous, and so I sent my two trusty generals with him to give him a feeling of security. Had he been true to me, he would have opposed this; but he accepted it gaily and went with them lest I should suspect him. He thought they could slay my two leaders and entice me in. But my two leaders already had orders what to do. Everything turned out as I thought, and as they did not expect.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'I sent one of my trusty people to pretend he was a certain Pei Xu of Wei and so deceive this Cui Liang. I also sent another to Tianshui to do the same, but nothing has happened yet; I do not know the reason. We will take this opportunity to capture that place.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 239, 'talk': "If anything sinister happens to the Imperial Son−in−Law, 'Golden Branch' and 'Jade Leaf' as he is, we shall be held guilty of having made no attempt to save him. Wherefore, O Governor, you must march all the forces you have to his rescue,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 96, 'talk': "O Governor, you are the sport of one of Zhuge Liang's wiles.", 'context': 'Then an outsider came in and said, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 403, 'talk': 'I hear Zhuge Liang is attacking Xiahou Mao, who is now in Nanan most closely besieged. How then can this messenger have got out? Pei Xu is an unknown officer whom no one has heard of, and the other messenger from Anding bears no dispatch. The fact is the men are imposters sent to beguile you into leaving your city undefended so that it may be the more easily captured.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei said to the Governor, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Were it not for you, I would fall into a ruse.', 'context': 'The Governor began to understand. He said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'But do not be anxious; I have a scheme by which we can capture Zhuge Liang and relieve Nanan.', 'context': 'Then Jiang Wei said, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 535, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang will lay an ambush behind the city, induce our soldiers to go out and then take advantage of its undefended state to capture it. Now give me three thousand good soldiers, and I will place them in ambush at a certain critical place. Lead your troops out, but go slowly and not further than ten miles, and then turn to retire. However, look out for a signal, and if you see one, attack, for the attack will be double. If Zhuge Liang is there himself, we shall capture him.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei propounded his scheme of defense, saying, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'I am Zhao Yun of Changshan; you have fallen into our trap, but if you will surrender quickly, you will save many lives.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun and his five thousand troops then quickly marched to the city wall and called out, “'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'On the contrary, you have fallen into our trap; only you do not know it yet.', 'context': 'But instead of being alarmed, Liang Xu looked down and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Look at me, Jiang Wei of Tianshui!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'No one knows there is such an able man in Tianshui.', 'context': 'Zhao Yun made at him, but after a few bouts he found Jiang Wei was getting very eager. He was surprised, and wondered, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who is this,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'who has thus seen into the dark depths of my secret plan?', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I want to take Tianshui now; I did not expect to find such a man as this.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 486, 'talk': "Zhao Yun's defeat will bring up Zhuge Liang with the main body. He will conclude that we shall be in the city, wherefore you would better divide your force into four. I, with one party, will go into hiding on the east so that I may cut off our enemies if they come that way. You, O Governor, and Liang Qian and Yin Shang will lie in ambush on the other sides of the city. Let Liang Xu and the common people go up on the wall to make the defense.", 'context': 'Jiang Wei went back to Ma Zun and said, “'},
{'istart': 133, 'iend': 340, 'talk': 'Attacking a city must be proceeded as soon as the army reaches it; and at the rolling of drums, incite and urge the soldiers to advance with a rush. The keenness of the soldiers will be spoiled by any delay.', 'context': 'Due to Jiang Wei, Zhuge Liang himself led the main army to Tianshui. When they reached the city, Zhuge Liang gave a general orders: “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 105, 'talk': "These are Jiang Wei's troops.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang bade Guan Xing find out what this meant, and Guan Xing report: “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'An army owes more to its leading than to its numbers. This Jiang Wei is a true genius.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang remarked, “'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'Where is the mother of this Jiang Wei?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang led the army back to camp, and then he thought for a long time. Suddenly he called up one of the Anding men and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'She lives in Jicheng,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'March off with a body of troops, giving out that you are going to take Jicheng. If Jiang Wei comes up, let him enter the city.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang called Wei Yan and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'What is the most important place in connection with this place?', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang asked, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'The storehouse of Tianshui is at Shanggui; if that is taken, the supplies are cut off.', 'context': 'The man from Anding replied, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 262, 'talk': 'My mother is in Jicheng, and I am worried about the attacking force. Let me go to its defense, that I may keep the city and do my duty by my mother at the same time.', 'context': 'When Jiang Wei heard that one army was to attack his own place, he pleaded with Ma Zun, saying, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Are you afraid of death?', 'context': 'said suddenly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'I am willing to induce him to yield to you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'We are Jicheng people,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei has surrendered the city and deserted to Zhuge Liang. The troops of Shu are looting and burning, and we have escaped. We are going to Shanggui.', 'context': ' said they. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Do you know who is holding Tianshui?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Governor Ma Zun is in there,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'I did not think Jiang Wei would have gone over to Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'It seems he thought by this to save you, Sir Commander−in−Chief,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Where is the pretense when it is a fact that he has surrendered?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': "Why did you surrender to Shu after enjoying so much of Wei's bounty?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'This fellow has came to beguile me into opening the gate,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'You traitor,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Dare you come to try to cajole me out of my city? I know you have surrendered to Shu.', 'context': ' cried Liang Qian. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Friend Jiang Wei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'is it not time to yield?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 341, 'talk': 'Ever since I left my humble cottage, I have been seeking some worthy person to whom I might impart the knowledge that my life has been spent in acquiring. I have found no one till this moment, and now my desire is attained. You are the one.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang at once got out of the chariot and bade him welcome, taking him by the hand and saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'The two civil officers in charge of the city, Yin Shang and Liang Xu, are excellent friends of mine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 113, 'iend': 246, 'talk': 'and I will write a letter to each, shoot it over the wall tied to an arrow, and ask them to help by raising a revolt within the city.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Put both the men to death,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'My brother, Liang Qian, holds that city, and I will call upon him to yield it.', 'context': 'Liang Xu said, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'O Minister, why do you not pursue and capture Xiahou Mao?', 'context': 'Next the army prepared to advance. His officers asked, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'I let him go as I would release a duck; in my friend Jiang Wei I recognized a phoenix.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'Xiahou Mao, the Imperial Son−in−Law, has lost the three cities and fled to the Qiangs. The enemy has reached Qishan, and their advanced columns are on the west bank of River Wei. I pray that an army be sent to repulse them.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'I observed that whenever General Cao Zhen was sent by the late Emperor on any expedition he succeeded; why not send him to drive off these soldiers of Shu?', 'context': 'Minister Wang Lang stepped forward and said, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'The late Emperor confided me to your guardianship; you cannot sit by while the enemy ravages the country.', 'context': 'Cao Rui approved of the suggestion, whereupon he called up Cao Zhen and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Your Majesty, my talents are but poor and unequal to the task you propose.', 'context': 'Cao Zhen replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'You are a trusted minister of state, and you may not really refuse this task. Old and worn as I am, I will use the little strength left me to accompany you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'After the bounties I have received I cannot refuse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'But I must ask for an assistant.', 'context': ' replied Cao Zhen. “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'You have only to name him, O noble One,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 504, 'iend': 571, 'talk': 'We request the leader of the opposing army to come out to a parley.', 'context': 'Next day, when the armies were drawn up facing each other in front of the Qishan Mountains, the soldiers of Shu saw that their enemies were fine, bold warriors, very different from those that Xiahou Mao had brought against them. Then after three rolls of the drums, Minister Wang Lang mounted his horse and rode out, preceded by the Commander−in−Chief and followed by Guo Huai. The two leaders of the van remained in charge of the army. Then an orderly rode to the front and called out in a loud voice, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'He intends to deliver an oration,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'I must answer as best I may.', 'context': ' thought Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister of the Hans is willing to speak with Minister Wang Lang.', 'context': 'His carriage was then pushed to the front beyond the line of battle, and he directed one of his officers to reply, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'I am happy to meet you, noble Sir; your reputation has been long known to me. Since you recognize the decrees of Heaven and are acquainted with the conditions of the world, why do you, without any excuse, lead out such an army?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'How mean you no excuse? I hold an edict to destroy rebels.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 403, 'iend': 774, 'talk': 'Now the armies of Wei are countless legions, and their able leaders are beyond number. Can the glowworm in the parched stubble rival the glorious moon in the sky? If you will turn down your weapons and throw aside your armors and dutifully yield, you shall not lose your rank. The state will have tranquillity and the people rejoice. Is not that a desirable consummation?', 'context': '“Noble Sir, you are a man of natural talent and acquired attainments, worthy, you say yourself, to be compared with Guan Zhong and Yue Yi. Why then place yourself in opposition to the decree of Heaven and turn away from the desire of humankind to do this thing? You cannot be ignorant of the wise old saying that he who accords with the Heavens shall flourish, while he who opposes shall be destroyed. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 551, 'talk': 'Since you are such a false and specious minister, you have but to hide your body and cover your head, concern yourself about your belly and your back. Do not come out before the armies to rave about the decrees of Heaven. You fool and rebel! Mark you, today is your last day; this day even you descend to the Nine Golden Springs. How will you stand before the two scores and four emperors of Latter Han that you will meet there? Retire, you rebel! Go tell your rebellious companions to come and fight one battle with me that shall decide the victory.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I thought of such a scheme myself,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'It exactly suits my plans.', 'context': ' said Cao Zhen. “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 128, 'talk': 'You two are to make a night attack.', 'context': 'When Zhuge Liang reached his tent, he called to him Zhao Yun and Wei Yan, and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Cao Zhen is a man of experience and will be on the lookout,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 330, 'talk': 'You are to take each ten thousand troops and hide in the high road to the mountain. When the troops of Wei come, let them pass and then march along the road they came by to their camp that they have just left.', 'context': 'These two having gone away to carry out their portions of the plan, Zhuge Liang next called up Guan Xing and Zhang Bao: “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Commander Guo Huai is an excellent strategist and of wonderful prevision.', 'context': 'Cao Zun thought to himself, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Whither go ye, O rebel leaders?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'Stop, for here is death!', 'context': ' cried Zhao Yun. “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'The enemy are too strong for us. Have you any plan to drive them away?', 'context': 'When they discussed the fight, Cao Zhen said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'Our defeat is one of the ordinary events of war. Let us not be cast down. I have a plan to suggest that will disorder them so that one body cannot help the other, and they will all be compelled to flee.', 'context': 'Replied Guo Huai, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 543, 'talk': 'The Qiang tribes have paid tribute regularly since the days of the Founder of Wei. Emperor Pi regarded them with favor. Now let us hold such points of vantage as we may, while we send secret emissaries to engage their help in exchange for kindly treatment. We may get the Qiangs to attack Shu and engage their attention, while we gather a large army to smite them at another place. Thus attacking, how can we help gaining a great victory?', 'context': 'The scheme by which Guo Huai proposed to overcome the army of Shu he laid before his colleague, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'We have had regular intercourse with the Wei nation. Now that Cao Zhen asks our aid and promises an alliance, we ought to accede to his request.', 'context': 'Ya Dan said, “'},
{'istart': 534, 'iend': 548, 'talk': 'iron chariots.', 'context': 'Cheli Ji agreed that it was so, and he ordered his two chief ministers to raise an army of two hundred fifty thousand of trained soldiers, archers and crossbowmen, spearmen and swordsmen, warriors who flung maces and hurled hammers. Beside these various weapons, the tribesmen used chariots covered with iron plates nailed on. They prepared much grain and fodder and many spare weapons, all of which they loaded upon these iron−clad chariots. The chariots were drawn by camels or teams of horses. The carts or chariots were known as “'},
{'istart': 179, 'iend': 212, 'talk': 'Who will go to attack the Qiangs?', 'context': 'The two leaders took leave of their King and went straightway to Xiping Pass. The commander in charge of the Pass, Han Zhen, at once sent intelligence to Zhuge Liang, who asked, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'We will see tomorrow what they will do when we make our array, and discuss our plans when we know more.', 'context': 'Ma Dai said, “'},
{'istart': 147, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Youthful general, flee not; I am Yue Ji!', 'context': 'As it grew dark a Qiang leader with a black flag approached, his warriors like a swarm of wasps about him. Presently the leader cried out to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I do not know how to overcome these men,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Let me protect the camp while you go back and ask the Prime Minister what we should do.', 'context': ' said Ma Dai. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'It is not difficult,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'My friend, do you know how to overcome them?', 'context': 'They having gone, he turned to Jiang Wei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'The Qiangs only depend upon force or courage; they cannot understand this fine strategy.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 204, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'You know,', 'context': ' was the reply. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'It is a ruse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 114, 'talk': "Zhuge Liang's base trick is the pretense of a pretense, and you would better attack.", 'context': ' said Ya Dan. “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'There may be an ambush, but I think we need not be afraid of these soldiers.', 'context': 'Then said Ya Dan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Who is it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 394, 'talk': 'My master, the Emperor of the Great Hans, sent me to destroy those who are in revolt; why are you helping them? But I will release you, and you will return to your master and say that we are neighbors and we will swear an oath of everlasting friendship, and tell him to listen no more to the words of those rebels.', 'context': 'Ya Dan was grateful for this kindness, and felt more so when Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'That is because the Qiangs have attacked,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Stop! You rebels!', 'context': 'Yan, who cried, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 243, 'talk': 'It will be necessary for Your Majesty to go in person. You should call together all the nobles, and each will have to exert himself. Unless this is done, Capital Changan will be lost and the whole country be in danger.', 'context': 'Thereupon Hua Xin said, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 450, 'talk': "The knowledge of every leader must exceed that of those led; then only will he be able to control them. Sun Zi the Strategist sums it up very briefly: 'Know the enemy, know thyself; and every battle is a victory.' I know Cao Zhen has had great experience in the field, but he is no match for Zhuge Liang. Still there is such a match, and I will pledge my whole family that he will succeed. But Your Majesty may be unwilling to listen to me.", 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 479, 'iend': 625, 'talk': 'You are a minister of high rank and old. If you know any wise person able to repel these soldiers of Shu, call him without delay and ease my mind.', 'context': ' The Ruler of Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 303, 'talk': "When Zhuge Liang decided to invade us, he was afraid of the one man I will name. Wherefore he spread calumnies concerning him, raising suspicion in Your Majesty's mind that you might dismiss him. That done, Zhuge Liang invaded. Now employ this man again, and the enemy will retire.", 'context': 'Then said Zhong Yao, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'I mean the Regent Marshal Sima Yi.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I have long regretted my action,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Where now is friend Sima Yi?', 'context': ' said Cao Rui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'He is at the city of Wancheng, idle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'What is your joyful news?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 547, 'talk': 'He used to talk about being originally one of the Shu leaders, and he was forced to do so−and−so. Lately he has sent several confidants with letters to my father asking that he would state his case to you as to the happenings when the five armies came upon Shu. Now he is at Xincheng, and, hearing you are attacking Wei, he proposes to lead the army of the three counties about Xincheng, Jincheng, and Shangyong to attack Luoyang while you attack Changan, whereby both capitals will be taken. I have brought with me his messenger and his letters.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'Cao Rui should not be your worry. If he goes to Changan, we will march there and capture him on the road, and there will be an end of him.', 'context': 'He told Ma Su, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Do you think I fear him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 301, 'talk': "But the recall of Sima Yi is another matter; that troubles me. And Meng Da's proposal will avail nothing if he comes across this man. Meng Da is no match for him. He will he captured, and, if he should be, the Middle Land will be hard to conquer.", 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang bitterly. “'},
{'istart': 304, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'Why not put Meng Da on his guard then?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'They say Zhuge Liang leaves nothing to chance,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'This proves it.', 'context': ' said Meng Da, smiling as he read. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Meng Da is a dead man;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'a victim of Sima Yi.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Why do you say that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'You would not understand,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I think you are grieving because the Ruler of Wei does not use you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'But they will send for you presently,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 474, 'talk': "This is the Emperor's great good fortune, high as heaven itself. Zhuge Liang's army is at Qishan already, and all people's courage is at the brink of breakdown. The Emperor must go to Changan, and if he does not use me soon, Meng Da will carry out his plan; his plot will succeed and both capitals will be lost. Meng Da is surely in league with Zhuge Liang, and if I can seize this Meng Da before he makes any move, that will damp Zhuge Liang's spirits and he will retreat.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'It is necessary to memorialize the Throne.', 'context': 'His elder son Sima Shi remarked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'that would take a month, and delay would mean failure.', 'context': ' replied his father, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'The Emperor has arrived at Changan to lead an expedition against Shu. Whither is the Commander−in−Chief going?', 'context': 'Xu Huang got an interview with Sima Yi, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Meng Da is on the verge of rebellion, and I am going to seize him.', 'context': 'Sima Yi, in a low voice, said to him, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'Let me go as your van−leader,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 116, 'iend': 292, 'talk': 'The Commander−in−Chief has received the edict of the Emperor to call in all the forces in this area, and he has sent me to direct you to hold your troops in readiness to march.', 'context': 'Just then Liang Ji came, and when he had been ceremoniously received, he produced the order from Sima Yi and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'On what day does the Commander−in−Chief start?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'He is just about starting now, and is on the way to Changan', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Let the traitor Meng Da yield quickly!', 'context': 'Then Xu Huang called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'This is what Zhuge Liang foresaw!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Rebel, stay!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'We have already yielded the city!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Once I doubted you;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'but then I did not understand, and I listened to mischief−makers. I regret it. You have preserved both capitals by the punishment of this traitor.', 'context': ' said Cao Rui, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 254, 'talk': "Shen Yi gave the information of the intended revolt and thought to memorialize Your Majesty. But there would have been a long delay, and so I did not await orders, but set forth at once. Delay would have played into Zhuge Liang's hands.", 'context': 'Sima Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'You are wiser than both the great strategists of old—Wu Qi and Sun Zi.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Just the man I wished to send,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 82, 'iend': 796, 'talk': 'A characteristic of Zhuge Liang is his most diligent carefulness; he is never hasty. If I were in his place, I should advance through the Ziwu Valley to capture Changan and so save much time. It is not that he is unskillful, but he fears lest that plan might miscarry, and he will not sport with risk. Therefore he will certainly come through the Xie Valley, taking Meicheng on the way. That place captured, he will divide his force into two, one part to take Chi Valley. I have sent Cao Zhen orders to guard Meicheng strictly and on no account to let its garrison go out to battle. The generals Sun Li and Xin Pi are to command the Chi Valley entrance, and should the enemy come, they are to make a sudden attack.', 'context': 'When encamped, Sima Yi summoned Zhang He to his tent and admonished him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'By what road will you advance?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 767, 'talk': "I know a road west of Qinling Mountains called Jieting, on which stands the city Liliu. These two places are the throat of Hanzhong. Zhuge Liang will take advantage of the unpreparedness of Cao Zhen and will certainly come in by this way. You and I will go to Jieting, whence it is a short distance to Yangping Pass. When Zhuge Liang hears that the road through Jieting is blocked and his supplies cut off, he will know that Xizhou is impossible to keep, and will retire without losing a moment into Hanzhong. I shall smite him on the march, and I ought to gain a complete victory. If he should not retire, then I shall block all the smaller roads and so stop his supplies. A month's starvation will kill off the soldiers of Shu, and Zhuge Liang will be my prisoner.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'O Commander, your calculation exceeds human!', 'context': 'Zhang He took in the scheme and expressed his admiration, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 395, 'talk': 'However, it is not to be forgotten that Zhuge Liang is quite different from Meng Da; and you, as leader of the van, will have to advance with the utmost care. You must impress upon your generals the importance of reconnoitering a long way ahead and only advancing when they are sure there is no ambush. The least remissness will make you the victim of some ruse of the enemy.', 'context': 'Sima Yi continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': "Meng Da's destruction was certain,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'Such a scheme could not remain secret. Now Sima Yi will try for Jieting and block the one road essential to us.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'I have studied the books of war since I was a boy, and I may say I know a little of the art of war,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 118, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'Why alone is Jieting so difficult to hold?', 'context': ' Ma Su replied. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Because Sima Yi is an exceptional man, and also he has a famous second in Zhang He as leader of the van. I fear you may not be a match for him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'To say nothing of these two, I would not mind if Cao Rui himself came against me. If I fail, then I beg you to behead my whole family.', 'context': 'Ma Su replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'There is no jesting in war,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I will give a written pledge.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 197, 'iend': 436, 'talk': 'Northeast of Jieting is a city named Liliu, and near it an unfrequented hill path. There you are to camp and make a stockade. I will give you ten thousand troops for this task; and if Jieting should be threatened, you may go to the rescue.', 'context': 'After Ma Su and Wang Ping had gone and Zhuge Liang had reflected for a long time, it occurred to him that there might be some slip between his two leaders, so he called Gao Xiang to him and said, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'As leader of the van, I should go first against the enemy; why am I sent to a place where there is nothing to do?', 'context': 'But Wei Yan thought this rather a slight, and said, “'},
{'istart': 169, 'iend': 503, 'talk': 'The leadership of the van is really a second−rate task. Now I am sending you to support Jieting and take post on the most dangerous road to Yangping Pass. You are the chief keeper of the throat of Hanzhong. It is a very responsible post and not at all an idle one. Do not so regard it and spoil my whole plan. Be particularly careful.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'Why was the Prime Minister so extremely anxious? How would the Wei armies dare to come to such a hilly place as this?', 'context': 'When Ma Su and Wang Ping had reached Jieting and saw what manner of place it was, Ma Su smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Though they might not dare to come, we should set our camp at this meeting of many roads.', 'context': 'Wang Ping replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'You are wrong, Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'You look at the thing like a child,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'The rules of war say that when one looks down from a superior position, one easily overcomes the enemy. If they come, I will see to it that not a breastplate ever goes back again.', 'context': ' said Ma Su, laughing. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 262, 'talk': 'I have followed our Commander−in−Chief in many a campaign, and always he has carefully thought out his orders. Now I have studied this hill carefully, and it is a critical point. If we camp thereon and the enemy cut off our water supply, we shall have a mutiny.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'No such thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'If you are determined to camp on the hill, then give me part of the force to camp there on the west so that I can support you in case the enemy come.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'Since you will not obey me, I will give you five thousand troops and you can go and make your own camp; but when I report my success to the Prime Minister, you shall have no share of the merit.', 'context': 'Wang Ping was still bent on going his own way, and so Ma Su said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is rather more than human,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'He is too much for me.', 'context': ' said his father regretfully when Sima Zhao gave in his report. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Why are you despondent, Father? I think Jieting is not so difficult to take.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'How dare you utter such bold words?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Because I have seen. There is no camp on the road, but the enemy are camped on the hill.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'If they are on the hill, then Heaven means a victory for me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'If Sima Yi has any luck, he will not try to surround this hill,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'In case the enemy come, you are to look to the summit for a signal with a red flag, when you shall rush down on all sides.', 'context': 'Ma Su issued an order to his generals: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'A man of false reputation and very ordinary ability,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'If Zhuge Liang uses such as Ma Su, he will fail.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'This is life for me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 565, 'iend': 587, 'talk': 'Wei Commander Guo Huai', 'context': 'Suddenly a bomb exploded, and a brilliant flash lit up the sky; drums rolled as though the earth was rending, and the enemy appeared. In a trice the armies of Shu found themselves hemmed in. Both Wei Yan and Gao Xiang pushed here and shoved there, but could find no way out. Then most opportunely from behind a hill rolled out a thunder of drums, and there was Wang Ping coming to their rescue. Then the three forced their way to Liliu. But just as they drew near to the rampart, another body of soldiers came up, which, from the writing on their flags, they read “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'I was disappointed at Jieting, but we have taken this place, and that is merit of high order.', 'context': 'Guo Huai, pleased with his success, gathered in his army after the victory and said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 194, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'Sima Yi, General Who Pacifies the West', 'context': 'Thereupon he proceeded to the city gates. Just as he arrived, a bomb exploded on the wall, and, looking up, he saw the rampart bedecked with flags. On the largest banner he read the characters “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'How late you are, friend Guo Huai!', 'context': 'He looked down and smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'He is too much for me,', 'context': 'Guo Huai was amazed. “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 741, 'talk': 'Cao Zhen and Guo Huai thought we should win too great merit, so they tried to get ahead of us here. We are not the only ones who desire to achieve good service and acquire merit, but we had the good fortune to succeed. I thought Wei Yan, Ma Su, Wang Ping, and Gao Xiang would first try to occupy Yangping Pass; and if I went to take it, then Zhuge Liang would fall on our rear. It says in the books on war that one should crush a retreating enemy, not pursue broken rebels; so you may go along the by−roads and smite those withdrawing down the Chi Valley, while I oppose the Xie Valley army. If they flee, do not press them too much, but just hold them up on the road and capture the baggage train.', 'context': 'Sima Yi called to him Zhang He, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': "Ma Su's foolishness has destroyed the army!", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Why are you so disturbed, O Minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'I am none too clever I know, but let me go to replace Ma Su.', 'context': 'Here High Counselor Yang Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'The whole scheme has come to nought, and it is my fault.', 'context': 'This made Zhuge Liang very sad, and he sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 350, 'talk': 'Each of you takes three thousand of good soldiers and go along the road to Wugong Hills. If you fall in with the enemy, do not fight, but beat drums and raise a hubbub and make them hesitate and be doubtful, so that they may retire. Do not pursue, but when they retire, make for Yangping Pass.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang sent for Guan Xing and Zhang Bao, and said, “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'Sima Yi is advancing rapidly on Xicheng with an army of one hundred fifty thousand troops.', 'context': 'But messenger after messenger, more than ten of them, came to report: “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'All the banners are to be removed and concealed. If any officer in command of soldiers in the city moves or makes any noise, he will be instantly put to death.', 'context': 'Then he gave orders: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I am certain there are no soldiers behind this foolery,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'What do you retire for, Father?', 'context': ' said Sima Zhao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'We should simply have run away,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': "But if I had been in Sima Yi's place, I should not have turned away,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'If we do not retire, we shall yet somehow fall victims to this Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'Sima Yi turned to his sons, saying, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'The army of Wei will surely come to smite us while we are retreating. Wherefore let me first take up a position in their rear, and then you lead off your troops and part of mine, showing my ensigns. I will follow, keeping at the same distance behind you, and thus I shall be able to protect the retreat.', 'context': 'Then said Zhao Yun, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun is a warrior whom no one can withstand. You must keep a most careful guard lest you fall into some trap while they are retreating.', 'context': 'Now Guo Huai was leading his army through the Chi Valley. He called up his van−leader, Su Yong, and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'If you will help me, O Commander, we shall be able to capture this Zhao Yun.', 'context': 'Su Yong replied, smiling, “'},
{'istart': 127, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Do you recognize Zhao Yun?', 'context': 'But before he had gone far a great uproar arose about him, and a mighty warrior came bounding forth on a swift steed, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Whence came you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 61, 'talk': 'Is there another Zhao Yun here?', 'context': ' he cried. “'},
{'istart': 248, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun is here!', 'context': 'However, Guo Huai was not content and ordered him to return to the pursuit of the retreating army. This time Wan Zheng led a company of several hundred horsemen. Presently they came to a wood, and, as they entered, a loud shout arose in the rear, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Be off! I will not kill you. Go and tell Guo Huai to come quickly, if he is coming.', 'context': 'Then Zhao Yun pointed his spear at him and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is a cleverer man than I am,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'It is by your good service that Xizhou is again mine.', 'context': 'He saw the Ruler of Wei, who was pleased with his success and said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'But the army of Shu is in Hanzhong undestroyed; therefore, I pray for authority to go against them that you may recover the Western Land of Rivers also.', 'context': 'Sima Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Noble Sir, expound your excellent scheme,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 825, 'talk': 'When your great progenitor, Emperor Cao, first got Zhang Lu, he was at a critical stage in his career, but thenceforward all went well. He used to say the land of Nanzheng is really a natural hell. In the Xie Valley there are one hundred fifty miles of rocks and caves, so that it is an impossible country for an army. If Wei be denuded of soldiers in order to conquer Shu, then for sure we shall be invaded by Wu on the east. My advice is to divide the army among the various generals and appoint each a place of strategic value to hold, and let them train their forces. In a few years the Middle Land will be prosperous and wealthy, while the other two Shu and Wu, will have been reduced by mutual quarrels and will fall an easy prey. I hope Your Majesty will consider whether this is not a superior plan.', 'context': 'And Sun Zi said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'Minister Sun Zi says well.', 'context': '“What does the General think? said Cao Rui to Sima Yi. He replied, “'},
{'istart': 140, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister should not have come forth to welcome a defeated general.', 'context': 'As they drew near, Zhuge Liang went out of the city to welcome them. Thereupon Zhao Yun hastily dismounted and bowed to the earth, saying, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'Mine was the fault, mine were the ignorance and unwisdom that caused all this. But how is it that amid all the defeat and loss you have come through unscathed?', 'context': 'But Zhuge Liang lifted him up and took his hand and said, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'It was because friend Zhao Yun sent me ahead, while he guarded the rear and warded off every attack. One leader he slew, and this frightened the others. Thus nothing was lost or left by the way.', 'context': 'And Deng Zhi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'A really great general!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 113, 'talk': "When the First Ruler lived, he never tired of extolling Zhao Yun's virtues; the First Ruler was perfectly right,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'I ordered you and Ma Su to guard Jieting; why did you not remonstrate with him and prevent this great loss?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 759, 'talk': 'You have filled yourself with the study of the books on war ever since you were a boy; you know them thoroughly. I enjoined upon you that Jieting was most important, and you pledged yourself and all your family to do your best in the enterprise; yet you would not listen to Wang Ping, and thus you caused this misfortune. The army is defeated, generals have been slain and cities and territory lost, all through you. If I do not make you an example and vindicate the law, how shall I maintain a proper state of discipline? You have offended and you must pay the penalty. After your death the little ones of your family shall be my care, and I will see that they get a monthly allowance. Do not let their fate cause you anxiety.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang got angry, saying, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 325, 'talk': 'Pity me, O Minister, you have looked upon me as a son; I have looked up to you as a father. I know my fault is worthy of death, but I pray you remember how King Shun employed Yu, after executing his father. Though I die, I will harbor no resentment down in the depths of the Nine Golden Springs.', 'context': 'Ma Su wept bitterly, saying, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'We have been as brothers, and your children shall be as my own. It is useless to say more.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang brushed aside his tears and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'Formerly the King of Chu put Minister Chen Dechen to death, and his rival Duke Wen of Jin rejoiced. There is great confusion in the land, and yet you would slay a man of admitted ability. Can you not spare him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'Sun Zi maintains that the one way to obtain success is to make the law supreme. Now confusion and actual war are in every quarter; and if the law be not observed, how may rebels be made away with? He must die.', 'context': "Zhuge Liang's tears fell, but he said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Why do you weep for him now that he has met the just penalty for his fault?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Why does the Prime Minister speak thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'It is but the ordinary fortune of war.', 'context': ' said the Latter Ruler. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'It was a great joy to the people of Shu when you, O Minister, captured the four northwest counties,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'What sort of language is this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Success followed by failure is no success. It shames me indeed to hear such a compliment.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, annoyed. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'His Majesty will be very pleased to hear of the acquisition of Jiang Wei.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'But with an army of one hundred thousand bold veterans, you can attack Wei again.', 'context': 'Fei Yi tried again. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Shu cannot be attacked,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'In this present hot weather they will not come out, but, if we invade, they will only garrison and defend their strategic points, which we should find it hard to overcome.', 'context': ' was the reply. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'What shall we do if they invade us again?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 368, 'talk': 'I have prepared for that. Just now Zhuge Liang is imitating Han Xin when he secretly crossed the river into Chencang. I can recommend a man to guard the place by building a rampart there and rendering it absolutely secure. He is a nine−span man, round shouldered and powerful, a good archer and prudent strategist. He would be quite equal to dealing with an invasion.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'His name is Hao Zhao, and he is in command at Hexi.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'It seems very reasonable,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Wu could be quite destroyed. Let me go with an army to help Cao Xiu.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 253, 'talk': 'What this man of Wu says may be understood in two ways; do not trust it. Zhou Fang is a wise and crafty man and very unlikely to desert. In this is some ruse to decoy our soldiers into danger.', 'context': 'But from among the courtiers stepped out Jia Kui, who said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Such words also must be listened to,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'Yet such a chance must not be missed.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'You and he might both go to the help of Cao Xiu,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 464, 'talk': 'The Governor of Poyang, Zhou Fang, has sent up a secret memorial saying that Cao Xiu intends to invade. Zhou Fang has therefore set out a trap for Cao Xiu and has drawn up a document giving seven plausible circumstances, hoping thereby to cajole the Wei army into his power. The armies of Wei are on the move in three divisions, and I need your advice.', 'context': 'Now the Prince of Wu, Sun Quan, was at the East Pass in Wuchang, and there he assembled his officers and said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'There is only one man fit to cope with the present need; he is Lu Xun.', 'context': 'Gu Yong stood forth, saying, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'There are Zhu Huan, General Who Fortifies Prowess, and Quan Zong, General Who Calms the South. These two should be in command.', 'context': 'Sun Quan asked their names, and Lu Xun said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 698, 'talk': 'Cao Xiu is neither able nor bold; he holds office because he is of the blood. He has fallen into the trap laid by Zhou Fang and marched too far to be able to withdraw. If the Commander−in−Chief will smite, Cao Xiu must be defeated. Defeated, he must flee along two roads, one Jiashi on the left, the other Guichi on the right, both of which are precipitous and narrow. Let me and my colleague go to prepare an ambush in these roads. We will block them and so cut off their escape. If this Cao Xiu could be captured, and a hasty advance made, success would be easy and sure. We should get Shouchun, whence Xuchang and Luoyang can be seen. This is the one chance in the thousand.', 'context': 'Then said Zhu Huan, “'},
{'istart': 701, 'iend': 730, 'talk': 'I do not think the plan good,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 746, 'iend': 766, 'talk': 'I have a better one.', 'context': ' said Lu Xun. “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 381, 'talk': "I received your letter and the memorandum, which was most logical, and sent it to His Majesty. He has set in motion accordingly three armies. It will be a great merit for you, Sir, if the South Land can be added to His Majesty's dominions. People say you are insufficient in craft, but I do not believe what they say, for I think you will be true to me and not fail.", 'context': 'Cao Xiu said, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 311, 'talk': 'As to the seven things I mentioned, my regret is that I cannot show you all. You doubt me because some persons from Wu and Wei have been poisoning your mind against me. If you heed them, the only course for me is to die. Heaven only can make manifest my loyal heart.', 'context': 'Still leaning on the sword, Zhou Fang said, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'I did not mean it; the words were uttered in jest. Why do you act thus?', 'context': 'Again he made to slay himself. But Cao Xiu in trepidation threw his arms about him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 262, 'talk': 'I have come to warn you, Commander, to be cautious and wait till you and I can attack the enemy together. The whole army of Wu is encamped at Huancheng.', 'context': 'General Jia Kui came to Cao Xiu, and when asked whether there was any special reason for the visit, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'You mean you want to share in my victory,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'It is said Zhou Fang cut off his hair as a pledge of sincerity; that is only another bit of deceit. According to the Spring and Autumn Annals, Yao Li cut off his arm as a pledge of loyalty before he assassinated Qing Ji; mutilation is no guarantee. Do not trust Zhou Fang.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Why do you come to utter ill−omened words just as I am opening the campaign? You destroy the spirit of the army,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Before the march, killing our general is not favorable to the army. O General, spare him until after the expedition.', 'context': 'In his wrath he told the lictors to put Jia Kui to death. However, the officers interceded, saying, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'If Cao Xiu had attended to his words, then Wu would have lost. Heaven is good to me and is giving me the means of achieving great things.', 'context': 'When Zhou Fang heard that Jia Kui had been broken, he rejoiced in his heart, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 239, 'talk': 'Shiding, lying over against us, is a hilly country fit for preparing an ambush. It will be occupied as suitable to array our army and await the coming of Wei. Xu Sheng is to be leader of the van, and the army will move there.', 'context': 'Lu Xun said, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'What is the place lying ahead?', 'context': 'Now Cao Xiu told Zhou Fang to lead the way for his attack. While on march, Cao Xiu asked, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Shiding, a suitable place to camp in.', 'context': 'Zhou Fang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Zhou Fang said there were no soldiers; why these preparations?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I have been deceived and am in a trap,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'However, there is nothing to fear.', 'context': ' said Cao Xiu, now very repentant of his easy confidence. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Rebel leader, come and surrender!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Xu Sheng is too strong,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Then will we defeat him by a surprise,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'Tomorrow I will lead a thousand soldiers to provoke the troops of Wu into battle, then I will feign defeat and lead them to the hills in the north, when a bomb will explode and a three−pronged ambush will bring us victory.', 'context': 'under Xue Qiao was sent north. And Cao Xiu arranged, saying, “'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 253, 'talk': "Each of you is to lead thirty thousand troops and take a cross cut from Shiding to the enemy's camp. Give a fire signal on arrival, and then the main army will advance.", 'context': 'On the other side Lu Xun called his two generals, Zhu Huan and Quan Zong, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I took no notice of what you said, and so this evil came upon me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Sir, you should quickly get out of this road; for if the troops of Wu block it, we shall be in grave danger.', 'context': 'Jia Kui replied, “'},
{'istart': 142, 'iend': 243, 'talk': 'This deed of yours, and the sacrifice you made to attain it, will surely be written in the histories.', 'context': 'When the officers presented their felicitations, Sun Quan noticed that Zhou Fang had no hair, and Sun Quan was very gracious to him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Cao Xiu has been thoroughly beaten, and the soldiers of Wei are cowed. I think now is an occasion to send letters into Shu to advise Zhuge Liang to attack Wei.', 'context': 'Lu Xun said, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'The defeat of Commander Cao Xiu is also partly yours. Why, O General, did you hurry home?', 'context': 'Then Sima Yi brought the army home again. The other officers went to welcome him and asked, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 217, 'talk': "I came for reasons of strategy, because of Zhuge Liang's probable intentions. If he knows I have suffered a defeat, he may try to attack Changan. The whole west would be helpless if I did not return.", 'context': 'Sima Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'That gale signals the loss of a great leader.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang cast lots to know what portent was intended, and announced, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'That is it; Zhao Yun is gone.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang, deeply affected, threw aside his wine cup and cried, “'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Our father died the night before at the third watch.', 'context': 'When the two young men came in, they prostrated themselves and wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'My friend is gone; the country has lost it great beam and I my right arm.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Zhao Yun was my savior and friend; he saved my life when I was a child in the time of great confusion,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'The dispositions of the army are complete, and the Prime Minister proposes to march against Wei without delay.', 'context': 'When the two sons had left, the ministers reported to the Latter Ruler: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'No need to fear anything with such a man,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 420, 'talk': 'A rampart has been built and behind it is a general named Hao Zhao in command. The rampart is very strong and is further defended by thorny barriers. Instead of taking Chencang, which seems difficult, it would be easier to go out to Qishan by the Taibo Mountains, where is a practicable, though winding, road.', 'context': 'The first companies of the army of Shu sent out their scouts as far as Chencang. They came back and reported: “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Due north of Chencang is Jieting, so that I must get this city in order to advance.', 'context': 'But Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 262, 'iend': 471, 'talk': 'I have followed the Prime Minister for a long time, but have not achieved worthy service. Now I want to go to Chencang and persuade Hao Zhao to yield; thus, our army does not need to use a single bow or arrow.', 'context': 'Wei Yan was sent to surround Chencang and take it. He went, but days passed without success. Therefore he returned and told his chief the place was impregnable. In his anger, Zhuge Liang was going to put Wei Yan to death, but an officer stepped forth and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'How do you think you will persuade him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'What will you say?', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'Friend, why have you come?', 'context': 'A sentry on the wall told Hao Zhao, who bade them let the visitor enter and bring him up on the wall. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'I am in the service of Shu, serving under Zhuge Liang as an assistant in the tactical department. I am created exceedingly well, and my chief has sent me to say something to you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is my enemy. I serve Wei while you serve Shu. Each serves his own lord. We were brothers once, but now we are enemies; so do not say any more.', 'context': 'Hao Zhao was rather annoyed, and said, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'My friend and worthy brother, why has your friendship become so thin?', 'context': 'He pulled up his horse, pointed with his whip at Hao Zhao, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Brother, you know the laws of Wei,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'I have accepted their bounty, and if that leads to death, so be it. Say no more, but return quickly to your master and tell him to come and attack. I am not afraid.', 'context': ' replied Hao Zhao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'He would not let me begin to explain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Try again,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Go and really talk to him.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 470, 'talk': 'My worthy brother, please listen to my words while I explain clearly. Here you are holding one single city; how can you think of opposing one hundred thousand troops? If you do not yield, you will be sorry when it is too late. Instead of serving the great Hans, you are serving a depraved country called Wei. Why do you not recognize the decree of Heaven? Why do you not distinguish between the pure and the foul? Think over it.', 'context': 'the tower, and Jin Xiang shouted to him, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Go! Or I will shoot. I meant what I said at first, and I will say no more.', 'context': 'Then Hao Zhao began to get really angry. He fitted an arrow to his bow and he called out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'The fool is very ill−mannered,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'I do not think such a small place can beat me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'So you burn my ladders; then I will use battering rams.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang angrily said, “'},
{'istart': 192, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': 'That was not all. The scouts reported the coming of a relief force of Wei, the flags of which bore the name of Wang Shuang. Some one had to try to turn him back, and Wei Yan offered himself. “'},
{'istart': 216, 'iend': 258, 'talk': 'you are too valuable as Leader of the Van.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Do not follow the fleeing general!', 'context': 'His colleague, Wang Ping, suspected this flight was but a ruse, so he called to Zhang Ni, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'Wang Shuang is very terrible and no one can stand up to him. Beside there is a strong camp at the city with double walls and a deep moat.', 'context': 'Zhang Ni was hurt internally and vomited blood at times. He came back and told Zhuge Liang, saying, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'We are stopped this way; can you suggest another road?', 'context': 'Having lost two generals, and a third being wounded, Zhuge Liang called up Jiang Wei and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Yes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 384, 'talk': 'Chencang is too well protected and, with Hao Zhao as defender and Wang Shuang as supporter, cannot be taken. I would propose to move away to some suitable place and make a strong camp. Then try to hold the roads so that the attack on Jieting may be prevented. Then if you will send a strong force against Qishan, I can do something which will capture Cao Zhen.', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 129, 'iend': 304, 'talk': 'I am not really a spy in the bad sense. I was bringing a secret communication for you, Sir, but I was captured by one of the parties in ambush. Pray send away your attendants.', 'context': 'Then they caught a spy. He was taken into the presence of the Commander−in−Chief to be questioned. The man knelt down and said, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'I am a confidant of Jiang Wei, who has entrusted me with a secret letter.', 'context': "The man's bonds were loosed and the tent cleared. The captive said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Where is the letter?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'If this should be deemed worthy of your attention, then without delay communicate your commands.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'This is heaven−sent help to aid me in an achievement.', 'context': 'The letter pleased Cao Zhen, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I have just had a secret letter from Jiang Wei telling me to act in a certain fashion.', 'context': 'to his councils and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'But Jiang Wei is really a man of Wei; he was forced into surrender. Why are you suspicious?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'If the soldiers of Shu come on, you are to retire and look out for a signal. If you see a blaze, you are to turn and attack, for you will be reinforced by Jiang Wei.', 'context': 'Fei Yao rode out and, seeing Zhuge Liang, he secretly rejoiced. Turning to those about him, he said, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'You rebel leader in front there; how dare you come here again after the last defeat?', 'context': 'Then Fei Yao rode to the front and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'Go and call Cao Zhen to a parley.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'My chief, Cao Zhen, is of the royal stock; think you that he will come to parley with rebels?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Faithless ingrate! I have haplessly fallen in your treachery and craftiness!', 'context': 'Fei Yao began to upbraid him, crying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'You are the wrong victim; we meant to capture Cao Zhen not you. You would do well to yield!', 'context': 'Jiang Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'My regret is that I did not slay Cao Zhen,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Indeed, yes,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'It is a pity that a great scheme should have had so poor a result.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'I have a scheme all ready, not only to turn back Zhuge Liang, but to do so without any exertion on our part. They will retire of their own will.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 731, 'talk': 'I have said repeatedly that Zhuge Liang would come against us by way of Chencang; wherefore I set Hao Zhao to guard it. If an enemy did invade, he could easily obtain his supplies by that road; but with Hao Zhao and Wang Shuang on guard there, he will not dare to come that way. It is very difficult to get supplies any other way. Therefore I can give the invaders a month to exhaust their food. Hence their advantage lies in forcing a battle; ours is postponing it as long as possible. Wherefore I pray Your Majesty order Cao Zhen to hold passes and positions tenaciously and on no account to seek battle. In a month the enemy will have to retreat, and that will be our opportunity.', 'context': 'Now Sima Yi spoke to the Ruler of Wei, saying, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'Since, Noble Sir, you foresaw all this so plainly, why did you not lead an army to prevent it?', 'context': 'Cao Rui was pleased to hear so succinct a statement, but he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 314, 'talk': "It is not because I grudged the effort, but I had to keep the army here to guard against Lu Xun of Wu. Sun Quan will declare himself 'Emperor' before long. If he does, he will be afraid of Your Majesty's attack, and so he will try to invade us first. I shall be ready to defend our frontier. The army is prepared.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 127, 'iend': 317, 'talk': 'Your Majesty should send someone especially to caution the general to be careful not to be tricked by Zhuge Liang, not to pursue rashly, and never to penetrate deeply into the enemy country.', 'context': 'Just then one of the courtiers announced dispatches from Cao Zhen on military affairs, and Sima Yi closed his speech, saying, “'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 355, 'talk': 'I am giving this magnificent opportunity to obtain glory to Cao Zhen, but do not tell him the suggestion was mine; only quote the royal command. Tell him that defense is the best, pursuit is to be most cautious, and he is not to send any impetuous leader to follow up the enemy.', 'context': 'Sima Yi escorted the royal messenger out of the city and, at parting, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': "That is Sima Yi's idea,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'But what of the idea?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'But if the Shu army holds its ground?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 389, 'talk': 'Let me go out to Qishan as if to escort a convoy from Xizhou, only the carts shall be laden with combustibles instead of grain. We will sprinkle sulfur and saltpeter over wood and reeds. The troops of Shu, who lack supplies, will surely seize the convoy and take it to their own camp, when we will set fire to the carts. When they are blazing, our hidden men can attack.', 'context': 'Then said Sun Li, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'It seems an excellent plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'I do not know what to do. The enemy refuse battle, because they know we are short of food. We can get none by way of Chencang, and all other roads are very difficult. I reckon the grain we brought with us will not last a month.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang called Jiang Wei and certain others to him and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'What is known of this Sun Li?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 316, 'talk': "He is a bold man. Once he was out hunting with the Ruler of Wei on Great Rock Hill, and a tiger suddenly appeared in front of his master's chariot. He jumped off his horse and dispatched the beast with his sword. He was rewarded with a leadership. He is an intimate friend of Cao Zhen.", 'context': 'A certain man of Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'This is a ruse,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 355, 'talk': 'They know we are short of food, and those carts are only a temptation. They are laden with combustibles. How can they imagine that I shall be deceived by this sort of thing, when I have fought them with fire so many times? If we go to seize the convoy, they will come and raid our camp. But I will meet ruse with ruse.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 281, 'talk': "You and three thousand troops are to make your way to the enemy's store camp and, when the wind serves, to start a fire. When the stores are burning, the soldiers of Wei will come to surround our camp. That is how we will provoke a battle.", 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang sent Ma Dai with order: “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 275, 'talk': 'The outermost camp of Wei is on the main road. This night, when the enemy see a blaze, our camp will be attacked, so you two are to lie in wait on the two sides of the Wei camp and seize it when they have left.', 'context': 'These having gone, he called Guan Xing and Zhang Bao, and said, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'You are to lie in wait outside the camp to cut off the retreat of the force of Wei.', 'context': 'Calling Wu Ban and Wu Yi, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Because we are short of food,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'I have received a royal command to come and to be into your arrangements.', 'context': 'When he saw Cao Zhen, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Did you take leave of friend Sima Yi?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'His instructions to me were to stay away if you were victor, to come if you were not. It seems that our side has missed success. Have you since found out what the troops of Shu are doing?', 'context': 'Zhang He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Not yet.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 297, 'iend': 318, 'talk': 'Do not flee, Wei Yan!', 'context': "When Wei Yan received his secret orders, he broke up camp that night and hastened toward Hanzhong. Wang Shuang's scouts heard this and told their chief, who hurried in pursuit. After about seven miles, he came in sight of Wei Yan's ensigns. As soon as he got within hailing distance, he shouted, “"},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Here is Wei Yan!', 'context': 'passed a hill, a horseman suddenly came out of a wood. “'},
{'istart': 305, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'Emperor.', 'context': "And many other officers supported Zhang Zhao's proposal. They finally persuaded Sun Quan to decide upon the 'tiger' day in the forth month, in summer. They prepared an altar on the south of Wuchang, and on that day his courtiers formally requested him to ascend to the high place and assume the style of “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Yellow Dragon', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 313, 'iend': 333, 'talk': 'My friend Zhuge Jin.', 'context': 'This son of Zhuge Jin was a person below middle height, but very clever, and especially apt at capping verses. Sun Quan liked him much. When Zhuge Ke was six, he went with his father to a banquet. Sun Quan noticed that Zhuge Jin had a long face, so he bade a man lead in a donkey, and he wrote on it with chalk, “'},
{'istart': 433, 'iend': 462, 'talk': "My friend Zhuge Jin's donkey.", 'context': ' Every one roared with laughter. But the youngster ran up and added a few strokes making it read, “'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'This is not the proper treatment for old age.', 'context': 'Another day, at a large official banquet, Sun Quan sent the boy with a goblet of wine to each courtier. When he came to Zhang Zhao, the old man declined it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Can you not make him drink?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 344, 'talk': 'You remember Father Lu Wang; he was ninety and yet gripped the signaling flags and wielded the axes of an army commander in the field. He never spoke of age. Nowadays in battle we put seniors behind, but at the banquet board we give them a front place. How can you say we do not treat old age properly?', 'context': 'Then said Zhuge Ke to the old gentleman, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 258, 'talk': "It is not well to begin Your Majesty's new reign with fighting; rather improve learning and hide the sword; establish schools and so give the people the blessings of peace. Make a treaty with Shu to share the empire, and lay your plans slowly and carefully.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': "We owe this to Zhuge Liang's fear of Sima Yi,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'However, we must consent since Shu asks it. We will make a show of raising an army and in a measure support them. When Zhuge Liang has actually attacked Wei, we will make for the Middle Land ourselves.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'That means success for me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'Take five thousand troops and hasten to Chencang. If you see a blaze, then attack.', 'context': 'He called in Wei Yan and Jiang Wei, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'In three days you should be ready to march. Do not come to take leave of me, but set out as soon as possible.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'You have come too late,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Really, you are supernatural, O Minister!', 'context': 'Both dropped out of the saddle and prostrated themselves. “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'But do not divest yourself of your armor. Go and attack San Pass and drive away the guards while they are in a state of surprise. If you delay, Wei will have sent reinforcements.', 'context': 'Turning once more to Wei Yan and Jiang Wei, he said, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 76, 'talk': "The Prime Minister's foresight was superhuman.", 'context': 'They remarked to each other, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 389, 'talk': 'Twice have I gone out by Qishan without success, but at last I am here. I think Wei will resume the former battle ground and oppose us. If so, they will assume that I shall attack Yongcheng and Meicheng and send armies to defend them. But I see Yinping and Wudu are connected with Hanzhong; and if I can win these, I can drive a wedge into the Wei force. Who will go to take these places?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'Chencang is lost, Hao Zhao is dead, San Pass is taken, and Zhuge Liang is again at Qishan; and thence has sent out two armies.', 'context': 'Zhang He went back to Changan and saw Guo Huai and Sun Li, to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'In that case, Yongcheng and Meicheng are in danger.', 'context': 'Guo Huai was frightened, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'In my humble opinion, Wu will not attack us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'What makes you think so?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Your insight is very profound,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I would rather go myself,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Shu and Wu have made an alliance to invade us, and Zhuge Liang is at Qishan. Have you heard, Illustrious Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'My people have kept back all news as I am ill,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'But if this is true, the country is in danger. Why have they not made you Commander−in−Chief to stop this invasion?', 'context': ' said he, startled. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I am unequal to the post,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Bring the seal and give it to him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'You are anxious on my account; really I am only come to lend you an arm. I dare not accept the seal.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Really the Emperor has already shown his kindness, but I dare not accept his offer.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'Not yet,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'How does Sima Yi compare with Zhuge Liang?', 'context': 'They set out to obey these orders, and on the way they fell to discussing Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is by far the better,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 236, 'talk': "Though Zhuge Liang may be the cleverer, yet this scheme of our leader's shows him to be superior to most people. The enemy may have got those two cities; yet when we unexpectedly fall upon their rear, they will certainly be disordered.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Wang Ping has captured Yinping, and Wudu is in possession of Jiang Wei. Furthermore, the Shu army is not far in front.', 'context': 'Soon after this a scout came in to report: “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'There is some crafty scheme afoot. Why are they prepared for battle in the open when they hold two cities? We would better retire.', 'context': 'Said Sun Li, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 333, 'talk': "Do not run away; did you think that your leader's ruse would take me in? Sima Yi sent a challenge to fight every day, indeed, while you were to slip round behind my army and attack! I have the two cities—Wudu and Yinping; and if you have not come to surrender, then hurry up and fight a battle with me.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang laughed and said, “'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 270, 'talk': "Wudu and Yinping were both in the enemy's possession, and Zhuge Liang had prepared an ambush, so that we were attacked front and rear. We lost the day and only escaped on foot.", 'context': "It has been said that Guo Huai and Sun Li escaped. They got back to Sima Yi's camp and said, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'It is no fault of yours,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'The fact is he is sharper than I. Now go to defend Yongcheng and Meicheng and remain on the defensive; do not go out to give battle. I have a plan to defeat them.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 620, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang has captured Wudu and Yinping. He must restore order and confidence among the people of these places and so will be absent from his camp. You two will take ten thousand troops each, start tonight and make your way quietly to the rear of the Shu army. Then you will attack vigorously. When you have done that, I shall lead out the army in front of them and array ready for battle. While they are in disorder, I shall make my attack. Their camp ought to be captured. If I can win the advantage of these hills, their defeat will be easy.', 'context': 'These two having left, Sima Yi called in Zhang He and Dai Ling and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'The enemy has been prepared,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'We should return.', 'context': ' said Zhang He. “'},
{'istart': 223, 'iend': 540, 'talk': 'Dai Ling and Zhang He, listen to my words! Your master reckoned that I should be busy restoring order in the two cities and so should not be in my camp. Wherefore he sent you to take the camp, and you have just fallen into my snare. As you are leaders of no great importance, I shall not harm you. Dismount and yield.', 'context': 'Just as they ordered the troops to turn about, torches broke into flame all over the hills, the drums rolled, trumpets blared, and soldiers sprang out on every side. At the same time Zhuge Liang shouted from the hill−top, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'You peasant out of the woods, invader of our great country! How dare you use such words to me? Wait till I catch you; I will tear you to shreds.', 'context': "Zhang He's wrath blazed forth at this, and he pointed at Zhuge Liang, crying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 213, 'talk': "I have heard that soldiers stood aghast when Zhang Fei fought his great fight with Zhang He. Now I can judge Zhang He's valor for myself. He will do harm to Shu one day if I spare him. He will have to be removed.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 106, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang forestalled us; he was well prepared, and so we were quite defeated.', 'context': 'army to attack. Then he saw Zhang He and Dai Ling come limping back dejected and crestfallen. They said, “'},
{'istart': 189, 'iend': 211, 'talk': 'He is more than human!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 233, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'We must retreat.', 'context': ' exclaimed Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 335, 'talk': 'But the world is in confusion, and the original evil has not been destroyed. You fill a great office, for you direct the affairs of the state. It is not well for you to remain under a cloud for any length of time and cloak your grand virtue, wherefore I restore you to the rank of Prime Minister and pray you not to decline the honor.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'My task is not yet accomplished; how can I return to my duties as Prime Minister? I must really decline to accept this.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang heard the edict to the end and then said, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'If you decline this, you flout the desires of the Emperor and also show contempt for the feelings of the army. At any rate accept for the moment.', 'context': 'Fei Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'It must mean that their food is exhausted. Why not pursue?', 'context': 'Zhang He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Ah; then he is not running away,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Remain on the defensive still more strictly and do not advance.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is certainly working some scheme,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Do not pursue.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'What makes you so over−suspicious? I can see that Zhuge Liang is retreating into Hanzhong, only he is doing it gradually and arousing our suspicion. Why not pursue before it is too late. Let me go and fight one battle.', 'context': 'Zhang He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 138, 'talk': "A defeat would destroy the morale of our soldiers, and I will not risk it. Zhuge Liang's vile tricks are innumerable.", 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'If I go and get beaten, I will stand the full rigor of military punishment,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'Well, if you are set on going, we will divide the army. You take your wing and go, but you will have to fight your best. I will follow to help in case of need. Tomorrow you should march only halfway and rest your troops for the battle.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'The enemy are coming in pursuit and will fight desperately. You will have to fight every one of you like ten, but I will set an ambush to attack their rear. Only a wise and bold leader is fit for this task.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'But if you fail, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'Then there is the military rule.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 396, 'talk': "Wang Ping is most loyal. He is willing to risk wounds and death in his country's service. However, the enemy are in two divisions, one coming in front, the other trying to get round to the rear. Wang Ping is crafty and bold, but he cannot be in two places at once, so I must have yet another general. Is it that among you there is no other willing to devote himself to death?", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang sighed. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'If I fail, may my head fall at the tent door,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 306, 'talk': 'I am going to give you a silken bag. You are to proceed secretly into those mountains in front. When you see that Zhang Yi and Wang Ping are in great straits with the enemy, then open the bag and you will find a plan of escape.', 'context': 'When they had gone, Jiang Wei and Liao Hua were called, and Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Hide in the valleys with five thousand troops till you see a red flag flutter out, and then fall on the enemy.', 'context': 'Then calling Guan Xing, he said to them, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Why do you not fight to death?', 'context': 'Presently, with a roll of drums, Wang Ping and Zhang Yi came out and made for the rear to cut the retreat. “'},
{'istart': 230, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'Our minister is truly wonderful. The battle goes just as he foretold,', 'context': 'The soldiers of Wei dashed this way and that, but were stayed at every attempt. Then there was heard another roll of drums, and Sima Yi came up in the rear. He at once signaled to his generals to surround Wang Ping and Zhang Yi. “'},
{'istart': 318, 'iend': 379, 'talk': 'He will surely send help now, and we will fight to the death.', 'context': ' cried Zhang Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Now surely is the moment to open the bag,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 326, 'talk': "If Sima Yi comes and Wang Ping and Zhang Yi seem hard pressed, you are to divide forces and go off to attack Sima Yi's camp, which will cause him to retire, and then you can attack him as his army is in disorder. The actual capture of the camp is not of great moment.", 'context': 'So the bag was opened, and they read the letter. It said: “'},
{'istart': 246, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'The soldiers of Shu are making for the main camp by two directions.', 'context': 'Now Sima Yi had really feared that he would fall victim to some ruse of Zhuge Liang, so he had arranged for messengers and news to meet him at intervals along the road. He was pressing his troops to fight when a messenger galloped up to report: “'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 214, 'talk': 'I knew Zhuge Liang would plan some trick, but you did not believe me. You forced me to pursue, and now the whole scheme has gone astray.', 'context': 'Sima Yi was frightened and changed color. He turned on his generals, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 301, 'talk': 'You are all ignorant of the proper way to wage war, and think it simply a matter of valor and rude strength. This is the result of your unbridled desire to go out and give battle. For the future no one of you will move without definite orders, and I will apply strict military law to any who disobey.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'I feel void and am too ill to carry on, and the best thing for me is to return into Hanzhong and get well. You are to keep my absence perfectly secret, for Sima Yi will certainly attack if he hears.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'The man appears like a god and disappears like a demon; he is too much for me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 78, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'The Commander−in−Chief speaks well. If that state be not destroyed, it will be to our hurt. Your Majesty should give effect to his desire.', 'context': 'Personally, the Ruler of Wei approved, but he consulted Liu Ye, who replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'No such thing,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'I have studied the details; Shu cannot be attacked.', 'context': 'Liu Ye replied, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'The moment is opportune; I do not think there is any danger from Wu.', 'context': 'Sima Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 134, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Eight Arrays.', 'context': 'The defenders of Hanzhong brought the news to Zhuge Liang, then quite recovered and engaged in training his army and elaborating the “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'You are to lead one thousand troops to Chencang and garrison that road so as to check the Wei army.', 'context': 'When he heard of the intended attack, he called up Zhang Ni and Wang Ping and gave orders: “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'It is said the Wei army numbers four hundred thousand, though they pretend to have eight hundred thousand. But they are very numerous, and a thousand troops is a very small force to meet them.', 'context': 'The two replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 729, 'talk': 'I would give you more, but I fear to make it hard for the soldiers. If there be a failure, I shall not hold you responsible. I send you thus; you may be sure there is a meaning in it. I observed the stars yesterday, and I see there will be a tremendous rain this month. The army of Wei may consist of any number of legions, but they will be unable to penetrate into a mountainous country. So there is no need to send a large force. You will come to no harm, and I shall lead the main body into Hanzhong and rest for a month while the enemy retreats. Then I shall smite them. My strong army needs only one hundred thousand to defeat their worn four hundred thousand. Do not say any more, but get off quickly.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 277, 'talk': "I have watched the Heaven, and the stars' movement signals long rains. If we get deep in a difficult country and are always victorious, it is all very well. But if we lose, we shall not get out again. Better remain in this city and build what shelter we can against the rains.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 503, 'talk': 'I may quote certain parallels. King Wu of Zhou attacked the last Shang King; he went through the pass, but returned. In recent times Emperors Cao and Pi, attacking Sun Quan, reached the river, and went no farther. Did they not recognize limitations and act accordingly? I pray Your Majesty remember the grave difficulties caused by the rain and put an end to this expedition. By and by another occasion will arise for using force, and in the joy of overcoming difficulties the people will forget death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Return is best.', 'context': 'Sima Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'If Zhuge Liang pursue, how shall we repulse him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'We can leave an ambush.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 182, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'The rain has driven the enemy away; surely it is the moment to pursue.', 'context': "When the Shu officers got to know that the Wei army had gone but they were not to pursue, they were inclined to discontent and went in a body to the Prime Minister's tent and said, “"},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 269, 'talk': "Sima Yi is an able leader who would not retreat without leaving an ambush to cover it. If we pursue we shall fall victims. Let him go in peace, and I shall then get through the Xie Valley and take Qishan, making use of the enemy's lack of defense.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'But there are other ways of taking Changan;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'why only take Qishan?', 'context': ' said they, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'This continuous autumn rain has rendered all the ways impassable; how could the soldiers of Shu know of our retreat?', 'context': 'Cao Zhen said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'They will appear later,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'How can you know?', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'These late five dry days they have not pursued, because they think we shall have left a rearguard in ambush. Therefore they have let us get well away. But after we have gone, they will try to occupy Qishan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Why do you doubt?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'If the army of Shu do appear, I will give you the girdle and the steed that the Emperor gave me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 188, 'iend': 323, 'talk': 'The rain has drenched us for days, and they would not retire. Now they have camped here for a wager. They have no pity for us soldiers.', 'context': 'Sima Yi disguised himself as a soldier and went among the soldiers to get a private survey of all the camps. In one of them he happened upon a junior officer who was complaining, saying, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 259, 'talk': "The state feeds and trains soldiers a thousand days for one hour's service. How dare you give vent to your spleen to the detriment of discipline?", 'context': 'Sima Yi returned to his tent and assembled his officers. Hauling out the grumbler, Sima Yi said to him, angrily, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'I am not here for a wager, but to overcome Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'I bear an order from the Prime Minister. As you go out of the valley, beware of the enemy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 103, 'talk': "You know the Prime Minister's plans always succeed. How dare you disobey his orders?", 'context': 'Deng Zhi replied, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'If he was really so resourceful, we should not have lost Jieting.', 'context': 'Chen Shi smiled, saying, “'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'If he had listened to me and gone out through Ziwu Valley, not only Changan but Luoyang too would be ours. Now he is bent on taking Qishan; what is the good of it? He gave us the order to advance and now he stops us. Truly the orders are confusing.', 'context': 'Wei Yan, recalling that Zhuge Liang had rejected his plan, also laughed, and said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 200, 'talk': 'I will tell you what I will do. I shall take only five thousand troops, get through the Chi Valley, and camp at Qishan. Then you will see how ashamed the Prime Minister will look.', 'context': 'Then said Chen Shi, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'That fellow Wei Yan has never been quite true; he has always been disposed to disobey and is unsteady. However, he is valiant, and so I have saved him for our use, but he will do real harm some day.', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'If there are any troops of Wei in the Xie Valley, you are to go across the mountains, marching by night and concealing yourselves by day, and make for the east of Qishan. When you arrive, make a fire as a signal.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang called to his tent Ma Dai and Wang Ping, and said, “'},
{'istart': 246, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'Dismount and yield!', 'context': 'defense, but the shouting quickly came nearer, and then Wu Ban and Wu Yi appeared advancing towards him. Retreat was impossible for Guan Xing and Liao Hua had blocked the road. The hills were on both sides, and from the hill−tops came shouts of “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'Our troops have fallen into an ambush, and many have been killed. Do not think any more about the wager: that is canceled. But take most careful precautions.', 'context': 'This news satisfied Cao Zhen. But just then a trusty messenger from Sima Yi came with a message: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'But there is not a single soldier of Shu near,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang has seized Qishan, and we cannot remain here; let us go to River Wei, whence we may try to recover our lost ground.', 'context': 'Then said Sima Yi, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'How did you know I was in danger of defeat?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 268, 'talk': "My messenger told me that you said there was not a single soldier of Shu near, and I knew Zhuge Liang would try to seize your camp. So I came to your help. The enemy's plan succeeded, but we will say no more about that wager. We must both do our best for the country.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Who caused the loss?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Chen Shi disobeyed orders and rushed into the valley.', 'context': 'Wei Yan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Wei Yan told me to,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Would you still try to drag him down after he rescued you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'You are Wei troops, and your families are all over there: it is wrong for you to serve me. Suppose I let you go home?', 'context': 'Then he called up the soldiers of Wei who had yielded, and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'Friend Cao Zhen and I have a compact, and I have a letter for him which you shall take. The bearer will be well rewarded.', 'context': 'Then Zhuge Liang continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 939, 'talk': "Alas! One of your sort, ignorant and inferior, rising impudently in heaven's vault, has had the presumption to assist a rebel to assume the imperial style and state at Luoyang, to send some miserable soldiers into Beach Valley. There they happened upon drenching rain. The difficult roads wearied both soldiers and horses, driving them frantic. Weapons and armors littered the countryside, swords and spears covered the ground. You, the Commander−in−Chief, were heart−broken and cowed, your generals fled like rats. You dare not show your faces at home, nor can you enter the halls of state. The historians' pens will record your defeats; the people will recount your infamies. 'Sima Yi is frightened when he hears of battle fronts, Cao Zhen is alarmed at mere rumors.' My soldiers are fierce and their steeds strong; my great generals are eager as tigers and majestic as dragons. I shall sweep the Middle Land bare and make Wei desolate.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 698, 'talk': "Our master's ascension of the throne was after the manner of King Yao, who abdicated in favor of King Shun. Two emperors have succeeded and have their seat in the Middle Land. Because of his liberality and graciousness, my lord has suffered the rule of Shu and Wu lest the people should suffer in a struggle. You, who are but a plowman from Nanyang, ignorant of the ways of Heaven, wish to invade us, and you should be destroyed; but if you will examine your heart and repent of your fault and retire, then each may maintain his own borders, and a settled state of three kingdoms will be attained. Thus the people may be spared distress, and you will save your life.", 'context': 'Sima Yi addressed Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 423, 'talk': 'Our First Ruler entrusted to me the custody of his orphan son: think you that I shall fail to exert myself to the uttermost to destroy rebels against his authority? Your soldiers of the Cao family will soon be exterminated by Han. Your ancestors were servants of Han and for generations ate of their bounty. Yet, instead of giving grateful service, you assist usurpers. Are you not ashamed?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang smiled and replied, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'We will try the test of battle. If you can conquer, I pledge myself to be no longer a leader of armies; but if you are defeated, then you will retire at once to your own village and I will not harm you.', 'context': "The flush of shame spread over Sima Yi's face, but he replied, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Do you desire a contest of generals, or of weapons, or of battle array?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Let us try a contest of battle array,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Then draw up your array that I may see,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Do you recognize my formation?', 'context': 'When he had finished, he rode again to the front, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'The least of my generals can do as well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Now you try while I look on,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'Do you recognize that?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang entered the lines and waved his fan. Then he came out and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Yes; you seem to know it. But dare you attack?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Why not, since I know it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Then you need only try.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 110, 'iend': 439, 'talk': 'That formation consists of eight gates—Birth, Exit, Expanse, Wound, Fear, Annihilation, Obstacle, and Death. You will go in from the east at the Gate of Birth, turn to the southwest and make your way out by the Gate of Annihilation. Then enter at the north, at the Exit Gate, and the formation will be broken up. But be cautious.', 'context': 'Sima Yi entered the ranks and called to him three generals—Dai Ling, Zhang Hu, and Yue Chen—to whom he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Indeed you are prisoners; are you surprised', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 286, 'talk': 'But I will set you free to return to your leader, and tell him to read his books again, and study his tactics, before he comes to try conclusions with me. You are pardoned, but leave your weapons and horses here.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'After this disgrace, how can I face the other officers in the Middle Land?', 'context': 'Said he, “'},
{'istart': 125, 'iend': 283, 'talk': "This grain is of the utmost importance to the army and you delay it. Three days' delay ought to mean the death penalty; what can you say to this delay of ten?", 'context': 'drunkard and loitered on the road so that he arrived ten days late. Zhuge Liang, angry at the delay, upbraided him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 207, 'iend': 257, 'talk': 'Your tale may be true, but it is hard to trust it,', 'context': "This punishment filled Gou An's heart with bitter resentment, and, in the night, he deserted to the enemy, he and his half dozen personal staff. He was taken before Sima Yi and told the tale of his wrongs. “"},
{'istart': 274, 'iend': 448, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is full of guile. However, you may render me a service, and if you do, I will ask the Ruler of Wei that you may be allowed to serve him and obtain a post for you.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'Whatever you ask, I will do the best I can,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'Then go to Chengdu and spread a lying report that Zhuge Liang is angry with the powers there and means to make himself emperor. This will get him recalled, and that will be a merit to you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'In such a case what am I to do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Recall him to the capital,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'and take away his military powers so that he cannot rebel.', 'context': ' said the eunuchs, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister has rendered many and great services since he led out the army; wherefore is he recalled?', 'context': 'Jiang Wan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'I have a private matter to consult him about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 72, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'I must see him personally.', 'context': ' said the Latter Ruler. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'The Emperor is young, and there is some jealous persons by his side,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'If the army retire, Sima Yi will attack,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 345, 'talk': 'I will retire in five divisions. Thus today this camp goes. Supposing that there are a thousand soldiers in the camp, then I shall have two thousand cooking places prepared, or if there are three thousand soldiers, then four thousand cooking plates shall be got ready; and so on, increasing the cooking arrangements as the troops are sent away.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'In the days of old, when Sun Bin was attacking Pang Juan, Sun Bin decreased the cooking arrangements as the soldiers were increased. Why do you reverse this, O Minister?', 'context': 'Yang Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 338, 'talk': 'Because Sima Yi is an able leader and would pursue if he knew we were retreating. But he would recognize the probability of an ambush; and if he sees an increase in the cooking arrangements in a camp, he will be unable to conclude whether the troops have gone or not, and he will not pursue. Thus I shall gradually withdraw without loss.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'I felt sure that Zhuge Liang would have more troops ready. He has increased the cooking arrangements, and so, if we pursue, he will be ready for us. No; we also will retire and await another opportunity.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Your Majesty recalled me just as I was about to advance upon Changan; what is the important matter?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 129, 'talk': 'I longed to see your face once more, that is the only reason.', 'context': 'For a long time the Latter Ruler made no reply. Presently he said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'I think my recall was not on your own initiative; some slanderous persons has hinted that I cherished ulterior objects.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 281, 'talk': 'Your late father laid me under an obligation which I am pledged to fulfill to the death. But if vile influences are permitted to work at home, how can I destroy the rebels without?', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler, who indeed felt guilty and ill at ease, made no reply, and Zhuge Liang continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'The fact is I recalled you because of the talk of the eunuchs. But I understand now and am unutterably sorry.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 526, 'talk': 'The soldiers are wearied by the many expeditions, and the supplies are not regular. I think a better plan would be to send half the army to Qishan for three months, and at the end of that time exchange them for the other half; and so on alternately. For example, if you have two hundred thousand troops, let one hundred thousand go into the field and one hundred thousand remain. In this way, using ten legions and ten legions, their energies will be conserved and you can gradually work toward the Middle Land.', 'context': 'Yang Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'I agree with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 144, 'talk': 'Our attack is not a matter to be achieved in haste. The suggestion for an extended campaign is excellent.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'I volunteer to guard Yongcheng and Meicheng against the Shu army.', 'context': 'Zhang He offered his services, saying, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 290, 'talk': "Our vanguard army is not strong enough to face the enemy's whole force. Moreover, to divide an army is not generally a successful scheme. The better plan will be to leave a guard in Shanggui and send all the others to Qishan. Will you undertake the leadership of the van?", 'context': 'But Sima Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'The main force of Shu is directed toward Qishan, and the Leaders of the Van are Wang Ping and Zhang Ni. The route chosen for their march is from Chencang across San Pass and to the Xie Valley.', 'context': 'The spies reported: “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 271, 'talk': "Zhuge Liang is advancing in great force and certainly intends to reap the wheat in Xizhou for his supply. You get sufficient troops to hold Qishan, while Guo Huai and I go to Tianshui and foil the enemy's plan to gather the wheat.", 'context': 'Hearing this, Sima Yi said to Zhang He, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'That must be the work of Sima Yi,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'But we have not enough food in camp. I have written to Li Yan to send grain, but it has not yet arrived. The wheat in Xizhou is now just ripe, and we will go and reap it.', 'context': ' remarked Zhuge Liang to his generals. “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'Where is the ripe wheat to be found?', 'context': 'After calming the people, Zhuge Liang asked, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 130, 'talk': 'Longshang is the place.', 'context': ' The Governor replied, “'},
{'istart': 147, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'Sima Yi has already occupied that city.', 'context': 'So Zhang Yi and Ma Zhong were left to guard the city, and the remainder of the army went to Longshang. But soon the leading body returned to say, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'He guessed what I intended to do,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': "Some of Zhuge Liang's odd doings,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 350, 'talk': "This Zhuge Liang is a master in the arts of necromancy and juggling and Eight Gates and knows how to call up the Deities of Six Layers to his aid. I know this trick of his; it is the 'Ground Rolling' in the 'Book of Six Layers Deities,' and it is vain to pursue.", 'context': 'Sima Yi now came up with a strong force. But he also halted, and said to his generals, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'But just now he was sitting in that other chariot, which we chased for fifteen miles; how can he be here?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'They must be heaven−sent soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'I was of the reaping party,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'They caught me when I was looking for some horses that had strayed.', 'context': ' said the man. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'What wonderful soldiers were they of yours that one saw here lately?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang was with one party of them, the others were led by Jiang Wei, Ma Dai, and Wei Yan. There was a thousand of fighting soldiers with each chariot and five hundred drummers. Zhuge Liang was with the first party.', 'context': 'The man replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'His comings and goings are not human,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'He threw dust in your eyes that time,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'The enemy will attack tonight. There is a suitable place for an ambush in the newly reaped fields, but who will lead for me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'We have long been at grips with these soldiers and are unable to drive them off. We have now lost another fight; and unless something is done, we shall not get away at all.', 'context': 'Guo Huai went to see his chief, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'What can we do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 263, 'talk': "You might write to Xizhou and Yongzhou to send their forces to our help. I will try my fortune against Saber Pass and cut off Zhuge Liang's retreat and supplies. That should bring about discontent and mutiny, and we can attack when we see the enemy in confusion.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 152, 'iend': 530, 'talk': 'The soldiers of Wei are well posted on the hills and refuse battle because, firstly, they think that we are short of food, and, secondly, they have sent an army against Saber Pass to cut off our supplies. Now each of you will take ten thousand troops and garrison the important points about here to show them that we are well prepared to defend ourselves. Then they will retire.', 'context': 'After many days had passed without sight of the enemy, Zhuge Liang thought it was time to make another move. Calling up Jiang Wei and Ma Dai, he said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 305, 'talk': 'O Minister, you have ordered the troops to be alternated every one hundred days. Now the time is due, and the replacing troops have already left Hanzhong and that dispatches from the leading divisions have come in. Here we have eighty thousand troops, of which forty will be due for relief.', 'context': 'Yang Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'There is the order; carry it out,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 345, 'talk': 'I must keep faith with the soldiers. Since the order for the periodical exchange of troops has been issued, it must be carried out. Beside, the soldiers due for relief are all prepared to start, their expectations have been roused and their relatives await them. In the face of yet greater difficulties I would let them go.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Since the Prime Minister loves us so much, we do not wish to go, but will prefer to remain to fight the Wei army to death.', 'context': 'And they said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'But you are due for home; you cannot stay here,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'As Wu is coming to invade our land, we shall have to retire quickly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'If I issue orders for the Qishan force to withdraw, Sima Yi will not dare to pursue while we are camped here.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'The enemy have retired, but I know not for what reason.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 176, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is very crafty, and you will do well to remain where you are and keep a careful lookout. Do nothing till their grain has given out, when they must retire for good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'But we should seize the occasion of their retreat to smite them. Are they tigers that you fear to move? How the world will laugh at us?', 'context': 'Here General Wei Ping stepped forward, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'If the soldiers of Wei pursue, wait till you hear a bomb. When you hear the bomb, at once barricade the road with timber and stones so as to impede them. When they halt, shoot at them with the bows and the crossbows.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 250, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'The city is deserted.', 'context': 'The spies of Wei returned to headquarters to say that most of the Shu soldiers had left, only a few being in the city. In doubt, Sima Yi went himself to look, and when he saw the smoke rising from within the walls and the fluttering flags, he said, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Then Zhuge Liang is really gone; who will pursue?', 'context': 'He sent men in to confirm this, and they said the place was empty. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Let me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'You are too impulsive,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'I have been leader of the van from the first day of this expedition; why not use me today, when there is work to be done and glory to be gained?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Because the utmost caution is necessary. They are retreating, and they will leave an ambush at every possible point.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'I know that, and you need not be afraid.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Well; you wish to go and may, but whatever happens you must be prepared for.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'A really noble man is prepared to sacrifice self for country; never mind what happens.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Zhang He, do not run away!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'Yield, rebel! I have not fought yet and you have had it all your own way so far. Now we will fight to the death.', 'context': 'Then suddenly Wei Yan made a real stand, and he rode to the front yelling, “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'I have blundered into an ambush!', 'context': 'Fear gripped Zhang He, and he cried, “'},
{'istart': 145, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'I, Zhuge Liang, am here!', 'context': 'their comrades had been victims of a cruel trick, and they turned back. But as they faced about, a shout was heard, and from the hilltops came, “'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 290, 'talk': 'I have gone hunting in this wood, as you see; only instead of slaying a horse, I have killed a deer. But you may go in peace, and when you see your general, tell him that he will be my quarry one day.', 'context': 'Looking up they saw his figure outlined against a fire. Pointing to the slain, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 92, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Letting friend Zhang He die is my fault!', 'context': 'The soldiers told this to Sima Yi when they returned, and he was deeply mortified, saying, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'Why does the Prime Minister return, for I have kept him fully supplied with all things needed for the army?', 'context': 'But Li Yan, who was in the capital, said to the Latter Ruler, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'Li Yan wrote to warn that East Wu was about to invade the country.', 'context': 'Yan, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'The fool has ruined the great design of the state just to save his own skin,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 186, 'talk': 'O Minister, the First Ruler had loved and trusted Li Yan with his son. Please forgive him this time.', 'context': 'He called in the offender and sentenced him to death. But Fei Yi interceded, saying, “'},
{'istart': 179, 'iend': 247, 'talk': 'Your late father named Li Yan as one of the guardians of your youth.', 'context': "And so Li Yan's life was spared. However, when Fei Yi made his report, the Latter Ruler was wroth and ordered Li Yan to suffer death. But this time Jiang Wan intervened, saying, “"},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 414, 'talk': "I have been training the army for three years; supplies are ample, and all is in order for an expedition. We may now attack Wei. If I cannot destroy these rebels, sweep away the evil hordes and bring about a glorious entry into the capital, then may I never again enter your Majesty's presence.", 'context': 'And the time passed quickly. In the second month of the twelfth year (AD 234) Zhuge Liang presented a memorial saying, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'Our state is now firmly established, and Wei troubles us not at all; why not enjoy the present tranquillity, O Father−Minister?', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'Because of the mission left me by your father. I am ever scheming to destroy Wei, even in my dreams. I must strive my best and do my utmost to restore you to the ancient capital of your ancestry and replace the Hans in their old palace.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'An army may not go forth, O Minister!', 'context': 'As Zhuge Liang said this, a voice cried, “'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 844, 'talk': "My present office involves the direction of the observations on the Astrological Terrace, and I am bound to report whether the aspect forebodes misfortune or promises happiness. Not long since, several flights of thousands of birds came from the south, plunged into River Han and were drowned. This is an evil augury. Moreover, I have studied the aspect of the sky, and the 'Wolf' constellation is influencing the aspect of the planet Venus. An aura of prosperity pervades the north. To attack Wei will not be to our profit. Again, the people in Chengdu say that the cypress trees moan in the night. With so many evil omens, I wish that the Prime Minister should not go forth to war, but remain at home to guard what we have.", 'context': 'Qiao Zhou, who protested against the war, was Grand Historian. He was also an astrologer. He opposed the war, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'How can I?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'His late Majesty laid upon me a heavy responsibility, and I must exert myself to the utmost in the endeavor to destroy these rebels. The policy of a state cannot be changed because of vain and irresponsible talk of inauspicious signs.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'How pitiful! Why does Heaven deny long life to the loyal and good? I have lost a most able general just as I am setting out and need him most.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'The commanders of the passes report thirty or so legions advancing in five divisions from Shu upon Qishan.', 'context': 'The courtiers said to the Ruler of Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Who are they? Name them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 94, 'iend': 136, 'talk': 'They are not like Xiahou Mao in the least.', 'context': 'and is still too ashamed to return to court. Are you sure these are not of the same kidney?” “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 304, 'talk': 'With the troops of Shu at Qishan, there is a possibility of their dominating River Wei, going up on the plain and pushing out a line to the northern hills whereby to cut off all highways in Xizhou.', 'context': 'While these preparations were in progress, Guo Huai and Sun Li came to the new camp, and the former said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'You say well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 236, 'talk': "See to it. Take command of all the Xizhou forces, occupy Beiyuan and make a fortified camp there. But adopt a defensive policy; wait till the enemy's food supplies get exhausted before you think of attack.", 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 808, 'talk': 'They camp there fearing that our holding this area will sever connection with Xizhou. I am pretending to look toward Beiyuan, but really my objective is River Wei. I am going to build several large rafts and pile them with straw, and I have five thousand of marines to manage them. In the darkness of the night I shall attack Beiyuan; Sima Yi will come to the rescue. If he is only a little worsted, I shall cross the river with the rear divisions. Then the leading divisions will embark on the rafts, drop down the river, set fire to the floating bridges, and attack the rear of the enemy. I shall lead an army to take the gates of the first camp. If we can get the south bank of the river, the campaign will become simple.', 'context': 'When he heard that the army of Wei had camped in Beiyuan, he said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang has some crafty scheme, but I think I know it. He proposes to make a show of taking Beiyuan, and then, dropping down the river, he will try to burn our bridges, throw our rear into confusion, and then attack our camps.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'You are to listen for the sounds of battle about Beiyuan; if you hear the shouting, you are to march down to the river, to the hills on the south, and lay an ambush against the troops of Shu as they arrive.', 'context': 'So he gave Xiahou Ba and Xiahou Wei orders: “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 469, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is coming to Beiyuan to cross the river secretly. Your force is small, and you can hide half way along the road. If the enemy cross the river in the afternoon, that will mean an attack on us in the evening. Then you are to simulate defeat and run. They will pursue. You can shoot with all your energy, and our marines and land troops will attack at once. If the attack is in great force, look out for orders.', 'context': 'Then he sent for Guo Huai and Sun Li, and said, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 356, 'talk': 'We do not know whether the cavalry sent to Beiyuan has been successful or not. It is strange that we do not see a single soldier of the enemy. Surely Sima Yi has found out the plan and prepared to frustrate the attack. Let us wait here till the bridges have been set on fire and we see the flames.', 'context': 'They heard loud shouting, and Wang Ping said to Zhang Ni, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister bade you retire immediately, as the attack on the bridges has failed.', 'context': 'So they halted. Soon after, a mounted messenger came up with orders: “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'I would trouble you, Sir, to carry a letter for me into East Wu; will you undertake the mission?', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang received him and, after the ceremonies were over, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Could I possibly decline any task you laid upon me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 508, 'talk': 'I have long desired to set my arm in motion, but have not been able to arrange with Zhuge Liang. After this letter I will lead an expedition myself and go to Juchao and capture Xincheng of Wei. Moreover, I will send Lu Xun and Zhuge Jin to camp at Miankou and Jiangxia, and take Xiangyang. I will also send an army under Sun Shao into Guangling to capture Huaiyang. The total number will be three hundred thousand troops, and they shall start at once.', 'context': 'Sun Quan was pleased at the news and said to the envoy, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 81, 'talk': 'In such a case the Middle Land will fall forthwith.', 'context': 'Fei Yi thanked him and said, “'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'Whom did the Prime Minister send to lead the battle?', 'context': 'A banquet was prepared. At this, Sun Quan said, “'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'Wei Yan was the chief leader.', 'context': ' Fei Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': "Your Majesty's words are to the point;", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'I will return at once and lay them before Zhuge Liang.', 'context': ' said the envoy, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Did the Ruler of Wu say nothing else?', 'context': 'Fei Yi quickly took leave and hastened to Qishan with his news of the intended expedition of Wu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Truly a comprehending ruler,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'But I could not be ignorant of this. However, I use Wei Yan because he is very bold.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, appreciatively. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'Then Sir, you ought to decide soon what to do with him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I have a scheme of my own.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'How does this man stand with you in fighting skill?', 'context': 'Said Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I should just kill him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'If you were to slay him, that would remove my doubts.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Give me back my horse you stole!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Take him away and behead him!', 'context': 'Seated in his tent, Zhuge Liang summoned Zheng Wen and burst out: “'},
{'istart': 99, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'I have done nothing wrong!', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'As if I do not know Qin Lang! The man you have just killed was not Qin Lang. How dare? you try to deceive me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'I will own up; but this was his brother Qin Ming.', 'context': 'Zheng Wen said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'How did you know this was only a pretended desertion?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Sima Yi looks to his people,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'We will fix today at the second watch for the raid, and I will lead in person. If it succeeds, I will give you a good appointment as a reward.', 'context': 'Presently he ordered in refreshments for the bearer of the letter, and then he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Father, you are going on a dangerous expedition on the faith of a mere scrap of paper,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'I think it imprudent. What if something goes unexpectedly wrong? Let some general go in your place, and you come up in rear as a reserve.', 'context': ' said his son. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'This is providential,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 166, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'Concealing Method.', 'context': 'After the third watch the sky cleared. Zhuge Liang from the hill−top sounded the gong of retreat. This obscurity in the third watch was due to an incantation called “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'It is called Shangfang Valley, and nicknamed Gourd Valley.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 219, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'wooden oxen and running horses', 'context': 'Returning to his camp, he called up two leaders named Du Rui and Hu Zhong and whispered into their ears certain secret orders. Next he called up a thousand craftspeople and sent them into the Gourd Valley to construct “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 237, 'talk': 'People from outside cannot enter, from inside cannot exit. I will visit the valley at irregular intervals to inspect the work. A plan for the defeat of Sima Yi is being prepared here and must be kept a profound secret.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang said, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'The stores of grain are all at Saber Pass, and the labor of transport is very heavy. What can be done?', 'context': 'One day Yang Yi went to Zhuge Liang and said, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 340, 'talk': 'I have had a scheme ready for a long time. The timber that I collected and bought in the Lands of Rivers was for the construction of wooden transport animals to convey grain. It will be very advantageous, as they will require neither food nor water and they can keep on the move day and night without resting.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, smiling, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'From old days till now no one has ever heard of such a device. What excellent plan have you, O Minister, to make such marvelous creatures?', 'context': 'All those within hearing said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'They are being made now after my plans, but they are not yet ready. Here I have the sketches for these mechanical oxen and horses, with all their dimensions written out in full. You may see the details.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 131, 'iend': 164, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is superhuman!', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang then produced a paper, and all the generals crowded round to look at it. They were all greatly astonished and lauded, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'I knew the transportation from the Lands of Rivers was difficult; therefore, I shut the gates and remained on the defensive waiting for the enemy to be starved. With this device, they may never be compelled to retreat for want of food.', 'context': 'This troubled him still more, and he said to his generals, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'Each of you with five hundred troops will goes to the Xie Valley by by−roads. When you see the Shu soldiers transport their grain by, you are to let them through, but only to attack at the end and capture four or five of the wooden horses and bullocks.', 'context': 'Then he called up Zhang Hu and Yue Chen and gave orders: “'},
{'istart': 287, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'animals', 'context': 'So a thousand soldiers went on this service disguised as soldiers of Shu. They made their way along the by−ways by night and hid. Presently the wooden convoy came along under the escort of Gao Xiang. Just as the end of it was passing, they made a sudden rush, and captured a few of the “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'If Zhuge Liang can use this sort of thing, it would be strange if I could not,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 384, 'iend': 391, 'talk': 'animals', 'context': "He called to him many clever craftspeople and made them then and there take the machines to pieces and make some exactly like them. In less than half a month, they had completed a couple of thousand after Zhuge Liang's models, and the new mechanical animals could move. Then Sima Yi placed Cen Wei, General Who Guards the Frontiers, in charge of this new means of transport, and the “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'I wished him to capture some of them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'I am just laying out these few, and before long I shall get some very solid help in exchange.', 'context': ' said Zhuge Liang, much pleased. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'How do you know, O Minister,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Because Sima Yi will certainly copy them; and when he has done that, I have another plan ready to play on him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Exactly as I thought,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 747, 'talk': 'Dress up a thousand soldiers as those of Wei, and find your way quickly and secretly to Beiyuan. Tell them that you are escort for the convoy, and mingle with the real escort. Then suddenly turn on them so that they scatter. Next you will turn the herd this way. By and by you will be pursued. When that occurs, you will give a turn to the tongues of the wooden animals, and they will be locked from movement. Leave them where they are and run away. When the soldiers of Wei come up, they will be unable to drag the creatures and equally unable to carry them. I shall have soldiers ready, and you will go back with them, give the tongues a backward turn and bring the convoy here, The enemy will be greatly astonished.', 'context': 'Calling Wang Ping, he said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 568, 'talk': 'Dress up five hundred soldiers in the costume of the Deities of the Six Layers so that they appear supernatural. Fit them with demon heads and wild beast shapes, and let them stain their faces various colors so as to look as strange as possible. Give them flags and swords and bottle−gourds with smoke issuing from combustibles inside. Let these soldiers hide among the hills till the convoy approaches, when they will start the smoke, rush out suddenly and drive off the wooden animals. No one will dare pursue such uncanny company.', 'context': 'Next he called Zhang Ni and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'You will take ten thousand troops, go to the border of Beiyuan to receive the wooden transport creatures and defend them against attack.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'Wang Ping is here!', 'context': 'The newcomers joined up with his own troops. But before they had gone much farther, there was a yell, and the men of Shu began to kill, while a voice shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'Truly these are supernatural helpers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 141, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'Zhang Yi and Liao Hua, Generals of Han', 'context': 'road, just where it was most precipitous, a cohort burst out upon him with fierce yells and bursting bombs. Upon the leading banner he read “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'The enemy think we shall be fatigued after a long march and have not troubled to prepare any defense; we should attack this night, and we shall overcome them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'What you say accords with my own ideas,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 309, 'talk': 'I must write to the Emperor to abandon the siege of Xincheng, that the army may be employed to cut off the retreat of the Wei army while I will attack them in front. They will be harassed by the double danger, and we shall break them.', 'context': 'When the report come to Lu Xun, he called together his officers and said, “'},
{'istart': 274, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'This Lu Xun of East Wu is really very resourceful.', 'context': 'All agreed that this was a good plan, and the memorial was drafted. It was sent by the hand of a junior officer, who was told to convey it secretly. But this messenger was captured at the ferry and taken before the Ruler of Wei, who read the dispatch, saying, with a sigh, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Why delay? If you think it best to retire, it had better be done quickly.', 'context': 'Zhuge Jin replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 328, 'talk': 'My army must retreat slowly, or the enemy will come in pursuit, which will mean defeat and loss. Now you must first prepare your ships as if you meant to resist, while I make a semblance of an attack toward Xiangyang. Under cover of these operations we shall withdraw into the South Land, and the enemy will not dare to follow.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'This Lu Xun is very crafty; keep careful guard, but do not risk a battle.', 'context': 'So he called his officers together and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 183, 'talk': 'Lu Xun knows the art of war even as did Sun Zi and Wu Qi. The subjugation of the southeast is not for me this time.', 'context': 'When he thus knew it was true, he consoled himself with the words, “'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 363, 'talk': 'These soldiers of Shu have despoiled us of much grain, and now they are mingling with the people of Qishan and tilling the fields along the banks of River Wei as if they intended to remain there. This would be a calamity for us. Why do you not appoint a time to fight a decisive battle with Zhuge Liang?', 'context': "Then Sima Yi's son, Sima Shi, went to his father and said, “"},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 103, 'talk': "I have the Emperor's orders to act on the defensive and may not do as you suggest.", 'context': 'His father replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': "The Holy One says: 'If one cannot suffer small things, great matters are imperiled.' Our plan is to defend.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Also, set up a seven−star signal at the mouth of the valley and arrange a night signal of seven lamps on the hill.', 'context': 'wood,” said Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 458, 'talk': 'Go to the camp of Wei with five hundred troops and provoke them to battle. The important matter is to entice Sima Yi out of his stronghold. You will be unable to obtain a victory, so retreat that he may pursue; and you are to make for the signal, the seven stars by day or the seven lamps at night. Thus you will lead him into the Gourd Valley, where I have a plan prepared for him.', 'context': 'After Ma Dai had gone, Wei Yan was called in, and Zhuge Liang said to him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'Take small herds, forty or fifty at a time, of the wooden oxen and running horses, load them up with grain and lead them to and fro on the mountains. If you can succeed in getting the enemy to capture them, you will render a service.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'The enemy have set out camps and are engaged in field work as though they intended to remain. If they are not destroyed now, but are allowed to consolidate their position, they will be hard to dislodge.', 'context': 'Xiahou Hui and Xiahou He went to their chief, Sima Yi, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': "This certainly is one of Zhuge Liang's ruses,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'You seem very afraid of him, General,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 200, 'talk': "When do you think you can destroy him? At least let us two brothers fight one battle that we may prove our gratitude for the Emperor's kindness.", 'context': ' retorted they. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'If it must be so, then you may go in two divisions,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 221, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister understood that you would not fight, and so had told off the soldiers to various places to work in the fields and thus provide for future needs. We had been unwittingly captured.', 'context': 'They told him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Why spare them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Where is Zhuge Liang now?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'He is no longer at Qishan, but in camp about three miles from the Gourd Valley. He is gathering a great store of grain there.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is not camped on Qishan, but near the Gourd Valley. Tomorrow you shall attack the Qishan camp, and I will command the reserve.', 'context': 'Calling together his officers, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': "Father, why do you intend to attack the enemy's rear?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Sima Yi, stay!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 162, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'Not a single Shu soldier is seen but a many straw houses on the hills.', 'context': 'Presently Wei Yan and his troops entered the mouth of the valley. Sima Yi halted a time while he sent forward a few scouts, but when they returned and reported: “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'This must be the store valley!', 'context': 'Sima Yi rode in, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'Supposing soldiers seize the entrance; what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'My sons, we three are doomed!', 'context': 'Sima Yi, scared and helpless, dismounted, clasped his arms about his two sons and wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'If we do not break out now, what better chance shall we have?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Human proposes; God disposes. We cannot wrest events to our will.', 'context': 'Soon after, the scouts reported the escape of his victims, and he sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'The enemy have been carefully spying out the country and are certainly selecting a new position for a camp.', 'context': 'Guo Huai went to the general to talk over plans. He said, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'If Zhuge Liang goes out to Wugong Hills, and thence eastward, we shall be in grave danger; if he goes southwest by River Wei, and halts on the Wuzhang Hills, we need feel no anxiety.', 'context': 'Sima Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Our great Emperor of Wei has remarkable fortune,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'So he regards me as a deer,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister works very hard,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Indeed, he eats little and works much,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Can he last long?', 'context': ' remarked Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 106, 'talk': "I told him that you ate little and worked long hours, and then he said, 'Can he last long?' That was all.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'He knows,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'I notice,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I know; I cannot but know,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'But this heavy responsibility was laid upon me, and I fear no other will be so devoted as I am.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang. “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 219, 'talk': 'We are reputable generals of the army of a great state; how can we put up with such insults from these soldiers of Shu? We pray you let us fight them.', 'context': 'They wished to avenge the taunt, and went to their general, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'It is not that I fear to go out,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 145, 'talk': "nor that I relish the insults, but I have the Emperor's command to hold on and may not disobey.", 'context': ' said Sima Yi, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'I will send your request to the Throne in a memorial; what think you of that?', 'context': 'The officers were not in the least appeased. Wherefore Sima Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Noble Sir, you interpreted my own desire correctly.', 'context': 'Sima Yi said to Xin Pi, “'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 533, 'talk': "This is only Sima Yi's method of pacifying his army. He has never had any intention of fighting and requested the edict to justify his strategy. It is well known that a general in the field takes no command from any person, not even his own king. Is it likely that he would send a thousand miles to ask permission to fight if that was all he needed? The officers were bitter, and so Sima Yi got the Emperor to assist him in maintaining discipline. All this is meant to slacken our soldiers.", 'context': 'When it was told to Zhuge Liang, he said, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 468, 'talk': 'The Ruler of Wei, Cao Rui, hearing that Wu has invaded his country at three points, has led a great army to Hefei and sent three other armies under Man Chong, Tian Du, and Liu Shao, to oppose the invaders. The stores and fight−material of Wu have been burned, and the army of Wu have fallen victims to sickness. A letter from Lu Xun containing a scheme of attack fell into the hands of the enemy, and the Ruler of Wu has marched back into his own country.', 'context': 'He replied, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'My mind is all in confusion. This is a return of my old illness, and I am doomed.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'My life may end at any moment.', 'context': 'He returned and said to Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Why do you say such a thing?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 197, 'talk': 'Just now in the Triumvirate constellation the Guest Star was twice as bright as usual, while the Host Star was darkened; the supporting stars were also obscure. With such an aspect I know my fate.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'If the aspect be as malignant as you say, why not pray in order to avert it?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'I am in the habit of praying,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 504, 'talk': 'but I know not the will of God. However, prepare me forty−nine guards and let each have a black flag. Dress them in black and place them outside my tent. Then will I from within my tent invoke the Seven Stars of the North. If my master−lamp remain alight for seven days, then is my life to be prolonged for twelve years. If the lamp goes out, then I am to die. Keep all idlers away from the tent and let a couple of guards bring me what is necessary.', 'context': ' replied Zhuge Liang, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 793, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang, born into an age of trouble, would willingly have grown old in retirement. But His Majesty, Liu Bei the Glorious Emperor, sought him thrice and confided to him the heavy responsibility of guarding his son. He dared not do less than spend himself to the utmost in such a task, and he pledged himself to destroy the rebels. Suddenly the star of his leadership has declined, and his life now nears its close. He has humbly indited a declaration on this silk piece to the Great Unknowable and now hopes that He will graciously listen and extend the number of his days that he may prove his gratitude to his prince and be the savior of the people, restore the old state of the empire and establish eternally the Han sacrifices. He dares not make a vain prayer; this is from his heart.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 377, 'talk': 'A leadership star has just lost position; surely Zhuge Liang is ill and will soon die. Take a reconnoitering party to the Wuzhang Hills and find out. If you see signs of confusion do not attack; it means that Zhuge Liang is ill. I shall take the occasion to smite hard.', 'context': 'One night as he sat gazing up at the sky and studying its aspect, he suddenly turned to Xiahou Ba, saying, “'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'The Wei soldiers are upon us!', 'context': 'Suddenly a great shouting was heard outside, and immediately Wei Yan dashed in, crying, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Life and death are foreordained; no prayers can alter them.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang threw down the sword and sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'It is my fate; not his fault.', 'context': 'The unhappy Wei Yan did not suffer the edge of the sword, for Zhuge Liang stayed the stroke, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Sima Yi thinks I am dead, and he sent these few troops to make sure. Go ye and drive them off,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 524, 'talk': 'My death is very near. My chief desire has been to spend myself to the utmost to restore the Hans and lead a glorious return of the Hans to their capital, but Heaven decrees it otherwise. I have never ceased from my studies. I have written a book in twenty−four chapters, 104,112 words, treating the Eight Needfuls, the Seven Cautions, the Six Fears, and the Five Dreads of war. But among all those about me there is no one fit to receive it and carry on my work save you. I pray you not to despise it.', 'context': 'Zhuge Liang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'I have also a plan for a multiple crossbow, which I have been unable to execute. The weapon shoots ten bolts of eight inches length at every discharge. The sketches are quite ready, and the weapons can be made according to them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 230, 'talk': 'There is no part of Shu that causes anxiety, save the Yinping Mountains. That must be carefully guarded. It is protected naturally by its lofty precipices, but it will surely be the cause of great losses.', 'context': 'The dying man continued, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'You are to follow out my instructions after my death.', 'context': 'Next Zhuge Liang sent for Ma Dai, to whom he gave certain whispered instructions, and then said, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'After my death, Wei Yan will turn traitor. When that happens and the army is in danger, you will find herein what to do.', 'context': 'As Zhuge Liang gave it to him, he said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 511, 'talk': "Unhappily I am dying and leaving my task incomplete. I am injuring my country's policy and am in fault to the world. After my death you must aid the Emperor in perfect loyalty, and see that the old policy is continued, and the rules of government maintained. Do not lightly cast out the people I have employed. My plans of campaign have been confided to Jiang Wei, who can continue my policy for the service of the state. But my hour draws near, and I must write my testament.", 'context': 'Zhuge Liang wept, and he replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'I shall never again lead the army against the rebels,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'O Azure Heaven, when will this regret end?', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 452, 'talk': 'To my household belong eight hundred mulberry trees and a hundred acres of land; thus there is ample provision for my family. While I have been employed in the service of the state, my needs have been supplied from official sources, but I have not contrived to make any additions to the family estate. At my death I shall not leave any increased possessions, even an excess roll of silk, that may cause Your Majesty to suspect that I have wronged you.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 433, 'talk': 'Let the army retreat, beginning with the rearmost division; send it away slowly, one camp at a time. If Sima Yi pursues, array the army and offer battle, turn to meet him and beat the attack. Let him approach till he is very near and then suddenly display the wooden image of myself that I have had carved, seated in my chariot in the midst of the army, with the generals right and left as usual. And you will frighten Sima Yi away.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'That is my star,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'I have foiled the great designs of the state.', 'context': 'When the anxiety caused by this state of coma was at its height, Li Fu arrived. He wept when he saw the condition of the great leader, crying, “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'I know your mission,', 'context': "However, presently Zhuge Liang's eyes reopened and fell upon Li Fu standing near his couch. “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'I came with the royal command to ask also who should control the destinies of the state for the next century,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 128, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'In my agitation I forgot to ask that.', 'context': ' replied Li Fu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'After me, Jiang Wan is the most fitting man to deal with great matters.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'And after Jiang Wan?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'After him, Fei Yi.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Who is next after Fei Yi?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'The Master is no more.', 'context': 'This message gave, “'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Then, after all, I am but a barbarian.', 'context': "When Liao Li heard of Zhuge Liang's death, he shed tears and said, “"},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is dead.', 'context': 'He was pleased and excited, and said to those about him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Zhuge Liang is a master of mysteries; he can get aids from the Deities of the Six Layers; and it may be that this is but a ruse to get us to take the field. We may fall victims to his guile.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'It is an auspicious dream. Dragon and Linlion both have horns on the head. It augurs transformation into an ascending creature.', 'context': 'Zhao Zhi thought a moment and replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 202, 'talk': 'From the camp of our friend Wei Yan. He dreamed that he grew horns upon his head, and I have given him an auspicious interpretation. But really it is inauspicious. However, I did not wish to annoy him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'How do you know it is inauspicious?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 148, 'talk': "The word for horn is composed of two parts, 'knife' above and 'use' below, and so means that there is a knife upon his head. It is a terrible omen.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'Keep it secret,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister died last night in the third watch. He left certain final orders, and among them, that you are to command the rearguard to keep Sima Yi at bay while the army retreats. No mourning is to be worn. Here is your authority, so you can march forthwith.', 'context': 'Then Fei Yi went to the camp of Wei Yan, and when they were alone, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Who is acting in place of the late minister?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'The chief command has been delegated to Yang Yi, but the secret plans of campaign have been entrusted to Jiang Wei. This authority was issued from Yang Yi.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 370, 'talk': 'Though the Prime Minister is dead, I am yet alive. The Military Counselor Yang Yi is only a civil officer and unequal to this post. He ought to conduct the coffin home while I lead the army against Sima Yi. I shall achieve success, and it is wrong to abandon a whole plan of campaign because of the death of one man, even if that be the Prime Minister.', 'context': 'Wei Yan replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': "The Prime Minister's orders were to retire, and these orders are to be obeyed.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'If the Prime Minister had listened to me, we should now have been at Changan. I am the General Who Conquers the West and Lord of Nanzheng. I am not going to act as rearguard for any civil official,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'It may be as you say, General, but you must not do anything to make us ridiculous. Let me go back to Yang Yi and explain, and I may be able to persuade him to pass on to you the supreme military authority he holds.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 257, 'talk': 'When near death the Prime Minister confided to me that Wei Yan would turn traitor. I sent him the authority to test him, and now he has discovered himself as the Prime Minister foretold. So I will direct Jiang Wei to command the rearguard.', 'context': 'Yang Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei is covering the retreat, and that most of the army has already gone.', 'context': 'Ma Dai returned and told him: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'How dare he play with me, the pedantic blockhead?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'But he shall die for this.', 'context': ' cried he. “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Will you help me?', 'context': 'Turning to Ma Dai, Wei Yan said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'I have long hated Yang Yi; certainly I am ready to attack him.', 'context': 'Ma Dai replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Then Zhuge Liang is really dead; let us pursue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Be cautious,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Send an subordinate leader first.', 'context': ' said Xiahou Ba. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'No; I must go myself this time.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 229, 'iend': 280, 'talk': 'Prime Minister of Han, Lord of Wuxiang, Zhuge Liang', 'context': 'and pressed on still harder. Then suddenly a bomb exploded, a great shout broke the stillness, and the retiring army turned about and came toward him, ready for battle. In their midst fluttered a great banner bearing the words, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Then Zhuge Liang is still alive!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'And I have rashly placed myself in his power.', 'context': ' gasped Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 168, 'talk': "Do not try to run away, O rebel; you have fallen into one of the Prime Minister's traps and would better stay!", 'context': 'As he pulled round his horse to flee, Jiang Wei shouted, “'},
{'istart': 334, 'iend': 354, 'talk': 'Have I still a head?', 'context': 'The soldiers, seized with panic, fled, throwing off all their gear. They trampled each other down, and many perished. Their leader galloped fifteen miles without pulling rein. When at last two of his generals came up with him, and had stopped his flying steed by catching at the bridle, Sima Yi clapped his hand to his head, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'Do not fear, General, the soldiers of Shu are now far away,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 351, 'talk': "The Shu army had really gone, and as soon as the retiring army entered the valley, they raised a wailing for the dead and hoisted white flags. Zhuge Liang was really dead, and Jiang Wei's rearguard consisted of only one thousand troops. The figure in the carriage was only a wooden image of the Prime Minister.", 'context': 'In a few days the natives brought news: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'While he lived, I could guess what he would do; dead, I was helpless,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'We can now sleep in comfort.', 'context': 'As he took the homeward road, he said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Truly a wonderful genius?', 'context': 'As they marched back, they saw the camps of their enemies, and were amazed at their skillful arrangement. “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'Just before his death the Prime Minister foretold that this man would one day turn traitor, and here it has come to pass. I did not expect to meet it thus, but now our road of retreat is cut, and what is to be done?', 'context': 'Then said Yang Yi, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 283, 'talk': 'He certainly has slandered us to the Emperor and said that we were rebelling, and therefore he has destroyed the wooden roads in order to prevent our progress first; therefore, we must memorialize to the Throne the truth about him and then plan his destruction.', 'context': 'Then replied Fei Yi, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'I know a by−way hereabout that will lead us round to the rear of these covered roads. True it is precipitous and dangerous, but it will take us to our destination. It is called the Chashan Mountain Path.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei said, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 243, 'talk': "Last night I saw a large red star fall from the northeast to the southwest; surely it forebodes a misfortune to the First Minister. Your Majesty's dream corresponds to what I saw.", 'context': 'When he had related his dream, Qiao Zhou stood forth and said, “'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'The Prime Minister is dead.', 'context': 'Li Fu bowed his head and wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Heaven smites me!', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler was overcome with great sorrow, and wailed, crying, “'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Wei Yan is a valiant warrior and could easily have overcome Yang Yi; why then did he destroy the Plank Trail?', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler said, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 574, 'talk': 'The First Ruler used to say that Zhuge Liang knew that treachery lurked in the heart of Wei Yan, and he wished to put Wei Yan to death; he only spared Wei Yan because of his valor. We should not believe too readily this tale of his that Yang Yi has rebelled. Yang Yi is a scholar and a civil officer, and the late Prime Minister placed him in a position of great responsibility, thereby proving that he trusted and valued Yang Yi. If we believe this statement, surely Yang Yi will be forced to go over to Wei. Nothing should be done without due meditation.', 'context': 'Empress Wu said, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'What is your opinion now?', 'context': 'The Empress Dowager listened to the end. Then, turning to the officers, she said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 781, 'talk': "Yang Yi is hasty and intolerant, but he has rendered great services in supplying the army. He has long been a trusted colleague of the late Prime Minister, who, being near his end, entrusted to him the conduct of affairs. Certainly he is no rebel. On the other hand, Wei Yan is bold and ambitious and thinks himself everybody's superior. Yang Yi is the only one who has openly been of different opinion, and hence Wei Yan hates him. When he saw Yang Yi placed over his head in command of the army, Wei Yan refused his support. Then Wei Yan burned the Plank Trail in order to cut off Yang Yi's retreat, and maligned him, hoping to bring about his fall. I am ready to guarantee Yang Yi's fealty to the extent of my whole house, but I would not answer for Wei Yan.", 'context': 'Jiang Wan replied, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 384, 'talk': "Wei Yan has always been conceited and discontented. His mouth was full of hate and resentment, and only fear of the late Prime Minister held him in check. The Prime Minister's death gave him his opportunity, and he turned traitor. This is certainly the true state of the case. Yang Yi is able, and his employment by the late Prime Minister is proof of his loyalty.", 'context': 'Dong Yun followed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'If this is true and Wei Yan is really a rebel, what should be done?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 386, 'talk': 'I think the late Prime Minister has framed some scheme by which to get rid of Wei Yan. If Yang Yi had not felt secure, he would scarcely have set out to return through the valleys. Your Majesty may feel sure that Wei Yan will fall into some trap. We have received, almost at the same time, two memorials from two men, each bringing against the other a charge of rebellion. Let us wait.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Where is that rebel Wei Yan?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'You aided that traitor Yang Yi;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'how dare you abuse me?', 'context': ' cried Wei Yan, no way backward with his tongue, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 101, 'talk': "You rebelled immediately after the late chief's death, before even his body was cold. How could you?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Will you really help me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'I will surely remember you in the day of success.', 'context': ' said Wei Yan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'What if we go over to Wei?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I think your words unwise,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 429, 'talk': 'Why should we join anyone? A really strong person would try to carve out his own fortune and not be ready to crook the knee to another. You are able enough and brave enough to be more than a match for any leader in the Lands of Rivers. No one would dare to stand up to you. I pledge myself to go with you to the seizure of Hanzhong, and thence we will attack the Western Land of Rivers.', 'context': ' said Ma Dai. “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Surrender!', 'context': 'As they drew near, both Wei Yan and Ma Dai shouted out, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Wei Yan is valorous, and he is having the help of Ma Dai. How shall we repel them?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'To be opened when Wei Yan is actually arrayed opposite you.', 'context': 'So Yang Yi opened the bag and drew forth the letter it held. On the cover he read, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'As this has all been arranged for, I would better go out, and when his line is formed then you can come forth.', 'context': 'Said Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'Rebel Wei Yan, the late Prime Minister never harmed you; why have you turned traitor?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 187, 'talk': 'Listen, you old fool! While Zhuge Liang lived I feared him somewhat. But he is dead and no one dares stand before me. I will not only shout the words thrice, but a myriad times. Why not?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Who dares kill me?', 'context': 'Wei Yan raised his sword, shook his bridle, and shouted, “'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I dare kill you!', 'context': 'He never finished. Behind him someone shouted savagely, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'When nearing his end, the Prime Minister commanded that he should be buried on Dingjun Mountain, in open ground, without sacrifice or monument.', 'context': 'Then Fei Yi said to the Latter Ruler, “'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'Here is Wu breaking their oath just as the Prime Minister has died,', 'context': 'with a large army from Wu and camped at the entrance to Baqiu. No one knew the object of this expedition. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'The envoy must have a ready tongue,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'Wu and Shu are one house; why has your master increased the guard at Baidicheng?', 'context': "But Sun Quan's countenance wore a look of anger, and he said, “"},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'It seemed as necessary for the west to increase the garrison there as for the east to have a force at Baqiu. Neither is worth asking about.', 'context': 'Zong Yu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'As an envoy you seem no way inferior to Deng Zhi,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'I would not go back upon the pledge between us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'I have been sent to inform you of the mourning for the late Prime Minister.', 'context': 'Zong Yu said, “'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'If I betray my oath, may my posterity be cut off!', 'context': 'Sun Quan took up a gold−tipped arrow and snapped it in twain, saying, “'},
{'istart': 153, 'iend': 430, 'talk': 'The Ruler of Wu has wept for our Prime Minister and put his court into mourning. The increased garrison at Baqiu is intended to safeguard us from Wei, lest they take the occasion of a public sorrow to attack. And in token of his pledge, the Ruler of Wu broke an arrow in twain.', 'context': 'Zong Yu and the envoy took leave of the Ruler of Wu and journeyed to Chengdu, where they went to the Latter Ruler, and Zong Yu made a memorial, saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'If when the Prime Minister died I had gone over to Wei, with the whole army, I should not have been thus left out in the cold.', 'context': 'He said to Fei Yi, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 243, 'talk': 'Yang Yi had followed the late Prime Minister in many campaigns and had had many good services. Your Majesty should not put him to death, but take away his rank.', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler intended putting him to death, but Jiang Wan interceded, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'Thy servant has eight sons, who will be a burden to Your Majesty after his death. I cannot say with what trepidation I await my fate.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'Has the man no fear of death?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'I have built high terraces and lofty towers with intent to hold intercourse with gods and goddesses, that I may obtain from them the elixir of life.', 'context': 'Then Cao Rui summoned his Master of Works, Ma Jun, and said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 621, 'talk': 'Of the four and twenty emperors of the line of Latter Han, only Emperor Wu enjoyed the throne very long and really attained to old age. That was because he drank of the essence of the brilliancy of the sun and the brightness of the moon. In the Palace at Changan is the Terrace of Cypress Beams, upon which stands the bronze figure of a man holding up a Dew Bowl, whereinto distills, in the third watch of the night, the vapor from the great constellation of the north. This liquid is called Celestial Elixir, or Sweet Dew. If mingled with powdered jade and swallowed, it restores youth to the aged.', 'context': 'Then Ma Jun replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Take workers to Changan immediately and bring hither the bronze figure to set up in the Fragrant Forest Park,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Where is the pedestal?', 'context': 'However, the bronze figure and the golden bowl were conveyed to Luoyang and presented to the Emperor. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 30, 'talk': 'It is too heavy to transport,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'It weighs a million and half of pounds.', 'context': ' replied the Ma Jun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 346, 'talk': 'The prince is the first and the head; his ministers are his limbs; they live or die together, they are involved in the same destruction. Though I am timorous, yet if I dared forget my duty, or failed to speak firmly, I should be unable to move Your Majesty. Now I have prepared my coffin and bathed my body ready for the most condign punishment.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'Why not invite the Empress?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'If she came, nothing would pass my lips,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Yesterday Your Majesty was walking in the north garden, and you had plenty of music too,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'I had forbidden you to tell things to the Empress, and you disobeyed my command.', 'context': 'Cao Rui was wroth and sent for all the attendants. He upbraided them with disobedience, saying, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'My lord, the central authorities have treated you well and honored you. I fear that Sima Yi is too skillful a leader for rebellion to succeed. You see even Zhuge Liang cannot defeat him; how much less can you?', 'context': 'One general, Jia Fan, opposed this and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 871, 'talk': "Jia Fan spoke well. The Sacred One says that extraordinary phenomena presage the destruction of a state. Now this time portents are not wanting, and wonders have been seen. A dog, dressed in red and wearing a turban, went up to the roof and walking like a man. Moreover, while a certain person living in a village south of the city was cooking his food, he saw a child in the pan, boiled to death. A great cave opened near the market place and threw out a large, fleshy body completely human save that it lacked limbs. Swords could not cut it; arrows could not penetrate it. No one knew what to call it; and when they consulted the soothsayers, they obtained the reply, 'Incomplete shape, silent mouth: a state is near destruction.' These prodigies are all inauspicious. Flee from evil and strive to walk in fair fortune's way. Make no move without most careful thought.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'My forty thousand troops will be equal to the task.', 'context': 'Sima Yi was not greatly perturbed, and said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'The task is heavy, for your troops are few and the road is long.', 'context': 'The Ruler of Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': "What do you think will be the rebel's plan?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 111, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'How long will the expedition take?', 'context': 'in Liaodong; his low plan would be to try to hold Xiangping. In the last case I shall certainly capture him.” “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'Suppose during that year we are attacked by Wu or Shu.', 'context': 'another hundred. The return will need a hundred, and with sixty days to rest we shall take a year.” “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'My plans provide for that; Your Majesty need have no anxiety.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'So the rebel does not want to fight, but thinks to weary my soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 336, 'talk': 'Now I am disposed to think that most of his army is within that wall, so that his stronghold is empty and undefended. I will make a dash at Xiangping. He will have to go to its rescue, and I will smite him on the way. I should score a great success.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 109, 'iend': 224, 'talk': 'They are going to attack Xiangping, which they know has few troops. If that base be lost, this position is useless.', 'context': 'Presently the scouts reported that the Wei army had marched south. Bei Yan at once saw the danger and said, “'},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'Now they will fall into the snare I have laid for them.', 'context': 'When Sima Yi heard it, he rejoiced, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'How can the army move away just when success is in sight? The rebels will be conquered now any day; and if any other speaks about drawing off, he will be put to death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 107, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'The soldiers are suffering from the rains. O Commander, let them camp on the hills.', 'context': 'Soon after, Chou Lian, Commander of the Right, came to see his chief and repeated the suggestion, saying, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'I have sent the command, and you are against it.', 'context': 'Sima Yi got angry and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'Sir,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 612, 'talk': 'I see you are ignorant of war after all. You do not understand the different conditions. Meng Da then had ample supplies and few troops; we were under exactly opposite conditions, and so we had to attack vigorously and at once. The suddenness of the attack defeated the enemy. But look at present conditions. The Liaodong troops are many and we few; they are on the verge of starvation, and we are full fed. Why should we force the attack? Our line is to let the soldiers desert and capture the city. Therefore I leave a gate open and the road free that they may run away.', 'context': ' replied the Commander−in−Chief, “'},
{'istart': 139, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'In Liaodong the rain has been continuous for a month, and the soldiers are in misery. Sima Yi ought to be recalled, and the war renewed at a more convenient season.', 'context': 'However, the war was not supported in the capital, for when the messenger arrived and the Ruler of Wei summoned his courtiers, they said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'The leader of our army is most capable and best able to decide upon what should be done. He understands the conditions and is teeming with magnificent plans. He will certainly succeed. Wherefore, Noble Sirs, wait a few days and let us not be anxious about the result.', 'context': 'The Ruler of Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Five days from now Gongsun Yuan will be slain where that star fell,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Therefore attack with vigor.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'We pray you, O Regent Marshal, retire seven miles and allow the officers to come forth and surrender.', 'context': 'Wang Jian and Liu Fu found their way to Sima Yi and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'Why did not Gongsun Yuan himself come?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'He is rude.', 'context': ' said Sima Yi. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'I pray you, O Regent Marshal, turn your thunderous wrath from us; we will send the son of our leader, Gongsun Xiu, the Heir Apparent, as hostage and all the officers shall appear before you bound with cords.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'There are five possible operations for any army. If you can fight, fight; if you cannot fight, defend; if you cannot defend, flee; if you cannot flee, surrender; if you cannot surrender, die. These five courses are open to you, and a hostage would be useless. Now return and tell your master.', 'context': 'Sima Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'Stop, O rebel!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'That night the star fell to this land, and today, five days later, the omen becomes true.', 'context': 'Sima Yi hardly looked at the two men, but he turned to his officers and said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'The Regent Marshal is superhuman!', 'context': 'They all felicitated him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Jia Fan and Lun Zhi had been against the revolt and had therefore suffered death.', 'context': 'Certain persons told him, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 168, 'talk': 'Who of the family is a suitable person to support the Heir Apparent?', 'context': 'The Ruler of Wei then turned to his two confidants, Liu Fang and Sun Zi, inquired of them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'None is so fit as Cao Shuang, the son of Cao Zhen.', 'context': 'As Liu Fang and Sun Zi had both received many favors from Cao Zhen, they replied, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'As Cao Shuang has been chosen, Cao Yu, the Prince of Yan, should be ordered to leave the capital and return to Yan, his own place.', 'context': 'Then Liu Fang and Sun Zi memorialized, saying, “'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 230, 'talk': "The edict in the Emperor's own hand bids you return to your own domain at once, and you are not to return to court without a special command.", 'context': 'The Ruler of Wei consented and issued an edict, which these two bore to Cao Yu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I feared lest I should not see you again;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'but now I can die content.', 'context': ' said the Ruler of Wei, “'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'On the road they told me the sacred person was not perfectly well; I grieved that I had not wings to hasten hither. But I am happy in that I now behold the dragon countenance.', 'context': 'The general bowed and said, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'My friend Sima Yi is as myself, and you are to treat him with the same respect and deference.', 'context': 'Turning to the young prince, he continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'Never forget the affection he has just shown,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 463, 'iend': 476, 'talk': 'Bag of Wisdom', 'context': 'Cao Shuang was no stranger at court. Cao Rui had respected him for his diligence and care and had been very fond of him, He had had the freedom of the palace all his life. He had a host of five hundred clients and retainers. Among them were five wholly light and foppish. Their names were He Yan, Deng Yang, Li Sheng, Ding Mi, and Bi Gui. Beside these five there was another named Huan Fan, Minister of Agriculture, a man of good parts, who had the sobriquet of “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'My lord, you should not let your great powers slip into the hands of any other, or you will repent it.', 'context': 'One day He Yan said, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 106, 'talk': "Sima Yi as well as I received the late Emperor's sacred trust, and I mean to be true.", 'context': 'Cao Shuang replied, “'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'Sima Yi should be promoted to the rank of Guardian of the Throne for his great merits and services.', 'context': 'to the Ruler of Wei a memorial, saying, “'},
{'istart': 225, 'iend': 346, 'talk': 'You call yourself a skillful diviner, but your speech does not resemble the language of the Book of Changes. How is that?', 'context': "Now He Yan heard of Guan Lu's great skill in divination and sent to Pingyuan to invite him to discuss about the Book of Changes. When the soothsayer arrived, Deng Yang was of the company to meet him, and he said to Guan Lu, “"},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'An interpreter does not use the language of the original.', 'context': 'Guan Lu replied, “'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 723, 'talk': 'Gao Kai and Gao Yuan aided King Shun; Duke Zhou assisted the young Emperor Cheng of Zhou Dynasty; all these were kindly and modest and enjoyed great happiness. You, Sir, have come to high honors and wield great powers, but those who esteem you are few and those who fear you, many. You are not careful to walk in the way of good fortune. Now the nose is an eminence. If an eminence retains its characteristic, thereby it remains in honor; But is it not that blue flies gather to foul objects and the lofty fears a fall? I would wish you to give of your abundance for the good of the poor and avoid walking in the wrong road. Then indeed may you reach the highest dignity, and the blue flies will disperse.', 'context': 'Guan Lu replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'This is mere senile gossip,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'The gift of age is to see that which is yet to come; the gift of gossip is to perceive what is not said,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'He is very mad, really,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Why did you anger them? They are too powerful for you to offend.', 'context': 'was alarmed at the probable consequences, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 60, 'talk': 'What is there to fear? I have keen talking to two dead men.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'What do you mean?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 172, 'talk': 'You are in an exalted position and yet you are constantly being out hunting. If anyone took advantage of this to work you evil, you might have to be exceedingly regretful.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'The whole military authority is in my hands and what is there to fear?', 'context': 'Cao Shuang only showed anger and replied, “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 123, 'talk': "This is Cao Shuang's wish to find out my real condition.", 'context': 'Sima Yi saw through the device at once and told his sons, saying, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 244, 'talk': 'It is a long time since I have seen you, and I did not know you were so seriously ill. His Majesty is sending me to Qingzhou, and I have come to pay my respects to you and bid you farewell.', 'context': 'Li Sheng came in and went up to the sick man, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'Ah; Bingzhou is in the north; you will have to be very careful there,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'I am going as Governor of Qingzhou, not Bingzhou,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'Oh, you have just come from Bingzhou.', 'context': ' said Li Sheng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'Qingzhou, in Huashang Mountains.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Just back from Qingzhou, eh?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'How very ill the Imperial Guardian is!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'The Minister is deaf,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Give me paper and a pen,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'My illness has made me very deaf; take care of yourself on the way,', 'context': 'Writing materials were brought, when Li Sheng wrote what he wished to say and put it before his host. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'I am very weak and ill,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'and may die at any moment. My sons are but poor things, but you will instruct them; and when you see the Regent Marshal, you will ask him to take care of them for me, will you not?', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'If the old man died, I should not be the one to grieve,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 90, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'Li Sheng will take a full account of this to Cao Shuang, who will not fear me any more. But wait till Cao Shuang goes on his next hunting trip, and we will see what can be done.', 'context': 'But no sooner had Cao Shuang gone than Sima Yi rose from his couch and said to his sons, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'Your Lordship are in charge of the capital security, and you and your brothers should not leave the city together. Suppose there were a revolt, what then?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'Who would dare make trouble? Hold your wild tongue.', 'context': 'But Cao Shuang asked angrily and rudely, “'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 247, 'talk': 'Cao Shuang has betrayed the trust placed in him by the late Emperor and has ruined the government. His fault must be expiated.', 'context': 'Having secured his position thus, Sima Yi and his supporters went to the palace of the Empress Dowager and said to her, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'What can be done in the absence of His Majesty?', 'context': 'Empress Guo replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'I have prepared plans for the destruction of these base ministers and will see to it that no trouble happens to yourself.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 198, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'The Master is outside, and Sima Yi is revolting: what does it mean?', 'context': 'Soon the news of the rising came to the knowledge of the family of Cao Shuang, and his wife, Lady Liu, came out from the inner apartments and summoned Pan Ju, Commander of the Gates, and inquired, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Your Ladyship need feel no alarm. Let me go and find out the truth,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Now that this revolt has begun, what should we do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Let us go to the Emperor with what troops we have,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Perhaps the best course,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'His Majesty is out on a hunt, and Sima Yi has closed the gates of the city. This is rebellion.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'I do not think so. He only means to slay Cao Shuang, his rival,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'What will be the outcome of this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Cao Shuang is no match for Sima Yi,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'If Sima Yi asks us to join him, should we?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 108, 'talk': "The Empress's command; open the gate for me.", 'context': 'Huan Fan pulled out from his sleeve a slip of bamboo and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Let me look,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'What! How dare you, an old servant of mine, behave thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': "So the 'Bag of Wisdom' has got away too; that is a pity, but what can we do?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'The old horse always hankers after the old stable and manger, and he would have been useless to us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Although in ill health, as a precautionary measure I have camped at the Floating Bridge, whence I write this.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'In the face of such words what mean you to do?', 'context': 'When they had made an end of reading, the Ruler of Wei turned to Cao Shuang and said, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'What now?', 'context': 'Cao Shuang was at a loss and turned to his younger brother, saying, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 274, 'talk': 'I remonstrated with you, but you were obstinate and listened not. So it has come to this. Sima Yi is false and cunning beyond measure. If Zhuge Liang could not get the better of him, could we hope to do so? I see nothing but to yield that haply we may live.', 'context': 'Cao Xi replied, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'How can we go to another place when all our families are in the city?', 'context': 'Cao Shuang replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Do not hurry me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 68, 'talk': 'Let me think it over carefully.', 'context': ' said Cao Shuang. “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'The Guardian of the Throne desires only to strip the military power of the Regent Marshal. If the Regent Marshal yields, he may return peacefully to the city.', 'context': 'Then came Xu Yun and Chen Tai, the two messengers of Sima Yi, and said, “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'The Imperial Guardian had sworn by River Luo to the singleness of his aim. Here is letter of Minister Jiang Ji. The Regent Marshal should relinquish the military power and return to the palace in peace.', 'context': 'Next arrived Yin Damu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 170, 'talk': 'You are a dead man if you listen to the voice of these people!', 'context': 'When Cao Shuang seemed disposed to accept the assurance of Sima Yi, Huan Fan inveighed against it, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 75, 'talk': 'You have had a whole day and a whole night for reflection and must decide,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'I will not fight; I will yield all; being a wealthy man is enough,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 69, 'talk': 'Cao Zhen might boast of his abilities, but his sons are mere cattle,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'The Imperial Guardian will surely keep faith with me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'What brought you to this?', 'context': 'As Huan Fan approached the bridge, Sima Yi, from horseback, pointed his whip disdainfully at him and said, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'We have but little food left. Let us write and ask for supplies. If Sima Yi sends us food, we may be sure he does not intend harm.', 'context': 'Then Cao Xi said, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'Our lives are safe in the hands of Sima Yi.', 'context': 'They wrote, and a hundred carts of supplies were sent. This cheered them, and Cao Shuang said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 134, 'talk': 'When a person maligns another and is false, the punishment for such a crime as he imputes falls upon his own head.', 'context': 'Then said Sima Yi, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'For whom are you keeping your vow?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'Man is but as the light dust upon the tender grass, and what is the good of mutilating your body?', 'context': ' said they. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 62, 'talk': 'They are righteous people who serves their master faithfully,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'Had I not listened to the advice of my sister, I would have walked in the way of unrighteousness.', 'context': 'Xin Chang sighed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 146, 'talk': 'How could you rebel against the ruling house, you who are of the same clan as our great founder, and you who have always been treated generously?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'My forefathers served the state right well, but who is this Sima Yi that he has put to death my kinspeople and would now destroy me? What is his aim, if it be not to usurp the Throne? If I can cut him off and so frustrate his design, I shall at least be no traitor to the state.', 'context': 'Xiahou Ba replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'In the ancient time Wei Zi left the court of Zhou in disgust, and this act has assured to him everlasting honor. You may be able now to assist in the restoration of the House of Han, and you will then stand no whit inferior to any person of antiquity.', 'context': 'Said Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 141, 'talk': 'The Simas are now most powerful and in a position to carry out any scheme they planned. Think you that they have any intentions against Shu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 256, 'talk': 'The old traitor has enough to do with his rebellion; he has no leisure to trouble about any outside matters. However, two other young leaders in Wei have lately come to the front, and if Sima Yi sent them against Shu and Wu, it might go ill with you both.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'And who are these two?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 46, 'talk': 'I do not think them worth even talking about,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 71, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'We have lately lost by death two trusty minister, Jiang Wan and Dong Yun, and there is no one left fit to take care of the government. The attempt should be postponed; no hasty move should be made.', 'context': 'But Fei Yi, Chair of the Secretariat, opposed any expedition, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Not so,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Life is short. Our days flash by as the glint of a white horse across a chink in the door. We are waiting and waiting. Are we never to try to restore Han to its old glory?', 'context': ' replied Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 196, 'talk': "Remember the saying of the wise Sun Zi: 'Know thyself and know thine enemy, then is victory sure.' We are not the equals of the late Prime Minister, and where he failed, are we likely to succeed?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 218, 'talk': 'I would enlist the aid of the Qiangs. I have lived near them in Xizhou and know them well. With their help, even if we do not gain the whole empire, we can at least conquer and hold all west of Xizhou.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei said, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Sir, as you desire to conquer Wei, do your best. I will not damp your enthusiasm.', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler here closed the discussion, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'We will first send an envoy to the Qiangs to make a league with them,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 411, 'talk': 'Then we will march out by the Xiping Pass to Yongzhou, where we will throw up two ramparts in Qushan in Qushan Mountains and garrison them. The position is a point of vantage. Then we will send supplies beyond the pass by land and waterways, and advance gradually, according to the plan devised by the late Prime Minister.', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 289, 'talk': 'In this high country the city must be short of water, which means that the besieged must come out for supplies. Let us cut off the streams that supply them, and they will perish of thirst.', 'context': 'At sight of the position he rejoiced exceedingly, and when he returned to camp he said to Chen Tai, “'},
{'istart': 105, 'iend': 175, 'talk': "I do not understand the delay of Commander Jiang Wei's reinforcements.", 'context': 'Meanwhile the soldiers were parched with thirst. Gou An discussed the circumstance with Li Xin, saying, “'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Let me try to fight my way out and get help.', 'context': 'Li Xin said, “'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'Qushan had been surrounded and cut off water supplies. By luck it snowed, and our soldiers were partly relieved. But the situation was very urgent.', 'context': 'He dismounted, prostrated himself, and told his story: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'The delay is not due to my slackness; the Qiang allies we depended upon have not come,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 143, 'talk': 'The Qiangs do not come, and the Wei army is besieging Qushan; General, do you have any plan to propose?', 'context': 'Turning to Xiahou Ba, Jiang Wei asked, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 357, 'talk': 'If we wait for the coming of the Qiangs, it looks as if we shall be too late to relieve Qushan. It is very probable that Yongzhou has been left undefended, wherefore I propose that you go toward Ox Head Hills and work round to the rear of Yongzhou, which will cause the Wei army to fall back to relieve Yongzhou and so relieve our force.', 'context': 'Xiahou Ba replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'The plan appears excellent,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 461, 'talk': 'Now that this man has got out, he will tell Jiang Wei of the danger and Jiang Wei will conclude that our efforts are concentrated on the ramparts and will endeavor to attack our rear. Therefore I suggest, General, that you go to River Yao and stop the supplies of our enemies, while I go to the Ox Head Hills and smite them. They will retreat as soon as they know their supplies are threatened.', 'context': 'When Chen Tai knew that Li Xin had escaped, he said to his chief, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'So you intended to attack Yongzhou, did you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'But we know it and have been watching for you a long time.', 'context': ' shouted Chen Tai. “'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 227, 'talk': 'This is no place to remain in. We can get no victory and are tempting fate by remaining open to a surprise. I think we should retire till some better plan can be tried.', 'context': 'Seeing no result after some days of this, Xiahou Ba said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Simpleton, how dare you stand in my way?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'I have served Wei many years and reached the highest rank possible among ministers. People have suspected me of ulterior aims, and I have always felt afraid of that. After my death the government will be in your hands, and you must be doubly careful.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'The county of Dongxing is most important to Wu. They have built a great rampart, with walls right and left to defend Lake Chaohu from an attack in the rear. You gentlemen will have to exercise extreme care.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 54, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Dongxing is of the utmost importance as its loss would endanger Wuchang.', 'context': 'Then said Ding Feng, General Who Pacifies the North, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'I agree with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Thirty ships are coming in the river.', 'context': 'In the midst of the feasting came one to report: “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Sima Zhao has suffered a defeat and retreated to the north. It is time to take the Middle Land.', 'context': 'Then he said to his leaders, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'It is a white rainbow,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'and it bodes ill to the army. I advise you, O Commander, to return and not march against Wei.', 'context': ' said Jiang Yan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'How dare you utter such ill−omened words and blunt the keenness of my army?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 131, 'talk': "Wei's chief defense is Xincheng; it would be a severe blow to Sima Shi to capture it.", 'context': 'Then Ding Feng offered a suggestion, saying, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 435, 'talk': 'It is a rule in Wei that if a city holds out against attack for a hundred days and reinforcement has not arrived, then its commander may surrender without penalty to his family. Now Xincheng has held out for over ninety days, and my master hopes you will allow him to withstand the few days necessary to complete the hundred, when he will yield. Here are all register documents that he desires to tender first.', 'context': 'And the messenger said, “'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 173, 'talk': "I have half a year's provisions yet and will not surrender to any curs of Wu.", 'context': 'As soon as the repairs were complete, Zhang Te threw off all pretense and cried from the wall, “'},
{'istart': 281, 'iend': 324, 'talk': 'The soldiers are sick and unfit for battle.', 'context': "Their leader's illness disheartened the troops, and, moreover, the weather became very hot. Sickness invaded the camp, so that soldiers and leaders alike wished to go home. When Zhuge Ke had recovered sufficiently to resume command, he urged on the attack, but the generals said, “"},
{'istart': 45, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'The next person who mentions illness will be beheaded.', 'context': 'Zhuge Ke burst into fierce anger, and said, “'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'This Zhuge Ke is as cruel as he is powerful. He abuses his authority and no one is safe against him. I also think he is aiming at something yet higher and you, Sir, as one of the ruling family ought to put a stop to it.', 'context': 'Minister Teng Yin, who had an old quarrel with Zhuge Ke, said to Sun Jun, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'I agree with you, and I want to get rid of him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Now I will obtain an edict condemning him to death.', 'context': ' replied Sun Jun. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I am afraid of him, too,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'I have wanted to remove him for some time, but have found no opportunity. If you would prove your loyalty, you would do it for me.', 'context': ' replied Sun Liang. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'Who are you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'I was in mourning for my father newly dead, and had come into the city to seek a priest to read the liturgy. I had entered by mistake, thinking it was a temple.', 'context': 'The person seemed too terror−stricken to reply or resist when he was seized. They questioned him, and he said, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'There are scores of us at the gate, which is never unwatched. We have not seen a man enter.', 'context': 'The gate wardens were questioned. They said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'The dog even mocks me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I feel doubtful about the real purpose of this banquet,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'and advise you not to go.', 'context': ' said Zhang Yue, “'},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'O Commander, why are you turning back?', 'context': 'Zhuge Ke gave orders to drive home again; but before he had reached his own gate, the two conspirators—Sun Jun and Teng Yin—rode up and asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'I feel unwell and cannot see the Emperor today,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'This court is appointed to be held especially to do honor to you and the army. You have not yet reported, and there is a banquet for you. You may be ill, but you really must go to court.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 74, 'talk': 'Will you have some of the medicated wine brought from your own residence?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Yes; I could drink that,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 180, 'iend': 228, 'talk': 'The Emperor has issued an edict to slay a rebel!', 'context': 'of the hall and changed his garments of ceremony for more homely garb, but underneath these he put on armor. Then suddenly he raised his keen sword and ran up the hall, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 179, 'iend': 217, 'talk': 'Why does your clothing smell of blood?', 'context': "While Zhuge Ke was absent in the palace, his wife sat in the women's quarters at home feeling strangely unquiet. Presently a maid came in and, when she drew near, his wife said, “"},
{'istart': 206, 'iend': 267, 'talk': 'I am Zhuge Ke, and I have been slain by that bastard Sun Jun.', 'context': 'To her horror the maid suddenly transformed into a weird creature with rolling eyes and gritting teeth, that went dancing about the room and leaping till it touched the roof−beams, shrieking all the time, “'},
{'istart': 239, 'iend': 262, 'talk': 'Zhuge Ke will die soon.', 'context': "Before Zhuge Jin died, he had a premonition that his son's ability would lead him into trouble and that he would not safeguard his family. Others had also predicted an early death. Zhang Qi, High Minister in Wei, used to say to Sima Shi, “"},
{'istart': 303, 'iend': 370, 'talk': 'Can a person live long when his dignity endangers that of his lord?', 'context': ' And when asked why, Zhang Qi replied, “'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Our former attack on Yongzhou failed, so this time they will doubtless be even better prepared to resist. What do you suggest?', 'context': 'Discussing the plan of campaign with Xiahou Ba, Jiang Wei said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 337, 'talk': 'Nanan is the only well−provided place in all Longshang; if we take that, it will serve as an excellent base. Our former ill−success was due to the non−arrival of the Qiangs. Let us therefore send early to tell them to assemble at Longyou, after which we will move out at Shiying and march to Nanan by way of Dongting.', 'context': 'Xiahou Ba replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'You spoke well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'Who will go out to meet the army from the west?', 'context': 'Sima Shi at once asked his leaders, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Xu Zhi is very formidable; how can we overcome him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Tomorrow make pretense of defeat and so draw them into an ambush,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'But remember whose son this Sima Zhao is,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'The Shu supplies are coming up along the rear of Iron Cage Mountain, and they are using the wooden oxen and running horses as transport.', 'context': 'The scouts reported to Sima Zhao: “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 180, 'talk': 'We formerly defeated the army of Shu by cutting off supplies, and we can do that again. Let five thousand troops go out tonight and occupy the road.', 'context': 'Then said Sima Zhao to Xu Zhi, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'Death will surely come to me here!', 'context': 'In despair, Sima Zhao looked up to heaven and sighed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'O General, why do you not imitate Geng Gong, who, being in great need, prostrated himself and prayed at a well, wherefrom he afterwards was supplied with sweet water?', 'context': 'had done in ancient time, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 332, 'talk': 'The humble Sima Zhao received a command to repulse the army of Shu. If he is to die here, then may this spring cease its flow, when he will end his own life and let his soldiers yield to the enemy. But if his allotted span of life be not reached, then, O Blue Vault, increase the flow of water and save the lives of this multitude.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 264, 'talk': 'I have always regretted that our great Prime Minister was unable to capture Sima Yi in the Gourd Valley, but now I think his son is doomed to fall into our hands.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei had surrounded the hill, holding the army thereon as in a prison. He said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 356, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei has made a league with the Qiangs, and they have arrived to help him. If you go away to rescue Sima Zhao, the Qiangs will attack from the rear. Therefore I would propose to send some one to the tribespeople to try to create a diversion and get them to retire. If they are disposed of, you may go to the rescue of Sima Zhao.', 'context': 'Chen Tai said to him, “'},
{'istart': 10, 'iend': 299, 'talk': 'Guo Huai sets himself up as superior to everyone and is trying to slay me. Therefore I have come to offer my services to you. I know all the secrets of the Wei army, and, if you will, this very night I can lead you to their camp. I have friends in the camp to help, and you can destroy it.', 'context': 'He said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'Our government has always regarded you as a loyal and true friend,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 85, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Why then are you helping our enemies?', 'context': ' said Guo Huai. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'What does this mean? Is this the correct etiquette for a prince when his minister approaches?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'I pray Your Majesty remember your dignity and listen while the ministers address the Throne.', 'context': ' said Sima Shi, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 67, 'iend': 213, 'talk': 'That man Sima Shi treats me as a child and regards the officers of state as if they were so many straws. I am sure the throne will be his one day.', 'context': "Seizing his father−in−law's hand, Cao Fang began to weep, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'It was from fear of this man that my brother Xiahou Ba was forced to go over to Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'If Sima Shi were destroyed, my brother could return. I belong to a family related to the rulers of the state for many generations, and I cannot sit still while a wretch ruins the government. Put my name in the command as well, and we will work together to remove him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'But I am afraid we can not overcome him,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'We pledge ourselves to work together for the destruction of the tyrant, and to show our gratitude to Your Majesty.', 'context': 'They wept and said, “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'My ancestor, the Emperor Cao, put to death Dong Cheng for just such a matter as this, so you must be exceedingly careful and maintain the greatest secrecy.', 'context': 'He gave it to his father−in−law, Zhang Qi, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'Oh, why use such ill−omened words?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'We are not like Dong Cheng, and Sima Shi cannot compare to the Founder. Have no doubts.', 'context': ' cried Li Feng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Why are you three so late in leaving the Palace?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'His Majesty was reading, and we stayed with him,', 'context': ' asked Sima Shi. “'},
{'istart': 133, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'What was he reading?', 'context': ' said Li Feng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'The histories of the Xia, Shang, and Zhou dynasties.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'What questions did the Emperor ask as he read those books?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'He asked about Yi Yin and how he upheld the Shang; and the Duke of Zhou, how he acted when he was regent. And we told His Majesty that you were both Yi Yin and Duke Zhou to him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'Why did you compare me with those two when in your hearts you think me a rebel like Wang Mang and Dong Zhuo?', 'context': 'Sima Shi smiled grimly and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 50, 'talk': 'How should we dare when we are your subordinates?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'You are a lot of flatterers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'We did no such thing.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Your eyes are still red; you cannot deny that.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Well, we were crying because of your conduct, because you terrorize over the Emperor and are scheming to usurp the Throne.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Seize him!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'So you wish to destroy me and my brother. This is too much!', 'context': 'Sima Shi, more angry than ever, said, “'},
{'istart': 162, 'iend': 242, 'talk': 'The palace is full of spies, and if this comes out, it will mean trouble for me.', 'context': 'Sima Shi then went to the rear apartments of the palace, where he found the Emperor talking with his Consort. Just as he entered, she was saying to the Emperor, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'I had no such intention,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 14, 'talk': 'Who did this?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'I was forced into it. How could I think of such a thing?', 'context': 'Shaking with fear, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'To slander ministers by charging them with rebellion is an aggravated crime,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 66, 'talk': 'Yes; I am guilty; forgive me.', 'context': 'Cao Fang knelt at his feet, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'I beg Your Majesty to rise; the laws must be respected.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 82, 'talk': 'She is of the Zhang house and must die.', 'context': 'Pointing to Empress Zhang, Sima Shi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'Spare her,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 10, 'talk': 'Farewell,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 198, 'talk': 'General, you are right to play the same part as Yi Yin and Huo Guang, thereby acting in accordance with Heaven and fulfilling the desire of humankind. Who dares dispute it?', 'context': 'They all agreed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'Whom do you propose to place on the throne, General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'I have observed that Cao Ju, Prince of Pengcheng, is intelligent, benevolent, and filial; he is fit to rule the empire.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 273, 'talk': 'He is my uncle, and it is not convenient. However, there is Cao Mao, Duke of Gaogui, and grandson of Emperor Pi. He is of mild temperament, respectful, and deferential, and may be set up. You, Sir, and the high officers of state might favorably consider this.', 'context': 'She replied, “'},
{'istart': 25, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Her Majesty speaks well; Cao Mao should be raised to the throne.', 'context': 'Then spoke one, saying, “'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 375, 'talk': 'You are vicious beyond measure, a companion of lewd men and a friend of vile women. You are unfitted to rule. Therefore resign the imperial seal and revert to your status of Prince of Qi (an ancient state). You are forbidden to present yourself at court without special command.', 'context': 'The Empress called Cao Fang into her presence in the Hall of Principles and blamed him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'The ruler ought not to return these salutations,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'I also am a minister and must respond,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'Father, you are chief of all this region. With this Sima Shi in such a position, the country is in danger, and you cannot sit still and look on.', 'context': "He was moved to great anger, and his eldest son, Guanqiu Dian, fomented his father's wrath, saying, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'My son, you speak well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'Think you that this conduct of Sima Shi does not tear my heart? He has deposed the Emperor and now holds in his grip all authority of the state. Things are all upside down.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 387, 'talk': 'You are the chief of this region. If you are willing to play the part, you ought to take arms and slay this rebel. I will help you, regardless of consequences. My second son, Wen Yang, is a good warrior and a man of great valor, Moreover, he hates Sima Shi and wishes to avenge on the Sima brothers the death of Cao Shuang. He would make an excellent leader of the van.', 'context': 'Wen Qin replied, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 461, 'talk': 'When Guan Yu was most famous, Sun Quan sent Lu Meng to capture Jingzhou. What did Lu Meng do? He first won over the officers of Guan Yu by taking care of their families and thus broke the power of his enemy like a tile. Now the families of all the officers in the South of River Huai are here in the Middle Land. Treat them well, at the same time taking care that they do not get away, and you will be irresistible.', 'context': 'Said Wang Su, quoting Guan Yu as an example, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Your words are good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'However, I cannot go out to war till I have recovered. Yet, to send another is to take great risks, and I shall feel insecure.', 'context': ' said Sima Shi. “'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 268, 'talk': 'The forces of the South of River Huai and Chu are very formidable. If you send another, there is danger whatever happens; and if your leader makes a serious mistake, your whole policy will fail.', 'context': 'There was also present Secretary Zhong Hui, who here interposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'No one but myself can succeed,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 75, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'I must go.', 'context': ' cried Sima Shi, starting from his couch. “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 399, 'talk': 'Guanqiu Jian is fond of laying plans, but slow to come to any decision. His fellow−conspirator Wen Qin is bold, but imprudent. Now this scheme of theirs is too large for their minds; but as their soldiers are full of spirit, they should not be engaged lightly. We should remain on the defensive till their ardor has burned out. This is what Zhou Yafu of old time did.', 'context': 'Zheng Mao spoke first, saying, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 254, 'talk': 'This is not a rising of the people, nor of the soldiers, but is the work of Guanqiu Jian. The people are merely his tools and cannot help themselves. The rebellion will go to pieces as soon as an army approaches the county.', 'context': 'But Wang Ji objected, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'I agree with you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 209, 'talk': 'Nandun is an excellent site for a camp, with a river beside it and hills at the rear. If the Wei armies camp there, we shall be unable to dislodge them. Let us occupy it.', 'context': 'The Leader of the Van, Ge Yong, said, “'},
{'istart': 35, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'Sun Jun of Wu has crossed the river to attack Shouchun.', 'context': 'Just then a scout came in to say: “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'If we lose that city, we shall have no base,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 361, 'talk': "The retirement to Xiangcheng was obviously due to Wu's threatened attack upon Shouchun. General, you should send three armies to attack upon Xiangcheng, Lojia, and Shouchun. The Imperial Protector of Yanzhou, Deng Ai, is a man of tactics; he should be sent against Lojia. Our main army will reinforce them.", 'context': 'High Minister Fu Gu, who was of the expedition, said, “'},
{'istart': 186, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'General, you need not be anxious. My son Wen Yang and I will answer for its safety. Give us but five thousand troops.', 'context': 'Camped at Xiangcheng, Guanqiu Jian sent spies to Lojia to see what might be happening there, for he feared it would be attacked. When he spoke of his fears to Wen Qin, the latter said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'We should attack before they have settled down in camp, Father,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'Let us go quickly and attack on two sides.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'When can we start?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 166, 'talk': 'Tonight at dusk. You lead half the force round by the south, and I will march the other half round by the north, and we will meet in the third watch at the Wei camp.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'An army has come round from the north and burst into the lines. The leader is too bold for anyone to face.', 'context': 'One replied: “'},
{'istart': 32, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Rebel, flee not!', 'context': 'Deng Ai rode forward shouting, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'Lo! Here is a man who has driven us all backward. But we are many and may not suffer that.', 'context': 'Then the Wei generals met and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'You fools?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'Have you then no regard for your lives?', 'context': ' cried Wen Yang, as he saw them coming on. “'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Wen Qin had no sincere intention to rebel, but was led astray by Guanqiu Jian. If you will let me go and speak with him, he will come over to you at once.', 'context': 'So he went in to see the sick Sima Shi, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Do you not recognize me? I am Yin Damu.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'The responsibility of power is heavy, but we must bear it; there is no possible relief. You must continue my plans and maintain my policy yourself, and you must be exceedingly careful how you entrust any other with power, lest you bring about the destruction of our whole clan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 241, 'talk': 'The death of your brother has disturbed the country; and if you remain here, some shifting of power at the capital will surely work to your disadvantage. It will be too late for regrets then.', 'context': 'Sima Zhao took counsel with Zhong Hui, who said, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 352, 'talk': 'Shu is not a big country, and its resources are not too abundant. Thus a far expedition should be avoided. The state policy should rather be the improvement of conditions at home. Thinking well for the soldiers and the people is the way to preserve the country.', 'context': 'However, Zhang Yi, General Who Conquers the West, was opposed to the expedition and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'You are mistaken,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 570, 'talk': 'Before our great Minister Zhuge Liang emerged from his reed hut in the wilds and undertook the affairs of a state, the three kingdoms were already a fact. Six times he led armies to try to gain the northern portion of the empire, but failed to attain his desire. Unhappily he died leaving his design unaccomplished. But he bequeathed to me the legacy of his intention, and I must be a loyal and worthy executor. If I die in the attempt, I will perish without regret. Now is our opportunity, and if we miss it, shall we find a better?', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'What you say is the real truth,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 51, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Let us send first some light horse out by Baohan to capture Nanan and thereby settle that county.', 'context': ' said Xiahou Ba. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'Wu, Shu, and Wei are now actually established as a tripod; why then have you invaded our borders these many times?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 177, 'talk': 'Because Sima Shi deposed hid prince without cause, and it behooves the neighboring countries to punish such a crime. Moreover, your country is a rival state.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 295, 'talk': 'You see that the enemy is drawn up with a river at his back, so that his troops must conquer or drown. Though Jiang Wei is bold, you four can fight him at the same time and pursue if he retires.', 'context': 'Then Wang Jing turned and said to four of his generals, Zhang Ming, Hua Yong, Liu Da, and Zhu Fang, “'},
{'istart': 226, 'iend': 265, 'talk': 'Danger, O Generals! Now do your utmost.', 'context': 'The four rode out two and two. Jiang Wei stood through a few encounters, but then moved backward toward his camp. At this, Wang Jing led on his main body to smite. Jiang Wei fled toward the river. As he drew near he shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'General, you have won a great victory, which will bring you fame. If you attempt more, things may go astray, and you will only add legs to your sketch of a serpent.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'When our army were defeated not long ago, they still desired to overrun the whole north. Now our opponents have been overcome, and that has broken the spirit of their army, and this city can be easily captured. Do not damp the spirit of my soldiers.', 'context': 'Said Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'That is well said!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'I have spoken to you of Deng Ai many times. He is perspicacious, valiant, resourceful, and has always delighted in the study of military topography. As he is coming, we shall have to put forth all our energies.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei called in his colleague Xiahou Ba, who said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'We will attack before he can get a foothold and while his soldiers are fatigued with the march.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'I have fallen into a trap set by Deng Ai!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 229, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei slipped off in the night because he was broken, and he will never dare to return.', 'context': 'After Deng Ai had rendered his thanks to the Emperor, Chen Tai spread a great feast in his honor, and in congratulating his guest, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'I think he will,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'I can give five reasons why he should.', 'context': ' replied Deng Ai, smiling. “'},
{'istart': 87, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'What are they?', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 1122, 'talk': 'First, although the soldiers of Shu have retired, they have the self−possessed and confident look of holding the victory; our soldiers are really weak and broken. Second, the soldiers of Shu were trained and inspirited by Zhuge Liang and are easy to mobilize; our generals are all of different periods of service, and our army indifferently trained. Third, the Shu soldiers often use boats for traveling; ours do all their journeys on land, so that while one army moves at leisure and the troops arrive fresh, those of the other arrive fatigued with marching. Fourth, again, Didao, Longxi, Nanan, and Qishan are all places suitable for defense or use as battle fields, and thus the army of Shu can conceal their intentions and strike where they will; we have to remain on guard at many points, thus dividing our forces. When they concentrate, they have only to reckon with a part of our force. And fifth, if they come out by way of Longxi and Nanan, they have the grain of the Qiangs to depend upon; and if they choose Qishan, they have the wheat there. These are the five reasons why they should make another expedition.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Sir, your foresight is godlike. I think we need feel no anxiety about what the enemy can achieve.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 284, 'talk': 'General, your expeditions have partly failed many times; you have never scored a complete victory. But now on River Yao the army of Wei recognize your superiority, and why should you try again? There is small chance of success, and you risk all you have gained.', 'context': 'But Fan Jian opposed. “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'You all regard only the largeness and population of Wei and the time necessary for conquest, but you do not see five reasons for victory.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 215, 'talk': 'Deng Ai is young, but he is deep and crafty. He has certainly taken great pains to secure the regions under his charge as General Who Pacifies the West. Victory will not be so easy as it was before.', 'context': 'Xiahou Ba said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Why should I fear him?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'You should not laud the spirit of the enemy and belittle that of our own soldiers. But in any case I have made up my mind and shall take Longxi.', 'context': ' cried Jiang Wei, angrily. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 31, 'talk': 'Xiahou Ba spoke only too well,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'The plan of those camps is excellent and only our Zhuge Liang could have laid them out with equal skill.', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 394, 'talk': 'They must have known of my coming, and I think Deng Ai is here too. Now from this as base you are to send out daily small reconnoitering parties showing my banner, but different flags and uniforms, blue, yellow, red, white, and black, in turns. While you are thus distracting attention, I will lead the main army by Dongting to attack Nanan.', 'context': 'Returning to his own army, he said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 179, 'talk': 'I have been here over twenty years and have never known so much of the military possibilities of the place. You are very wonderful and must carry out your plan.', 'context': 'Chen Tai replied, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 161, 'talk': 'That hill is our point, and Nanan is close. I fear lest the artful Deng Ai may seize and fortify it.', 'context': 'Near the Wucheng Mountain, he turned to Xiahou Ba and said, “'},
{'istart': 261, 'iend': 269, 'talk': 'Deng Ai.', 'context': "They hastened, anxious to reach the hill before the enemy. But it was not to be. Presently they heard the roar of bombs and the beating of drums, and then flags and banners appeared, all of Wei. And among them fluttered the leader's standard, bearing the name “"},
{'istart': 101, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Since we cannot take Nanan, our next best plan is to try for Shanggui, which is the storehouse of Nanan.', 'context': 'Seeing that a camp could not be made there, Jiang Wei retired to consider new plans with Xiahou Ba. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 124, 'talk': 'And if a force held the mouth, we should be in sorry straits.', 'context': "“That sounds too much like 'Cut−off Valley,'“ said Jiang Wei. “"},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'We cannot go thither, for Chen Tai has destroyed the force under Bao Su, and he himself was killed. All that was left of that army has gone back into Hanzhong.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei proposed to return to Qishan, but Xiahou Ba said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'Sir, all real authority is in your hands, and the country is not tranquil. The only remedy is for you to become actual ruler, and you should find out who are your supporters.', 'context': 'Jia Chong said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 240, 'talk': 'This has been in my thoughts a long time. You might be my emissary to the east to find out the feeling there. You can pretend you go to thank the soldiers who took part in the late campaign. That would be a good pretext.', 'context': 'Sima Zhao replied, “'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'I only repeat what people have said.', 'context': 'Kui of Yuzhou, and your family have received the bounty of Wei. Yet you dare speak of rebellion!” Jia Chong said, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'If the state is in difficulty, then one ought to stand up for it even to the death.', 'context': 'Zhuge Dan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'The rat!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'Zhuge Dan is exceedingly popular there in the South of River Huai; and if he is left too long, he will do harm.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'How does he know?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'General Sima Zhao sent him a private letter.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'How dare this fellow Yue Chen treat me thus?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 271, 'talk': 'Your father, Yue Jin, enjoyed the bounty of Wei; yet you have not sought to repay the kindness of the Ruling House, but you want to help the rebel Sima Zhao.', 'context': 'The Imperial Protector sought refuge in a tower, but Zhuge Dan made his way up and reproached his enemy, crying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 342, 'talk': 'Zhuge Dan is a cousin of the Lord of Wuxiang in Shu. Zhuge Dan had been in service of Wei; and seeing Sima Zhao depose the his prince and oppress good people, he wants to punish the tyrant. But his force is not enough, and he asks for your help. To show his sincerity, he sends his son Zhuge Jing as a token of good faith.', 'context': 'Wu Gang explained, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'That is an excellent plan.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'General, you command all the armies and dispose them as you will; why do you ask me to go?', 'context': 'Cao Mao said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 279, 'talk': 'Your Majesty is wrong to hesitate. Your ancestors traveled over the empire and wished to unite the whole under one ruler. Wherever there was a worthy opponent, they went to face him. Your Majesty should follow their example and sweep the land clean. Why fear?', 'context': 'Sima Zhao replied, “'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 137, 'talk': 'The Wu army is helping our enemies for the sake of profit, and hence we can seduce them with an offer of greater profit.', 'context': 'Zhong Hui said, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 741, 'talk': 'Zhuge Dan has been worsted, but the city wherein he has taken refuge is well supplied, and his allies, the troops of Wu, are not distant. His position is strong. Our soldiers are besieging the city all round, which means that those within will hold out for a long time, or they will make a desperate sortie. Their allies also may fall upon us at the same time, and it would go hard with us. Therefore, I advise that the attack be made only on three sides, leaving the south gate open for them if they wish to flee. If they flee, we can fall on the fugitives. The troops of Wu cannot have supplies for very long; and if we sent some light cavalry round by their rear, we might stay their fighting power without a battle.', 'context': 'Then said Zhong Hui, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'You are my Zhang Liang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 77, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'Your advice is excellent.', 'context': ' said Sima Zhao, stroking the back of his adviser. “'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 194, 'talk': 'If we cannot succor Shouchun, how can we hope to overrun the Middle Land? Now and here you have to win a victory or die, for another defeat will mean death.', 'context': 'Sun Chen said to his general Zhu Yi, “'},
{'istart': 47, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'This is a plan to defeat our army by making a front and rear attack.', 'context': 'When this was reported to Sima Zhao, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 44, 'talk': 'What is the use of leaders who always lose?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 234, 'talk': 'The food in the city is short, and the soldiers are many; this can not last long. General, you should let the Wu troops to go out and make a decisive fight with the Wei army.', 'context': 'Two advisers, Jiang Ban and Jiao Yi, came to him and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'Why do you tell me to fight when I am set on holding out to the very last? If you say that again, you shall die as traitors.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'He is lost,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'We can do no other than surrender or we shall die too.', 'context': ' said they, going away. “'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'The northern troops should be sent away in order to save food.', 'context': 'Wen Qin went to Zhuge Dan with a proposal, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Do you want to kill me that you propose to send the northern soldiers away?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'The real offender was his father, Wen Qin,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 62, 'iend': 223, 'talk': 'but he is dead, and these two come to you in desperation; and if you slay those who surrender, you will strengthen the obstinacy of those who remain in the city.', 'context': ' said Zhong Hui, “'},
{'istart': 103, 'iend': 236, 'talk': 'We have received great kindness at the hands of Sima Zhao, who not only has pardoned us but given us gifts. Why do you not all yield?', 'context': 'After expressing their gratitude, they rode about the city on the horses he had given them, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 171, 'talk': 'This Wen Yang was an enemy, and yet he has been well received; how much more may we expect generous treatment?', 'context': 'When their companions heard this, they said one to another. “'},
{'istart': 89, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Why do you not yield?', 'context': 'Wang Ji fought his way to the west gate, where he fell in with the Wu general, Yu Quan. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 108, 'talk': 'Where is the principle for yielding when I have my orders to rescue the city and so far have not succeeded?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 146, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'The happiest death a man can die is on the battlefield.', 'context': ' Throwing off his helmet, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'We would rather share the fate of our leader.', 'context': 'They all refused, saying, “'},
