{'istart': 43, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'I will display them to him.', 'context': ' replied Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'General Deng Ai has excellent plans and does not think much of such tactics.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 100, 'talk': 'What plans? I suppose you mean a plan to keep me here while he tries a surprise attack in the rear.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 302, 'talk': 'Recently the Ruler of Shu has had a favorite, Eunuch Huang Hao, in whom he places all his trust and with whom he spends his time in one round of pleasure. Let us use the eunuch to sow distrust between the Emperor and his general and so get Jiang Wei recalled. In that way we shall retrieve our defeat.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'A leader in the field is independent and need not obey even the command of his prince.', 'context': 'When the order to retreat was given, Liao Hua said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'The country begins to resent these many years of war; rather take the occasion of the victory you have just won to return and pacify the people.', 'context': 'Zhang Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 12, 'talk': 'It is good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei is a worthy inheritor of the warlike methods of Zhuge Liang.', 'context': 'As he saw his enemy disappearing in perfect order, Deng Ai sighed, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 149, 'talk': 'Because you have been so long on the frontier, noble Sir; I thought the soldiers must be weary. There was no other reason.', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 222, 'talk': 'Your Majesty, thy servant had got his camps on Qishan and was on the eve of complete success. To leave off thus in the middle just played into the hands of our enemies. Surely Deng Ai found means of sowing distrust in me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'I am pledged to destroy those rebels and prove my devotion to my country. Your Majesty should not listen to the babble of mean persons till distrust grows in your heart.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I do not distrust you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 68, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'You may return into Hanzhong and await the next favorable opportunity.', 'context': ' said the Latter Ruler after a long pause. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'What do you think of an attack upon Shu?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Not to be considered,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 79, 'talk': 'This fellow is very like Cao Fang, and if I do not remove him he will hurt me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'I will see to it for you,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 184, 'talk': "The services of the Regent Marshal are so magnificent, and his virtue so high that he should be rewarded with the title 'Duke of Jin' and the Nine Gifts of Honors.", 'context': 'The courtiers said, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'My father and my brother have all given great services to Wei, and yet I deserves not being a mere Duke of Jin?', 'context': 'And Sima Zhao himself said discontentedly, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Should I dare not do what you requested?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'That poem about the Lurking Dragon called us slimy creatures; what sort of politeness is that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'He may not be slain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 595, 'talk': "That will not do. In the old state of Lu, King Zhao could not bear with the Ji family, and ran away, thus losing his country. But this Sima Zhao and his family have been in power very long and have innumerable supporters, many of whom are quite independent of any act of his whether loyal or disloyal. They support him under any conditions. Your Majesty's guards are few and weak and incapable; not the ones for any desperate effort. It would be most lamentable if Your Majesty could not bear this trial. The correct course is to wait and not act hastily.", 'context': ' said Wang Jing. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'If I can bear this, what cannot I bear?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 109, 'talk': 'But I will do something, and if I die, what matters?', 'context': ' said Cao Mao. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 147, 'talk': "To go against Sima Zhao with such a force is driving the sheep into the tiger's jaws. To die such a death is a vain sacrifice. You can do nothing,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'Do not hinder me. I have made up my mind,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Death or capture?', 'context': 'Cheng Ji took his halberd and turned to Jia Chong, saying, “'},
{'istart': 80, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Duke Sima Zhao said the man had to die,', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Fool! How dare you?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 110, 'talk': 'Rebel and traitor! How dare you kill the Emperor?', 'context': 'Wang Jing, who had followed, upbraided Jia Chong, shouting, “'},
{'istart': 138, 'iend': 181, 'talk': 'It is my fault that they slew Your Majesty!', 'context': 'When Imperial Guardian Sima Fu saw the dead body of the Emperor, he threw himself beside it, his head resting thereon, and wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 119, 'talk': 'Gossips often class me and my uncle together. Yet today is my uncle less virtuous than I.', 'context': 'Chen Tai wept aloud, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': "How can this day's work be judged?", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'If only Jia Chong be put to death, that will only be a slight atonement to satisfy the empire,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 70, 'iend': 101, 'talk': 'How about a little less severe?', 'context': 'Sima Zhao was silent and thought long before he spoke. Then he said, “'},
{'istart': 104, 'iend': 173, 'talk': 'That is only the beginning; I know not other punishments less severe.', 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'The Emperor must die,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'O unfilial son to bring distress upon a gentle mother!', 'context': 'He knocked his head on the ground and wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Who does not die?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'How do you know for certain he is a false?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 249, 'talk': "Formerly King Wen had two−thirds of the empire, and yet he supported and served the state of Yin to its end. Wherefore Confucius called him 'Complete of Virtue.' Emperor Cao of Wei would not replace the Hans, nor will I accept an abdication of Wei.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 150, 'talk': 'I have a plan to propose, but I will not tell it openly. However, I have written it down for your consideration.', 'context': 'And Military Adviser Wang Guan said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Though excellent, I fear it is not enough to beguile the leader of Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'I am willing to stake my life on it,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'and I will lead the way.', 'context': ' said Wang Guan, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'Since you have such confidence you may try. You ought certainly to succeed.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 49, 'iend': 84, 'talk': 'We are deserters: tell your leader.', 'context': 'Seeing these, their leader, Wang Guan, shouted, “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 103, 'talk': 'Hold up the soldiers, letting their leader only come to me.', 'context': 'So the scouts told Jiang Wei, who replied, “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'Since you are sincere in your desertion, I must be sincere in my treatment of you. The one thing my army needs is grain. There is plenty at the border of the Lands of Rivers; and if you can transport it to Qishan, I can go straightway and take the Qishan camps of Deng Ai.', 'context': 'Then said Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'But you will not need five thousand troops to see after the transport. Take three thousand and leave two thousand as guides for me.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 66, 'iend': 307, 'talk': 'O Commander, why have you believed the tale of this Wang Guan? In Wei I never heard that Wang Guan was related to Wang Jing, though it is true I never made particular inquiries. You should look to it, for there is much pretense in his story.', 'context': 'Then Xiahou Ba was announced, and, when he was come in, he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I know Wang Guan is false,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'That is why I have taken away many of his force. I am meeting trick with trick.', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei, with a smile. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 191, 'talk': "Sima Zhao is as crafty as Cao Cao. If he slew all Wang Jing's family, would he have left a nephew and sent that nephew to the pass beyond his own reach with soldiers? You saw this, as did I.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 30, 'iend': 121, 'talk': 'It is getting dark; O General, hurry to help Wang Guan escort the convoy out of the valley.', 'context': 'His staff urged him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 35, 'talk': 'The mountains ahead are hazardous,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 56, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'If by any chance an ambush has been laid, we could hardly escape. We will wait here.', 'context': ' said the general. “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 182, 'talk': 'Just as General Wang Guan was crossing the frontier with the convoy, he was pursued, and reinforcements are urgently needed.', 'context': 'But just then two horsemen came up at a gallop and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Deng Ai, you are stupid! You have just fallen into the trap set for you by our general. Dismount and prepare for death!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 157, 'iend': 266, 'talk': 'A thousand ounces of gold for anyone who captures Deng Ai, and a lordship of ten thousand households as well!', 'context': 'Deng Ai halted and turned to flee. Then the wagons burst into flame. That flame was a signal, and down came the army of Shu. He heard shouts all round him, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'The case is desperate,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'It is a fight to the death!', 'context': ' cried Wang Guan. “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'I have observed the heavens. I have seen the leader stars in Shu dull and obscured. This expedition will be disastrous, and I hope Your Majesty will not approve.', 'context': 'As he was hesitating, Qiao Zhou stood forth and said, “'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'Let us see the results of this campaign; if it fails, then the war shall cease.', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'The late Prime Minister made six attempts, all for the state. I have attacked eight times. Was any one of those attacks to serve my private ends? This time I go to attack Taoyang, and no one shall say me nay. I will punish opposition with death.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei was annoyed. Said he, “'},
{'istart': 114, 'iend': 203, 'talk': 'That move is a blind; he does not mean it. What he really intends is an attack on Qishan.', 'context': 'It happened that Sima Wang was with Deng Ai discussing military matters, and the former, when he heard it, said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'However, he has really gone to Taoyang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'How can you know?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'Supposing this true, what should we do?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 327, 'talk': 'I advise the abandonment of this place and a march in two bodies toward Taoyang. I know a small town called Houxia, eight miles from Taoyang, which is the throat of the place. You go to Taoyang, hide your force and open the gates. Then act as I shall tell you presently. I will lie in wait at Houxia. We shall score a victory.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 245, 'iend': 272, 'talk': 'Is there any ruse in there?', 'context': 'Meanwhile Xiahou Ba led the van of the Shu army toward Taoyang. As he drew near, he noticed the place seemed to have no defenses; not a flag staff reared its head. The gates stood wide open. He was too wary to go straight in however, and said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 140, 'talk': 'We think the city was deserted when they heard your army coming. A few people were running away along the southern road.', 'context': 'His generals said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'The city is really empty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Caught!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 96, 'iend': 340, 'talk': 'Loss or gain is the platitude of war; but I am not worried yet about our recent defeats, for a total victory will surely come in this expedition if all of you strive your best. But remember, no mutiny! He who talks of retreat will suffer death.', 'context': 'Twice beaten, the soldiers of Shu were very downcast. Jiang Wei tried to console them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'With so many troops of Wei here, their camp at Qishan must be undefended. I propose, General, that while you continue the contest here with Deng Ai, I go to try to capture the nine camps. If I succeed, Changan will be at our mercy.', 'context': 'Then Zhang Yi said, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 245, 'talk': 'There must be some reason for this persistence. I think they have sent an army to try to seize Qishan while they hold me here. Shi Zuan and the force there are insufficient, and I shall have to go to the rescue.', 'context': 'Then Deng Ai thought within him, “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'Hold this place most carefully. Let them challenge as they may, do not go out. Tonight I go to the help of Qishan.', 'context': 'Deng Ai called his son Deng Zhong, and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'Let no one move!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'General Jiang Wei has come!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 204, 'talk': 'Soldiers are not proper persons to administer a punishment to a woman, and the face is not a portion of the body to be mortified; the author of this crime ought to be put to death.', 'context': 'The judges found that: “'},
{'istart': 248, 'iend': 364, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei should be recalled as he has not been able to score a decisive victory. Yan Yu can be sent to replace him.', 'context': "Among the sycophants of Huang Hao was Yan Yu, General of the Right Army, whose lack of merit had not stood in the way of preferment. Hearing of Jiang Wei's defeats at Qishan, Yan Yu got his friend Huang Hao to propose to the Latter Ruler, saying, “"},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Do you know the reason for my recall?', 'context': 'One day near the palace gate he met Secretary General Xi Zheng, and asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 208, 'talk': 'What General! Do you not know? Huang Hao wanted to push Yan Yu into favor, so he intrigued for your recall. Now they have found out Deng Ai is too clever to be tackled, and so they are not fighting any more.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'I shall certainly have to put this eunuch fellow out of the way,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Sir, what you say is true,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 162, 'talk': 'Why did Your Majesty recall me? I had the enemy in my power at Qishan when the triple edict came.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei approached his master and prostrated himself, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Unless Your Majesty gets rid of him, evil is very close,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 27, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'If you love anyone, you want him to live; if you dislike him, you desire his death; can you not bear with my one poor eunuch?', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler replied, “'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 255, 'talk': 'I am always in attendance upon the Sacred One; that is all I do. I never meddle in state affairs. I pray you, General, pay no heed to what people say. If you desire my death, I am in your hands, but pity me.', 'context': 'Huang Hao prostrated himself and wept, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'General, you are in grave danger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'And if you fall, the country falls with you.', 'context': ' said Xi Zheng. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'Can you advise me?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'How can I secure the state and myself?', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Your speech is gold and jewels,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 513, 'talk': 'Our many expeditions have failed to achieve success owing to lack of supplies. Now I am about to take eighty thousand troops to Tazhong to form a cantonment and grow wheat and corn ready for the next expedition. You are spent with much fighting and may now repose while collecting grain and guarding Hanzhong. The armies of Wei are from home and have to drag their grain over the mountains. They will be worn out with the labor and must soon retire. That will he the time to smite them, and success must be ours.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 125, 'talk': 'This Jiang Wei has invaded our country many times, and we have been unable to destroy him. He is the one sorrow of my heart.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 207, 'talk': 'He has carried on the work of Zhuge Liang only too thoroughly, and it is hard to force him back. What you need is some crafty brave to assassinate him, so remove this constant menace of war.', 'context': 'Said Jia Chong, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 421, 'talk': "That is not the way. Liu Shan, the Ruler of Shu, is steeped in dissipation and has given all his confidence to one favorite, the eunuch Huang Hao. The higher officers of state are concerned solely with their own safety, and Jiang Wei has gone to Tazhong only that he may save his life. If you send an able leader and a strong army, victory is certain. Where is the need for an assassin's dagger?", 'context': 'But Adviser Xun Xu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'These are excellent words,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 60, 'iend': 107, 'talk': 'but if I would attack Shu, where is the leader?', 'context': ' said Sima Zhao, with a laugh, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'Deng Ai is the ablest leader of the day,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 57, 'iend': 113, 'talk': 'Give him Zhong Hui as his second, and the thing is done.', 'context': ' said Xun Xu. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 22, 'talk': 'Exactly what I think,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 97, 'talk': 'I desire to send you as leader against Wu; can you go?', 'context': 'So he summoned Zhong Hui and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 100, 'iend': 144, 'talk': "My lord's design is not against Wu, but Shu,", 'context': ' “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'How well you know my inmost thought!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Thinking that my lord would desire to attack Shu, I have already prepared plans. Here they are.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'You are an excellent leader,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 41, 'iend': 76, 'talk': 'What say you to going with Deng Ai?', 'context': ' said he. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'I am sending a righteous army against an unrighteous ruler; how dare you oppose my designs?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 259, 'talk': 'If Shu hears that we intend to attack the west, they will ask assistance from Wu. So I pretend to attack Wu, and Wu will not dare to move under a year. When Shu is beaten, the ships will be ready and useful for an expedition into the East.', 'context': 'Zhong Hui replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 118, 'talk': 'My lord has sent Zhong Hui with a large army against Shu. I think he is too ambitious to be trusted with such powers?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'Think you I do not know?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'Then why have you sent him alone and without a colleague?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 81, 'iend': 748, 'talk': "This morning the officers all maintained that Shu should not be attacked, because they are timid. If I let them lead the army, they would surely be defeated. You saw Zhong Hui was set upon his plan, and he is not afraid. Shu must therefore be beaten, and then the Shu people's hearts will be torn. Beaten leaders cannot boast, and the officers of a broken state are no fit guardians of its welfare. When Zhong Hui turns against us, the people of Shu cannot support him; and our troops being victors, they will wish to return home and will not follow their leader into revolt. Hence there is nothing to be feared. I know this, as you do, but it must remain our secret.", 'context': "The words whispered in the ear of Shao Ti proved Sima Zhao's subtlety. Said he, “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 36, 'talk': 'Firstly I want a Leader of the Van,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 112, 'talk': 'He must be skilled in making roads and repairing bridges.', 'context': ' said Zhong Hui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'I will take that post,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Nobody is fitter!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'You shall have the seal,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 408, 'talk': "According to the book, 'water on a mountain' signifies the diagram Jian, whereunder we find that the southwest augurs well, but the northeast is unpropitious. Confucius said of Jian that it meant advantage in the southwest, i.e., success, but the northeast spelt failure, i.e., there was no road. In this expedition, General, you will overcome Shu, but you will not have a road to return.", 'context': 'Shao Yuan replied, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 90, 'talk': 'They will overcome Shu certainly, only I think neither will ever come back.', 'context': 'Said Liu Shi, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 21, 'talk': 'Why do you say that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'Here Jiang Wei says that the Wei armies under Deng Ai and Zhong Hui are on the way against us. What shall we do?', 'context': 'He read the document and said to the eunuch, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 238, 'talk': 'There is nothing of the sort. Jiang Wei only wants to get a name for himself, and so he says this. Your Majesty need feel no alarm, for we can find out the truth from a certain wise woman I know. She is a real prophetess. May I call her?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'The spirit has now descended. Send everyone away and pray to her.', 'context': 'Huang Hao then said, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 114, 'talk': 'If we can take this pass, then we can march directly into Hanzhong; the defense is weak.', 'context': 'He said to his officers, “'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 422, 'talk': "You were appointed Leader of the Van to see that the roads were put in repair, and your special duty was to see that the bridges were in good condition. Yet on the bridge just now my horse's hoof was caught, and I nearly fell. Happily Xun Kai was by, or I had been slain. You have been disobedient and must bear the penalty.", 'context': 'Xu Yi was called to the tent, and Zhong Hui blamed him for the lack of care in his task, saying, “'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'His father is Xu Chu who had rendered good services to the state.', 'context': 'The delinquent was sentenced to death. The other generals tried to beg him off, pleading, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'How can discipline be maintained if the laws are not enforced?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 28, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Speed is the soul of war; no halts.', 'context': 'Zhong Hui issued an order, “'},
{'istart': 64, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'The enemy is too strong to think of any other course.', 'context': 'command, and Jiang Shu was wholly in favor of defense, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'I do not agree,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'They are now fatigued with marching, and we need not fear them. Unless we go out and attack, the two cities will fall.', 'context': ' replied Fu Qian. “'},
{'istart': 44, 'iend': 285, 'talk': 'We have here a host of one hundred thousand. If you yield, you shall have higher rank than you hold now; but if you persist in holding out then, when we take the pass, you shall all perish. Jewels and pebbles will share the same destruction.', 'context': 'As soon as Zhong Hui saw them, he shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 16, 'talk': 'I have yielded,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Ungrateful and treacherous rogue! How can you ever face the world again?', 'context': 'Fu Qian shouted angrily, “'},
{'istart': 123, 'iend': 195, 'talk': 'Alive I have been a servant of Shu; dead I will be one of their spirits!', 'context': 'desperately, but could not win clear. His troops fell one by one, and when they were reduced to one out of ten, he cried, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'What hill is that?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'It is known as the Dingjun Mountain,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 93, 'talk': 'It is where Xiahou Yuan met his death.', 'context': ' was the reply. “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'Is there any temple to any supernatural being on the Dingjun Mountain?', 'context': 'Zhong Hui called the surrendered general Jiang Shu and asked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 4, 'talk': 'No,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 64, 'talk': 'there is nothing but the tomb of Zhuge Liang.', 'context': ' replied he, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'Then this must have been a manifestation of Zhuge Liang,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 104, 'talk': 'I ought to sacrifice to him.', 'context': ' said Zhong Hui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'Who are you, Sir?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 124, 'iend': 152, 'talk': 'Secure state, comfort people', 'context': 'He issued an order that the leading division of his army should bear a white flag with four words plainly written thereon, “'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 278, 'talk': 'Our forces are numbered by millions, our generals by thousands. Two hundred thousand are marching against you, and Chengdu has already fallen. In spite of this you do not yield, wherefore it is evident you do not recognize the divine command.', 'context': 'When near enough, Wang Qi shouted, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'Dead rat! No match for me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 74, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'The Governor of Jincheng, Yang Xin, has destroyed the camps at Gansong.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei retired the way he had come, and presently one came to report: “'},
{'istart': 21, 'iend': 334, 'talk': 'Zhong Hui has defeated the Yangping Pass; Jiang Shu has surrendered, while Fu Qian has fallen in the field. Hanzhong is now in the possession of Wei. Wang Han of Yuecheng and Jiang Bin of Hancheng has also opened their gates and yielded to the invaders at the loss of Hanzhong. Hu Ji has gone to Chengdu for help.', 'context': 'Next came the news: “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 117, 'talk': 'Zhuge Xu, Imperial Protector of Yongzhou, is holding Yinping Bridge, our retreat path.', 'context': 'However, the scouts reported: “'},
{'istart': 127, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Heaven is destroying me!', 'context': 'So Jiang Wei halted and made a camp in the mountains. Advance and retreat seemed equally impossible, and he cried in anguish, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 371, 'talk': 'If our enemies are blocking Yinping Bridge, they can only have left a weak force in Yongzhou. We can make believe to be going thither through the Konghan Valley and so force them to abandon the bridge in order to protect the city. When the bridge is clear, you can make a dash for Saber Pass and plan for a recapture of Hanzhong.', 'context': 'Then said Ning Sui, one of his generals, “'},
{'istart': 83, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Yongzhou is my own city, and headquarters; if it would be lost, I would be punished.', 'context': 'When Zhuge Xu, who was at the Yinping Bridge, heard this, he said in great shock, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'We are attacked all round, and the grain transportation is blocked. It seems to me wisest to retire on the Saber Pass and plan other designs.', 'context': 'Liao Hua said, “'},
{'istart': 159, 'iend': 352, 'talk': 'This country of White Water is too narrow and difficult to fight in with any hope of success. It would better to retreat to the Saber Pass. If we loss that pass, all paths will be closed to us.', 'context': 'But Jiang Wei was doubtful. Then they heard that Deng Ai and Zhong Hui were approaching in ten divisions. Jiang Wei was disposed to stand, but Liao Hua said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 19, 'talk': 'But do not grieve;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'so long as I live, I will not allow Wei to come and conquer Shu.', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 77, 'talk': 'Though we are holding this pass, yet Chengdu is well−nigh empty of soldiers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'My orders to you were to hold Yinping Bridge so as to stop Jiang Wei, and you lost it. Now without any orders you attack and are defeated.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 263, 'talk': 'Jiang Wei played so many deceitful tricks. He pretended to be going to take Yongzhou, and I thought that was very important, so I sent troops to rescue it. Then he meanly got away. I followed to the pass, but never thought he would come out and defeat my troops.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'Zhuge Xu is really a subordinate of Deng Ai and, admitting that he is in fault, his punishment should not have been pronounced by you, O Commander.', 'context': 'Now Wei Guan, Army Inspector, said, “'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'I have a command from the Emperor and orders from the Prime Minister to attack Shu; if Deng Ai himself offended, I would behead him.', 'context': 'But Zhong Hui swaggeringly replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 165, 'talk': 'Father, if you cannot suffer small things, you may upset the grand policy of the state. Unfriendliness with him may do great harm, so I hope you will bear with him.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 59, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'How many soldiers are following Deng Ai?', 'context': 'When his coming was announced, Zhong Hui asked his staff, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'He has only some twenty horsemen,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 71, 'talk': 'The capture of Hanzhong is a piece of excellent fortune for the state,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 88, 'iend': 145, 'talk': 'The capture of Saber Pass can now be accomplished easily.', 'context': ' said Deng Ai. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'What is your own idea, General?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 18, 'iend': 257, 'talk': 'In my simple opinion one might proceed by by−roads from the pass through the Yinping Mountains to Deyang in Hanzhong, and thence make a surprise march to Chengdu. Jiang Wei must go to its defense, and you, General, can take the Saber Pass.', 'context': 'Finally he said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 18, 'talk': 'A very good plan,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 116, 'talk': 'You may start forthwith, and I will wait here till I hear news of your success.', 'context': ' said Zhong Hui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 67, 'talk': 'They say Deng Ai is able; I think he is of most ordinary capacity,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 9, 'talk': 'But why?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 91, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'What did Zhong Hui think of me?', 'context': 'Deng Ai went out to the main gate of the court. While mounting, he said to his followers, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'He looked as though he held a poor opinion of what you had said, General, and disagreed with you, although his words were fair enough.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 56, 'talk': 'He thinks I cannot take Chengdu; and so I will take it.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 115, 'iend': 251, 'talk': 'I am going to make a dash for Chengdu while it is still undefended, and success will mean unfading glory for us all. Will you follow me?', 'context': 'From his camp Deng Ai sent a letter to Sima Zhao. Then he called his officers to his tent and asked them, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 41, 'talk': 'We will follow you and obey your orders,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 178, 'talk': 'We have found an impassable precipice away to the northwest which we cannot get through. All our labor has been in vain.', 'context': 'Deng Ai asked why they were so sad, and his son replied, “'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 235, 'talk': 'We have got over two hundred and fifty miles, and just beyond is Jiangyou. We cannot go back. How can one get tiger cubs except by going into tiger caves? Here we are, and it will be a very great feat to capture Chengdu.', 'context': 'Deng Ai said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Two fires were just founded; armies pass by here. Two soldiers compete; both soon die.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'O Martial Lord, immortal. I grieve that I am not thy worthy disciple.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'Now retreat is impossible, there is no road back. Before you lies Jiangyou with stores in abundance. Advance and you live, retreat and you die. You must fight with all your strength.', 'context': 'He said to his troops, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 28, 'talk': 'We will fight to the death!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 188, 'talk': 'If there is so great danger on the borders, how is it you are so unaffected?', 'context': 'His wife was of the Li family. When she heard of the state of things on the frontier, she said to her husband, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': "The affair is in Jiang Wei's hands and is not my concern,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 89, 'talk': 'Nevertheless, you finally have to guard the capital, and that is a heavy responsibility.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 63, 'talk': 'Lady Li has hanged herself!', 'context': 'Then came a servant with the news: “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 160, 'talk': 'We have just finished a long and perilous march and are weary and worn out. We ought to repose for a few days to recover.', 'context': 'General Tian Xu remonstrated, saying, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 120, 'talk': 'Speed is the one important matter in war: do not encourage any discontent. I will not have it.', 'context': 'Deng Ai angrily replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 70, 'talk': 'That is just false rumor. The spirits would not deceive Your Majesty,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 29, 'iend': 115, 'talk': 'In this extremity Your Majesty should call in the help of the son of the Martial Lord.', 'context': 'Finally Xi Zheng spoke out, “'},
{'istart': 84, 'iend': 199, 'talk': 'Deng Ai has defeated Fucheng, and the capital is seriously threatened. You must think of your father and rescue me.', 'context': 'As suggested, the Latter Ruler summoned Zhuge Zhan to court, and he said, weeping, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 242, 'talk': "My father and I owe too much to the First Ruler's and Your Majesty's kindness for me to think any sacrifice too great to make for Your Majesty. I pray that you give me command of the troops in the capital, and I will fight a decisive battle.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 120, 'iend': 151, 'talk': 'Who dares be Leader of the Van?', 'context': "So the soldiers, seventy thousand, were placed under Zhuge Zhan's command. When he had gathered all together, he said, “"},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 126, 'talk': 'Since my father commands the army, I volunteer to lead the van.', 'context': 'His son, Zhuge Shang, then nineteen, offered himself, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 155, 'talk': 'If they defend the hills in front, I shall fail; for if I am delayed, Jiang Wei will come up, and my army will be in great danger. The army must press on.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 249, 'talk': 'Lead one army straight to Mianzhu to keep back any Shu soldiers sent to stop our march. I will follow as soon as I can. But hasten; for if you let the enemy forestall you, I will put you to death.', 'context': 'He called Shi Zuan and his son Deng Zhong and said, “'},
{'istart': 505, 'iend': 539, 'talk': 'The Han Prime Minister Zhuge Liang', 'context': "They went. Nearing Mianzhu they met the army under Zhuge Zhan. Both sides prepared for battle. The Shu armies adopted the Eight Diagrams formation and presently, after the usual triple roll of drums, Shi Zuan and Deng Zhong saw their opponents' ranks open in the center, and therefrom emerge a light carriage in which sat a figure looking exactly as Zhuge Liang used to look when he appeared on the battlefield. Everybody knew the Taoist robes and the feather fan. The standard bore his name and titles: “"},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 54, 'talk': 'If Zhuge Liang is still alive, that is the end of us.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 38, 'talk': 'We saw Zhuge Liang leading the enemy,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'So we ran away.', 'context': ' said Deng Zhong, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 147, 'talk': 'Why should we fear, even if they bring Zhuge Liang to life again? You ran away without cause, and we have lost. You ought both to be put to death.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'This is the critical stage; and if you lose the next battle, you will certainly lose your lives with it.', 'context': 'Deng Ai, however, said to Deng Zhong and Shi Zuan, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 191, 'talk': 'This Zhuge Zhan well continues the paternal tradition. Twice they have beaten us and slain great numbers. We must defeat them, and that quickly, or we are lost.', 'context': 'To his officers Deng Ai said, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 83, 'talk': 'Why not persuade their leader with a letter?', 'context': 'Then Military Inspector Qiu Ben said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 514, 'talk': 'But now this Latter Ruler is dull and weak, and his kingly aura is already exhausted. I have a command from the Son of Heaven to smite Shu with severity, and I already possess the land. Your capital must quickly fall. Why then do you not bow to the will of Heaven and fall in with the desires of people by acting rightly and coming over to our side? I will obtain the rank of Prince of Langye for you, whereby your ancestors will be rendered illustrious. These are no vain words if happily you will consider them.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Do not go out to battle;', 'context': 'Deng Ai was very angry at this insult and wished to go forth at once to battle. But Qiu Ben dissuaded him. “'},
{'istart': 144, 'iend': 190, 'talk': 'rather overcome him by some unexpected stroke.', 'context': ' said he, “'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 133, 'talk': 'The land of Shu being in danger, I cannot sit and look on unconcerned.', 'context': 'Then the Ruler of Wu assembled his officers and said to them, “'},
{'istart': 55, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'This long defense is useless; I will fight.', 'context': 'Weary of the hopeless delay, he said to his generals, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 11, 'talk': 'I am done,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'But in my death I will do my duty!', 'context': ' cried he. “'},
{'istart': 143, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'Young general, do not go out immediately!', 'context': 'From the city walls his son Zhuge Shang saw the death of his father. Girding on his armor he made to go out to fight. But Zhang Zun told him, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'My father and I and all our family have received favors from the state. My father has died in battle against our enemies, and can I live?', 'context': 'Cried Zhuge Shang, “'},
{'istart': 26, 'iend': 132, 'talk': 'Panic has seized upon the people, and they are leaving the city in crowds. Their cries shake the very sky.', 'context': 'Then the officials said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 105, 'talk': 'We do not have enough troops to protect the capital. Leave the city and flee south to the Southern Land,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 119, 'iend': 206, 'talk': 'The country is difficult and easily defended. We can get the Mangs to come and help us.', 'context': ' said they. “'},
{'istart': 46, 'iend': 142, 'talk': 'No, no; that will not do. The Mangs are old rebels, ungentle; to go to them would be a calamity.', 'context': 'But High Minister Qiao Zhou opposed, saying, “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 139, 'talk': 'The people of Wu are our sworn allies, and this is a moment of extreme danger; let us go thither.', 'context': 'Then some proposed seeking refuge in Wu: “'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 562, 'talk': 'In the whole course of past ages no Emperor has ever gone to another state. So far as I can see, Wei will presently absorb Wu, and certainly Wu will never overcome Wei. Imagine the disgrace of becoming a minister of Wu and then having to style yourself minister of Wei. It would double the mortification. Do neither. Surrender to Wei, and Wei will give Your Majesty a strip of land where the ancestral temple can be preserved, and the people will be saved from suffering. I desire Your Majesty to reflect well upon this.', 'context': 'But Qiao Zhou also opposed this, saying, “'},
{'istart': 53, 'iend': 210, 'talk': 'The ministers have decided otherwise; they advise surrender. You are the only one who thinks that boldness may avail, and would you drench the city in blood?', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler turned feebly to his son and said, “'},
{'istart': 79, 'iend': 122, 'talk': 'Be silent! You are too young to understand.', 'context': 'The Latter Ruler became angry at this harangue and turned to his son, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 310, 'talk': 'If we have done our best and defeat yet comes, if father and son, prince and minister have set their backs to the wall and died in one final effort to preserve the dynasty, then in the shades of the Nine Golden Springs we shall be able to look the First Ruler in the face, unashamed. But what if we surrender?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 135, 'talk': 'Is it not shameful in one day to throw down all that our ancestors built up with so great labor? I would rather die.', 'context': 'The Prince cried, “'},
{'istart': 238, 'iend': 301, 'talk': 'My Prince, why does your face bear this look of terrible anger?', 'context': 'The wrath of Prince Liu Chan swelled high as heaven when he heard that his father had actually arranged the date of his abdication. Girding on his sword, he was setting out for the Palace when his Consort, Lady Cui, stopped him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 13, 'iend': 313, 'talk': 'The army of Wei is at the gates, and my father has made his Act of Surrender. Tomorrow he and all his ministers are going out of the city to submit formally, and the dynasty will end. But rather than bow the knee to another, I will die and go into the presence of the First Ruler in the realms below.', 'context': 'He replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'How worthy; how worthy!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 40, 'iend': 138, 'talk': 'And if my lord must die, I, thy handmaid, prays that she may die first. Then may my Prince depart.', 'context': ' replied she. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'But why should you die?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 102, 'talk': 'The Prince dies for his father and the handmaid for her husband. One eternal principle guides us all.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 215, 'iend': 381, 'talk': 'Thy servant is ashamed at seeing the kingdom pass to another. Therefore has he slain his Consort and his sons that nothing should induce him to live and forego death.', 'context': 'off the head of his Consort that he might sever all ties to life lest he be tempted to live. Bearing the head of the princess in his hand, he went to the Temple of the First Ruler, where he bowed his head, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'My ancestors, if you have spiritual intelligence, yon know the feelings of your descendant.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 340, 'iend': 405, 'talk': 'While we are fighting to our death, the Latter Ruler has yielded!', 'context': "In due time Jiang Xian reached the Saber Pass, and gave Jiang Wei the Latter Ruler's command to surrender to the invaders. Jiang Wei was dumb with amazement at the order; his officers ground their teeth with rage and mortification. Their hair stood on end with anger; they drew their swords and slashed at stones in their wrath, shouting, “"},
{'istart': 112, 'iend': 174, 'talk': 'Generals, grieve not; even yet I can restore the House of Han.', 'context': 'The roar of their angry lamentation was heard for miles. But Jiang Wei soothed them with kindly words, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 5, 'talk': 'How?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 37, 'talk': 'Why have you been so long in coming?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 98, 'iend': 169, 'talk': 'The whole armies of the state are under me, and I am here far too soon.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei looked him straight in the face and said, without a tremor, but through falling tears, “'},
{'istart': 61, 'iend': 225, 'talk': 'You are lucky in that you have had to do with me. Things might well have been otherwise, and you might all have been put to death, if you surrender to other leader.', 'context': 'With a patronizing wave of his hand, he said to his guests, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 745, 'talk': 'Further, generous treatment of Liu Shan will tend to weaken Sun Xiu; but if Liu Shan be removed to Luoyang, the people of Wu will be perplexed and doubtful about what may happen to them, and they will not be amenable. Therefore it seems the most fitting to leave the late Ruler of Shu here. Next year, in the winter season, he might be removed to the capital. For the present I would recommend that he be created Prince of Fufeng, and granted a sufficient revenue and suitable attendants. His sons also should receive ducal rank. In this way would be demonstrated that favorable treatment follows upon submission. Such a course would inspire fear of the might of Wei and respect for its virtue, and the result will be all that could be desired.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 303, 'talk': 'The merits of Deng Ai surpass those of Bai Qi, who subdued the mighty state of Chu, and Han Xin, who conquered the state of Zhao. Deng Ai is created Grand Commander, and we confer upon him a fief of twenty thousand homesteads, and his two sons are ennobled, each with a fief of one thousand homesteads.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'A general in the field may decline to obey even the orders of his prince. My commission was to conquer the west; why are my plans hindered?', 'context': 'Then said Deng Ai, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 457, 'talk': 'Now seeing that Wu is still unsubdued, all interest centers upon this country, and schemes of settlement should not be nullified by strict adherence to rules and formalities. In war advances are made without thought of reputation, retreats without consideration of avoiding punishment. Though I do not possess the fortitude of the ancients, I shall not be deterred from acting for the benefit of the state by craven and selfish fears for my own reputation.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 52, 'talk': 'Why not order Zhong Hui to reduce him to obedience?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 76, 'iend': 298, 'talk': 'Deng Ai has been rewarded more richly than I and is a Grand Commander. But Sima Zhao suspects him of rebellion and has ordered Wei Guan and myself to keep him in order. What does my friend Jiang Wei think ought to be done?', 'context': 'When this edict reached Zhong Hui, he called in Jiang Wei and said to him, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 579, 'talk': "They say Deng Ai's origin was ignoble and in his youth he was a farmer and breeder of cattle. However, he had good luck and has won a great reputation in this expedition. But this is due not to his able plans, but to the good fortune of the state. If you had not been compelled to hold me in check at Saber Pass, he could not have succeeded. Now he wishes the late Ruler of Shu to be created Prince of Fufeng, whereby he hopes to win the goodwill of the people of Shu. But to me it seems that perfidy lies therein. The Duke of Jin suspects him, it is evident.", 'context': 'Jiang Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 127, 'talk': 'If you will send away your people, I have something to say to you in private.', 'context': 'Zhong Hui complimented him. Jiang Wei continued, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': "By making use of the Duke of Jin's suspicions,", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 205, 'talk': 'Send up a memorial to say that it looks as if Deng Ai really contemplated rebellion. You will receive direct orders to check the revolt.', 'context': ' replied Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 20, 'talk': 'Have you forgotten?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 33, 'talk': 'I feared lest you had forgotten,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 14, 'iend': 111, 'talk': 'Had I sent you, I should have felt doubts, too. However, come to Changan and you will understand.', 'context': 'who replied, “'},
{'istart': 86, 'iend': 216, 'talk': 'Send Wei Guan. If Deng Ai tries to kill Wei Guan, he will manifest the desire of his heart. Then you can destroy him as a traitor.', 'context': 'Asked to say what was the best plan to secure the arrest of Deng Ai, Jiang Wei said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'Do not worry. I have a scheme prepared.', 'context': 'But Wei Guan said, “'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 82, 'talk': "I serve the Son of Heaven's command to arrest Deng Ai and his son!", 'context': 'He roared out: “'},
{'istart': 93, 'iend': 148, 'talk': 'Vile cattle breeder! How dare you have your own scheme?', 'context': 'prisoners, struck the elder about the head and face with his whip and insulted him, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 57, 'talk': 'You fool! See what your good luck has brought you today!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'Today I have attained the one desire of my life,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 170, 'talk': "I do not think your advice much to the point. I am a young man, not forty yet, and think rather of going on than halting. I could not take up a do−nothing hermit's life.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 157, 'talk': 'If you do not, then take heed and prepare for dangers. Think out a careful course, as you are well able to do. You need not trouble any old fool for advice.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 65, 'iend': 106, 'talk': 'How well you know my thoughts, my friend!', 'context': 'Zhong Hui laughed loud and rubbed his hands together with glee. “'},
{'istart': 160, 'iend': 294, 'talk': 'I am at Changan with an army lest there should be any difficulty in disposing of Deng Ai. I need you to come to discuss state affairs.', 'context': 'While Zhong Hui and Jiang Wei were planning how best to outwit each other, but both being against Wei, there suddenly arrived a letter from Sima Zhao, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 13, 'talk': 'He suspects,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 17, 'talk': 'This decides me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'Will you lead the van?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 42, 'iend': 88, 'talk': 'When success is ours, we will share the spoil.', 'context': ' said Zhong Hui. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'The little I can do, I will do most willingly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 308, 'talk': 'The Empress has just died, but before her death she gave me an edict, which is here, recounting the crimes of Sima Zhao and charging him with aiming at the Throne. I am commissioned to destroy him, and you all must join me in the task.', 'context': 'Everyone asked what was the cause of this grief, and Zhong Hui replied. “'},
{'istart': 121, 'iend': 156, 'talk': 'Here is death for those who oppose!', 'context': 'The guests stared at each other in amazement, but no one uttered a word. Then the host suddenly drew his sword, crying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'They are not really with us,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 86, 'talk': 'I venture to request you to bury them.', 'context': ' said Jiang Wei. “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 34, 'talk': 'A great pit has been already dug,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 63, 'iend': 159, 'talk': 'And I have a lot of clubs ready. We can easily club those who disagree and bury them in the pit.', 'context': ' replied his brother host. “'},
{'istart': 23, 'iend': 231, 'talk': 'My son, Hu Yuan, is in command of a force outside the city. He will never suspect Zhong Hui capable of such a crime, and I pray you tell him. If I am to die, it will be with less regret if my son can be told.', 'context': 'Hu Lie wept and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'Kind master, have no anxiety; only leave it to me,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 201, 'talk': 'Sir, you are holding in captivity a large number of officers, and they are suffering from lack of food and water. Will you not appoint an officer to supply their needs?', 'context': 'He went to Zhong Hui, and said, “'},
{'istart': 152, 'iend': 232, 'talk': 'I am placing great trust in you, and you must be loyal. Our secret must be kept.', 'context': 'Zhong Hui was accustomed to yield to the wishes of Qiu Jian, and he made no difficulty about this. He told Qiu Jian to see to it himself, only saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 85, 'talk': 'My lord, you may be quite content. I know how to keep a strict watch when necessary.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 156, 'iend': 196, 'talk': 'We would rather die than follow a rebel.', 'context': "When Hu Yuan knew the whole story, he was astonished and told his subordinates, and they were greatly enraged. They came to their commander's tent to say: “"},
{'istart': 38, 'iend': 131, 'talk': 'Last night I dreamed a dream, that I was bitten by many serpents. Can you expound the vision?', 'context': 'One day Zhong Hui said to Jiang Wei, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 96, 'talk': 'Dreams of dragons and snakes and scaly creatures are exceedingly auspicious.', 'context': 'Jiang Wei replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 95, 'talk': 'I know they are opposed to us, and you would do well to slay them all, and that right quickly,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 6, 'talk': 'Good,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'The officers must be raging,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 80, 'talk': 'We would best slay them at once.', 'context': ' said Zhong Hui. “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 59, 'talk': 'The outside soldiers are in the Palace.', 'context': 'But they told him: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 8, 'talk': 'Failed!', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 24, 'iend': 53, 'talk': 'But it is the will of Heaven.', 'context': ' he shrieked, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 42, 'talk': 'If Deng Ai lives, I will die in his hand,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 36, 'iend': 184, 'talk': 'When Deng Ai took Jiangyou, he wished to put me to death. It was only at the prayer of my friends that he let me off. May I not have my revenge now?', 'context': 'Furthermore, General Tian Xu said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'Now that the capital has fallen and the Ruler of Shu is a captive, it would be well to surrender,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 17, 'iend': 254, 'talk': 'There is a hindrance. I know not how fares our lord, whether he is in comfort or in misery. If his captors treat him generously, then will I yield. But perhaps they will put him to shame; and when the prince is shamed, the minister dies.', 'context': 'Huo Yi replied, “'},
{'istart': 58, 'iend': 220, 'talk': 'The man lacks feeling; that is what has ruined him. Even if Zhuge Liang had lived, he could not have maintained such a man. It is no wonder that Jiang Wei failed.', 'context': 'Half way through the feast, Sima Zhao said to Jia Chong, “'},
{'istart': 39, 'iend': 65, 'talk': 'Do you never think of Shu?', 'context': 'Turning to his guest, Sima Zhao said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 39, 'talk': 'With such music as this, I forget Shu,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 97, 'iend': 123, 'talk': 'Do you never think of Shu?', 'context': 'When the wine had gone round several more times, Sima Zhao put the same question a second time: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 48, 'talk': 'Is not that just what Xi Zheng told you to say?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 23, 'talk': 'It is just as you say,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 267, 'iend': 302, 'talk': "The empire was really my brother's.", 'context': 'The second son, Sima You, was mild of disposition, a filial son and a dutiful brother. His father loved him dearly. As Sima Shi had died without leaving sons, this youth, Sima You, was regarded as his son, to continue that line of the family. Sima Zhao used to say: “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 55, 'talk': 'It is improper and infelicitous to prefer the younger,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 9, 'iend': 153, 'talk': 'Certain former dynasties have preferred the younger before the elder and rebellion has generally followed. We pray you reflect upon these cases.', 'context': 'saying, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 154, 'talk': 'The care of the empire devolves upon the Prince of Jin; let us induct the heir. Then we can perform the sacrifices to the late prince.', 'context': 'Then said He Zeng, “'},
{'istart': 249, 'iend': 263, 'talk': 'Scholar Prince', 'context': "Thereupon Sima Yan was set up in his father's place. He gave He Zeng the title of Prime Minister; Sima Wang, Minister of the Interior; Shi Bao, Commander of the Flying Cavalry; and conferred many other titles and ranks. The posthumous title of the “"},
{'istart': 102, 'iend': 252, 'talk': 'Cao Cao said that if the celestial mandate rested upon him, he could be no more than King Wen of Zhou, who served as a regent only; is this really so?', 'context': 'When the obsequies were finished, Sima Yan summoned Jia Chong and Pei Xiu into the palace, and said, “'},
{'istart': 20, 'iend': 189, 'talk': 'Cao Cao was in the service of Han and feared lest posterity should reproach him with usurpation. Wherefore he spoke thus. Nevertheless he cause Cao Pi to become Emperor.', 'context': 'Jia Chong replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 40, 'talk': 'How did my father compare with Cao Cao?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 456, 'talk': "Although Cao Cao was universally successful, yet the people feared him and credited him with no virtue. Cao Pi's rule was marked by strife and lack of tranquillity. No single year was peaceful. Later the Original Prince and Wonderful Prince of your line rendered great services and disseminated compassion and virtue, so that they were beloved. Your late father overcame Shu in the west and was universally renowned. Comparison with Cao Cao is impossible.", 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 87, 'talk': 'Still Cao Pi continued the rule of Han; can I not in like manner continue that of Wei?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 43, 'iend': 187, 'talk': "Cao Pi's action may be taken as a precedent to continue an older dynasty. Wherefore prepare an abdication terrace to make the great declaration.", 'context': 'Jia Chong and Pei Xiu bowed low and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 43, 'talk': 'By whose merits did Wei succeed to empire?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 47, 'talk': 'Certainly success was due to your forefathers,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 58, 'talk': 'If you do this thing, you will be a rebel and an usurper,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 51, 'talk': 'And what shall I be if I avenge the wrongs of Han?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 52, 'iend': 98, 'talk': 'What should I do? Some decision must be taken.', 'context': 'Cao Huang turned to Jia Chong and Pei Xiu, saying, “'},
{'istart': 73, 'iend': 78, 'talk': 'mouse', 'context': 'Cao Huang could only accept this advice, and the terrace was built. The “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 73, 'talk': 'I have been a servant of Wei and will never turn my back upon the House,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 136, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Wan shui! O King, live forever!', 'context': 'The new Emperor was now seated in his place, and all the officers made their salutations and felicitated him. The very hills rang with “'},
{'istart': 50, 'iend': 167, 'talk': 'Prince Sun Wan is too youthful to rule in such troublous times. Let us confer the throne to Sun Hao, Lord of Wucheng.', 'context': 'Then Wan Yu, Left Army Inspector, rose and said, “'},
{'istart': 69, 'iend': 158, 'talk': 'Sun Hao is able and prompt in decision. He can handle the responsibilities of an emperor.', 'context': 'Zhang Bu, General of the Left Army, supported his election, saying, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 32, 'talk': 'Settle this with the officials;', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 48, 'iend': 94, 'talk': 'I am a widow and know nothing of such matters.', 'context': ' she replied, “'},
{'istart': 442, 'iend': 450, 'talk': 'sewn up.', 'context': 'However, the year−style was changed to Sweet Dew the very next year. The new ruler soon proved himself cruel and oppressive and day by day grew more so. Sun Hao indulged in every form of vice and chose Eunuch Cen Hun as his confidant and favorite. When Prime Minister Puyang Xing and General Zhang Bu ventured upon remonstrance, both, with all their family, were put to death. Thereafter none dared to speak; the mouth of every courtier was “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 537, 'talk': 'In former times the palace women numbered less than a hundred; for years past they have exceeded a thousand. This is an extravagant waste of treasure. The courtiers render no disinterested service, but are split into cliques and cabals. The honest are injured and the good driven away. All these things undermine the state and weaken the people. I beg Your Majesty to reduce the number of officers and remove grievances, to dismiss the palace women and select honest officers, to the joy of the people and the tranquillity of the state.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 37, 'iend': 125, 'talk': "All is propitious, and in the year of the 'mouse' your blue umbrella will enter Luoyang.", 'context': 'Shang Guang cast a lot and replied, “'},
{'istart': 31, 'iend': 315, 'talk': 'The former rulers listened to your words and sent generals to various points and placed defensive camps along the rivers. And over all these was set Ding Feng. Now my desire is to conquer Han and avenge the wrongs of my brother, the Ruler of Shu. What place should be first conquered?', 'context': 'He said to Minister Hua Jiao, “'},
{'istart': 19, 'iend': 387, 'talk': 'Now that Chengdu has fallen and the Throne there been overturned, Sima Yan will assuredly desire to absorb this land. Your Majesty should display virtue and restore confidence to your people. That would be the best plan. If you engage in war, it will be like throwing on hemp to put out a fire; the hemp only adds to the blaze. This is worthy of careful consideration.', 'context': 'Hua Jiao replied, “'},
{'istart': 34, 'iend': 233, 'talk': 'I desire to take this opportunity to return to my real heritage. Why do you employ this ill−omened language? Were it not for your long service, now would I slay you and expose your head as a warning.', 'context': 'But Sun Hao grew angry and said, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 15, 'talk': 'It is pitiful,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 33, 'iend': 92, 'talk': 'Ere long our silky, beautiful country will pass to another.', 'context': ' said Hua Jiao. “'},
{'istart': 22, 'iend': 422, 'talk': 'You must not despise Lu Kang, for he is able and crafty. Formerly his master sent him to attack Xiling, and he slew Bu Chan and many of his generals, before I could save that city. So long as Lu Kang remains in command, I shall remain on the defensive. I shall not attack till there be trouble and confusion among our enemies. To be rash and not await the proper moment to attack is to invite defeat.', 'context': 'But Yang Hu replied, “'},
{'istart': 12, 'iend': 99, 'talk': 'The soldiers of Yang Hu have so high a discipline that I may not make any invasion now.', 'context': 'He sighed, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 29, 'talk': 'Does your leader drink wine?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 15, 'iend': 45, 'talk': 'Only fine wines does he drink.', 'context': 'They replied, “'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 27, 'talk': 'I have some very old wine,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 26, 'talk': 'Why do you give him wine?', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 72, 'talk': 'Because he has shown kindness, and I must return courtesy for courtesy.', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 25, 'talk': 'So he knows I can drink,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 24, 'talk': 'Lu Kang is no poisoner,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 1, 'iend': 49, 'talk': 'I think he suffers from the same complaint as I,', 'context': '“'},
{'istart': 16, 'iend': 91, 'talk': 'What! Think you that old Uncle Yang Hu would poison a person? Do not doubt.', 'context': 'Lu Kang cried, “'},
{'istart': 108, 'iend': 326, 'talk': 'If our opponents take their stand upon virtue and we take ours upon violence, they will drag us after them without fighting. See to it that the boundaries be well kept and that we seek not to gain any unfair advantage.', 'context': 'He drank the decoction. Next day he was much better; and when his staff came to congratulate him, he said, “'},
